	('000fef03-5b12-4058-8b28-a633ed7bab4a','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Councillors have given the go-ahead to turn Grade II listed former council-owned buildings into a £62m student accommodation scheme. ... McLaren Property intends to repurpose the Leonardo Printworks, the Leonardo building and Thoresby House in the Civic Quarter of Leeds city centre, as well as build new accommodation on the former car park site. ... Operational carbon emissions are minimised through connection to the city council\'s low-carbon district heating system, as well as through a thermally efficient fabric and the use of rooftop photovoltaic panels. ... Construction is due to start in August 2021 and to complete by August 2023 in time for the 2023/2024 academic year.','Historic civic buildings in Leeds to become £62m student accommodation scheme','Yorkshire Post','2021-07-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/business/historic-civic-buildings-in-leeds-to-become-ps62m-student-accommodation-scheme-3309062','The Yorkshire Post reported on Leeds City Council\'s approval for McLaren Property\'s £62m student accommodation scheme at Leonardo Printworks, the Leonardo building, and Thoresby House. The article highlighted the repurposing of Grade II listed buildings and the plan to minimize carbon emissions through connection to the city council\'s low-carbon district heating system. Construction was slated to commence in August 2021, with completion by August 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('00420c77-8ed0-451b-9244-00d956c4c98d','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The second stage of consultation has launched today to improve two key roads linking Leeds to Wakefield and Pontefract. Run in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, the consultation aims to make it safer and more accessible to walk, wheel and cycle, as well as improving bus reliability. [13]','Consultation launches on travel improvements to A61 junctions and B6481 Pontefract Road','Leeds City Council News / Yorkshire Evening Post','2025-02-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF7pqVSrIekUQUnUR_UhRaKbObfVijjj_EAZs4RHu0J1M1XRUunwUJ80g1ITJBiNNvaMGLdkK5Pg7XxpZbntKIuk6qLdqIKWuc4MM4du-pCjOXTrU6F9PSyNa471RQS7k6Q-gUWh5l8PG1ZnjuVROy7EICZSFIQ12rtFGwJYiH5b1AOSGOyuI-6XWl_B3urgduipcTPie_W2WD8GqiHLpYLFVslN4XwHL0gYrIBOA-_DEY=','Leeds City Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a second stage of public consultation on February 4, 2025. This consultation focused on specific safety and accessibility improvements for the A61 in Lofthouse and the B6481 Pontefract Road, proposing a £9.14 million investment to enhance walking, cycling, and bus reliability in these areas. [12, 13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('00a66292-7bda-451a-be91-f8e4e00da520','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Overall, our current programme should deliver more than 2,000 new homes by 2030. Work has already begun to deliver around 800 of these new homes, including two Extra Care schemes which will provide supported housing for older people. What did Cabinet discuss? Cabinet discussions specifically focussed on developments at Dewsbury Riverside and Fenay Lane in Almondbury. Both developments are set to deliver more affordable housing for Kirklees, and form an important part of the council\'s overall housing growth programme. Dewsbury Riverside. The development at Dewsbury riverside...','Cabinet have discussed progression of plans for housing growth in Kirklees','Kirklees Together (Kirklees Council)','2023-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/news/2023/cabinet-discusses-plans-for-housing-growth.aspx','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet discussed plans for housing growth, including the Fenay Lane site in Almondbury, which has the capacity to deliver around 160 new homes. The discussion covered the potential sale of this land to a strategically selected housing provider, with the aim of maximizing affordable and energy-efficient homes. This was part of a broader strategy to deliver over 2,000 new homes by 2030 across Kirklees.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('00e647ef-468f-4979-8d49-23c2f5cc5aaf','infrastructure-toby-carvery-leeds-aberford-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.388','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2024-08-05) Residents are set to have their say on plans to improve electric vehicle infrastructure across Leeds and West Yorkshire. ... The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is working to bring more electric vehicle charge points to the region through its £17 million Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme. ... The consultation runs until Thursday, September 12, with people able to feedback at various drop-in sessions, webinars, online.','West Yorkshire: Public to have their say on £17m plans to improve EV charging infrastructure in Leeds','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-08-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/west-yorkshire-public-to-have-their-say-on-ps17m-plans-to-improve-ev-charging-infrastructure-in-leeds-4745344','This news article announced a public consultation on plans to improve electric vehicle charging infrastructure across Leeds and West Yorkshire as part of the £17 million Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme. The consultation, led by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, ran from August 2024 until September 12, 2024, seeking public input on charge point locations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('01122f61-25fe-44ec-8936-6e79ffbe910a','infrastructure-a638-doncaster-road-corridor-improvement-programme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.997','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council is looking to make improvements to the A638 Doncaster Road in Wakefield and would like your feedback on the proposed improvements. The Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP) is part of a West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund package of highway related schemes. The CIP aims to provide low and medium cost interventions on the key highway network to deliver benefits for all road Users... The improvements on the A638 Doncaster Road between the junction with the A655 Black Road at Heath Common and the A61 Barnsley Road at Chantry Bridge are key to providing the Wakefield City area with the infrastructure it needs to support development.','Is Doncaster Road good enough? Wakefield Council wants to know what you think','Wakefield Express','2021-07-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/transport/is-doncaster-road-good-enough-wakefield-council-wants-to-know-what-you-think-3306821','A news article from Wakefield Express reported on Wakefield Council\'s public consultation for the A638 Doncaster Road Corridor Improvement Programme. The article highlighted the program\'s goals of improving bus services, walking, and cycling facilities to tackle issues like high traffic, limited crossings, and air pollution along the stretch between Heath Common and Chantry Bridge.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('013803d9-b930-483f-9545-70aa736801e4','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Electric vehicle public rapid charging network InstaVolt has introduced additional security measures following a spate of cables being cut which are leaving chargers unusable and harming critical infrastructure. InstaVolt has seen more than 20 EV charging sites across the Midlands and Yorkshire targeted by gangs since November. The company has introduced robust measures around its charging stations to deter any further damage including installing extra CCTV; introducing security patrols; using SmartWater to tag property and utilising tracking devices to ensure InstaVolt cables can be identified.','InstaVolt introduces additional security measures after EV charging cables cut','Transport + Energy','2024-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.transportandenergy.com/2024/05/01/instavolt-introduces-additional-security-measures-after-ev-charging-cables-cut/','InstaVolt implemented additional security measures across its network, including in Yorkshire, following a spate of cable cutting incidents at over 20 sites since November 2023. The measures include extra CCTV, security patrols, SmartWater tagging, and tracking devices to deter theft and disruption to EV drivers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('014d9646-52d0-4654-9619-e57c36f5b341','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Pipeline. West Halifax - Improved Streets for People. Borough Council of Calderdale. UK1: Pipeline notice - Procurement Act 2023 - view information about notice types. Notice identifier: 2025/S 000-025777. Published 23 May 2025, 10:03am. Scope. Description. - Placemaking and urban realm improvements. - Improvements to signal technology at junctions, incorporating bus priority. - New pedestrian crossings serving desire lines. - Footway improvements including refurbishment and widening. - Formalisation of car parking and parking controls. Traffic calming/speed reduction measures and \'behavioural deterrents\'. - Aesthetic enhancements including planting, street furniture and other attractive roadside landscaping. - Improvements to resting places and small \'pocket\' parks. - Implementation of one-way systems. - Informal street / plaza areas to create open pedestrian-friendly streetscapes.','Pipeline Notice: West Halifax - Improved Streets for People','Find a Tender service (UK Government)','2025-05-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHubdI1RgHxrnTPOPzO_7u2OVCUyetOwoA6nE4SoSuG8yRm6SgP0W5fyZ_UMtj7o1_fb6B1x_X6Hr7lnYy0Ys0BjVEPQa0UoeOi421NyJ8jenuukccN4Tl8ol_hyIFsK4m7tJeEyQUnwaCBIy2ph90YGdSPUyeALZM=','A pipeline notice was published detailing the scope of works for the West Halifax - Improved Streets for People project. This includes placemaking and urban realm improvements, upgrades to signal technology for bus priority, new pedestrian crossings, footway improvements, formalisation of parking, traffic calming, aesthetic enhancements, and creation of informal street/plaza areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0152451f-eaeb-4e78-92e7-d298614ad86d','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council announced an additional £12 million in government funding for the Hebden Bridge flood alleviation scheme. This investment, part of a new multi-billion-pound national effort, will accelerate construction and aims to protect around 150 homes and 200 businesses, contributing to local economic regeneration and climate change efforts.','£12 million boost for flood protection in Hebden Bridge','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2020-07-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/news-articles/2020/12million-boost-for-flood-protection-in-hebden-bridge/','Calderdale Council announced an additional £12 million in government funding for the Hebden Bridge flood alleviation scheme. This investment, part of a new multi-billion-pound national effort, will accelerate construction and aims to protect around 150 homes and 200 businesses, contributing to local economic regeneration and climate change efforts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0199ba4b-ce0e-4456-9360-ccb1baed8ee3','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This consultation has closed. The Kings Road Outcome Report has been published and you can read it here: Kings Road Consultation Report. Key Dates: Consultation closes. 16 March 2025. About the scheme. Kings Road is an important part of the Bradford district\'s transport network. It connects communities such as Five Lane Ends, Swain House and Ashbourne, providing access to schools, shopping and amenities along the route and access to Bradford city centre via Canal Road. The scheme is expected to cost around £35 million and, if approved, would be funded by the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) to transform this vital 2-mile route.','Kings Road Connect | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Consultation Closed)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice)','2025-03-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/kings-road-connect','This is the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s official consultation page, confirming that the public consultation for the Kings Road Connect scheme closed on March 16, 2025. It also provides a link to the Kings Road Consultation Report, which contains the outcome of the consultation. The page outlines the overall aims and proposed measures of the £35 million scheme, including improvements for public transport, walking, wheeling, and cycling along the route.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('01c91839-bb06-4243-bd28-99aebcc20084','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a638-doncaster-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.598','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans which could see more than £6m of funding being made available to improve travel on a \'torturous\' have been approved. Councillors agreed to a proposal to enable a range of works along Doncaster Road in Wakefield for the benefit of bus users, cyclists and pedestrians. A total of £6.3m could be made available to Wakefield Council once detailed plans have been drawn up. The council is will receive an initial £1.09m of funding from West Yorkshire Combined Authority to fund a full business case and detailed designs of highway improvement works. A further report will then be put to the Cabinet seeking approval for full funding for the scheme. [5]','Wakefield Council Cabinet Approves £6m Doncaster Road Scheme','Wakefield Express','2022-06-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/plan-approved-for-ps6m-scheme-to-improve-torturous-stretch-of-a638-doncaster-road-in-wakefield-3733220','Wakefield Council\'s Cabinet approved plans for the £6m scheme to improve the A638 Doncaster Road. The approval, reported on June 16, 2022, allowed for a range of works along the road between Black Road (Heath Common) and Chantry Bridge, benefiting bus users, cyclists, and pedestrians. An initial £1.09m from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority was secured for a full business case and detailed designs, with a further report planned for full funding approval. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('01d10ae8-6a00-40de-ba96-4c1f3f4f4b8f','infrastructure-halifax-future-high-streets-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.256','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Re-roofing starts at Halifax Borough Market this month. The milestone marks the start of the first major project funded by the Future High Street Fund in Halifax. ... The £2.3m contract will take around 18 months to complete. The work starts 22 August 2022 and will be undertaken in 5 phases to minimise disruption.','Re-roofing starts at Halifax Borough Market this month','Calderdale Next Chapter','2022-08-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFq4RIrSfM0WqiEQ7p_U5vc7dD2Rg54hFMSzYnMyvjznYDHtoqKLeuBn_a60MI-_T2x8EK0TCRc8xiPy1skoDrkSOEufDQitsN_eQvyMS_mwaMK8gJWotXfXh47Qgq4HuAgWIP4jPUJMZwqWA_wPhXqnR94PBM_nWEPCXTi2Otd7IccXAKt8Q==','This news item details the commencement of re-roofing works at Halifax Borough Market, funded by the Future High Streets Fund. It marks the start of the first major project under the FHSF in Halifax, with a £2.3m contract taking approximately 18 months.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('01d716d2-a63b-4c99-b4c3-6991b857c970','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Spinners Yard is a 185-apartment, U-shaped built-to-rent scheme constructed on Regent Street in Mabgate in the city centre. It\'s set to be completed in early 2025. The Spinners Yard development will draw heating and hot water from the Leeds pipe network, a district heating system linked to the City\'s energy from waste plant, resulting in Spinners Yard\'s carbon footprint being just 10% of that allowed under current building regulations. This is a step change in creating homes for the future that have a much lower environmental footprint. Nigel Rawlings, CEO of Rise Homes, added: “We are delighted with Clegg\'s progress at Spinner\'s Yard and we are very much looking forward to the completion of this sustainable development linked to the Leeds City energy from waste plant offering high-quality, spacious apartments at both affordable and market rents featuring many other environmental benefits.”','Spinner\'s Yard: New 11-story apartment complex in Leeds city centre due for completion in early 2025 | RISE Homes','RISE Homes','2024-09-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.risehomes.co.uk/news/spinners-yard-new-11-story-apartment-complex-in-leeds-city-centre-due-for-completion-in-early-2025/','Rise Homes provided an update on the Spinner\'s Yard development, an 11-story, 185-apartment complex in Mabgate, Leeds. The development is designed to connect to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, aiming to achieve a carbon footprint of just 10% of that allowed under current building regulations. Completion was projected for early 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('01f6f0f1-60c8-46f2-9bf9-9c1f699ebc9c','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle charging points will be installed across the district if Wakefield Council\'s key decision makers give the go ahead at their meeting next week. Cabinet are being asked to accept a grant of £1,520,938 from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority\'s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant funding scheme.','More EV charging points coming to Wakefield as part of our plans to go green - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2024-10-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/news/more-ev-charging-points-coming-to-wakefield-as-part-of-our-plans-to-go-green','Wakefield Council announced that its Cabinet would consider accepting a £1,520,938 grant from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority\'s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant funding scheme. This initiative aims to expand the number of publicly available EV charging points across the Wakefield district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('01fe5416-357f-4d18-a045-79fd539a5f80','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'\'CYCLOPS\' junctions are among the proposals for the second phase to improve one of Bradford\'s biggest corridors. Phase One of the Thornton Road Improvements Project - from the city centre to the junction of West Park Road on Thornton Road - is well underway with it due to be complete this August. Now Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), have launched a public consultation on the next stage of the proposals... To ensure that the proposals meet the needs of the local community, a consultation is being held on the plans until Monday, July 21. [6] The consultation period runs until 11:59 pm on 23 July 2025. [11]','Consultation launched for Phase Two of Thornton Road Improvements Project, including new CYCLOPS junctions','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / Travel and Tour World / Bradford Council','2025-06-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEKWb5MroYuwijcits-jNxyZ-L5aI5jBc2yUJfcPd2ElqJsj0elpan8RPy9Wk_cGzj7Dr1V9yUJE3gjyRbGGa0KU1LuGD4SHj3Vp1o1CX2KPDdy7_ucPOI0-cw_FqtgWA8LcP-frJz71TKsV5Ce_T-ZrIYik81zHUZ4NsZn2gW-9GyBGtXUAeSoH6P8JxF8r2c2E-4dEtrC2qDmaql0ChiOW8ca4g==','Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a public consultation for Phase Two of the Thornton Road Improvements Project. This phase incorporates the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Phase 2 and the Four Lane Ends Corridor Improvement Scheme. Key proposals include 2.9km eastbound and 2.6km westbound segregated cycleways, and two new \'CYCLOPS\' (Cycle Optimised Protected Signals) junctions. The consultation is open until July 21, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0207e8da-0749-4eda-9137-4d6f941e8150','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan (LCWIP) Phase 1 summarises proposals developed during an initial pilot phase. It aimed to test approaches by looking at two specific geographic areas: a cycling route in Brighouse and walking improvements in Halifax. Proposals were developed through workshops, street audits, data analysis, and technical assessments. Further stakeholder engagement was undertaken in winter 2019 to get feedback on these proposals. The plan sets out a new, strategic approach to identifying required cycling and walking improvements at the local level and forms part of the West Yorkshire LCWIP development coordinated by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [3, 5]','Calderdale Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan (LCWIP): Phase 1','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHkzJi9wdxCWBpK-KgeQeiw24_xtZJxl1cwzpSCQO2z5sZsmCNz7ejKVkcl_KGzGCHoqJwnF2bVqC1fpriG6Z3pWAGdV8XstuiTohC4MWq2LopIqLNRjZZe13ZOrMcE9yxIe4h1KvGQdjlMom0mxRGNZNI83SvFgXK11cuogKY5Ja59RAADrkag6UY=','This document outlines the strategic approach and initial pilot phase for improving active travel in Calderdale, specifically focusing on a cycling network in Brighouse and walking improvements in Halifax. It details the methodology, informed by street audits and stakeholder engagement, with feedback gathered in winter 2019, leading to proposed infrastructure improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('022b7afb-7673-4783-890a-c97e9dae6ac2','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The site exists within greenfield associated with brownfield area. The site is on risk from Lumb Clough running in the north of the site. Couple of land drainage issues have been been reported in the past in the close vicinity of the site. ... FRA of the site is a mitigation measure because of site is located along Lumb Clough. [10]','Calderdale Council Site Assessment Report Identifies Flood Risk from Lumb Clough','Calderdale Council','2017-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/sites/default/files/SiteAssessmentReport-MainReport.pdf','A site assessment report for \'Land off, Halifax Road, Triangle, Sowerby Bridge\' by Calderdale Council identifies flood risk from Lumb Clough, a UK Biodiversity Action Plan habitat, and notes past drainage issues in the vicinity. This report highlights historical flood concerns in an area geographically close to Cottonstones and Lumb, indicating a need for flood alleviation measures.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0259dd4d-14a8-43e6-ac44-3c69cb726486','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire and the Humber will benefit from 108 flood schemes totalling £59.5 million protecting homes and businesses, boosting the local economy, and creating construction and infrastructure jobs, the Environment Agency has announced. ... Here is a list of Calderdale schemes to be invested in between April 2025 and March 2026: ... Hebble Brook, Halifax.','List of Calderdale flood schemes to receive a funding boost, the Environment Agency has announced','Halifax Courier','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGIgODs_1BBfCaXC10aY5aKLEsd-Bx-nmEEyu2XTaKH4wy-3bWE8mQHfwWI7oiRUvoFwhOAglmssurgJDORg8a7bn9gmJg56XEP0E4LgOhNaXEtl3t9ugSgg7hWvIU2ThTm1F54rOo7GywVeFIVA2gkcUiqReWmbJH4kC6d8wySbMZ8E7SDU1zasUeSS6zR1gwuA4Ya-C03PcRNwf_avQC-SEl-f5IZU-G4rsRJdErKAgTyfDLSxaFiZ-PKcxWizdiAZxj1hJyHgb_XhdFPE41NSpL4xlua','The Environment Agency announced that Yorkshire and the Humber would benefit from 108 flood schemes totaling £59.5 million, with Hebble Brook, Halifax listed among the Calderdale schemes to receive investment between April 2025 and March 2026. This funding aims to kickstart or progress construction to protect homes and businesses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('026a1089-3a85-40de-8712-2088d88b38cf','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2021-01-26) Premier Inn to roll out high-powered GeniePoint electric charging at hundreds of locations across the UK. Whitbread – owner of brands including Premier Inn hotels and restaurants Beefeater and Brewers\' Fayre has announced it has struck a deal with energy giant ENGIE, to deliver the UK hospitality sector\'s biggest roll-out of high-powered electric charging points. Whitbread, which has over 800 hotels across the UK and more car park locations than the NCP, aims to install up to a thousand GeniePoint Network rapid charging points, beginning with 600 committed over the next three years as part of its Force for Good sustainability scheme.','Whitbread PLC Announces Major Rollout of Rapid EV Charging Points in Hospitality Sector','Whitbread PLC Press Release','2021-01-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFJGBdHhR2rb7qW3U7Uj8Uy2Awn5HyeQr-glhNf9tgvfKwX-DskHbLJ4uKWuB3Gna-mXRaBnmWa7UN4tMbuLl2aNFIrvNBXkjd4-WdVGxaXJx-0o13gyHRjIwWJ6O82U6Ktw7mZszg5HQJDptglKG_-hS3ZoUrXnZ8=','Whitbread PLC, owner of Premier Inn, announced a deal with ENGIE to install up to a thousand GeniePoint Network rapid charging points across its hotels and restaurants over three years. This initiative highlights a significant trend within the hospitality sector to integrate EV charging infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('029aa664-e6c8-4283-8e5d-4da889396046','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to build tram lines in Leeds and Bradford are set to move to the next phase. Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million for ongoing detailed planning and development work on Mass Transit, which will see a line run through West Leeds. The work will include further technical and environmental assessments on phase one tram route options, as well as progressing the business case and preparing the plans to go before government decision-makers in the coming years. [9], [11]','Mass transit: Detailed planning and development to keep mass transit on track for 2028 start','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/mass-transit-detailed-planning-and-development-to-keep-mass-transit-on-track-for-2028-start/','Regional decision-makers are set to approve an additional £40 million for detailed planning and development work on the Mass Transit project. This funding will cover further technical and environmental assessments of tram route options and progress the business case, aiming to keep the project on schedule for a 2028 construction start.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('02b59166-5bad-450f-b92c-fdcc2411427c','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £35 million project to improve a main route into Bradford city centre has moved to the next stage. Kings Road, which runs from Wrose to Bradford city centre, will get over 4km of bus lanes and over 5km of cycle lanes under the major transport scheme – funded by West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA). The work, due to start in 2026, will also see 10 new pedestrian crossings and improvements to 21 bus stops. An underpass under Botany Avenue will be upgraded and the work will create 1,700 sqm of new public green space. Last week WYCA released £3.5m of funding for the development of a business case for the project. A report that went before the Authority gave an update on the scheme, saying work was likely to begin in February 2026 and be completed by March 2027.','£35 million scheme for Bradford road moving to next stage - Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFiQk1KC6L5_JP2GV-pyRIej50qhIs3O7fEPwPXYDDBJEkU6EY7-BShx9LRrjwjY15tDW8Wb-mXE4iyRlHYrb1TuwGZYezQlPBs1gG71QZqCU2bjBYVUyoNI8JNqQlYFUjL5mNHgi4uUrXquKw5DoXJT3N7oezNI1w1hgmi_bvinFTYiGfGs9xnRsaARvsnA28WpeKFnUKOQ4JBV_MqaSSroYE=','A £35 million project to improve Kings Road, running from Wrose to Bradford city centre, moved to its next stage. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) released £3.5 million for the development of a business case. The scheme, funded by WYCA, will include over 4km of bus lanes, over 5km of cycle lanes, 10 new pedestrian crossings, and upgrades to 21 bus stops and an underpass. Work is anticipated to start in February 2026 and be completed by March 2027.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('02c2fe41-8d97-4945-8107-04be459f9267','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The next major phase of the Huddersfield Southern Corridor improvement programme is set to commence on Monday, 17 March 2025, at Lockwood Bar, a key route into Huddersfield town centre. Kirklees Council is overseeing the scheme, with completion expected in early 2026. The upcoming works will introduce several key changes, including: Limiting the left turn from Lockwood Road into Bridge Street and the right turn from Bridge Street into Lockwood Road to buses only. A new link road with traffic signals at Crowther Street, providing a two-way traffic connection between Albert Street and Lockwood Road. New pedestrian crossings on Lockwood Road and Crowther Street. [4, 5]','Next Phase of Huddersfield Southern Corridor Road Works Set to Begin at Lockwood Bar','Kirklees Local TV / Kirklees Together','2025-03-17 00:00:00.000','https://kirkleeslocaltv.com/2025/03/17/next-phase-of-huddersfield-southern-corridor-road-works-set-to-begin/ [4] / https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/roads-and-highways/huddersfield-southern-corridors-phase-3.aspx [5]','The third phase of the Huddersfield Southern Corridor improvement programme is scheduled to commence on Monday, March 17, 2025, at Lockwood Bar, a critical route into Huddersfield town centre. Kirklees Council is overseeing this phase, which is expected to conclude in early 2026. Improvements include limiting turns for buses only, a new link road with traffic signals, and new pedestrian crossings, all aimed at reducing congestion and improving air quality.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0306d4f7-d852-4e3a-bc40-2c5878026a56','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Artist impression of the new look Brighouse outdoor market as part of a £19million Town Deal investment regeneration programme. The approved projects are: Brighouse Welcome – £400,000 to develop the public realm on the edge of the town centre and enhance the welcome to everyone, encouraging active lifestyles, contributing to Calderdale\'s climate action, and creating a place that enhances Brighouse\'s profile as a destination. [20] Proposals comprising The Brighouse Deal have now been approved by Ministers, which unlocks £19.1m worth of funding. Business cases for five projects were approved in July by Calderdale Council and the Brighouse Town Deal Board. [30] The Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities has now confirmed it is confident in the extensive engagement and consultation process which has taken place over the last three years, which led to the projects being developed. Plans can now progress to the next stage. [22]','Government approval unlocks £19.1 million for Brighouse Town Deal plans','Halifax Courier, TheBusinessDesk.com, News Centre','2022-10-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/ps191-million-brighouse-deal-plans-approved-by-government-green-light-given-to-ambitious-plans-for-town-centre-3875880, https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/2104118-ministerial-approval-unlocks-19m-to-radically-improve-town-centre, https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/19-1-million-brighouse-deal-plans-approved-by-government/','In October 2022, the UK Government formally approved the proposals comprising The Brighouse Deal, unlocking the £19.1 million funding. This allowed plans to progress to the next stage, focusing on projects like a new market, public realm improvements, and investment in skills.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0311a3f9-d6c5-4b55-9d85-e0508c39ecd8','infrastructure-manchester-road-bus-improvements-scheme-south-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.869','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BRADFORD\'S first double red lines could be installed on Manchester Road as part of a scheme to improve public transport on the key route. Proposals for changes to Manchester Road, which have now gone out to public consultation, also include new crossings, tree planting, more bus lanes, and improved bus shelters. Plans for a South Bradford Park and Ride have been massively scaled back since funding was first announced by Government over five years ago due to rising costs.','City\'s first double red lines could be on Manchester Road','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG_wEDQ4i0QIvNgfexnqrO3Xtrwz3NixIxNrp0EN3Ktpscnfnl70RngMMiUFGxsXxQoGCoQQu4nEBs8qV1KUrC7zk6tuy3ms17XHDefiC5tlb1qgh60yBvWujQ8Ac0oLWIEmbsOCytXi0OGIxHv4_qA6d78reA3HipIK8e9t59-elwjacFiH5lhDoBtqPMJOP6jot2lIEDt7OdkQl_b','A news report detailing the public consultation for the Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme, highlighting the controversial proposal for Bradford\'s first double red lines in bus lanes to enforce parking restrictions. The article also reiterated that the wider Park and Ride scheme had been scaled back due to rising costs, with the current focus being on bus improvements, new crossings, and tree planting.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('033daf0a-2d8c-4f67-845a-4ebbf828f3f9','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford District Local Plan- City Centre. • Emerging Draft Local Plan 2020-2028. • Bradford City Centre prime focus for regeneration, employment, retail, leisure and housing growth – creating a more liveable city. • 7000 new homes, key commercial sites for high quality office/business use & major transport infrastructure. Page 7. Top of Town - City Village Neighbourhood. Page 9. The Southern Gateway. • Identified as an extension to the city centre & key future \'location for growth\'. • Potential for regeneration and long term change to current land use including: 2500 new homes, new business opportunities & environment for sustainable urban living.','Draft Bradford District Local Plan includes City Village Neighbourhood','City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council','2021-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG6XV3uFBdfy2n4I29VqOJ7EolKxpxWJtKRPSzmJVwTqrrinj3GQt_njFvfTbzxd73JI6Qp2RdjTUhNR3o6nIDym8FBVtenRI2l_2mmnz5zSTL_fYHdMPlqBRdnQsDEaBm9aRxa','The City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council\'s Draft Local Plan, Preferred Options (Regulation 18) identifies the \'Top of Town - City Village Neighbourhood\' as a prime focus for regeneration, employment, retail, leisure, and housing growth. It anticipates 7,000 new homes across the city centre, with 2,500 new homes linked to the \'Southern Gateway\' extension, reinforcing the strategic importance of the Oastler site\'s redevelopment. [17, 19]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('03429ace-1b5f-4c12-8441-f0730b99177a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This report confirms that the Mayor has decided on behalf of the Combined Authority, in accordance with section 123G(4) of the Transport Act 2000 as amended by the Bus Services Act 2017, to make the West Yorkshire Franchising Scheme and publish the Transitional Notice. ... The draft Franchising Scheme (originally Appendix 3 to the Combined Authority paper considered at the Combined Authority meeting on 14 March 2024) is set out at Appendix 1 to this Report. The final Franchising Scheme and Transitional Notice dated with today\'s date (27th March 2024) are also published today. [28]','West Yorkshire Bus Reform: Report on Franchising Decision and Scheme Publication','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHHHH_HyMceH1NGdjt4vKhXMLVAGjXF4-o3MZa-volvi1wlKOwLE522FM7RMlFrwpwBq6EZhB3c0v-tugBNsacBahw13Gb2Srwj1MgydhHo-KPXpo3uRxBNAmBGdfXZFeCDRIFrXqnelFk3EnpSfwznKyGARDFZYSMMAfbDb7kOJoZ39i9e6FuyyOtb4H4dEgI=','Following the Mayor\'s decision, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) published its Report on the Franchising Decision and the final West Yorkshire Franchising Scheme for Buses 2024, along with a Transitional Notice. This officially confirmed the legal framework and implementation details for the publicly-run bus network. The scheme outlined how WYCA would facilitate the involvement of small and medium-sized operators in the procurement process. [28]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('03ab9784-a26d-4a27-adb2-b7b8a8fcd8b5','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calverley Flood Storage Reservoir (FSR) will provide online storage for 1.8Mm3 of flood waters... The scheme was granted planning permission in May 2021, with works commencing on site the following month.','Planning Permission Granted for Calverley Flood Storage Reservoir','The British Dam Society','2021-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEvdDv_Hw4EVvm6rvG7CZr36z1Upv6KOBTZniMJattP26DoZbP8iSvgWpn7GyQtshye613-Kvv3opTZ20hoWOv-uOW-wE2i2AJT4V-VWS4VYsyDj6MNLRGf08MXa7iOijwIHfQMpomqfSqE-KAW_yCpuEuhrZyTD-xe3aAT8tgfXOXMLb4mf_ZN1GfYoNcznyX-mW_I_bVZkPlqemAw62w','The Calverley Flood Storage Reservoir, a key component of Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2, received planning permission in May 2021. Works on the site commenced the following month. This reservoir is designed to provide online storage for 1.8 million cubic meters of floodwaters.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('03e991b3-fc90-4954-bf5e-3bda5aa034e8','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Organising for the 150th Anniversary celebrations began in February 2023 with an open community brainstorming session. A wide range of community groups were represented there, and small groups discussed ideas for how they would like to see the anniversary celebrated.','Community brainstorming for 150th Anniversary celebrations','Friends of Todmorden Town Hall','2023-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEaZ-xmtk8H4xbmmVRTc10PiCVTLPvMMr-_z6_D7850jPbVoFHgKaV6ENXAsl3K24Z_S-Ilt6e368yvMKPTppNXYcozwbVNuxJKCryocLlPAZp0MO0EbQ-_SbRijeGu_iv1VWEvoA==','The \'Friends of Todmorden Town Hall\' website indicates that organizing for the Town Hall\'s 150th-anniversary celebrations began in February 2023 with an open community brainstorming session, showing early community engagement and planning for future use of the building.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0451f223-f5b8-40b3-9c94-527b6627a86f','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WORK on a scheme to improve cycle and pedestrian links between Bradford city centre and the west of the city entered the next stage this week. Although work on the city centre side of the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway extension began earlier this year, the past week has seen construction start at various other sites along the planned route. [20] Works are now starting to construct the cycleway between the city centre and West Park Road for completion in Autumn 2025. [10]','Work on next stage of West Bradford cycle route begins, targeting autumn 2025 completion for Phase 1','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / West Yorkshire Combined Authority \'Your Voice\'','2024-05-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQECReQIyK77rMRfSbz1ZbdQeVtXK_36I0V-8SqqmOkepPAe7DH11INtptLLTlsOBoDIWTDq9w8jHJNnbInQISnNcesK0WLk4WUSX8YQtol7pq-8Sx1ka9bybhCkkapPvdQfHhcwLKtZMcB5kTpxiQa3HDm_8xgLbyJvNzd-GhK3XPF8s52iAeZk8j6qmVrl_-sOf45gZ4xcOGQFc5JDaPbc5w==','Construction for Phase 1 of the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension has commenced. This phase covers the route from Bradford city centre to West Park Road along Sunbridge Road and Thornton Road, with an estimated cost of £12 million, funded by the Transforming Cities Fund. Completion is anticipated in Autumn 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0487a975-bda0-43f5-b1dd-53d6d06ecbdc','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Challenges and considerations for the combined authority: 1. Financial Implications: The transition to a franchising model involves substantial initial and ongoing costs, including investment in assets such as bus depots and a zero-emission bus fleet. The Combined Authority needs to carefully assess the financial implications and ensure that the model remains economically viable. ... 7. Environmental Impact: Assessing and addressing the environmental impact of franchised services, including considerations for fuel efficiency and emissions reduction, aligns with broader sustainability goals. [8]','West Yorkshire Bus Franchising Consultation 2024 - Bus Users response','Bus Users','2024-01-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG2NpRS55O4v8H8PpN2DHArlSyGM6LjFub7EGC9FnaCsBlGlCVZELLcYBGy7tVHlq_6556gmPqcxIn8JoTPhICWNKfhXeJAc7QK1loefkcshoqbAGLBZk1UhgI7-oBqaJRQonQeRg3AZTxNdGyXB7n1OmCm3_AGtB4Nwe7PyUJnS0ra5aXIg8yn-Q==','Bus Users provided a response to the West Yorkshire Bus Franchising consultation, highlighting various challenges and considerations for the Combined Authority. These included significant financial implications for the transition and ongoing costs, such as investment in bus depots and a zero-emission bus fleet. The response also addressed environmental impact assessments, advocating for fuel efficiency and emissions reduction, and stressed the importance of collaboration with bus operators. [8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('052e9f3b-1bc6-4237-bc53-319cbf36c7b2','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds PIPES is the most significant heat network in Leeds, supplying low carbon heat from the RERF to over 3,000 homes and public buildings. ... LCC has recently completed phase 3 of the Leeds PIPES networks which extends the network by 2.5 km. Phase 3 adds several connections including St James\'s University Hospital, Leonardo/Thoresby student residential accommodation, Old Technology Campus student residential accommodation, and Lovell Park multi storey flats.','Heat Network Zone Opportunity Report - Leeds','GOV.UK','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/heat-network-zone-opportunity-report-leeds','A government report published on GOV.UK, dated February 2025, provides a retrospective look at the Leeds PIPES network\'s development. It states that \'LCC has recently completed phase 3 of the Leeds PIPES networks\' which included \'Lovell Park multi storey flats\' among other connections, serving as an official confirmation of the completion of the connection project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('05400efb-8da4-48ed-89db-b1b0db6bb2a1','infrastructure-west-bradford-junctions-improvement-scheme-a6177-ring-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.879','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The public engagement ran from 23 February 2023 to 22 March 2023. To find out more and view the final report, please visit the Your Voice website. ... This public engagement was open 23rd February - 22nd March 2023. The Engagement Report is available to read here. [2, 12]','Thornton Road / Cemetery Road Junction Public Engagement (2023)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2023-02-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/westbradford2c','A public engagement period for the proposed improvements at the Thornton Road / Cemetery Road junction was held from February 23 to March 22, 2023. This engagement allowed the public to provide feedback on the detailed designs for the junction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0556a465-21c3-408b-b491-5315ecff0bf6','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We will be piloting a week-long, School Streets trial at Golcar Junior, Infant and Nursery School during Road Safety Week. School Streets are a pioneering approach to promoting active travel to school. By closing roads to traffic at the start and end of the school day they tackle both road safety and air quality outside schools. ... Golcar J, I&N school will pilot a time-limited closure (between 30 and 60 minutes) of Manor Road, Golcar, at the start and end of the school day, from Monday 20 November to Friday 25 November.','Kirklees introduces trial for School Streets','Kirklees Council','2023-11-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/news/article/688/kirklees-introduces-trial-for-school-streets','Kirklees Council launched its first week-long School Streets trial at Golcar Junior, Infant and Nursery School from November 20 to 25, 2023, during Road Safety Week. The trial involved a time-limited road closure during school drop-off and pick-up times to assess its impact on road safety, air quality, and active travel, with potential for wider rollout based on evaluation.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('059c80eb-c363-43e6-98da-4185e48f1abc','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Hailed as a game changer for the Yorkshire city of Bradford, One City Park already is attracting national and international names and burgeoning local businesses. The state-of-the-art building has 5,240 square metres of Grade A office space and a striking steel and glass structure, which won it a CoStar Impact Award. The project was delivered by main contractor, Caddick Construction, and was designed with sustainability at its core achieving BREEAM excellent, Wiredscore and Smartscore Gold standard. Year: 2024. Region: Yorkshire and Humber. Award Category: Building Project of the Year.','One City Park Hailed as Bradford\'s Biggest Game-Changer in 20 Years - CoStar / One City Park, Bradford - Constructing Excellence','CoStar News / Constructing Excellence','2024-03-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHZjpsubZ_cQxzW-9QBBT8vXwFfggU3UxIa52wx5ga5qlJshREBZg87wPKRMrquTgMuRUjaz-Z4H4lnQg1U8o-vmBCqBr58-Ay5w2iKA4B-TIrVROf_XHcNQoYz7hRnRjP8j_krIR63udOSaKyQywjJuZtTjcz8Gq-tk0ltr-Pkdn_Pf2xu7Qa6ABsp7S_LSLBw7sC_-PJsgVEN9E5Xb2atV8Fk5Uk=','One City Park has been recognized as a \'game-changing development\' for Bradford, marking the city\'s first purpose-built, high-quality office building in two decades. It received a CoStar Impact Award and was listed in the \'Building Project of the Year\' category for the Constructing Excellence Yorkshire and Humber Awards in 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('05e82f2f-5608-402d-957f-ab51cfb8ed6e','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This strategy sets out our plans to improve EV charging. It will help us to make sure switching to an an EV is an option for more people. ... The information below was presented during the consultation in 2024. Our ambition is to build a network of public electric vehicle (EV) chargepoints in West Yorkshire. We want to install the right chargers in the right places so more people will be able to charge their EV. ... Open (25 July - 11 September 2024) Electric Vehicle Charging for West Yorkshire has finished this stage. [24]','Electric Vehicle Charging for West Yorkshire - Your Voice','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/electric-vehicle-charging-in-west-yorkshire','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s consultation on its EV Infrastructure Strategy and the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme. This regional initiative aims to increase public EV charge points.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('06067a36-ca92-4915-bbe3-f197ba35a10a','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Thousands of households across Wakefield, and throughout West Yorkshire, will benefit from free upgrade work thanks to new funding. ... The upgrade work is part of a programme to reduce energy costs across the region, and will be delivered by a consortium of ten housing providers, and led by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. Work will include measures such as external and internal wall insulation, heat pumps, solar panels, double glazing, roof insulation, and low energy lighting. ... The investment includes £25 million from the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero through the Warm Homes: Social Housing Fund, matched by £25 million from local social housing providers, and an additional £20 million from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','Thousands of households across Wakefield to benefit from free upgrade work to reduce energy costs','Wakefield Express','2025-07-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGezCp3fOlhcYDwuRnDkYOkjWfkGoyfHZUIZBRJmOUC7zV7K6ISAa1i8Pmaqn_bqt-kXrEiSAJuUqPvzJdSghCBbJwlWjiWi9K8rQstDz6fRb54cXpQFV01a6nKkb5tfR3lAZpShVwzF256VqADe8UlLKHjgtHPgInoUIEoNJGvspQ-8_B_ApNk71jf-3eRapRW4h5JcR8LN3UngbvW0JgdCzuoXzWt25JckwmEGhyB-S39yqCQP0BAlhGu1a20EeC1OfuL7iuwuTg62ACaTBtQRQSNOInt2jw=','Thousands of households across Wakefield and West Yorkshire will benefit from free upgrade work, including solar panels, heat pumps, and insulation, through new funding. This programme, led by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and delivered by a consortium of ten housing providers, is part of a regional effort to reduce energy costs and decarbonise homes. It includes £25 million from the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero\'s Warm Homes: Social Housing Fund, matched by housing providers, and an additional £20 million from WYCA. The initiative supports Mayor Tracy Brabin\'s pledge to retrofit social homes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('06331c07-ba7c-4807-8ac8-2fbb08e874c5','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first phase of the Calderdale LCWIP covers: An initial area of cycling network development in Brighouse; A Core Walking Zone in Halifax; and Lists of potential infrastructure improvements for walking and cycling. The report was published in November 2019. [19]','Calderdale Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan: Phase 1 Final Report','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/media/3119/calderdale-lcwip-phase-1-final-report.pdf','This plan, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, identifies priority areas for cycling and walking infrastructure improvements, including a focus on Brighouse. While not exclusively \'minor traffic\', these schemes often involve traffic calming, parking management, and improved facilities for active travel, contributing to overall traffic and parking improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('06ac4d77-5cf7-4d34-864f-90ff01aa90e5','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In December 2015, the project team achieved one of the road\'s biggest challenges, with the installation of a 1200 tonne traffic bridge underneath the railway lines serving Wakefield Kirkgate Station, near to the Eastmoor estate. The 56-hour round-the-clock operation was a major feat of engineering (Source 2). Leca LWA was specified for the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road, including the construction of a rail bridge over a new road and the need to be completed within a 56 hour window over the Christmas period (Source 12).','Major Engineering Feat: Rail Bridge Installation for WERR','Wakefield Council / Hochtief UK / LECA','2015-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGyqfWepC837q9ssuut_fY0uILeNrLvgYdUHH0iMuKM2KIUsTINQM7_V1gFM6oQdQ8bBxeAUIeUDjLq5uDNA8y5DJHXBFQbbeHjGvsPstPvKy0MDUrLCGdTY2-3D1Ikpd4nnck7ElP8dOvjUfklVsbqMcstTm3-_BZVkbvzqazLaaqVG08JmLLaczyqyocSets1leKub1CF46VOOf3mCuDZUUlC_8Xhzw=','In December 2015, a significant engineering challenge for the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road was completed with the installation of a 1200-tonne traffic bridge beneath railway lines near Wakefield Kirkgate Station. This 56-hour operation was a key component of the project\'s construction, ensuring the railway lines could reopen after the Christmas bank holidays.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('07048e6e-0b90-466c-b5ab-52cfa47349e4','infrastructure-halifax-future-high-streets-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.256','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Sowerby Bridge is set to benefit from a share of £95m of government funding to improve its historic high streets. ... The initiative will be funded by combining £40 million from the Department for Digital, Culture Media and Sport\'s Heritage High Street Fund with £52 million from the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government\'s Future High Street Fund.','Calderdale town to get share of £95m to revive its historic high street','Halifax Courier','2019-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGKU-26kQbyBpL1zh6_lFmrjlzsJT87TczwDB7bOStZJf84R6OLj18qBPj3ePJ_p6qR1FkfhXM4QUohsHwMYD2fFhvFWXA-CTWOoV2FiGcq_MS-yyY6RvCcFN8qVklC_u-pPbwFPDzenE91UIjXM_W2V59IAJk1f_MMVJdVJNMzBn6Y1roqm5VjTrag1jdwAJq8Wr-fEifhKqPXKHECzsoqtaRZ72EhXu6iTNMbpwQmBTsMPGSwgjKa','An announcement of £95 million government funding for high streets across England, combining the Heritage High Street Fund and the Future High Street Fund. While Sowerby Bridge is specifically mentioned, this article provides the broader context of the Future High Streets Fund that Halifax later benefited from.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('076b72ac-b5b8-4b2d-8637-85950687f9c8','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Northern Trains announced on January 13, 2025, that it is ready to welcome millions to Bradford for the 2025 UK City of Culture celebrations, having made station improvements. The entrance to Bradford Interchange has been upgraded by West Yorkshire Combined Authority as part of a multi-million-pound project to create a new gateway to the city. The taxi rank was replaced by a seating area with colourful panelling, and the ramp leading up to the station has been repaved. Northern and ISS also undertook a deep clean and repainted the inside of the station, installed artwork and posters, refreshed floral displays, and repainted waiting rooms.','Northern ready to welcome millions to Bradford for UK City of Culture celebrations after making station improvements','Northern Trains Limited','2025-01-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGwn2GBepRIJmst321ogLNKrVFChWYHjspSkA_Wiu8wvzBH9_DH2sIGeYYtIgoqJ5evPy2sAS9bla62FU4RmeIwkrneMwYpUYpB1x9F1cG-0x4EsVAZGJG12E6hqdP_wdzzM-vzgxc1-kvJ_qsxcGsLHtafz_ih1w3MOiM9ghf3g49AfUSKQapUxzqp2S60fy9ifFhZjvNiALCvWn4oBbSAf2DpBzms-Bwtpzkwb7QC2_zOhr_J4Lk5O8qMHkgtXnblQ8gaQ2TJrptcZ184uDjS4qV8PJWx-Qro','Northern Trains announced that improvements at Bradford Interchange have been made as part of a multi-million-pound project to create a new gateway to the city, in preparation for Bradford UK City of Culture 2025. The upgrades include a transformed entrance, replacement of the taxi rank with seating, repaved access ramp, deep cleaning, and new artwork inside the station.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('07abca50-b6ec-42b3-963e-e63b1d7e53ad','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Previous work undertaken for WYCA has shown that there no option to serve LBA directly by conventional rail that is considered feasible in engineering terms. That work did, however, identify a potential tram-train link to the Airport from a point north of Horsforth station on the existing Leeds to Harrogate railway line. The same work also showed that a tram-train link from the Airport to Bradford was not feasible in engineering terms. [31]','Leeds City Region Metro: Final Report - Tram-Train to LBA (feasibility)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA)','2016-08-01 00:00:00.000',NULL,'A report by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) on the Leeds City Region Metro project identified a potential tram-train link to Leeds Bradford Airport from north of Horsforth station. However, crucially, the same work concluded that a tram-train link from the Airport directly to Bradford was *not feasible* in engineering terms. This indicates a significant hurdle or abandonment of the direct Bradford-LBA tram-train idea by WYCA at this point.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('07b59c54-66ff-48b0-b7b4-ac1d27fb1a57','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In October 2023 the previous Government announced a £2bn investment for a brand-new rail station and through line connection for Bradford to give a 30 minute journey to Manchester via Huddersfield. This is on top of £500m already committed to improve rail connectivity between Bradford and Leeds. Alongside this investment, the Government also committed £2.5bn for the new West Yorkshire Mass Transit system, improving connections between Leeds and Bradford. ... Source: Department for Transport Press Release, January 2024. \'THE KING\'S CROSS OF THE NORTH\'.','Consolidated Funding and \'King\'s Cross of the North\' Vision for Bradford Southern Gateway','Invest in Bradford / Department for Transport','2024-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHty4zAHMC_YtHnQAIR9uLHwy4HydzEo88nEe-d2FOvg5gtjpL29TVnzqT3QZvgBRvFizBNsm-GjIVcd5uLbpGOmiVSky3D60aJLaJCUJNjx0miY3DlIWeV95do0IK3JhBvB1iNxzvaOvfsJvQUg9QLq7mkcRp_mUy0B3aoClH1E9nUgyC3n7E2p2eBYqliNA==','An Invest in Bradford document highlighted several key government funding commitments for the Southern Gateway, including the £2 billion for a new rail station, £500 million for improved Bradford-Leeds rail connectivity, and £2.5 billion for the new West Yorkshire Mass Transit system. It also cited a Department for Transport Press Release from January 2024 which referred to the new station as \'THE KING\'S CROSS OF THE NORTH\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('07d8f445-0ac3-4472-9dbe-e5eacb54a6c9','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This Order is made by Kirklees Council (\"the authority\") under Section 257 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 because it is satisfied that an application for planning permission (ref: 2023/93805) has been made under Part III of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 in respect of development of an Integrated Constructed Wetland (ICW), motor control centre kiosk, wetland outfall weir and associated ancillary plant for operational improvements to Clayton West Waste Water Treatment WwTW Works (WwTW) and if the application were granted it would be necessary to authorise the diversion in order to enable the development to be carried out.','Kirklees Council (Public Footpath Denby Dale 13 (Part) at Land Off Public Bridleway Denby Dale 15, Clayton West Public Path Diversion Order 2024)','Kirklees Council','2024-07-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE2HUa0m9MnX2lVZ0Zr3-9KB3p0Os378xmBE7d7kkHfRU1izMWuAtdN3P1LxYkngQb2eiGNCqBV49Jokr1rIdgsLAIG-oosMPi0AYymBJ6Dn1sTwIi5hsP_o270MzgHkJAehmQEFceyTFNKyR1ZNrcbjfr0DoyACRfFSl2CXPFURUTRIS6WklApG9QQkOvAv8kEkFYgM_Qkf7Lhy4eC8aXJ','Kirklees Council issued a public path diversion order on July 16, 2024, to divert a public footpath at Clayton West. This order was made under the Town and Country Planning Act 1990, as a planning application (ref: 2023/93805) had been made for the development of an Integrated Constructed Wetland (ICW), motor control centre kiosk, wetland outfall weir, and associated plant for operational improvements to Clayton West Wastewater Treatment Works, necessitating the diversion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('08263390-894e-47e6-bc4a-5002e91f2537','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In Cleckheaton, there are proposals to improve connection to the Spen Valley Greenway with a new ramp, as well as improving lighting under the bridge and converting a small section of the Crown Street car park into a pocket park. The active travel proposals in Cleckheaton also include improving connection to the Spen Valley Greenway. The consultation for Kirklees starts on Tuesday, April 1, and will last for six weeks.','Proposal to convert section of Cleckheaton car park into a pocket park as part of £5.1m active travel plans across West Yorkshire - Dewsbury Reporter','Dewsbury Reporter','2025-03-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.dewsburyreporter.co.uk/news/politics/council/proposal-to-convert-section-of-cleckheaton-car-park-into-a-pocket-park-as-part-of-ps51m-active-travel-plans-across-west-yorkshire-4564887','This article outlines proposals within the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s £5.1 million active travel plans, specifically for Cleckheaton. These include improving the connection to the Spen Valley Greenway with a new ramp, enhancing lighting under the bridge, and transforming a portion of the Crown Street car park into a pocket park. Public consultation for these plans in Kirklees began on April 1, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0859d872-4cd8-4d65-9f2e-35498f37fc05','infrastructure-bus-lane-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.094','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In early 2026, we will bring in this type of camera enforcement at seven key locations. This initiative: aligns with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) Bus Service Improvement Plan (BSIP); and contributes to our climate and transport strategies. ... Locations/sites. (A629) Skircoat Road, Halifax. (inbound), ... (A629) Huddersfield Road, Halifax. (inbound), ... (A629) Huddersfield Road, Halifax. (outbound), ... (A646) Burnley Road, Trimmingham. (eastbound), ... (A646) King Cross Road, Halifax. (eastbound), ... (A646) King Cross Road, Halifax. (westbound), ... Wade Street, Halifax. (westbound).','Bus Lane Enforcement in Calderdale: Early 2026 Implementation Announced','Calderdale Council','2025-09-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/parking/bus-lane-enforcement','Calderdale Council announced plans to implement Automatic Number Plate Recognition (ANPR) camera enforcement at seven key bus lane locations across the district in early 2026. This initiative aligns with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Bus Service Improvement Plan (BSIP) and aims to enhance bus journey times, reliability, and contribute to climate and transport strategies. Locations include sections of A629 Skircoat Road, A629 Huddersfield Road, A646 Burnley Road (Trimmingham), A646 King Cross Road, and Wade Street, all in Halifax.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('087d3798-9157-41d4-89ac-39167ae688ae','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The consultancy will create the masterplan for the new district, which will double the size of the city centre. Located to the south of the city and bordered by Manchester Road and Leeds Road, the vision currently includes ECF\'s City Village, which will see around 900 city centre homes built across Chain Street, Oastler, and Kirkgate. The final phase of public consultation on phase one is underway, with work expected to start next spring. Other plans for the Southern Gateway site include £4.5bn of transport upgrades, including a new railway station and Mass Transit, a new CBD, more housing, public realm, and green spaces.','Arup to Create Masterplan for Bradford Southern Gateway, Including City Village','Place Yorkshire','2025-05-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEXbOcholI-SUT2ewc8DQuQQyX_PXCK-AIfXZoMWJ7FFAIqjl6NzSqZnftXyv8gSfLBe70294L5Pq--ngZUMqbULcyb7_FBNKyiT_R6sxGJzj2oracfLCEca8sqm9Jz7H1lW6AYq1QZQ-eVbKAd5wlRYs_yXqK24LMvyV7brd7sjNaeqIhL98U=','This report reaffirmed Arup\'s role in developing the masterplan. It highlighted that the Southern Gateway\'s vision incorporates ECF\'s City Village, which plans for around 900 new city centre homes across Chain Street, Oastler, and Kirkgate. The final phase of public consultation for City Village phase one is underway, with construction expected to start in spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('08e12246-b57e-429d-bd14-0ab339f03906','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This report contains outputs from the Heat Network Zoning Pilot Programme. Leeds PIPES is the most significant heat network in Leeds, supplying low carbon heat from the RERF to over 3,000 homes and public buildings. The scheme has been developed by Vital Energi in phases since 2018 with 26.5 km of heat network pipe installed to date and over £47m of capital investment. LCC has recently completed phase 3 of the Leeds PIPES networks which extends the network by 2.5 km. The report highlights the ambition for continued growth and the strategic importance of district heating in Leeds.','Heat Network Zone Opportunity Report - Leeds','GOV.UK','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/65bc579f1504930018d96076/heat-network-zone-opportunity-report-leeds.pdf','This GOV.UK report, produced by Arup in partnership with Leeds City Council, outlines the existing and planned heat networks in Leeds. It mentions the completion of Phase 3 of Leeds PIPES and future expansion plans, providing a strategic overview of the network\'s development and the policy context for connections like Spinner\'s Yard.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('097bdd32-91d5-48f7-9a32-267f3fd809b0','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Services at Halifax Bus Station are set to change from later this month (February) as work progresses on a new £17.7 million state-of-the-art facility delivered by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority in partnership with Calderdale Council. Alongside improved passenger facilities and better access to the town centre, plans for the new station include environmentally friendly features, such as measures to enable the future introduction of electric bus charging points, bike parking and solar panels, a living roof complete with plants, and a water storage tank to manage the flow of rainwater in a storm. Overall, the scheme will deliver more green space as well as other environmental benefits. [25]','Changes to services at Halifax Bus Station as work progresses on new £17.7 million state-of-the-art facility','Calderdale Council News Centre','2022-02-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGoE0V9HeM2COV25SKkH00OGfUVi5nBfZi8NHUd20r7-zMfcrLHJpjGgM_5TWZ8f6_CLvSniaUA2MAbE70k2QVz2OHjmR6vOBhM71rxES2O5L-R_zKc9yj8_mVvsFTvqu20flDI9T2GgudZz4w1xfGT6sPduC8V5jze2bHw7ve-4parP8iHGEb_iKE3mfOedlHaP-ElVUw1m6d3DoBu-BGRH_zelgtKxyDMcRbgpZE6_gIwE24HndAJZxR9wLc2jX-9XxAW_YO0IA==','An update on the progress of the £17.7 million Halifax Bus Station redevelopment was released, announcing changes to services from February 27, 2022. This demonstrates ongoing work at the trail\'s starting location, delivered by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0987c896-3bd5-4bb8-a600-f59bc7107a3d','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme provided £553m in government grants to 160 public sector organisations across the country to install 217 clean heat and energy efficiency projects. ... Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme opened for applications at 2pm on Wednesday 6 October 2021, with scheme guidance published on Wednesday 8 September 2021. The Application Portal closed four weeks later at 2pm on Wednesday 3 November 2021.','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme - Salix Finance','Salix Finance','2021-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.salixfinance.co.uk/schemes/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme','Salix Finance, the delivery body for the PSDS, provides an overview of Phase 3a. It notes that the scheme provided £553m in government grants to 160 public sector organisations for 217 clean heat and energy efficiency projects. It also specifies the application window for Phase 3a, which opened on 6 October 2021 and closed on 3 November 2021.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0989f814-c19c-46e6-8913-ce180d0cb868','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Platforms 1 and 2 at Huddersfield station have been demolished during the first half of a 30-day closure. GB Railfreight steps up preparations for Network Rail seasonal trainsGB Railfreight has been stepping up its preparations for operating Network Rail\'s autumn and winter treatment trains. [19]','Platforms demolished as Network Rail provides Huddersfield station update','Railnews','2025-09-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.railnews.co.uk/news/2025/09/15-platforms-demolished-as-network.html','Network Rail confirmed that Platforms 1 and 2 at Huddersfield station have been demolished during the first half of a 30-day closure. This work is a key part of the larger Transpennine Route Upgrade (TRU) at Huddersfield Rail Station, which aims to improve the station\'s capacity and infrastructure, complementing the public realm enhancements of the \'Connections\' project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('09a20821-f9cd-4efe-b5e5-850c5fb758ce','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The infrastructure and the main A646 road in particular is constricted by the landscape topography with river, canal, railway and road all crammed into the narrow corridor through the Pennines know as the Upper Calder Valley. Construction and residential access to the site between Bridge Lanes and Heptonstall Road would exacerbate the problems of a bad road junction. Drivers often get stuck in the junction box because of poor sight lines, as the junction is formed on the crest of a hill on the congested A646 road. The turning circle for Heptonstall traffic currently cannot cope with the volume of traffic for Heptonstall at peak times, as the cars queue back onto the main A646 road. The poor sight lines to the steep approaches to the Heptonstall Road junction with the A646 also present a safety hazard for access to the site at a constricted junction.','Local Plan Initial Draft 2017 - LP0920 Land at Heptonstall Road/Albion Terrace, Hebden Bridge','Calderdale Council','2017-10-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGUvmvT4SQjQaQCOGe3X34gqlRMcbW2gEPWW8wJ1iJWFEk1yuFsWZLRNiDnQo9ET_Py6bshjcpqbUVMs7KeYoPeoqfeOkDqEXi6lbTrhYhrfWcsT8eQhg9hO4dOBJCQ5XYBzo-CJXusXC3huM1VZ0h897_B_OlYr5-qEpqyQjciQcqgnHpRnxKNyCzGtDGlwVeqWg_syGl43efR7OeKe_XFoxz7O_pkp6xGqcEbrDvCvBh4P7AVfPSpOEG4u1U__P3mqDTfxhoWnyS9xikk4QpncMiNYjklEinWJYTCLomG','The Calderdale Local Plan Initial Draft from 2017 identifies existing traffic and safety issues at the Heptonstall Road junction with the A646 in Hebden Bridge. It highlights concerns about congestion, poor sight lines, and the junction\'s inability to cope with traffic volume, particularly if new residential developments were to proceed nearby. This document serves as evidence of the recognized need for improvements at this junction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('09beab55-3deb-47fc-8f97-6051528b7af6','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The A650 Connect project is made up of two Bradford Council projects, one covering Tong Street and the other covering Wakefield Road. The projects have different funding sources, with Tong Street being funded primarily by the central government\'s Major Route Network fund and supported by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Plus Transport Fund. Subject to successful business case approval, the Wakefield Road section would be funded by the Combined Authority\'s City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS). The Tong Street section of the project is forecast to cost £25m... The Wakefield Road section of the route is expected to cost £20m... Across the whole route: Cycle Paths: A two-way cycle path along the route with a protective buffer separating it from the road... Improved Bus Stops: Upgraded shelters with seating, lighting and CCTV... Enhanced Crossings: Road-level toucan crossings and priority for pedestrians and cyclists at side roads... Better Footpaths... Wakefield Road only: Bus Lanes: Dedicated bus lanes in both directions... Subway Removal: Filling in subways... Tong Street only: Road Widening: Making space for two lanes of traffic in each direction... [6]','FAQs | A650 Connect: Wakefield Road / Tong Street | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a650connect/faqs','This FAQ page provides detailed information about the A650 Connect project during its public consultation. It clarifies the funding structure, stating the Tong Street section is forecast to cost £25m (from Major Route Network fund and Plus Transport Fund) and the Wakefield Road section £20m (from City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement). It outlines proposed improvements including cycle paths, upgraded bus stops, enhanced crossings, and better footpaths, with specific measures for each road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('09dc132a-f72d-445e-aed8-9ab1821a1809','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'June 2023. We\'ve started work at the Heptonstall Road junction in Hebden Bridge. Here we are widening the footways on the southern side of Bridge Lanes and outside the Fox and Goose and making improvements to crossing facilities.','A58/A672 and A646/A6033 improvements progress report','Calderdale Next Chapter','2023-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHt9jRj4p40DzrMTD35LQNXxVgzFxzIjWj48QtPc-DsZt1Zk2ew_zrp3aTT3bNUh10_RmEVRd1aUrswW7lLKuC_jFptdOBazSnX5GjmFfkPJow84GR9oUxx1cGnPpGZcXcIUFrkJAE8oq7B6t84zmhbk7PTn1IAvpJ_1UK7aBRfUp2LPb5C8C0-yJ86sMG','A progress report from Calderdale Council confirms that work started in June 2023 at the Heptonstall Road junction in Hebden Bridge. The work involves widening the footways on the southern side of Bridge Lanes and outside the Fox and Goose pub, as well as making improvements to crossing facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0a49b617-35d0-4549-8a2b-8a89939fa516','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Our Flood Action Plan sets out the actions that we will take to recover from past floods, reduce the impact of flooding and build resilience for future events. The Plan, initially published in October 2016, is a dynamic \'living document\' that has undergone multiple updates to incorporate completed, revised, and new actions. It is continuously monitored and updated by the Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Board to ensure it remains effective and relevant. View the refreshed Flood Action Plan. Key Areas Covered in the Plan. The Plan outlines a comprehensive programme of work designed to help our area recover from past floods, improve resilience, and reduce the risk of future flooding. It focuses on four key areas: Strengthening Defences: Implementing projects and schemes to reduce flooding from rivers and surface water. Resilient Infrastructure: Reinforcing our infrastructure, such as sewer systems, electricity substations, and transport routes. Natural Flood Management: Managing the landscape to slow down the flow of water. Community Resilience: Collaborating with the community to help them prepare for and recover from flooding.','Calderdale Flood Action Plan Published','Eye on Calderdale - Calderdale Flood Action Plan','2016-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHiKSU9YJ4XPXDxU2DiqWRs3i7f7mCAhRhvtUNCHL8fWytFCf4EEcCREy4CbH9x_HCC7I5hMtmNjb-nNabf6jrouMteoUWFHMz5zztUFOlgr9vbOH-fPjS3iqgtP1I1jNgwRgxpn6o8cKAoM=','The Calderdale Flood Action Plan, a comprehensive \'living document\' to guide flood recovery, resilience, and risk reduction efforts, was initially published in October 2016. It outlines actions across four key areas: Strengthening Defences, Resilient Infrastructure, Natural Flood Management, and Community Resilience, and is continuously updated.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0a51dd3b-56f7-40c9-a0b8-6a15195e1819','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-weaver-network',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.799','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In summer 2024, almost 5000 people had their say in our Mass Transit route options consultation. We asked for your views on 10 route options, which would see a tram linking Leeds and Bradford and from south Leeds to the city centre. View the full outcome report. [4]','Mass Transit Route Options Public Consultation','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/getting-here/mass-transit/','In summer 2024, nearly 5,000 individuals and organizations provided their feedback during a public consultation on 10 proposed tram route options for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system. These options were designed to connect communities between Bradford and Leeds, and from south Leeds to the city centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0a83221f-ef24-4254-98fb-dde62c4a90c0','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A meeting of West Yorkshire Combined Authority today agreed to progress plans for the £12.8m A638 Dewsbury/Cleckheaton Sustainable Travel corridor.','Major transport scheme, including safety boost for Greenway, moves ahead | Bradford Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2022-06-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/20202682.major-transport-scheme-including-safety-boost-greenway-moves-ahead/','A meeting of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on June 8, 2022, approved the progression of plans for the £12.8 million A638 Dewsbury/Cleckheaton Sustainable Travel Corridor. This larger scheme includes significant upgrades to the Spen Valley Greenway, such as widening, resurfacing, and improved lighting, aimed at boosting active travel options in the area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0ad8ec45-a6d4-4975-a86e-6625c5a3aced','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'NEW \'mobility hubs\' could be built in Bradford and other West Yorkshire areas as part of a push to reduce the number of cars on the region\'s roads. The hubs... make up part of West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \"Future Mobility Strategy\" - a push to develop state of the art public transport that is easier to use. A recent report by the Authority said the plan is for a number of hubs to be developed in West Yorkshire in the coming years. There are four trial sites \"currently in development\" and funding bids are being prepared for another ten, although locations have yet to be decided. ... The strategy aims to have a \"wider rollout\" of hubs within the next five years.','Bradford could get new \'mobility hubs\' within five years - Telegraph and Argus','Telegraph and Argus','2021-11-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHuf4EBXNPkhCKLHPVeEFIMT9YhrM4QPcot9HvOXr14M7U1HK2jK-DAMKcAVXDjJMPimKuxVrrsaPI3pWzx-zncumRD9LKHdsAjmhUyL267i0gAGt-uXuqEN8T_6OdZr4-NOW4ea9OzvMGgc_Nz8yTf882Sk3VE_0zCkhj8c-wFw6JgX-BDSBIoZV0iSbHQqVR4dh-ojsWF3VYBqNh-apfQNA==','A news article discussing the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \"Future Mobility Strategy,\" which aims to introduce new mobility hubs across West Yorkshire, including Bradford, within five years to reduce car reliance. It mentions four trial sites in development and funding bids for ten more, without specifying locations. The strategy references a Vienna hub as an example of the kind of facility envisioned, integrating various travel methods like bike storage, car hire, cafes, and delivery lockers at bus, rail, or tram stops.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0b8bc423-6084-4ca2-99bd-535c6f29994a','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme has been in place since the flood events in 2012. It brings together a range of partners that include: Calderdale Council; Environment Agency; Canal and River Trust; Local Flood groups; Yorkshire Water; Network Rail; the voluntary sector and others. Its aim is to reduce the impact of flooding in Calderdale. Also, it is to work with local communities to build resilience against future events. The delivery of the programme is overseen by a Programme Board, which is chaired by the Calderdale Council Leader. [2, 3]','Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme established after 2012 floods','Calderdale Council, Eye on Calderdale','2012-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/environment-and-planning/flooding/calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme','The Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme was established following significant flood events in 2012. Its primary goal is to mitigate the impact of flooding across Calderdale and enhance the region\'s resilience against future flood incidents. The programme operates through a partnership model, involving key stakeholders such as Calderdale Council, the Environment Agency, Canal and River Trust, local flood groups, Yorkshire Water, and Network Rail. [2, 3]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0b910ab7-d28a-4a45-a9ff-109c72d8c311','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-enquire-learning-trust-buckingham-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.379','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3a opened for applications on 6 October 2021 and closed on 3 November 2021. [4]','PSDS Phase 3a Application Window Opens','Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: Phase 3a Summary Report - GOV.UK','2021-10-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGSC2f-QxnHD5kNvAJ8jiuIvfYYO1n8votI51kklSdYVtPcDJFxvYoSOrNlX2yCoMZIkA1VGhzbRbKZl1_eTKXgoFDXMYdRTWKiMXPR8jBiSsLnpEtJYZPGvYJk89hgrOEjjSPr5LjHMDjdaQRz3ms1RAdJAtWQuPeuu52r02K48mtCS6XQ_r4P0T34nBGQ28c6QAiPdyRYE4WY4Lcnua2bpauH','Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS) officially opened for applications on 6 October 2021. This was the period during which organisations like Enquire Learning Trust would have submitted their proposals for decarbonisation projects.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0b999bec-53c3-4ba4-a2f9-978e5c82da53','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-weaver-network',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.799','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million for ongoing detailed planning and development work on Mass Transit, which will see a line run through West Leeds. ... At a full Combined Authority meeting on September 18, West Yorkshire council leaders will hear how the extra £40 million of funding would support key works to keep the Mass Transit project on track for spades in the ground by 2028. The work will include further technical and environmental assessments on phase one tram route options, as well as progressing the business case and preparing the plans to go before government decision-makers in the coming years. [5, 6, 9, 10]','Proposed £40 Million for Detailed Mass Transit Planning Set for Approval','West Leeds Dispatch / Yorkshire Evening Post','2025-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.westleedsdispatch.com/mass-transit-detailed-planning-and-development-to-keep-mass-transit-on-track-for-2028-start/','Regional decision-makers are poised to approve an additional £40 million in funding for the ongoing detailed planning and development work on the Mass Transit system and bus franchising. This investment will support further technical and environmental assessments for phase one tram route options and help keep the project on track for a 2028 construction start.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0b9ee24f-4b19-4868-867e-702c1ede7bd8','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Hundreds of Leeds homeowners, renters, and landlords of properties without gas central heating can now get energy saving green measures installed free of charge or at a significant discount, thanks to a new Leeds City Council scheme. The council\'s Home Energy Help team is working in partnership with energy services provider Everwarm Ltd to help as many households as possible benefit from £15.5 million of government funding secured for Leeds homes from the Home Upgrade Grant, before it expires in March 2025. [16]','Council launches new scheme to help Leeds residents cut energy bills (Home Upgrade Grant)','Leeds City Council','2024-01-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEt8rkBogoVddBWEU2WjuslcCuutBtbnF6FmOSCwxcg2CP86N9Epe24tVuS5XOZWDrcFB_psJAEk0Ju38bQ1xT3THGap8OCzXk8WcsMIye8wqrOgMD9Fk15YIlhcyXt5qTPMdbxu5qcd6wNG_DNMPgG932QDEIRl-wkOJSVb7LLrITpA441Opi0Vc8A6oWlUJaETdktecyxLuBaK7S2eg==','Leeds City Council launched a new scheme on January 3, 2024, in partnership with Everwarm Ltd, making £15.5 million of government funding available through the Home Upgrade Grant. This scheme provides free or significantly discounted energy-saving measures (insulation, heat pumps, solar panels, electric radiators) for homeowners, renters, and landlords of off-gas properties in Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0bf5ed5c-e441-4b2c-803c-69748b4fc28a','infrastructure-pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.548','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We were awarded £2.7m of grant funding for rooftop solar at Pinderfields. Once implemented in March 2026, the annual solar output will equate to just over 200 tonnes of CO2 equivalent in terms of carbon reductions. [12]','MY Community Promise (Project Completion Target)','Mid Yorkshire Teaching NHS Trust','2026-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://www.midyorks.nhs.uk/about-us/my-community-promise','The Mid Yorkshire Teaching NHS Trust\'s \'MY Community Promise\' document indicates that the £2.7m grant funding for rooftop solar at Pinderfields, once implemented, is targeted for completion within the 2025/26 financial year, equating to March 2026. This project aims for annual carbon reductions of over 200 tonnes of CO2 equivalent.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0c200e55-ecfb-4081-b3c7-b65582164010','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'1 & 3 South Brook Street at Vastint UK\'s Aire Park have achieved an \'Excellent\' BREEAM rating, marking a major milestone in the delivery of sustainable commercial space in the heart of Leeds. The buildings - the first to be delivered in the city\'s newest commercial district - comprise 220,000 sq ft Grade A office and retail space. Designed with ESG and resilience at their core, the certification joins a growing collection of sustainability accreditations for the buildings, including EPC A and WELL Platinum. [18, 23]','Aire Park\'s First Commercial Buildings Achieve BREEAM \'Excellent\' Rating','Vastint UK / Aire Park','2025-08-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEhc_NI2ezpW5RwQGyIZnlSiLX4yw4sBTHPX4nnoYjL3vG4rP6yKqk66NXBQIJ-5k3vxybm7N3V5GTu3jHcH_ESfcqGHrJREFlcHA4eEoTSwFhwi-xhSCgzQgbNIYIDcTm-ujCLOiDH_gWRhmaRCkgTQL78JmrrgvPct2mVcCrgVMnQIK2lzr6w6W0dqgaM8BhSmb2kt4fS [18], https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEvdclN4PiMTJ-VASJoQJFPTsb8TJog1rvYk9FhyvSQb464fOXvij3QpqJCKyGoypUew8uu8F2bPvRQQ3un-C1K7j_Hc-3JcmBAgWBxuzpuh5VrIlEBJifP3PrEEtrXGn7fe2dkC5k2FzasiCc0sV63fOUAH-92zaIAPkefHXjX88Dja4qP0rN4pGhT7Ah2 [23]','1 & 3 South Brook Street, Aire Park\'s first delivered commercial buildings, achieved a BREEAM \'Excellent\' rating. This significant environmental accreditation highlights the development\'s commitment to sustainability, energy and water efficiency, responsible construction, and occupier well-being, complementing their EPC A and WELL Platinum certifications.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0c4ed87f-a6ec-4446-a3fa-ff67de3eddaa','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A case study published by West Yorkshire Combined Authority highlighted Platform 1, a mental health charity in Huddersfield, which received £4,800 from the UKSPF Digital Capital Gains fund. This grant, facilitated by Kirklees Council\'s digital inclusion team, allowed Platform 1 to acquire tablets for loan, enabling remote counselling and greater accessibility for their service users.','Empowering mental health support through digital inclusion: Platform 1 case study','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-01-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/economy-projects/digital/digital-inclusion/platform-1/','Platform 1, a mental health charity in Huddersfield, successfully secured a £4,800 grant through the UKSPF Digital Capital Gains fund, with support from Kirklees Council\'s digital inclusion team. This funding enabled them to purchase tablets for loan to service users, facilitating online counselling sessions and improving access to vital support for individuals facing mobility or mental health challenges.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0d53a4c0-718c-45a2-99b4-080d83d8fa9c','infrastructure-west-bradford-junctions-improvement-scheme-a6177-ring-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.879','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2019-02-18) A NEW road, introducing one way systems and adding new traffic lights are some of the changes proposed as part of a £14 million project to improve some of the city\'s worst Junction. ... More details of those plans have now been revealed – and the public are being asked to have their say on the proposals. The West Bradford Junctions Improvement Scheme is being fully funded by the Authority, and work is expected to start early next year. The three junctions being targeted by the scheme are Great Horton Road/Horton Grange Road, Toller Lane/Whetley Hill and Thornton Road/Cemetery Road. ... Although work could start next year, the Authority has said: “Due to the size and complexity of the proposed works the improvements may be introduced in phases and it is expected that all schemes will be delivered by 2022.” [5]','Full details of £14 million plan for West Bradford Junctions Improvement Scheme revealed','Telegraph & Argus','2019-02-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/17441589.full-details-14-million-plan-cut-congestion-three-bradford-junctions-revealed/','Detailed plans for the £14 million West Bradford Junctions Improvement Scheme were revealed. This included specific proposals for the Great Horton Road/Horton Grange Road, Toller Lane/Whetley Hill, and Thornton Road/Cemetery Road junctions, aiming to reduce congestion, improve journey times, and enhance road safety. Work was expected to start early 2020 and complete by early 2022. The scheme is funded by the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0daa0d64-8301-429f-873c-e84692ce3b81','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council is set to approve its new Transport Strategy which aims to put active travel – walking, cycling or wheeling – and public transport at its heart. The council\'s Cabinet is today (Tuesday September 9) expected to approve the document which outlines the council\'s aims for transport across the district. Huddersfield\'s public transport infrastructure is currently seeing major investment through the TransPennine Route Upgrade, a new £70 million Huddersfield Railway Station and the new £27 million Huddersfield Bus Station. Meanwhile, West Yorkshire\'s bus service is being brought back under public control by the Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin (below). It is hoped that will make for more reliable services and improved routes. The council wants a “joined-up network” so that people can “choose what they consider is the most suitable mode of travel” for their journey. They want people to have “multiple transport choices over and above the private car.” Clr Moses Crook, deputy council leader and Cabinet member for housing and transport, said: “Kirklees is currently undergoing some major investment in our towns, and it is essential we develop a transport network that reflects the needs of everyone who lives and works here. “It\'s an exciting time for transport across the district as we invest in our bus and rail stations, cycle provision, footways and much more. “We are committed to improving links between our towns and villages, creating more opportunities for people whilst addressing our environmental, social and economic priorities.” [16]','New Transport Strategy for Kirklees aims to give people the option to leave the car at home','Huddersfield Hub','2025-09-09 00:00:00.000','https://huddersfieldhub.co.uk/new-transport-strategy-for-kirklees-aims-to-give-people-the-option-to-leave-the-car-at-home/','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet was set to approve a new Transport Strategy emphasizing active travel and public transport. The strategy highlights ongoing major investments in Huddersfield\'s transport infrastructure, including the TransPennine Route Upgrade, a new £70 million Huddersfield Railway Station, and the new £27 million Huddersfield Bus Station, all of which contribute to the broader goals of improved connectivity and reduced car reliance that the \'Connections\' project supports.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0e2b7c42-1818-47da-a3f1-f672e4d710ad','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Vastint UK has received planning permission for the first homes at Aire Park, at the heart of Leeds South Bank. The approved plans will see the development of 418 build to rent homes across seven buildings on the corner of Crown Point Road and Bowman Lane. Featuring a mix of studio, one, two and three-bedroom apartments, the new buildings also include 44 affordable homes which will be the first to be delivered by the developer. [24] Councillors on the City Plans Panel approved planning permission for the first residential blocks at Aire Park, the development on the former Tetley brewery site, at the meeting on 13 March 2025. [25]','Planning Permission Granted for First Residential Buildings (418 Homes)','Vastint UK / South Leeds Life','2025-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFDQ4QD4eWq59147iLTKx-xD9ZZei8wVbLfRNqyC1OUpn5BWCuko3KrZLjI6QxhRUj32jVa4LgjZygOUXZkNYfHhkwSThkJ8VdNLKxySN0wsgi8dC2327DZli1MJmgLCmXv2SRp1llcwBoGiDBRHQ8mYA5VRw7GCfKrLRVNp-kobhVpBDGz5LBJJIxThWIiNscj0KMJ [24], https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFYoca-jLAMQAjKu5utymwqbaNKjHZXfp3zyedAWI5AiEaE5fWPQsHrJCM2hLhzuBE8nk6t4Z1EwjdzT_EtRbiLWltnx_Q9gOQzzEj2JXhDq_wapEjINTDqsgued9feuKPncf2H0clKe7IsCQBIyctZWz2Nmdvz8qOrn15Qu5mpRGKQig1oKuoCjnRIiAIRJmM [25]','Leeds City Council\'s City Plans Panel granted planning permission for the first 418 build-to-rent homes at Aire Park, located on Crown Point Road and Bowman Lane. These residential blocks will include a mix of studio, one, two, and three-bedroom apartments, with 44 designated as affordable housing, marking a major step in the creation of homes within the development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0e447f51-decd-4cff-8ffb-d0b2599058f6','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'1 Electric Vehicle (EV) Charging Station at Snowhill Retail Park - Aldi. Stations maintained by Pod Point and located at Unit 1 , Snow Hill Way , Wakefield , WF1 2UZ.... 2020-06-29T07:18:22Z.','Snowhill Retail Park - Aldi | Wakefield, England | EV Station - PlugShare','PlugShare','2020-06-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHd49GvQ0qEK4BW8k80GHCvCWqdacoZM7Tngtcr4srXoqfD11hDKpi8w5IjvFz-K6id2hGnKqZiWZlV5sgSjLg7uCvVe0M98eWPvb3fJgCbtyMIiZKU8PZjVVKXU5cqbAPfMxeb','This PlugShare entry indicates the presence of Pod Point EV charging stations at the Aldi located within Snowhill Retail Park. The earliest user activity (check-in/comment) recorded for these chargers dates back to June 2020, suggesting that EV charging infrastructure was available at the retail park from this period.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0f3872e6-a2a4-43c0-8dc0-d88b94a72e29','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The transformation of Bradford’s former retail heart into a vibrant new sustainable community known as ‘City Village’ has taken a further step forward with the launch of the final phase of public consultation. Detailed plans for phase 1 of the neighbourhood, which ECF, our partnership with Homes England and L&G, is delivering in partnership with Bradford Council, were revealed today (Wednesday 21st May) as part of Bradford Council’s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock. Later phases of the neighbourhood will include approximately 400 apartments on the Kirkgate site. The final phase of consultation launched today – inviting feedback on updated plans for the neighbourhood ahead of a planning application to be submitted in late summer. It will run until Weds 18 June.','Detailed plans unveiled for first phase of \'City Village\' transformation, Kirkgate apartments in later phases','Bdaily, Muse, Bradford City Village Website','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGPICXyidAUZ9Fujoy8_F_7q81Q3akJ-iyC3QKPiCjLpfnVezem8iO0G5ZJe7JH-lZ-I5DE41_4ZPBT_t6cpVMkr3hlwZyFFK5TFtRT802GR3JhIwb0InLL6eJY9bWIjnYukUnCxJ5SrDpypcK-g737Ru6splTRN01LbLAzVee8UbTgGpzAmQ15MvXQ1ceO-d9HsIexfEpB8FkiUCB9ECxXLsLYhdEsCGvMRRgQ_NUCK7RL_RttoDir, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFmnvolHX3h84pcYlBGHFJJzHqrduhiSnR6Tl2AwJM8nm1h2HGpHAByJP8Tx6AtBAIM8hIIuFcp6ND0POf2kNdyg-O3brPf5jMuUXfOdQP879FxnZh3ujh5USh9tp_DSJUxC4pYVvz9BqfVYFEPt9Dw9wv8i-qKhbOkySQHuF4QqLyBB2qT4apx1rVfb6Jz1rDEFyVpB0rl0u6YdSTiQFW4QtpCoPDE13armbbY_V2Z-Ks_MeWw, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGBkjggqv1XarTmqVVMhwKtF7T5T-TCthQoGJZuRCoISzhxkzNZslaob3oI5ZAxb1CQcwRjthoeg58Tym6wfrpWN7I1P-FwAh37feH6GvW3LaoDbf2HKqvQqbijnZ7WXhtFRtSpw0kjXf3EHmN5Yip9XJprR4e1V2uCtzUniN23_dM','Detailed plans for Phase 1 of Bradford City Village were revealed, along with an update on future phases. The Kirkgate site, located closest to the city centre, is planned to offer a high-density residential community with around 400 new apartments. These plans were presented as part of Bradford Council\'s \'Bradford Showcase\' event and included a final phase of public consultation inviting feedback on the updated masterplan before a planning application submission.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0f6af8dd-4b13-4e0e-83fd-db30dc1677bf','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Hello and welcome to another video a brand new adventure in Bradford. Again this time we\'re going to be looking at the improvements that they\'ve made in the city. Center. Now if you\'ve been to Bradford recently you\'ll know there\'s been a lot of upheaval. And a lot of closed streets in the city whilst they carry out a lot of work on the local area in the town. And uh also in preparation for Bradford City of Culture in 2025. Which is next year. As you can see they\'ve closed the main road off through the center which again I\'m happy about because this was always a bit of a bottleneck. Here for pedestrians. And they\'ve made this a new sort of uh turnaround section now. So you come down on Sunbridgeidge Road and uh swing round here. And you can head just down there towards Sunbridge Wells. As you can see now a nice uh pedestrian thoroughare through and into City Park. And they\'ve got the Bradford 2025 sign outside again which they had last year. A lot of it is now finished.','Bradford Becoming a Car Free Zone? (YouTube video progress update)','YouTube (AdventureMe)','2024-12-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F3vX8v2pA50','A video update showcased the significant progress and transformations in Bradford City Centre, indicating that much of the area was becoming pedestrianised and car-free in preparation for Bradford City of Culture 2025. It highlighted new planters, shrubbery, green spaces, and improved pedestrian thoroughfares, especially connecting areas like Market Street to City Park, and noted the removal of traffic from bottlenecks.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('0fca2df8-401a-4d14-a821-967bae802646','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A West Leeds Dispatch article, dated 7 January 2025, reports that planning permission has been granted to BP Pulse to install EV charging points at Kirkstall Bridge Retail Park, repurposing existing parking spaces. [5]','Green Light for BP Pulse EV Charging Points at Kirkstall Bridge Retail Park','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-01-07 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/green-light-for-electric-charging-points-at-kirkstall-bridge-retail-park/','Planning permission was granted to BP Pulse to convert three existing car parking spaces into two electric vehicle charging spaces at Kirkstall Bridge Retail Park. The Leeds City Council planning officer\'s report concluded that the proposal would not have a significant detrimental impact and would create new EV charging infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('10038e08-a55a-4348-973c-c18a7fd6d3c3','infrastructure-a629-halifax-to-huddersfield-corridor-improvement-phase-4-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.884','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'An Air Quality Assessment by Arcadis version 2 (no ref) (dated 23/03/2021) has been submitted in support of the application. The proposed development seeks to deliver improvements and widening of the A629 between Huddersfield town centre and Ainley Top roundabout... Having reviewed the Air Quality Assessment by Arcadis... we are satisfied with the methodology, approach and content of the report and concur with the conclusions, that the operational phase of the scheme will not have a significant impact on air quality.','2021/92734 A629 Halifax Road, Edgerton, Huddersfield - Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council','2021-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEktSoY51IH8vtZjJBvyfsHzrOL9YzziuJS3Gfm-Gws7Yd0bvJr6-1mZ-V9zQVwPQZZl-t9vPiyvnUScANthuw2X1fLO5SZ9gBLP8dkcuPl1-3TfU3JMGoF9WIPjo0nUsboJbsgkcRMYUSyfMfz22rkyqmeQ4ZVGjiQPmn6jj751LYcnI_7F45ZdazZMjq_RJkx6bsO-1wcRSfFthCouL0shm-HUJGjya-5oGPjuNoHB8j3vBlT3AZGTFvDPZcU7SrdXnNO-sErdq4EOVyW9pHfp31kyygPzmiYCCoIWz7AiOrEVv1vjdK9aDKC','An Air Quality Assessment, dated March 23, 2021, by Arcadis was submitted to Kirklees Council in support of the A629 improvement application between Huddersfield town centre and Ainley Top roundabout. The assessment concluded that the operational phase of the scheme would not have a significant impact on air quality, with only slight adverse increases predicted in the Huddersfield Town Centre Air Quality Management Area (AQMA) which are below health-related objectives.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('100f2404-e060-4614-9831-7c7858832a0f','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Council regards the DHN as the key to unlocking long-term decarbonisation of heat in the city... Initiation of a strategic network to allow the council to implement Core Strategy Policy EN4, requiring new developments to connect and providing an outlet for heat from proposed waste/energy activities in Aire Valley Leeds... Since the LDO\'s inception in 2016...','Local Development Order (LDO 3) - Leeds District Heating Network','Leeds City Council / GOV.UK','2016-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHZjpF4LsvuYWHgVKPjbz6_XNYduuYTHBxPqPY96CqDR38S7WIMBPspCl85929bIFyqQpFC5G3QrWhmJTTp4nyVqSRh1drppbkkPItTGbp4VO6xDz_rmua8DEN8bZ2LLxQgRJrjbTEkINvUXKvSqil7_FK6bWCpvwNuE7eR-hhjT5_n2m6OXayLAMmYiQDcyfafIlhp4cQALfJoUDKLJpOFRowSB534DFwPrS2XxA3KHwziP2T-9iaZkpizTjcUVEykN1xtOHPdMLsv8A86Jh4sI8ntIqdIbqVL2ENYtnlQ1Ve6j9my8mmY0CluXQOUNxbBBw==','Leeds City Council\'s Local Development Order (LDO 3) for the Leeds District Heating Network outlines the strategic intent to create a city-wide network, explicitly mentioning \'providing an outlet for heat from proposed waste/energy activities in Aire Valley Leeds\'. This document sets the early strategic framework for heat networks, including those planned for the Aire Valley area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('104e8f6b-178c-4c7a-9200-ee915d289d49','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The safety critical repair works to Stanningley ByPass have been on-going since May 2021. This is mentioned in multiple articles (e.g., [4], [8], [9]) in the context of the larger Dawson\'s Corner scheme.','Safety critical repair works to Stanningley Bypass ongoing','Highways News / Leeds City Council News / Major Funding Boost for Leeds Infrastructure','2021-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF8Hj5uuFTPqZl9Z4xXPynMGMZksCu1VKb7PFPVx-28g-539M-_MQuAgNeFpD9YPmu6BMm9DxN9lJ-jSw-qe5h1xrf2OOXWMS4rJiX8SfxUlDXmnFaCAVkvGIz1qbuNqI9i6rWPBWUMcm3-RBmbsB5n10Oo_L3UNivwW54wt8n19WhOI2oMrh8yaTU','Safety critical repair works on the Stanningley Bypass, which forms part of the wider Dawson\'s Corner project, were already underway. These initial works are a precursor to the main junction remodelling. This indicates the early stages of activity related to the overall scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('10603e61-b251-4a50-a276-faf9dd543a6c','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council is excited to test cutting-edge, innovative technology alongside leading industry partners on the EV-elocity project... The Project EV-elocity is part of the Vehicle-to-Grid (V2G) competition... [8]','Leeds City Council Involvement in EV-elocity Vehicle-to-Grid Project','EV-elocity Project website blog','2020-11-10 00:00:00.000','https://www.ev-elocity.org/partner-introduction-leeds-city-council/','Leeds City Council became a partner in the EV-elocity project, a national initiative funded by the Department for Business Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) and the Office for Low Emission Vehicles (OLEV), to test Vehicle-to-Grid (V2G) technology and further decarbonize transport and energy infrastructure within the city. [8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1075f7f1-6cb6-4eb3-91ef-2aee0a50edd1','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Equipping the people of West Yorkshire with the right set of digital skills is one of my key priorities as Mayor. This Digital Skills Plan is our footprint for delivery to support everybody, from the residents who want to use digital to connect with their families, to the businesses looking to grow and innovate here, to the people looking for opportunities to work in our thriving tech sector. Tablet lending, Digital Champions Network, digital support across West Yorkshire\'s libraries and community networks that reach out to those most in need, supported by national charities such as Good Things Foundation.','West Yorkshire Digital Skills Plan','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-11-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHtZapn0wr2LJVT47itkKqEvGiwmNF14Vpkjb1fEDYFtN3y9mZXJo9QTwl1OPireorkoL1MZcnR0EGrYkUL8f8K_lmgoH0SSaDZc4ZV32TTJdJPkoo5Hg1fXAwanAuTc0qyl4UT5z1K1a66xrbG9QajO5SObIrLXh_Kg2iMlw==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority published its Digital Skills Plan, outlining a comprehensive strategy to reduce digital exclusion across the region. Key initiatives include expanding tablet lending schemes, developing Digital Champions networks, and enhancing digital support available through libraries and community networks, with a goal to boost essential digital skills by 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('10b85d01-cd53-41a5-884e-77ff001ed4df','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water // The Science Behind // How we play our part in natural flood management. Landscapes for Water is a partnership. project it grew out of an initial project we did around Gorpley reservoir where we planted over 100,000 trees. The Landscapes for Water partnership has been in existence now for around five years. Besides ourselves and National Trust it involves the Woodland Trust, the White Rose Forest, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authorities. There are two main aspects to the Landscapes for Water project: the tree planting element, and then the natural flood management which is the installation of over 3 and a half thousand leaky dams. The leaky dams have been funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority as part of their wider flood mitigation measures. And the woodland element has been funded by the White Rose Forest. Today we\'ve already planted over 73,000 trees.','The Science Behind: How Yorkshire Water plays its part in natural flood management with Landscapes for Water','Yorkshire Water (YouTube)','2025-04-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kY6v4b3z1r0','A video/podcast released by Yorkshire Water on April 29, 2025, provides an in-depth explanation of their role in natural flood management through the Landscapes for Water partnership. It details the project\'s two main components: extensive tree planting (with over 73,000 trees planted by this date) and the strategic installation of 3,500 leaky dams. The funding for these initiatives comes from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and White Rose Forest, emphasizing their combined benefits for climate mitigation and effective flood reduction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('10c4493e-e440-4b6a-bf74-3578dbf82048','infrastructure-manchester-road-bus-improvements-scheme-south-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.869','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Consultation starts. 19 March 2025. Bradford Council in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority is proposing the Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme, which was formerly one part of the South Bradford Park & Ride Scheme proposals. The Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme proposes a series of bus improvements, some walking, wheeling and cycling improvements, and planting and landscaping improvements. The scheme aims to reduce congestion and offer better options for people travelling between south Bradford and the city centre.','Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme Consultation Starts','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE10y4WMCZBaMXuxi4c5Dv1g2HwAGHyo9OWEYLVACN10tpE-H92yfC4V9epY1fVBNhme0LjZzMP-MliPXnjYvfs11l4PgPiQjZ3Xqc_umU-f753Efm6M1RWAHJJaO9-Ygkh8S8aFfL7f-zMQDU5voyNZ8wiMA==','Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched the public consultation for the Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme. This scheme, a phased delivery of the wider South Bradford Park & Ride proposals, aims to introduce bus priority measures, walking, wheeling, and cycling improvements, and landscaping along the Manchester Road corridor to reduce congestion and improve travel options.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1238585d-e3f9-4bfd-b4ac-3c7fc4f88c83','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A consortium made up of Jacobs and Mott MacDonald has been appointed as the Design Development Partner for the system – which will start with a new Bradford to Leeds tram line running through West Leeds. The Jacobs – Mott MacDonald consortium will support the West Yorkshire Combined Authority in developing the mass transit programme’s first phases. The CA anticipates the early construction stage will begin in 2028. [8], [12]','Consortium chosen to deliver Bradford to Leeds tram line','West Leeds Dispatch','2024-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/consortium-chosen-to-deliver-bradford-to-leeds-tram-line/','A consortium comprising Jacobs and Mott MacDonald was appointed as the Design Development Partner for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system, with the Bradford to Leeds tram line being the initial focus. This partnership will support the development of the programme\'s first phases, targeting an early construction stage in 2028.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('12443964-e5b2-4aa8-9097-0423c51f9129','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds will be awarded £24.5 million for an extension to the LeedsPIPES network. The South Bank extension, located in one of Europe\'s largest brownfield regeneration sites, will allow an additional 8,000 homes and buildings to connect to the low carbon heat network, powered using a local source of waste heat. [16]','£57 million of GHNF funding set to benefit 17000 new homes and buildings - Leeds South Bank awarded £24.5 million','Gov.uk (reported by news outlet)','2024-08-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEkzkOOtb0YnJIV6NROegJZJH2SOeBjtHH0n-WWCBUdfSdJkgU74VkYC6qLtFjbFs9usE4jFwubrF1RLTyYSTINojnWkPGl3xl9b-etgjoRLUJg-3szg4OADFuiuiwATB0H5vQbQiZCdt0C','The UK government\'s Green Heat Network Fund (GHNF) officially announced a £24.5 million award for the Leeds PIPES South Bank extension. This funding will support commercialisation and construction, enabling an additional 8,000 homes and buildings in one of Europe\'s largest brownfield regeneration sites to connect to the low carbon heat network, powered by a local source of waste heat.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('12a097d9-44e1-4e0d-8376-2d2ab6288195','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'re very excited to share the news that we are hosting a prestigious event for electric vehicles at Tingley next month. Tingley is home to one of the largest electric vehicle (EV) charging stations in Yorkshire and we were proud to selected to host an event as part of a five-day 1400-mile showcase of all things EV and demonstrates vehicle capability from cars to all-electric HGV, charging infrastructure and clean energy projects. On 2nd July, over 50 vehicles participating in the rally will arrive at Tingley Garden Centre. Electric vehicles will be on display, and experts, including representatives from Women Drive Electric, will give advice. “With 56 Compleo chargers, which are powered by solar panels and 100% green electricity, we are well-placed to be an official Check Point in the AtoZ EV Rally. We\'re celebrating our participation in this prestigious event by offering customers free charging all day on 2nd July, said Jo Dales, head of marketing at Yorkshire Garden Centres.','We\'re celebrating a nationwide EV rally at Tingley with free charging on 2nd July','Tingley Garden Centre','2024-06-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGFKXVTepDLXrsBPodSUxpQ60kSNhQvR6ym5Vgywi1c1LRjFzaJ_X0Li8JF9WVej5_IMPUMr1cpk9wABIY2lhkn04vC51iCdmOsxEj-zSxtqbQS_kf--JufZCnEbEX-nXVQ1lIStrofcBhjadXRsm0zQlP0aNeIALqZFTw7WdJIm5leLpWno0p9lWvMnV2vjqPDHJ1ipsDZD6M8Z85jyC38XMwByyqin_52FoMOqRIp9htZb6wXyh1ctg==','Tingley Garden Centre announced it would host a checkpoint for a nationwide EV rally on July 2nd, 2024, offering free charging for customers. The centre highlighted its status as a large EV charging station in Yorkshire, featuring 56 Compleo chargers powered by solar panels and green electricity.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('130c0b76-366c-4387-bf99-614ff076e2b9','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Hundreds of children across the region are benefiting from a safer journey to school thanks to a partnership between parents, schools, local councils, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. Following a successful pilot in 2019, the Combined Authority has invested over £600,000 into the School Streets programme – which sees streets outside schools become safer and cleaner by reducing traffic and addressing dangerous parking. Having already delivered 33 \'School Streets\', 15 more are now being planned across the region through funding from Active Travel England.','Nearly 50 schools across West Yorkshire to benefit from a cleaner, safer school run','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQENgFZ7kI331AtoIGM84AGyvkKuJmfabTtzsbQ-YjYpPXlvUpNdbV1qKC97kjJZxsFPhvXPPEL2Mlj-Rro1Jza6fPGPXAdcN_Ssf-it5jHU_9zRE9a5EhbIV0hzm2zkE7Xe7evcNLuza35kA_E2dUxIXifi9ohibo4jkmWlKKfmZZsXjH5ruZeLUbetOMA46LFQXghnWMhDUT1Q_OfBFFS7ivlnLMsN7USpWmQa9Ee2NISSzPrP7OqT_IPukVECqYVchw==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced an investment of over £600,000 into its \'School Streets\' programme, aiming for safer and cleaner journeys to school by reducing traffic and addressing dangerous parking. This follows a successful pilot in 2019, with 33 \'School Streets\' already delivered and 15 more planned across the region through funding from Active Travel England.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('138f6151-e342-4cd6-b29c-cad4bd5ea7f7','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2018-12-06) The improvement works between Salterhebble and Shaw Hill are the first project being delivered as part of the £120m A629 improvement programme, funded by the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund. ... However, the project has now been completed and the attention now turns to the next phase which will see work of the Calder and Hebble junction. ... Construction will begin around early 2020.','When the next phase of the major £120m A629 scheme will begin','Halifax Courier','2018-12-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQExlTJpgbo1xicM0h8K0SKa1yJ21gQsAdw4bMlW42e6aur820q8XXsGzHdVoL2-twv1x_VCxRDISRCaWC0hmXjozL6wqBfdf-y00vT4fwMQ3MWy1vHUAd3zRs55-wLItT2wuR3hS5mehtWeq0YpqjxTL6m_QE7bnlGYXlJ5LJ82BLfebdAuX6-_fGUW1Xs4BS35ZeUT10F8BpaSOR-ThoO5eEIryCGTHhQWeEonoHngTholaOhS-yysq9s=','This article published in December 2018 officially confirmed the completion of the A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill improvement works, marking it as the first project delivered under the wider £120 million A629 improvement programme. It stated that attention would now turn to the next phase, focusing on the Calder and Hebble junction, with construction expected to begin around early 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('13e062e9-2820-46fc-8408-fd028ce80245','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious plans to regenerate Wakefield city centre are accelerating, with Wakefield Council set to formalise its partnership with Muse – one of the UK\'s leading placemaking and regeneration specialists. This announcement marks the next phase in delivering the city\'s long-term transformation, starting with the Cathedral Quarter and Borough Road. These changes are part of the wider Wakefield City Centre Masterplan and supported by the Towns Deal investment. Public consultation will be a key part of shaping the final proposals.','Wakefield BID Welcomes Partnership with Muse for City Centre Transformation','Wakefield BID','2025-07-16 00:00:00.000','https://wakefieldbid.co.uk/news/wakefield-bid-welcomes-bold-plans-to-transform-wakefield-city-centre/','Wakefield Council is formalizing a partnership with Muse, a leading regeneration specialist, to accelerate the city centre\'s transformation. This marks the next phase in delivering the long-term vision, focusing initially on the Cathedral Quarter and Borough Road. The plans, supported by the wider Wakefield City Centre Masterplan and Towns Deal investment, aim for new high-quality homes, reimagined public spaces, improved connectivity, and a boost to retail and leisure offerings. Public consultation will be a key component.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('14192697-cc4f-4687-9d7e-ca51353b0efb','infrastructure-north-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.153','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The information below was presented during the public consultation between Thursday 4 November to Sunday 30 January 2021. Please note - the below consultation has now closed. [7]','North Halifax Improved Streets for People Round 2 Public Consultation','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Your Voice','2021-11-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHYNmDdtVvtF3UmdupHGRSK7hEiekchlwBmCeUei6g5xcDbJpjoDy51g1y37UlGx7oAIYnnLy8qyE43sTAtdzjrLEi7PuvADgyrqjA8fPpQYr0O1hQwltyytKNyY9cKiRYHSoV6GOX_8ZjTFqV5724GXIDOlQ==','A second public consultation for the North Halifax Improved Streets for People project was held from November 4, 2021, to January 30, 2022, seeking further public input on the evolving plans. [7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('142cdc68-6779-46c7-a51a-8ea9e078d281','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale CIP: Public drop-in session at Todmorden Town Hall. 12pm - 6pm. Todmorden Town Hall, Bridge Street, Todmorden, OL14 5AQ Plans will be on display for the proposed improvements to the A646 and A58. Members of staff from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council will also be on hand to answer any questions. 29 August 2018.','Public Drop-in Session for Calderdale CIP in Todmorden','West Yorkshire Combined Authority: Your Voice','2018-08-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGG52VU1KpgvH1I-Oo4olhhDQE4oXVzfG4gfCEj4Xocm9eBQZ5t6dCSWh9uNIX7t5afNeFeHis0nHvj7dQ_2OIdoW05gh5MrztEarVdx6O1jQthK3e9RDmE7CP3wVmPckJeaJsLpuQAKFqtkPAqUveI-0Y=','A public drop-in session was held at Todmorden Town Hall as part of the Calderdale Corridor Improvement Programmes. Plans for proposed improvements to the A646 and A58 were on display, with staff from West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council available to answer questions and gather feedback.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1499a92c-7c7a-44aa-9a19-f91d01adfc3c','infrastructure-leeds-to-micklefield-rail-upgrades-transpennine-route-upgrade',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.980','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Network Rail carried out a second public consultation between 13 March and 11 April 2023 on the additional proposals to permanently close Garforth Moor and Highroyds Woods Level Crossings. Both of these crossings have already been closed on safety grounds, but we are proposing to apply to permanently remove them and divert or extinguish the Public Rights of Way across them. [4]','Public Consultation on Garforth Moor and Highroyds Woods Level Crossings','Network Rail (Leeds to Micklefield Upgrades)','2023-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/railway-upgrade-plan/key-projects/transpennine-route-upgrade/leeds-to-micklefield-upgrades/','Network Rail conducted a second public consultation regarding additional proposals to permanently close Garforth Moor and Highroyds Woods Level Crossings, which had already been closed for safety reasons. The consultation aimed to gather feedback on diverting or extinguishing the Public Rights of Way across them.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('156d2600-95e5-443a-9d5d-4b8c11e9e816','infrastructure-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-corridor-improvement-phase-1b-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.863','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Public engagement took place in early autumn which informed the proposals that will be submitted for planning permission in late 2018. [3] A summary of the feedback received can be downloaded here. [4] Public engagement analysis - October 2018 report (440 KB) (pdf). [15]','Public Engagement on A629 Calder and Hebble Junction Improvement','Calderdale Next Chapter / Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2018-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/road-schemes/a629-calder-and-hebble-junction','Public engagement took place in early autumn 2018, informing the proposals for the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction Corridor Improvement (Phase 1b) project that were later submitted for planning permission. This stage allowed the public and interested parties to provide feedback on the proposed plans to improve the A629 from Halifax to Huddersfield. [3, 4, 15]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('156d2905-fd98-4741-b98d-8190c336ba0c','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first two phases of the scheme were designed to reduce the risk of flooding to properties from the River Calder and were completed in 2007. Works included flood storage areas at Centre Vale Park and Millwood and the construction of new flood walls along Sackville Street, River Street, Key Syke Lane, Commercial Street and Hall Royd Crescent.','Completion of Initial Phases of Lower Todmorden and Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme','Premier Construction News','2007-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://premierconstructionnews.com/2012/02/03/todmorden-welcomes-flood-alleviation-scheme/','The first two phases of the Lower Todmorden and Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme were completed in 2007. These works were designed to reduce flood risk from the River Calder and included the creation of flood storage areas and the construction of new flood walls in various locations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('157c2aa3-2877-4dc2-9b82-1363f46c97e1','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-04-29) project it grew out of uh an initial project we did around Gorpley reservoir where we planted over 100,000 trees. and we did that in partnership with the with the National Trust and the Woodland Trust and it worked so well that we looked at our wider land holdings. so how can we impact natural flood. management across the whole of our combined ownership. so landscapes for water partnership has been in existence now for around five years besides ourselves and national trust it involves the woodland. trust it involves the white rose forest. and it involves the west Yorkshire combined authorities. so there are two main aspects to the landscapes. for water project the tree planting element. and then the natural flood management which is the installation of over 3 and a half thousand leaky dams the leaky dams have been funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. um as part of their wider flood mitigation measures. and the woodland element has been funded by the White Rose Forest. [22]','Yorkshire Water // The Science Behind // How we play our part in natural flood management (Video Transcript)','Yorkshire Water (YouTube)','2025-04-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGnldsYOOHnynONX2O8_sgmJU4uuAZeeOLxRLA7xPZmEiKo_-9V8w_UU87kBWOJPpO7Np_Ls8LEDUh7aQ_kkYEltSa62yFPgNjAhGbpXHolNnjUICSH2OdMOS4yxwWTLjMl08syMyk=','A video transcript from Yorkshire Water provides an update on the ongoing \'Landscapes for Water\' project, detailing the installation of over 3,500 leaky dams (funded by West Yorkshire Combined Authority) and woodland creation (funded by White Rose Forest) across the South Pennines. This collaborative project, involving National Trust and Woodland Trust, aims to slow water flow and enhance flood resilience, particularly in the Calder and Colne catchments. [22]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('158ea5d8-2be1-4804-a831-3776079f2d35','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'An ICSC article published on 25 July 2024, discusses the commercial benefits of EV charging in retail spaces and mentions BP Pulse\'s large-scale partnership with Simon for charging installations in retail properties. [18]','EV Chargers Boost Retailer Bottom Line: ICSC Report Highlights Industry Trend','ICSC','2024-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.icsc.com/news-and-views/icsc-exchange/ev-chargers-boost-bottom-line-lvmh-backed-firm-buys-outlet-stake-4-deals-defining-todays-trends-and-more','An ICSC article highlighted that electric vehicle charging stations are becoming lucrative investments for retailers, boosting foot traffic and revenue. It noted that Simon (a major mall owner) signed a deal with BP Pulse to install approximately 900 EV charging bays across 75 properties, with the first openings expected in 2026, demonstrating a significant trend in retail park EV infrastructure development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('159c88bf-1669-47d4-9b84-47df10d5e149','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Open (25 July - 11 September 2024) Electric Vehicle Charging for West Yorkshire has finished this stage. [17]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) EV Infrastructure Strategy Public Consultation','WYCA Your Voice','2024-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/ev','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) initiated a public consultation on its Electric Vehicle Charging Infrastructure Strategy. This consultation aimed to gather feedback on plans to establish a comprehensive and reliable public charging network across the entire West Yorkshire region. [14, 17]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('15a5beb5-7850-4185-baea-09d0662fa6ad','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council chose ChromeOS devices with managed guest sessions to expand digital outreach to residents through public digital hubs and loaner devices. More than 1,500 ChromeOS devices are used by residents through programs that offer a range of lending options, from short-term via \'digital hubs\' located in libraries, courthouses, and other council buildings, to longer-term loans where residents can take devices home to use for weeks or months. We have increased the number of devices we have by 1,500, however, management is now easier than ever!','How Kirklees Council brought digital inclusion to its communities with ChromeOS','Google Cloud','2024-09-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG3uGn_-76N8hiiziTVYdix9kmKzUqpxtYN6DKrPedw8olvz9aUXckkEP0A34rcMFWmD7wKrUy3WQPwQjtXAUbvLX51tjjE9O3hYQMzrpV56n8eUw7_VCt4M86EicRZgxexoxQUQ1dW1BuBb6JFVO3L7YmxKzUx1ZMkBSf-pYB4RCUWip90nXE1zyHC0ecZnX07hY72OY4v1spde-RNRiAcFFGYxrzeNFnZ6BmuffLME4iREQ_B6zba59OBzrStvOeQcb5N','Kirklees Council successfully implemented a large-scale digital inclusion project by deploying over 1,500 ChromeOS devices. These devices are used in public digital hubs (libraries, courthouses, council buildings) and provided as loaner devices to residents, significantly expanding digital access, improving digital skills, and streamlining IT management across the borough of Kirklees.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1627072f-8820-40b9-8090-b494f4989e82','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yesterday\'s meeting of Kirklees Council\'s Growth and Regeneration Panel heard that 2,001 properties are set to be delivered at sites across the borough by 2030 as part of the council\'s plans for housing growth. The largest number of homes - 474 - from a single development will come from the first phase of the Bradley Park scheme. However, the scheme at Bradley Park hinges on the completion of the A62 Leeds Road to Cooper Bridge scheme which is designed to cut congestion. In January, it was revealed that soaring costs saw the Cooper Bridge scheme now forecast to cost £94m - £20m over budget. As a result, the road scheme is being phased, with the first phase focusing solely on improvements to the Cooper Bridge roundabout. This was said to allow for the first phase of the Bradley Park scheme to go ahead.','Kirklees\' biggest housing projects explained as 2k homes to be built by 2030','YorkshireLive','2024-03-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEuZiPSt_Bi0ofiYYgmtiwiPvlTFLBhN5jLhFq1nCKotfpxrPkIOMLIUdCURU7GrpCpUnSPPGPCnFvHZmM7t416tWtSsngkrz3l-viwAEuMgt8nQmYaG0A5-MG_dbxbhtag0M4a1xIJHpSqdLbKGf8Tz1wCRyPrF0qbwcj4jZhSd9PWOwX6k2TK32owzjkpu33l1wemEGopZIMxqFoJ6ESnrgcA3rRkDw==','A Kirklees Council Growth and Regeneration Panel meeting revealed plans for 2,001 new homes by 2030, with 474 homes from the first phase of the Bradley Park scheme being the largest single development. However, the scheme is contingent on the completion of the A62 Leeds Road to Cooper Bridge scheme, which faced soaring costs (forecast at £94m, £20m over budget) and is being phased, with immediate focus on the Cooper Bridge roundabout to allow Bradley Park Phase 1 to proceed.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('162bd887-90eb-4ad6-8f14-dcd26a6fa012','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This engagement will close at 11.59pm on Sunday 14 August 2022. Feedback gathered from the public consultations will be taken into consideration and will inform the development of more detailed proposals. A consultation outcome report summarising the feedback will then be added to this webpage. [8, 20]','Transforming Travel between Leeds & Wakefield - A61 Public consultation / Transforming Travel between Leeds & Pontefract - A639 | Your Voice','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Your Voice','2022-08-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH_Ymd5sX8iPMSr4b6-Zyv7SZ8BQ1U_5CzxbTeNQiqR36BtCDjKuFpK_mcZT4eOeg5ANDkbnvmEVr58krXmVNvlNZKsA7KgkFl_fpXVsjDaMtpZu9W4E0F9TVuZMRTm-LuUFNe2kJSRnJV2Y_u4ak_Lk-5TB0x6ZOMkN5EsAqvTqZsJmhi5YUW5','The initial public consultation for the A61 and A639 corridor improvements closed on August 14, 2022. The feedback collected from residents and businesses during this period was to be used to shape the more detailed plans for the project. [19, 20]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('16426db8-52bf-4abf-b924-a4c21fafa1d9','infrastructure-moving-traffic-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.124','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Moving traffic offences in Calderdale are currently enforced by West Yorkshire Police, but Calderdale Council is planning to apply for new powers from the Department of Transport to allow it to manage enforcement at specific locations. ... The Council is proposing to use the new powers to enforce moving traffic offences in 15 locations across the borough...','Have your say on plans for new enforcement powers - Calderdale Council – News Centre','Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-05-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/have-your-say-on-plans-for-new-enforcement-powers','Calderdale Council announced its intention to apply for new powers from the Department for Transport to enforce moving traffic offences, which were previously exclusively handled by West Yorkshire Police. A public consultation was launched to gather feedback on proposed enforcement at 15 specific locations across the borough.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('166d6e91-0e91-4c7a-a1b5-e8a8589ebacb','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---ling-bob-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.178','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Projects include making streets around schools safer and easier to get around, with improved footways, green spaces and junctions near to Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax. [11]','Calderdale projects to boost walking, wheeling and cycling take a step forward','Halifax Courier','2025-08-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/calderdale-projects-to-boost-walking-wheeling-and-cycling-take-a-step-forward-4247831','Following a £12.8 million funding boost from Active Travel England to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, regional leaders have approved schemes including improved footways, green spaces, and junctions near Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax. This aims to make streets safer and easier for active travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('167fa31a-610f-4de7-85c9-1a8e62efe614','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A joint press release from the Environment Agency and Calderdale Council announced significant progress on the new Caldene Bridge, a crucial component of the flood alleviation scheme. The new bridge, which has nearly twice the capacity of the old one to improve flood flow, was set to open by Spring 2020. The demolition of the existing Caldene Bridge would commence after the new one opened.','New bridge to help reduce flood risk in Mytholmroyd set to open in Spring','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2020-01-21 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/new-bridge-to-help-reduce-flood-risk-in-mytholmroyd-set-to-open-in-spring/','A joint press release from the Environment Agency and Calderdale Council announced significant progress on the new Caldene Bridge, a crucial component of the flood alleviation scheme. The new bridge, which has nearly twice the capacity of the old one to improve flood flow, was set to open by Spring 2020. The demolition of the existing Caldene Bridge would commence after the new one opened.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('16a020a2-10a9-43b5-8c1b-8d449dc578bd','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority, working in partnership with Wakefield Council and Leeds City Council, is investing £22.5m in two key roads connecting the Wakefield District with Leeds – the A61 and A639. It is part of £317m allocated to Leeds City Region (LCR) from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF). An initial consultation on these proposals was held during July and August 2022. [11]','Transforming Cities - A61 and A639: West Yorkshire Combined Authority investment','Wakefield Council','2022-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/roads-and-transport/transport-projects/transforming-cities-a61-and-a639','West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Wakefield and Leeds City Councils, announced an investment of £22.5m from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) for improvements on the A61 and A639 corridors. This fund aims to reduce car journeys, improve connectivity, and support healthier lifestyles by encouraging public transport, cycling, and walking.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1712df23-ef46-42b5-a2b7-d923dd031eb7','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Today (Thursday 3 April), the regional mayor and five district leaders of West Yorkshire cemented their commitment to the long-term prosperity of Bradford by approving funding for its City Village scheme, pending final business case agreement. The development aims to transform Bradford City Centre with almost a thousand new homes and three new green spaces... The Mayor’s in-principle investment of £13.2 million for Bradford City Village is another major boost for the UK’s City of Culture 2025, after the Government committed £30 million of funding for the scheme, which will be delivered by Bradford Council working with ECF, formerly the English Cities Fund. The City Village masterplan proposes the re-development of Kirkgate, Oastler, and Chain Street. All owned by Bradford Council, the three sites will accommodate over 900 new homes...','Regional Leaders Approve Funding for Bradford City Village','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / Bdaily','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEvyzIixm_KNeCt4CIsellCnNqnNmnFSzCRHP0gn81b3JDPAoGbZE6WAueHf-b_bb0WiCAcGDAaQetE1VnmEO9oiLKbFi-C8cAbIcNPyH1TeEpgAxmIX2CRB3nPmBGLzB3Ms1tlSSKS5LbMd5p94eh2PELStrQXkVdRcZNF5tpg3Zxk7eYDoFezeiy7y5wZlAyj4D4sy4gClEB35wPOho79szTx3t9AMJcO_iJeh_VyYME2Blw1eBhnmOggJ1mTms-8jac','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority approved in-principle funding of £13.2 million for the Bradford City Village scheme, complementing a £30 million government grant via Homes England. This funding commitment by regional leaders underscores the project\'s significance for urban regeneration, aiming to deliver almost a thousand new homes across the Kirkgate, Oastler, and Chain Street sites. [12, 13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('17217fd4-3851-46c6-8849-fce4072e91db','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The latest plans for active travel routes in Todmorden will be available to view at upcoming information events in the town. On Thursday 24 and Saturday 26 October 2024 from 10am to 2pm, the project team will be available at Todmorden Market for people to find out more about the latest plans for the project and share their feedback on proposals. The £3.2million Active Todmorden project is designed to promote healthier communities and create a more attractive and welcoming town.','Help shape the next steps for Active Todmorden','Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-10-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/help-shape-the-next-steps-for-active-todmorden','Calderdale Council announced further details of upcoming information events regarding the Active Todmorden project. These events, scheduled for October 24 and 26, 2024, at Todmorden Market, aimed to allow the public to view the latest plans for active travel routes and provide feedback. The project\'s £3.2 million funding was reiterated.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1724c0b6-7473-42ac-b580-df789ad4ef6b','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A raft of Calderdale towns and villages have been picked for a share of a Government cash pot to help protect them from flooding. ... Copley Village Flood Alleviation Scheme. ... This much-needed funding will go a long way to support those whose homes and livelihoods are repeatedly threatened by flooding.','Hebden Bridge, Copley, Brighouse and more Calderdale flood-hit areas will get chunk of £100 million Government fund','Halifax Courier','2023-04-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEjb_2tyYTi1z-MoBuxjInLmMvt1iY3JG4Wjc_M4QS0hp2f1KXby_hz-anH1hnjM6czQgul5Z7DtGLu29mfjdIZvlwYp6WSndP3Q0zTeOuyIthRlCyQncYzZIx2ztPAnKcB2xVS772wMjCKh-pueQV2eScdYk2KpKgr5PaVnSthcKfHSZcX5dohbik4h0FlU3axMOYDSHXUqXa4prGSQ0aTBjOFw3NFIjxqg2PbkAGEZNKykpS7MLMQ0s5GpAwjT2WhggL9JREdfIg0ffnp8z7MTQywS_d5SBgplwJ4WR2_v4aSfZrY-s6n','Calderdale towns and villages, including Copley, are set to receive a share of a £100 million Government fund to help protect them from flooding, targeting communities with repeated flooding incidents.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('173f9fde-8bcc-4846-ab72-a3ef87fa4ab4','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The overall investment programme is progressing well. Work has started on the refurbishment of the Hippodrome Theatre, Todmorden Community Learning Hub, the Town Hall and the bandstand and bowling pavilion at Centre Vale Park, where the tennis courts have been completed.','Todmorden Town Deal project update','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2025-04-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFDIReAp3sLJPpLb-5-HeJW2tqeMEiP552l1-HCuRBHAJ2SslW441db3UoypmbchR72pRQTt-DzllyGlI3B93RuP2RlAH64O2XuGY3PPa-Zy6_wqvURnr_bIuRmPhj6qf2NyQpY3_ZWq5dESs0vL8flsrQPEsrLcDT2XkG7wA==','This update from Calderdale Council\'s News Centre details the progress of the broader £17.5 million Todmorden Town Deal program. It explicitly states that work has started on the refurbishment of the Town Hall, alongside other key projects in the area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1741dfe1-e44c-409d-92d7-d06036232ed7','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) programme, funded through £317 million from the Department for Transport (DfT) plus local match funding up to £140 million, aims to provide an accessible, attractive and cleaner alternative to car journeys. This major new programme of transport infrastructure investment was secured as part of the West Yorkshire devolution deal in March 2020. It benefits communities across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield with schemes including new or improved bus and rail stations, cycling and walking infrastructure, and new Park and Rides. It is estimated TCF schemes will improve journeys by bus, rail, bike and on foot for up to 1.5 million people, take up to 12 million car trips per year off our roads and reduce CO2 emissions from car travel by up to 15,000 tonnes by 2036. The overall programme is expected to deliver one new rail station, two new Park & Rides, bus priority along six key routes, five new or improved bus stations, seven improvements to Rail Station Gateways, 800 new cycle parking spaces, six new high-quality cycle routes, and four new foot and cycle bridges. The programme is being delivered over three years, up to the end of 2025. [5, 6, 7, 13, 18, 21, 24, 31]','Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) - West Yorkshire Combined Authority secures £317m funding','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / Future Bradford / Kirklees Council','2020-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGpAZUq2m5eFuROH91RA24VvtUQGx5Vc1UHP0l8EgPVlWrDFuccXusRZhj07G4vttT8_-8HWYgirUCGVXmetYFRa4eWwIqvk2HNj_k_x4rpnQkYZdBTo0lUJF7JUfOUdPVAx1L497UVgdD0RFXbrArUjVbRJtMx6i2wKl5l2CAJs8ptG4leIS-hNyaxB-eIJg==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with local authorities, successfully secured £317 million from the Department for Transport\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF), complemented by up to £140 million in local match funding. This major programme of transport infrastructure investment aims to provide accessible, attractive, and cleaner alternatives to car journeys across the Leeds City Region, including Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield. The programme\'s objective is to boost productivity, living standards, and air quality, with an estimated impact of improving journeys for 1.5 million people and reducing CO2 emissions by 15,000 tonnes by 2036. The funding was part of the West Yorkshire devolution deal.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('177cf940-c4ef-477f-9de5-1834940c2a07','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Back to brick... The development of Horton House for Westgate Arcade\'s Phase II is making good progress, and our building team will soon be ready to take it to the next level. [13]','Westgate Arcade Phase II News','Westgate Arcade','2022-03-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGVplJdTQeisx7Iyyw0dwkfHODzluBhyGf0WvFYBBtU0x4zY2UDCE9-a5ZFBS6bDUY1tfspSbR3aeCQ3MQnwz9f2OSennZkZK8uKpZa_yDj7KMQT9f5ltXb8XMvT3opnZQNHNZBbFLaKNwJ7vOwadzdugbQZF8ejbzhQVYlhdVgDzG0WJHr1qbiqqeGEr2v','An update on the Westgate Arcade website stated that the development of Horton House for Westgate Arcade\'s Phase II was making good progress, with the building team preparing to take it to the next level.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1796d53d-9f5c-4a71-adad-15866a7b8ee1','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We have a formal policy to assess and implement minor traffic and parking improvement schemes. Updated: 26th June 2025. This helps requests to be dealt with in a fair and consistent way through a simple priority system. Many requests we get need a Traffic Regulation Order (TRO). [3]','Minor traffic and parking improvement scheme','Calderdale Council','2025-06-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/highways/minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-scheme','Calderdale Council\'s official policy page detailing its formal process for assessing and implementing small-scale traffic and parking improvements borough-wide. It outlines how requests are prioritised, particularly those related to injury accidents, and the process for Traffic Regulation Orders (TROs).','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('184c7663-f874-4e8a-baa4-c3fbd6304ffc','infrastructure-ionity-leeds-skelton-lakes-ev-charging-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.372','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Extra MSA Group has opened the first phase of its new £64m Leeds Skelton Lake Services. The new motorway service area, which is located at Junction 45 of the M1, two miles east of Leeds, opened its doors this week but has been forced to limit its offering to essential services only during the COVID-19 lockdown. Facilities that are open at the MSA during the COVID-19 lockdown include the fuel filling station, toilets and shower facilities, IONITY electric vehicle charging points and a small shop. [13]','Leeds Skelton Lake Services Opens First Phase, Including IONITY EV Chargers','Motor Transport','2020-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://www.motortransport.co.uk/article/new-64m-leeds-skelton-lake-services-opens-at-junction-45-of-the-m1/','Extra MSA Group officially opened the first phase of its new £64 million Leeds Skelton Lake Services at Junction 45 of the M1 in late March 2020. During the initial COVID-19 lockdown, essential services including the fuel station, toilets, showers, and IONITY electric vehicle charging points were operational.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('185a576a-6646-4718-989a-038a9564e45d','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work to further boost flood protection in Calderdale could soon be given the go ahead. At Calderdale Council\'s next Cabinet meeting on Monday 2 June 2025, Councillors will be asked to accept external grants worth nearly £2 million to strengthen flood defences and reduce the impacts of flooding in areas most at risk. Together, Calderdale Council and its partner organisations on the Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Board have secured £133 million since 2012. [4, 5]','Calderdale Council Cabinet to Consider £2M Grants for Flood Protection','Calderdale Council News Centre, Halifax Courier','2025-05-23 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/boosting-flood-protection-in-calderdale/','News released on May 23, 2025, announced that Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet would convene on June 2, 2025, to consider approving nearly £2 million in external grants for a two-year flood risk management works program. This proposed funding aims to further bolster flood defences and enhance resilience, building upon the £133 million already secured since 2012 by the Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Board. [4, 5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1867b6bf-66e5-4c35-94aa-366211eab8b6','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The second round of the Kirklees Digital Hubs capital grant scheme, funded by UKSPF, opened in April 2023. This round had £23,794 (later updated to £34,500 by other sources) allocated for grants of up to £5000 to improve digital infrastructure and equipment for community use within Kirklees.','UKSPF Digital Infrastructure Capital Funding - Year 2 Round 2 Opens','Kirklees Council','2023-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/grants-and-funding/ukspf-digital-infrastructure-capital-funding.aspx','Kirklees Council announced the opening of the second round of its UKSPF Digital Hubs capital grant programme. This round, for the 2023-24 funding year, made £23,794 available for community organisations to apply for grants up to £5000 to enhance digital equipment or infrastructure for local residents.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('18f74d6d-67e5-4b14-bbfb-8af508907b7f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Kirklees Council Cabinet meeting on 1 September 2020 made a decision regarding the Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) Programme. The TCF is a national sustainable transport fund for projects in 2020/21 to 2022/23. Kirklees Council, working with West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), developed a TCF Bid for Leeds City Region, which was submitted in November 2019 and awarded £317m in March 2020. The eight projects in the Kirklees TCF programme, with their indicative budgets in the Low Bid scenario, total £39.5m. An additional £6m of local match-funding from the Town Centres Action Fund was identified for relevant TCF projects, bringing the total current Kirklees TCF programme budget to £45.5m. The Council also noted a \'High Scenario\' with a total funding of £72m. Schemes include Dewsbury Bus Station, Dewsbury Town Centre Walking & Cycling Transformations, Heckmondwike Bus Hub, Huddersfield Major Walking & Cycling Routes, Huddersfield Bus Station Improvements, and Huddersfield Rail Station Access. [16, 18, 24, 31]','Kirklees Transforming Cities Fund Programme - Cabinet Decision and Budget Allocation','Kirklees Council','2020-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE6EJpqrTyCYKqO8cvEUXZH1Phat0TftF8JeaBesCzfRGHsD_1iIDNXcj41lHIfpWbD5SXLl7LDSHRnfP0sGJcJRQgIb7p4knqch9gKsFjG8_aC_ulEcAWUTDVJz3BSSt9lt6s0bid1YcOz_pLigRMvNe6-nmtZzKI8bxumXw==','The Kirklees Council Cabinet approved the Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) projects and their inclusion in the Kirklees Capital Plan on September 1, 2020. The Kirklees TCF programme has a budget of £39.5 million from the DfT\'s TCF, supplemented by £6 million in local match-funding from the Town Centres Action Fund, bringing the total to £45.5 million for the \'Low Scenario\'. Key schemes include transforming access to Dewsbury town centre with a revitalised bus station and improved walking and cycling routes, enhancing public transport in Huddersfield (refurbished bus station, rail station upgrades, new walking/cycling routes), and providing a new bus hub at Heckmondwike. A \'High Scenario\' with a total budget of £72 million with devolution top-up was also noted for future consideration.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('18feba6b-b7df-455e-be9f-93dcedd13b3b','infrastructure-wakefield-cathedral-square-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.682','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council will be working in partnership with Muse to set a strategy that will transform the city centre. The work will consider new public realm at Cathedral Square, how to increase green space, bringing new homes into the city, increasing leisure footfall, and improving connectivity across key areas of the city. [10]','Wakefield Council Partners with Muse to Accelerate City Centre Regeneration','Wakefield Council, Wakefield BID','2025-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/latest-news/2025/july/plans-moving-forward-to-transform-wakefield-city-centre [10], https://wakefieldbid.co.uk/news/wakefield-bid-welcomes-bold-plans-to-transform-wakefield-city-centre [17]','On July 15, 2025, Wakefield Council announced a strategic partnership with Muse, a leading regeneration specialist. This collaboration aims to accelerate the delivery of the city\'s masterplan, focusing on the Cathedral Quarter and Borough Road, enhancing public realm, green spaces, and connectivity within the city centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('19514b8f-8f86-484f-991a-b437d78b8b70','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'“What a moment for West Yorkshire, what a moment for devolution,” declared mayor Tracy Brabin as buses were brought back into public control. Debate over the issue of bus reform took up roughly the first hour of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting on 14 March, the final meeting of its kind in this mayoral term. Brabin described the decision as “the biggest change in the way buses are run for 40 years”. [23]','New era beckons as WYCA opts for bus franchising - Place Yorkshire','Place Yorkshire','2024-03-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHHiZnA8yPLh4F6kqYzeRUyFOicppcAKhwmqKXaOU1U77B6HKwdAGqs1Kbtn2-_4yzzwSLVPJ9Uy_XwurRzk1y67OFhIew_gG_8W4d4-zrJhBey3s4wIrEjsZz7eVOlME9ysdSCdmAZbZc53DKlrzStJp2R35By1lswjg','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin announced the decision to bring buses back under public control through a franchising model, representing the biggest change to the region\'s transport network in decades. This strategic decision impacts the future direction and control of all bus services, including how routes like the 571 will be managed in the long term. [23]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1a3ff463-eb27-48c0-b08b-6d5d733add4e','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Floods Minister Rebecca Pow has today (Wednesday) announced the first areas to receive money from the £100 million Frequently Flooded Allowance – and many of them are in Calderdale. Among the schemes listed to benefit from this funding is the Walsden FAS. This allowance targets communities where 10 or more properties have flooded twice or more in the last 10 years.','Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme Receives Government Funding','Halifax Courier','2023-04-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/hebden-bridge-copley-brighouse-and-more-calderdale-flood-hit-areas-will-get-chunk-of-ps100-million-government-fund-4091321','In April 2023, the Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme (FAS) was announced as one of the projects to receive funding from the Government\'s £100 million Frequently Flooded Allowance. This funding is dedicated to supporting flood defence initiatives in communities severely affected by repeated flooding across Calderdale.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1a6a63a3-762c-4dfd-82b6-17e70609f39b','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'1 Electric Vehicle (EV) Charging Station at Morrisons Wakefield (2). Stations maintained by MFG CPO and located at Dewsbury Road , Wakefield , WF2 9BY ,UK. Application Approved : Decision Issued Date : Tue 10 Dec 2024 24/01637/FUL| Creation of charging zone with erection of EV chargers, sub-station enclosure, LV panel, meter cabinet and associated works. https://planning.wakefield.gov.uk/online-applications/applicationDetails.do? activeTab=documents&keyVal=SK0MYRQQJT60.','Morrisons Wakefield (2) | Dewsbury Road, Wakefield, WF2 9BY, UK | EV Station - Planning Application Approved','PlugShare','2024-12-10 00:00:00.000','https://www.plugshare.com/location/587989','An electric vehicle charging station at Morrisons Wakefield on Dewsbury Road is associated with a planning application (24/01637/FUL) for the \'Creation of charging zone with erection of EV chargers, sub-station enclosure, LV panel, meter cabinet and associated works\'. The application was approved, with the decision issued on December 10, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1a9ee681-b498-4318-9667-62b85640ef8e','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'People around Leeds are being asked to have their say on major changes planned for Armley Gyratory. Leeds City Council wants to make several changes (detailed below), to try and improve traffic flow, reduce congestion and emissions and make it more accessible to pedestrians and cyclists. This includes plans to reduce the speed limit to 30mph and construct a road  and footpath that cut straight through the busy roundabout, which is used by around 100,000 vehicles a day. The council has launched a public consultation on the plans and people have until September 23 to comment. It wants to submit a planning application in autumn 2019, start construction in 2020 and complete the project within two years.','This is what Armley Gyratory could soon look like as major changes announced','Leeds Live','2019-08-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFV-jrFqUvd1HcHBIKTQUT2o_5dJ9PljYujtpFCWtD8yzrtSTChZg4Th7hCvwhYoNRU_lQAh4YAMqaPFobKaOwxbH7GzL-wK_03fv2NvoFDWnZzsPRlFl4GbqrZXRM7HqK64NERGsb7XZDe-VWPRgqHSMYluIYSITUFv_WoBroWQEMpijZYTCxr3EtwR80eYN3u2U4=','Leeds City Council launched a public consultation on major changes planned for Armley Gyratory, aiming to improve traffic flow, reduce congestion and emissions, and enhance accessibility for pedestrians and cyclists. The plans included reducing the speed limit to 30mph and constructing a new road and footpath through the roundabout. The consultation was open until September 23, 2019, with a planning application submission targeted for autumn 2019 and construction to start in 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1ace7c8c-fd3b-488a-96bb-8b3804123f89','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2020-06-12) Detailed plans to redevelop Armley Gyratory should be advanced as soon as possible and co-ordinate with other major highway schemes to minimise disruption to motorists, a Leeds City Council report has said. The council last year announced plans to revamp the roundabout, by building a new road that cuts straight through it and installing new crossings, traffic lights, footpaths and cycling and pedestrian walkways. The draft Armley Gyratory scheme.','Armley Gyratory improvement works move step closer to reality','West Leeds Dispatch','2020-06-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGqSdaIgyYwwTEi68XEvEkMkhk2aDxnrLHm2_imTSIIWDiATkGbB-ZwwR8lMaLSn8uDSB-a-78E3FhU01t3KiExIrHibhRH4UUFvkMFJBroW3NAai0yv2behHxB5_YSW2ET5d0Jf5f4Bu7_a3YrPDpBwoTUtyqFvnbM7UjYFcfbLTrQJUCMISWSHuoh3vClCSluZUMYmdKu','Leeds City Council highway officers approved the preliminary design of the Armley Gyratory improvement scheme and authorized the appointment of Balfour Beatty to carry out the work. A sum of £5 million was released to fund the detailed design phase. This step aimed to coordinate with other major highway schemes in Leeds, working towards the closure of City Square to general through traffic by 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1ad128fa-f703-42ca-916e-c5bdf9cb53f3','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Detailed plans for phase one were revealed today – 21 May – as part of Bradford Council\'s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock, which is running alongside this year\'s UKREiiF. [15] Phase one will include: Creation of 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. Featuring a mix of two and three-bedroom homes. A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces. Supporting infrastructure including safer roads, landscaped public spaces and active travel routes that promote walking and cycling. [15]','Detailed plans unveiled for first phase of \'City Village\' transformation','BusinessLive','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.business-live.co.uk/economic-development/detailed-plans-unveiled-first-phase-30310232','Detailed plans for Phase 1 of Bradford City Village were revealed, showcasing the creation of 33 townhouses on Chain Street and 64 townhouses on the northern Oastler site, alongside supporting infrastructure. This announcement was made during Bradford Council\'s Bradford Showcase event, coinciding with the launch of the final public consultation for Phase 1.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1aeb9177-7b16-4b5d-add0-29bb57c735ce','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2021-08-26) Renovation work of the Kellingley Social Club is underway to create flexible and multi-use spaces for the new Knottingley Community Hub. In this video Cllr Darren Byford explains why the Council is spending millions of pounds on this project while Chris Kitchen, Chair of the Board of Trustees of Kellingley Club, explains how this will be beneficial to residents of Ferrybridge and Knottingley.','Knottingley Community Hub development August 2021 Project Update','Wakefield Council (YouTube)','2021-08-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFTmKmYnVvHVYG9MBoMB284GFGxecplYmmN-_DWzYrBUi-qeg-rgY62PCao2CvjKqOO7sIBVyHSoefktDV8KGPT3QEYYGOksE4Lr5lz6NL86hsJ7JArmqYvaPqgdoibhL1oyx4W8vI=','A video update from Wakefield Council showing renovation work underway at the Kellingley Social Club to create a flexible, multi-use community hub. Cllr Darren Byford discusses the council\'s significant investment in the project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1b5c6583-1f84-434c-908b-d853e4ca2034','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Construction work has also now started on the Brighouse flood alleviation scheme, along the River Calder. Further work is also due to start this year at three additional sites, including Shaw Wood Road, Todmorden; Stubbing Holme Road, Hebden Bridge; and Copley.','Celebrating the distinctiveness of Calderdale and its flood programme','Calderdale Council News Centre','2023-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/celebrating-the-distinctiveness-of-calderdale-and-its-flood-programme/','Calderdale Council announced that further flood alleviation work was due to start in 2023 at three additional sites, including Stubbing Holme Road in Hebden Bridge. This was part of a broader programme of flood schemes across the borough.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1b781a40-ff34-440f-b2d6-69d70adcff8a','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work is set to begin on the £43.5 million transformation of Bradford City Centre with new public spaces and improved cycle lanes. According to Bradford Council, the plans will transform the \"look and feel\" of the centre, and work will begin on Monday, July 10. The funds are coming from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund.','Work to begin on \'ambitious\' £43.5m scheme to transform Bradford city centre','Yorkshire Live','2023-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/work-begin-ambitious-435m-scheme-27278272','Bradford Council announced that work was set to begin on the £43.5 million transformation of Bradford City Centre. The scheme, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund, aimed to create new public spaces, pedestrianise some roads, upgrade existing spaces with paving, landscaping, and green areas, and improve walking and cycling routes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1bd3aef1-1beb-4219-adb8-c356cd34461a','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Rangers have spoken of their pride at being involved in a major tree-planting scheme, as the landscape restoration project celebrates its first anniversary. Landscapes for Water is a partnership between the National Trust, Yorkshire Water, White Rose Forest, West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the Woodland Trust. The aim is to plant over 300,000 trees and install 3,500 leaky dams in the Upper Calder and Colne catchments, at sites such as Marsden Moor and Ryburn Reservoir. These initiatives not only aim to slow the flow of water off the steep valleys, reducing flood risk in downstream urban centres such as Halifax and Huddersfield, but they also look to increase biodiversity, capture carbon, reduce wildfire risks and improve water quality. Adam Nowak is volunteer and community officer at the National Trust and says they have already worked with nearly 1,500 children across eight schools.','Building a future for our children – Landscapes for Water celebrates its first anniversary','Huddersfield Hub','2025-02-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.huddersfieldhub.co.uk/building-a-future-for-our-children-landscapes-for-water-celebrates-its-first-anniversary/','On February 16, 2025, the Landscapes for Water project marked its first anniversary, celebrating significant progress in its mission. This partnership, involving the National Trust, Yorkshire Water, and other key organizations, aims to plant 300,000 trees and install 3,500 leaky dams in the Upper Calder and Colne catchments. The initiative has successfully engaged nearly 1,500 schoolchildren in tree planting and continues to focus on reducing flood risk, enhancing biodiversity, and capturing carbon.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1c2a1117-6f31-4467-b3f4-192bf92edcba','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The plans for the £22 million project were first proposed in 2019, and Government approved funding in March 2020 through its Transforming Cities Fund. The project, discussed by West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transport Committee on March 10, 2023, aims to make Bradford Interchange a \'world class gateway\' to the city. This involves the demolition of the Hall Ings car park and a new pedestrian entranceway to the Interchange. The scheme is to be completed by 2025 for Bradford\'s City of Culture celebrations.','£22m project at Bradford Interchange will create \'world class gateway\' to city','Telegraph and Argus / Yorkshire Post','2020-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHGPySS_oakmOqqZ0-z-xso1Dilf3QGeKYjZmdGU8XA2CfXkbvNoE71LMPcpzg8YCdIWUULrJ9HM9TpH8vQrked-rxzFeoHjxvmzcYh08A3VHNKLSBjqcImn7vCBofEPp3QSw4XYhnDFuvUvz_RvcPpEFrUs5s7IGoY51V12gJz6nqvsULiTBqIyJFk04d7sfz6a5a175aCL01N8xHSQZ1o21hOPUXHqrurwsE','Government approved funding for a £22 million project to improve access to Bradford Interchange in March 2020 through its Transforming Cities Fund. This project aimed to make the interchange a \'world class gateway\' to the city, including the demolition of the Hall Ings car park and the creation of a new pedestrian entranceway.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1d4ac0da-e445-4460-b8ae-9587a846e6e2','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Staff from the National Trust and Yorkshire Water recently invited Councillor Scott Patient (Calderdale Council\'s Deputy Leader and member of West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Climate, Energy and Environment Committee) for a tour of the latest conservation works around Baitings and Ryburn Reservoirs. The tour highlighted the installation of leaky dams, a form of natural flood management to slow the movement of rainwater during heavy rainfall, alleviating the risk of flooding in lower areas. This year, the project has seen the installation of 71 leaky dams around the Baitings area. The project\'s leaky dams have benefitted from £1.9 million worth of funding from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. The group also visited Ryburn Reservoir to observe the tree planting efforts that have taken place so far in a bid to tackle climate change. Since the start of the project, just over 31,500 trees have been planted in this area, with a total of 300,000 trees planned in the South Pennines as part of the five-year project plan.','Cllr Scott Patient applauds Landscapes for Water progress around Baitings and Ryburn Reservoirs','Hebden Bridge Web News','2025-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.hebdenbridge.co.uk/news/2025/007.html','On May 1, 2025, Councillor Scott Patient, Deputy Leader of Calderdale Council and a member of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority’s Climate, Energy and Environment Committee, visited the Landscapes for Water project around Baitings and Ryburn Reservoirs. During his tour, he observed the successful installation of 71 leaky dams in the Baitings area and noted significant tree planting efforts, with over 31,500 trees planted in this specific region. He emphasized the project\'s crucial role in addressing the climate emergency and enhancing protection for local communities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1d7fe80b-8e9f-493f-8689-0ca6096ad367','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'These tables show the capital funding allocations to local and combined authorities under the LEVI Fund and project status. ... West Yorkshire CA, £14,326,000, Approved for delivery.','Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) capital: funding amounts and project status (West Yorkshire CA)','GOV.UK','2025-07-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEAbksApGqtHV7CYPnDB4WAb0CBJmL4ypyzBekGioypUoporxcRnwd2x_N908xA9iUbQc8nB8dzQwLiLdiN63g9LHV66KZoZxGralLDDv2rx9N9PH6qmfxnaF_B-4uXNyX0t0kvcoxKfvONM962FqncThAGDfoMq1Y--sFtEp1zHCmWacTdqA0oCu7WwEJoUybwrZJKNrMpq_SH_KJsjMAUq48eG0ez3uwpIgN555y2QED-hDkua0RI7iQh0vMXIUuJ8eeWs92Rp7ab65LHl2Aq3GtTe_M=','This GOV.UK publication provides tables detailing the capital funding allocations to local and combined authorities under the LEVI Fund and their project status. It confirms that West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) was approved for delivery of £14,326,000 in LEVI capital funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1d9bc6a6-29a7-44b3-9440-c89db7f29712','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Leeds.gov.uk website references the \'Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030\'. This strategy guides the local authority\'s efforts in promoting and implementing EV charging solutions, often partnering with commercial entities for installations in retail and leisure settings. [13]','Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022-2030','Leeds City Council (Leeds.gov.uk)','2022-10-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/electric-vehicles/electric-vehicle-charging-in-leeds','Leeds City Council published its Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan for 2022 to 2030. This document outlines the council\'s approach to expanding EV charging infrastructure within the city, including requirements for new developments and collaboration with commercial partners.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1da07643-6de3-4a5f-b55b-6c2d7bfd1ac4','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Looking to improve water quality with a nature-based solution, Yorkshire Water set out to establish the Clayton West Integrated Constructed Wetland (ICW). The 43,000-square-metre (462,848-square-foot) free surface water wetland, which resides within a site double the size, is the largest ICW in the UK to treat stormwater overflow discharges. ... By incorporating over 300,000 plants, Clayton West aims to deliver an over 30 percent positive biodiversity net change (PBNC) across the site.','Clayton West Integrated Constructed Wetland','Stantec','2025-08-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG5bY-K_5bJCgxaBz3-hlUz3u9Z86BMI5fgmYQQ8G073U0PCPraZN5JjztuVS5EkdJvS5evsYF7gnEhzWyDG-GqKH3kBzKD-HMBAWenWdLvqeCN9m3PZrDQb_p7XeDDv4Qz_uVf_1ND9QwoPQzaBsJhquSSQk3dV4s-adHvu7h7T30ElH1T3pWzWuxGJkGP5SYjvWs44rdFzNpIFXHr8r7wAcsThQ==','Stantec\'s project overview describes the Clayton West Integrated Constructed Wetland (ICW) as the UK\'s largest ICW designed to treat stormwater overflow discharges. This 43,000-square-meter wetland, incorporating over 300,000 plants, aims for more than a 30% positive biodiversity net change and delivers substantial reductions in embodied and operational carbon compared to traditional engineering solutions. The project also created a public right of way, enhancing social value.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1e4c68c4-feec-4e66-954f-dfd66de349b5','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The transformation of Leeds City Station\'s main entrance is reaching its next milestone, with demolition works coming towards the end and construction due to begin in earnest in the New Year. The Leeds City Station Sustainable Travel Gateway scheme is being delivered at the same time as essential maintenance work by Network Rail to reinforce the underground structure below New Station Street, which supports much of the station above it. The £46.1m Sustainable Travel Gateway scheme is being delivered by Leeds City Council on behalf of Network Rail as the landowner, and in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [6, 11]','Leeds City Station: laying the foundations for New Year construction','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2023-12-12 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/leeds-city-station-laying-the-foundations-for-new-year-construction','An update from Leeds City Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority highlighted that demolition works at Leeds City Station\'s main entrance were concluding, with main construction for the Sustainable Travel Gateway scheme set to begin in the New Year. The scheme, which includes pedestrianising New Station Street and installing new passenger lifts, is being delivered concurrently with Network Rail\'s essential maintenance to the underground Mill Goit structure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1ea9fd5d-85fa-4750-93be-c476412e2f1b','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following a public consultation in 2020 seeking feedback about a busy junction on the A6120, (Leeds Outer Ring Road) preliminary works will be starting this week. The Fink Hill junction is north of Horsforth Roundabout. Consultation took place in 2020 on an improvement scheme to reduce delays and enhance pedestrian safety. We are making changes to address the current issues at Fink Hill. There is a lack of pedestrian and cycle facilities causing severance between communities and businesses north and south of the Ring Road in Horsforth. This scheme is part of West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Corridor Improvement Programme.','Public Consultation on Fink Hill Junction Improvements','Leeds City Council / Commonplace / AWS','2020-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGuA4ZgJEtSXUU3e7fX4GtXuJx3PrKSBUvrzNYb-OswSt2D9QWRnMzVcdzwMX4sVVEq0dIV19oGnjyRKJttUox-Sg89fpeVAjS6sfVQHOhOGeQ26hrzImmbvImEj5wJyNy_fxaqb60v7CJ7Ai3xojfr4hiXFnAvLyI0jslslY9aQ60fSSmclqRzIEuFzXVcHwGrGdwciQ4XQeJp4ijf7fetROb-aiYRGJVpFsf4_4W1EA28fvaXhADpQu20_C0=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG1BeJsY8mrfcKeZ_T0PM-bQPni9N75OASQAXZfmd8XVvkQbSmZH2eao_qQwZmxw5rv7SG4BfrcqzPKLU86ie_4a_aW-fx7ZXYiCdngrLvTJPO1KP2j-03Mb-nn9jA7b5dzx0CGqw==','A public consultation was carried out in 2020 seeking feedback about improvements to the busy Fink Hill junction on the A6120 Leeds Outer Ring Road. This consultation aimed to address issues such as a lack of pedestrian and cycle facilities and to improve safety for all users by enhancing the road layout. The scheme is part of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Corridor Improvement Programme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1ec40feb-2970-4bad-a419-1f28b6bc653d','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This year, connections have been completed at Leeds Conservatoire and the former Technology Campus Student Residential development and both sites are now receiving heat from the network. [10]','Leeds low carbon heat network set to expand to thousands more residents','Modern Building Services','2024-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.modbs.co.uk/news/full/leeds-low-carbon-heat-network-set-to-expand-to-thousands-more-residents','Further details on the expansion of the Leeds PIPES network, confirming that connections at Leeds Conservatoire and the former Technology Campus Student Residential development have been completed, and both sites are now receiving heat from the network. This news follows a £24.5m funding boost for the network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1edd92e7-6c81-4a46-9912-4e07791d9ff3','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Mott MacDonald Bentley provided design and build services on behalf of Yorkshire Water to deliver an innovative nature-based solution for wastewater treatment. An integrated constructed wetland totalling 4.3ha of planted area was constructed to treat storm flows, reduce levels of ammonia... This webinar took place on 25 February 2025.','Dearne Reach An Integrated Constructed Wetland for wastewater treatment (Webinar)','YouTube (Tyne & Humber)','2025-02-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGIyY3OQBoICFwFvgLpbyNtJTyr4-LVP94QU_nW7mwo_PGbvFggd7-1LHgFXtm6VSWi_8zNyJ1nfPFGttjND-iw9sGFUinD7bYQrec3-eKfk-IcKPo9QEEmU_brDxBwRMKmvJWBVmg==','Olivia Rowe, a project leader at Mott MacDonald Bentley, presented a webinar on the Dearne Reach project at Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works. The webinar provided an overview of the design and construction of a 4.3-hectare integrated constructed wetland, which aims to treat storm flows, reduce ammonia levels, and improve 4.1km of the River Dearne. It emphasized the sustainable environmental and social benefits of this nature-based solution.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1ee35afb-81ad-490e-9476-b77f706b162d','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first round of consultations for the cycleway was held between July and August 2021. [4] Following our first round of consultation between July and August 2021, we reviewed the design of the scheme in response to feedback and have made some changes to the proposals. [16]','West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension First Public Consultation','West Yorkshire Combined Authority \'Your Voice\' / Bradford & Keighley News','2021-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/thorntoncycle','Bradford Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority conducted the first public consultation for the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension. This initial phase sought feedback on proposals to extend the existing Bradford-Leeds Cycle Superhighway to Thornton village along Thornton Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1f513f60-59d5-4a41-aae5-7c51af1a3b28','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This consultation is now focusing on improvements at Cooper Bridge junction only. Works at Bradley junction will be looked at as part of a future phase. ... The consultation period for the revised plans will run from Monday 28 October until Sunday 8 December 2024.','Second Public Consultation for Cooper Bridge Junction Improvements (Phase 1)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority / Kirklees Together','2024-10-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/CooperBridge','A second public consultation for the A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme ran from October 28 to December 8, 2024. This consultation focused solely on improvements at the Cooper Bridge roundabout, presenting three options, and incorporated feedback from previous rounds, including environmental impacts and bus priority. [5, 7, 8, 10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1f6c8de7-2c0a-41f3-a5b2-5f9825aa4f03','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work to further boost flood protection in Calderdale could soon be given the go ahead. At Calderdale Council\'s next Cabinet meeting on Monday 2 June 2025, Councillors will be asked to accept external grants worth nearly £2 million to strengthen flood defences and reduce the impacts of flooding in areas most at risk. The proposed two-year flood risk management works programme would build on the substantial progress already made to strengthen defences, carry out natural flood management and improve community and infrastructure resilience. Together, Calderdale Council and its partner organisations on the Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Board have secured £133 million since 2012. They have put this to use through projects to help combat flood risk in line with the Calderdale Flood Action Plan. The Council has identified DEFRA Flood Defence Grant in Aid and the Yorkshire Region Flood and Coastal Committees (YRFCC) Local Levy as the main sources of funding for the new projects. This would provide nearly £2 million up until 2027, if approved by Cabinet Members and the funders.','Calderdale Council to Accept Nearly £2 Million in External Grants for Flood Protection','Calderdale Council News Centre - Boosting flood protection in Calderdale','2025-06-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFrAeVLDxhVodG4FMVQtx9B_oF0PhsIhpMjTW-UNWDIjTxTOoDfH4OlM67JGKSOHpViuxp8eeJwE4p6EG4mr5i6HpYbkXtnR9h3P8Kmk_e14QVi5iq4-Rk8wjawsYfYYaRohftBN26bPRTAHURokjCaO00rXzJIKWAzDudcnTjPaTi0','On June 2, 2025, Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet is set to approve the acceptance of nearly £2 million in external grants. This funding will support a two-year flood risk management works programme until 2027, further strengthening flood defences and enhancing community and infrastructure resilience across Calderdale.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1f73a1ed-6e7f-481c-966f-c36d8414d982','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council extended the deadline for public consultation on its flagship Transforming Cities Fund proposals to Wednesday 22 September 2021. The consultation covered four major transport-related projects, developed in conjunction with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. These proposals aim to transform Bradford\'s city centre environment, improve options for public transport, cycling, and walking, facilitate major regeneration, and benefit residents and visitors. Schemes include city centre walking and cycling improvements, a pedestrianised approach to Bradford Interchange, an extension to the Leeds-Bradford Cycle Superhighway, and a new Park and Ride site with a bus expressway. [15, 22]','Bradford\'s £80 million Transforming Cities Fund Proposals Public Consultation Extended','Bradford Means Business / UKREiiF','2021-09-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHzaFxSozyMWcw9111MRTAMbxtTmWybGaYflRL3iS8oLb005yqHzX-50ZL9biOsy9Cp_Ore0J9szOKbtgDouJ09YLTN_PSHpBSgKLyqj_DXBuEe4nGww_-xODgY5LqRlel9H-S_QJx-qJKsf9UmpyB-RClraz2nu5JRcbnPcH0k6tHnUlifZQ_I4NFr-qio_xp84Onf__itUAr6VnPZR-qAL8k1GfMBBJgDbcFAWKqI8jFcrrwMzC1YqOKNvvcs6-Yf6A==','Bradford Council, in collaboration with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a significant public consultation on its £80 million Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) proposals. These four major transport-related projects are designed to reshape Bradford city centre, reducing traffic and enhancing air quality. The plans include improvements to the city centre environment, a new pedestrianised approach to Bradford Interchange, an extension to the Leeds-Bradford Cycle Superhighway to the west, and a new Park and Ride site adjacent to Junction 2 of the M606 with a complementary Bus Expressway. The consultation period was extended, with a final closing date of September 22, 2021, to allow greater public input.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1f809688-8df9-4eda-bf73-7865e82ab924','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We are pleased to see the allocation of £29.9 million to Bradford Council through Homes England\'s Brownfield Infrastructure & Land (BIL) funding for its Bradford City Village project. The grant funding will be used to deliver around 1,000 new homes along with retail and leisure spaces including three community parks, right in the heart of Bradford city centre. [3]','£30m allocation for Bradford City Village development','Northern Housing Consortium','2024-11-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.northern-housing.org.uk/news/30m-allocation-for-bradford-city-village-development/','Homes England allocated £29.9 million to Bradford Council through its Brownfield Infrastructure & Land (BIL) funding for the Bradford City Village project. This grant is intended to deliver approximately 1,000 new homes, along with retail, leisure spaces, and three community parks in Bradford city centre. Senior civil servants from MHCLG visited the site in May to review the plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('1fd8c98b-9507-4c9f-ae1f-6c31d5bfa75a','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The area of public realm surrounding the HS2 Leeds station would provide some visual integration and enhance the setting for recreational users of the waterfront along the River Aire... Engagement with Leeds City Council (LCC), West Yorkshire Combined Authorities and Historic England has commenced. [20]','High Speed Rail (Crewe to Manchester and West Midlands to Leeds) Working draft Environmental Statement Volume 2: LA18','GOV.UK','2018-10-02 00:00:00.000','https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/746815/LA18_working_draft_ES_report.pdf','This working draft Environmental Statement, prepared for HS2, considers the environmental impact of proposed high-speed rail developments in Leeds, including mentions of the public realm surrounding the HS2 Leeds station. It notes that this public realm would provide visual integration and enhance the setting for recreational users, with ongoing engagement with Leeds City Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('200c3552-9bba-484e-b42a-b91083dd8ec3','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The application was submitted 22nd April 2016 and approval was granted unanimously at planning committee on 6th October 2016. Climate Innovation District Phase 2. Project. Winner. Planning Application Link View map. Number/street name: Clarence Road. Address line 2: City: Leeds. Postcode: LS10 1ND. Architect: Ollier Smurthwaite Architects. Developer: CITU Group LLP. Planning Authority: Leeds City Council. Planning Reference: 16/02420/FU.','Planning Approval Granted for Climate Innovation District Phase 2','Housing Design Awards','2016-10-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFrY7AACkDq25PhtyHUcPomePMshagj6LAd7pqQZb09VMs8TDwrxvDxK0xlBSIAHppI5LA0Vl1jARs3MgA0YbB1y7--ObMmyi0TSyDRfn7Chv5gIhyuJ11cH5W_GWeVx6o_r8IpNYBIZ_PRKvQ84NvcHM4BD5BQQMOyRkA=','Leeds City Council unanimously granted planning approval for Phase 2 of the Climate Innovation District. The application, submitted in April 2016, included plans for 204 dwellings and two commercial units, car parking, landscaping, and public realm along Clarence Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('20128971-7064-4d0f-8dd9-7b8474e317d4','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BRADFORD\'S year as City of Culture got off to a spectacular start with an opening event that featured choirs, orchestras, rappers and magic from hometown hero Dynamo. RISE, held in City Park, is estimated to have attracted around 10,000 people. A choir performed on the steps of Bradford and Keighley Magistrates\' Court while an orchestra played in One City Park, an office building overlooking the crowd. One City Park will feature prominently throughout the year as a signal of Bradford\'s quality, prosperity, and opportunity and played a key part in \'RISE\' the recent opening ceremony for the City of Culture year.','Thousands enjoy spectacular start to Bradford\'s City of Culture year / Our Sustainable Future case study: One City Park, Bradford','Telegraph and Argus / Muse','2025-01-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHGuVtoKaF8WfKiCmkh1ecqCvQSIL-I3lWHWR9w-2zXOdi5M3NW2hfMcyUORc7wNnm2ht8k6_AfTnsMitbS3e1VZU5nCMoeBuLz9oknGrhIF1pZYOAQXdvAqK2FtjuHh38BMGoR-_52yw44k6ikjsZmwqnviJ7-jB3Ffz9UXFDdrtun0bHleN9H47E3W-Gdm6ygXtmiOUU_NoGt4nk-NA9MIJTIQkYYuzDy05P-Iw==','One City Park played a prominent role in the \'RISE\' opening ceremony for Bradford\'s UK City of Culture 2025. An orchestra performed in the office building overlooking City Park during the spectacular outdoor theatrical event, highlighting the building as a landmark for the City of Culture year.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('202098ae-03a2-42a4-85c5-57ee67eb4168','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Recent additions to the network include Leeds Conservatoire, Tec Campus, and social housing at Lovell Park, with new installations planned at Leonora House and 24-28 Great George Street. ... Patsy Gilbert, vice principal at Leeds Conservatoire, shared: “Leeds Conservatoire is committed to continuing its path towards finding more environmentally sustainable ways of offering high-quality education environments for all of our community. “We are thrilled to be joining organisations across Leeds as part of the district heating network as a substantial part of that commitment. [13]','Leeds PIPES connects 3000+ dwellings, celebrates major milestone','Vital Energi','2024-11-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.vitalenergi.co.uk/news/leeds-pipes-connects-3000-dwellings-celebrates-major-milestone/','This article celebrates a significant milestone for Leeds PIPES, having connected over 3,000 dwellings. It explicitly lists Leeds Conservatoire as one of the recent additions to the network, and includes a quote from Patsy Gilbert, Vice Principal at Leeds Conservatoire, expressing enthusiasm for the connection as part of their environmental sustainability commitment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2038d00d-c3f9-4423-a7c4-a9dfe1823c63','infrastructure-pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.548','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been submitted for a rooftop solar farm at Pinderfield\'s Hospital as part of a government-backed green energy project. The £2.7 million scheme involves placing panels on top of eight buildings within the site in Wakefield and would contribute to an NHS trust\'s net zero ambitions. The initiative aims to cut energy bills at the sites, allowing savings to be reinvested into delivering more frontline services for patients. Once installed, the projects are estimated to save the NHS an additional £8.6 million each year, ultimately contributing up to £260 million in savings over their lifetime. [9]','Pinderfields Hospital to receive solar panels as part of government scheme','YouTube (channel not specified but content from news report)','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0k57_jWlK7Y','A YouTube news report summarized the submission of plans for the Pinderfields Hospital rooftop solar farm, reiterating the £2.7 million investment and its aim to cut energy bills and contribute to NHS net-zero goals. The project is estimated to save the NHS an additional £8.6 million each year.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2060b67d-0417-43a9-9167-bb2bc636e123','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched the first public consultation on Mass Transit, presenting early plans for a new tram network to connect Leeds and Bradford. The consultation invited public feedback on various proposed route options for the Leeds Line and Bradford Line, running from July 15 to September 30, 2024.','West Yorkshire Mass Transit Public Consultation on Phase One Route Options','Caring Together in Woodhouse and Little London / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFt2TdkUIjUPBn-oNn1RdhjnfdlDLpizU3fa7-ZhT6PleV2wEM6_a_ZOj3XfvQLkpXHI5qicDIG-92tE1LISTQ7eU2iMllxoTGLVd0UWXnmTr6vSB2V-4cyaZBQgMo1VuYrCoSHsQNO1I7PDfdr4cYiObmNQMYape3_f6PkIKUbKCJ0ZGuJ2kDK','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched the first public consultation on Mass Transit, presenting early plans for a new tram network to connect Leeds and Bradford. The consultation invited public feedback on various proposed route options for the Leeds Line and Bradford Line, running from July 15 to September 30, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
