	('20a298cb-62f7-426e-bc54-dd6d785ad610','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Charging station with fast-chargers for electric vehicles (EV). 4 outlets, max capacity: 75 kW. Network: Engenie Ltd. - (GBOSP). ... Woolpack Inn, Leeds Charging stations for EV in Leeds.','Woolpack Inn, Leeds EV Charging Station Technical Specifications on ChargeFinder','ChargeFinder','2022-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGb_cMaHS1vR4Jy3KRc5BsKGbpcwiPqqqTfV3dspfZpBYVHfKyf9XP54iXq6zQumHSV5jOB5_T80YfogIVKeNntpZIMjhgM_659EUvIj1P36y1-5reVIoYJ97lUqXF0vkvs15ozRE01pUwwWXFRrfN_uYj_tA5aqgaxghp1bNg33Zbg6WXDWw==','ChargeFinder listed the Woolpack Inn, Leeds, as an EV charging station with 4 outlets and a maximum capacity of 75 kW, part of the Engenie Ltd. (GBOSP) network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('20ed79a5-f26e-48f7-b033-139ec168db92','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Application for a non-material amendment to 23/03322/FU for an electric vehicle charging facility and retail unit. Changes include reducing the retail unit\'s height, shortening the shopfront canopy, removing some glazing on the eastern side, adding a roof safety barrier, altering the EV charging bay canopies, relocating 3 trees, and removing and reorienting electrical cabinets. Non Material Amendment. The White Bear, Dewsbury Road, Tingley, Wakefield. W/C 13/01/2025.','Planning Application 25/9/00006/MOD Details — Leeds','Leeds City Council Planning Portal','2025-01-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHmmWkWWVnn3Qsn2z_MZw2G8E74qPzFQZYh-jk82P-xP-SyMB9EeGTdCTP1cvy5fjgykYIJhta8MDstthQFZK0OnIXCb94_5_06ExeKsk45PNRmnUMFQL4JE_JGDtTTp4aFhZg-4bt33IDuvmgbZ-GO0KOm6AiJNA==','A non-material amendment (application 25/9/00006/MOD) was submitted to Leeds City Council for the electric vehicle charging facility and retail unit at The White Bear, Dewsbury Road, Tingley. The amendment details minor changes, including reducing the retail unit\'s height and altering the EV charging bay canopies.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2134229d-c823-4914-851d-60e851bebfcf','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'First established in 2016 with the purpose of providing support and grant funding to SMEs, the third iteration of Digital Enterprise (DE3) was launched in July 2023. Funded by the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, DE3 provides access to much-needed funding and support to West Yorkshire SMEs in the form of match-funded grants. Over the past eight years Digital Enterprise have supported more than 2,500 businesses and awarded over £13.5m in funding. [16]','UMi supports Digital Enterprise 3 to celebrate digital adoption across West Yorkshire','UMi','2023-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.weareumi.com/news/umi-supports-digital-enterprise-3-to-celebrate-digital-adoption-across-west-yorkshire','This article highlights the launch of the third iteration of Digital Enterprise (DE3) in July 2023. Funded by the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, DE3 provides match-funded grants and support to West Yorkshire SMEs. It mentions that since its establishment in 2016, Digital Enterprise has supported over 2,500 businesses with more than £13.5m in funding. The campaign aims to showcase the achievements of businesses that received DE support.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2143c1dc-63a5-4a3b-b823-f9524732a4a6','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-weaver-network',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.799','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Over 5,000 environmental surveys have been carried out as plans for a new tram line between Bradford and Leeds gather pace. ... The report to a committee meeting next Thursday says: “To comply with the Mass Transit overall programme, preparation work for the Environmental Impact Assessment has been progressed, noise and air quality modelling has commenced to support these deliverables. “Land access for 869 sites across the Leeds and Bradford lines has been agreed, and over 5,000 surveys covering bats, birds and badgers have been undertaken.” [8, 11, 14]','Over 5,000 Environmental Surveys Completed for Bradford-Leeds Mass Transit Route','Yorkshire Evening Post / Telegraph and Argus','2025-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/transport/leeds-trams-over-5000-environmental-surveys-carried-out-as-mass-transit-plans-gather-pace-4338947','More than 5,000 environmental surveys, including those for bats, birds, and badgers, have been completed across 869 sites between Leeds and Bradford. This work forms a crucial part of the preparation for the Mass Transit system\'s Environmental Impact Assessment, with noise and air quality modeling also underway.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2153cbb8-36ef-448d-8e2c-bb4f644ae02b','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The ASAS complements the LBA Strategic Development Plan (SDP), ensuring there is a joined up approach to airport operations, land use planning and transport. The SDP and the ASAS together provide a clear statement of intent to enable future development of the Airport to be given due consideration in local planning processes. The need for improved access to the airport has long been an aim for the council, helping to support one of the fastest-growing airports in the UK which already contributes more than £336m annually to the regional economy and is forecast to see passenger numbers increase to 7.1m by 2030 and to 9m by 2050. [13, 8]','Leeds Bradford Airport Strategic Development Plan – Surface Access Strategy','Leeds Bradford Airport (via AWS)','2017-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://route-to-2030-strategic-development-plan-update.pdf','Leeds Bradford Airport published its Strategic Development Plan (SDP) and accompanying Surface Access Strategy (ASAS). These documents set out a clear intent for the airport\'s future development and address the need for improved access to accommodate forecast passenger growth, which was predicted to reach 7.1 million by 2030 and 9 million by 2050.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('21f620ad-fb4a-4e98-90ae-ab5aa5d59326','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The latest plans to upgrade Huddersfield\'s 1970s Bus Station have been revealed – and the investment has been doubled to just short of £20 million. It had been thought that the improvements would cost around £9 million but latest estimates put the cost at £19.9 million. The bus station will undergo a major revamp both inside and out and the most striking feature will be a sweeping canopy with a living grass roof which will run right across the main frontage from Macaulay Square to Upperhead Row. Underneath the canopy there will be a \'cycle hub\' for bike parking as well as seating and new planters. ... The scheme will include some of the latest carbon reduction methods such as solar panels, an air source heat pump and low energy fittings. The investment will be a partnership between West Yorkshire Combined Authority, which owns the bus station, and Kirklees Council, which owns the car park above. The bulk of the money (£18.99 million) will come from the Combined Authority via the Transforming Cities Fund while Kirklees will contribute £1 million.','New-look £20 million Huddersfield Bus Station will have sweeping canopy and real grass growing on roof','Huddersfield Hub','2022-10-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGjAalcFnFrH5BvE_9qfAgTr6LyL0ZoAY8ts7Wad5J7UXtrQrE7guj8EqgOBKrdg1qek15FMQssf5YAwxcUK4ZxSRfTEALL0Jhw-Xxb9nAAE8YNzdeHwO6G654NHMUtycw2k3CFr_TljWN11Sn-qhLYwUeopxGz4MkKZ80rWNjFdOiN4py80oiDVj54AFNUS0HwaKIEp8SijRRvlHLYB--mS9Sek_75G8okLh3iGWJRwiSYdMUHvDIYcV2c1xFkwseOrA4WPIGT2dfZUA==','Updated plans for the Huddersfield Bus Station revamp were revealed, with the estimated cost increasing to nearly £20 million. Key features included a sweeping canopy with a living grass roof, a \'cycle hub\', enlarged Henry Street entrance, and interior modernizations. The scheme, funded by WYCA (Transforming Cities Fund) and Kirklees Council, aimed for improved accessibility, safety, and sustainability.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('223bea12-2cbb-4d74-a1b9-8596572fbfa8','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council\'s Energy Savers scheme aims to help people save energy and enjoy a warmer home. Thanks to a £100,000 investment, free cavity wall and loft insulation is available for homeowners and private rented tenants that qualify. Free gas central heating upgrades are also available for private rented tenants that qualify. [10]','Energy Savers Scheme secures additional funding to provide more support - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2025-06-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGW2vebcWwjWxgd3zDJoaWiasShQU6XMR5nPgQHqI78fkCwqTHzdhE9saske04tXnguE3GZPezd5GTnqJfbLAkWZz0SYiLpPLAZMtHkM_CQuSnab8c-kxPPzG3T6oNn9oMnTOrwZLt-_DErR6WtoJK1FAkP1SwH7KlNzX-DchzK8_z5CZGFQNyQ2WCvoXMHb88vRyF7ZZsqaf_e6EbUAlQUUsWGx7YpA7Y_9IIRpw==','Wakefield Council announced on June 26, 2025, that its Energy Savers scheme has secured an additional £100,000 investment. This funding provides free cavity wall and loft insulation for qualifying homeowners and private rented tenants, as well as free gas central heating upgrades for eligible private rented tenants in the Wakefield district. Landlord approval and membership in the Responsible Landlord Scheme are required for private tenants.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2240b43a-2b7f-405b-9b3f-fddd7682d378','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Integrated Rail Plan for the North and Midlands (IRP) is a government document that was published on 18 November 2021. This document says that the line from Leeds to Bradford Interchange will be electrified. [7] A3 Leeds-Bradford electrification is also welcome, but we are disappointed that this is not described as a first phase of the full Calder Valley Line electrification that was given top ranking by the 2015 Northern Sparks task force report. [14]','Integrated Rail Plan for the North and Midlands (IRP) Publication','Government (Integrated Rail Plan)','2021-11-18 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEXXJTkaxryQlOCLVZWineUfMRTVAyVu-XGH_SIxBBw7ExEc4uF9zdopF1gzhnAyqbjRvw29czJZ0Mxkt5wpFByYD1fWr5JZ5l62aZ6_cVUh02atKS_ZCaj5Ht9OkBSFACa87iqvmU0dh20Mg==','The government\'s Integrated Rail Plan (IRP) for the North and Midlands was published, stating that the railway line from Leeds to Bradford Interchange would be electrified. This was a key government document outlining rail investment for the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('227d170b-5b4e-4a29-a696-141a1e57ba45','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Everybody Arts are working with Calderdale Council\'s Capital Regeneration team to develop new public art commissions for Art & About, a new arts and cultural trail for Halifax. Including a Poetry commission to be installed near Halifax Central Library and a Sound Art commission for Halifax Town Hall. Interested? Read the details below. Date: Deadline: 01/05/2024, 12pm. [17]','Call for Poetry and Sound Art Commissions for Art & About Trail','Culturedale Noticeboard','2024-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHDKUDTh8I8ChRXU4oe99nMI35QXPZ7w0UzjihvV94pSMljC8paMqnmJlrXaaqe9ZtCihZIHxcUMTI_keUsmR0cyAeNk8knNmfPuQaNylk4dvfJbpnT2c3MwIniXUHWm6asvmaw','Everybody Arts, in collaboration with Calderdale Council\'s Capital Regeneration team, sought submissions for new public art commissions for the Art & About Trail. This included a Poetry commission for Halifax Central Library and a Sound Art commission for Halifax Town Hall, with a submission deadline of May 1, 2024. [17]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('22af8864-5358-41ad-a316-bb944f73e39f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for a tram system running in West Yorkshire have been set out as the West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin aims to revolutionise the region\'s transport network. The Combined Authority will continue to work with local authorities to ensure that future phases of a mass transit network reach Wakefield, Kirklees and Calderdale, ensuring no part of West Yorkshire is left behind. It is hoped that spades will be in the ground in 2028 when construction of the early stage of the project will begin. The Combined Authority will ask the public to have their say in the summer on the possible routes, with the two “phase one” Leeds and Bradford lines expected to be joined later by potential further schemes covering the rest of the region.','Mayor sets out plan for tram system as Wakefield, Calderdale and Kirklees to be part of mass transit network','Halifax Courier','2024-03-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE0iRkJzaWfbfTcAfa6_3Xs6ctfMSVpy6hCUwSCnhjTH_OQxo9GWN--Ta8-DfVx_lxI55MTKXJrdOUP8KKs11iOiOyA0TikKIfJUosV4APPtGCoxci-yxYuFrakCewQOve2oFm3INM2vfnbR2cH8GXAETg9ezMGDqhcktFvtFbxkiqHTVw_Ga6KhyJHGbz6pzivVe7Wmu-T1fMlVeJcFnNg0f0RXHX3bmArO-f73G8ycLAC69Hdp4Cw-TSouwKdUUemXrfG33t','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin outlined plans for a tram system, confirming that while Phase One would focus on Leeds and Bradford lines, future phases would extend to Wakefield, Kirklees, and Calderdale to ensure no part of West Yorkshire is left behind. A public consultation on the initial Leeds and Bradford routes was announced for summer 2024, with construction hoped to begin in 2028.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('22b14dfd-ec13-48cb-98dc-2a12c6a6b598','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield is on the brink of a transformative journey aimed at redefining its city centre and boosting inward investment. Unveiled at the UK Real Estate Investment and Infrastructure Forum (UKREiiF), Wakefield Council\'s comprehensive plan introduces a Strategic Regeneration Partner to propel the vision and stimulate growth in Wakefield City Centre. Collaboration with West Yorkshire Combined Authority. The council\'s efforts are further supported by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Homes England, who have identified Wakefield City Centre as a strategic focus area.','Wakefield City Centre Set for Transformative Journey with Strategic Regeneration Partnership','Yorkshire.com','2024-05-23 00:00:00.000','https://yorkshire.com/business-hub/transformative-journey-for-wakefield-city-centre/','Wakefield Council unveiled ambitious plans at the UK Real Estate Investment and Infrastructure Forum (UKREiiF) to redefine its city centre through a Strategic Regeneration Partnership. This initiative aims to foster collaboration between public and private sectors, integrating diverse investments to create a more dynamic and interconnected cityscape, with support from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Homes England.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('22c8d411-6a19-4597-98b6-aafa3efabc28','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A new project is set to help wildlife thrive, cut carbon, boost flood resilience and reduce wildfire risk in Calderdale and Kirklees. Working with partner organisations, Calderdale and Kirklees Councils have secured grant funding to prepare for a large-scale project to restore moorlands, plant trees and create wildlife-rich habitats that better connect valley towns with moorland tops along the rivers Calder and Colne. The \'Calder and Colne Landscape Links\' (CCaLL) project is funded by £750,000 from the second round of the Government\'s Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs (Defra) Landscape Recovery programme, and £100,000 from the Yorkshire Regional Flood and Coastal Committee. The project was designed and will be delivered by a partnership of organisations including Calderdale and Kirklees Councils, the Calder and Colne Rivers Trust, Environmental Projects in Kirklees (EPIKs) and Moors for the Future Partnership, with support from the Environment Agency. The restoration efforts will cover approximately 10,000 hectares of the Colne and Upper Calder Valley.','Restoring landscapes from towns to tops (Calder and Colne Landscape Links - CCaLL project)','Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-05-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/restoring-landscapes-from-towns-to-tops/index.html','The \'Calder and Colne Landscape Links\' (CCaLL) project, a complementary initiative, was announced by Calderdale and Kirklees Councils. It secured £750,000 from Defra\'s Landscape Recovery programme and £100,000 from the Yorkshire Regional Flood and Coastal Committee. This two-year initial phase aims to restore moorlands, plant trees, and create wildlife-rich habitats across 10,000 hectares in the Colne and Upper Calder Valley to enhance flood resilience, cut carbon, and boost biodiversity.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('23173ac4-f752-4720-9b32-05acfd59ae12','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This year saw the market revitalisation project take a major step forward. Demolition of the canalside site began back in October with the work expected to take around a year. The transformed permanent market building will have 21 fixed stalls, each with water, drainage and power. [11] Another project that was the first to be delivered this year was Brighouse Industry 4.0 with the opening of the skills hub. The project has seen £650,000 put into high-tech manufacturing at the heart of the town\'s future by creating an Industry 4.0 Hub where small and medium sized businesses can explore how digital technology can improve their productivity and increase innovation. The Hub, part of the Brighouse Town Deal programme led by Calderdale Council and the Brighouse Town Board and delivered by a partnership between Calderdale College, launched in July. [11]','Progress made on £19.1 million projects including Brighouse Market and Industry 4.0 Hub','Halifax Courier','2024-12-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/brighouse-town-deal-progress-made-on-ps191-million-government-funded-projects-in-2024-including-brighouse-market-4460613','By December 2024, significant progress was reported on the Brighouse Town Deal projects. Demolition for the canalside market revitalisation project began in October, with work expected to take a year. Additionally, the Brighouse Industry 4.0 Hub, a skills hub, was launched in July as the first delivered project, investing £650,000 in high-tech manufacturing skills.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2319e3f0-88d1-4b8e-b638-d4b20f1a8454','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council has said following positive feedback from schools and parents on the temporary road closures outside schools, the Council is proposing to make the \'School Streets\' permanent. It is consulting with Ward Councillors and working to get more schools on board for the new term in September. According to the Council the borough\'s schools and parents have reported benefits including easier social distancing, safer walking and cycling, cleaner air and a more enjoyable environment. The scheme was introduced to number of roads outside Calderdale schools in June. Roads outside 14 Calderdale schools were closed to cars and other motorised traffic at school drop-off and pick-up times.','Proposals to make Calderdale school road closures permanent and expand them across the borough','Halifax Courier','2020-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHbHvdn9BAjT1u3eYW1CD3FH2-jYkpoN4n5vpUTh32drtSPTjw0twdvS3o__8P8n0Y1JbCtvG8DCEchiti5dEbUt1lJepDm6rEqnshf64BezzJQYzyDiuGTHlOkk0XHAlmaPK8Ace8g-u6yC5xA_y5C6c5Y9Xqh-iJ_FMGT_IslQ56LpsTX81Y_9z3Vo__0s65_8s_oeap6zqAsSt2LfTgdKoHANpr394s0SZTiuNAQGfYpvqEi4MoSFC2N22zbK1OFc0RISgots9ifPNYh','Calderdale Council considered making temporary \'School Streets\' road closures permanent after positive feedback from schools and parents, reporting benefits like easier social distancing, safer walking and cycling, and cleaner air. The Council was consulting with Ward Councillors and aimed to involve more schools for the new term in September.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('232a79f8-e351-4902-aa75-3ea02a0c693b','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.902','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of the A629 Phase 2 Halifax Town Centre Corridor Improvement project, a new one-way system on Powell Street came into force on September 8, 2025. The system was reversed to operate in a northerly direction from Fountain Street to Rawson Street. Additional elements of the project\'s proposals also came into force on May 20, 2025.','New Powell Street one-way system implemented as part of A629 Phase 2 improvements','Calderdale Council','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/streets-and-transport/transport-improvements-and-initiatives/a629-phase-2-halifax-town-centre-western-corridor','As part of the A629 Phase 2 Halifax Town Centre Corridor Improvement project, a new one-way system on Powell Street came into force on September 8, 2025. The system was reversed to operate in a northerly direction from Fountain Street to Rawson Street. Additional elements of the project\'s proposals also came into force on May 20, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('23d73582-8b36-440f-a54f-f659ac6ad5b5','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Around £2m worth of compensation has been paid out to neighbours of Wakefield\'s eastern relief road. Wakefield Council said it had reached settlements with 400 people whose properties all fell in value because the bypass, now named Neil Fox Way, was built (Source 13).','Neighbours of Wakefield\'s eastern relief road get £2m in compensation','Wakefield Express','2020-06-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF39nY3aAaiT9YWSI-VT9j0_TpHk4TOQXUXWzpk1LNrl5TXyPQhAHEHlh5lPSPQ096qy3vyp03XOwIwn8mTx6MmEqCXtxCDiEbU2F1CiyHYqzJkZLh91c3tlTKFCt1jQkqFpzWdVPTW_EVtkTRDQEgqSSdT9Xtk8SvRxnvuUXZh8lOqOULaEKV2LJg0GC44W4pzQvCajN9CopMP5e0fI4b6dUugQGUC62cEpdz47bWJDNo2d5FnIG76pd8=','By June 2020, Wakefield Council had paid out approximately £2 million in compensation to 400 residents whose properties saw a decrease in value due to the construction and operation of the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (Neil Fox Way). The payouts covered factors like noise, vibration, and artificial lighting.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('240860f7-b33a-4cb4-a97d-d8b98afa473d','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As Bradford\'s first Grade A office for 20 years, the landmark One City Park development takes pride of place at the centre of ongoing regeneration in the city. Delivered by Caddick Construction on behalf of Bradford City Council and its development partner, Muse, this stunning development owes its aesthetic to its striking façade, delivered by CCL Facades incorporating a bespoke package of industry-leading Speedpanel solutions. In January 2023, CCL Facades commenced work alongside main contractor and sister company, Caddick Construction, to deliver the £4.8m façade contract at One City Park. One City Park uses photovoltaic solar electricity panels and air source heat pumps and supports local biodiversity through the planting of diverse tree species and the instalation of nesting boxes for birds. It also has floor-to-ceiling windows that give views across City Park. The state-of-the-art building has 5,240 square metres of Grade A office space and a striking steel and glass structure, which won it a CoStar Impact Award.','Creating a Unique & Striking Facade at One City Park / One City Park Hailed as Bradford\'s Biggest Game-Changer in 20 Years','CCL Facades / CoStar News','2024-03-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGfVBLcEOp432v3xqnbM11hyZu4SgVf6yo6p7UEIt_Tr85L3nqJcdAfjezp38O2kplnSoeLyQoq63EFBMKedRjXVxYON-lFQjycwHNFP0J4Vo0XgBFMDgbaNcMBN6k_0F0RIddRi6uxFRO66-0nCLi-XJkGW7NqnFSRAcL0VcTs6TaoqqXhI97787LM5Co2nQ==','One City Park features a distinctive steel and glass facade, delivered by CCL Facades, which incorporates bespoke Speedpanel solutions. The building was designed with strong sustainable credentials, including photovoltaic solar panels and air source heat pumps, and achieved a BREEAM \'Excellent\' rating. The project has also received a CoStar Impact Award.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('245d945f-4850-4a37-a1d0-04deb4ffb3d2','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Three “corridors of opportunity” will headline West Yorkshire\'s UKREiiF showcase, featuring more than 40 investment-ready sites: Southern Corridor: Stretching from Leeds to Dewsbury and Huddersfield, this area features plans for 50,000 new homes and a National Health Innovation Campus. [17]','West Yorkshire Rallies Behind UKREiiF 2025 Plans with Bold Vision for Growth (Southern Corridor inclusion)','KLTV','2025-04-24 00:00:00.000','https://kirkleeslocaltv.com/2025/04/24/west-yorkshire-rallies-behind-ukreiif-2025-plans-with-bold-vision-for-growth/ [17]','As part of West Yorkshire\'s plans for UKREiiF 2025, a \'Southern Corridor\' spanning from Leeds to Dewsbury and Huddersfield was highlighted. This broader strategic vision includes plans for 50,000 new homes and a National Health Innovation Campus, underscoring the regional importance of Huddersfield within the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s economic development and infrastructure initiatives.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('24b8985d-30fd-4cce-a1f8-77429a8f11d8','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leonardo Printworks and Thorseby House are Grade II listed Victorian buildings. Re-purposing of the listed elements as well re-use of the modern building structure substantially reduces the embodied carbon of the new development. Operational carbon emissions are minimised through connection to the city council\'s low-carbon district heating system, as well as through a thermally efficient fabric and the use of rooftop photovoltaic panels. Construction is due to start in August 2021 and to complete by August 2023 in time for the 2023/2024 academic year.','Historic Leeds civic buildings given green light for £62m PBSA transformation','Cartwright Pickard','2021-07-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.cartwrightpickard.com/news/historic-leeds-civic-buildings-given-green-light-for-ps62m-pbsa-transformation/','Cartwright Pickard announced that the transformation of Leonardo Printworks and Thoresby House into student accommodation, with a value of £62 million, received planning approval. The project aims to reduce embodied carbon by repurposing listed elements and minimize operational carbon emissions by connecting to Leeds City Council\'s low-carbon district heating system. Construction was anticipated to start in August 2021 and complete by August 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('24ce6100-ff90-4713-bbf4-3543a890cd72','infrastructure-enfinium-skelton-grange-energy-from-waste-facility',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.539','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'LONDON, July 8, 2021 /PRNewswire/ — enfimium today reached financial close on a new 410,000 tonnes per annum waste-to-energy facility in Leeds, West Yorkshire. … enfinium Skelton Grange is a combined heat and power facility which will process 410,000 tonnes of residual (post-recycled) waste to generate 49MW (gross) of partially renewable, baseload electricity to power the needs of more than 100,000 U.K. homes.','Enfinium Skelton Grange waste-to-energy facility achieves financial close','enfinium, PR Newswire UK, letsrecycle.com','2021-07-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHk4IDEwfk16mC-sKRX2fH9010-hjF8CYHkYWTt3PS-99JFZroD_7DywUWhwzpa0bpP3qYKP-SEMntKD8kgYXO99S-f2KTCjhA2a9LUds8U7DGLPHERJZnZH7QeTk6HDVYAi65n1Vho4_itm9WkRYxsWUqwhzZ3xXuS6ZTTc8X9A6SBELKbjaa97XnZvJkZ792OpmDmzAmR2rRK','Enfinium announced on July 8, 2021, that the Skelton Grange waste-to-energy facility in Leeds reached financial close. This £500m project secured funding to proceed with construction, which would process 410,000 tonnes of residual waste annually to generate 49MW of energy.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2503091a-38d9-430a-8469-829b6836a697','infrastructure-a638-doncaster-road-corridor-improvement-programme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.997','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This contract has been undertaken as a Direct Award under the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Framework Agreement; Ref: CA1550, Title: Transforming Cities and Other Funded Programmes; Lot 2: Highways Schemes and is for the production of a fully completed and compliant Full Business Case submission to WYCA, building on the original option appraisal outcomes already defined for the Outline Business Case. A Contract Award Notice by Wakefield Council. Value £641K.','Doncaster Road FBC [Award]','Bidstats','2024-02-09 00:00:00.000','https://bidstats.uk/tenders/2024/W06/871032126','Wakefield Council awarded a Direct Award contract valued at £641,000 for the production of a fully completed and compliant Full Business Case (FBC) for the CIP II A638 Doncaster Road project. This contract was undertaken under the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Framework Agreement for Transforming Cities and Other Funded Programmes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('251af19a-ab8c-4cec-8654-a6b82ada7b89','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'People are being asked for their views on plans to better connect Huddersfield Rail Station with the town centre. The £16 million scheme will make it easier for people to travel between the rail station and the places where they live, learn, work or visit. It is being delivered in partnership by Kirklees Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. ... The first phase of public consultation took place in November 2021, and the feedback from this has been used to progress the plans further, including modernising the arrival to the station square. The revised series of proposed improvements are broken down into four distinct areas. At the heart of the gateway is Huddersfield Rail Station, the second busiest in West Yorkshire. Network Rail\'s Transpennine Route Upgrade will improve the railway that runs through Huddersfield to Leeds, Manchester and beyond, to help support economic growth. The aim of this scheme is to prepare the town centre for the rail upgrade. [14]','Public asked for views on plans to better connect Huddersfield Rail Station with the town centre','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-11-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/huddersfield-rail-station-connections-second-stage-consultation','Kirklees Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced a renewed call for public views on the £16 million scheme to improve connections around Huddersfield Rail Station. This followed an initial consultation in November 2021, with feedback used to progress plans. The revised proposals aim to make it easier for people to travel between the station and the town centre and are part of the broader Huddersfield Blueprint, preparing the area for the Transpennine Route Upgrade.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('251f6490-4c91-484a-b942-7651a480934c','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s page on Calderdale outlines specific Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) schemes. These include improving access to Halifax Rail Station with a new footbridge, the redevelopment of Halifax Bus Station, improving bus access in West Halifax, transforming walking and cycling access into Halifax town centre, and creating a segregated cycle route linking north Halifax to the town centre. Better cycling and walking routes to the new Elland Rail Station and through Brighouse town centre are also part of the plan. These schemes fall under the broader TCF programme which was officially funded in March 2020. [9]','Transforming Calderdale: TCF schemes for Halifax and Brighouse','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEFB_-dN_7y9MUQ3QYVG-yITzyCHFFn59un24qxeQbmabYtKz0_6tGUp462D1p-Z-_x_WrqPM5jwTspSCzRxJXSqQqtGKCiibpvp0fkilbsl-ehXU4uI7q-tBX09Xi6GnOsuwXv04xO_fdXwluSO-RzDjoVF_KrB1IwntNXwhZ6aXvZfiVTrX4woED32o8wwZOxVrLlm1dHhqhc','As part of the wider Transforming Cities Fund programme, Calderdale is set to benefit from schemes designed to improve transport infrastructure. These include enhancing access to Halifax Rail Station with a new footbridge, redeveloping Halifax Bus Station, and improving bus access in West Halifax. Additionally, the programme will transform walking and cycling access into Halifax town centre, introduce a segregated cycle route linking North Halifax to the town centre, and establish better cycling and walking routes to the new Elland Rail Station and through Brighouse town centre. These projects are part of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s commitment to creating a cleaner, more accessible transport network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2595f4aa-898a-431b-aaec-120e4657ab09','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Updated details on the plans to improve transport connectivity to Leeds Bradford Airport and in the north west of the city have been released today. Leeds City Council, working with West Yorkshire Combined Authority and partners including Leeds Bradford Airport, has issued new details of the three options being considered to improve road access to the airport as well as more information on the proposed new airport parkway rail station on the Leeds to Harrogate line. This forms part of a phase of public consultation and engagement which begins on all aspects of the proposals on from today (18 Feb) running to Friday 12 April. [2, 5, 9, 16]','Update on Leeds Bradford Airport and North West Leeds connectivity improvement plans as further public engagement begins','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2019-02-18 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/update-on-leeds-bradford-airport-and-north-west-leeds-connectivity-improvement-plans-as-further-public-engagement-begins','Leeds City Council, in conjunction with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a new phase of public consultation (February 18 - April 12, 2019) on connectivity improvements. This included updated details on the three road access options and information on a proposed new airport parkway rail station on the Leeds to Harrogate line, aiming to support forecasted airport growth and address congestion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('25dd8558-dc41-4430-8034-16101f502331','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Up to 50% grant support from Digital Enterprise for eligible small to medium businesses looking to invest in digital projects. Digital Enterprise supports growing businesses across West Yorkshire on their digital transformation journey to enable them to improve performance, productivity and competitiveness, reduce environmental impact, and ultimately achieve sustainable growth by investing in digital. Two levels of grant funding are available for growth-focussed businesses, operating for more than three years that need investment in digital innovation to propel them to the next stage. Grants can support hardware, software, technology, connectivity and internet upgrades. The programme ends in March 2025 and businesses are encouraged to apply as soon as possible. Eligible businesses considering a digital investment between £2,000 to £25,000 can apply for a Digital Accelerator Grant for up to 50% of the project costs, with a ceiling value of £10,000. A limited number of High Impact Grants will support substantial and transformative digital projects. Eligible businesses can receive up to 50% contribution, (capped at a maximum value of £35,000) towards new digital projects costing between £25,000 – £100,000. Businesses will also receive impartial advice and support from their dedicated Digital Advisor, who will be on hand throughout the application process to help them make the best use of digital solutions. Digital Enterprise 3 is funded with £4.6 million from the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund (UKSPF). [11]','Grants to invest in digital','Business Kirklees (Kirklees Council)','2023-10-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/business-and-licensing/news/2023/grants-to-invest-in-digital.aspx','Business Kirklees announced that Digital Enterprise 3 offers up to 50% grant support for eligible SMEs in West Yorkshire looking to invest in digital projects. The program, funded by £4.6 million from the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, aims to improve performance, productivity, and competitiveness. It details two grant types: Digital Accelerator (up to £10,000 for projects £2,000-£25,000) and High Impact (up to £35,000 for projects £25,000-£100,000). The program is set to end in March 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('25df243c-0aaa-49de-8adb-6bb8509bda4b','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Panel was advised that the Penistone Line has secured £48m of Levelling Up funding and officers are working with partners including WYCA, South Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority, Barnsley, Northern, Transport for the North, and Network Rail to come to an understanding of a governance structure that will help to deliver that project. ... Work put into these schemes is not wasted or lost in this pipeline approach, as has recently been demonstrated by success in being allocated funding from the Levelling-Up Fund, round three, for the Penistone Line Upgrade. [21]','Decision - Major Projects Transport Programme Update (General) - Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council - Council and democracy','2025-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://democracy.kirklees.gov.uk/documents/g5517/Decisions%2013th-Mar-2025%2017.00%20Cabinet%20Highways%20and%20Transports%20Panel.pdf?T=9','A Kirklees Council report on Major Projects Transport Programme update confirmed the Penistone Line has secured £48 million of Levelling Up funding. It notes ongoing work with partners, including WYCA and South Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority, to establish a governance structure for project delivery, indicating active planning and progression despite economic challenges.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2677b9e8-4f09-4ec4-bae4-8d9175a7af97','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'For Residents and Visitors to Luddenden, West Yorkshire. Flooding: According to the Environment Agency, over two million people in England live and work in properties at risk of flooding from rivers or the sea, whilst more face flood threats from groundwater, surface water, sewers, and reservoirs. (c) Luddenden Conservation Society 2025.','Residents - Luddenden (Flooding Information)','Luddenden Conservation Society','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHiiZn_v9wJICo8RpYfTkOcWuGwFcLUnPFDggOk7R988joafa5dPtPo3KDqrPY_x5ha6ej1-GdzElT-yymojZBPkYL7OPW9Dr2E2fhAg_blbJRM_MR-4KO79yQ9','The Luddenden Conservation Society\'s website provides general information to residents and visitors regarding flood risk in England. It notes that millions of people are at risk of flooding from various sources and offers advice on preparation and property protection, reflecting the ongoing awareness of flood challenges in the Luddenden area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('26aa4469-e430-43ed-9904-e3c4980c4a67','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Recent additions to the network include Leeds Conservatoire, Tec Campus, and social housing at Lovell Park, with new installations planned at Leonora House and 24-28 Great George Street. Connecting over 3,000 dwellings marks a major achievement for this project.','Leeds PIPES connects 3000+ dwellings, celebrates major milestone','The District Heating User (via Vital Energi)','2024-11-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.districtheating.co.uk/leeds-pipes-connects-3000-dwellings-celebrates-major-milestone/','Vital Energi, a key partner, announced that the Leeds PIPES network had surpassed 3,000 connected dwellings. The report explicitly mentioned \'social housing at Lovell Park\' as recent additions to the network, confirming their successful integration into the system.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('27016eda-5ca7-44e3-9e9a-4d5be4db1916','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Next Tuesday\'s (November 14) Cabinet discussions will specifically focus on developments at Dewsbury Riverside, as well as Fenay Lane in Almondbury. In November 2023, cabinet gave the go-ahead for the council to enter into legal agreements with Network Rail and Homes England, and carry out work to appoint a master developer. (See Source [5] for full context). Cabinet will discuss proposed next steps for Dewsbury Riverside, relating to collaboration with other local landowners and with Network Rail, whose development of Ravensthorpe Railway Station as part of the Transpennine Route Upgrade will help support development around the Dewsbury Riverside site. (See Source [19] for full context).','Kirklees Council Cabinet Approves Next Steps for Dewsbury Riverside Housing Growth','Dewsbury Reporter','2023-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.dewsburyreporter.co.uk/news/dewsbury-riverside-kirklees-council-cabinet-to-discuss-plans-for-housing-growth-4399757','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet discussed and approved proposed next steps for Dewsbury Riverside on November 14, 2023. This included entering into legal agreements with Network Rail and Homes England, and advancing work to appoint a master developer for the strategic site. The aim is to deliver thousands of new homes, shops, and schools, with a strong focus on affordable and energy-efficient housing.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('27112b0b-955e-450e-96e1-e378a3022bfc','infrastructure-enfinium-skelton-grange-energy-from-waste-facility',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.539','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Progress to reach financial close follows planning permission by Leeds City Council in March 2020 and the award of an Environmental Permit by the Environment Agency in December 2020.','Enfinium Skelton Grange Energy from Waste facility granted planning permission by Leeds City Council','enfinium, Urja Daily, letsrecycle.com','2020-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFw3Hlja5wF8F9DfOIvsF1F2Edjq7-dNDQ811x2ubgmPl_Hka1y3wjVbVySvsE0_cF4JSPfBfZVBUHqanCtHfFEDNaEKZJHQjj-WqUJzSLKxh72XLQ_NtEhn0-_h9nBzgzXvGnKHNWGJkTGTDUwA4VqJ-rYa98DOslUjAH4enPFEro8OxPmAk4M3kB2HPojl9ARHC47ET5jRz4rHg==','Leeds City Council granted planning permission for the Enfinium Skelton Grange Energy from Waste facility in March 2020. This was a crucial step for the project to proceed, allowing for the development of a facility capable of processing 410,000 tonnes of waste annually to generate 49MW of energy.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('272fc4f4-26c0-49fc-b0ea-a6fd0403d2d3','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds\'s South Bank is to enjoy more affordable and lower carbon heating after £24.5m funding was secured to further expand the Leeds PIPES district heating network. The expansion is planned to include up to 28 buildings, with up to 8,000 residents and mixed-use customers benefitting from connections, making it the most significant single investment into the project since its inception. [4]','Leeds low carbon heat network set to expand to thousands more residents','Leeds City Council News','2024-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHHUiszZ1xpfqMv-aGMxFMcedPaGvkFIPUUFwm9lPoSRRaL3WNyduVTWqYNUKKagxAguMHGMYXJaLSdMW8AisIXG1PrH9wRC8PORBcZgxaq_oz-ZUTQJiW1PLg7dQl3Zo_UJMoKJ3-LBgc4S4fMuWjCD-gYW8rvcSl56RHMYcriCqxDbGFECKq2RUjyXcJ5c_QXOkgmLeSJfGGkWksjkvo15g','Leeds City Council officially announced that £24.5 million in funding had been secured for the further expansion of the Leeds PIPES district heating network. This expansion is targeted at Leeds\' South Bank, aiming to connect up to 28 buildings and benefit up to 8,000 residents and mixed-use customers with more affordable and lower carbon heating.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('274363a0-529a-40a4-8e09-d67675bd69db','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'KNOTTINGLEY COMMUNITY HUB COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY - Free company information from Companies House including registered office address, filing history, accounts, annual return, officers, charges, business activity. GODDARD, John. Correspondence address: Kellingley Miners Social Welfare Club, Marine Villa Road, Knottingley, West Yorkshire, United Kingdom, WF11 8ER. Role: Director. Date of birth: August 1958. Appointed on: 11 December 2020. Nationality: British. Country of residence: United Kingdom. Occupation: Retired.','KNOTTINGLEY COMMUNITY HUB COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY - Director Appointment','GOV.UK Companies House','2020-12-11 00:00:00.000','https://find-and-update.company-information.service.gov.uk/company/06801990/officers','Details the formal establishment of the \'KNOTTINGLEY COMMUNITY HUB COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY\' and the appointment of John Goddard as a director, indicating a formal governance structure for the hub, likely associated with the Kellingley site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('27cd260d-afae-48d2-b8c1-9bd494503776','infrastructure-moving-traffic-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.124','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council are considering embarking on a trial of new government powers of enforcement as relates to moving traffic on our roads. ... The council are launching a consultation exercise to gather public feedback on specific site for which a trial may take place. When we\'re doing it? Between 27-May-2025 and 07-Jul-2025.','Consultation on moving traffic enforcement | Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council','2025-05-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/involve/moving-traffic-enforcement.aspx','Kirklees Council launched a public consultation, running from May 27, 2025, to July 7, 2025, to gather feedback on its proposals to apply for powers to enforce moving traffic contraventions. The council is considering adopting these powers from the Department for Transport to improve its road network and address congestion and road safety.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('27df5404-6fcf-4c5f-b92f-8c7261ab7825','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'InstaVolt, the UK\'s largest ultra-rapid electric vehicle (EV) charging network, has officially opened its latest charging site at Cliff Court Services, on the southbound A1 near Wentbridge, just in time for the busy summer travel season. The new site features 12 ultra-rapid charging bays, including two fully accessible bays, offering drivers a reliable and convenient stop-off point on one of the country\'s key arterial routes. Located just off the A1, with easy access to the M1, this new hub will cater to a growing number of EV drivers, whether they are local commuters, long-distance travellers, or holidaymakers heading north or south. The location is complemented by on-site Starbucks and McDonald\'s.','InstaVolt brings 12 new ultra-rapid chargers to A1 corridor near Pontefract','Wakefield Express','2025-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/instavolt-brings-12-new-ultra-rapid-chargers-to-a1-corridor-near-pontefract-4658097','InstaVolt officially opened a new ultra-rapid charging site with 12 bays at Cliff Court Services on the southbound A1 near Wentbridge, Pontefract. This significant hub, located close to the M1, offers ultra-rapid charging and is complemented by on-site Starbucks and McDonald\'s, serving the wider Wakefield and West Yorkshire region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('281f1173-d790-4dbd-83eb-2e7382889bd9','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water is investing over £3.4m in three storm overflows in and around Halifax to reduce the number of storm water discharges into Helliwell Syke, and tributaries of Hebble Brooke and Shibden Beck. ... £1m to install 900m of surface water pipes on Long Lane and City Lane, install oversized storage pipes, and line an existing sewer to reduce discharges from Hebble Lane CSO to a tributary of Hebble Brook by 54%. The projects are part of a £180m investment project across Yorkshire by the end of April 2025 to reduce discharges from storm overflows.','£3.4m investment in Halifax storm overflows to reduce discharges to local watercourses','Yorkshire Water','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGQ1SgB08XFBBRmrXqOGQbdSwfFEBB0lffumdKm8DemAaxyh2cIXf7w3VHDqmNHL9fdLnWJWyPZNQQmYFkCg60SAWEXpi4EI6UcR_F0ggq448e3veLygryf3-GtZGFuu8eQsWDkM2M33FqFcVL0QhCJYRjO4imi7zDZPn2TAJLUXwX-xzeQ9CoaQJENhu0KDhSw6aY3vIFAsczgDhBPtN','Yorkshire Water announced an investment of over £3.4m in three storm overflows in and around Halifax, including £1m to install new surface water pipes and other measures on Long Lane and City Lane to reduce discharges from Hebble Lane CSO to a tributary of Hebble Brook by 54%. This is part of a larger £180m investment project across Yorkshire by April 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('283b4eef-9c91-45a8-9e7b-1d496cd184ce','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On 2nd November 2023, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority agreed to provide £1,064,793 to develop the Phase 2 scheme to a full business case. [7]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority agrees funding for Phase 2 Full Business Case development','All About Thornton / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2023-11-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF-fngv28HNQcKH-PaPCDeHwVJ_fJJwwY6McN14UyAUaDbeDLgsUcxaYaVEDsTFySRBCcINLJF2czzNIcnG5KNHTua5nCpVMBmkoiG6VeHyNR1vDGQ3hhYq8oSeKqG0QBByDM56spLPW-w4WwAwQVzDc4QlX4QOtJYQg0OXNKXeaxEiHK432SHfXPYA==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority approved £1,064,793 to develop the Phase 2 scheme of the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension to a full business case. This decision supports the progression of the project\'s detailed planning.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('28610eeb-ba87-4fd2-b89a-2cee0b9c9ddf','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin has decided to take control of the buses in the biggest shake up to public transport in the region for decades. In a landmark move, the Mayor decided to bring buses under local control - through a process known as franchising - as recommended by the Combined Authority at its meeting in Leeds today. Routes, frequencies, fares and overall standards for buses in the region will be set by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority – not private operators, who will instead be contracted to run services on the Combined Authority\'s behalf. ... To ensure a smooth transition, franchising will be introduced in phases, with the first franchised buses up and running in parts of Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield from March 2027.','West Yorkshire Mayor takes buses back under public control','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/west-yorkshire-mayor-takes-buses-back-under-public-control/','Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin, formally announced the decision to bring bus services across the region back under public control through a franchising model. This landmark decision followed a three-month public consultation that showed significant support for franchising. The first franchised services are expected to begin in March 2027 in parts of Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901');
