	('286fc8aa-1eb7-4d12-b0ae-870debd6ca4c','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-enquire-learning-trust-buckingham-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.379','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Enquire Learning Trust has been awarded £310,393 to replace the existing oil boilers with an air source heat pump at Buckingham Primary Academy. [2]','Enquire Learning Trust Awarded PSDS Phase 3a Grant for Buckingham Primary Academy','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: project summaries - GOV.UK','2025-04-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGzdgXgQszp6063JvM-kj37ofyzEHQba9qKuxeP1QLPSHvOda36MELseqSS3c96gfy6zuJMYxxFDb4ILtubPlN_yVGs6m-S4vZosXJpNjkyK-kJgIAIpLNr9KkeiYORo3_vqIVFOimMdTj2ERbTnJBJBkI8Ea2F1aQxBZvNquFyu7Ca7hBvtnHO7PNO328y4mWH1wEaW-9wtwUqCpkRL0lt3wOaOL4eJ5CXzL5hmaSjg8_WY793y3qDA8sfdMMI8qwj5IKh2qrcDqkRT6nHdqUwFgYz','Enquire Learning Trust was awarded a grant of £310,393 under Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. This funding is specifically designated for Buckingham Primary Academy in Leeds to replace existing oil boilers with an air source heat pump.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('287598e7-8710-445f-9398-ac32077f8a2e','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2023-09-14) Three 50-year-old footbridges around Armley Gyratory will be replaced with new ones in the next stage of construction of the major route into Leeds City Centre. The removal of the Spence Lane footbridge over the Armley Gyratory begins later this month and will be the first of three footbridges that will be removed and replaced with new footbridges with more accessible footways, set to complete next year. To allow for this work to be carried out, motorists are warned that there will be a weekend partial closure, from 8pm on Friday, September 29, 2023 to 5.30pm on Sunday, October 1, 2023.','Armley Gyratory, Leeds: Construction of major route into Leeds City Centre enters its next phase to replace 50-year-old footbridges','Yorkshire Evening Post','2023-09-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGtpimK_7kSb8Qr4Rm7K5lqbC2DVJCbbMH6tn0XI99Bh8mbR8PkFUnMO_bnqd82A1-isSxXlonBjA4VqR3Ck5jcYCT7G7i-fcIJanAfPde3EBWv__zCK4u7QBpdso1YWdLL1PaEag5BWUv3__0IutdxfoUJtFlc6NZP_KV2xVuKNy4AxnfG4vkV31Niv9qzMH2fckEq8X5Y3btyyxROFGgkn4g0MUJulxhuS07d5_uG-8IkjdeSlCBjPGgQhBWw5_nSoutRJvX8lGZ5EfRjeEPYHYze5D__pEo4WAelDYCKEDb-3mdMnsxnUcikawb4Obd4dc6o','The replacement phase for the three 50-year-old footbridges around Armley Gyratory commenced with the demolition of the Spence Lane footbridge on September 29, 2023. This marked the beginning of work to replace existing footbridges with new, more accessible structures, enhancing pedestrian and cyclist facilities and improving overall accessibility around the gyratory.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('287a31d2-e2b4-47c5-a574-f21ff54f054e','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In this public consultation we will be seeking feedback on initial proposals for the bus station, which will help shape the development of more detailed plans. ... This engagement will close at 11.59pm on Sunday 12 September 2021.','Transforming Huddersfield Bus Station - stage one engagement','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH7uNB3g5QD2Q4kDs72Z_S6B9tNw_oYESxYELH1kcoaN4hKCYcPqNG8FuGJuk9ahs5W3zUp-m4MBAMwCRxBXzib5IcXgxmQSXEHgO0RPZ_glzXoqJRW_7k1kywpWLXBkEqZot1dtbSHMwo=','This public consultation sought feedback on initial proposals for the Huddersfield Bus Station upgrades. The engagement aimed to gather public views to help shape the development of more detailed plans. The consultation closed on September 12, 2021.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('28a7ee95-1c6b-42d9-a7b6-15be273d44c1','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority, working in partnership with Wakefield Council and Leeds City Council, is investing £22.5m in two key roads connecting the Wakefield District with Leeds – the A61 and A639... Delivery of the improvements is scheduled for 2024 subject to approvals. [4]','Transforming Cities - A61 and A639 - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2022-07-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHoM76NLLzvUU6Yf6ThWOcIGXlbT_q5HUVeQpgAyyDb6MOQp4E6Nh2Xunk9mGKkN213UQFsHoIb6gdISgqms_JEi2SiNSFDKTwt6iF6xdANSADbbZMu5A83ofaxtu1PAVObM0lABRqNeGt7rpXA2P5PqKBlCRzk3dR_NXCXZxsw2udLwI8F_U6HABjMwC5WjzOzw3GdMC7nexfUrErY9DKEzkCGXvpWwN-nH0w=','The Wakefield Council website states that the delivery of improvements for the A61 and A639, funded by the Transforming Cities Fund, was scheduled for 2024, subject to approvals. This indicates the planned implementation phase for the project. [4]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2944f8ea-abfa-4d0e-957c-19e6025af49a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority website states that construction has started on the new Halifax Bus Station and White Rose Rail Station in Leeds as part of the Transforming Cities Fund programme. A news article confirms that construction work on the new White Rose Rail Station in Leeds officially began on 24 February 2021. [7, 37]','Construction Starts on White Rose Rail Station in Leeds','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-02-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGMz0ShMSCOJdpl2xcuUfVg8eZEFjMWV3aol6Wy4j5Ow_zQvf9YIbp2ElMcKvCoghgXgb9v56VpYXmKsI3sw9FqGpuTVoo42ij2utayNdTP7AH11U4fi_BqeXrjYrQVjAEvOLE9G16k-lDx00oFNOHVSyCMRHer8kh6dpJ3kOMIaX-Rxm7beg8mHOKwUPZLVVg1yWDL','The Transforming Cities Fund programme includes the development of new transport infrastructure in Leeds, with construction having commenced on the new White Rose Rail Station. This project is a key component of the wider regional effort to improve connectivity and offer more sustainable travel options. The station is designed to serve the White Rose shopping centre and surrounding communities, providing better rail access and supporting economic opportunities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('29476195-7fb0-4f03-9c40-7ece7910c115','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A huge scheme to turn a “tired and rundown” area of Bradford city centre into a new urban village has now been submitted. The first planning application for Bradford’s City Village is now officially live, and - if it is approved – work could begin with the demolition of the Oastler Shopping Centre later this year. The plans will see around 1,000 homes built on three sites in the city centre – the former Oastler Market site, the site of the Kirkgate Shopping Centre and on a collection of car parks in the Chain Street Area. Later phases of the neighbourhood will include more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site, alongside approximately 400 apartments on the Kirkgate site. A detailed planning application for Phase One, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site, has been submitted.','Plans submitted for Bradford City Village regeneration, including outline for Kirkgate site','Bradford Telegraph and Argus, Business Link Magazine, ECF, Place Yorkshire, Build News','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEzqRBam2bViflHkCg-9vyPzhmhPzHdxrU4c_4q_hum0oSIDxQ2hrHhW0A_00sLZ_Bas4BpSrXsTwJN9cSIKidgPw4zPofloZKsxMQoo7n4aCWD05gFJ4He4F2XxIizvlH1Y707e2Dr4CBXXXc7s53YIG-nBcZGZZUsI0I2fn4rX6VCJw828txWHEH6ahE8ny0-uHfqJnws5TeB6z7abc7j, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEHKlJYug4gbykKBDrd6EHyGHT5ZHN_pzZw5R48oN4C5SkbQa47xO6HkraoiRLrLrhBQoqMbQrKsJoN_5CcZ_VIcAKZfEsPT0luOqPMsyRWq9lipRm0o46tDuiCtV3pqmKqzl63teaGnRd42qNafua9t2KL0jq34RlnN3lZ1iVUnPHCzuJwToSxAF7w9Q==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFsoDI3aCr10QNgCKlfbuZhx_814MB0rujCw4SA0TxVbNkNN07Q2WqVfaCq0kVazkBngwJzkQfju1eesVvpJPDgYJ2ZGCgE393dX9CP1W8vBtk5XoHtq097MH17pd2iU2IQPei4AJADL4becnr0d7jOWuiQG9FwN0S-85wgWKLLryNFRYMQ-7GxJcNm9zs=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHLSGMdEcczFOmYccJMueMplMoQLDVCbooYCUYo2pEA1EH8RYfw0PIjIyFRwFaHTlXDFl_6Z_LTwfBo-7gUPx0lvjuBP85LqT8U4XdUZW_zHT8pM-Y1pnD3lO3yt0qYwTTLbpTiJJ145VvOMTJv5pzDG6opFOvUk-LlIpfzH0YO, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF7MloAQmS_Hmz6bxZv9jD11ugAMst9_g-FjMmEYn6K2mlqgHIW4FSLU1Yud_iPkQBu7SY_yJ6VhV_LAFjOHSnYv8YMXOCazmkd02yDlI7p9LJZWWgfM3912cqeRgFrBh_DkydFT7phj0-h2utNUScPKkyGmN-_u1_HnIivlOvQD0XjYN2miNXVwn2VdSlj9xkq','A detailed planning application for Phase One of Bradford City Village, along with an outline planning application for the rest of the site (including the Kirkgate and southern Oastler sites), has been submitted by ECF and Bradford Council. The project aims to create nearly 1,000 homes across three sites, with later phases planned to deliver approximately 400 apartments at Kirkgate. The submission marks a significant step towards transforming the city\'s former commercial core into a new sustainable neighbourhood.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('29939184-7aa8-4101-b15d-246222e960d4','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a638-doncaster-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.598','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Public engagement. Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is looking to make improvements to the A638 Doncaster Road in Wakefield and would like your feedback on the proposed improvements. ... During this consultation in summer 2021, 164 people completed our public survey. Nine out of ten of you said you agreed that investment to improve transport is needed in the area. Generally, you said you agreed with the proposals. You also made suggestions for some changes and raised some concerns. You can read the outcome report here. [6] Wakefield Council is looking to make improvements to the A638 Doncaster Road in Wakefield and would like your feedback on the proposed improvements. This consultation will close on July 18, 2021. [7]','Public Consultation on A638 Doncaster Road Improvements','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / Wakefield Express','2021-06-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a638-doncaster-road-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme','Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a public consultation on the proposed improvements for the A638 Doncaster Road. The consultation ran from June 21 to July 18, 2021, seeking feedback on proposals aimed at reducing traffic congestion, improving bus journey reliability, enhancing walking and cycling facilities, and reducing noise and air pollution. [6, 7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('29bdb825-d030-4a26-9995-36bf19adf39c','infrastructure-a629-halifax-to-huddersfield-corridor-improvement-phase-4-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.884','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following a tender exercise, Mott MacDonald has been appointed to support the development of Phase 4 - a £25.9million project which is fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority through the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund. ... It focuses on reducing congestion at Ainley Top and improving the pedestrian, cycle and bus connectivity along the A629 route. It is anticipated that the Full Business Case will be completed by spring 2022 and subject to approvals, it is hoped that work can start on Phase 4 scheme around summer 2022.','£26m A629 highway upgrade plan between Halifax and Huddersfield reaches next milestone','Halifax Courier','2020-10-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHaKDDWAmZpgH1EPgmIN7jg6vLv2t8MCEGQE4XkqeRka7sEEjkpj-IcFysRvqDw54RWuvwkuBdwi0W-Ubh9ziFj75ShjudQ4t6Dk-ah3knO8c4awwLDUxmOVVmTnjiPa7YojPqT9EQbyLv0uhC5ShwcMeL9ryKySIzEBn97t-WzqRe8748VYBu_grUTojiL126unUzc-G6QBgdkHII5-zjPKCad-Psb8OuuhU_oy801x5rY1cImmAanYnA3ll1d_x8X3Ilo6omGUere_w==','This article reports that Mott MacDonald was appointed as the design contractor for Phase 4 of the A629 project in October 2020. The £25.9 million project, fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, aims to reduce congestion at Ainley Top and enhance pedestrian, cycle, and bus connectivity along the A629 route. The Full Business Case was anticipated to be completed by spring 2022, with construction hoped to start around summer 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2a0f1bc5-8227-4945-a7dc-4ee1f38dd065','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Bradford Telegraph and Argus reported on 30 April 2025, about a significant £3.8 million investment for new EV chargers across Kirklees, funded partly by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s LEVI Fund, highlighting regional efforts to expand charging infrastructure. [19]','£3.8m Investment for New EV Chargers Across Kirklees as part of LEVI Fund','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-04-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24290740.3-8m-investment-new-ev-chargers-across-kirklees/','Twenty-three areas in Kirklees, a local authority within the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, are set to receive new Electric Vehicle Charging Points through a £3.8 million investment. This funding, including £2.5 million from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s LEVI Fund and private investment, will support the region\'s net-zero ambitions.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2a2d7749-0482-4dd2-a0a4-b463e308ffb2','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Halifax Bus Station will soon be home to the first in a series of artistic installations showcasing the unique heritage and culture of Halifax, as part of a new trail around the town. The \'Art and About\' trail is part of Future High Streets Fund work in Halifax, funded by the Government and being delivered by Calderdale Council. The trail is being created in partnership with local arts organisation, Everybody Arts and will include brand-new art installations developed by local creatives and using local suppliers. The trail will take in 20 locations around the town, featuring existing points of interests and exciting new works inspired by the town\'s history but using modern techniques and influences. The first artwork to be installed will be a new moquette fabric which will be displayed at Halifax Bus Station. [4]','Getting Art and About with new creative trail - Halifax Bus Station to be home to first Art and About trail installation','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-08-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGhebfDU6yCHmj23NL3yMza0ngcVVkJnOmEN-O8PvwMnzEouC0bD6pRF9gj4xzjKwPZRo_3riNcIBMVNfe0pXVW2xOjexJCaTf9Tj0hwxJCDGe_LS9b0L2xEtPEniQbwkN4Wfk79ubSThbrYl0tPX3nG2v1L3lUJYsZWx6ro6SeSuVHX0LgSkvc','Calderdale Council announced that the first Art and About Trail installation, a new moquette fabric, will be displayed at Halifax Bus Station. This marks a significant milestone for the trail, which features 20 locations showcasing Halifax\'s heritage and culture through artistic installations, funded by the Future High Streets Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2b3f8a4f-182d-4ce8-86af-9ce7ea6771c3','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'TWO more schools in the Bradford district will launch “School Streets” schemes designed to improve safety, as well as reduce traffic congestion and air pollution outside the schools. The latest schools to adopt a School Street are The Academy at St James Primary in Allerton and Horton Park Primary in Canterbury. ... The two latest additions to the scheme will take the number of School Streets across Braford district to 10. When a School Street is introduced, parents and carers are encouraged to leave their cars at home and walk, scoot or cycle with their children to and from school where possible. ... Implementation of the two latest School Streets is expected late spring/early summer','Two more Bradford primaries to adopt \'school streets\' scheme','Telegraph and Argus','2024-03-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24220261.two-bradford-primaries-adopt-school-streets-scheme/','Bradford Council announced that two additional primary schools, The Academy at St James Primary and Horton Park Primary, would implement School Streets schemes, bringing the total in the district to 10. These schemes aim to improve safety, reduce congestion, and lower air pollution during school drop-off and pick-up times, with implementation expected in late spring/early summer.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2b412b16-ddf2-4f6a-ae2e-e0c9fa25afb9','infrastructure-normanton-golf-club-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.339','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We are pleased to announce that Alfa Power, a Leeds-based electric vehicle (EV) charge point operator, is the latest network to go live on Zap-Pay, the simple way to pay for EV charging across networks from Zapmap. ... Alfa Power operates a network of around 55 fast, rapid and ultra-rapid charging devices stretching from Yorkshire to Somerset. Indeed, the network sees itself as well positioned to play a significant role in supporting the transition of the UK market towards the widespread uptake of EVs by providing necessary infrastructure in key locations. ... Alfa Power\'s growing network was founded in 2017.','Alfa Power now takes Zap-Pay','Zapmap','2023-04-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG_IQsq25BhClOkg58xI7im4XrdaeQkETrppXt85SzTiLF9igHB9-vxSn3uJXNE3AkCqArN2uf4sI1v0vx7GeM9lz5QHTNNl_1pOZLKJ5mCFkg2O-T-SBreHB0LfMbdFpWyxR7HrowMJkGCbCa8d1Q=','Zapmap announced that Alfa Power, a Leeds-based electric vehicle (EV) charge point operator, integrated with Zap-Pay. Alfa Power operates an extensive nationwide public charging network, including locations like golf clubs, confirming its role in providing EV infrastructure across the UK. The network was founded in 2017.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2b4f9bcf-8c05-4084-9ce4-6a2fe8d85cdd','infrastructure-a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction-improvement-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.993','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Corridor Improvement Programme - A639 Park Road/Beechnut Lane junction. Options have been developed to handle existing and future traffic levels to allow for better overall traffic flow and more active travel. West Yorkshire Combined Authority, working in partnership with Wakefield Council and Leeds City Council, is investing £22.5m in two key roads connecting the Wakefield District with Leeds – the A61 and A639. [3]','Transport Infrastructure Schemes - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2023-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/roads-and-transport/transport-plans-and-policies/transport-infrastructure-schemes','This page on the Wakefield Council website lists various transport infrastructure schemes, including the \'Corridor Improvement Programme - A639 Park Road/Beechnut Lane junction\'. It states that options have been developed to manage current and future traffic levels, enhance traffic flow, and promote active travel. It also mentions that the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Wakefield and Leeds Councils, is investing £22.5m in key roads, including the A639. [3]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2b942ffa-adc8-4a78-8c33-cadde57750e2','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Huddersfield Rail Station Connections – The Station Gateway Development. Through significant levels of investment, Kirklees will deliver high-quality, transformational projects to improve key sustainable transport routes across Kirklees. Aiming to rejuvenate and regenerate our area, these plans will connect areas helping us to grow and build back our local economy whilst also addressing poor air quality, carbon emissions and congestion. Huddersfield Rail Station Connections – The Station Gateway Development. Huddersfield Railway Station is at the heart of the Station Gateway, which is a key development site for the Huddersfield Blueprint. The station is a Grade I listed building and is the second busiest in West Yorkshire. In front of the station, St. George\'s Square is bordered by other historic buildings, including Estate Buildings and the George Hotel. Both of these buildings are part of the Station Gateway development. The journey so far … Huddersfield Railway station. With such a busy railway station, people need easy access to buses, taxis, cars and there needs to be easy access for pedestrians and cyclists. Walking and cycling accessibility needs to be safe and reliable, currently, there is a lack of cycle lanes, with junctions on the ring road not easy for people to cross. ... The project aims to make it easier for everyone to make their way between the railway station and the places they live, learn, work or visit. The proposed areas are: Northumberland Street & John William Street; St. John\'s Road; Trinity Street On-street Improvements Underpass Improvements; Cycle link to Greenhead Park; Brunswick Street Footpath; Huddersfield Rail Station Entrance Hall; Mobility Hubs. [9]','Huddersfield Blueprint Newsletter: Huddersfield Rail Station Connections – The Station Gateway Development','Kirklees Council (Huddersfield Blueprint Newsletter)','2022-07-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/huddersfield-blueprint/pdf/huddersfield-blueprint-newsletter-july-2022.pdf','A July 2022 newsletter from the Huddersfield Blueprint provided an update on the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections, framing it as part of \'The Station Gateway Development\'. It highlighted the project\'s aim to deliver high-quality, transformational projects to improve sustainable transport routes, address air quality, and support local economic growth. Key proposed areas of improvement included Northumberland Street & John William Street, St. John\'s Road, Trinity Street, Brunswick Street Footpath, and the Huddersfield Rail Station Entrance Hall.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2ba28976-d45f-4500-81b4-11b1f9847145','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first stage of the consultation on Kirklees\' updated Local Plan began on Monday, November 25 and will run until Friday, February 28, 2025 and asks residents and businesses to give their views on what they would like to see in a Local Plan. ... It includes some of the borough\'s most controversial developments, including the 4,000 home Dewsbury Riverside scheme and the 1,500 home development at Chidswell.','Residents asked to have their say as overhaul of Kirklees Local Plan - including Dewsbury Riverside development - continues','Dewsbury Reporter','2024-11-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHcc44Y-oitWBfPzjZ9CwkkZaIu7ibD_q6I34og3iE_2YhcU6pqargg7zYYZlJjb7rFUecFLlARwnFAnUk_g-heUjiJwTdcV4i0cD_usG8IEUD-URmzUltqfPRYbM3-2jv7PeTPF7PAtl30XbhmAg6n-HzDuve5Z1Tup38GRi4HnMbIR84bhOKOGBOxcBao6GLMVxfEu8y0Trudav2Py8amg2lAOy1NxCQ7uh5FEkphdBpHAQYASdRofkxGbHesRiUssKIX9qPH3mCzPUtj_FXfgMHfSHDTV6o92rfdmAkbLeD1nIOpBa5oEjvvZ3klNlRYm9DRUTdEaHCtpkyrrw==','The first stage of a public consultation on the overhaul of the Kirklees Local Plan, which includes the 4,000-home Dewsbury Riverside scheme, began on November 25, 2024, and runs until February 28, 2025. Residents and local businesses were invited to provide feedback on the future development strategy for the borough.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2bd37330-78d6-4861-b66d-580c83991037','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Tracy Brabin, the Mayor of West Yorkshire, visited Huddersfield bus station which has plans for a development with £32 million to be spend on transport in the area. The Mayor went to see the exciting plans which will be starting to take place in the not-so-distant future. ... In my manifesto, I committed to making public transport work for you, increasing people\'s access to opportunities, and helping tackle the climate emergency on our way to becoming a net-zero carbon economy by 2038 and prioritizing inclusivity across all of the transport system. And that\'s why I\'m delighted to be here today at Huddersfield Bus Station. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Kirklees Council are working together in partnership on plans to the bus station as part of a £32 million package of transport improvements to the town. And now we need you to help us shape these plans by having your say as part of the public consultation so please do get involved, it\'s important we know what you think. Thank you.','The Mayor of West Yorkshire Visits Huddersfield Bus Station','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (YouTube)','2021-08-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFzFdtu5vr79U0AzD66KxqYWG0AFrzon5icdKhsPDp1mqsxy-DOJFzTp02Hze_CU8dgPcCCqFbMhieYve0rYSUvhM88Glr-jMjsaHFBAf9lRE8TSIqLXblzd3M90NeqAl2H5sEwcEk=','Tracy Brabin, the Mayor of West Yorkshire, visited Huddersfield bus station to announce plans for a development with a £32 million package of transport improvements for the town. She emphasized increasing public transport access, tackling the climate emergency, and prioritizing inclusivity. A public consultation was launched to shape these plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2be1624e-99f7-4f66-af91-2abcd0f13ebf','infrastructure-a660-holt-lane--otley-road-junction-improvements-adel-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.964','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A review of pedestrian crossing needs on A660 Otley Road at its junction with St. Helen\'s Lane, dated January 13, 2024, mentioned the existing signalised junctions along the A660 in Adel, including Holt Lane. [16]','Junction of A660 Otley Road with New Adel Lane and St. Helens Lane','Barry Anderson (Councillor\'s website)','2024-01-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE3Hj8XWm8Ww7BIDAEM8wd1S7jsW6pfun2bCwa6KIZLnqzq7RBuqzp4tBIYkzvQG04Aa8RZsmrag3jfTljMg664SBsSgIETxtSaCCa3goUWumnqulsXnniA-hImOyj8dMFH2hKqNNi_XY2ynpv5400H385YrRT1CDxNIYgx9dl4MZrnbUL2OUraU32Q3z-ILZ9jXPMbblh6jDyz','Councillor Barry Anderson shared information on January 13, 2024, regarding a request for a formalised pedestrian crossing at a nearby junction on A660 Otley Road. The response from Highways noted concerns about congestion with further signalisation, and implicitly acknowledged the already signalised Holt Lane junction, demonstrating that the improvements at Holt Lane were in place and considered in broader traffic planning for Adel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2be19dd0-eba7-4f0d-814d-2cc9886d0234','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle charging points will be installed across the district if Wakefield Council\'s key decision makers give the go ahead at their meeting next week. Cabinet are being asked to accept a grant of £1,520,938 from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority’s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant Funding scheme.','More EV charging points coming to Wakefield as part of our plans to go green - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2024-10-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGTnt3Uydni_m51kXrCsSKCYcBw3k_01DFmFpgEeMHOS-ni87QJGAw5p4o4bFkO-rNodfB6wmDBGJl_sZG6Qw6gRpGOH50l5BEfvJc1VdsaXEvFLFsMmz2Z5wRY8IjQJzVACa7PSCC08ithJ3NBKiQoRPQq27d-fdG3cmK9pm2OnEPe6kxPJR_YYbkqkR_-fGYLtJKR-ja-u9DlaRlqdr7UNfK8oAk6m4zgdmuEU9WbHo_EMQ==','Wakefield Council announced that its cabinet was asked to accept a grant of £1,520,938 from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority’s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant funding scheme. This funding aims to install more public EV charging points across the district to meet growing demand and support decarbonisation targets.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2be29a4e-854c-4d38-98b4-b6643c751f4b','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'He said construction work at Erringden should start in spring 2024, a pre-planning engagement event for people affected around March for the Stubbing Holme Road project with construction to follow later in 2024 or early 2025, and construction of the major Hebden Bridge scheme from 2025.','Busy two years of work set for Hebden Bridge as flood scheme set to begin in 2024','Halifax Courier','2023-12-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/environment/busy-two-years-of-work-set-for-hebden-bridge-as-flood-scheme-set-to-begin-in-2024-4458390','The Halifax Courier reported on the progress of flood schemes in Hebden Bridge, stating that a pre-planning engagement event for the Stubbing Holme Road project was anticipated around March 2024, with construction expected to follow later in 2024 or early 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2bf2147c-9ec4-432a-bedf-0c8c92e504fc','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious plans to bring trams back to West Yorkshire, and deliver a multibillion-pound boost to the economy, have secured a major funding boost from the government. The Chancellor Rachel Reeves today (Wednesday 4th June) announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to get spades in the ground on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. Speaking ahead of next week\'s Spending Review, the Chancellor joined West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin at a bus depot in Huddersfield where she unveiled West Yorkshire\'s \'transport for city regions\' funding for 2027-2032. The funding will also support other vital transport infrastructure projects across the region including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield, extensive bus priority measures and cycleways on the A641 and North Kirklees transport corridors, and access improvements to unlock regeneration across six key neighbourhoods bordering on Leeds City Centre. [8]','Major funding boost secured for West Yorkshire trams','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG1eUMlacEym5lsk4z7dX59e9JLssgvjbw3EOhIdOta7TDsO2gjD99D2p1Hm7iTyaupZk5iLVb_PGncFJFdOXJTfFlJ5wq5faYOoeNkFnLR-jrzgufbERw011itmp0B67XIAY6Q4zhndemk0ros34QXM0SdOtDnjcVMXYbrc3qCslQdLpPtTNFBO7RYrdVTkoc-w2RnxDeVHiijFybv4DHqJw8Q','Chancellor Rachel Reeves announced a significant funding boost of £2.1 billion for local transport in West Yorkshire. This funding will enable the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to begin work on the region\'s tram project by 2028. Additionally, the investment will support other critical transport infrastructure, including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield, bus priority measures, cycleways in Kirklees, and access improvements in Leeds. This Mass Transit network represents a major regional infrastructure project. [8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2bf21fc7-3291-42c5-8cea-2dbfa2ecda22','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At a meeting of West Yorkshire Combined Authority on Thursday morning, members voted to award over £13m to help kickstart the City Village project, which will eventually see 900 homes built on the Kirkgate and Oastler Centre sites and other city centre locations. The money is on top of £30m funding from Homes England that was pledged towards the development last year. [4]','£13m Funding Towards Bradford City Village is Approved by West Yorkshire Combined Authority','Telegraph and Argus','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24227092.13m-funding-towards-bradford-city-village-approved/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) approved over £13 million in funding for the Bradford City Village project. This investment, from the Brownfield Housing Fund, builds on the earlier £30 million from Homes England and is crucial to kickstart the scheme, which aims to create up to 1,000 homes and new business/leisure spaces.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2c233c37-9f91-44f7-86bf-4780d088f409','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to transform Bradford\'s former retail heart into a “City Village” have advanced with the Government confirming nearly £30m for the scheme from the Brownfield Infrastructure and Land Fund. Homes England, the Government\'s housing and regeneration agency, has allocated £29.5m to support Bradford City Village, which is a major development project to transform key brownfield sites into residential areas within the city centre. The funding will be used to make improvements to the road network and public spaces, as well as support the demolition of the Oastler and Kirkgate Shopping Centres.','Government Confirms £30m Funding for Bradford City Village from Brownfield Infrastructure and Land Fund','TheBusinessDesk.com','2025-02-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGaB__AKP_wCXFv7OdPhe2hp1yGf8pqQ-RgLjBBF3pzXxPmJBpNclqV3c3VuFnBybSqr2TyLBBCI9N5pSfH4lkgOKpCuTKigF0U95Cyv5nvAAbioRdM1kIHHsepjuXpOPo1Zows4dS-G-f-V_o_QA23qhRQCE6THrimpoUKQ0hESvq4DdC10OvKV6nZ3bdNvbS6KJwVSqNg0oG9_ACLrkIirpJw9RCvI6u2BoX9mNpbSyLfX37B9C9K_nDI=','Homes England allocated £29.5 million from the Brownfield Infrastructure and Land Fund to support the Bradford City Village project. This funding is aimed at transforming key brownfield sites in the city centre into residential areas, supporting demolition and public realm improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2c3a4cbd-45c4-476c-b19f-6f436dad55b7','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'What will the new development be? The land, on Fenay Lane, could potentially deliver around 160 new homes. We identified it as part of our housing growth strategy, which was approved by Cabinet in November last year. By strategically choosing a housing provider to sell this land to, a well-resourced development partner will be able to develop these new homes on Fenay Lane – helping us address the national housing shortage without ongoing investment from us as a council. What\'s happened so far? We identified the land on Fenay Lane as part of our housing growth strategy, which was approved by Cabinet in November last year. We gave public notification that this land would be sold. Since then we\'ve considered all objections received...','Cabinet approves sale of Almondbury land for housing','Kirklees Together (Kirklees Council)','2024-01-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/news/2024/cabinet-approves-sale-of-almondbury-land-for-housing.aspx','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet approved the sale of council-owned land on Fenay Lane, Almondbury, for a housing development with a capacity for around 160 new homes. This decision was made despite 84 objections from local residents, many of whom raised concerns about the principle of building on the land, flood risk, and increased traffic. The council stated the sale aimed to deliver quality, affordable, and energy-efficient homes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2c58fc16-42c1-4f33-a977-82b262e89f2b','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2018-11-02) The final Salterhebble phase of major multi-million pound works to the A629 route which links Halifax and Huddersfield take place over the next few weeks before the focus falls on the Calder and Hebble junction. These will see completion of resurfacing work up to Falcon Street and on Salterhebble Hill itself, and follows completion of the Dryclough Lane scheme, which has now re-opened to traffic. After completion of the Salterhebble phase, works will be left in a position to continue seamlessly with the next phase of A629 corridor upgrade programme, the Calder and Hebble junction at Halifax. ... New traffic signals have also been installed, which will communicate with each other via smart technology. ... Through the £1 billion West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund, West Yorkshire Combined Authority has committed £150 million of investment into schemes such as the A629 improvements.','Work on Salterhebble phase of A629 reconstruction nears completion','YorkshireLive','2018-11-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEgwE0QtVGNPITttGsIcMVyrbU951OtJvsYivdSehl7Wuf0Q6ehThRDJGJCeOQ38M30qR1gi_FmwaTPrtP4S4xZ4rX-wtBgabnhuAlEJ-6Jw7VxJPJfflJn3Cc9uxgqBoL4yoCjgJWwbMCTizze6ZxhUyZPptDj4Z01ETA7SZp873HDwqIpi5_Knsg245drWmpOjfpOYefCWpHPGz4PzQ_eaE4ubveHug==','This news article from November 2018 reported that the final Salterhebble phase of the major A629 works linking Halifax and Huddersfield was nearing completion. It highlighted the installation of new smart traffic signals and the completion of resurfacing work and the Dryclough Lane scheme, creating additional capacity for Calderdale Royal Hospital.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2c5a4a2b-d873-4759-9d5b-d73f270a53df','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Over 2025-30, we expect Yorkshire Water to deliver a 32% reduction in storm overflows and a 75% reduction in harmful nutrients in rivers. We allow the company to invest £1.5 billion in reducing storm overflows and expect it to spend £98 million on installing water quality monitors in rivers. In return, our final decision allows Yorkshire Water to collect £8.2 billion through bills from both households and businesses over the 2025-30 period. This will recover a share of the cost of historical expenditure, as well as a portion of the £8.3 billion expenditure planned for 2025-30. [13]','Overview of Yorkshire Water\'s PR24 final determination','Ofwat','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.ofwat.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/PR24-FD-YW-overview-document.pdf','Ofwat\'s final determination for Yorkshire Water\'s PR24 (2025-2030) business plan approves an £8.3 billion expenditure. Key outcomes expected include a 32% reduction in storm overflows and a 75% reduction in harmful nutrients in rivers. Ofwat allows £1.5 billion investment specifically for reducing storm overflows and £98 million for installing water quality monitors. Average household bills are projected to increase by £177 (before inflation) from 2024-25 to 2029-30.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2cba95bd-2ad7-4554-a427-882be0fc7d40','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Officers from the Environment Agency are hosting two events where residents can view final designs for the scheme, ask any questions and meet the project team. ... On Thursday 27 February and Thursday 6 March, designs will be displayed at Hebden Bridge Town Hall. People are invited to pop in from 12pm to 8pm to view the designs and ask any questions, prior to the main planning application being submitted to the council. Environment Agency work to reduce flood risk from the River Calder and Hebden Water will consist of raising and strengthening river walls, using glass panels and raising barriers to minimise any intrusion on the iconic views for those living on the riverside. Working in partnership with Calderdale Council, the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme is designed to reduce flood risk from the River Calder and Hebden Water.','Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme designs to be put on show','GOV.UK (Environment Agency)','2025-02-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme-designs-to-be-put-on-show','The Environment Agency and Calderdale Council hosted public events on February 27 and March 6, 2025, at Hebden Bridge Town Hall, to display the final designs for the flood alleviation scheme. Residents were invited to view the plans, ask questions, and provide feedback before the main planning application was submitted. The designs include raising and strengthening river walls, using glass panels, and raising barriers to minimize visual intrusion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2cc3663f-851b-4e08-ba18-f120f4369cfd','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'SIR - While there is no answer forthcoming as to those questioning when the Bradford Interchange will re-open, the greater question is why did a block of concrete fall into the car park below, after just over eight and a half million pounds, was spent on what was described as “significant wholesale repairs” to the concrete deck, to waterproofing and drainage, and to the buses\' carriageway?','Reader letter: \'What went wrong with Interchange repairs?\'','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-04-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFhC0Ql_AInYPKw3lQOe-20EDsdIF3gvBC_Kocj9pME_DGdkRY0G1VxVemU9O4qT8nf3yfUoBBLSVF7TKZDR-q0R9iAuEei8Lk4GwkX9Z5nLNIW7DR0_H6DCgEivAK37xxU3eFgZVWpE1w9jPa5cizHoKK1NhMTcnlmHsfEFE8nugyFNCwuDmX4F4zwW6wq4K7dWcDjEugmshSua_LycYPZUqllFU3aIA0w3tjN5IU=','A reader\'s letter expressed concern and questioned the effectiveness of the previously completed £8.5 million repair scheme at Bradford Interchange. The writer highlighted the incident of concrete falling into the car park, asking why this occurred after substantial funds were spent on \'significant wholesale repairs\' to the concrete deck, waterproofing, drainage, and bus carriageway. [12]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2ce9ffaa-3afb-4465-a3a4-1770daad4fae','infrastructure-a638-doncaster-road-corridor-improvement-programme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.997','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Public engagement. Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is looking to make improvements to the A638 Doncaster Road in Wakefield and would like your feedback on the proposed improvements. The Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP) is part of a West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund package of highway related schemes. The CIP aims to provide low and medium cost interventions on the key highway network to deliver benefits for all road users, with an emphasis on reducing journey times in order to make it easier for people to get around the area and travel to work as well as improving air quality and associated health benefits. During this consultation in summer 2021, 164 people completed our public survey. Nine out of ten of you said you agreed that investment to improve transport is needed in the area. Generally, you said you agreed with the proposals. You also made suggestions for some changes and raised some concerns. You can read the outcome report here. The improvements on the A638 Doncaster Road between the junction with the A655 Black Road at Heath Common and the A61 Barnsley Road at Chantry Bridge are key to providing the Wakefield City area with the infrastructure it needs to support development.','A638 Doncaster Road, Wakefield - Corridor Improvement Programme | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-06-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a638doncasterroad','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Wakefield Council, launched a public engagement on the A638 Doncaster Road improvements during summer 2021. The initiative, part of the West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund, aimed to address issues like traffic congestion, pollution, and inadequate facilities for walkers and cyclists between Heath Common and Chantry Bridge. The consultation received 164 responses, with strong agreement on the need for investment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2d24c680-9bdf-4f9b-8b60-d76abe658993','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This Report contains a summary of the Environmental Assessments conducted by AMEC Foster Wheeler in support of the Leeds Bradford Airspace Change Proposal which is being submitted under the legacy process CAA Publication (CAP) 725 “Guidance on the Application of the Airspace Change Process”. Any change to airport operations must be assessed to establish how the change may impact noise exposure. The changes may affect people differently; for example, people living close to the Airport and in locations close to aircraft flight paths, the changes could affect the number and frequency of aircraft that are observed. This will therefore bring associated environmental effects, particularly changes in the locations of where aircraft noise is observed, changes to the amount of aircraft fuel burnt and therefore an effect on both CO2 emissions and local air quality. [19]','Leeds Bradford Airport Airspace Change Proposal Environmental Impact Report','Civil Aviation Authority (CAA)','2018-12-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.caa.co.uk/media/3956/lba-airspace-change-proposal-environmental-impact-report.pdf','An Environmental Impact Report was produced as part of Leeds Bradford Airport\'s Airspace Change Proposal. While primarily focused on airspace changes, the report summarises environmental assessments regarding potential impacts on noise exposure, fuel burn, CO2 emissions, and local air quality, reflecting broader environmental considerations related to airport expansion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2d833fc0-951b-47f7-a319-a6c4284eaf63','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This project brief sets out the scope of the feasibility study considering access improvements to Leeds Bradford International Airport (LBIA). It outlines the: scope of the requirement; study methodology; arrangements for stakeholder involvement. The brief specifies that the study should consider improved access by road, rail and bus. This study began on 1 April 2014 and concluded in November 2014. The government has now responded to this study in the 2014 Autumn Statement. [10, 11, 20]','Leeds Bradford International Airport access improvements: feasibility study brief','GOV.UK','2014-12-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/leeds-bradford-international-airport-access-improvements-brief-for-a-feasibility-study','The Department for Transport published a project brief for a feasibility study to consider options for improving road, rail, and bus access to Leeds Bradford International Airport. This study was one of six identified \'notorious and longstanding road congestion hotspots\' studies initiated by the government.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2dd08f2e-c0cf-4b1d-8d94-9e2030acf329','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Subject to planning approval, demolition of the Oastler site is anticipated to begin later this year, with construction starting in spring 2026.','Anticipated Demolition of Oastler Site and Construction Start for Phase 1','Place Yorkshire / Build News','2025-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGHWLhHyIYCTc211sub0cX6t4waKHNgz4jtNbBNVMEKDrWvzhRuILuy4eOlhNYMHZiKN8QG4eiar3tz3y8HlfJObfa7i3813_BIEIJ_kg-s_tQBNIOFjTJgOBDeCvNq4KkEd-8aAFNj685vRWep5cKpFTfv10omY25kdOTAFSfAA7Dkawg9au4fTXeqQj-9TX8','Subject to planning approval, demolition of the Oastler site is anticipated to begin later this year (Autumn 2025), preceding the commencement of construction for Phase One, which includes the Chain Street townhouses, scheduled for Spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2e123ade-3c23-4872-85ee-6876c89cc3eb','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Over the past five years, we have helped Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust to cut the carbon emissions from its St James\'s University Hospital site and reduce its electricity bill at the same time. The second and third phases of the project were supported with £22 million of grants from the UK Government\'s Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS). The project achieved the \'high commended\' accolade for sustainable achievement for Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust at the 2024 IHEEM awards.','Vital Energi helps St James\'s Hospital cut carbon emissions and receive \'high commended\' award','Vital Energi','2024-10-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.vitalenergi.co.uk/case-studies/st-james-university-hospital-heat-pumps-solutions/','Vital Energi has partnered with Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust over five years to cut carbon emissions at St James\'s University Hospital. The project, including heat pumps and connection to Leeds PIPES, has reduced gas usage significantly and earned a \'high commended\' accolade for sustainable achievement at the 2024 IHEEM awards.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2e240e26-ef7d-4642-a2cf-eb2ff36bcea8','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'AN £8.5 MILLION project to repair the bus carriageway at Bradford Interchange could start as soon as next month. The project to refurbish the surface used by buses to enter and exit the station was first proposed over two years ago. The existing carriageways were said to be “deteriorating” and the work would include waterproofing and resurfacing large sections of the station. It is made more difficult by the fact that the bus station surface lies above a car park and retail units - including a bingo hall. Originally costed at £2m, a report late last year revealed the budget had spiralled to £8.5m.','£8.5m scheme to resurface Bradford Interchange could start next month','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2022-04-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEBU0p7LTqjcdq00m2mpAdZrHhoWfjMDIshCyV9GyoPzW6HEkfKL9O5O0DL5LkZdAT69JnuLecNGq61ZZVdTIijZhvmN5nA72GItGfnN-vOh6fuyokwZyjPQWcT8wUv-tDz2q6wOsYLPunvEf5FAr-yzPdgXaKL_z72FiNXT94_hXYgz4DfM-izN-JW_IUhxV0TagkS7V5sqkJPWF7mAMmYsjDI97A4ek3FkMW4','An £8.5 million project to repair the bus carriageway at Bradford Interchange was anticipated to start as early as May 2022. The scheme, which had been proposed over two years prior, aimed to address deteriorating carriageways through waterproofing and resurfacing, a task made complex by the bus station\'s structure above a car park and retail units. The budget for the project had increased from an original £2 million to £8.5 million. [4]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2e9f53ca-05d9-403d-8232-85f45cd7de07','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Woolpack 18 New Road Yeadon Leeds LS19 7SE. 0113 250 8687 · Directions. ... © 2025 Designed & built in Burton by Punch Digital.','Woolpack Inn (Yeadon) Website Confirms Location and Services','The Woolpack','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHIGb-fU9LJrcX2UTJ8tKMSy13PnQWHbTEU1RwofI8zXB6fNxkr7IoLg1kCMRduiaS5Xgs0cQMp-35CkfR9riYouIvgfwBExiMWVOn3LALRZw-XjiAcdTtPkrl4Z22xucEy','The official website for The Woolpack in Yeadon, Leeds, provides its address and general information about the pub, including its operating hours and services. This confirms the location of the establishment hosting the EV charger.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2ed17761-c469-42eb-8a67-dddf694693e7','infrastructure-leeds-to-micklefield-rail-upgrades-transpennine-route-upgrade',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.980','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The application for The Network Rail (Leeds to Micklefield Enhancements) Order was made by Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd to the Secretary of State for Transport on 11 July 2023. [19]','Network Rail Submits Transport and Works Act Order (TWAO) Application','GOV.UK (The Network Rail (Leeds to Micklefield Enhancements) Order 2024 - Inspector\'s report)','2023-07-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/network-rail-leeds-to-micklefield-enhancements-order-inspectors-report','Network Rail Infrastructure Ltd submitted its Transport and Works Act Order (TWAO) application to the Secretary of State for Transport for the Leeds to Micklefield scheme. This order sought powers for land acquisition, temporary land use, authorisation of works, deemed planning permission, diversion of public rights of way, environmental consents, level crossing closures, and alterations to public highways.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2f4939c0-a6b3-4a08-b714-5b570dceb5a0','infrastructure-manchester-road-bus-improvements-scheme-south-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.869','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is inviting the public to give their views on proposed improvements to Manchester Road, one of the city\'s key transport routes. Key proposals include: New and extended bus lanes; Safer pedestrian and cycle crossings; More trees and greenery; Formalised parking spaces; Automatic bus lane enforcement. A drop-in information session was held on Wednesday, 2 April 2025, from 2 PM – 7 PM at the Mayfield Centre, 35 Broadway Avenue, Bradford, BD5 9NP.','Have your say on plans to improve Manchester Road','Asian Standard Newspaper','2025-03-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFF6vXuyBcX3YWrjXuTdNZMn4caG4p2pie295omsx8OKlY0uBMcfhe5xvNIxdBwr1wGsbI--nAg6hI9nWiOYsjxs874w35c1v0xkuaS6Gckz6r96wN90FIaDEmbhCWQr04bMCQ8ASVW5Edk9RE3htvRH9deL3oTi0r-7InAdk_IeFd0oNvUaFmSK6RpAzk=','This news article encourages public participation in the ongoing consultation for the Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme. It outlines the proposed upgrades, including new bus lanes, safer pedestrian and cycle crossings, more greenery, and formalized parking. It also mentions a drop-in information session at the Mayfield Centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2f694d9e-bb60-4222-88d9-0727b53ad884','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'It follows the submission of a planning application by Kirklees Council for works to create site access from Forge Lane and Ravensthorpe Road to land it owns. Up to 350 homes are earmarked for this section of the overall scheme. As part of its controversial Local Plan the council intends to build more than 4,000 houses on a vast swathe of land at Thornhill Lees between Ravensthorpe and Mirfield. ... The council\'s “hybrid” application has been submitted to its own planning department. It requests full planning permission for engineering works, drainage and utilities connection “for the provision of site access” from Forge Lane and Ravensthorpe Road. It also asks for outline planning permissions for up to 350 homes and a mixed-use development with community facilities.','Dewsbury Riverside housing scheme moves a step closer as plans submitted','Dewsbury Reporter','2021-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEaYg57_zLdYNoKYEBk3lTSvHYac7b-v3orwhe5CVOCzYB3J1PtmJduTVEbvWKqYAHqwV9EenoavDCdb6tGqDtob3M1a1El3l4gsVLQGZlKEq7CrehLk1tu0GTsyCwvgCHw3z4oPwspJiIFJ6__KVRZbntxyBp8lH8o62tmM9S_5510jc-Hpg9i2F2cPbIo6pVCLiRAzURhwkh-p4oq658aZSBP2d2EKqZ_b1g1aY-ihYeFTW2k_f9CjQHhV4sM1xdlymOKVQ==','Kirklees Council submitted a hybrid planning application for the first phase of the Dewsbury Riverside development. This application includes full planning permission for engineering works, drainage, and utilities for site access from Forge Lane and Ravensthorpe Road, as well as outline permission for up to 350 homes and mixed-use community facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2f7f9d0d-4cf8-4c52-a6ee-9185c8ed319b','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Reference: CC/094. Organisation: City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council. Start date: 2018-11-01. End date: 2023-07-07. Entry date: 2019-12-01. Point: POINT (-1.75792 53.796366). Site address: Oastler Centre, John Street. Notes: Buildings identified for redevelopment. Currently market hall. The Council are progressing plans to replace the market and have announced plans to bring this site forward for residential use. Maximum net dwellings: 1000. Minimum net dwellings: 1000. Planning permission status: not-permissioned.','Brownfield Land Register entry for Oastler Centre','Planning.data.gov.uk','2018-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://planning.data.gov.uk/brownfield-land/CC/094','An entry on the national brownfield land register identifies the Oastler Centre in Bradford for redevelopment, noting that the Council is progressing plans to replace the market and bring the site forward for residential use. This provides official recognition of the site\'s potential for housing development as early as 2018. [18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2f8b9888-14b6-4e78-8fd3-d47b5698c662','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A public consultation has been launched on plans to improve a key route into Bradford to ease congestion. The £45m proposal for the A650, along Tong Street and Wakefield Road, also aims to make public transport and active travel such as walking and cycling more reliable and accessible. If approved, it could include new bus lanes and a two-way cycle path, improved footpaths, pedestrian crossings, bus stops and junctions and road widening along parts of Tong Street. The scheme, delivered by Bradford Council in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, covers a combined 2.2 mile (3.6km) stretch of Wakefield Road and Tong Street, from the junction with Croft Street in the city centre to the Tong Leadership Academy School. [9]','Public consultation launched on Bradford A650 improvement works','BBC News','2025-03-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-leeds-68506110','BBC News reported on the public consultation launched for the £45 million A650 upgrade along Tong Street and Wakefield Road in Bradford. The project aims to ease congestion and make public transport and active travel more reliable and accessible. If approved, it could include new bus lanes, a two-way cycle path, improved footpaths, pedestrian crossings, bus stops, junctions, and road widening along parts of Tong Street. The scheme, delivered by Bradford Council in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, covers a combined 3.6km stretch.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2f9eb821-b4a5-4114-b8da-f870a3e011a6','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'O and C Management Limited wants to convert currently unused office and storage space at 12-16 Horton Street into four two-bedroom flats. Number 12 is Grade II listed, says the application, which is seeking planning permission and listed building consent for the work from Calderdale Council. The company says the application forms part of an ongoing wider regeneration strategy within the town centre, seeking to refurbish and redevelop “dozens of sites” in the Westgate Quarter. [10]','Westgate Quarter: Plans for four new flats submitted as part of latest stage of plans to bring Halifax town centre buildings back to life and avoid \'urban decay\'','Halifax Courier','2024-05-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFe524Ny-loPkn1oCjDGcj34ddlGRljKmw4sWNIJHzczYXg3s3dLQoE8ffk3Q-PKjZ8Ld0ePOHuOSXp0Qyd4ytH4LCVJTSIPHFH96szecxNOtuJuMwwzyOJBwNjyEFL2Iy98PKaidcG7P847epVwo6yNTH-YLRDkbujTRcmLaeTqeE6N3WeH72CyuzV766EH6SU5K3v7o-tW0kV-MEbODywbCgpFKqoPrQbpuPczpBuAh2pgu4bQzwHEL1oYCDPUqyJ6Jl8SmaOsbB-QXolL1sLDq0lptUwQ1dkBUfauVwbDfC6Vi2rSuhczNToCiss6ua24tWl0WS9rXXKNeade6nGF790dP2xASC1Pso=','O and C Management Limited submitted planning applications to Calderdale Council to convert unused office and storage space at 12-16 Horton Street into four two-bedroom flats. This forms a part of a wider ongoing regeneration strategy within the Westgate Quarter aimed at revitalizing derelict premises.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2fefed8a-91a8-481a-816b-159fbab7992c','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Energy Savers Loan, funded by Wakefield Council and provided by Leeds City Credit Union, offers an interest-free loan for privately rented homes. This loan can be used to cover expenses related to insulation, heating, and microgeneration projects. Loans are available up to a maximum of £7,000, with a repayment period of 5 years. Private landlords must also be a member or agree to join the Council\'s Wakefield Responsible Landlord Scheme where insulation and/or heating measures are being installed. [3]','Help with home energy improvements - Wakefield Council (Wakefield Landlords Energy Savers Loan)','Wakefield Council','2024-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFPzrXDb09YdvFZOFvvZFC031dbKcH1mHKmSqdsBEvBMaoANJoCFijU_rlvF5bDFWD1Ylu_8fizk7OlO8fAlSG6osuYhSp_HXnK9CPHhpxl2w0lV_TirgGxHuLhKc1LzEOOeay_entVfPZd2bQq680UDAJYQGWNmsY6GOnDYjue5vR5HSsaoBS2RUiobQWepXPO','Wakefield Council offers an interest-free \'Wakefield Landlords Energy Savers Loan\' of up to £7,000, funded by the Council and provided by Leeds City Credit Union. These loans are for privately rented homes within the Wakefield district to fund insulation, heating, and microgeneration projects. Landlords must be members of or agree to join the Wakefield Responsible Landlord Scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('2ff21992-de6a-423b-a199-b9dc0189150b','infrastructure-bp-pulse-stourton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.422','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BP Pulse reports significant progress in expanding its rapid and ultra-fast EV charging infrastructure in 2023, committing to invest £1 billion in the UK\'s EV infrastructure over the next decade. This indicates ongoing network development that would include sites like Stourton.','BP Pulse delivers significant progress in the rollout and reliability of its rapid & ultra-fast EV charging network','BP News and insights','2023-12-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.bp.com/en_gb/united-kingdom/home/news/press-releases/bp-pulse-delivers-significant-progress-in-the-rollout-and-reliability-of-its-rapid-and-ultra-fast-ev-charging-network.html','BP Pulse reports significant progress in expanding its rapid and ultra-fast EV charging infrastructure in 2023, committing to invest £1 billion in the UK\'s EV infrastructure over the next decade. This indicates ongoing network development that would include sites like Stourton.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3013852b-1297-4c85-a3f8-7c91802e1b73','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority, working in partnership with Wakefield Council and Leeds City Council, is investing £22.5m in two key roads connecting the Wakefield District with Leeds – the A61 and A639. It is part of £317m allocated to Leeds City Region (LCR) from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF). ... An initial consultation on these proposals was held during July and August 2022. Feedback received will be used to help shape more detailed plans. West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s website has more details on each scheme. Delivery of the improvements is scheduled for 2024 subject to approvals.','Transforming Cities - A61 and A639','Wakefield Council','2022-07-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFnO5sWgYYXzUFq9blZuL1hETp0OSnFIGPk9Re__sP85bhf2FQRjiyKH9XevVVRfsu94sw24iPnk6mKyTxspRNcunN4gH7y6I6lroDmzgBSIUMCSFmIThTESfBFJZvUftJKT2gb_LhNRi3EeFUxyH08tUzIwCGM6gIZMncBnbtUb-nPW7RVX0x-zZt0hlmSuvaU7xZvwe54qKjVs7At7YuqvnCQRA0lCdWBYXs=','West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Wakefield Council and Leeds City Council, is investing £22.5 million in improvements to the A61 and A639. These schemes are part of the broader £317 million allocated to the Leeds City Region from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund. The proposals include dedicated bus and cycle lanes, wider pavements, and smart traffic lights, with delivery of improvements scheduled for 2024 subject to approvals. [3, 7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('304e0c8f-117c-4b2c-b130-6d84cd77d4f2','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(Press release Leeds City Council:) Leeds, 21 June 2023 - Construction is underway to protect a section of railway by Kirkstall Bridge that has flooded several times in the past, most notably in the 2015 Boxing Day floods. Part of the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 (FAS2), the flood defence works on the right bank (railway side) of the River Aire upstream of Kirkstall Bridge will comprise of a flood defence solution stretching 1.4km using an earth embankment or steel sheet piled flood walls in some areas.','Construction Underway to Protect Kirkstall Railway Infrastructure','Royal BAM Group (Press release Leeds City Council)','2023-06-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE_uLECeYXnRSxRDmVyyTw-q7-Y6J2wjkEnpnURIv00fLAiXU78Z_bhkVfI5OInB3gbath-lCvfsUZteFs8AtamJOgWgfuMb4fGAS5aYV9LE3y00JijqDLBkXNKk-qMzJ0Om8co0S0chcZtmgLeJSJsixUTf_dM4xhQRZFT9CXkzzsnNOgsVI_nuI2Vy3KL21somyJhamTutCTVsPo52kebCdbVTeyOZc5nawgP7nvH0ie1fQ==','Construction began in June 2023 on flood defence works upstream of Kirkstall Bridge to protect a section of railway that has historically flooded. These works, part of Leeds FAS2, include a 1.4km earth embankment or steel sheet piled flood walls, and are being carried out in partnership with Network Rail.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('30743599-65d5-4870-b311-636df1a02b4b','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The government is set to confirm an indicative allocation of £2.1 billion in the second round of the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS 2) funding stream for West Yorkshire, covering future sustainable transport projects between 2027 and 2032. This represents a significant future investment, with the first phase of West Yorkshire\'s Mass Transit network being a key part. This phase aims to create two tram lines: a Leeds Line (from St James\'s University Hospital through Leeds city centre to the White Rose) and a Bradford Line (connecting Bradford and Leeds city centres). The Combined Authority will publish its preferred route options later this year, with a full public consultation planned during 2026.','Government to confirm £2.1bn transport funding for West Yorkshire','Wakefield First','2025-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldfirst.com/news/government-to-confirm-2-1bn-transport-funding-for-west-yorkshire/','This news article reports on the government\'s indicative allocation of £2.1 billion to West Yorkshire for the second round of CRSTS funding (CRSTS 2), covering sustainable transport projects between 2027 and 2032. A significant component of this future investment is the first phase of West Yorkshire\'s Mass Transit network, which will create two tram lines: a Leeds Line and a Bradford Line. The Combined Authority plans to publish preferred route options later this year, with a full public consultation scheduled for 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('30779652-76a3-4651-b2ee-5a26f70cdd89','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3 of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme is providing £1.425 billion of grant funding over the financial years 2022/23 to 2024/25 to public sector bodies to install low carbon heating measures that reduce direct carbon emissions from their buildings. Over £613 million of this funding has been awarded through the first Phase 3 application window, Phase 3a. For Phase 3a, 381 applications were submitted with a combined value of over £861 million. 231 projects were awarded funding, to be delivered by 170 public sector organisations.','Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: Phase 3a Summary Report','GOV.UK','2023-08-31 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-phase-3a-summary-report','This report provides an overview of Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme, highlighting that over £613 million in grant funding was awarded to 231 projects by 170 organisations. It also details the scheme\'s objectives, which include funding heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures for public sector bodies. This context applies to the South Crosland Primary project as a recipient.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3088133c-8c92-4d94-aa23-d16fa639fec2','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Luddenden | Conservation-area | Planning Data. Reference, 9. Name, Luddenden. Organisation, Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council. Start date, 1973-02-26.','Luddenden Conservation Area Designated','planning.data.gov.uk','1973-02-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGUW6eh2nnE5xbPXW4i-kWDzVE9qckbQB4qzSbGP6evabNqmm9hnt80m-Xqujb3_RHBJ2aUb3Ol7YH0Kz3ZmpNjQ6vHlcY8lfcwB51TDoI7K-fo_eGHtmpzGPdxRtdXfbuOufFLgelzJ6dMNQ==','The Luddenden Conservation Area was officially designated on February 26, 1973, by Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council, acknowledging its special architectural or historic interest. This designation provides a historical context for the area where the flood alleviation scheme is located.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('30b35d25-060d-4f57-8706-a2e27152a39c','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water has embarked on a series of major investments to reduce storm overflows and improve water quality across the region. These projects form part of a £180 million program slated for completion by April 2025, with an additional £1.5 billion planned between 2025 and 2030 to reduce storm overflows and improve water quality. The three examples below are the latest announced as part of the utility\'s £180 million storm overflow improvement plan... In Sheffield, a £1.4 million upgrade is underway at Cricket Inn Crescent... Northallerton is another key focus, with a £445,000 project... In Marton, near Pickering, Yorkshire Water is investing £835,000... [17]','Yorkshire Water invests in reducing sewer overflows across its service region','Water & Wastewater Treatment (WWT)','2025-01-21 00:00:00.000','https://wwtonline.co.uk/news/yorkshire-water-invests-in-reducing-sewer-overflows-across-its-service-region/23722','Yorkshire Water announced major investments to reduce storm overflows and improve water quality across its service region. This includes an additional £1.5 billion planned between 2025 and 2030 as part of its AMP8 programme. Examples of ongoing projects include a £1.4 million upgrade in Sheffield, a £445,000 project in Northallerton, and an £835,000 investment in Marton, aimed at reducing storm discharges and infiltration.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('310c017b-f943-49b8-acbe-6b2dc3390bad','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first planning application for Bradford\'s City Village scheme has now been made - and if it is approved work could begin later this year. An additional 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces, each with a designated parking space. Several consultations have been conducted regarding the City Village plans, with feedback from these consultations included in the application. [7]','Full details of Bradford City Village scheme outlined ahead of construction - Business Live','Business Live','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFs5VJ8GRXByabcRCpsX_-6ItmOyzVNmzhu2zq3xRXatE9-aCyzlijTDVuoD7Eaq2VHk0CCAZSw7jIQXYl-_JNzs9lCnlZLKJRSo08QtuiOnalDYPpdKDBjZZt_28sgEdtDbFRM5KNyVA7P-7pLreMuWLK3pc1l81HgZZKbiX-kZ3P60Z6Ivbz','The first planning application for Bradford\'s City Village scheme was formally lodged, detailing the initial phase of development on Chain Street and a portion of the Oastler site. It included 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, each with designated parking. The submission followed several public consultations, with construction potentially commencing later in the year with the demolition of the Oastler Shopping Centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3136658c-4080-4041-8c4b-387c1e701a79','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WHAT IS YOUR PROPOSAL? … Brief outline of proposal and the overall aims/purpose of making this change: To reduce a service or activity (i.e. do less of something) To increase a service or activity (i.e. do more of something) To implement the first phases of developing for infrastructure and housing at Dewsbury Riverside urban extension, south of Ravensthorpe Road, Ravensthorpe. Including allotment, mosque and playgroup relocation, alongside the construction of new highway infrastructure.','Dewsbury Riverside Integrated Impact Assessment Stage 1','Kirklees Council','2020-01-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGY2NFHO2iZvpNGXyk4tQkJrWtVrGpb7UuBvdodMQcFxR_nkbdcQ0ALI5Qn7F6r9tfo8hKByd4YwujB8ZpZt3impVy6nVKh-nHhivTz0FTjCqgkAwHPmw9rN8Nx6ojn0skvEwofMslWXjAUfg-WAXLeQWz9Za_Kh8Qox2reTg9OMnqpePgI1MsvnFQX_4o6E6zH_hP4SXUqjHSobO5oU-pR_2UvUHiN-A1D9yvbpY0MYAtmbEN5tPClQCpE1RJ32oOyVS0=','Kirklees Council published an Integrated Impact Assessment (Stage 1) for the Dewsbury Riverside urban extension. The assessment focuses on the initial phases of infrastructure and housing development, including the relocation of allotments, a mosque, and a playgroup, alongside the construction of new highway infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('31418ff1-f2c7-4852-8b6c-df274fcecdb9','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is seeking feedback from people who live in, work in, and visit Wakefield city centre on plans to improve travel and the city centre. A four-week public consultation was held from Monday 1 March to Sunday 28 March 2021.','Public Consultation on Wakefield City Centre Improvements','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/wakefield-city-centre','Wakefield Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a four-week public consultation from March 1 to March 28, 2021. This consultation sought feedback from residents, workers, and visitors on initial proposals to improve travel and the city centre. Proposals included new cycle lanes, better connectivity between rail stations, and improved bus journey reliability, with plans divided into specific \'Zone\' locations across the city centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3144c3b9-a92c-47aa-8f2e-e7bf092a2279','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In July 2024, community engagement consultants AR Urbanism were appointed by Homes England to develop a series of place-based indicators for Dewsbury Riverside. These indicators outline and inform specific and local opportunities for social value that reflect the local needs of each place. Notably, there was significant crossover between the issues outlined in the \'Listening To..\' work and the issues discussed by residents in the AR Urbanism consultation work, particularly surrounding local transport infrastructure.','Dewsbury Riverside Housing Delivery Update','Kirklees Council','2024-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEl7DJsUqWMYt3vwT_VNOA5jC_SLoe4VG_eFRa9hIaIS7XzDjRB7-GEv8cm_23IqQXVjNUcx_dwh7vRv_LCNSum_sB-ujmfrrKrcBDqijgGJWdj0lMox-MVcleMA2LFeNEQqeTb-bGCl_V4tOGzmBZY1PNWq4t04zeJxDbK7-w=','In July 2024, Homes England appointed community engagement consultants AR Urbanism to develop place-based indicators for Dewsbury Riverside. This initiative aimed to outline and inform specific local opportunities for social value, reflecting local community needs, particularly concerning local transport infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('315dd0c6-a8d7-474b-9bf4-d290286f043f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Chancellor Rachel Reeves today (Wednesday 4th June) announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to get spades in the ground on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. [27]','Major funding boost secured for West Yorkshire trams','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (press release via news report)','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/major-funding-boost-secured-for-west-yorkshire-trams/','Chancellor Rachel Reeves announced a significant allocation of £2.1 billion in local transport funding for West Yorkshire, which will enable the Combined Authority to commence construction on the tram project by 2028. This investment is aimed at improving public transport connections and boosting economic growth in the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3192b990-4724-4a18-943e-2f097e6b59f3','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Working for developer CEG, BAM has completed its 37,800 sq ft seven-storey office development on Globe Road, marking the first new build office to be delivered in Leeds this year. Globe Point provides next generation workspace for over 400 people and its striking flat iron design offers spectacular views across the city from the roof terrace gardens. [15]','BAM completes Globe Point – the first new office development to complete in Leeds in 2022','BAM News','2022-08-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.bam.co.uk/news/bam-completes-globe-point-the-first-new-office-development-to-complete-in-leeds-in-2022/','BAM Construction completed Globe Point, the 37,800 sq ft, seven-storey office development, marking the first new build office delivered in Leeds in 2022. It provides modern workspace and features a flat iron design.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('31f48212-c428-4c52-a7c0-3f5a3eba05fb','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Elsewhere, Penistone line capacity work now has government approval (p2). Let\'s get on with it! ... Funding will be centred on enhanced route capacity and increased line speeds, leading to a half- hourly timetable – doubling of frequency on the line – and reducing timings. This should make the railway more relevant to the places it serves. To increase train frequency there will have be longer lengths of double track. This could mean more loops, existing loops extended, or both. [28]','Yorkshire Rail Campaigner - Number 63: Winter 2023-4','Railfuture','2023-12-16 00:00:00.000','https://railfuture.org.uk/article1287-Yorkshire-Rail-Campaigner-number-63-Winter-2023-4','A Railfuture Yorkshire newsletter mentioned that Penistone Line capacity work has government approval. It highlights the need for longer lengths of double track and higher line speeds to achieve a half-hourly timetable and improved reliability, addressing population growth along the route.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('31ffa166-139b-4f74-a362-6547bbc3b66b','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'June 2022. Work has started in Todmorden to install a new crossing point outside Lidl on Halifax Road. These works are expected to last until 28 June 2022. Work on the islands, kerb lines and footpaths near the roundabout at the junction of Rochdale Road and Halifax Road is underway. These works are expected to be complete by 20 July 2022.','Work Starts on Todmorden Area A646 Improvements','Calderdale Next Chapter (Calderdale Council)','2022-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGDz6N-pAvKM03re_O3p_9uT2NXRUQFmP51UUGzAZYwRdKdE3Cp6DFEaU8Jd49qops5v_tKt-bbVLP3eABhWiRza00qvyWxFC3q5uTEcf4VBmyrV_otwHu_pigs5-y7vGbqxi0NIa69fk2Vz9QKp6Bg546pVDnG6CqrnRo2S0Xc38v_PqYwuym0mpokzWY=','Calderdale Council announced the commencement of work in the Todmorden area as part of the A646 Corridor Improvement Programme. This phase included improved pedestrian facilities, junction enhancements, paving, and bus stop upgrades. Specific projects mentioned were a new crossing point outside Lidl (scheduled to finish by June 28, 2022) and improvements near the Rochdale Road/Halifax Road roundabout (expected complete by July 20, 2022).','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('32357958-722b-414e-88cf-10df21bdd11d','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'There is still some uncertainty about funding being secured for some of the later phases of flood alleviation work at a Halifax project. ... A lot of work has been undertaken at Copley village, but funding for some planned elements as still to be signed off by Government, flood partners heard. ... Environment Agency senior advisor Paul Swales said there was still work to do with later phases, for example securing planning permission for some of the work and some design work. There was still some uncertainty about funding arrangements going ahead.','Copley flood scheme progress: Uncertainty around funding being secured for later phases of flood work','Halifax Courier','2025-04-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHJGTpJnSs89kZWyaG5yAMAMgE9S1ZYMMNacMwetfJ4yB9uSA1LuC1oUJStO5b_lJWAhZO8I3mvMnZcSv4v98kk8qdzLhF5MsXa6Sf6Ke4p0fyio4qi3lHxdj2ynwM7ge0R2YxzwiQ3RtNSym2yJzmgN00UIgXRTeyfBNRNn9_CcmAL-P-zqd3zN350HS3m5AQjP7vpCeE-6FU0tYQLIbaVXPXhucnuWIm6ZKxPMYPWm-MTRyXMbRQhJtyZfDpAR38gJMfggxdBDYzOaVO_ZvXBOtpX_z4VlQ50uw==','A report from the Halifax Courier indicates that there is still uncertainty regarding securing funding for later phases of the flood alleviation work in Copley, specifically concerning further planned elements such as drainage at Copley cricket ground.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('323b6d31-19ee-4b28-9ace-ca6936885f62','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (A6194, also known as Neil Fox Way) is a new single-carriageway road opened in 2017 (Source 4). The relief road\'s opening, within programme, in April 2017 (Source 6). The Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (WERR) has been officially opened by Cllr Peter Box CBE, Leader of Wakefield Council and Chair of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Source 2).','Wakefield Eastern Relief Road Officially Opened','Wakefield Council / Wikipedia / Local Government Association','2017-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHQBNYsAyMEtmJWZz6dCgy-CB_Rc-Jg4JU9u4Rtajvh0wpPGbzWBZ1vjsyDYx-vzaGK9Lz2sGZdecAFL2G3i7pw9iJWykmXVTO0Y8jNjaH2O0lAxDSGdJHaglZoXSPql_R3s1YQfTiP7AzpN2VTZJVaC0-HC4Wo1dl5N77VLmztw_jdGGOASPfl3KUIpyCHDFUubPLtXdmlKQT4r79BehDSQ4jgWA2J12R3hXapvHE3fnBdzA==','The Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (WERR), also known as Neil Fox Way, officially opened in April 2017. The 5.5km road was designed to alleviate congestion within Wakefield and support the development of 2,500 new homes at the City Fields urban extension.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('328ab40d-72dc-470a-892b-5b11bb643ba8','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-ministry-of-justice-leeds-courts-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.352','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Application Portal closed four weeks later at 2pm on Wednesday 3 November 2021. The Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme provided £553m in government grants to 160 public sector organisations across the country to install 217 clean heat and energy efficiency projects. [6]','Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme Phase 3a Application Window Closure','Salix Finance','2021-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.salixfinance.co.uk/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme','Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme, under which the Ministry of Justice secured funding for the Leeds Courts project, closed for new applications on 3 November 2021. This scheme provided government grants totaling £553 million to 160 public sector organisations for 217 clean heat and energy efficiency projects across the country.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('328e54b2-5e79-4ad7-8d5c-6fb7216d5668','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A series of major transport schemes are set to begin in Kirklees in July 2025, with funding secured from the Transforming Cities Fund (now part of the CRSTS programme). These projects aim to transform key travel routes in Dewsbury and Huddersfield, making it easier to walk, cycle, and use public transport. Work on the A638 Dewsbury to Cleckheaton Sustainable Travel Corridor is expected to start from Monday 14 July, prioritising pedestrian safety with new controlled crossings and improved public transport with a new bus lane on Bradford Road. The first phase of the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme will also get underway, transforming Northumberland Street, Trinity Street, and St John\'s Road with high-quality paving, wider footways, and improved cycle infrastructure.','Multi-million-pound investment to transform transport links across Kirklees','Kirklees Council','2025-07-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/news/2025-july/multi-million-pound-investment-to-transform-transport-links-across-kirklees/','Kirklees Council announced that several major transport schemes, funded partly by the Transforming Cities Fund (now incorporated into CRSTS), are set to begin in July 2025. These projects aim to transform key travel routes in Dewsbury and Huddersfield. Specific schemes include the A638 Dewsbury to Cleckheaton Sustainable Travel Corridor, which started work on July 14, and the first phase of the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections. These improvements will enhance pedestrian safety, public transport provision (e.g., new bus lanes), and cycling infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('32c0c111-5296-4629-833f-fcfe27498225','infrastructure-normanton-golf-club-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.339','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'EV charging stations in Wakefield ... Alfa Power/menqXamjbZ - Alfa Power Charging - Aberford Rd, Stanley Normanton Golf Club. ... Find electric car charge points in Wakefield or nearby. ... © 2025 - ChargeFinder - Charging stations for electric cars (EV)','Charging stations for EV in Wakefield - ChargeFinder','ChargeFinder','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFCU_URuZ0jT-hHyRkQ4fqBa9-14dFSAa-3mNyhA8bxC2RGP5eqJZ-9eH90Ou_t20yoaDvYfACLRuX_iV4op3S_vnEPdf6A2AZ5N4FCHmOZDiSG7BsfY9acE7VzhQpny5Wto93QUsQnPnqunQ_Cq0mS2x','ChargeFinder lists \'Alfa Power/menqXamjbZ - Alfa Power Charging - Aberford Rd, Stanley Normanton Golf Club\' as one of the operational EV charging stations in Wakefield. This inclusion in the 2025 data confirms the availability of EV charging at the golf club.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('32db1b05-2d55-465a-ba2f-ff7a737803c4','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Environment Agency-led FRRS 2 Group A projects (Copley, Shaw Wood Road, Machpelah and Calderside) have funding approval to progress to Full Business Case (FBC). The Calderdale Council-led projects (Railes Close, Cottonstones) are progressing with site investigation and hydraulic analysis complete. In Group B, the strategic outline business case for Hebble Brook (Dean Clough) has been approved. Sowerby Bridge has received £1.7m of funding from central government and will now be progressed as a standalone project. Calderdale ... In the light of a recent announcement about further government funding for the scheme, the proposals for Stubbing Holme Road and Erringden Hillside will be progressed to full business case.','Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Updates','Calderdale Council','2024-09-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG8OLFguz9bDL9b_3YgqCnpW5TozHN-0s7lQLFbrzAJ0NuQR0vFizGERQpa0H5kioome2riI5tmLSJ4pmZ6CmrBmdGWuX4DqNUszcCcgavuc6ExEqI3G9ixCm2bCYovQsyNhUuHz6KDrav1SI9455I1EKgw7HXo2a31PyyRm1XRH1saAeQ_bI8yJkyyaMhhtg==','Copley, along with other projects (Shaw Wood Road, Machpelah, Calderside), has received funding approval from the Environment Agency to progress to Full Business Case as part of the FRRS 2 Group A.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('33a27eab-3dc9-4e12-a0a2-880c30b179e6','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-weaver-network',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.799','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Chancellor Rachel Reeves today (Wednesday 4th June) announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to get spades in the ground on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. Speaking ahead of next week\'s Spending Review, the Chancellor joined West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin at a bus depot in Huddersfield where she unveiled West Yorkshire\'s \'transport for city regions\' funding for 2027-2032. The £2.5bn mass transit programme will have spades in the ground by 2028, with the intention for the first trams to be operating before the mid-2030s. [12]','Major Funding Boost Secured for West Yorkshire Trams (£2.1 Billion)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/major-funding-boost-secured-for-west-yorkshire-trams/','Chancellor Rachel Reeves announced a substantial £2.1 billion allocation of local transport funding to West Yorkshire. This significant investment is earmarked to enable the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to commence construction (\'spades in the ground\') on the Mass Transit tram project by 2028, with the intention for operations to begin before the mid-2030s.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('33b25865-501f-41d3-8a41-25054e73df69','infrastructure-frizinghall-station-revitalization',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.032','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Schoolchildren have been proving it\'s not only the major gestures that matter as Bradford celebrates being UK City of Culture 2025. Monday 19 May saw the opening of a new platform 0, built by Network Rail to boost the number of LNER seats between Bradford Forster Square station and London by more than 36,000 a week. A couple of miles up the line from Forster Square is Frizinghall Primary School, who have been busy sprucing up nearby Frizinghall station. Tim Goddard, Network Rail maintenance protection co-ordinator, said: “This was a joint initiative we ran with Bradford Council\'s enforcement officers and Frizinghall Primary School, assisted by Railscape.”','Bradford school\'s station clean-up for City of Culture 2025 - Network Rail media centre','Network Rail media centre','2025-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEG1ROB_boWvEcCk6Z3ew4RcCMurBA9Y8bye9QT5ysl7gHaVIBKWhO0s2v-_fRuiataITRqZIaE14nXyfLLmgpPNDdXHCZuOYC8UQq01PKvcUUzL_W8JxFpRDwaU_qqJ1OS_INU0iWCt-eZ1vJnJ1L365K39HrPCYqgjho_LrVRC439DaaV-E2bTotzYy66n6nWk3nyP0GapJOQifrdTU2nuRpG','Network Rail reported on a community engagement project where pupils from Frizinghall Primary School, alongside Network Rail, Bradford Council, and Railscape, conducted a clean-up operation at Frizinghall station. This initiative, part of Bradford\'s UK City of Culture 2025 celebrations, aimed to tackle litter and fly-tipping and foster a sense of ownership and pride among the children for their local railway asset.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('34260c08-65fb-4053-97a9-9f982f746cd4','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This is the dealership page for Lookers Nissan Leeds, formerly owned by the Benfield Group. ... Lookers Nissan Leeds 83-85 Kirkstall Road Leeds West Yorkshire LS3 1HS. ... Lookers have a new Nissan dealership near you in Leeds at Kirkstall Road. We stock a great range of new and used Nissan cars.','Lookers Nissan Leeds Dealership Operations and Benfield Group Legacy','Car Dealer Reviews / Lookers.co.uk','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.cardealerreviews.co.uk/dealership/lookers-nissan-leeds-3171','The Lookers Nissan Leeds dealership, located at 83-85 Kirkstall Road, currently operates at a site formerly owned by the Benfield Group. It serves as a hub for new and used Nissan car sales and aftersales services, which implicitly includes support for electric vehicles, substantiated by the presence of on-site charging infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3451eeef-bc28-419b-90e9-7b1fb23463be','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council cabinet members agreed to allocate the money to settle claims over the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (WERR), also called Neil Fox Way. The local authority will now apply to West Yorkshire Combined Authority to recover the sum. A council report said \'insufficient budget was made available\' to cover the cost of the claims which was higher than expected (Source 9).','Neil Fox Way: £3.4m bypass compensation funding approved by Council','Wakefield Express','2024-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGIcbBmzB9McnTlXbQQUiJRJm3VIp8J9EcjSF_R-6pZ2yTbpMSTHjZrrAw_D3XFd961ukVo3DPJosVBL_NVvIGMQGCsNzG1ZfYlFBFBMGJnCgsYNvQyeQHcWWkg7pmox5Jl6HbwEQtpcBlxC9QVfjMNedey2eUM4X3cG1uJoIvc6jBac-s7BEBZsion_4SgOWWYBPLrH5T8ul_Ygdnd4juXsRGf5cgcBwhr','On March 20, 2024, Wakefield Council cabinet members approved the allocation of an additional £3.4 million to settle outstanding compensation claims related to the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (Neil Fox Way). The council planned to seek reimbursement for this sum from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, citing an insufficient initial budget for claims.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3491d868-d36c-4572-9fef-25d6f0332247','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'CEG has selected BAM Construction as preferred contractor for the first phase of its £350million developments at Globe Road. This will include a 38,000 sq ft speculative development incorporating office space with ground floor break out space, retail and leisure. The news was announced last night (25/09/19) at the launch of Temple. Temple is a new district within the city centre and forms a key part of the South Bank Regeneration Area of Leeds adjacent to Leeds Railway Station. [2]','£350 million project set to start on site as Temple district launches','CEG','2019-09-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.ceg.co.uk/news-insight/350-million-project-set-to-start-on-site-as-temple-district-launches/','CEG officially launched \'Temple\', a new district within Leeds city centre\'s South Bank. BAM Construction was selected as the preferred contractor for the first phase of Globe Road developments, including a 38,000 sq ft office, retail, and leisure space.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('34c3acf8-b9de-49f8-9667-05b731972b5c','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council is working with developers to build new affordable homes for rent. As work has been completed on a new development in Soothill, Batley, the council has announced it has appointed the Vistry Group to work on a 150-home development in Almondbury. The site on Fenay Lane was identified as part of the council\'s housing growth strategy, which was approved by Cabinet in November 2023. Since Cabinet, the site has undergone a rigorous competitive land sale process where bids were considered to maximise the number of affordable homes and ensure all new housing is energy efficient...','Kirklees Council works with Vistry Group to build 150 new homes in Almondbury','Huddersfield Hub','2025-03-26 00:00:00.000','https://huddersfieldhub.co.uk/kirklees-council-works-with-vistry-group-to-build-150-new-homes-in-almondbury/','Huddersfield Hub reported on Kirklees Council\'s collaboration with Vistry Group for the 150-home development on Fenay Lane, Almondbury. This follows a competitive land sale process after the site was identified in the council\'s housing growth strategy. Vistry, a Homes England Strategic Partner, will develop the homes, with Yorkshire Housing managing the affordable units. Planning application submission is expected in winter 2025-26, and construction by late summer 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('355d1582-ad55-48eb-9c5e-95dd8512cd8c','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Department for Transport (DfT) are providing local authorities funding to deliver publicly accessible charge point infrastructure through the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) fund. As a result, West Yorkshire Combined Authority has been awarded grants of £15.83 million from the LEVI fund. Kirklees has been awarded a total of £2,494,389 to deliver EV charging infrastructure in areas which are predominately without off-street parking. These areas currently deemed to be non-commercially viable to the private sector, therefore the fund is designed to support commercial partnerships in the EV space. Phase 1 of the project is expected to provide up to 150 charging points to be distributed in key areas of Kirklees, both off-street and on-street, to support current and future uptake of Electric Vehicles.','Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure fund (LEVI) Charging Points in Kirklees Residential Areas (Decision)','Kirklees Council','2025-05-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH94Cy0Wt3I0s2rzipA0DRmexLGDsUXxP_uzYLYh-IcPA1FWMAfolGU3gGej7qP-9sexS2oaBrg5ZQqAFPRPWhAbPmZnhr_3_t0fyKdqs1axfF9LqJPLGJ0n7se9vPqdSX5VOfUrXWML8GS1bg_a5Dv9yIQd5zZu9RViaw=','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet approved a report detailing its £2,494,389 allocation from the LEVI fund, provided via the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. This funding is aimed at delivering publicly accessible EV charging infrastructure in residential areas, particularly those without off-street parking, which are currently non-commercially viable for the private sector. Phase 1 of the project is expected to provide up to 150 charging points.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('35690086-3769-4d19-a2a6-4488e1208ecb','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Pupils in Calderdale took to their local streets (Monday 23 May) to identify the problems they experience on their journey to school, including litter, heavy traffic and pavement parking. St Augustine\'s VA Junior and Infant School pupils were joined by representatives from Living Streets, the UK charity for everyday walking, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council on the School Route Audit. The audit aims to identify improvements that could be made to the local streets to enable even more families to walk to school. The recommendations will be brought together in a report by Living Streets to help inform Calderdale Council\'s actions.','Calderdale pupils set on making the walk to school safer','Living Streets','2022-05-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQESLyvhkTVpZQ0n770BnAgx1s1FPatVvkY4QVcJra8YbHEov1wbdUAwohiSwDbI89JkLuR1pwY0-jgaNf1JvVrzZ9V9pRRwJuWEbP134i6cWUnZIlN_pTXs5GFaSir83Qf4oPelGhWynkRVoPUnEdPmNfAMTZ47hlW1o8c-8By2WpRWOki2PaEnnIOcja-vIAfS8oTfIyjal3emXTTmdJ85WQ==','Pupils in Calderdale, including those from St Augustine\'s VA Junior and Infant School, participated in a School Route Audit with Living Streets, West Yorkshire Combined Authority, and Calderdale Council. The audit aimed to identify problems such as litter, heavy traffic, and pavement parking on their journeys to school, with recommendations to inform Calderdale Council\'s actions to make streets safer and encourage active travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('35d9226b-4051-43bd-9f38-7a5a5f2662ac','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Southern Gateway is being shaped with the support of world-class expertise. Initially developed in partnership with WSP, the masterplan is now being advanced by Arup, who bring global experience in sustainable urban regeneration. Their involvement ensures the vision for Southern Gateway is not only ambitious but also deliverable. This ambitious regeneration will not only modernise infrastructure but also pave the way for the creation of vibrant new inner-city communities. By consolidating existing uses and reimagining underutilised land, the Southern Gateway will support the delivery of high-quality homes, accessible green spaces, and sustainable transport connections.','Bradford Southern Gateway: Project Vision and Regeneration Opportunity','Invest in Bradford','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGsLjOEFH8HMSFS8UhDThggLl2zvle_4YLXgPsYYfGoTKUtAtX3HyEGztO2jt9UEjWi3lsL3ACBFXXe7vlogUIQL8KyCdEhQDUvQDdEVLEWu5vxuAW0_3kwcnxlww==','This Invest in Bradford page presents the overarching vision for the Southern Gateway, describing it as one of the UK\'s largest regeneration sites. It emphasizes creating new inner-city communities, delivering homes, green spaces, sustainable transport, and employment areas, supported by expertise from firms like Arup.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('35dfd7aa-25da-4a6e-ab6b-d9c69517a5b6','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Adam Tunnicliffe, nature-based solutions project manager at Yorkshire Water, said: \"South Elmsall is one of our flagship works, as well as Ilkley, Clifton and Clayton West, to adopt this low-carbon, climate-resilient alternative to wastewater treatment.\"','Yorkshire Water donates plants to Howardian Hills project','The York Press','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFloDEOkjQzt9POpBljlbjx2sjKjWQ-vz1XZT43v0xOiKoPKK0eXLy3x-HOTEY8i0yRBgcDo8zyp4uEnI3osBL7DN4FS2SSpS_NcOQXwR0EitGjQpoEEp6JWNytzVZlT6e7cz_-w7T0ZNPTDhpOWFUeav2rnu_HGqWI','Yorkshire Water has donated aquatic and wetland plants from its South Elmsall wastewater treatment wetlands to the Howardian Hills National Landscape\'s \'Forgotten Flora\' initiative. The article highlights Clayton West, along with other sites like Ilkley and Clifton, as a \'flagship work\' for Yorkshire Water\'s adoption of low-carbon, climate-resilient nature-based solutions for wastewater treatment, indicating the successful operation of the Clayton West wetland.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('360106d8-3840-4a78-8671-1ad76f210139','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'When Tingley Garden Centre opened, we wanted to make sure we went the extra mile to reach our goal of becoming a more sustainable business. Located just off the M62, this was an excellent opportunity to increase the offering of electric vehicle charging stations around the Wakefield and Leeds area. Our pathway to sustainability included using a large proportion of our car park to install Electric Vehicle Charging Units so that electric vehicle users travelling through West Yorkshire have greater availability to charge their cars quickly and efficiently. Compleo, a leading manufacturer of quality AC and DC charging stations, supplied 54 electric vehicle charging units along with 2 rapid charging units, which we\'re thrilled to announce are the first to be in the UK! The entire installation was managed by Westwood Energy. Our charging units are supplied with power from our 1200 solar panels and when needed, backed up with 100% green electricity, which is generated from natural resources such as sunlight, wind, and water. The two different methods of charging available. 1. Plugging into the AC charger which can deliver up to 22kW AC power is great for those looking to charge their vehicles and have a leisurely shop around our centre. 2. If you\'re in a rush or on the motorway and need to recharge, plugging into our rapid DC chargers that are 50kW each will charge your car at round 200 miles per hour! This gives you chance to grab a takeaway coffee from our Costa machine and stretch your legs ahead of your journey. HOW TO USE. Our Electric Vehicle charging points are located at the far end of our car park.','EV Charging Units Now Available at Tingley Garden Centre','Tingley Garden Centre','2022-12-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHeK_thx0z1orsqE2_7_JgfI-qMtoj4_ZBZu75dH2vSx8gH1yw2IdYzBFjKIzLNeM7OKOwZi8I2Ei5QJ3ezcLd6Bj0_5cBGJBbLmlj6lia6VufTYvRNwWf2Md64NOTlj9qAJkXPoupVby_AtrXHhLJQRlY7hYFtOmV8naCw1QaOLmYfPz4JhpREK9N9SShe6HmsWoNYxrHwGrIR45swmf0xdg==','Tingley Garden Centre announced the installation of 54 AC and 2 rapid DC electric vehicle charging units, supplied by Compleo and managed by Westwood Energy. The chargers are powered partly by solar panels and 100% green electricity, aiming to increase EV charging availability around the Wakefield and Leeds area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('363f1c38-2282-4c36-8cf6-51a48db4bbc1','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (CA) has opened its \'dynamic market\' for potential franchised bus services. The technical procurement process sets out criteria for any bus companies looking to bid to run services throughout the region. ... The CA has stated it hopes the first contracts will be awarded in Spring/Summer 2026, with a start in 2027. [5]','West Yorkshire CA Opens Dynamic Market for Franchised Services','Bus-News','2025-08-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGkSwdO_4rcwh7bkFQ8ZLIEIjvvNFgrN7fvgK5fphZAnh_IJ6_X12m5n1L8PuQyDrwAEmYe02nRP_WGIUQU_wsSFFmqIfamZnwj2z6X3sSq9n_w6GkhUnezFAlUdivOUUakjWgYqO1nJlYijUi_8S6fyKCOO5caticX7l1nNLmNg9vDdvhZAvgdEQHe4IfS','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) officially opened its \'dynamic market\' for potential franchised bus services. This technical procurement process sets out criteria for bus companies interested in bidding to run services across the region. WYCA aims for the first contracts to be awarded in Spring/Summer 2026, with services commencing in 2027. This marks a significant step towards the fully-franchised network, where the CA will set fares, routes, and timetables. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('364f66fd-2c1f-472d-ad67-0522f54d2650','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The next phase for Kirklees Dewsbury Riverside Development has been approved at Strategic Planning Committee on 3 November, paving the way for Kirklees Council to carry out the next steps of the Local Plan allocation for housing development. Strategic Planning Committee granted planning permission based on full details of the first phase of access road into the site, and outline details for the provision of new community facilities and up to 350 new homes. The first phase of construction has recently been completed by local company, The Casey Group Ltd with the creation of a new allotment site that will replace the original site of 25 plots with 43 plots. (See Source [6] for full context).','Dewsbury Riverside Development Takes Positive Steps Forward: Strategic Planning Committee Approval','Kirklees Together (Kirklees Council newsroom)','2022-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://kirkleestogether.co.uk/2022/11/10/dewsbury-riverside-development-takes-positive-steps-forward/','The next phase of the Dewsbury Riverside Development was approved by the Strategic Planning Committee. This approval granted planning permission for the first phase of the access road into the site and outline details for the provision of new community facilities and up to 350 new homes. It also noted the recent completion of the new allotment site, replacing the original 25 plots with 43.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3688952f-7a15-47e5-abb6-450823139e5e','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council, Kirklees Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority have developed a series of improvements along the A629 route from Halifax to Huddersfield. The aim is to provide enhanced and safer accessibility by improving walking, wheeling, cycling and bus travel. Preliminary designs were being prepared, with plans to share them for consultation in Autumn 2021 to gather feedback for detailed designs ahead of construction. [14]','A629 phase 4 walking and cycling Halifax - Huddersfield: Preliminary designs consultation planning','Calderdale Next Chapter','2021-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEe2kb0UBnIXl0ZYlStmkfmmxakquRDGM1342N1RmUEYkDgXEAeOufRUDsp9sbLPS_5SnsiMZN3ICJm9SZHTtT9GEcYm5WPrHQVx7-X3g3W9H20J56nNRmG9GF4anL8AuMHhW--x2fPQahlxA7RJGXt5gB5-yQXg7Gpo1Ovnq_4kuN3B5w=','This project aims to enhance and provide safer accessibility between Halifax and Huddersfield by improving walking, wheeling, cycling, and bus travel along the A629 route. Preliminary designs were being prepared, with plans to share them for public consultation in Autumn 2021.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3699642e-ec47-409c-868b-aaf788dcaa60','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Name of meeting: Cabinet Date: 26 May 2020 Title of report: Huddersfield Southern Corridors Scheme Approval & Land Acquisition. Purpose of report: To Seek formal approval from Cabinet for the WY+TF Huddersfield Southern Corridors Scheme, to acquire necessary third-party land and to progress construction (subject to Full Business Case approval, funding confirmation and obtaining the necessary planning and consents). 1.1 Congestion, long journey times and poor air quality is currently experienced along Huddersfield\'s Southern Corridors (HSC). Kirklees Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), is working toward a programme of transport improvements at key locations that will seek to address these issues and drive economic growth. HSC is funded via the West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund from its Phase 1 Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP). [13]','Huddersfield Southern Corridors Scheme Approval & Land Acquisition','Kirklees Council - Council and democracy','2020-05-26 00:00:00.000','https://democracy.kirklees.gov.uk/documents/g2945/Public%20reports%20pack%2026th-May-2020%2014.00%20Cabinet.pdf?T=10 (referenced in [13])','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet formally approved the Huddersfield Southern Corridors Scheme, including the necessary land acquisition. The report highlighted the project\'s objectives to reduce congestion, improve journey times, support housing and employment, encourage modal shift to sustainable transport, enhance safety for pedestrians and cyclists, and improve air quality. The Outline Business Case had previously received approval from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority in February 2019.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('36ac9020-a33c-4f8d-a979-9e1f1e7c25f6','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In summer 2024, almost 5000 people had their say in our phase one Mass Transit route options consultation. We asked for your views on 10 route options, which would see a tram linking Leeds with Bradford and south Leeds with St James\' Hospital. The tram would also link key places like the White Rose, Elland Road, Bradford Forster Square Station and Leeds Rail Station. View the consultation report below or continue reading for the key findings. ... Since then, we\'ve been reviewing and analysing your responses. The findings show that there is strong support for the Mass Transit Phase one proposals. More than two thirds of respondents supported the plans for a line between Leeds and Bradford, and more than three quarters supported a line from St James\'s Hospital to the White Rose. Extent of support for the Leeds Line. Extent of support for the Bradford Line. The route between St James\'s ... February 2025: Route options consultation outcome report. Current.','Mass Transit Hub - Consultation Outcome Report','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGplOkiaHm0uBiiP0GIKOuM4WbQGXx2VItPR7_lWgzPGpfgewsBH9NUHyQ5Ke0aWDho7dEVeDKg1oKGbtHdtGTL7c3EnAEc9iJf9uS7Mmuko1edT4H-8imfpxNlI5IXtWLOmvNG4znYqU1DUGfKl24FLu1pKFGw0ow3ueH','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority published the outcome report for the Phase One Mass Transit route options consultation (held in summer 2024). The findings indicated strong public support for the proposed tram lines linking Leeds with Bradford and South Leeds with St James\' Hospital.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('36d0cbab-1112-4159-80d4-7e07f9898577','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Previous successful bids for Project Gigabit contracts in West Yorkshire and South Yorkshire have already started to be connected by Quickline, bringing full fibre broadband to a further 60,000 premises. [20]','Quickline secures further Project Gigabit contracts for East Riding & Lincolnshire and North Yorkshire','Choose','2024-07-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFOfeG8u1Qv0afs5MSPH8Jr2GUi-SJLltMJxYvZ958x6AhYUv_8blknPc_rUDpeN7FeNAsTrvZNeavdiIJFAAxB584BNQz7BjrPgdpP_O8osvgelvGQjjMGA3RfqDjRX_CYy1Ngem-5hb0-SWnPveFm-kCXFSISSZrjGv1XgKqo1gcLbMvKYEz-_31lEHIsKvwOt_e_UaDSpKvEbzfYs10wTcokDUc','Quickline has secured two more Project Gigabit contracts for East Riding of Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, and North Yorkshire, bringing their total public investment across all contracts to £300 million to cover almost 170,000 premises. The article notes that previous bids for West Yorkshire and South Yorkshire have already started to be connected.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3704348b-62d9-4c51-86a7-69180cbc95ed','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Cotton Stones is a hamlet in Calderdale, England. Cotton Stones is situated nearby to the hamlet Mill Bank, as well as near Hubberton Green. 53.69163° or 53° 41′ 30″ north. Longitude. -1.95742° or 1° 57′ 27″ west. Elevation. 702 feet (214 metres). [4] and Cotton Stones is located in the county of West Yorkshire, Yorkshire and the Humber, one mile south-west of the town of Sowerby Bridge... Cotton Stones falls within the metropolitan district council of Calderdale. The centre of Cotton Stones is located at position 53.69166° latitude and -1.95765° longitude. [5]','Cotton Stones Hamlet Location and Nearby Lumb Hill','Mapcarta, Get The Data','2000-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://mapcarta.com/13280162, https://getthedata.com/postcode/HX6-3EU','Provides the geographical coordinates for Cotton Stones, a hamlet in Calderdale, England, confirming its location within West Yorkshire. Lumb Hill is also mentioned as a notable nearby place, indicating the specific area of the flood alleviation scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('372a358c-adb3-4ac8-8c00-2dbc68c048f5','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Take a look behind the scenes of Huddersfield Railway Station\'s 30-day blockade as the first week of major works is complete. The month-long closure of the station kicked off on 30 August and will run until 28 September as its huge transformation continues as part of the Transpennine Route Upgrade (TRU). At this time, no services are running through Huddersfield station. The railway is also closed between Berry Brow, Stalybridge and Heaton Lodge Junction, affecting train services to and from Manchester, Leeds, Sheffield, and York. Passengers are being kept on the move through diversionary routes or rail replacement buses, with Brighhouse serving as the main interchange point for passengers travelling to and from Huddersfield. ... So far, teams have demolished Huddersfield station\'s Platform 1 and have removed all the beams on John William Street bridge. Other work completed so far includes installing an under track crossing between Platforms 2 and 3 at Huddersfield, drainage work around part of the bridge at Huddersfield viaduct, removal of footbridge and platform infrastructure at Deighton, and preparatory work for beam installation on the A62 Leeds Road bridge. At this moment in time, 10,392 tonnes of soil have been excavated and 1.5km of track installed. By 2027, Huddersfield will have longer platforms, more railway lines, a new layout, new footbridge, improved accessibility features and refurbished roof structure with restored lantern. [18]','Behind the scenes look at first week of Huddersfield station closure for Transpennine Route Upgrade','Network Rail','2025-09-10 00:00:00.000','https://news.networkrail.co.uk/news/behind-the-scenes-look-at-first-week-of-huddersfield-station-closure','Network Rail provided an update on the first week of a month-long closure (August 30 - September 28, 2025) of Huddersfield Railway Station, as part of the broader Transpennine Route Upgrade (TRU). While distinct from the \'Connections\' project\'s public realm work, this major upgrade within the station itself aims for longer platforms, more railway lines, a new layout, footbridge, and improved accessibility by early 2027, which the \'Connections\' project is designed to complement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('376be0a4-8901-4445-a73f-11cbe217dc45','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The £62million network continues to expand and is regularly connecting to new buildings. Leonardo & Thoresby student accommodation buildings and St James\'s Hospital are the latest buildings to have begun taking heat from the scheme.','Hundreds more households in Leeds to benefit from low carbon heat network','Leeds City Council (via Public Sector Executive)','2023-12-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.publicsectorexecutive.com/articles/low-carbon-heat-network-for-leeds','Leeds City Council announced a significant expansion of the Leeds PIPES network, with hundreds more households benefiting from affordable, reliable, and lower carbon heating. The announcement specifically stated that \'Leonardo & Thoresby student accommodation buildings and St James\'s Hospital are the latest buildings to have begun taking heat from the scheme\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('37745c81-d355-446f-aa7c-ac4df3e0b70a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million for ongoing detailed planning and development work on Mass Transit, which will see a line run through West Leeds. This funding would support key works to keep the Mass Transit project on track for spades in the ground by 2028. The work will include further technical and environmental assessments on phase one tram route options, as well as progressing the business case and preparing the plans to go before government decision-makers in the coming years. Mass Transit and bus franchising represent two of the West Yorkshire Mayor\'s biggest priorities, and will form a key part of an integrated Weaver Network connecting bus, tram and train services as well as walking and cycling routes. At a full Combined Authority meeting on September 18, West Yorkshire council leaders will hear how the extra £40 million of funding would support key works to keep the Mass Transit project on track for spades in the ground by 2028.','Mass transit: Detailed planning and development to keep mass transit on track for 2028 start','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFUAgFTTqrLDBJjKNsfZ0gUzcIcl-Sa2oh4nxovFBBxRC-yfliZqaXVIvMMJsPHqr5f4u18eVYnJJvyqBi3_3Ts5gRtIVCOxGHGh2px2miqKJI2pFJ6MDuJ-8R9NA-zCLcE2FHTkIw21mE1Kk8mRq8e3YdEnL3IXSnHolIenJWVh39FcFgZ0fy7lq1rg1DIPbp5DWjf8SHDtrOQD8M6JryEzXpjGLPO3AOFwlM0_RINlNFaSYHv','Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million for ongoing detailed planning and development work on the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system. This funding will support technical and environmental assessments for phase one tram route options (Leeds and Bradford lines), progress the business case, and prepare plans for submission to government. The goal is to keep the project on track for groundbreaking by 2028, with the Mass Transit system forming a key part of an integrated Weaver Network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('37aaffc4-4ab3-4a34-b383-c81c625e07c4','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Environment Agency has been developing the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme, which aims to increase the standard of protection to the town from all sources of flooding. Total value (estimated) £67,600,000 excluding VAT; £81,120,000 including VAT. Contract dates (estimated) 8 September 2026 to 30 August 2030; Possible extension to 28 February 2031; 4 years, 5 months, 23 days. Main procurement category. Works. CPV classifications. 45246000 - River regulation and flood control works. Engagement deadline. 29 August 2025. Publication date of tender notice (estimated). 22 September 2025.','Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme - Find a Tender (Market Engagement)','GOV.UK (Find a Tender)','2025-06-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.find-tender.service.gov.uk/Notice/015757-2025','On June 19, 2025, the Environment Agency published a preliminary market engagement notice for the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme, estimated at £67.6 million (excluding VAT). This marks the start of the procurement process, with a formal tender notice anticipated on September 22, 2025. The project involves complex river regulation and flood control works to increase protection for the town from all flood sources.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('37bbac4f-b641-418e-bf85-5fe23ad7b2dd','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The design of an electric vehicle charging programme is a significant project and therefore, required that we spent some time looking at successful schemes in other regions. We proposed a network of 88 charging points across the West Yorkshire region, all placed in convenient locations, such as city-centre car parks and supermarkets. We were able to secure almost £2 million from the Office for Zero Emission Vehicles for the project and we provided an additional £1.2 million in matched funding. The chargers remained free to use for over two years, until 29th October 2021. Updated Dec, 2024.','West Yorkshire electric vehicle charging network | sustainable transport','Carbon Copy','2024-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://carboncopy.eco/solutions/west-yorkshire-electric-vehicle-charging-network','This article describes the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) broader efforts to establish an electric vehicle charging network across the region, including Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield. It mentions an initial network of 88 charging points, funded by OZEV and WYCA, which offered free charging until October 29, 2021, and was updated in December 2024. This sets the context for local installations like the one at Morrisons Wakefield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('37bccd1a-6540-4d95-af80-fbd796596234','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-ministry-of-justice-leeds-courts-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.352','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Ministry of Justice has been awarded £3,538,164 to install heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures at Leeds Combined Court Centre and Leeds Magistrates\' Court. The two court buildings will be connected to Leeds PIPES, an established district heat scheme, and the energy efficiency will be improved through the installation of double glazing, LED lighting and insulation. The Ministry of Justice is based in Greater London and will invest this funding in Yorkshire and the Humber. [2]','Ministry of Justice Awarded PSDS Phase 3a Grant for Leeds Courts Decarbonisation','GOV.UK (Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: project summaries)','2022-05-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-project-summaries','The Ministry of Justice received £3,538,164 under the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme Phase 3a to implement heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures at Leeds Combined Court Centre and Leeds Magistrates\' Court. The project involves connecting the two court buildings to Leeds PIPES, an established district heating scheme, and improving energy efficiency through the installation of double glazing, LED lighting, and insulation. The funding will be invested in the Yorkshire and the Humber region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('37bdc02a-c4b5-42b9-8922-1f0967f65e82','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'And Kirklees Council says work on the wider Huddersfield Southern Corridor improvement programme isn\'t expected to be completed until early 2027. The part of the scheme around Lockwood Bar is designed to ease traffic flow, cut congestion and improve air quality. Work will see the left turn from Lockwood Road into Bridge Street and the right turn from Bridge Street into Lockwood Road limited to buses only. A new link road with traffic signals at Crowther Street will provide a two-way traffic link between Albert Street and Lockwood Road. [15]','Road improvement works to cut congestion in south Huddersfield gateway set to last into 2027','YorkshireLive','2025-03-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/road-improvement-works-cut-congestion-30238466 [15]','Kirklees Council has indicated that the entire Huddersfield Southern Corridor improvement programme is anticipated to be completed by early 2027. This update was provided as the Lockwood Bar phase, a significant part of the project, began in March 2025 with an expected completion in early 2026, suggesting a staggered delivery across the various southern corridor locations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('37ecbe1f-319e-4d94-9080-8b8356b5cd26','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Co-op Academy Brierley joins a number of educational establishments that have already connected to Leeds PIPES, including Trinity Academy Leeds, Leeds Beckett University and Leeds Conservatoire. [12]','Ribbon Cutting Ceremony Held to Celebrate Leeds PIPES Expansion','Ener-Vate','2025-01-09 00:00:00.000','https://ener-vate.co.uk/news/ribbon-cutting-ceremony-held-to-celebrate-leeds-pipes-expansion/','A news article detailing the connection of Co-op Academy Brierley to the Leeds PIPES network, which also mentions Leeds Conservatoire as one of several educational establishments already connected to the network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3801229b-8e1e-47bf-9d85-b1815730612a','infrastructure-a660-holt-lane--otley-road-junction-improvements-adel-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.964','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A660 Otley Road/Holt Lane corner is mentioned in the Adel Neighbourhood Design Statement. Adel is situated on the A660 between Leeds and Otley in West Yorkshire, 5 miles north west of the centre of Leeds. [9]','Adel Neighbourhood Design Statement','Leeds City Council','2006-03-17 00:00:00.000','https://a-j-s.org.uk/assets/Uploads/Adel-Neighbourhood-Design-Statement-Adopted.pdf','This document, from 2006, provides a design statement for the Adel neighbourhood, mentioning the A660 Otley Road/Holt Lane corner as a specific location within the area. It serves as early contextual evidence for the importance and recognition of this junction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('381d50ce-f2eb-4d57-ac53-7e2694b47e5e','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust (LTHT) has been awarded over £20m from a government fund to install low carbon heating and energy efficiency measures across the Trust estate. Funded through the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS), the scheme provides grants for public sector bodies to fund heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures. In April, Beckett Wing at St James\'s University Hospital became the first Trust building to connect to Leeds PIPES.','Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust awarded over £20m for decarbonisation schemes','EM Magazine','2022-06-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.emgmagazine.co.uk/leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-invests-in-energy-efficiency-and-decarbonisation-schemes/','Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust (LTHT) was awarded over £20m through the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS) to implement low-carbon heating and energy efficiency measures across its estate. This included initial works like air source heat pumps, photovoltaics, LED lighting, and double glazing, with subsequent phases focusing on draught-proofing, roof insulation, and district heating connections. The Beckett Wing at St James\'s University Hospital connected to Leeds PIPES in April 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('38237697-05bf-4409-97ab-5408b35b0375','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to speed up the delivery of new electric vehicle chargepoints across West Yorkshire have been agreed by the region\'s leaders. The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy sets out how West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the region\'s five councils will work together to ensure there are enough places to charge cars and vans in public where people need them.','More electric vehicle chargepoints planned for West Yorkshire - West Yorks CA News','West Yorkshire Combined Authority News','2025-05-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGa_20-FmY_ha1o851TvqloJFmRWaeFTrrl9Q21Gk0ICL1qwrbVRMJW1s5AM2FyrTqnY69Tt_xOSgexicqywsCB3L2qp7n1zcP70ufbnd0IYW92hQNJR7Ng87D4KLQQw2FyZZ-0wVOC-2yrAyUxV9Pa4wWvCGz1NXD69MvhtEwilnUa2mS8PF3ACIv03So6HcrYdxUfnAxs-Ha7oUkT666vHyJ0rO8','Leaders of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority approved an Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy. This strategy outlines how the Combined Authority and its five councils will collaborate to increase public EV chargepoints, aiming for 15,180 to 17,080 chargers by 2030 across the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('38354dea-3fcf-4fd6-9eb2-180e9c571e74','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Parking charges may have brought Calderdale Council £1m surplus – but it will be swallowed up by highway and other related costs, councillors have heard. [12]','Increased parking charges help bring in £1m surplus to Calderdale Council','Halifax Courier','2025-06-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/increased-parking-charges-help-bring-in-ps1m-surplus-to-calderdale-council-4683050','A news report indicating that increased parking charges in Calderdale generated a £1m surplus, which was used to limit overall overspends in the council\'s neighbourhoods directorate, including covering a £1.2m overspend on maintaining Calderdale\'s roads. This demonstrates a funding source implicitly supporting road and parking improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('384b79c0-fbf7-4524-87a1-e7045f083d22','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A planning application to build a bridge over a Castleford railway line as part of a larger redevelopment project has been approved. The bridge will cross the railway line around Wheldon Road. It is part of a scheme intended to improve the route between Saville Road and Wheldon Road, so Fryston and Airedale are better connected to Castleford town centre. [10]','Plan for Castleford railway bridge is approved','Wakefield Express','2024-12-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/plan-for-castleford-railway-bridge-is-approved-4866635','A planning application to construct a bridge over a railway line near Wheldon Road in Castleford, as part of the wider Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme, has been approved. The bridge is intended to promote active travel and connect Fryston and Airedale to the town centre, contributing to the broader regeneration goals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('38cc33f4-8ca6-4f0a-8d40-7dfa9c3a5d4a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Political leaders in West Yorkshire are being asked to spend up to £150,000 to help decide whether the county\'s struggling bus services could be taken under public control. Using the Bus Services Act to bring the network under public control is one of the options that the combined authority has been considering for months. But the future of the bus industry, which has been in a decline for decades, remains uncertain because of the collapse in passenger numbers during the lockdown. Last year, the combined authority commissioned Ernst & Young to advise on what steps it could take. A report going before today\'s meeting says \'there is a need to understand the financial, legal and technical issues faced by the industry.\' It adds: \'Additional funding is required to access technical expertise where the skills are currently not available in-house, an indicative budget of up to £150,000 is proposed.\'','West Yorkshire leaders consider spending £150,000 to help make bus franchising decision','Yorkshire Evening Post','2020-07-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/west-yorkshire-leaders-consider-spending-ps150000-to-help-make-bus-franchising-decision-1845175','Political leaders in West Yorkshire considered allocating up to £150,000 to fund technical expertise needed to assess whether to bring bus services under public control through franchising. This was during a period of uncertainty for the bus industry due to declining passenger numbers and was an early step towards bus reform.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('38d3afba-c8ea-4082-b0b9-1aba66f37b59','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Local Transport Projects Ltd (LTP) has been commissioned to produce a Travel Plan in support of a planning application for a proposed residential development consisting of 105 dwellings at land at Tithe House Way in Bradley, Huddersfield. The site forms Phase 1 of the wider proposed Bradley Park development. The proposed development is to be accessed via an extension of Tithe House Way. The local planning and highway authority for the site is Kirklees Council.','Proposed Residential Development (Bradley Park Phase 1) Land at Tithe House Way, Huddersfield Travel Plan','Kirklees Council','2018-11-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGhhpbz_-kjjSKDnAY5c_RaXCoPyr0Q2B1GLrlwf22-xyXv6zUtaHAQCzl9c5TAkMgcq0YCbA-P01bBBdFBWw6jdgkjk5o-AiwbqNkumHGoeiz26JI4mRgIaHU_E0oiBg4b6nryINrCZnASaaAB_IBE3MfirtQtDpDAXr2MO4yJQgtvod_I_rl0ciHpBK1wYBiJia78VN2bSYEbNvLlQFvPCBHWy3viIi-eClRUg63aXEDPQFhkxyGVrtffC_0cNXvQJeJyfrHbllSrA2uk0bTc-4THXyz-BRHQ==','A Travel Plan was commissioned in support of a planning application for 105 residential dwellings at Tithe House Way, Bradley, Huddersfield. This site is explicitly identified as \'Phase 1 of the wider proposed Bradley Park development.\' The plan details development proposals, access arrangements via an extension of Tithe House Way, and adherence to Kirklees parking standards.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('38fd4d94-9fb4-45bb-9d3e-e4c55589c9b2','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Part of Huddersfield\'s \'game-changing\' bus station revamp is set to be cut back as new plans await a decision. The project has already seen several delays, with the upgraded station originally expected to be up and running by the end of this year, following the submission of a planning application in the summer of 2023. However, this never came to fruition, with planning permission finally granted in February 2025. Now, further plans to change some elements of the scheme have been submitted. If approved, this will see the size of the canopy, which will be complete with a green \'living roof\' dramatically reduced, with an area of 545 square metres, rather than 915 square metres as was originally the plan. ... On top of this, the cycle hub, which was set to house storage racks, lockers and helmet storage, has been axed in this latest application, along with the bin store. Instead, they have been replaced with a dedicated cycle parking area for 32 bikes. ... A decision on the changes is expected by September 10, 2025.','Huddersfield\'s \'game-changing\' bus station revamp set to be \'scaled back\'','YorkshireLive','2025-06-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFi7FPZR0XPfBjY-jV_cCXkxOqe3wtkdK-EMgYZBzgMC6W6d0hjC_6JJ7V81Q0ZY5coaxu3jiUbA1Gn7ORrCR6ZMqIZrD_pRdhCuB65_P1hzwBIdVLb29hEixLjwh9BmSGXZ-RWFSRJz6eNwmBX_mq_JQKbWEngLkMrCu37t_9Onzk2adxET0zIm9eVtGEF_-gSAxW9jlg84F71PUghQdah5vcI','New plans submitted by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) and Kirklees Council indicate that parts of the Huddersfield Bus Station revamp, specifically the canopy roof and cycle hub, are set to be scaled back. The size of the green \'living roof\' canopy would be significantly reduced from 915 sqm to 545 sqm, and the dedicated cycle hub replaced with a cycle parking area. A decision on these changes is expected by September 10, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('391197ea-24f8-4e3f-9e1a-eb4fd0ffcfc5','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-weaver-network',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.799','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A bold new era for public transport in West Yorkshire is set to begin, with the unveiling of the Weaver Network by regional leaders today. ... The modern brand will offer a single branding for passengers, making it easier and more accessible, however they choose to travel around the region. ... The branding will then be rolled out further when buses are taken under local control from 2027, before being included on the planned West Yorkshire tram system, for which construction work will start in 2028. Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin said: “The Weaver Network is a fresh, modern identity for transport in West Yorkshire, reflecting our greater powers through devolution, as well as our ongoing work to bring buses back under public control and create a fully-integrated mass transit network.” [13, 16, 18]','Weaver Network Unveiled as New West Yorkshire Transport Brand','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / Public Sector Executive','2025-05-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/weaver-network-will-offer-made-to-measure-public-transport-for-west-yorkshire/','West Yorkshire\'s regional leaders launched the \'Weaver Network\' as the new, integrated public transport brand, replacing the existing Metro identity. This new brand aims to unify buses, the planned Mass Transit tram system (from 2028), and active travel, with the goal of simplifying fares and improving journey planning across the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('393ed2c0-1396-4dbe-a5dd-34e38aea1e73','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We first shared our early-stage ideas during a phase of visioning engagement with the local community and businesses in Winter 2022/23. We carefully considered the feedback received to help inform the evolving masterplan, which we provided an update on in Summer 2024. Since then, we\'ve continued to refine the plans. We are now introducing detailed plans for the first phase of the project and are once again inviting community feedback before submitting a planning application later this year. [3]','Bradford City Village: Early-Stage Visioning Engagement','Bradford City Village Official Website','2022-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.bradfordcityvillage.com/about/','Bradford Council and ECF initiated early-stage visioning engagement with the local community and businesses for the Bradford City Village project, outlining initial ideas for the transformation of the city centre\'s former retail heart into a sustainable residential neighbourhood with up to 1,000 homes in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('39868aa8-c524-45c9-a183-3cc4787cf82f','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The case for electrification of the railway line into Bradford Interchange – long promised but so far not delivered – must be pressed with the new Government, senior politicians agree. As well as improving services for passengers on the Calder Valley line, it would be strategically important, councillors said in a questions session with Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin. The Calder Valley line, previously known as the Caldervale line, connects Leeds and Manchester via Bradford Interchange, with a mix of older and newer diesel-powered trains operating services. [5] The Combined Authority had agreed an emerging growth plan, setting out the ambitions members – Calderdale, Kirklees, Bradford, Wakefield and Leeds councils – had for the region\'s people. “It includes transport and making the case for electrification,” she said. [5]','Case for electrification of rail line into Interchange debated','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-12-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFparPToJCpIZR6-BIGfbTS-wY_hxoZdC3WnY1cyAs7pF5JV12cOaYiEE_MjDuUWC3Q3np0wmwlxhjewz2Ui7Qy6nX3ePzlf9U8EOnAja9asyJaKsBH2i6n1R-YuRo8d-OHePQESTb_-m4q0f2DcSvKTk3-0Vqxr2CF7-86GYI2Y1dom8wDCBaLOGwFOttYLACDDzL2QmG3_VnW32lc2A5W78qBL2890O0gHuE=','Senior politicians debated the case for electrification of the railway line into Bradford Interchange, agreeing that it must be pressed with the new government. Councillors emphasized its strategic importance for improving services, reducing travel times, and supporting climate goals, connecting Leeds and Manchester via Bradford.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('39f8795c-5bc4-4402-9edc-f4708f63aab3','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School. Moor Lane, Netherton, Huddersfield HD4 7HF. ... South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School is a Church of England primary school maintained by the local authority (Kirklees).','South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School, Huddersfield','The Schools Guide','2025-02-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.theschoolsguide.com/school/south-crosland-church-of-england-voluntary-aided-junior-school-huddersfield/','This page provides general information about South Crosland C of E Voluntary Aided Junior School, confirming its location and identifying Kirklees as the local authority. While not directly about the decarbonisation project, it establishes the entity receiving the grant.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3a354394-344e-46e9-a64f-d48ca3ce8c54','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The highly anticipated Darley Street Market has reached a significant milestone as building work is completed on the state-of-the-art building. ... Bradford Council is set to start the fit-out stage, following the formal handover from construction partners, Kier Group, scheduled for next week. ... The top floor of the building is where the food and drink hall will be... The middle floor is all things fresh food... Non-food stall will be located on the ground floor including haberdashery, hair and nail salons, gifts, jewellery, key cutting, shoe repair and clothes. Also on the ground floor will be cafés which lead out on to the spectacular Market Square, which features a big screen and can hold around 500 people for events and concerts.','Building Work Completed On Darley Street Market','Bradfordian','2024-07-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.bradfordian.co.uk/','The main construction work for the state-of-the-art Darley Street Market building reached completion. Following a formal handover from construction partners Kier Group scheduled for the next week, Bradford Council was set to commence the fit-out phase. The market boasts three floors: a top-level food and drink hall, a middle floor dedicated to fresh food, and a ground floor for non-food stalls and cafes that open onto a new Market Square.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3a7f79f6-92a8-434e-8087-dc265d087b69','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WORKS to repair the bus carriageway at Bradford Interchange will last for 18 months. The £8.5 million scheme to repair the carriageway used by buses entering and exiting the station was first proposed over two years ago, and finally began on Monday. West Yorkshire Combined Authority, which is behind the work, said it aims to keep disruptions to a minimum during the lengthy repair period.','£8.5m repair works to Bradford Interchange to last 18 months','Telegraph and Argus','2022-10-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF_JIOBf38n1wlXVzm7RvH3t2e2ZtnGsAvU2iihjibY8FVBJUtl6zU5t5-MI6zLADQpC5HfTtPJ_SM1xmCsDglSDU6tVHkurlJyyBQ4ECUYVMlGps-ilOxU1_Hvr13-rLtxEkhJX-y4-b7Gwlns42cesUel6_HV75VrjZuDdXjHIZdjU_yBpA4tjDYqaeWW1pxrb85CmzJmoCPKwljL5XQQMUK0Z55U','The £8.5 million scheme to repair the bus carriageway at Bradford Interchange officially commenced on a Monday, early in October 2022, with an estimated duration of 18 months. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, funding the project through the Local Transport Plan, committed to phasing the work to minimize disruption. The comprehensive repairs involve waterproofing and resurfacing the carriageway. [3]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3a825713-dad9-4218-afd3-57820d1c6108','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---ling-bob-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.178','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Projects include making streets around schools safer and easier to get around, with two \'school streets\' sites to be introduced in Bradford, and improved footways, green spaces and junctions near to Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax. [7]','Plans to boost walking, wheeling and cycling take a step forward','Calderdale Next Chapter','2025-08-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/news/plans-to-boost-walking-wheeling-and-cycling-take-a-step-forward/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, after receiving a £12.8 million Active Travel England funding boost, approved several schemes to enhance active travel. Among these are improved footways, green spaces, and junctions near Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax, making routes to school safer and easier.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3af9a9ce-3d62-4ebe-8d70-a3c42ac2c7b0','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We have appointed a development partner to purchase, design, and deliver a new housing development in Almondbury. What will the new development be? The site on Fenay Lane was identified as part of our housing growth strategy, which was approved by Cabinet in November 2023. Since Cabinet, the site has undergone a rigorous competitive land sale process where bids were considered to ensure they aligned closely with those of the council. For example, creating as many new affordable homes as possible and making sure all new housing is energy efficient. Vistry Group has now been confirmed as the development partner to build around 150 much-needed new market and affordable homes on the site at Fenay Lane, Almondbury/Fenay Bridge...','Development partner appointed for Fenay Lane housing scheme - Kirklees Together','Kirklees Together (Kirklees Council)','2025-03-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/news/2025/development-partner-fenay-lane.aspx','Kirklees Council officially announced the appointment of Vistry Group as the development partner for the Fenay Lane site in Almondbury. Vistry will purchase, design, and deliver around 150 new market and affordable homes. The affordable housing units will be owned and managed by Yorkshire Housing. Design work is set to begin, with a planning application expected in winter 2025-26 and construction starting in late summer 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3b1df6a1-3050-4cd0-9e66-8a0579d478ed','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) is an £830 million fund for an integrated and inclusive transport network, delivered by the Combined Authority in partnership with local authorities between 2022 and 2027. In 2023, the Combined Authority was awarded an additional £41.3 million from round two of the Government\'s Levelling Up Fund which will further build on the CRSTS programme. The investment includes funding for the first phase of a Mass Transit network, fifteen new bus and cycle priority corridor improvements, three new cycling corridors, new zero-emission buses, new electric vehicle charging points, improvements to rail stations, and essential highway maintenance and road safety improvements. Communities across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield are set to benefit.','City Regional Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) and Levelling Up Fund','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2023-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/transport-projects/city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-and-levelling-up-fund/','This overview page details the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) programme as an £830 million government fund awarded to West Yorkshire to provide an integrated and inclusive transport network, delivered between 2022 and 2027. It also highlights that in 2023, the Combined Authority was awarded an additional £41.3 million from round two of the Government\'s Levelling Up Fund (LUF) to further build on the CRSTS programme. The programme aims to benefit communities across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield through bus and cycle priority improvements, zero-emission buses, EV charging points, and rail station upgrades.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3b5490ec-8f8c-43ba-8090-6acaf24bc6d4','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Through the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund; to transform Wakefield city centre by reducing traffic in the Northern and Civic Quarters, enhancing cycling and walking routes, and improving operating conditions for buses. The £13.6m programme is funded by government\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) through Leeds City Region Local Enterprise Partnership and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. A four-week public consultation was held from 1-28 March 2021 to comment on proposals.','Transforming Cities – Wakefield city centre Project Outline','Wakefield Council','2021-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/roads-and-travel/transport-infrastructure-schemes/transforming-cities-wakefield-city-centre','Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is leading a £13.6 million programme funded by the Transforming Cities Fund (TCF). The project aims to transform Wakefield city centre by reducing traffic, enhancing cycling and walking routes, and improving bus operating conditions. Key plans include a new cycle route between Kirkgate and Westgate stations, improved access to Wakefield Bus Station, and public realm improvements in the Civic Quarter.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3bbd030f-8bab-4610-9bb5-82edc15baddf','infrastructure-ionity-leeds-skelton-lakes-ev-charging-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.372','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'25/02324/FU | Electric Vehicle charging hub and associated works | Leeds Skelton Lake Services Lakeside Way Skelton Gate Leeds LS9 0AS. publicaccess.leeds.gov.uk. The planning application lists 17*350kw units right next to a new Starbucks. This is the largest IONITY site currently under development by some way... [12]','Planning Application for Expansion of IONITY Hub at Skelton Lake Services (17 x 350kW Units)','Speak EV - Electric Car Forums (referencing Leeds City Council public access)','2023-10-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.speakev.com/threads/ionity-new-sites-in-construction-being-upgraded.147668/page-36#post-3037689','A planning application (reference 25/02324/FU) was identified for an \'Electric Vehicle charging hub and associated works\' at Leeds Skelton Lake Services. The application details plans for 17 x 350kW charging units, indicating a significant expansion of the existing IONITY facility due to high demand.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3c02932c-8665-4631-9a46-952cbe899054','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme. Highway improvements and new road scheme around the north of Castleford. Reducing traffic through the town centre and allowing the development of land for housing, employment and mixed-use schemes,. West Yorkshire Plus. Transport Fund. In Development. Wakefield. 84. [18]','Infrastructure Delivery Plan 2021 - Calderdale Local Plan','Calderdale Local Plan / Kirklees.gov.uk (document reference)','2021-04-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/planning-policy/pdf/examination/matters-issues-and-questions/matter-30/M30-1-Council-response-H1747-H351.pdf','The Calderdale Local Plan\'s Infrastructure Delivery Plan 2021 lists the Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme as a project aimed at highway improvements and a new road scheme around the north of Castleford. The objective is to reduce town centre traffic and facilitate the development of land for housing, employment, and mixed-use schemes, supported by the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3c504038-9172-4763-ab28-246246d1c0b8','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work began in April 2015 (Source 5). Launch of the construction of Wakefield Eastern Relief Road. First transport project funded as a result of the £1 billion transport fund for West Yorkshire and York is underway. The £33 million scheme which was secured as a result of the Leeds City Region\'s growth deal with government in 2014. Will create jobs and growth and ease congestion between the North and East of the city (Source 15).','Wakefield Eastern Relief Road Launch / Work Begins','Yorkshire Voice / West Yorkshire Combined Authority (via YouTube)','2015-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFWJ-zF-p90271NDfkv-gqfJ_P1tSSxVTbfub-FAW92puMAei8o4ii_cNWMi6EMLvn_iEIkvVDQY37b5HfVF1MUloiwMMcTkSOeUHblJ3bA3-L07DShFk4yTYKqZKcHF-2iOKEFSkM=','Construction of the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (WERR) began in April 2015, marking it as the first transport project funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s £1 billion transport fund, secured through the Leeds City Region\'s Growth Deal in 2014. The £33m scheme aimed to create jobs, ease congestion between the north and east of Wakefield, and facilitate housing development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3c58db1f-2343-4844-8f4f-759c19493c2d','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for a new electric vehicle charging zone and jet wash bays in the car park at Kirkstall Morrisons have been approved by council planners. Applicants Motor Fuel Group have received permission to remove 31 parking spaces in the car park and replace them with eight bays powered by four new electric vehicle chargers. Three new jet wash bays will be added.','Planning Permission Granted for EV Charging Zone at Kirkstall Morrisons','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-02-11 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/green-light-for-electric-vehicle-charging-at-kirkstall-morrisons/','Leeds City Council approved plans for an electric vehicle charging zone and jet wash bays at the Morrisons car park on Kirkstall Road. While not directly for Lookers Nissan, this nearby development highlights the broader trend and demand for increased EV charging infrastructure in the Kirkstall area of Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3cacd64f-305d-496b-a0e8-612b524a4844','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious planning work has been proceeding apace for a flooding scheme to better protect Walsden village in the upper Calder Valley. Members of Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Board heard the strategic outline case for funding for the Walsden scheme has been approved and scope for delivering the outline business case agreed. Environment Agency area lead Paul Swales said modelling was at an advanced stage for the scheme and a further internal funding bid submitted.','Strategic Outline Case Approved for Walsden Flooding Project','Halifax Courier','2022-07-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/ambitious-planning-work-on-flooding-project-in-walsden-3760443','Ambitious planning work for a flooding scheme in Walsden was reported in July 2022. The strategic outline case for funding the Walsden scheme received approval, and the scope for developing the outline business case was agreed upon by the Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Board. The Environment Agency confirmed that modelling for the scheme was at an advanced stage.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3ce35bf1-a2a8-462b-9d7f-cab4f54f215d','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At this year\'s UKREiiF, we\'ll be presenting some fantastic opportunities for investment in and around Dewsbury. One of the key opportunities we\'re going to showcase is the Dewsbury Riverside housing development – Kirklees\' largest-scale housing development in living memory. ... We\'re about to launch procurement of our Master Developer for Dewsbury Riverside, which will be an incredible investment opportunity for those attending UKREiiF between 20 and 22 May or email us at invest@kirklees.gov.uk.','Spotlight on Dewsbury: Exciting new potential for businesses, investors and developers','Business Kirklees','2025-05-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEJv4jtJom2mcHsO4ggZgGoqE5I7xtb_UcWQcHGY32aAW8Bu95esJxWaHdB_uzG-sTOgVSVqo3mMsEEonXN64kuA8kQFlJdQFLo326Lo13HpyrMDE7-qd648uMP_lsfktS1-TMNrHw2mNSbyC2WlWCGI0ka7pGSndmyhwlMTiRFcS1FC3pslM5rBT4JWFMVt4D0d0j3Z-IYuwYrCoSpTPAlvvaqQlkgxFoxyGgVrw==','Kirklees Council announced at UKREiiF that they were about to launch procurement for a Master Developer for the Dewsbury Riverside project. The project was highlighted as a significant investment opportunity to deliver thousands of new homes and expand local facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3cf16516-db33-4879-ba9a-45cdaf8fcd1b','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The bill for compensation payouts residents to suffering a drop in house prices from the construction of a new bypass in Wakefield has passed £5m. A total of 1,074 claims have been settled since the Wakefield eastern relief road (WERR) opened in 2017. Settlements totalling £5.1m have made, with a further £200,000 of payments likely before the claim period ends next month (Source 7, 10).','Compensation bill for Neil Fox Way relief road passes £5m','Wakefield Express / Yorkshire Post','2024-03-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGrnEXnjqsH1qljDDuxcavgxGF07MjW_a4Pg2rFEOq3DJtPaz9-SLexrqcLffbqAKSnUyCGPEj6bvW7_AgU62iW5tW0luy4jd6wnmt7FFSLM7k2MQFTQEE09ICVvAqXFnZawTugXFwWWXT3vCISfS-oZe0kPeQsO-uXIdo3NzG1SVa2VRorLCk7a_Pj3HBdBh5V9FIK8uOBrTkCNxLEtl9s7vtaDXSubne_DAVz','By March 2024, the total compensation bill for residents affected by the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (Neil Fox Way) exceeded £5 million, with 1,074 claims settled since the road opened in 2017. The claims related to decreased property values due to factors like noise and vibrations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3d80c603-5edd-4287-92a8-c94e8312f653','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The new Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme is now available across the district to help qualifying private households install free solar power, insulation and other measures. HERO is a £1.5m Wakefield scheme which is part of the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme – and applications are now being taken. The measures available could include solar PV electric panel systems, loft insulation, cavity wall insulation, air source heat pumps and high energy efficiency electric storage heaters. To qualify, Wakefield district residents must meet certain household and property related criteria set out by the Government and the council can quickly check this with anyone that applies. The HERO scheme is available until March 2028, but funds are restricted each year and will be allocated on a first come, first served basis so interested residents are urged to apply now. Contact the Council\'s Energy Team on either 01924 305887 or email energyteam@wakefield.gov.uk who will help with applications.','Wakefield Council launches new £1.5m scheme to provide free home energy improvements','Wakefield Express','2025-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHgV4vA-De_eVVIJm_aRExr5A_HeHBhO0ellnFR2SkOesfIF4tShJnje6Y6GQ-z9sSGVtnemmjDCtbXsGKC5CUBwCc43mfKvMpcDVzaMn8aTWffy3C2aMa7JFtcWUcwjO-kNsshsI8S2usGJi6Uc8231c_B2P1u8eiqMuGEOI7MkjRCAo7JOB0yrwv7BVIzIpOPJi1pq3VRuDUIH9tgU52QIW8kTUYu0dAZTFkILhUyHRUcZ_MwMjLOeEKw9-eUuc2W36ai7g3UwYd50IA=','This news article from August 7, 2025, also reports on the launch of the HERO scheme by Wakefield Council. It reiterates that the £1.5m scheme is part of the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme and offers free measures such as solar PV, loft insulation, cavity wall insulation, air source heat pumps, and high-efficiency electric storage heaters to eligible Wakefield residents until March 2028. Applications are being taken, and residents are advised to apply promptly due to limited funds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3da67eea-5538-4f77-ab6f-6b0f7cf09f29','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council considered a proposal for a joint Mass Transit Spatial Development Framework Development Plan Document with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and other local authorities. This high-level document aims to provide an overarching framework to support the mass transit network and its business case.','Mass Transit Spatial Development Framework (SDF) Development Plan Document (DPD)','Kirklees Council and Democracy','2025-03-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFTFjvW72V9fy2KsLMP2ynEKHMuAw9yGJZhK9nA3GxS_4sBbPjlJ0-6lOW3rj9eOx9MQQHAt3ko5pFMQJeBspePJ1PiQgNF9Ol0wIE8jCsiMJhPISzVcW5I3f7BBlowDvnZIl0MEfXUxbL1yhgtJrdIY6YNByJ6gQYh5aqU-SY=','Kirklees Council considered a proposal for a joint Mass Transit Spatial Development Framework Development Plan Document with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and other local authorities. This high-level document aims to provide an overarching framework to support the mass transit network and its business case.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3db48d82-67fd-415f-adcb-33ee3f01efea','infrastructure-moving-traffic-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.124','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This Order designates part or parts of the following local authority areas as moving traffic contravention civil enforcement areas for the purposes of Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004: ...the City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council, ... Leeds City Council...','The Civil Enforcement of Moving Traffic Contraventions Designation Order 2023','Legislation.gov.uk','2023-07-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2023/698/made','This Statutory Instrument, effective from July 22, 2023, designated parts of the areas of several local authorities, including the City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council and Leeds City Council within the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, as civil enforcement areas for moving traffic contraventions. This empowers these councils to enforce various moving traffic offences.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3dd1a2d7-20a8-4797-a0cd-e9e2dee398aa','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a638-doncaster-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.598','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A638 Doncaster Road - Construction Works. The Council of the City of Wakefield. UK1: Pipeline notice - Procurement Act 2023 - view information about notice types ... Construction works of A638 Doncaster Road. Contract dates (estimated). 3 August 2026 to 17 December 2027; 1 year, 4 months, 15 days. Main category. Works. CPV classifications. 45233000 - Construction, foundation and surface works for highways, roads. Contract locations. UKE45 - Wakefield. Publication date of tender notice (estimated). 5 January 2026. [8]','Pipeline Notice for A638 Doncaster Road Construction Works','GOV.UK Find a Tender','2025-05-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.find-tender.service.gov.uk/Notice/012217-2025','A pipeline notice for the construction works of the A638 Doncaster Road improvement scheme was published on GOV.UK Find a Tender on May 25, 2025. This notice from the Council of the City of Wakefield indicates estimated contract dates for construction from August 3, 2026, to December 17, 2027. [8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3e3a4714-44b7-417a-ade7-da5dba6b6af7','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A decision on the future of Bradford Interchange bus station will be made in September – but, transport bosses say a temporary station will be in place for 2025 whatever the final decision. And it has been revealed that the closure of the bus station is costing its operators West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) up to £238,000 a month.','Combined Authority to decide future of bus interchange in September','Asian Standard Newspaper','2024-05-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGkctzSMwWJwKs2leNXRIJE6X0RqAzlup_HMLnV7lk8zHSB7RRahDnQIbbqZ0F_Brop0w36JRU6EsrwcZTtnWWXq0S_FazOUo154BMvpPZ7qfmANoGJ7ETDKKKtdzwx8A5GFFB8jXipoYZOfars4LuiiSy9qQA9g3bscCz3CPFcvPuEbz_qtAzNW3B4TumyizZDE0zleguskoXVXm2K3Ig=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced that a definitive decision on the future of Bradford Interchange bus station, which had been closed since January 2024, would be made in September. Options under consideration include permanent closure, partial reopening, or full reopening. Regardless of the decision, a temporary bus station is planned to be operational for Bradford\'s City of Culture year in 2025. The closure was reported to be costing WYCA between £204,000 and £238,000 per month. [13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3ebb4007-670c-4819-acb3-7dc62739579f','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The new Wellington Square scheme will incorporate Build to Rent homes and commercial space in Leeds\' West End. Following the submission of a planning application in Feburary last year, developer McLaren Property has announced that its plans for the Wellington Square mixed-use development have been approved by The City Plans Panel of Leeds City Council. ... McLaren\'s 45-storey residential tower will deliver 464 Build to Rent units and will be home to households of up to six people in apartments ranging from one to three bedrooms. ... The twin office buildings, totalling around 364,000 sq ft (NIA) over 14 and 15 storeys, accommodate up to 3,500 new jobs and aspire to set new standards for workspace in the region.','Plans approved for McLaren\'s Wellington Square BTR','Business Live','2024-04-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFpwOhx6uvT1zYvrQXQsZ77NtfckhPJk0xOyclkwklPQ43t9T16LZ_dP-TG8MPibxz2B0JX4iQT2j5foEWBoWaifMHiEYZ6366ujH0SOjPpJ2ZdQm-oMF4QYWhq2-gEKGdO2vk5Ee5HhmbJeds-RxUhW6U8vn7RFcvF4KxrlBnW3t5GzUIq8-0KUvRn3l14ed0pm2YGtdiF','Following the planning application submitted in February of the previous year, McLaren Property announced that its plans for the Wellington Square mixed-use development, including Build to Rent homes and commercial space, were approved by The City Plans Panel of Leeds City Council. The project will transform a 2.47-acre site into a city centre gateway with a 45-storey residential tower delivering 464 units and twin office buildings (14 and 15 storeys, 364,000 sq ft). [4]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3efd56c1-0d95-4c5a-887a-3cc19724dc82','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water has begun work at its Clayton West wastewater treatment site in West Yorkshire in an investment totalling £18.9m to improve water quality in the river Dearne. The overall investment is split over two projects, one of which will see the installation of a £14m nature-based wetland solution. ... Both schemes at Clayton West are expected to be complete in summer 2025.','Clayton West wastewater treatment works undergoing £18.9m investment','Yorkshire Water','2024-11-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHGR8M8UuGoXdmxYDzbMiBqI9xLBTkOyx6Q6Z5tHEnJwg0F8yjMOUREx4Hdeg_ie8SFFjeqRBE7_LQ2eGCjdd3h8qdaCqlsxGJ3bdW-LH4pB-GEP3-liAczNZCsFs0Ycr8NKemTq53iIcjpPl3yr_9jMaPApQz6dTM2h89vyvq3AWIteBXyn-UhQbIjBo1OQiUiow4n0DYkNgc-gEJwl4uSp2EJHAfefL71aTdUD-qTZ2ftUqstlWGnnwtRbg==','Yorkshire Water announced an £18.9m investment at its Clayton West wastewater treatment site in West Yorkshire to enhance River Dearne water quality. The investment is divided into two projects: a £14m nature-based wetland solution, delivered by Mott McDonald Bentley, and a £4.9m phosphorus reduction scheme, delivered by Eric Wright Water. Both projects are anticipated to be completed in summer 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3f8d715b-42bd-4bb2-96c3-c8502525f5fc','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A confirmation letter was received from the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (MHCLG) which confirmed that the Leeds City Region LEP (Now West Yorkshire Business and Skills) passed the first Independent Review of the Transport Fund 2019 (also known as the Gateway review) on 12 May 2020. Passing this review confirmed that the \'gainshare\' investment of £30 million per year for the Transport Fund would be paid for the five years 2021/22 to 2025/26. [7]','West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund - Gateway Review Passed','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-05-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGw7LoX0La_h1nQhH-7OksN1B4WfGbv_9ITfn3tQLC8UHfYda8sdEb4UI4IeezX4V-u1ciiSN3wqAJkDEPc7YJfB8BSRgkCaC1Wo3LRQDALOBbRt-CjC3qIVD5EuWfprFZ5un_LIxs1lTkKKt8YLcA0RFL_61FbICiBUKa04RcFH262yxBYsVPT_Y9su4HG3bsjG9zAcvxpv6ZQ','The Leeds City Region LEP (now West Yorkshire Business and Skills) successfully passed the first Independent Review of the Transport Fund 2019 (also known as the Gateway review) on May 12, 2020. This positive outcome, confirmed by the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (MHCLG), secured a \'gainshare\' investment of £30 million per year for the Transport Fund for the five years from 2021/22 to 2025/26. [7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3f966a1e-0dec-4a9c-99ab-9c975598959c','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Network Rail was scheduled to present plans for a new two-platform station at land south of Manston Lane, Thorpe Park, to Leeds City Council\'s North & East Plans Panel on November 21, 2024.','Network Rail to present plans for new Thorpe Park station to Leeds City Council','Place Yorkshire','2024-11-21 00:00:00.000','https://placeyorkshire.co.uk/news/new-railway-station-considered-for-leeds/','Network Rail was scheduled to present plans for a new two-platform station at land south of Manston Lane, Thorpe Park, to Leeds City Council\'s North & East Plans Panel on November 21, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('3fcc31c9-a50a-4b8d-a0e6-3b0dc2f9de91','infrastructure-home-bargains-garforth-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.429','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Caddick Construction completed the build at the end of 2018... The site includes 298 car-parking spaces for shoppers, with five electric vehicle charging facilities. [14]','East Side Retail Park in Garforth Completed, Featuring Home Bargains and EV Charging Facilities','Caddick Construction','2018-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE_1hSxJovNSQ8K_lyy0K_Xs4BSxF97jkICAeurlr_FAWZatK6oPITTenCcqoiVSKY1zsx8mHgHWkzHe1f6Oo_6ZEfOW15pB27Q_EG6FgnCLrXXkYvEdrTH1c7FPq-aFGKR0hEBuISOObPCOe9zshSM8fxHDxszg3pMR9dUQbMCNGhNpf0aFwZWAtFV-cUS6o5Sti2ukp2k99uhfw','Caddick Construction completed the new East Side Retail Park in Garforth, Leeds, by the end of 2018. This development included a Home Bargains store and was equipped with five electric vehicle charging facilities as part of its infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('40a63906-b7ea-45c6-bd90-d764068751c7','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council says its £48 million upgrade for the Penistone Line is still on track after the latest Government confirmation that funding remains available. In May this year the council was awarded £1.4 million to draw up a full business case and the council says it\'s full steam ahead. ... The Penistone Line, a key route between Huddersfield, Barnsley and Sheffield, will see improvements to stations including Lockwood, Berry Brow, Honley, Brockholes, Shepley, Stocksmoor and Denby Dale. The investment would also see two trains an hour instead of one, boosting the local economy. [6]','Full steam ahead for £48 million Penistone Line rail upgrade says Kirklees Council','Huddersfield Hub','2025-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://huddersfieldhub.co.uk/full-steam-ahead-for-48-million-penistone-line-rail-upgrade-says-kirklees-council/','Kirklees Council announced that the £48 million upgrade for the Penistone Line is \'full steam ahead\' following the latest government confirmation of funding availability. The council was awarded £1.4 million in May 2025 to develop a full business case for improvements including station upgrades, increased train frequency (two trains an hour), and more reliable services between Huddersfield and Sheffield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('40c121c3-ecee-4c7e-ab3d-687b8bd0d88a','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This LCWIP identifies a proposed walking network, proposed intervention sites and a list of proposed infrastructure improvements for Wakefield. ... The LCWIP process aims to identify infrastructure improvements to create a safe, coherent and pleasant walking environment. ... Phase One aimed to test our approach and our tools through focussing on Wakefield itself, looking at cycling routes to the north and south, and walking improvements in the north east, of the city centre.','Wakefield Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan: Phase 1','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-11-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/media/7665/wakefield-lcwip-phase-1-report.pdf','This Phase 1 LCWIP report for Wakefield, developed by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, identifies a proposed walking network, intervention sites, and infrastructure improvements for Wakefield. It details the process of creating a safe and coherent walking environment, focusing on primary and secondary walking routes into the Core Walking Zone and specific cycling routes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4100b2b1-5737-4999-83ec-ae9323ca7d1f','infrastructure-west-bradford-junctions-improvement-scheme-a6177-ring-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.879','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority are planning £14 million improvements to three junctions in West Bradford on the A6177 Ring Road and want to hear people\'s views and ideas on the second phase of the project to upgrade the junction at Great Horton Road / Horton Grange Road. ... The public engagement is open until 5th August 2019. Plans have been refined based on initial feedback from the public and the authorities are giving local people the opportunity to give their opinions and ideas via a public engagement programme running from 8th July until 5th August. [11]','Public Engagement for Great Horton Road / Horton Grange Road (Phase 2A) launched','Telegraph & Argus / Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/17772718.bradford-views-sought-14-million-improvements-three-junctions/','Bradford Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched the second phase of public engagement for the Great Horton Road / Horton Grange Road junction improvements, seeking public views on the refined plans. This consultation ran from July 8th to August 5th, 2019.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('415bcce0-7ec6-4bcf-807c-89e9a6a73ffa','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Wakefield Mega Solar project aimed to improve the EPC score for low-income households living in homes with poor energy efficiency. This was to be achieved primarily by installing solar PV systems with average funding of up to £10,000 available for installations for owner-occupiers. ... There were 115 solar PV installations installed between October 2021 and September 2022. The project was led by Wakefield Metropolitan District Council, with project management by Equans and solar PV installations by ASK Renewables. ... The Wakefield Mega Solar project was funded through phase 2 of the Green Homes Grant LAD scheme in partnership with the North East Yorkshire and Humber Energy Hub.','Evaluation of the Wakefield Mega Solar project by Wakefield Council','National Energy Action (NEA)','2023-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF1-F1Mai3xb4SM0sIcSbt_JKrdTjifekOM2pCe1arIr3aTxD0EjC_PAn66cFUneyhclSClzgaGkNsdqtmZyC0EpK88oDowOgRWaMa1-r83poWj1uxzSJ2BMyufUrMPHEblNOCpcin751ays9ucIqkFta4tzePXihEcgI1QVUCQ66fR1M47SO6c_vrite5eivsx','National Energy Action (NEA) evaluated Wakefield Council\'s Mega Solar project, funded by the Green Homes Grant LAD scheme. This project aimed to improve the EPC score for low-income owner-occupier households in the Wakefield district by installing free solar PV systems. A total of 115 solar PV installations were completed between October 2021 and September 2022, led by Wakefield Metropolitan District Council with project management by Equans and installations by ASK Renewables. The project targeted properties in EPC bands E, F, and G.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('41967fb4-6d3b-4fc6-a39e-05aa7ae3fbc8','infrastructure-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-corridor-improvement-phase-1b-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.863','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work is now underway to transform the Calder and Hebble junction corridor of the A629 near Halifax – the largest individual civil engineering project ever undertaken to date by Calderdale Council. Following final funding approvals from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, work can progress on Phase 1b of the A629 improvement scheme, which focuses on the key areas of Huddersfield Road, Stainland Road and Wakefield Road. [7] The £28.1 million project is funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [5]','Work Underway on £28 Million A629 Calder and Hebble Junction Transformation','Halifax Courier / Calderdale Council – News Centre','2021-12-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/council/progress-update-on-ps28m-project-to-transform-the-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-3494793','Work commenced on the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction Corridor Improvement (Phase 1b) project near Halifax, following final funding approvals from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. Announced on December 15, 2021, this £28.1 million scheme is Calderdale Council\'s largest individual civil engineering project to date, focusing on transforming the road layout in key areas like Huddersfield Road, Stainland Road, and Wakefield Road. [5, 7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('42bbfb8a-a8a0-4878-8282-2dee5d1a689d','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In December 2018 / January 2019 we asked for your views on our plans to relieve congestion in the Cooper Bridge area by constructing a new link road between the A62 and A644 (Wakefield Road). Since we presented our original proposals Kirklees Council has declared a climate emergency. Considering this and the feedback we received during the engagement period, we have been reviewing our options with a view to minimising the scheme\'s impact on the local environment. This has resulted in us developing new options which are different from those presented in 2018. None of these options include a link road, instead they aim to enhance the existing network by improving Cooper Bridge and Bradley junctions.','A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme Consultation (initial proposals with link road)','Calderdale Council / Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2018-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFvZ8Ge2bh9s-Nel2ev1Y0Qr_4DS5X4tmtxt9LBGyzKf2SeUy4ZvgmMgGV5q-nbBem-9mh_K-psBVAylVGtqwIdwuQgWXJv32xIPCueTEqRlb1pM4D3o429N-Z0bj-Tih0L_WK54vSoW-Q-nvfMUhqCI5wp0ieIDzQAPIFZGLCurSmZhRPgvOEqZKjqIYW5Qd5GGYC5rA4hKL0tai6jG0xLRk83ks1f_6nEh3ZkWoX9Z3VDGfk9naKlV_4n2-YMF7xcM-dsy9j0zyv0k3YtIyk9I67XJXnZ6I2huRcuYjQd','Kirklees Council, in partnership with West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council, held a public engagement on initial proposals to construct a new link road between the A62 and A644 in the Cooper Bridge area. However, concerns were raised regarding environmental impacts. [4, 6]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4355616c-2135-4399-a80c-507c61b8bfdb','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'To improve parking practices in this area, we are proposing to standardise restrictions to ensure they are fit for purpose, managed, and balance the needs for all road users. [8]','Minutes of Traffic Regulation Order Governing Body Meeting','Calderdale Council','2024-12-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/democracy/documents/g10793/Printed%20minutes%20Wednesday%204-Dec-2024%2014.30%20Traffic%20Regulation%20Order%20Governing%20Body%20Meeting.pdf?T=1','Minutes from a Calderdale Council meeting where various traffic regulation orders were discussed, including proposals for standardising parking restrictions in areas like Longfellow Court/Red Acre Lane and addressing indiscriminate parking. This demonstrates the ongoing assessment and implementation of specific minor traffic and parking improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('43d8ddc3-5825-46ce-8c82-6c28745f795f','infrastructure-normanton-golf-club-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.339','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Venue Details. Find us at. Hatfield Hall, Aberford Road, Wakefield, WF3 4JP. Phone. 01924 200900. Open in Google Maps Visit website. Venue Facilities. Electric Vehicle Charging; Free Parking.','Normanton Golf Club | Experience Wakefield','Experience Wakefield','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEk4TxQPg0P9eTCkhuPEExQEFSQ2xVFiluxqsTxbTBuL0wnoqxCGORx8Jh_RXrMAG-HSMgu67oXeNBmQVCpYB9HY6uhDshfBjY9vRlLOyObU6cnDTdb6lspA9Vaz5BrvQ_xMmtM9Aj_X5rWF-9z1XomHQwujK0frw==','The official tourism website for Wakefield, \'Experience Wakefield\', lists \'Electric Vehicle Charging\' as one of the available facilities at Normanton Golf Club, Hatfeild Hall, Aberford Road, Wakefield, WF3 4JP. This indicates the golf club actively promotes EV charging as a service to its visitors.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('440a0c6d-91bf-42b5-8946-abaaeb75d1e7','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BRADFORD’S “most ambitious regeneration project in generations” will move ahead thanks to almost £30m in funding from a Government agency. City Village will see over 1,000 homes built on three locations in the city centre – the Kirkgate Shopping Centre site, the Oastler Market site and on car parks in the Chain Street area.','Government Commits £30 Million Funding for City Village','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-11-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFRl6jg1Znv6WJS6i_c2BwsAk1AN5KLBFG0GDI2AzVTqW5VIHbXY0Fa4Q4J4Q5TX8EnVrPhmPYN416uWgCTI1GOKnHpAuvIoR-zKvBKq4qfLJEyy8U6vwF1BmSIViNw1PMZsGSIeJr1Y6UqGG_4bSMf-d2ogRdYvjTeMHD9PvUVxdpPip8z2D-CpmNdn3YkeWB4bnvRY525e7WpL2_f_9A','The Government, via Homes England, committed a significant £30 million funding pledge to support the delivery of the Bradford City Village scheme, highlighting major inward investment in the project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('44365d22-e85b-4f18-9e83-a9034dcb5a98','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Leeds Station Sustainable Travel Gateway Scheme was expected to cost £35.6m when funding was originally approved back in June this year. However, Leeds City Council officers now say that, due to cost pressures and inflation, the total price for the works has now ballooned to just over £46m. [13]','Leeds City Council says rail station gateway improvement costs increased by £10m due to \'inflation\' and \'economic pressures\'','Yorkshire Evening Post','2022-10-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/leeds-city-council-says-rail-station-gateway-improvement-costs-increased-by-10m-due-to-inflation-and-economic-pressures-3896502','Leeds City Council announced that the estimated costs for the Leeds Station Sustainable Travel Gateway Scheme increased by over £10 million. Originally set at £35.6 million, the total cost for the works, including the pedestrianisation of New Station Street, a new taxi rank, and passenger lifts, rose to just over £46 million due to inflation and economic pressures.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('447abedd-3122-42d2-8b86-dff32ec4708f','infrastructure-north-halifax-streets-for-people-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.173','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) was approved in Summer 2020 and the North Halifax Active Travel package will now progress to develop an Outline Business Case (OBC). At this stage we will continue to define the scope of the project to identify the locations and type of improvements required in order to achieve the benefits. [4]','Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) Approved for North Halifax Active Travel package','Calderdale Next Chapter - North Halifax Improved Streets for People','2020-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHSGqBROegSMIkY6t3wjo-PoPYWhsFZ8FkhXGNJz6aVcRqhkJI5ATkqf8LoQNu78z5TjD2E3er-JOG2El0Rh2JOIe4kvHb8QzRbdMUr6iC1gnE8y4LKSCIRY2YjhfQHv6K2aoC8O-DVqokCxs57IqWoqQBhY1-F78k5OdQLLcpx-7ARjaSP60TIh-njK2BQNv0','The Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) for the North Halifax Active Travel package received approval in Summer 2020. This allowed the project to move forward with developing an Outline Business Case (OBC) and further defining the scope of necessary improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('44cfb7ad-ab0e-4b8e-af57-cc2ebe076d9b','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme has been in place since 2012 with the aim of reducing the impact of flooding in Calderdale and working with local communities to build resilience against future events. The delivery of the programme is overseen by a Programme Board, which is chaired by the Calderdale Council Leader. Members include local Councillors, the Calderdale Council Chief Executive and the two MPs for the Borough. There are four operational groups that report to it: Natural Flood Management. Flood Risk Reduction and Investment. Resilient Infrastructure. Community Resilience.','Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme established post-2012 floods','Eye on Calderdale - Calderdale Flood Programme Board','2012-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEX5fvbEUS5LH_Z0ECxsE_85XA_NB3uCagudSxKChwIKc09HdoqfhsBls79OvV07GS0EtbF8icyXk91xcPCdb3AvuAdr2x5eN1F89JMgR0CDdJjuWFjwE1HceHVHloYr8LbfQ==','The Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme was established in 2012 following significant flood events, aiming to reduce flooding impacts and build community resilience. It is overseen by a Programme Board with various partners, including Calderdale Council and the Environment Agency.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('456df45c-5157-4c7d-978d-a3f9a31c5ea8','infrastructure-bus-lane-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.094','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet will now consider the possible use of enforcement cameras, initially as part of work on the A629 Calder and Hebble junction project and in Halifax town centre schemes. ... The initial costs for camera installation would be funded through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority West Yorkshire Transport Fund as part of wider scheme costs.','Bus lane enforcement camera plan from Halifax to Huddersfield','Halifax Courier','2018-07-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/bus-lane-enforcement-camera-plan-from-halifax-to-huddersfield-1-9257218','Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet considered proposals to introduce Automatic Number Plate Recognition (ANPR) cameras for bus lane enforcement, initially in Halifax town centre and along Stainland Road as part of the Calder and Hebble junction remodelling scheme. The initiative aimed to improve bus service reliability and punctuality, reduce congestion, and improve air quality. Funding for initial camera installation was anticipated from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s West Yorkshire Transport Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('45a232e0-4454-4542-a6ff-0bbb4672d547','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At Budget Council on Monday 26 February Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet budget was approved. ... The consultation also highlighted opposition in the community to the closing of the Elland Household Waste Recycling Centre. No final decision on the future of the site will now be taken until the end of the year when the effectiveness of the resident permit scheme can be assessed. Cllr Tim Swift, the Deputy Leader of Calderdale Council said: “My colleagues on Cabinet and I would like to thank everyone who took the time to contribute to the consultation. Your feedback was greatly appreciated, we carefully considered the responses and made changes to the proposals which we presented at Budget Council.','Approved budget for 2024/25 to 2026/27 - Calderdale Council','Calderdale Council','2024-02-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE-fLMPntL21wRqHOvMaXqdovO1grMIuaX4a4p4ei5YK4G1dkVnTfFTbBFiaBvysX6xv2IzfF_9Tge1goW1L2SlTkAMvBEnSgjHbhkTjF5Nr03U6n_Wc8LmNe1Uvtvk3nOmCjSjaPghMPuDpWq0dnjq439k_wxlrc_QWtKiURpSYpiYvbCz--SdxGQ==','This budget report indicates that the effectiveness of a resident permit scheme would be assessed by the end of the year (2024), delaying a final decision on the future of a specific site (Elland Household Waste Recycling Centre). This highlights ongoing evaluation and potential adjustments to existing resident parking schemes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('45bfe926-93f4-4a08-bd87-f1a7686ef3d7','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'No sooner than the 150th Anniversary celebrations are completed, work has now begun on internal improvement works to secure the future of Todmorden Town Hall for generations to come. Our project partner, Calderdale Council, has issued the following update on their website. ... Code Building Solutions has now been appointed as the contractor to carry out the works, with work on site now underway and due to be completed this autumn.','Grand Plans For A Thriving Future For Todmorden Town Hall','Todmorden Town Deal','2025-04-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF3iTHWm0KUUf4vRBaFP8JFH3LLk6e5OuOuUQqQG1LgVTKQYCyxDuP4szpHL5vQwBut3GBkT1ItDKJ0PKgNNmq2ja2bk0JKZ8YHAhqTeHYnjeo74dGtjOCEQiwQ6c0ASIuiTr5ByNxekNYQchmDUrYG5PL4OZY6Wt9SJ-O-SICp0Zw_dZ4XZLHjFTZ66vz_lRV9NADd0agY5D0=','This press release announces that Code Building Solutions has been appointed as the contractor, and work has begun on the planned improvements for Todmorden Town Hall. The project is part of the larger £17.5 million Todmorden Town Deal programme, aiming to make the Grade I listed building more accessible, welcoming, flexible, and sustainable.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('45f227c3-6152-4aed-a78e-551098f815ff','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Landscapes for Water is a £7 million, 5,500ha programme of landscape recovery devised by the National Trust and Yorkshire Water through their Common Cause partnership. Across the next five years it will plant more than 350 hectares of new native woodland across five main areas of the South Pennines – around 300,000 trees. The programme was officially launched at a community planting day today (9th February) with the Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin, and Yorkshire Water CEO, Nicola Shaw, as well as National Trust Regional Director, Mike Innerdale, and White Rose Forest Programme Director Guy Thompson in attendance. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority has contributed £1.9m to the programme\'s plans for Natural Flood Management, which includes interventions, such as leaky dams, while the tree planting has been supported with over £1 million from the White Rose Forest, via their Trees for Climate programme, part of the Government\'s Nature for Climate Fund.','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin and others brave the snow to plant trees on Marsden Moor and help restore landscape (Official Launch)','White Rose Forest','2024-02-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.whiteroseforest.org/news/west-yorkshire-mayor-tracy-brabin-and-others-brave-the-snow-to-plant-trees-on-marsden-moor-and-help-restore-landscape','The Landscapes for Water programme, a £7 million, 5,500-hectare initiative by the National Trust and Yorkshire Water, was officially launched on February 9, 2024, with a community tree planting day on Marsden Moor. The project aims to plant 300,000 trees and install 3,500 leaky dams over five years to mitigate flooding, wildfire, and climate disaster. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority explicitly contributed £1.9 million to the Natural Flood Management plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('461cf90e-885f-4bb9-b0e0-3c16b9b927cc','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We received the following response: I would like to take this opportunity to thank you to the Bradford Cycle Campaign for the response to the Kings Road Connect Project briefing that I shared with you. I would like to take this opportunity to reply as below if you could share with the group: Prioritise Cycling at Junctions: Cycle tracks are proposed off the main road from Five Lane Ends roundabout through to the NCN66 tie-in at Valley Road. At key junctions, cyclists are given clear priority using parallel crossings, which allow both cyclists and pedestrians to cross safely. Avoid Diversions and Inconveniences: In our design, all proposed cycle tracks run parallel to the carriageway without any significant diversions, ensuring a straightforward and efficient route for cyclists. Additionally, adequate spacing as per LTN 1/20 has been incorporated to prevent “dooring” incidents when the cycleway runs adjacent to parking bays, enhancing safety for all users. Surface Quality: Agreed. High standard, smooth and durable surface will be provided. Clearance and Obstruction Prevention: Agreed. Preventive measures will be implemented where necessary.','Bradford Council\'s Reply to our Kings Road Consultation Response - Bradford Cycling Campaign','Bradford Cycling Campaign','2025-05-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF2RNOdt0mWqFzlu6zOdX4qge3snaCBxxx1CxnAeq4E7LK3O5gQ0QGr0ZjNrGdh348ccnKCZZiubf8RTcFZZCd2yWRRRkSV0UjUx-GnFp78LACEWS532eFGSOG46dh81ETq','This article presents Bradford Council\'s response to the Bradford Cycling Campaign\'s feedback on the Kings Road Connect project consultation. It details specific points raised by the campaign regarding cycle lane priority at junctions, avoiding diversions, ensuring adequate space to prevent \'dooring\' incidents, and maintaining high surface quality. The Council\'s replies indicate agreement on these points, with plans for parallel crossings at key junctions, continuous footways/cycleways, and adherence to design standards like LTN 1/20.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('479aba44-cb5d-49db-a0d6-01b3a6bc43dc','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On August 23 planning permission was granted to create the main access road into the site and deliver the first 350 homes. (See Source [4] for full context). Planning permission was granted for the main access road for the development and the first 350 homes in August 2023, with these expected to be finished by 2030. (See Source [5] for full context). In August 2023, planning permission was granted for the main access road and the first 350 homes to be constructed, with these expected to be finished by 2030. (See Source [7] for full context).','Planning Permission Granted for Main Access Road and First 350 Homes at Dewsbury Riverside','Business Kirklees / Dewsbury Reporter','2023-08-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.businesskirklees.com/invest/strategic-sites/dewsbury-riverside/','Planning permission was officially granted on August 23, 2023, for the creation of the main access road into the Dewsbury Riverside site and the delivery of the initial 350 homes. These homes are expected to be completed by 2030 as part of the larger 4,000-home development within the Kirklees Local Plan.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('479c221a-8de1-4e03-9e83-ba29407f6ba3','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'McLaren\'s property arm has submitted plans to add a 45-storey hexagonal tower to an emerging cluster of tall buildings in central Leeds. The Wellington Square development would contain 464 build to rent apartments in the tower and more than 40,000sq m of office space in two neighbouring 14 and 15-storey blocks. ... The Glenn Howells Architects-designed plans, lodged with the city council yesterday, would be located on the western side of the city centre close to where the Leeds Inner Ring Road crosses the River Aire. ... The McLaren application can be viewed at 23/00608/FU on the planning portal. [11]','McLaren lodges plans for 45-storey hexagonal tower in Leeds','Building / Building Design','2023-02-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE3BFt9UW47lEs4dfJAJKaDx7CvhLtT97wbgiZLG6pGTgkavdUS07Rsh9mTY2t3fkZTwPjjMREkuu1ZpXOi3C8J0tn7mNZXdLLCX4yc8cyGrWKYmxy-76d2AqYB7Fszl4RNWypweUkjlS6HWJPSk_gvz8GDFCSALU28XdY6xLEdSd69uDdeGPtXKvKHCYnDuTYxt0q_5Dzn8-qX5x91j6jSqKpe19Yg','McLaren\'s property arm submitted formal plans (application reference 23/00608/FU) to Leeds City Council for the Wellington Square development, featuring a 45-storey hexagonal build-to-rent tower (464 apartments) and two neighbouring 14 and 15-storey office blocks (over 40,000sqm). The Glenn Howells Architects-designed project is located on the western side of the city centre near the Leeds Inner Ring Road and River Aire. [7, 9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4843f3b0-a30f-48a9-bfad-7f485e767c4e','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A cabinet meeting report from Kirklees Council provided a general summary position on the Transport Capital Programme, with a focus on the West Yorkshire Transport Fund Programme and the City Regional Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS). It highlighted progress made, current financial challenges due to inflation, and a proposed funding strategy to address project funding gaps. The report noted that original budget envelopes for WYTF and TCF/CRSTS schemes were set years ago, and inflation has caused some allocations to be amended or projects to be paused/reprofiled. It confirmed that the Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) has since been incorporated into CRSTS. Schemes mentioned include the A629 Wakefield Road Sustainable Transport Corridor.','Kirklees Major Transport Schemes; West Yorkshire Transport Fund (WYTF) and City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) Programmes','Kirklees Council - Council and democracy','2024-01-23 00:00:00.000','https://democracy.kirklees.gov.uk/documents/s52525/Cabinet%20Report%20Major%20Transport%20Schemes%20WYTF%20and%20CRSTS%20Programmes.pdf','This cabinet report provides an update on Kirklees\' transport capital programme, focusing on challenges posed by inflation to West Yorkshire Transport Fund (WYTF) and City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) schemes. It notes that several schemes have been paused or reduced in scope, and a revised funding strategy is being developed with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to manage funding gaps. Specific projects like the A629 Wakefield Road Sustainable Transport Corridor are mentioned in the context of these reviews.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('486b5cb0-e71b-44b5-ba5b-3e9ada67254d','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Residents of Walsden in West Yorkshire film flash floods after torrential rain turned roads into rivers and flooded homes on Monday. Parts of the market town of Todmorden are left under 45cm (18in) of water. Emergency services worked late into Monday night to clear the water and deal with hazards such as partially collapsed roads.','Flash Floods Devastate Walsden, West Yorkshire','The Guardian','2013-07-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/video/2013/jul/30/flash-floods-walsden-west-yorkshire-video','Walsden was hit by devastating flash floods on July 29, 2013, after torrential rain caused roads to turn into rivers and homes to be flooded. This severe weather event also significantly impacted parts of Todmorden.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('487e87e7-068a-45d4-ba4e-7e3de7f29c17','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Penistone rail line which connects several major cities across Yorkshire is set to receive £48 million extra funding to help improve services. The line, which runs through Huddersfield, Sheffield, Penistone and Barnsley, is essential for commuters in the area, but has long been plagued with slow travel times due to insufficient railway investment in recent years. ... One of the big changes to the line will be the addition of a second section of track on some parts of the line, which will allow trains to run more frequently in both directions. [16]','Penistone rail line to receive £48 million in Levelling Up funding boost','RailAdvent','2023-11-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.railadvent.co.uk/2023/11/penistone-rail-line-to-receive-48-million-in-levelling-up-funding-boost.html','RailAdvent reported that the Penistone rail line, connecting Huddersfield, Sheffield, Penistone, and Barnsley, will receive £48 million in Levelling Up funding. The funding aims to address slow travel times and insufficient infrastructure, with plans for a second section of track on some parts to increase train frequency and overall speed.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('48863a0d-178b-4ebe-9518-525fbda135c1','infrastructure-frizinghall-station-revitalization',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.032','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Schoolchildren have been proving it\'s not only the major gestures that matter as Bradford celebrates being UK City of Culture 2025. Monday 19 May saw the opening of a new platform 0, built by Network Rail to boost the number of LNER seats between Bradford Forster Square station and London by more than 36,000 a week. A couple of miles up the line from Forster Square is Frizinghall Primary School, who have been busy sprucing up nearby Frizinghall station. Tim Goddard, Network Rail maintenance protection co-ordinator, said: “This was a joint initiative we ran with Bradford Council\'s enforcement officers and Frizinghall Primary School, assisted by Railscape.”','Bradford school\'s station clean-up for City of Culture 2025 | RailBusinessDaily','RailBusinessDaily','2025-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHlS9LJ5F71R-gaq_n5O9wp4qQ1YyjjRxtZV7117iGcI_WrurfChYXpgHQnP2hJOa6_YYd7yHL_A4OBsZ_KPOsn2hHAnzmhrvKNg-sHpETSXk_vVscLp7XMv_Aadmx43vav8qxdZPrUsl-zGWUqbAnoxvSFeoM3arm1sEhAINqaa3PPkh0Pdqc8gzNvR2CztlG_thNApE0q_D8=','This article details a community clean-up initiative at Frizinghall station on May 19, 2025, involving pupils from Frizinghall Primary School, Network Rail, Bradford Council, and Railscape. The effort focused on removing litter and fly-tipping, contributing to Bradford\'s UK City of Culture 2025 celebrations and fostering community pride.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4899753a-a918-44ab-88c9-fb725a6a2b63','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Further Consultation & Funding Secured. June 2021. Government writes to offer Brighouse Town Deal funding for £19.1 million. Calderdale Council agree to accept the funding on behalf of the Town Deal Board. [9] Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet has agreed to accept £19.1 million of Towns Fund money for Brighouse to build on existing strengths and take the town to the next level. [18] Business leaders have welcomed the £19.1M to boost the economy in Brighouse as part of the Government\'s long-term Town Investment Plan (TIP). [19]','Brighouse secured £19.1 million from the Government\'s Towns Fund','The Brighouse Deal - The Timeline, YorkshireLive, Halifax Courier','2021-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.brighousedeal.co.uk/the-timeline/, https://www.yorkshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/brighouse-town-centre-set-huge-20986915, https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/brighouse-business-leaders-welcome-new-prospects-as-town-receives-ps191m-3302798','In June 2021, the Government offered Brighouse £19.1 million in funding as part of the Towns Fund. Calderdale Council agreed to accept this funding in July 2021 to support the regeneration of the town centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('497338e3-9fa6-4d4a-bf71-d2ef852a7942','infrastructure-elland-rail-station-and-access-package-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.897','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Submitted planning application for the Rail Station. [4]','Planning application submitted for Elland Rail Station','Calderdale Next Chapter','2021-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/projects/elland-rail-station','The project team from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority submitted a planning application for Elland Rail Station in October 2021.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('497c8d5c-1e27-4ef8-9697-84f3c344f9a7','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Quickline\'s fast and reliable full-fibre broadband is now live and bringing high-speed connectivity to rural communities across West Yorkshire, thanks to the government\'s Project Gigabit. Homes and businesses in villages like Streethouse and New Sharlston, near Wakefield, and Emley and Upper Cumberworth, near Huddersfield, now have access to gigabit-capable broadband. So far around 600 premises in these areas can now get connected through Project Gigabit funding and another 1,100 premises have gained access through Quickline\'s commercial build. [9, 19, 22]','Quickline brings full fibre broadband to rural communities across West Yorkshire','UKTIN, Fibre News, Quickline','2024-11-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGvB_AclYaNHqYP3DivgHtdzDZIWlcjYZS6ve1YlHI4iMk86LCq92mNuEjMCFmoQyaVk6JUG34JTuS_5scDhvFIgSO7kroQ5NZSVtwFC_J8CB9uvRyOsp7MY-EmLrdih3v-UmdhQ7Jj0i8C18O1tA_sU6UFwDug8xiqFZBhNSmAfXoHsEY9NHo8OBlMXrfSJEcs8K4KxwYuPFHzctAltgVoaBkr6z9SXpTxkQwEVDwX','Quickline\'s full-fibre broadband is now live in rural West Yorkshire, bringing high-speed connectivity to villages like Streethouse and New Sharlston (near Wakefield) and Emley and Upper Cumberworth (near Huddersfield). Approximately 600 premises have been connected through Project Gigabit funding, with an additional 1,100 premises connected through Quickline\'s commercial build.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('49da5135-b7ac-484d-919a-d8282c065d25','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Preliminary work began at the end of January with the main construction expected to start in April. It will see the creation of single-lane segregated cycle routes on Sunbridge Road in the centre of the city, as well as a two-way route along Thornton Road. Originally, £17.5million of Government funding was put forward for the cycleway, although this was revised to £12million. [15]','New £12million cycling \'superhighway\' launched with preliminary work underway','GB News','2024-01-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGj9Xc_0q__c4IxqMckrlDtgYZMc5c89uTdjsVuP_spCkFG7jLht4WDlyyu_Z-UjEJP6ynGl6Bi3gQ0F7ozY8vPqHECdeuH5Ggpsmy5I1EWR322JSnC3iV6F590H6vn-e5-m8HuqmqWkOmpfszce28smHMNrtVIYwenRM_c0DsCA57AfZanYxNSdUxiVxMCbB4_mw==','Preliminary work for the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway project, a £12 million scheme, began at the end of January, with main construction expected to start in April. This involves creating segregated cycle routes on Sunbridge Road and a two-way route along Thornton Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4aa98970-37fe-4c3e-babd-987e4f63c245','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield District Housing Association are committed to becoming a sustainable business. As part of this goal, they sought to install a solar PV system on their Merefield House offices in Castleford. To do this, they went to tender for the array to find the most appropriate supplier to meet their environmental objectives. Due to our expertise and experience, we were successful in our tender bid for the project. After some careful site consumption analysis by our technical department, both sides agreed to install a larger 150 kWp PV system to optimise payback for the system and offset more carbon for WDH. ... Working over a two-week period, the array of 516 panels was installed as the team worked hard to install a mixture of 290W & 295W Trina solar panels on roof pitch of 10 degrees. ... Now complete and commissioned, the system is generating over 109.2 MWh of clean energy every year. Over 30.9 tonnes of carbon emissions will be offset each year.','Wakefield District Housing Association Solar Panel Installation at Merefield House','EvoEnergy','2020-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFLYNf2uduzccik_Z0MLlWzmy7TYJd-BwCk0wDk67u7euoEcnTEQGQHMiRKxH08loLX1p9PuoXEPvYrij1UJ8ZDwqNRYa-gryb7ztEeUic8J7JpCPA0lcaeFPmtaFonTxyuHA_p6sg-czOBC7X42m7WKZN-qngnM0sbszgxyeaZePJBVDPsA4oopw==','EvoEnergy installed a 150 kWp solar PV system consisting of 516 panels on Wakefield District Housing Association\'s Merefield House offices in Castleford, West Yorkshire. This project aimed to achieve WDH\'s sustainability goals by offsetting over 30.9 tonnes of carbon emissions and generating 109.2 MWh of clean energy annually. The installation was completed over a two-week period with a focus on design optimisation and safety features.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4af88897-c481-4f50-ad60-e52d56ea532f','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Improvements to the Dewsbury Riverside area are set to begin in April, marking the first phase of development of thousands of new homes. ... The Dewsbury Riverside site is currently home to 25 allotments which are in use by the public. This first stage of work will focus on replacing these (allotment) plots and adding more, resulting in a total of 43 plots in a new location. This part of the project received planning permission in June 2021, and Kirklees Council has contracted local construction firm Casey Ltd to complete the bulk of work during this stage. A new vehicle entrance will be created on Ravensthorpe Road, along with a new car park and drainage improvements.','Work on the Dewsbury Riverside development set to begin next month','Dewsbury Reporter','2022-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGyO73yyCB6_2MaIXU81uAwP261XUGnW3SJNzUGG9o4f89RumNTqSED0vmHm5IKD2Eqr0xBfQkce0jg7-lC_I_3XHV6xDyxrKC3UewTIHZYP8LZt4PzNhSW-BW8LH88wv-lhnzTUZn2V7Dp_5Ddr5bXGtOBo_uM0UJ0gyD-hIF8hMdmW9MFBeoRKGDl7bSgN8tXcDzDxdtNI59vUVUOb4RO2Zbr6xk73qwLitDtdBX9JKEwouvAO2ps-9-yGcCZ8g==','The first phase of work on the Dewsbury Riverside development, focusing on replacing existing allotments with 43 new plots in a new location, was set to begin in April 2022. This phase included creating a new vehicle entrance on Ravensthorpe Road, a car park, and drainage improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4b0a8713-a554-4574-906f-1bc598534b49','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At a meeting on Tuesday, June 3, Bradford Council\'s Executive will rubber stamp the local schemes that make up the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement awarded to West Yorkshire. Among the projects to benefit from the scheme is… Around £35m of funding will go towards works on Kings Road, which runs from Wrose to Bradford city centre. That work will include improvements to pavements, crossings, bus stops and green spaces along the roadside and the creation of bus and cycle lanes.','Bradford Council bosses to approve major road schemes - Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-05-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHsApZqohLGWx9gbDzSkx3qS8wyrldtIXGkfF_Y1qRwN2ulXY5S1mUyW8Kh2ft97gQpe4PXssGSXp5-nmu6Az5U1fW96kpi2wlsxkPaEaBJYoJfiSdwOAncj1Dw9AI9fwuXl9O9AqaH53W0pz7MnJSI_fSHR07pCgnwfVgcEQq9WuY8w44BOga94jg7SO7J-eitvgu2I0a9s19f7ogczlsMgZR','Bradford Council\'s Executive was set to approve various local schemes making up the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) at a meeting on June 3. This included approximately £35 million for works on Kings Road, covering improvements to pavements, crossings, bus stops, green spaces, and the creation of bus and cycle lanes. This approval by the Executive is a crucial step for the project\'s progression.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4b404333-23ac-4d06-a1b0-7e5ad62f5e45','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The information below was presented during the public consultation between 1 April to 13 May 2025. ... The West Yorkshire Places project aims to help create safer, healthier and better connected streets in Cleckheaton. We want to improve connections between Spen Valley Greenway and Cleckheaton town centre. This will provide a new, accessible access to Cleckheaton for pedestrians and cyclists, helping to drive footfall and support local businesses. We want to implement traffic calming measures and new crossing points to make road travel near the Greenway safer. We also want to make things safer for people walking and cycling, by removing parking in the underpass and improving lighting. The scheme is part of Kirklees Council\'s wider Cleckheaton Blueprint. What sort of improvements could be made? Our proposals contain: Widening of the footway into Cross Crown Street and creating a new zebra crossing leading to Station Approach. Improve accessibility for cycling and wheeling between Railway St and Northgate using a modal filter and dropped kerbs. Widening the footway under the bridge on Station Approach and restricting some parking. Painting, installing new lighting and repairing the road surface under the bridge. Connect the greenway to Crown Street with a new accessible ramp. Convert a section of Crown Street car park into a mini park with seating, landscaping, events space and cycle parking. Tidy up and seating on the Greenway. New uncontrolled crossing over Station Approach to...','Cleckheaton Greenway Connection - Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/cleckheaton-greenway','This page from West Yorkshire Combined Authority details the public consultation for the \'Cleckheaton Greenway Connection\' project, which ran from April 1 to May 13, 2025. Proposals aim to enhance connections between the Spen Valley Greenway and Cleckheaton town centre, featuring a new accessible ramp, improved lighting in the underpass, and the creation of a pocket park from part of Crown Street car park.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4b566157-4565-4c7b-a459-c1528b06b69b','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £3.2 million project to make it easier and more pleasant to walk, wheel and cycle around Todmorden is set to move forward. Calderdale Council has listened to feedback from local people on what they want the \'Active Todmorden\' project to look like. The Council engaged with the community on the updated proposals in November 2024. Feedback from that engagement has informed the approval of the walking and wheeling improvements as the preferred option. The Council has removed the dedicated cycle lane element on Burnley Road. The detailed designs for these plans will be progressed in early 2025, with construction due to complete in spring 2026.','Moving forward with active travel in Todmorden','Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-12-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/moving-forward-with-active-travel-in-todmorden','Calderdale Council announced its decision to proceed with a refined \'Active Todmorden\' project following community feedback. The revised plans focused on walking and wheeling improvements and specifically removed the dedicated cycle lane element on Burnley Road due to local concerns. The project, part of the £17.5 million Todmorden Town Deal, was cited as a £3.2 million investment, with construction due to complete in spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4b62d90e-6be3-40b9-b039-77e66072d471','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'EVBox, a provider of electric vehicle (EV) charging solutions, is launching its most powerful charging station – EVBox Troniq High Power – which can deliver 400 kilowatts of power... [11]','EVBox Launches Troniq High Power, its Fastest Standalone EV Charging Station','Environment+Energy Leader','2023-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.environmentalleader.com/2023/06/evbox-launches-its-fastest-standalone-ev-charging-station/','EVBox introduced its most powerful charging station, the Troniq High Power, capable of delivering 400 kilowatts. This global product development by EVBox demonstrates their commitment to advanced charging solutions and potential deployment in various locations, including cities like Leeds. [11]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4bfe7252-28a3-4e59-9b4a-72e99108997d','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At a meeting of West Yorkshire Combined Authority on Thursday morning, members voted to award over £13m to help kickstart the City Village project, which will eventually see 900 homes built on the Kirkgate and Oastler Centre sites and other city centre locations. It will also see new business, café and retail space and three parks developed in this area of the city centre. The money is on top of £30m funding from Homes England that was pledged towards the development last year. That funding was dependant on today\'s funding from WYCA. The £13m has come from the Brownfield Housing Fund – money given to WYCA by Government to kickstart the development of housing on long empty brownfield sites.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Approves £13m Funding for City Village Project','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFe3e8GomTAViihVqG5YkgvtsCgdEfkTsjOJMqzKiD8mZi-Jxl5iaxoaMNUbo8cQVoQUVDWorWJhqZln3SNo2hd1v9GqgL5AoP12Tz9Q4cY4-vB6mDoVFtHPX_9XFmIK_ShwYbOYFpCdVAqyeVAQ6e8widAYo8EcbfaKxRzDbr85gEniQIGYIm1z9bSTzsGywWsB_4fVZtZACuT81HBMxO6eUk3','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) voted to approve over £13 million in funding for the Bradford City Village project. This investment, from the Brownfield Housing Fund, is intended to kickstart the first two phases of the scheme, supporting the development of 900 homes and associated amenities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4c319f2a-7ec6-44a4-8900-1b0d420d0264','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Home Upgrade Grant (HUG) and Local Authority Delivery scheme (LAD) are government schemes supporting energy efficiency upgrades of low-energy efficiency (EPC of D or lower) low-income (household income below £30k) households across England. HUG Phase 2 (HUG 2) is actively reporting and has allocated £630 million for delivery between September 2023 and March 2025. HUG 2 is exclusively for off-gas-grid properties. LAD Phases 1 and 2 previously received £500 million between them. These schemes ran between 2020-2022. LAD Phase 3 made £287 million of funding available for Local Authorities. HUG 1 allocated £220 million, exclusively for homes that are off the gas grid. Both schemes ran from 2022-2023.','Summary of the Green Homes Grant Local Authority Delivery (LAD) and Home Upgrade Grant (HUG) statistics: September 2024','GOV.UK','2024-09-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHB7XxuJaxnmrIBuNtYoP98sMcT-FFojRIyxX0BFlV1owgFFysT8CI6U0BBwwt8C1xxfg-CBeLE1ly34paEG1yYYHuGbPvJOAjN9DPegJBC0Vy8doGCnmHtHyfC9JC784F822K-FckQC46sNckaAuJ8MmU2gLgyyX3P3gQRtgdfc6mK4Dc81ijDaNsEfkDv5KXx4qhlVlRVXG3zYaNaMWi2utP9HrleXAMFJmYsTkly8Znwj_6tyn_1s5MwNOVkrHSuwqDsYp04CnsGoz-8jG0sZYymUg3y9AKzV6ZzjMhc83hbz5mrL_CFHJvu_KnY7SopJ8DjmDIZX4m0Fj-xwVeeMKiWvD4tInY8dxP3pCY_cZICAvYNO9_d7c5lyCVk1RBYgBRoLSU1COffswULc4MZA3cY-LNw6No=','This GOV.UK publication provides statistics on the Home Upgrade Grant (HUG) and Local Authority Delivery (LAD) schemes across England. It confirms HUG Phase 2 (HUG 2) has allocated £630 million for delivery between September 2023 and March 2025, specifically for off-gas-grid properties. These national schemes are the funding backbone for local initiatives like those in Wakefield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4c8071fa-ffff-4415-85e5-11f4e2f149e7','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The creation of a flagship new sustainable community in the heart of Bradford took a major step forward this week as Bradford Council and ECF, our partnership with Homes England and Legal & General, entered into a Development Agreement to kick-start the first phase of Bradford City Village. [14]','Landmark Development Agreement Signed for Bradford City Village','Muse','2024-12-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.museplaces.com/news/landmark-development-agreement-signed-for-bradford-city-village/','Bradford Council and ECF (a partnership between Homes England, Legal & General, and Muse) signed a Development Agreement to officially kick-start the first phase of the Bradford City Village project. This marks a significant step towards transforming Bradford city centre into a sustainable community with up to 1,000 new homes, parks, public spaces, and commercial units.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4cecf19e-6a67-4ee6-aac3-2f4a198f32e8','infrastructure-halifax-future-high-streets-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.256','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale, Halifax Town Centre, £11.8m. ... The Communities Secretary announced on 19 May 2021 confirmation of funding for all 57 places that previously received provisional offers in December 2020.','Future High Streets Fund: successful and unsuccessful applications - GOV.UK','GOV.UK','2021-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFSyzNWWBZBG7PZ4kLbDoWuKHMrfFWIbvG2srvArCIHYXaTjN18OSPfyM6B8GpRAVb6R-jEprBVDl1sHSvNhOwatu4jnzLIGzhyY8pvi7WrKi0g1aaZ_4DWnjuYFCHiq5VcdgE1eq-h1qFdy9q4eTLsYlBPYzuzKr6T8v0L6OkUE39GIIOrqshJR-byNtlP0rw-XuEXTJ7gnn68rrVPagp6QcTmeJf4Oh_hhP7ie8Ed4sMbPvyg29CZ_1vHq8qYuVUP81Hi8ChRbAhPGCPLNt0PkgzudMzDWx7PusUuTVLhiiY=','Official government publication confirming the successful applicants for the Future High Streets Fund. Halifax Town Centre is listed as a successful applicant, receiving £11.8m, confirming the provisional funding announced earlier.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4d375281-13f7-4627-8105-f6b17ba75232','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Cycle Superhighway Maps. Last updated 20 June 2024. The West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension Scheme will begin on Sunbridge Road at the junction with Barry Street. The route will continue into the city centre as part of the city centre transformation. Below you can view the maps of the route with details about what\'s happening in each section. [17]','West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension Scheme maps updated','Future Bradford','2024-06-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGO3Z_Rg11CV3Sw-ytVZdQCQyYXlU-DCHQCYydk00eG96OA22fUTeFIyTLRDdu3iaW74J1OBZqrrOpTRuXIq4p227t69txd-tIN1WktwbRwn5-3n0ezaHh7hg95HaubqwJ_WKiQXx8USBUzRL9GKQRFn-hlNYA=','Updated maps for the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension Scheme were released. These maps detail the route starting from Sunbridge Road (at the junction with Barry Street), extending into the city centre, and continuing along Thornton Road. They include specific details on changes related to parking, crossings, and landscaping elements of the project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4d42991d-01ec-499a-a208-50891ce905aa','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds\'s South Bank is to enjoy more affordable and lower carbon heating after £24.5m funding was secured to further expand the Leeds PIPES district heating network. The expansion is planned to include up to 28 buildings, with up to 8,000 residents and mixed-use customers benefitting from connections, making it the most significant single investment into the project since its inception. By using heat recovered from the city\'s non-recyclable domestic waste to provide warmth and hot water to buildings in the city, the Leeds PIPES district heating project is helping businesses and residents to move away from costly fossil-fuel powered heating systems. The continued expansion of the district heating network is supporting efforts to end the city\'s contribution to climate change.','Leeds low carbon heat network set to expand to thousands more residents','Leeds City Council News','2024-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/leeds-low-carbon-heat-network-set-to-expand-to-thousands-more-residents','Leeds secured £24.5 million in funding for further expansion of the Leeds PIPES district heating network, particularly in the South Bank area. This expansion aims to connect up to 28 buildings and benefit up to 8,000 residents, underscoring the ongoing growth and strategic importance of the overall network to which Spinner\'s Yard connects.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4d681cf4-083e-4de8-aeba-65f11a3b2fb0','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2018-08-28) The A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill transport scheme is due to enter one of its last major stages, as overnight road resurfacing work is scheduled to start today ... Coun Kim Groves, Chair of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Transport Committee said: “I am pleased to see this key West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund scheme, designed to support inclusive growth and jobs by speeding up journeys along this major route, is reaching its final stages. “I hope people won\'t be too inconvenienced by this re-surfacing work, which is vital to bringing the scheme\'s significant benefits into effect.” Calderdale Council said that the resurfacing works are highly… (2018-08-28) The phased works will be carried out overnight, between 7pm and 6am, and any works involving pneumatic breaking equipment will be completed by 11.30pm to minimise any disturbance during the night. All road closures, diversion routes and traffic management will be clearly marked, and signs notifying people of closures will be in place two weeks before the closure.','Extensive planning in place as A629 Salterhebble road closures begin','Halifax Courier','2018-08-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFc2WnFYS-ZeddiNo-uDoKrS5A-OShQyZXv21_1aExMmKIbSwplfILDpL3V3LxpfgQ5Rnh1BF-ZN06ob1mnKjFSlrXSE5t7MdtX5Udkw8DOrZPPZ2vhv8xYzntdYJ2NscZsnG-aX-clXln25va_nKWxH0FCAD6w-S0cgD7gtIPbJ8-IAjq_60et5AzAmitB9KNqzobmA1FNGJMVCTJSH4-2FKTBa_zcFLFFD42lk0_fnL29H5kNQ==','This article announces that the A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill transport scheme is entering its final stages, with overnight road resurfacing work scheduled to start. Councillor Kim Groves of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Transport Committee expressed satisfaction that the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund scheme was reaching its conclusion, highlighting its role in supporting inclusive growth and jobs by speeding up journeys.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4d6bcc00-a991-4fb1-ac9a-fec84ec36540','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Virgin Media O2 is using this next-generation network to deliver its broadband and TV Stream services to homes and businesses in the area. Councillor Graham Turner, Cabinet member for finance and regeneration at Kirklees Council said: “This is a huge step forward for our digital connectivity. Over the last few years, we know more people than ever before are working from home, gaming online and using streaming services every day. As we all conduct more of our lives online, digital connectivity becomes a crucial part of the infrastructure to support our modern lives.” [4]','Virgin Media gigabit broadband now available to 11,000 more homes in Huddersfield for first time','Virgin Media O2 Newsroom','2024-08-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHXmK5srGnUplVtKfhI_flrK9mLw5U2Vcd54_4mi_KN9o5PECC6Z_JCKAkLbKkA0qHYWO1Ve3v6_kgBSZs_TxJtoRDgpsH8pdDPQ40hmsximcyrViB-1vmnXtG1Um8ZZlI9T-PZzZeRpldY3cHMsu__Emu_986_mtv37na9v8_14ZMVUlUv91-lirFh2sOjRZl-SfrIOvdbDItXcfdzHfVjp9tOauLf8l68yKNcNCcGu7yXLHsreAbI3d1VT80=','Virgin Media O2 expanded its gigabit broadband network to 11,000 additional homes and businesses in Huddersfield, a key town within Kirklees. Councillor Graham Turner of Kirklees Council highlighted this as a significant step for digital connectivity in the district, demonstrating ongoing collaboration between Virgin Media O2 and local authorities to enhance broadband access.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4d6d5c53-5c0c-4824-879c-09776a7848b9','infrastructure-north-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.153','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'September 2021 West Yorkshire Combined Authority have published the Consultation Analysis Report for the North Halifax Improved Streets for People consultation held in March and April 2021. [5]','Publication of Consultation Analysis Report for North Halifax Improved Streets for People (Round 1)','Calderdale Next Chapter','2021-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF_imu2sLdwoefBfOAmaCMLbYu2oziB03cP-y5ni59uvcknf9kLYeshUlI_VM345NRZi0TKGXAmiOVO73RrgGbNI8UCLpd6Qffkv_XDGTBhy48YahUafaB5hXoGfmTy023OBtP3UMNIpidQk8p0dsw2R8VPN6kHBzrO7P5pkiJOQDoaYpTslu5xBdpk8Ubn7eY=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority published the Consultation Analysis Report for the first public consultation on the North Halifax Improved Streets for People project, which was held in March and April 2021. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4e103125-6a2f-4b0d-9f3e-dabc35916831','infrastructure-ionity-leeds-skelton-lakes-ev-charging-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.372','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Motorway service area operator Extra MSA Group, which opened its flagship Leeds Skelton Lake Services in 2020, has completed the roll-out of ultra-fast electric vehicle charging points across its sites. The company partnered with high-power charging network IONITY to install 38 charging points with a charging capacity of up to 350kW across all eight of its locations, with more to follow at existing and proposed new MSA developments. IONITY is continuing to increase the number of high-powered electric vehicle charging points across Extra MSA Group\'s sites and is on track to deliver six high-powered chargers at each site ahead of the Government\'s 2023 target. [6]','Extra MSA Group Completes Ultra-Fast EV Charger Roll-out Across Sites, Including Skelton Lake','Yorkshire Post','2022-04-10 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/business/motorway-services-operator-extra-msa-group-completes-network-of-high-power-electric-vehicle-chargers-3648173','Extra MSA Group, the operator of Leeds Skelton Lake Services, announced the completion of its network-wide roll-out of ultra-fast electric vehicle charging points. The company partnered with IONITY to install 38 charging points with a capacity of up to 350kW across its eight locations, with plans for further expansion to six chargers per site ahead of a 2023 government target.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4e105a05-6980-4d06-9a3f-1a50a927ceb1','infrastructure-five-towns-leisure-hub-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.669','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Building work on the venue is now complete. A new leisure centre will open its doors to the public as soon as lockdown restrictions allow. The government has provisionally said that leisure centres, gyms and swimming pools will be allowed to reopen on April 12. Wakefield Council leader Denise Jeffery who cut a ceremonial ribbon at the venue today said she was \'delighted\' that the centre was now built. [4], Work has now been completed on the main building at the £22m Aspire@ThePark. [5]','Aspire@The Park: New Pontefract leisure centre could open on April 12 as Wakefield Council declares building work complete','Wakefield Express / Yorkshire Live','2021-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHSznlzxqFvEPhlDUxZXWO7S7qU6ysc_E7HmSErvW_h6VYUDzx0LJNqXPpBlFH59hnEWUBp4wHVrgUVhYws5Ao--uA3Adqg7_0bPXopF9pxDmD08ln4r7LO5zM522rF9guDoteJ7C-zptNTOYSV-KB1Kb28JO4iMMVYDTo-0kcqp0fQBB7dzBJ0uFqpUrVYkgFw_lXUDKSvsDDiPEwq1lyNCJK1MjJWB0aqKHXYARgcQVrKaDt4AvWTS0cIk0evrFthjG3kvyftbj6PLbkpp4DWaVwZT9mcSs2j5lvo3eGfd7P_JZC_mkoKhQLK0G_Xo5W1fa1F','Building work on the Aspire@ThePark leisure centre in Pontefract was declared complete by Wakefield Council. The facility, costing around £22 million, was provisionally set to open to the public on April 12, 2021, in line with government lockdown easing.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4e33380d-5344-45e2-8f5d-1999a2c35a81','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following a public consultation in 2020 seeking feedback about a busy junction on the A6120, (Leeds Outer Ring Road) preliminary works will be starting this week. In November 2022, improvement works started and completed in December 2023. The works are expected to last for 12 months, with the main construction starting in January 2023, after the busy Christmas period to allow for minimum disruption to road users.','Preliminary Works Begin for Fink Hill Junction Improvements','Leeds City Council News / Ilkley Gazette / Commonplace','2022-11-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH4ARm1n3HdfoAtXxWosycGlgZxwCuXgAw277AWzXsWVpJNAv2b_vx8D57FSJjviJvzAAWAvukUJV48ukwH8lWVq-9yW6Tthqd5OHOoUkFrgBRLXboq87oBV6-uVYWjUAFOmKxbAh_1m7Z6v1UrmMAXruBpK-tQ2NcEoMW62eMzjZDyNiLiIbs4FBLKO2kLzHcGExGK_ZoSXUgMYizs=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHC5jaRdQQXp7nPHNRqdvVC_U01eZGLmDQixH4zVaSk4ETCCZewVV-KKvFI3Zz0N5Byz8WxVE0srEx0v5AKV-qcPqYzhx3AydT_d2g5xtWJtBiXbvho1CSNcH7tFb2Bjew87EZlQire52Tsgb6ZkpbyPzOz4ksvJnpI_4B0ZD8ghk5unSb5M_T8alSqLOox5gE3-zK2NHnysBh3Eo9xuA5NDdbaGRw=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG1BeJsY8mrfcKeZ_T0PM-bQPni9N75OASQAXZfmd8XVvkQbSmZH2eao_qQwZmxw5rv7SG4BfrcqzPKLU86ie_4a_aW-fx7ZXYiCdngrLvTJPO1KP2j-03Mb-nn9jA7b5dzx0CGqw==','Preliminary works for the Fink Hill junction improvements began the week of November 22, 2022. The scheme aims to improve connectivity, provide new pedestrian crossing facilities and cycle lanes, and offer a better junction layout to enhance safety and reduce congestion. Main construction was expected to start in January 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4e71728c-86f7-46d0-83c2-c90b5e9829a5','infrastructure-north-halifax-streets-for-people-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.173','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In September 2020, Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council (CMBC) conducted a survey with those who lived, worked and travelled through North and West Halifax to understand their barriers to walking and cycling, and the perceptions of traffic and movement in the two areas. [5], Between Monday 14 September and Friday 16 October 2020, a period of engagement took place where the public and other interested parties were asked to participate in a baseline engagement survey. [10]','Calderdale Streets for People (Park Ward and North Halifax) Engagement Survey','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/calderdale-streets-people','Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, conducted an engagement survey from September to October 2020. This survey aimed to understand existing barriers to walking and cycling in North and West Halifax, as well as public perceptions of traffic and movement, informing the initial development of active travel schemes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4eac47db-9cf7-4a61-b6c5-4e2386d8df07','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Aire Park, Leeds\' 24-acre mixed use development, has now opened the next phase of its much-anticipated park that will bring 6200 square metres of new green space to the South Bank. Connecting the public realm in front of the Tetley building to Crown Point Road, this new park area marks the largest segment of the park to open so far, as the city prepares for what will be the biggest new public park in the UK upon completion. [12]','Largest Segment of Aire Park\'s Public Green Space Opens to Public','Yorkshire Evening Post','2025-07-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQENt-jHowDIYUx6WOBfVhiROGhNhH40eNNZjFQf2aUZV4TBfBB4dPZ8Yk2gD9DAiJ7lfAquO0YPszT1EpGGjTOxBFRGQjoojZ3CV11a1XVCyELZrI0wKNv0da7fAsS55XyXDpgDuQCFlCFNaF7Hv7pLPEjaPxZqMdbKEfU3Su1VVHm6phrIx2rMMNsL9ooy2FGfqLGB1bN-RWerQk0-3Qz5TIT5F-kjFXuA2N3XXLPjKW3hLCMStKzguBSRETM-Jcaayrc3ouqSjNhL3kfumTyVy_DznFCS8ggsjNWqLGO9vfWZwqbJYIxv [12]','A significant section of Aire Park, bringing 6,200 square metres of new green space to the South Bank, officially opened. This phase connects the area in front of The Tetley building to Crown Point Road, offering large lawns, flowering gardens, play mounds, and a new woodland belt, contributing to what will be the UK\'s largest new urban park.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4eef0cdb-8153-4c88-8e49-f8a87f37427d','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In July, the first phase of the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme got underway on Northumberland Street in Huddersfield Town Centre. Northumberland Street is set for a major transformation and aims to bring the streets to life with high-quality paving, wider footways and improved cycle infrastructure, creating a more welcoming and accessible environment for all. After completion, Northumberland Street will benefit from improved traffic flow whilst prioritising pedestrians and inclusive access. More to Come. With further upgrades planned for Trinity Street and St. John\'s Road, the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme will improve links between the towns rail and bus stations, supporting more sustainable and efficient journeys. Councillor Moses Crook, Deputy Leader of the council and Cabinet Member for Housing and Transport said:“It\'s great to see spades in the ground on these really important transport schemes. “We understand that there will be some short term disruption, but once completed, these schemes are set to have lasting positive impacts, opening up better access to more education, employment and training opportunities across Kirklees and beyond. [8]','Huddersfield Railway Station Connections Scheme Update','Grapevine Magazines','2025-08-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.grapevinemagazines.co.uk/huddersfield-railway-station-connections-scheme-update/','The first phase of the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme commenced in July on Northumberland Street in Huddersfield Town Centre. This phase focuses on transforming the street with high-quality paving, wider footways, and improved cycle infrastructure to create a more welcoming environment. Further upgrades are planned for Trinity Street and St. John\'s Road to enhance links between the rail and bus stations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4ef4280b-5e1d-4e84-8f85-7f35460b7c95','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'John Sisk & Son has been appointed to carry out works on the £27m A629 Phase 1b, Halifax to Huddersfield improvement scheme. The road improvement scheme focuses on the key areas of Huddersfield Road, Stainland Road and Wakefield Road. A new link road will be created via a bridge spanning the Calder and Hebble navigation to a roundabout on Stainland Road. The project will include facilities for pedestrians and cyclists and a section of new northbound bus lane on Stainland Road. A new signal-controlled junction at the interchange of A629 / Jubilee Road and an improved approach lane will also be provided, as well as landscaping along Stainland Road and additional access points to the canal towpath. Completion of the Phase 1b improvement scheme is expected to be late 2022. The A629 scheme has received funding through the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund, and the Leeds City Region Growth Deal. [25]','Sisk wins A629 road improvement scheme','PBC Today','2021-01-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.pbctoday.co.uk/news/planning-construction-news/sisk-wins-a629-road-improvement-scheme/87841/','John Sisk & Son was appointed as the contractor for the £27m A629 Phase 1b, Halifax to Huddersfield improvement scheme. This phase focuses on Huddersfield Road, Stainland Road, and Wakefield Road, including a new link road, bridge, roundabout, and facilities for pedestrians and cyclists, with an anticipated completion by late 2022. While Phase 1b, it sets the context for overall A629 improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4f410c6d-9e2f-4726-9b51-a5a365a84145','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2024, February 13) Work in this winter\'s planting season has seen 350 trees planted in the local community as part of the Armley Gyratory improvement scheme. This is in addition to the 206 trees planted last year, making a total of 556 trees, which is well on the way to a target of planting over 660 new trees for the scheme. Last week at Armley Park, 10 Walnut trees were planted by volunteers, councillors, project team and organised by Leeds City Council\'s parks and countryside rangers.','Over 550 Trees Planted for Armley Gyratory Improvement Scheme','Leeds City Council News','2024-02-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEMxyUg21XTTCy-XD9TfSlXCkaOAVKMySvoBjHA2h2TCcXm5MDBOgVRjvNuKD2cjSL6LaH4uBj-w5xtIzEERoULLt062pd4ttsY7ERIMUgPXjj9q92efO45sVR5BZzwIkkKaxScIHZ_0JFQ7nRxPRnv-gmO6nlP7T8elzaDUrFQ5wQD4erf5P8HLjZjMVqwn1B735URp9Nl','Leeds City Council announced that 556 trees had been planted as part of the Armley Gyratory improvement scheme, working towards a goal of over 660 new trees. This initiative aimed to enhance local greenery, support urban wildlife, improve air quality, and contribute to climate change efforts. The planting included a diverse range of species across Armley and other local communities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4f4a7ea6-56a6-4403-a5c2-54ba61e9a331','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-ministry-of-justice-leeds-courts-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.352','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds Combined Court Centre and Leeds Magistrates\' Court are the latest buildings to announce plans to connect to the scheme. The two buildings will connect as part of a wider programme of green upgrades over the next year. (Photo credit: Vital Energi) [3]','Leeds Courts Announce Plans to Connect to Leeds PIPES District Heating Scheme','TheBusinessDesk.com (with credit to Vital Energi)','2022-08-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/2100803-leeds-combined-court-centre-and-magistrates-court-to-connect-to-district-heating-scheme','Leeds Combined Court Centre and Leeds Magistrates\' Court are among the latest buildings to announce plans to connect to the Leeds PIPES district heating scheme. This connection is part of a broader program of green upgrades planned for the courts over the coming year.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('4ff36851-aec1-4cef-8923-c19c22d0b5ad','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Name of meeting: Cabinet. Date: 19 March 2019. Title of report: Dewsbury Riverside Masterplan & Masterplan Framework. Purpose of report: This report seeks: Endorsement of the Masterplan and Masterplan Framework for development of the Kirklees Local Plan housing allocation at Dewsbury Riverside. Authority for the Council to enter into an agreement with the Combined Authority to accept Local Growth Fund grant to facilitate infrastructure delivery at Dewsbury Riverside. 1.1 Dewsbury Riverside is a key site within the North Kirklees Growth Zone which is identified as a spatial priority area for housing growth in the Leeds City Region Strategic Economic Plan. The site is allocated for housing in the recently adopted Kirklees Local Plan with capacity for up to 4000 homes, of which approximately 1869 are proposed to be developed within the Local Plan period up to 2031. 1.2 The vision for Dewsbury Riverside is to create a sustainable urban extension that will deliver social, environmental and economic benefits, provide a mix of high quality homes of different tenures together with community infrastructure to create a sustainable, vibrant mixed community; and to retain, expand and enhance existing green infrastructure, connecting new and existing communities to healthy lifestyle opportunities. The scale of the development is intended to be large enough to allow a degree of “market repositioning” and thereby to act as a catalyst for the regeneration of the wider area. 1.3 The masterplan and masterplan framework together set out the \'what and where\' for the development of the allocation. The masterplan framework brings together a significant amount of technical and design work that has been undertaken, it explains the context for the masterplan and sets out the high level phasing of development across the site. The masterplan sets out the distribution of and inter-relationship between land uses across the allocation, the points of access into the site from the local highway network and the internal layout of the site. 1.4 The masterplan has been designed around a series of neighbourhoods radiating from a central urban park, new local centre and primary school, phased to be delivered early in the development to act as a catalyst and driver for the early development of the scheme and that form the heart of the urban village centre. It seeks to retain existing green infrastructure in the form of woodland belts, (See Source [12] for full context).','Dewsbury Riverside Masterplan & Masterplan Framework Approved','Kirklees Council (Cabinet Report)','2019-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/council-and-democracy/pdf/cabinet-agenda/2019/march/dewsbury-riverside-masterplan-and-masterplan-framework.pdf','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet approved the Dewsbury Riverside Masterplan and Masterplan Framework. This plan outlined a vision for developing up to 4,000 homes, new schools, roads, and a local centre on a 160-hectare site in South Dewsbury. It also set out the high-level phasing of development and infrastructure delivery, with an initial focus on 1,869 homes within the Local Plan period.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901');
