	('4fff67e1-9a65-4000-8137-a7eb8d9877c5','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds Central and Headingley MP Alex Sobel, accompanied by Councillor Helen Hayden, Leeds City Council\'s Executive Member for Children and Families, toured the construction site, which, upon its completion in summer 2025, will mark a significant expansion of Leeds City College. [14] Milestones completed include the installation of the structural steelwork and the completion of a section of concrete forming a wall of the library. [14] The development will provide around 70,000 sq. ft of additional educational space, while contributing to the area\'s regeneration and providing much-needed community resources. [14]','Leeds MP and Councillor tour Mabgate Campus, marking construction progress','The Yorkshire Post','2024-10-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEmGkhUG8x0AHWz_FfUthiqivM6mEIEeUckMoyq-QkOOJsiWtFsjaWrTTo-aelYB_Er8J5i5qk6eOIZgfKzvjyXLKDwh0jlqll6QEOo_Yh9WpZd2Vb-oi3KaZUA_FwkPg1zCz2SJE-0n1IS0-ir1sOXi9FvHgIPJUHZlxSTCY8JfziSfHpAxt9Dkb_QjnVY4QzBlEoCR-ae_e22nTXuIJV9vR7XgYbHhHvHA2m1xso=','Alex Sobel MP and Councillor Helen Hayden visited the Mabgate Campus construction site to observe the progress of the £26 million expansion. Milestones achieved included the installation of structural steelwork and the completion of a section of the library wall, with the project slated for completion in summer 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('504ace03-d8bb-4ae1-99c9-c82505c509dd','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been submitted for 1,000 homes to be built on the site of the Oastler Shopping Centre in Bradford city centre. Now, a planning application has been put forward for the first steps in the development. Phase One of the development will focus around the former Oastler Centre and the Chain Street Car Park, deliver 97 new townhouses, as well as \'enhanced green spaces, and improved public realm, forming a strong foundation for future phases.\' There would also be 20 two bed two storey homes, eight three bed three storey homes, and 64 parking spaces at Oastler in this phase. The work, including the demolition of the Oastler Centre, requires approval from Bradford Council before it begins. [6]','Bradford city centre housing plans submitted for 1000-home mega \'city village\'','YorkshireLive','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGy9gXZ9dOmQDC8heJAp-_8RmeDdyDxP30Zaugj86saX7Pa_PTA3bGA7yG_RvQJSgPaGT75ZDpBTSb7V5aERhLQXBPOuWb75rgjbtgBNMmvca89LzSvbWbnVm7OqjmC_u-MjDVhhehuL4GqLtzutMXgMTMf7rNqog9qB-e7y3Og5CA6G52sMoJyDutKd7E7RRSaNJ2-ZA==','Plans were formally submitted to Bradford Council for the 1,000-home Bradford City Village project. Phase One focuses on the former Oastler Centre and Chain Street Car Park, proposing 97 new townhouses (64 at Oastler, 33 at Chain Street), enhanced green spaces, and improved public realm. Demolition of the Oastler Centre and construction requires council approval.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5089a00c-2744-4bcf-8e18-949d9d894413','infrastructure-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-corridor-improvement-phase-1b-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.863','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Planning permission has now been granted for the next phase of the £120 million, A629 improvement programme, which will see work take place around the Calder and Hebble junction. [...] The planning application for the project was approved by committee on Tuesday 21 May, allowing the project to move to the next stage. [6]','Green Light for Calder and Hebble Junction Project: Planning Permission Granted','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2019-05-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/green-light-for-calder-and-hebble-junction-project','Planning permission was granted for the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction project on May 21, 2019, following approval by committee. This marked a significant step forward for the next phase of the £120 million A629 improvement programme, allowing the project to proceed with land acquisition and tendering for detailed design. [6]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('50a60da8-efa1-42e7-a820-9c4ceb9e9fa5','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Bradford City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements scheme aims to radically upgrade the look and feel of Bradford city centre through the introduction of new green spaces and the removal of through traffic from key civic areas. The proposals would also see better quality walking, cycling and public transport infrastructure provided, to offer people improved transport choices. The public consultation ran from Monday 28 July to Sunday 22 September 2021.','Bradford City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements scheme - First Public Consultation','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-07-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme','Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched the first public consultation for the Bradford City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements scheme. The scheme aimed to radically upgrade the city centre by introducing new green spaces, removing through traffic from key civic areas, and providing better walking, cycling, and public transport infrastructure. Proposals included expanding Norfolk Gardens and pedestrianising Hall Ings.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('50eb7976-6d03-4625-b211-5e14e78cba88','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Progress. A four-week public consultation was held from 1-28 March 2021 to comment on proposals for addressing the problems. Comments are being integrated into the plans which will be made available later for public comment. Funding. The £13.6m programme is funded by government\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) through Leeds City Region Local Enterprise Partnership and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. Policy alignment. The project aligns with national and regional plans, transport and clean air policies and strategies as well as the West Yorkshire Transport Strategy, Wakefield District Local Plan, Wakefield District Economic Strategy 2018-2023, Wakefield Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan, West Yorkshire Bus Strategy and Wakefield District Transport Strategy.','Transforming Cities – Wakefield city centre','Wakefield Council','2021-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEcZMdY00c4Jt6MUq0UCG2VlFRr0Q1eZDevMxxBWo4cDFQRdbdqL04DpeYQKD_Xim72zYzIWcJhjuQyTxGP9Wo2-NFwPvKa_RNHkgOfDlgU_i8TaFSAKZoJ_d6hiRD70vUZzz_rFb4smnwGXOsBPvsjVpHcuO_VHNYBD9smMfLGoZz7JkaYQH425AqnC6OtJ6fU6--aEJQeHUpYNMQHzWkyrPYSkpTfch5oivTywFtsTdXQR5I','Wakefield Council launched a four-week public consultation for a £13.6m Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) programme focused on Wakefield city centre. The project aims to reduce traffic in the Northern and Civic Quarters, enhance cycling and walking routes, and improve bus operating conditions. This scheme, distinct but related to the A61/A639 corridors, sought public feedback on initial proposals. The funding, originally from TCF, is being reviewed due to the economic climate, with additional funding options being explored.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('51224b79-4824-4828-96ba-19cf548c5b7d','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Leeds PIPES district heating network has marked the latest major milestone in its journey, having connected over 3,000 dwellings across the region since a scheme began back in 2018. Asserting itself as one of the fastest growing and largest heat networks in the UK, the scheme connects circa 55 individual buildings across multiple sectors, including student living and social housing, as well as public and commercial residencies. Delivered by Vital Energi, in partnership with Leeds City Council and Ener-Vate, the network has connected to 29 key buildings such as St James\'s Hospital, Leeds Playhouse, Leeds Town Hall and Leeds Beckett University, and has been responsible for the reduction of nearly 6,000 tonnes of carbon in 2023 alone.','Over 3,000 dwellings connected: Leeds PIPES network celebrates major milestone','Vital Energi','2024-11-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.vitalenergi.com/news/over-3000-dwellings-connected-leeds-pipes-network-celebrates-major-milestone/','The Leeds PIPES district heating network celebrated connecting over 3,000 dwellings across the region since its inception in 2018. This milestone highlights the rapid growth and success of the network, which Spinner\'s Yard has committed to joining, making it one of the UK\'s largest and fastest-growing heat networks.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('51673719-5d2d-4560-b9bc-88e5508b8b9e','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle (EV) charging points are set to be installed across the Wakefield district after senior councillors agreed to accept £1.5m of funding. ... Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept the grant from West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of measures designed to achieve net zero targets.','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for EV charging points across city after study from Leeds university - Yorkshire Evening Post','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-10-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGZyZyYh-kxmyTMZ_HiiH-4BVLNNVeLD6WjidV9N6wEHdbfz6bPBeCbOLHvui0rLF6PxT8RM7vd0gfSD5d89smzzVJnXQZ9pwiVBAsZ1_SL7WALPkdl_uDvBZW5RdavKcWYlBcTAAarohb79lsU3jv07Vc8rQYg0ef0P_NRo-zsRd2BxvQAkEc5KNjVhcIfmYIVMHufxgU5wQS6Eh4tNbjg6JzqP2b7bz8FB0-W8SUSR3uYNlt1SKtuhwyGwSC7-cUb5i_FNjVCde9O0mQFuijjjSeca6WM8NkX1ng1','Wakefield Council\'s cabinet officially approved the acceptance of £1.5 million in funding from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) for the installation of new EV charging points across the district. This decision was influenced by a University of Leeds study on regional EV charger requirements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('518661ee-49ee-43f7-ae44-80974295d1fd','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As reported by the Courier, Arriva has announced that “after struggling to deliver services reliably in Yorkshire recently”, it will not be running some routes in the future. These include the 571 between Halifax and Shelf which Arriva holds the contract for until February 22. Arriva will continue operating the service until its contract runs out but after that, it will only be continued if another bus company bids to take it on. [7]','Arriva cutting bus routes: Axing Halifax bus service \'would leave residents isolated\' says town\'s MP Kate Dearden','Halifax Courier','2024-11-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH2kkFgWNIrFOWEjQxEKVMQ3dVCxBepJVfMNRXQxLyT7ifbLuXVXJGLxW2L07JiaLaHbHnSmhrEKdZ9ho2BxYgfziH0vnKg0ECgUjfBt6Ab5NpMfNtAR1VASDMFaL8AswgVJ3KNXxrun01kl39iYUxzQmL1L2Jbtumc7MH4Jc-scPAXxrCSpvRFj3b10VGiGBYfqdak60DN7cupco4zKpHHkpEOnJSg5HktiVlyWAK_ZsxeWxONkne1jQUNDhR5V1tvZHKhXbHZt5XnU3Tj8EuU7CpqyLwNLLY8EXI-ZhfiocI','Arriva announced its intention to cease operating the 571 bus service between Halifax and Shelf by February 22, 2025, due to difficulties in reliably delivering services. This decision raised significant concerns among local residents and politicians, who stressed the route\'s importance for community connectivity. [7, 18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('519f3d6f-359e-4206-820f-e83f578f1139','infrastructure-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-corridor-improvement-phase-1b-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.863','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to improve the A629 between Halifax and Huddersfield have taken a step forward with the appointment of John Sisk & Son as contractor for Phase 1b of the project – the Calder and Hebble junction. Following a tender exercise, construction company John Sisk & Son has been hired to carry out the construction work of the A629 Phase 1b – a £27m project which is fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority through the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund. [16]','Contractor Appointed for £27m A629 Phase 1b Road Improvement Scheme','TheBusinessDesk.com','2021-01-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/contractor-appointed-for-27m-road-improvement-scheme','John Sisk & Son was appointed as the contractor for Phase 1b of the A629 project, the Calder and Hebble junction, following a tender exercise. The £27m project is fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority through the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund. This appointment, announced on January 27, 2021, allowed plans to move forward with construction. [16]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('519fe820-09db-452b-b4bb-5ab7dcb7f99a','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Proposals went before a full West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting for major improvements to cycling and bus infrastructure on one of our busiest roads... West Yorkshire Council chiefs heard how the £20 million Wakefield Road Bus and Cycle Priority Corridor will move one step closer to delivery. The scheme focuses on a two-kilometre stretch of the A650 from Croft Street to Dudley Hill in Bradford, and will deliver new bus lanes, as well as upgraded facilities and extra real-time information displays at 14 bus stops. The work, funded by the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, will create a 1.7-kilometre stretch of new segregated cycle paths on Wakefield Road, provide new pedestrian and cycle crossings and includes plans to fill in a subway. [10]','Combined Authority approves extra £30m towards green infrastructure (Includes A650 Connect)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-09-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/combined-authority-approves-extra-30m-towards-green-infrastructure/','West Yorkshire Combined Authority leaders approved plans for major improvements, including the £20 million Wakefield Road Bus and Cycle Priority Corridor, bringing it closer to delivery. The scheme focuses on a 2km stretch of the A650 from Croft Street to Dudley Hill in Bradford, and will deliver new bus lanes, as well as upgraded facilities and extra real-time information displays at 14 bus stops. The work, funded by the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, will also create a 1.7-kilometre stretch of new segregated cycle paths.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('51a067ee-3396-4cd9-a56b-37b12d8753cb','infrastructure-five-towns-leisure-hub-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.669','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work will start next month on the £20.8million Five Towns Leisure and Wellbeing Hub in Pontefract Park. Planning permission has now been granted and work on site will begin in March. The hub will be the largest of its kind ever built in the Wakefield district. The flagship leisure facility is due to open in autumn 2020. [11]','New £20.8million Pontefract Park leisure centre a step closer to being built','Yorkshire Evening Post','2019-02-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFOpQBrcHVGl11J1yIgpO4cNtEGGZ3NIpmVFS7f1rDlzKjvjgYRrbupkVoA5F1Y2o1u_2qwlfB4m5VcvSMQQDmAh1g0FiZ7VhvUIbzWPOQVY316oWTI8aVonVD3KDf2gIVp04yjfiZt6DjsNdG7GL5zOay7D_FxtrtdHPAoA6zQzYDYUFJc_zO4U9pSb7S3KE829WRH7R3EonhkZK8E3vbEumtFSO8l86f-_QwVG-vhIs6MMm1AbC0xOoC0xOoC','Planning permission was granted for the £20.8 million Five Towns Leisure and Wellbeing Hub in Pontefract Park. Work was scheduled to begin in March 2019, with the facility, the largest of its kind in the Wakefield district, expected to open in autumn 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('51b29c09-3793-44c4-ad36-24257e0b0a21','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2024-10-25) First of 3,500 leaky dams installed for National Trust and Yorkshire Water joint conservation scheme in the South Pennines. ... The Landscapes for Water project is installing 3,500 leaky dams across five main areas of the South Pennines over the next four years. Landscapes for Water is a joint programme between the National Trust and Yorkshire Water that aims to restore upland landscapes across the two organisations\' landholdings in the South Pennines, specifically in the Upper Calder and Colne catchments. [20]','Leaky dams installed in landmark Natural Flood Management partnership project for South Pennines','Yorkshire Water','2024-10-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE65K1FuaS4B4lxw9cGdN5hX1S6TCmKDF4QwzCDkhBJzX98OaBi507iiuZ2wTZ2a1A5EsWF5zrvQ1XGt6hTKlnqvrxVwr4cwb05Wb062Hr1hMR5C2Q64JGtKYKQxtoZP2HBMWxA6r-mC98txg9m3Pt7VGEMJk13p1xgWxMQ0swuPAvdr8F7i4hTSNCnUYrWf2vd8TH3RFb4jKm73qYv3Y-TQ4GnS3FLxO-UMFNhrtxPawF3mT7eatKU6bf6RPf8JHomU00T6u2E7HmG4w49-B3c_Jy5w9lqTgiqMA==','The \'Landscapes for Water\' project, a collaboration between the National Trust and Yorkshire Water, commenced the installation of 3,500 leaky dams across the South Pennines, specifically within the Upper Calder and Colne catchments. These NFM measures, funded in part by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, are designed to significantly slow water flow and mitigate flood risk downstream. [20]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('51ba5dd6-18af-4af4-857e-016cb97395ed','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2023-12-12) Hundreds of Leeds tower block flats are to get cheaper heating as part of a council scheme. ... They are in Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers. ... The three tower blocks are set to receive heat from the network in the next six months. ... The new connections are expected to reduce the city\'s annual carbon footprint by 279 tonnes, supporting efforts to end the city\'s contribution to climate change by transitioning to \'net zero\' emissions.','Hundreds of tower block flats to get cheaper heating as Leeds City Council scheme extended','Yorkshire Evening Post','2023-12-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/council/hundreds-of-tower-block-flats-to-get-cheaper-heating-as-leeds-city-council-scheme-extended-4444585','The Yorkshire Evening Post reported on Leeds City Council\'s initiative to expand the Leeds PIPES district heating network to 259 council properties in Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers. The article highlighted the scheme\'s benefits, including cheaper, more reliable, and lower carbon heating, and the expected reduction in the city\'s carbon footprint.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5204ab46-391b-4f0f-a620-eecb64ca0647','infrastructure-bp-pulse-stourton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.422','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point located at Stourton Service Station, LS10 1SP is part of the BP Pulse network. There are 1 device and 2 connectors available at this charging location. ... This electric car charging point is located at 53 Pontefract Road, Leeds, LS10 1SP and it has 1 devices. This charging point is part of the BP Pulse charging network.','Stourton Service Station EV charging point, Leeds - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.zap-map.com/charge-points/stourton-service-station-leeds/','Zapmap, an EV charging point map service, confirms the Stourton Service Station charger as part of the BP Pulse network, featuring 1 device and 2 connectors, located at 53 Pontefract Road, Leeds, LS10 1SP.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('521d8648-896f-4a0d-b71d-31e976e69112','infrastructure-a660-holt-lane--otley-road-junction-improvements-adel-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.964','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Further highways work was announced for the A660 Otley Road in Adel, near the Kingsley Drive junction, starting in early 2022, including junction and footway improvements. [11]','Further Highways Work - A660, Adel','Barry Anderson (Councillor\'s website)','2021-12-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG36CbjCjZ0ohY4TBtQkqqy0InC4QaE7ggKC7_46w-ou8pZLmNSidohqx5x0lWuipyLEFO6FkWdc_4JwQYPQ7R8XZ0fQhNrJmEMzcT6peSBO3Db33ekuC7ehtyBdGjZpx9PNzH5E-R-E3kIqmgXZq2t0vaaThOlszKRRYwNq2vG9Q==','Councillor Barry Anderson provided an update on December 21, 2021, regarding upcoming highways work on Otley Road, Adel, in the vicinity of the Kingsley Drive junction, starting early 2022. This includes gas connection installation and a highways junction and footway improvement scheme related to a new Barratts housing development, indicating ongoing local road infrastructure work in Adel during the period the Holt Lane junction project was being completed.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('52969bcf-0116-470c-947d-ab4d11d9b895','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Thirteen major new Leeds City Region transport improvement schemes with an investment value of over £200 million are scheduled to get underway this financial year. Financed by the Combined Authority through the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund, projects include improvements to the Harrogate Road and New Line junction in Bradford and the next stage of work to upgrade the A629 between Halifax and Huddersfield. In Leeds, work will start on the Corridor Improvement Project at the Dyneley Arms junction. Garforth and Mytholmroyd are two of six West Yorkshire rail stations where park and ride car parks are being built or extended. And in York, the next phase of Outer Ring Road improvements will begin. [18]','WORK TO START THIS YEAR ON OVER £200 MILLION OF COMBINED AUTHORITY-BACKED, LEEDS CITY REGION TRANSPORT SCHEMES','Yorkshire Reporter','2019-06-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGMn287imlgBeP3h6kx1TIuR-txGEwpg612QMdFTqhIJ8lE9LHe2tjVlkiYeSlDCgpS03mqbZFKhJwIf4a6ySg5z0yZhC6BaUPA-O1hti5kTiSueNsVKcjeMoIfcJEwa2_pxnkLE-jPOpdPxDwOstzVFbfcxDOIjadnFoFhBsWa5A4mAJWd7ixam9FmXkm3satRrDe4FFN2FCP1ExBbVBP5rZbZHDcjOo_RoeHg79Vf2ewL4T-agVZaSA==','Thirteen major new Leeds City Region transport improvement schemes, collectively valued at over £200 million and financed by the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund, are scheduled to commence within the current financial year. Projects include enhancements to junctions in Bradford and Leeds, the next stage of A629 upgrades between Halifax and Huddersfield, and park and ride extensions at several rail stations. [18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('52b69b56-1921-4814-8db1-ed95feb7a1b3','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million funding towards mass transit and bus franchising plans. ... At a full Combined Authority meeting on September 18, West Yorkshire council leaders will hear how the extra £40 million of funding would support key works to keep the mass transit project on track for spades in the ground by 2028. ... Work is also ongoing to introduce a fully-franchised, publicly-run bus service in three phases between April 2027 and October 2028, which will apply to services running solely in West Yorkshire. [9, 10, 23]','Mass transit and bus franchising plans set to accelerate after £40m funding boost','Yorkshire Evening Post / Public Sector Executive','2025-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGAHQfOd-Bs3G2JN07OHZvZ70FNEyAPfzjtfWczczxKAwNAM7cXgTl0vA2rSTpxnY1Ug9fzGKrhO-NaBIvQKnBhFXzhNWr_m4K62GtP8I9Ab8yYGVapuQufc3zjr7PGVuHqSKLEE4aC2Se-2Wwe2EjQEXf71IZXhoquVBpD2CK8Bc4K73afNgAonvzhzwP7wZE8QdrATl0nRORofzxHE6XwImW4c9HodLOsHsQ=','Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million in funding to accelerate detailed planning and development work for both mass transit and bus franchising in West Yorkshire. This funding, to be discussed at a Combined Authority meeting on September 18, will support technical and environmental assessments for tram routes and progress the business case. The bus franchising initiative is proceeding with plans to introduce a fully-franchised network in three phases between April 2027 and October 2028, forming a key part of the integrated \'Weaver Network\'. [9, 10, 23]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('52c8b0db-6e6c-4251-a34b-230b0804b2fd','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following the completion of the Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme, an innovative wetland project commenced at Brearley Fields in April 2023. This initiative, complementing the main flood defences, aims to transform former playing fields into a wetland nature reserve to increase floodwater storage and enhance natural flood management in the area.','Brearley Fields, Mytholmroyd: An innovative wetland project to enhance naturally managed flood risk','Slow The Flow','2023-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://slowtheflow.net/project/brearley-fields-mytholmroyd/','Following the completion of the Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme, an innovative wetland project commenced at Brearley Fields in April 2023. This initiative, complementing the main flood defences, aims to transform former playing fields into a wetland nature reserve to increase floodwater storage and enhance natural flood management in the area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('52ca3d64-c13c-4b74-9a63-78b6819ce06c','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'2022-04-08T16:38:09Z. Successful Charge. E.on Drive charge points x 6.','Successful Charge at Thorpe Park Hotel & Spa, E.on Drive charge points','PlugShare','2022-04-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.plugshare.com/location/437158','A user reported a successful charge at Thorpe Park Hotel & Spa, specifically mentioning \'E.on Drive charge points x 6\'. This indicates the chargers were operational by this date.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5394330b-811b-4b2f-8edb-b2d5584e29c4','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The National Databank was set up by Virgin Media O2 and Good Things Foundation in July 2021 to provide free mobile data, texts, and calls, to help low-income people stay connected. They can access 20GB of free O2 data enough for around 220 hours of internet browsing a month. People can find their nearest National Databank Hub here. Since it was set up the National Databank has provided more than 70,000 free O2 SIM cards and 50,000 free O2 data vouchers. Virgin Media O2 has committed more than 61 million GB of free O2 data to the initiative by the end of 2025. [16]','Virgin Media O2 and Good Things Foundation launch National Databank to help tackle data poverty','Virgin Media O2 Press Release (via ISP Review and other articles)','2021-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEQtjCeuv66AB_8KlzwMivKGeWEB0fioLlH2HP8BKfCVtYBjdspeW0Knx3Ry-EeHsAlGsr2uyj94kt-Cs1DEitcuuY-gpIYXTeQ1hrHENvjEjtgEKJRzZhkh86o_2iguIRhSkNFDITLW6tn2sAk9Z-hE9wA5iJsPackhflAudIeZKOEmV6p3eM54XMyGR6Z6-IWK-mpabqzT5DZFzUhncyN5m2xaMWniPaoextZUw==','Virgin Media O2 and the charity Good Things Foundation established the National Databank in July 2021, providing free mobile data, texts, and calls to low-income individuals to help them stay connected. This initiative is a core part of Virgin Media O2\'s digital inclusion efforts, setting a precedent for community support through connectivity.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('539d54d5-254d-4db5-8fc6-f3a21047f45c','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Major housing plans for Huddersfield are moving forward as a new application is submitted for Bradley Park. The Bradley Park housing scheme is one of the largest in the council\'s Local Plan, covering the 60 hectares of land at Bradley Park Golf Course which will deliver around 2,000 homes. These include properties to be built at the privately owned Bradley Villa Farm, with this the subject of the latest planning application. Full planning permission was secured by Redrow Homes Yorkshire back in August 2023, with this allowing the construction of 277 homes and associated infrastructure at Bradley Villa Farm. As for the plans for the wider development of up to 2,000 homes, the last we reported was that Kirklees Council was focusing on the delivery of \'Phase 1\' of the scheme, which is concerned with around 500 homes. Back in March, the local authority said it hoped to begin procurement for a partner for this first phase in the middle of this year but highlighted that \'strategic issues\' relating to access need to be resolved beforehand.','New plans submitted for 277-home Huddersfield development','YorkshireLive','2025-05-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE99f5mIMluO6_0KPNYtDjxxf1hsmWuHwumO9Iq-f-KHqLvLEF_qtqHYrgf42_QfSK8Nrxz-QSUnce9VVTw0SmasDVyq1ek0DsSHxzjtmh3DoW4qksusmSmGGCqQgdxF_QwwMUfFHsD6IF7qsx1hqOEVvVue7UAmsVNUd9QXO-5qAK0S0nRROSsFGg3kAWAbzOcPiCdA-WrrQ==','New planning application was submitted for Barratt David Wilson Homes to build 277 homes at Bradley Villa Farm, which forms part of the larger Bradley Park housing scheme. This follows previous permission secured by Redrow Homes Yorkshire in August 2023 for 277 homes. Kirklees Council is reportedly focusing on delivering \'Phase 1\' of the wider scheme, comprising around 500 homes, but strategic access issues need to be resolved.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('540b1725-d1b3-4d1d-81f3-c33a1c8e6ea3','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Councillors have agreed to ramp up the pressure on transport chiefs to get the Calder Valley railway line electrified, calling it “a vital artery” for Calderdale. [12] They were unanimous in supporting a campaign with all other local and regional stakeholders to make the case for electrification, inviting businesses and public sector partners including health organisations to sign up. Calderdale councillors have also instructed Chief Executive Robin Tuddenham to write to Calderdale\'s two MPs... asking them to sign up to the campaign and lobby on its behalf. Leader of the Council, Coun Jane Scullion... is also to write to the new Secretary of State for Transport, Heidi Alexander, inviting her to visit and hear the “strong” business case for electrification of the line. [12]','Councillors to ramp up the pressure to get the Calder Valley railway line electrified','Halifax Courier','2025-02-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHgiZQ8dLjK2BTCVV10RYl_ncPaMCYqEwrtQ1VSQRM7tVTa6Zz-EwFynW9_9wqai-IK-RtlbBf5gcgOiDCl1-EL-EM-pU5-H6nvmAclOR0ykIlGaUPOXkeZF-aGW36pjWjiyoyV3czKORDTdplBpv6bHWch7ceGDrLkcwABfAl0AnaDJNN04f4FerWskHiAF_YRg8NdzeTivFpIM8vm_18e0UJeb24dNRwhPRF6GLBJiQJYAxpxyivV83X4CJxV7eeSbVgVjcJBdmI=','Calderdale councillors unanimously agreed to ramp up pressure on transport chiefs to electrify the Calder Valley railway line, calling it a \'vital artery\' for the area. They resolved to campaign with stakeholders, write to MPs, and invite the Secretary of State for Transport to visit and hear the business case for electrification.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('548e56b4-d482-4eaa-acae-7440d51e7a2a','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On March 18, 2024, the Yorkshire Post reported that Caddick Developments received unanimous approval from the Leeds City Council planning committee for a major, new, mixed-use neighbourhood in the South Bank of Leeds. Lee Savage, director at Caddick Developments, stated that \'South Village will offer a revolution in city-centre living, transforming this strategically located brownfield site into an ambitious and accessible new neighbourhood.\' [18]','Leeds South Bank set for major new 1,925 home development featuring \'village green\' commercial space','Yorkshire Post','2024-03-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/business/property/leeds-south-bank-set-for-major-new-1925-home-development-featuring-village-green-commercial-space-4559814','The Yorkshire Post covered the planning approval for the South Village development, highlighting its scale with 1,925 homes and significant commercial space, centered around a \'village green\'. Lee Savage of Caddick Developments emphasized the project\'s aim to redefine city-centre living.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('548efae9-9b8d-4691-b907-f477e414fd53','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council backed a £18 million plan by the charity Bradford Live to convert the derelict Odeon cinema into a 4,500-capacity concert hall. The council supported the plan, but Bradford Live was tasked with securing funding from private sectors and grants. The renovated venue was initially aimed to open in early 2018.','Bradford Odeon\'s £18m revamp gets council backing','The Stage','2014-12-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQET5wgMgsS28Kz1vVoc5xVICVEd9UBeSkzJ1UMwGiiaQnF6YGhDsyVFHo3ToHcdXwjyMZ29kdJfloKXax3dBNaVwNHhL1Qtml6YinXdpbbQQ568lZyr5xYg9WLzv0S-w-dyERnupuHNdpQgE7iyFsdSnLggfDfQKkAp1Vr94NqGkZ6x0_0ix9coyg==','Bradford Council backed a £18 million plan by the charity Bradford Live to convert the derelict Odeon cinema into a 4,500-capacity concert hall. The council supported the plan, but Bradford Live was tasked with securing funding from private sectors and grants. The renovated venue was initially aimed to open in early 2018.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('54bb85c0-2804-4556-aa28-5a52b2d79cd8','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2022-03-23) Woolpack Inn, Leeds charging stations for electric vehicles located in Yeadon, West Yorkshire (United Kingdom). This EV charger has 4 connectors for your electric car. ... It was added on 23/03/2022 and last updated on 14/01/2025.','Woolpack Inn, Leeds EV Charging Station Added to Electromaps','Electromaps','2022-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFykFIbYlF4pVjQCbW2LZgni-vOrN5xrnXw2YY-fKy9vq0-naSyTuQ-wy3mXp8HYIOe4CIldIxTlVLpCQ8cVUL1mkg_bpEuGjVZwZtpZo9i20Uva4XXTeDOeqUP9gEd2SRNF3xUWyCZt9KtBZfJMSacJD-MCnYDMQ5qwLCUzh39I4nrOckxRPC4fUofWUx6-BeCbBkSzcZzG0kSucOV1-mj7wrHLT5r','Electromaps listed an EV charging station at the Woolpack Inn, Leeds, located in Yeadon, West Yorkshire. The listing noted the presence of 4 fast charge connectors.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('551d6a20-93c0-434b-8425-81074bfbd402','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Transforming Cities Fund ( TCF ) is a £2.45 billion capital grant transport fund aimed at driving up productivity through investments in public and sustainable transport infrastructure in some of England\'s largest city regions. It was launched at Autumn Budget 2017 and expanded in Budget 2018. Aims of improving access to good jobs within English cities and encouraging an increase in journeys made by low-carbon and sustainable modes of transport are key objectives.','Transforming Cities Fund','GOV.UK','2018-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/transforming-cities-fund','The Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) is a £2.45 billion capital grant transport fund launched by the UK government. Its aim is to boost productivity through investments in public and sustainable transport infrastructure across England\'s largest city regions. Key objectives include improving access to jobs, encouraging low-carbon transport, tackling air pollution, and supporting housing delivery and skills investments.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('553ede8f-b4af-4c20-bcb7-2686f71d9def','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Between Tuesday 12 October and Monday 8 November 2021, Kirklees Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, sought feedback on Huddersfield Rail Station Connections. The scheme proposes a series of travel and access improvements aiming to make it easier for everyone to make their way between the railway station and the places where they live, learn, work, or visit in Huddersfield town centre. This project is being funded through the Transforming Cities Fund (TCF). The scheme forms part of the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund (TCF), a major new programme of investment to improve access to public transport, cycling and walking, whilst helping to reduce car journeys and tackle the climate emergency. Background. The Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme forms part of a wider ten-year vision for Huddersfield, to help create a thriving, modern-day, family-friendly town centre. The Huddersfield Blueprint has five key objectives: • A vibrant culture, art, leisure, and nightlife offer. • Thriving businesses. • A great place to live. • Improved access. • Enhanced public spaces. One of the six key areas earmarked for regeneration through the Huddersfield. Blueprint is \'The Station Gateway\'. At the heart of the gateway is the Grade I listed. Huddersfield Railway Station, the second busiest in West Yorkshire. In front of the station, St George\'s Square is bordered by other historic buildings, including Estate. Buildings and the George Hotel. Proposals within the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme will also help make the town centre ready for the Transpennine Route Upgrade. In the upgrade,. Network Rail plans to invest in the railway that runs through Huddersfield to Leeds,. Manchester and beyond, to improve connectivity and help support economic growth in the north of England. [13]','Huddersfield Rail Station Connections Public Consultation 2021','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-10-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/huddersfield-rail-station-connections','Kirklees Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public consultation on the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections scheme. The project, funded by the Transforming Cities Fund, aimed to gather feedback on proposals to improve travel and access for walking, cycling, and public transport between the railway station and Huddersfield town centre. The consultation ran for four weeks from October 12 to November 8, 2021, and is part of the broader Huddersfield Blueprint vision for regeneration.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('557d4099-737b-47dc-ba42-b47a93ab557b','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle (EV) charging points are set to be installed across the Wakefield district after senior councillors agreed to accept £1.5m of funding. ... Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept the grant from West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of measures designed to achieve net zero targets. ... Wakefield will receive a total £1,520,938, based on a University of Leeds study into EV charger requirements for the region.','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for more EV charging points across the district','Wakefield Express','2024-10-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/wakefield-council-to-get-ps15m-for-more-ev-charging-points-across-the-district-4826131','The Wakefield Express confirmed that Wakefield councillors agreed to accept £1.5 million in funding for the installation of more electric vehicle charging points across the district. This funding originates from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority through the LEVI scheme, supporting the wider decarbonisation goals for the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('557d9562-b3b9-4ad2-be24-335372f3b2a5','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority will consider whether to fund £13m for Phase 1 of the regeneration project being developed by ECF at its meeting on Thursday. The total cost for Phase 1 is around £33m, which includes £29.3m of Brownfield Infrastructure & Land funding that was agreed with Homes England in February. This funding, however, is dependent on investment from WYCA during Phases 1 and 2, in order to in order to \'de-risk\' the site and bring confidence to the market. The gap-funding from WYCA is intended to ensure that the entire scheme of 900 homes becomes commercially viable, although the WYCA would not be expected to invest after Phases 1 and 2. [17]','Bradford City Village goes before WYCA for funding assurance','Place Yorkshire','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.placeyorkshire.co.uk/news/bradford-city-village-goes-before-wyca-for-funding-assurance/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) considered providing £13 million in funding for Phase 1 of the Bradford City Village regeneration project. This investment, alongside £29.3 million from Homes England\'s Brownfield Infrastructure & Land funding, aims to de-risk the site and make the entire 900-home scheme commercially viable. Phase 1 will deliver 96 affordable townhouses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('559af5ed-dd62-4f8a-8597-0452fa0c2e4f','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point is located at Snowfield Avenue, Wakefield, WF1 2UZ and it has 2 devices. This charging point is part of the EV On the Move charging network. ... Snowhill Starbucks charging point ... Network: EV On the Move. Address: Snowhill Starbucks. Snowfield Avenue. Wakefield. Yorkshire and the Humber. WF1 2UZ.','Snowhill Starbucks EV charging point, Wakefield - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.zap-map.com/charge-points/snowhill-starbucks-wakefield/','Zapmap, an electric vehicle charging point mapping service, confirms the presence of an EV charging point at Snowfield Avenue, Starbucks, Wakefield, WF1 2UZ. The listing indicates that it is part of the EV On the Move network and features 2 devices. This further corroborates the availability and operational status of EV chargers at the specified Starbucks location.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('55b14cad-02c6-4fb3-b835-cff99ca1f90f','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A major £30m flood scheme to protect homes and businesses in Mytholmroyd is a step closer thanks to a decision made on 25 July by the Calderdale Flood Partnership Board. The board approved the allocation of funding for the scheme following detailed investigation work carried out by the Environment Agency to ensure the highest possible standard of flood protection for the village. The Environment Agency will now apply for planning permission and construction is expected to commence in the autumn. Following the flooding of December 2015, the Environment Agency has completed six new schemes, reducing flood risk to 500 homes as part of a £9 million recovery programme across Calderdale. In Mytholmroyd, significant work to clear the channel, repair damaged walls and make safe damaged buildings has already been carried out.','£30m Funding Approved for Mytholmroyd Flood Defence Scheme','GOV.UK - Funding announced for a major flood defence scheme to protect Mytholmroyd','2017-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH2rLHjzdQEcDRPmVfudIcZHRsGZ24lcjp8nbLRMJW8qLPHz-8pxVay9eEMZysHs1-LtN5_NfVfcJBS-4IZTkM7St9H0ZHtegTFUONfQsPpxXIMSexLGZwDzHXTQjlu8H2zpvBSrU1m2qX1f23B19l_EN_77wTTaj83g0xDHdb3Sg4ub9Z-Pek1-vzugsXpxUiXPjW3uaKohUImG2yz7fgn26v7b52Kvg==','A significant £30 million funding package was approved for a major flood defence scheme in Mytholmroyd on July 25, 2017, by the Calderdale Flood Partnership Board. The scheme aims to protect homes and businesses in the village, with construction expected to commence in autumn 2017.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('55dc5ae8-6710-4336-bb5b-fca4cf49744e','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2024-05-23) Wakefield is on the brink of a transformative journey aimed at redefining its city centre and boosting inward investment. Unveiled at the UK Real Estate Investment and Infrastructure Forum (UKREiiF), Wakefield Council\'s comprehensive plan introduces a Strategic Regeneration Partner to propel the vision and stimulate growth in Wakefield City Centre. ... The council\'s efforts are further supported by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Homes England, who have identified Wakefield City Centre as a strategic focus area. This collaboration aims to create a broader Strategic Regeneration Partnership, aligning resources and efforts to maximize the impact of the regeneration initiatives.','Transformative Journey For Wakefield City Centre','Yorkshire','2024-05-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFR9bl0lYBUrpdsKuQYTN6RBQn6PqnyVm0sIYg4cLkWNqV1nbHhkiFAxbcDNvGQvwuA_yUv5T7k1qaiWt340pTfzcB80iXuYLo1rv2U6JAPZiunVSNkv4COhHupd94Xq5TRffUXd6IRck156RUyt6rvxcNh77eWQSx4wCHzWwJVYg==','Wakefield Council announced a transformative journey for its city centre, aimed at redefining its urban landscape and boosting inward investment. Unveiled at UKREiiF, the plan involves a Strategic Regeneration Partner and is supported by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Homes England. This broader regeneration initiative encompasses improved infrastructure and urban spaces, aligning with the goals of the Transforming Cities Fund, even if not directly detailing the A61/A639 corridor works. [13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('55e38b89-6ac2-45b8-89a4-946ee286dbbc','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Leeds City Council are developing Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans for West Yorkshire. ... Phase one of the LCWIP for Leeds includes plans to improve walking in Harehills, and for cycling in north east Leeds. ... Further stakeholder engagement was undertaken in winter 2019 to get feedback on the proposals.','Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans: Leeds | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2019-09-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/cityconnect/local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-leeds/','This outlines the Phase One LCWIP for Leeds, developed by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Leeds City Council. The plan focuses on walking improvements in Harehills and cycling infrastructure in north-east Leeds, aiming to create a comprehensive network for active travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('55f179b8-7697-41a9-9631-b0563c17d65c','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Restricted 2 stage tender utilising a SSQ. The 5 best scoring tenderers will be asked to price the works. Works are Public Realm Improvements to Brighouse Town Centre to include highways works, the creation of pedestrianised areas and uplifted spaces to encourage visitors to dwell longer. Response deadline (UK time): 13/01/2025 12:00:00. [36] The contract period for these works is 2.0 years, with a start date of 10/01/2025 and an end date of 30/12/2026. [25]','Public Realm Improvements to Brighouse Town Centre tender','EU-Supply.com','2025-01-13 00:00:00.000','https://uk.eu-supply.com/app/rfq/publicpurchase_eu.asp?PID=402096&B=EUROPE','A public tender for \'Brighouse Town Investment Plan Public Realm\' works was published by the Borough Council of Calderdale, with a response deadline of January 13, 2025. These works include highways improvements, creation of pedestrianised areas, and uplifted spaces to encourage visitors to dwell longer, with a planned completion date of December 30, 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('56268e46-0ae0-4659-b5b2-44621c017ac3','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council\'s \'Transforming Cities – Wakefield city centre\' outlines plans to reduce traffic, enhance cycling and walking routes, and improve bus operations. A four-week public consultation was held from 1-28 March 2021. Furthermore, West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Wakefield Council and Leeds City Council, is investing £22.5m in the A61 and A639 roads, connecting the Wakefield District with Leeds, as part of the TCF. Initial proposals for these corridors, including dedicated bus and cycle lanes, wider pavements, and smart traffic lights, were subject to a consultation during July and August 2022. Delivery of these improvements is scheduled for 2024. [14, 19]','Wakefield City Centre and A61/A639 Corridor Improvements Consultations','Wakefield Council','2021-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH-rj5VYUTEVdjsJQNvjaCa0az8xgDURjuTQ1-Py4hvIZhnDd7bp8e2eM2N02Jsh4Ytwl8cuC44_JCpF4tnUwrDrSRMuV4ZeGMOZlT3v9OIAE5ZKsawy1mPa9BVx-cjt0AW205Mlw3YwKXPVqPnxIFA5l-db2GhThk_MWnvGkOvA-6cV6yyfDIcLwHzqsdT_U2dhH6sgONiLt7JgksF1cn8qpPw2_kzPNMp39oXymrfx1FTFQ==','Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Leeds City Council, is delivering significant Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) schemes. A £13.6 million programme is focused on transforming Wakefield city centre by reducing traffic in the Northern and Civic Quarters, enhancing cycling and walking routes (including a link between Wakefield Kirkgate Rail Station and the city centre), and improving bus access and operating conditions. A four-week public consultation on these city centre proposals was held from March 1-28, 2021. Additionally, a £22.5 million investment on the A61 and A639 corridors, connecting Wakefield with Leeds, involves bus priority measures and cycling/walking infrastructure. An initial consultation for these corridor improvements was conducted during July and August 2022, with delivery scheduled for 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5628bc75-afef-4595-9c79-45e7fca9e10f','infrastructure-normanton-golf-club-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.339','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Conveniently charge your electric vehicle at Normanton Golf Club with Wattly\'s reliable EV charging location. ... Normanton Golf Club in Stanley offers public EV charging stations that require payment at the location. The chargers available are Type 2 with a socket only and have a power output of 22 kWh. These chargers are suitable for electric vehicles that are equipped with a Type 2 charging port. Located at the golf club, these EV charging stations provide a convenient option for golfers and visitors to charge their electric vehicles while enjoying a round of golf or other activities at the club. ... *This information may not be up to date. Please check with operator.','Alfapower (UK) Normanton Golf Club WF3 4JP Public - Pay At Location EV Charger Available | Wattly Your Local Charging Community','Wattly','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGy-vG5LqWFgfhChcOqrtYZOtCXNavRG6oME32n4WK_jhvUqWdJXwMTLT1g6pIW6bwm1uU3QGIHYiOXy5Xgs_K4fTbgYCwJVlwZSccx53z6vmRX1gD5wu7rxQdgpKCSb5ayCO6A5SCX2A-u5tKGFVuQmajbdXSqIumrWfqt','Wattly confirms the availability of public EV charging stations at Normanton Golf Club, Stanley, Wakefield, WF3 4JP, under the Alfa Power network. The chargers are Type 2 with a power output of 22 kWh and support pay-at-location functionality, providing a convenient charging option for visitors.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('56312d44-fe3d-497b-ad1c-6cfab79f4324','infrastructure-moving-traffic-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.124','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In early 2026, we will bring in this type of camera enforcement at seven key locations. This initiative: aligns with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) Bus Service Improvement Plan (BSIP); and contributes to our climate and transport strategies.','Bus Lane Enforcement | Calderdale Council','Calderdale Council','2025-09-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/bus-lane-enforcement','Calderdale Council has announced plans to implement Automatic Number Plate Recognition (ANPR) camera enforcement for bus lanes at seven key locations, with this initiative expected to begin in early 2026. This measure, a form of moving traffic enforcement, aims to improve bus service reliability and journey times, aligning with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Bus Service Improvement Plan.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('568a4400-5502-4a51-9743-6330b0e218a5','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first newsletter for the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme announced that the project plans have been split into three areas (Hebden Bridge FAS, Stubbing Holme Road FAS, and Erringden Hillside FAS). It detailed planned works including raising river walls, using glass panels, installing a canal overflow, and improving surface water drainage. Construction for the main elements of the scheme was programmed to commence in Summer 2022.','Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme Newsletter - July 2021','AWS (Environment Agency Newsletter)','2021-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://environmentagency.blob.core.windows.net/portal/Hebden%20Bridge%20FAS%20-%20Newsletter%20-%20July%2021.pdf','The first newsletter for the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme announced that the project plans have been split into three areas (Hebden Bridge FAS, Stubbing Holme Road FAS, and Erringden Hillside FAS). It detailed planned works including raising river walls, using glass panels, installing a canal overflow, and improving surface water drainage. Construction for the main elements of the scheme was programmed to commence in Summer 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('56c47375-6a00-40b7-a68b-b8d46723f2a9','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Due to adverse weather conditions across the winter months, a new timeline for Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 (FAS2) works in Apperley Bridge has been formulated. ... All the civils work on the new pumping station and drainage improvements in Apperley Bridge are currently programmed to be completed by late-March 2024, with all traffic management measures to be removed, and access for road users, pedestrians, and the equestrian crossing on Harrogate Road all fully reinstated. ... Councillor Alex Ross-Shaw, Bradford Council\'s Executive Member for Regeneration, Planning and Transport said: “Although the Leeds FAS2 is a Leeds City Council scheme, the works including a new pumping station and drainage improvements, will also deliver flood risk benefits to residents in the Apperley Bridge area of the Bradford District. [9, 12]','Apperley Bridge Flood Alleviation Works Timeline Adjusted Due to Weather','Leeds Star / Leeds City Magazine','2024-03-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEeAAzOF9Q9oRJqqdawxFR0DBGxyY5LPsq8ypj9B5U76hRAkD5F6YFqgPAvp-etE7AKAnvdTF8AgDm0H9y1aQ96R4ajBIrsmJnP6dQg9tU1DMhg49dbh80hcXFldO3egyl9ExMSe7fFtI5CMpgp2jSm3S9WeTLXIFuwix72wKZJOg5ViyjKeP1-kHerk8k4IvS3LRiUmYlR2LZ2brux8csGnBXA1NTZqmlyAI','Due to adverse winter weather, the timeline for Leeds FAS2 works in Apperley Bridge was adjusted, with civils work on the new pumping station and drainage improvements programmed for completion by late March 2024. Apperley Road was expected to reopen around this time. Bradford Council confirmed the scheme would deliver flood risk benefits to residents in the Apperley Bridge area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('56deaa98-d46c-43bf-a9f6-ce9367037d33','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The former Kellingley Club site is to be transformed with the help of funding provided by the Ministry of Housing Communities and Local Government, Wakefield Council, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. A planning application to obtain permission to carry out the demolition work has been submitted, and a decision is expected 20 March 2025. If successful a planning application to carry out the new build work will be submitted later in 2025. Timeline: planning application to carry out demolition submitted – December 2024. planning decision expected – March 2025. site preparation works to begin – May 2026. demolition works to begin – Summer 2025. demolition works to complete – Late 2025. Phase 1: New Build Work to begin – 2026. (all work associated with phase 1 expected to take 12 to 18 months).','Knottingley community hub - Wakefield Council (Current Project Updates)','Wakefield Council','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGLsvy-zm9-a7ZErKhB_HbTanHckgr6SkMgkNUoE4gfoLnoEjCrQMPkIvoxoSUKhjldIcpUhOKs4p5LzW7AAX6aPAkJJesnXew9cWhRneZq8TadklMM2Zh5lNgcaJ1e4lIibt7MixKvgFmDomgmPCHxcskFdZWuRfS_w1kE8k5y96uLy4FV38SpV0L4hItze4hf4xhbddnoZk8zYxd0G_dBPTu_Xw==','This Wakefield Council webpage provides current updates and a timeline for the Knottingley Community Hub project at the former Kellingley Club site. It details phases including planning application for demolition submitted (December 2024), planning decision expected (March 2025), site preparation (May 2026), demolition (Summer-Late 2025), and new build work starting in 2026. Funding is from the Ministry of Housing Communities and Local Government, Wakefield Council, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5755ca58-47fc-44e3-9b12-28af5c503043','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BT recently announced plans to roll out its new home phone service, Digital Voice, on a region-by-region basis. Having started in the East Midlands, BT is now moving on to Yorkshire and the Humber. ... Townhall events: 2nd August, 10:00 – 15:00: Leeds, Headingley Enterprise and Arts Centre West Yorkshire, LS6 3HN. [8], [13]','BT\'s Digital Voice rolling out in Yorkshire and the Humber - BT Group Newsroom','BT Group Newsroom','2023-08-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEh_skpaUOkBLISpF2o_pciv4xgj_dcXKMW5Wxo4B6xQBTTkG8euZEz8H4yJCab-HKaYwvEWAvIkWaSJHE6_xZPwUdUSoMWjPsaMHidsWi27vLXAQ6JTG2dLuLCZfOLaoa8tBHXSTDUBIht_sAUltPj_3aNPTYrlhwnhnmJPu0hyT_8GJEFC0ciNbUNeBNAZ5ez4ytIqpKqgLrBkrI2jHjZSuJwi2DfdWzM0-4aIw==','BT announced the rollout of its Digital Voice service in Yorkshire and the Humber, following its start in the East Midlands. This industry-wide shift from analogue to digital landlines is a \'once-in-a-generation upgrade\'. A town hall event was held in Leeds as part of a regional roadshow to engage with customers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('576d8f55-5623-4806-96e0-0aadf9b8fdf1','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On 4 January 2024, a large chunk of concrete was found to have fallen from the Interchange\'s underground car park ceiling, situated directly underneath the Interchange\'s bus station. As a result, the bus station was closed on 5 January, whilst survey work was conducted to repair the affected concrete and the bus station\'s structure. [10] The bus station section of Bradford Interchange was closed in early January after concrete fell into the building\'s basement following damage thought to have been caused by “severe water ingress.” [13]','Bradford Interchange Bus Station Closure due to falling concrete','Wikipedia, Asian Standard Newspaper','2024-01-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFavqMzO5UA4LtU7PyTwW6m7i0dR99ogSBamdCqkOYCCyJOUcj7F7GA5g_aZ7t3idZsbclHW9-i1Xs48qDUvGpDeG0WZ6Nj9d01k4SwttSBfUEsBCI_CeRDfjQuZ1EaeiXf18hkhJLCQePlBIWO','On January 4, 2024, a large chunk of concrete detached and fell from the ceiling of the underground car park at Bradford Interchange. This incident, attributed to severe water ingress and structural safety concerns, led to the immediate closure of the bus station on January 5, 2024, to allow for extensive surveys and subsequent repairs. [10], [13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('58167850-9c32-4acb-891a-4952ce640667','infrastructure-moving-traffic-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.124','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Government has given powers to enforce moving traffic violations to a third tranche of 22 English highway authorities after the process was stalled in the spring. The Bus Lane Contraventions (Approved Local Authorities) (England) (Amendment) and Civil Enforcement of Moving Traffic Contraventions Designation Order 2024, designates parts of each of the 22 councils\' areas as civil enforcement areas for moving traffic contraventions.','New government rolls out moving traffic enforcement powers','Highways Magazine','2024-11-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.highwaysmagazine.co.uk/New-government-rolls-out-moving-traffic-enforcement-powers/13350','The UK Government, through a \'Bus Lane Contraventions (Approved Local Authorities) (England) (Amendment) and Civil Enforcement of Moving Traffic Contraventions Designation Order 2024\', granted powers to enforce moving traffic violations to a third tranche of 22 English highway authorities in November 2024, indicating a broader national push for local enforcement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('582abd64-5067-45f3-b285-60a7f854c08a','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Pupils returning to school in Calderdale have seen the roads around some of their schools transformed into safer spaces – supporting active travel, such as walking and cycling. After a successful trial period at schools earlier this year, Calderdale Council has introduced School Streets at nine schools in the borough. This means that the roads around the schools are only open to pedestrians and other non-motorised vehicles during term-time at the school\'s opening and closing times.','Safer streets for schools - Halifax - Calderdale Council – News Centre','Calderdale Council News Centre','2020-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/safer-streets-for-schools/','Following a successful trial in June 2020, Calderdale Council introduced School Streets at nine schools in the borough on September 11, 2020. This initiative transforms roads around schools into safer, car-free spaces during drop-off and pick-up times, promoting active travel, improving air quality, and supporting social distancing during the COVID-19 pandemic.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('586f712e-abf1-4e87-8fa6-c6a8e8b72024','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At there meeting on Wednesday (20 November 2024) senior Councillors on the Executive Board approved plans to develop the PIPES district heating scheme with a new network being created for the South Bank area of Hunslet and Holbeck. ... The new South Bank scheme will use heat from Verallia\'s glass manufacturing process in the South Bank area (formerly Allied Glass). It is anticipated that the project will heat up to 28 buildings, covering 8,000 residents in existing and new developments including those around Leeds Dock and those under construction along Sweet Street... The scheme is estimated to cost £67.1m. Of that £24.5m is being provided by central government through the Green Heat Network Fund. ... Early work is scheduled to be undertaken at Clarence Road to tie in with a Highways scheme, but the main construction work is expected to take place from 2026-28. [9]','Councillors approve plans for South Bank district heating scheme','South Leeds Life','2024-11-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEn-pOBy1ysZeX3nFoewhEGlCNJ4q_ODWmTEcpduG9GnUYRlAZXWofvz0X8mKB7uNOF7vGU8j_OXs7hVZ0X-FgUgV_BOg9mcZwzFvQbeBjKXSgaBr27wTNpAlpljj_t4bimh5CUrZPCgnCpsxWziwTCdCGMAUitSIXPick6rQa2KTOe8KC6j8TN8-ekSaVdcSnOYgwPkYzT','The Leeds City Council Executive Board approved plans on 2024-11-20 to develop a new PIPES district heating scheme for the South Bank area, specifically Hunslet and Holbeck. This new scheme will utilize heat from Verallia\'s glass manufacturing process and has secured £24.5m from the Green Heat Network Fund. Main construction is expected to take place from 2026-2028, heating up to 28 buildings and 8,000 residents.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('58a8733d-e754-4fcd-9c2c-0938b28882f9','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This evidence details the Kirklees Energy Saver Scheme (KES), a Green Deal pilot initiative launched in January 2013. It offered free energy assessments and interest-free loans or grants for homeowners to install energy-saving measures. The project involved Kirklees, Bradford, Leeds, Wakefield, and York local authorities, highlighting early regional collaboration on energy efficiency funding.','Written evidence submitted by Kirklees Council (CLC059)','Parliament UK','2014-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE-sskAVn3ClepIgFFdO9EB3w1Cev3bZWXfiOIqKNUAfRRL38hoLzNkzPYgCP0OQhAlb4KK2aiKUQCY_I0czZXLgq_gXBPi1uKkxugQeNFhqQqgM1ZwOMBLadg4KOB_qLiZuZBaomMoI2gyJlsi7kQu2zzc_WCdGtMQgLYIer4dQjIO3_vCcwYAa1mF','This evidence details the Kirklees Energy Saver Scheme (KES), a Green Deal pilot initiative launched in January 2013. It offered free energy assessments and interest-free loans or grants for homeowners to install energy-saving measures. The project involved Kirklees, Bradford, Leeds, Wakefield, and York local authorities, highlighting early regional collaboration on energy efficiency funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5904defe-4b2f-45cc-9aca-155cc1fc31df','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Today will also see the announcement that Incommunities has been selected as ECF\'s preferred funding partner to deliver the first phase of townhouses for sale and rent at Bradford City Village, subject to a final legal agreement. The more detailed plans released today show how 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses will be built on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces. Work could begin as soon as this Autumn when demolition of Oastler Market begins, with construction of the homes due to begin next Spring. [4]','\'City Village\' Bradford: New images have been released','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEdTTe0QIX69jih1df-sKMnComNnONodPn0DqnUE060Qm6N8MGK1SE0bWVpwm1EKdkspWqa6XQ0vhRGtVBH1Ap6zlQ4NPnrrzkDAjxAOfLkwJJ_Bo9ICiX5ruUouDGGt8OlieuJarUMWEHWN7nW3wFCn4X-HCiXhhy2xRkaxNATIXPE2OnDrheJCbjGOzsRZtKKF0TP6Bs0oXlo33XChErZnYys4Q=','New images for Bradford\'s \'City Village\' project were released, coinciding with the announcement that Incommunities was selected as ECF\'s preferred funding partner for the first phase of townhouses. The detailed plans showed 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site and 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site. Demolition of Oastler Market was anticipated to begin in Autumn 2025, with construction of homes starting in Spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('592acfa6-e5ae-48af-b93a-2e49a2c90dd9','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford city centre is on the brink of one of its most ambitious transformations in decades. Backed by over £40 million in funding, the City Village project will reimagine the “Top of Town” area into a thriving new neighbourhood of homes, parks, and community spaces. [6] The regeneration will unfold over a 10-year period, with demolition of outdated structures beginning later this year and construction starting next spring. [6] Funding includes £13.2 million from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and £30 million from Homes England, alongside private investment from partners including Legal & General and Muse. [6]','Bradford\'s \'City Village\': £40 Million Urban Regeneration to Create 1,000 Homes and a Greener City Centre','UK Estates','2025-09-10 00:00:00.000','https://uk-estates.com/development/bradfords-city-village-40-million-urban-regeneration-to-create-1000-homes-and-a-greener-city-centre/','Bradford\'s City Village project, backed by over £40 million in funding (including £13.2m from WYCA and £30m from Homes England), is set to begin demolition of outdated structures in Autumn 2025, with construction of the first phase of homes anticipated to start in Spring 2026. This 10-year regeneration aims to create 1,000 new homes, parks, and community spaces in the \'Top of Town\' area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('59a3d1a8-4547-4d40-ab02-af876802be1b','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Northern Gas Networks (NGN), the gas distributor for the North of England, will be carrying out essential gas network upgrade work in Heptonstall and Hebden Bridge, to ensure the continued safe and reliable supply of gas to local homes and businesses. The work will start on Monday 13th June 2022, and is expected to last for seven weeks, having been planned in collaboration with Calderdale Council. ... So engineers can carry out the work safely and efficiently, and to protect the public, traffic management measures will in place throughout the eight-week scheme. Because the work is being completed in phases, traffic management will be introduced in several locations between Heptonstall and Hebden Bridge at the same time.','Eight weeks of roadworks in Heptonstall and Hebden Bridge to carry out essential gas network upgrade','Halifax Courier / Northern Gas Networks','2022-05-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGS_PAhK_RJig2ccMk7Ulw2DX97XITuQFSyx8G9vs5rRYSQ5VgDJfTUzS_fTh1z_SzUm32t7TO07Ft5bvmZjIkovuQ7cFD9T1QtL8mK4gLbhnIPkbN8kYvf_fBM0cTF9PumxYP4vU1Fala9w8X0ESPAjWiUe1KjVKn_u9IiqrCHenCHcer3ETkpgipyL5p2pzi7H1NZld6FHLI92uIrgPlnW_YstHAKCrc00Q_Bo_0W8W7jUGUSTnpkooGM9UqSIXEqtyGqur_FoW_p8AU18SMOazACo93iJD8','Northern Gas Networks announced essential gas network upgrade work on Heptonstall Road, Heptonstall and Hebden Bridge, starting Monday 13th June 2022. These works involved significant traffic management and were planned in collaboration with Calderdale Council, impacting the local infrastructure around the junction area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5a17a086-e865-4604-b9e5-021f65a0e21b','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A series of drop-in events will be held across Bradford and Leeds, as part of a major consultation on West Yorkshire\'s plans to create a Mass Transit network. ... The events, taking place between July and September, will allow people to learn more about proposed routes for phase one of the network, which would link areas in Leeds and Bradford. ... The 11-week consultation will close on September 30, 2024. [13]','Local consultation events for Mass Transit plans in Leeds and Bradford','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-07-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/latest-news/local-consultation-events-for-mass-transit-plans-in-leeds-and-bradford/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) is holding public consultation events from July to September on proposed routes for phase one of its Mass Transit network. These routes would link areas in Leeds and Bradford, with the public having the chance to learn about and provide feedback on the \'Leeds Line\' and \'Bradford Line\' options. This shows the project is actively progressing through public engagement phases, with the consultation closing on September 30, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5a1a1200-22aa-46c8-99f5-14e1bbfe2d12','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'re delighted to receive £120,000 funding from the Local Government Association (LGA) to use digital innovation to create social care of the future. The £120,000 funding for the implementation phase will enable the prototype to be created into a working online self-service account giving service users access to their information 24/7 and ultimately more control. This will then be piloted with service users and carers in Kirklees later this year.','We have been awarded funding to bring social care into the digital age - Kirklees Together','Kirklees Together (Kirklees Council news)','2020-04-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGy4HfQeYuvoA1OLD5TCtkQ50aH2mVnXBGeQF2PKBIvtbkSkasOB5w4EkEumDTRZgF2qQj7E_XBTvU46cYOlNN6bMOgMRpgKAoVpvln1EFY_uvXloshwD33mmDCWTlJt1ydE_6pTQ5TYIxPFquo2rgF1bbEyu2YOIgygAYOFuVvjRaPxsstpppSrzF8SBLF8R6x9V5KksCO7bp1RthMrsToSIBCKrXRQ==','Kirklees Council received £120,000 in funding from the Local Government Association (LGA) under the Social Care Digital Innovation Programme. This funding was allocated to develop and pilot an online self-service account for social care users and carers in Kirklees, enhancing access to information and promoting digital engagement within social care services.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5a1df706-0e63-4c18-a9f6-d77f795b1040','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2022-05-16) The WY FLIP is a collaborative, innovative programme to reduce the impact of flooding and climate change in West Yorkshire. The Programme was launched by the region\'s five lead local flood authorities, the University of Leeds and the Environment Agency (EA) to work at catchment levels across administrative boundaries. [21]','West Yorkshire Flood Innovation Programme – Roadmap | iCASP','iCASP','2022-05-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEaaEXLybvygRK-B_xa4Hd-tB-PZGAyDFh4WEDbV1nZKHLY06fM5XjALRw5a0MIyet-PKhuDiCZEROPk381V1teSQfEpG6_fb9RYPH25E1ml5HYoB04SJrQUdmDx8odjRnO39O8zpW-uNWdRFwbxOiLf81LiTrHueMiiQbLarM3MfEYl97Mq6b0f9F_HuB9','The West Yorkshire Flood Innovation Programme (WY FLIP) was launched by five local flood authorities, the University of Leeds, and the Environment Agency. This collaborative program aims to enhance flood resilience across West Yorkshire through integrated water management and natural flood management solutions, fostering cross-sector partnerships and innovative approaches. [21]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5a3f1109-a6f5-428a-b85a-e023b3f13970','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This February marks the fifth anniversary of flooding in Calderdale caused by Storm Ciara. Calderdale Council is reflecting on the progress made to increase resilience, as well as highlighting the ongoing risks. Over the past five years, the Council and partners, including the Environment Agency, have made significant strides in supporting flood resilience and taking climate action. This has included: Securing £133 million to fund initiatives focused on strengthening defences, implementing natural flood management, improving infrastructure resilience, and building community resilience. Making significant progress on flood alleviation schemes across the borough. By 2027, seven schemes in Calderdale will protect over 1,390 properties. [14]','Hebden Bridge Web Reflects on 5 Years Since Storm Ciara and Flood Resilience Progress','Hebden Bridge Web News','2025-02-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.hebdenbridge.co.uk/news/2025/storm-ciara-five-years-on.html','On February 18, 2025, the Hebden Bridge Web reported on the fifth anniversary of Storm Ciara, reflecting on the significant strides made in flood resilience across Calderdale. The update highlighted the successful securing of £133 million to fund initiatives across defence strengthening, natural flood management, resilient infrastructure, and community resilience, with seven schemes projected to protect over 1,390 properties by 2027. [14]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5b2ca84c-c255-426b-a57c-a190d544705f','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Map of HX2 6RQ postcode. Geography: Latitude, 53.732733. Longitude, -1.941347. Easting, 403967. Northing, 426262. Railes Close in Luddendenfoot is in the Yorkshire and The Humber region of England. The postcode is within the Luddendenfoot ward/electoral division, which is in the constituency of Calder Valley. HX2 6RQ is a postcode in Railes Close located in Luddendenfoot, an area in Halifax, Calderdale, with 22 households (from Rightmove, 2025-08-05).','Area Information for Railes Close, Luddendenfoot, Halifax, HX2 6RQ','Doogal / StreetCheck','2025-08-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFcv7tFwoRtaNXezloPpkjfbrBDTb1ZHZEjbo9iPI73wF70llY2Xuer-LtnLWNd5Q-WCGVF-HiZokAmD0vE28XdUNxQ542LMsgPHNFpbAaW6HSLGaACTT1THjK7JuEqAPfbNley0Vp2tL6nxo-1uA==','This provides geographical and demographic information for the HX2 6RQ postcode, which includes Railes Close in Luddendenfoot. It confirms the location within the Luddendenfoot ward and provides precise latitude and longitude coordinates for the area where the flood alleviation scheme is being implemented.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5b5e6a12-b7bc-4e8e-8b69-61da0623bb82','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The council said the latest purchase will enable it to double the number of homes planned for its \'city village\' in the centre of Bradford from 500 to 1,000. The authority has not yet secured planning permission for the development and detailed plans for the 13-acre have yet to be drawn up. However, it said it is hoping to start demolition of the shopping centre and site preparation works in early 2024. The council said it will now work with Homes England and West Yorkshire Combined Authority to secure a private developer to make the plans a reality. [19]','Bradford council eyes 1000-home city village after buying shopping centre','Housing Today','2022-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFXLT2iudIjFrGmFgZVBvcFyKyPSczUUNhvzHAK-BP1P7MtTDkgTKqBn_Ee0MaY2ZMMAWokUoON8qjy_8gROIwX9uWqeE09D0eeI3UWJwcdNpiIAfyMCS86l1Gc','Bradford Council announced its intention to build a 1,000-home \'city village\' after completing the £15.5m purchase of the Kirkgate Shopping Centre. The plans include building homes across this site and the adjacent Oastler Shopping Centre site, both of which are to be demolished. This acquisition doubled the planned homes from 500 to 1,000 and the council aimed to start demolition and site preparation in early 2024, working with Homes England and West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5bcd995b-93f1-4cab-8d5e-b8d08c867bc4','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Floods Minister Rebecca Pow has today (Wednesday) announced the first areas to receive money from the £100 million Frequently Flooded Allowance – and many of them are in Calderdale. Areas include: Copley Village Flood Alleviation Scheme, Cottonstones in Sowerby Bridge, Railes Close, between Luddenden and Midgley.','Calderdale to receive share of £100 million Government flood fund, including Railes Close','Halifax Courier','2023-04-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF1pD-uhyYwGb80MVYA_jdfDmmkfzSMV-w9chUZvc1em3cJtrjD1Kal_ek5U-m9CYwytYY8y_tBjDcpSgXhUmwfuAVrNshKicMxH9jdvM45Zx_RkihMbmgTgIHTR6qxA7qC3snFlQaPQZ3n0Xg5Y1Rz2G9ePSNs5S2BBX23nGkOOzXbc-S13WIHafZRXf0PVvrwxtJaxasBt2bPmjsbPwSTT_g31ggquhZjARogY-FR-QTRyaXE6tb-h8flNl8iTIwhEvZOdkrluk7ychiUzy39GwGxZ4gJpTZH7ciRbcUO5l4ZJyRED-ta','A Government announcement confirmed that several Calderdale towns and villages, including Railes Close between Luddenden and Midgley, would receive a share of a new £100 million \'Frequently Flooded Allowance\'. This funding aims to protect communities where properties have experienced repeated flooding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5be866c7-2fd0-4cea-9d55-1b24da1fda7a','infrastructure-frizinghall-station-revitalization',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.032','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Frizinghall railway station is situated in the Frizinghall district of Bradford, West Yorkshire, England. It is an unstaffed halt on the Airedale Line, 2 miles (3 km) north of Bradford Forster Square... The current station, opened on 7 September 1987, has its two platforms separated... Indeed, it was an English teacher at Bradford Grammar School, Dr Robin Sisson, who actively fought for the Frizinghall station to reopen. Sisson was killed in a car accident in Sheffield on 24 June 2008.','Frizinghall railway station - Wikipedia','Wikipedia','1987-09-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGGCdrIjD_VnT1jotN6nUTmaBQjbucAX_UX1eVnnJr2zb5wUhk4QUPTBWmB96EFhyGCVJDYvdSv1MFxMymRTZkgTrSw8Mn92yT13IFsoRzcVW8O7XkC8sPo2EeawKmC6-haAVY842seBR9tvWPCpXqoOKLuqA==','This Wikipedia entry details the history of Frizinghall railway station, including its original opening in 1875, closure in 1965, and significant reopening on September 7, 1987. It highlights that the reopening was influenced by efforts, including those of an English teacher from Bradford Grammar School, demonstrating early community involvement in the station\'s existence and \'revitalization\' after closure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5c1710fe-8a14-473e-8619-ce4ef2ad13fd','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The value of the program There\'s approximately 200 to 250 million pounds worth of investment. so post 2015. and the 2020 flooding the government provided significant amount of funding support to support this program of works. [22] We\'re into Hebd bridge now so this is a stubbing home road flood alleviation. um suffers from significant flood. risk um from both the river CER. and the Rodale. Canal. it aim this project aims to better protect 36 properties. [22] The detail design for the fyville scheme for the river cauldron and he water is now complete and we are progressing towards the outline. the full business. case. [22]','Calderdale Flood Recovery & Resilience Programme Board Meeting Updates on Investment and Projects','Calderdale Council (YouTube)','2024-10-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Qx4Q51W23A','During a Calderdale Flood Recovery & Resilience Programme Board meeting on October 3, 2024, discussions highlighted approximately £200-250 million worth of investment secured for flood recovery and resilience efforts since the 2015 and 2020 flood events. Updates were provided on ongoing schemes, including the Stubbing Home Road Flood Alleviation and the Hebden Bridge scheme, with a focus on incorporating environmental act requirements and property flood resilience measures. [22]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5c33b0df-9997-46ec-83b5-b3fdb6e0b4f4','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds property developer CEG\'s surprise announcement on Wednesday that it had agreed terms to buy the Grade One listed building. The privately-owned former flax mill, on Marshall Street in Holbeck, had been due to be one of the lots at an auction at Leeds United\'s Elland Road ground yesterday. [4]','CEG acquires historic Grade I listed Temple Works in Leeds','Yorkshire Evening Post / CEG','2017-12-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/historic-temple-works-in-leeds-could-be-centrepiece-of-south-bank-regeneration-1-8902507','CEG agreed terms to purchase the Grade I listed Temple Works building in Holbeck, Leeds, which would become a centrepiece of the South Bank regeneration.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5c526585-2fce-4357-bda2-194e59096d85','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority will consider whether to fund £13m for Phase 1 of the regeneration project being developed by ECF. The total cost for Phase 1 is around £33m, which includes £29.3m of Brownfield Infrastructure & Land funding that was agreed with Homes England in February. Phase 1 will deliver 96 affordable town houses on Chain Street and Oastler, while Phase 2 will consist of 174 BTR apartments on Kirkgate. The City Village is a 61-acre development to the north of Centenary Square with proposed development on three sites: Kirkgate, Oastler, and land at Chain Street, all of which is owned by Bradford Council, to deliver approximately 900 homes in the city centre.','Bradford City Village goes before WYCA for funding assurance','Place Yorkshire','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQErFcrOU9yAYcOlDtKDIu1AmWVNtHNxzNJuX6PCBD5OE-Ocehgkm2GnqLR-DBQsI0s4gQG48kR2OYc257IpTH5sQu1OY71D3DWb31jhg7-qRftLVARjDLNLwcCVuMIofyRXxWKLI4tkKIrerMNp4nS9iUxSRiE5wl252W0Sff-eNa0tU3elgTnIcZwWmO8lu3oaJPH1XCOrMlI','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) considered providing £13 million in funding for Phase 1 of the Bradford City Village project. This funding, alongside a £29.3 million grant from Homes England, aims to de-risk the site and ensure the commercial viability of the entire scheme, which includes approximately 900 homes. Phase 2 of the development is noted to consist of 174 BTR (Build to Rent) apartments on the Kirkgate site, differing slightly from the approximate 400 apartments mentioned in other documents, possibly indicating evolving plans or sub-phases.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5c93f0a4-920e-40ea-8251-0810b3dfd38b','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On Thursday, members of West Yorkshire Combined Authority voted to support plans to move forward with franchising the region\'s bus services – a move that will give the Authority a say over where and when buses run. ... A report to the committee revealed that West Yorkshire would be divided into nine zones, with different “rounds” of franchising. The first round – and the first areas to get franchised buses, will be the Heavy Woolen area, Kirklees and West Leeds/Ilkley. The second round will include Five Towns, the remainder of Leeds and Wakefield. The final round will include Bradford, Calderdale and Keighley. ... If these negotiations fail, the Authority could force the sale of the depots through compulsory purchase orders. [24]','Bus companies could be forced to sell West Yorkshire depots','Ilkley Gazette','2025-07-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHWd7j94BNKH7INhpjQY5TP0Bv9Am3SK_I3eAFwF8bVRIiW152BfdkJVUXDeNGgNvzpo2L-_ijlikCuxiSuyXNDm5bZ5yFD0p2Y9JLnPJ7siuYxMpFYAC0XPDbI3Cq1EvdPQLkw4g4JTMgeyzYx1_QvH2QhU7_nqvXAOP1XkG6xwLY-5J8DZQGP8yWhUVvvnbyYkUcLAuC2Lw==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) supported plans to move forward with bus franchising, including negotiations to purchase bus depots. If negotiations fail, WYCA may use compulsory purchase orders to secure control of these critical assets, which are essential for operators to bid for contracts. The phased rollout of the Weaver Network was detailed: Round 1 will include the Heavy Woollen area, Kirklees, and West Leeds/Ilkley in 2027. Round 2 will cover Five Towns, the remainder of Leeds, and Wakefield. Bradford, Calderdale, and Keighley will be part of the final round. [24]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5cc85748-7cd8-4067-9399-e30734d8b1dc','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'McLaren has submitted plans for Wellington Square, a mixed-use development of build-to-rent homes and commercial space on Wellington Street and Lisbon Street in Leeds City Centre. The new mixed-use neighbourhood, designed by Glenn Howells Architects, will create a gateway to the West End of Leeds. The plans will transform the 2.47 acre site into a thriving urban quarter, bringing forward high-quality new homes and best-in-class innovative workspace, in the heart of the city\'s professional core and within Leeds City Council\'s Innovation Arc vision, establishing the area as a world-class hub for research and innovation. The plans see McLaren Living deliver 464 build-to-rent homes in a striking 45-storey building while McLaren Property will bring forward 364,000 sq ft of commercial space across two 14 and 15 storey buildings. Placemaking is key to the Wellington Square proposals, with a new public square set to be delivered at the heart of the scheme. ...The build-to rent phase will have residential amenity on the ground and first floor, as well as a sky lounge with panoramic views from the 45th floor along with flexible ground floor uses to activate the public realm and new public space. The office buildings aspire to set new standards for workspace in the region ... The plans will deliver high quality, sustainable and energy efficient office buildings through design and construction, targeting the highest standards such as BREEAM outstanding and Nabers 6*.','McLaren submits plans for Wellington Square, Leeds','McLaren Property','2023-02-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHZtlkwTj7PqCG9LP3AjVZfzg77F0FdOorRB25-qtIp3d0bC-0Hhz-LMNt3T7BxzSVDkWkUHJrLTid2TJKHwnjN8UFcx7XoAp_kMckVPtKn-YbzS8YjB10Jv8N8VJ5zgvXRatXIFiHlUQVKef1RoCd53PjlQhGlg8d6e3sRSdS7sLuH2yDbmhOoiT8v6MCL4kOxZV38_Mjf','McLaren officially submitted plans to Leeds City Council for the Wellington Square development, a mixed-use scheme on Wellington Street and Lisbon Street. The proposal included a 45-storey building with 464 build-to-rent homes and two commercial buildings of 14 and 15 storeys offering 364,000 sq ft of office space. Placemaking and sustainability were highlighted as core to the design by Glenn Howells Architects, aiming for BREEAM Outstanding and NABERS 6* ratings. [16]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5cea7a65-191a-4d44-8ec1-860a30535d4c','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'An initiative to install 88 rapid chargepoints across West Yorkshire is a partnership between West Yorkshire Combined Authority, ENGIE and district councils. The £3 million programme is the result of a successful bid for £1.98 million funding from the Government\'s Office for Low Emission Vehicles (OLEV). ree. The Combined Authority and the partnering local authorities are also providing a further £1.2million of match funding for the scheme. Leeds-based ENGIE was appointed to install, own and operate the new charging points, which will result in West Yorkshire having 88 of around 500 rapid vehicle charging points across the country. Combined Authority Transport Chair Cllr Kim Groves has welcomed the installation of the first rapid electric vehicle charging points in the Wakefield district as part of its programme to provide a network of 88 rapid chargepoints across West Yorkshire. Normanton\'s West Street car park is the location of the first new rapid charging point, powered by 100% renewable energy, with a second coming online at High Street car park in Horbury, from the end of November. Each chargepoint will have two parking bays for electric vehicles, with one dedicated for hackney carriage and private hire vehicles in order to encourage a growth in the number of electric vehicles in the taxi sector. The rapid chargepoints typically take under an hour to provide a full vehicle charge depending on your vehicle, with the benefit of electricity provided free of charge until 29 October 2021. Cllr Groves said: “I am pleased to see the roll out of what will be a network of 88 rapid chargepoints across West Yorkshire continuing here in Wakefield today. “Each site has two bays, one of which is exclusively for taxis and private hire vehicles and it is forecast that around 500 diesel taxis and private hire cars will convert to hybrid and pure electric vehicles as a result of this programme.','First electric vehicle rapid chargepoints going live in the Wakefield district','TaxiPoint','2019-11-18 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFeQhz44qUHA1YwA6MjsxtmoprvuJJpFcnQywZxoEPoOqUOk_karLeqT1OS4A-C-4HzTSRZyl5UtYrSa1AAEbfLnSVLfqqpfBlE2fOJ8aVX0IW74BS4oTnbOy3Nl0ahiHUTzEDSJU2bortOGF1aozzTcgi9xcBu3eRxczniKwA-0sIe1awro2rB6ZSlnE4Wm-6cQRktdaPX1MtapMKpDv3eRT-Ca4PBhaYeag==','This article announces the installation of the first rapid electric vehicle charging points in the Wakefield district, specifically at Normanton\'s West Street car park and High Street car park in Horbury. This was part of a broader £3 million program by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with ENGIE and district councils, to install 88 rapid chargepoints across West Yorkshire, funded by £1.98 million from the Government\'s Office for Low Emission Vehicles (OLEV) and £1.2 million match funding. Each chargepoint has two parking bays, one dedicated for taxis and private hire vehicles.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5cf1d8bd-2cd9-4af3-87a3-9fe94d8dbe2e','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On August 8, 2025, it was reported that the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) had approved schemes for a £12.8 million funding boost from Active Travel England. These schemes will benefit Calderdale by making streets around schools safer, with improvements near Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax, and by enhancing the Rochdale Canal towpath in Walsden. [9, 11]','Calderdale projects to boost walking, wheeling and cycling take a step forward with £12.8 million funding','Halifax Courier','2025-08-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEzs3ksHRKGxROaGXqa8bb8IAvUYHKomiEtWz4sJ0IKulzF0UWltmQZo4CLp686DKoBTvwBk9GfL_zN3T3Hb5OIk0lKRwojWPgtwCZkLGl5mb6lzaSiEQXZkFhmgFXqy8-_PavVDD3UD7T-fiEqXdKN2SbYokDEfRFZym95ykc0pNa72wWLb9HlkKRQqYhJZ9-aqzgt66ZN3k2fLZv4BMkSPw2KGbFt2N7eFpi8mK2PmTdtHk8bXr0jRDgkPQ4-kC8N','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) approved schemes to be funded by a recent £12.8 million boost from Active Travel England. This funding will support projects in Calderdale, including making streets around schools safer (e.g., near Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax) and improving the Rochdale Canal towpath in Walsden.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5d6a13fd-7041-44b2-9379-7e0a0ffd7a29','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Coalfields Regeneration Trust (CRT) has announced the development of a new community hub at Hill Top in Knottingley, due to open in the New Year. The new facility will offer local people access to one to one support from coaches who can offer nutrition advice, improve skills, support with anxiety and depression, help to manage long term health conditions and exercise classes through the Coalfields Regeneration Trust\'s CRT Engage programme. An internal refurbishment programme of the building is due to begin in October and will last for several months before opening it\'s doors to the Knottingley community next year.','Coalfields Regeneration Trust to Open New Community Hub in Knottingley','Wakefield Express','2025-08-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGsw0BeVICaWn3feIN7IyjHUTBEF6Ki3EutXvLw4P0UJD8F4qDHmeomuIWzo0RerC71tpheyA5xZZ_m8716diScVk92LRNgll4kABpd2isNTt8AZnTgWd8FKNjheJebfpZfTtx7xdRv_hP-Xpt5vyBOI4AYpBF1rxxcQVvG-d17RA3wYP1lsUlOE1qCf07rGqeYnUmsLKeXDF_JvpBFkvHoj2i0rk7t48_oiA=','An announcement regarding the development of the \'CRT Knottingley Hub\' by the Coalfields Regeneration Trust at Hill Top, Knottingley. The facility is expected to open in early 2026, with internal refurbishment commencing in October. It will offer one-to-one support, health advice, and exercise classes as part of the CRT Engage programme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5d86880d-6fd5-4ed8-9750-dd065aad6c52','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A major £30m flood scheme to protect homes and businesses in Mytholmroyd is a step closer thanks to a decision made on 25 July by the Calderdale Flood Partnership Board. The board approved the allocation of funding for the scheme following detailed investigation work carried out by the Environment Agency to ensure the highest possible standard of flood protection for the village. The Environment Agency will now apply for planning permission and construction is expected to commence in the autumn. [23]','Major £30m Mytholmroyd Flood Scheme Funding Approved','GOV.UK (Environment Agency news)','2017-07-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/funding-announced-for-a-major-flood-defence-scheme-to-protect-mytholmroyd','A substantial £30 million flood alleviation scheme for Mytholmroyd received funding approval from the Calderdale Flood Partnership Board on July 25, 2017. This project, led by the Environment Agency in collaboration with Calderdale Council and the local community, aims to provide high-standard flood protection for the village following the devastating December 2015 floods. Construction was expected to commence in the autumn. [23]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5daf2c86-93a4-4505-a97c-1242b36c5495','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A blog post by Kirklees Council\'s IT Change Manager, dated September 25, 2024, describes the successful deployment of over 1,500 ChromeOS devices to enhance digital inclusion. These devices are available in digital hubs across various council buildings and through loaner programs, allowing residents to access technology for education, job searching, and social connection, demonstrating the impact of investments in digital infrastructure and equipment.','How Kirklees Council brought digital inclusion to its communities with ChromeOS','Google (via Kirklees Council IT Change Manager)','2024-09-25 00:00:00.000','https://cloud.google.com/customers/kirklees-council','Charles Crossland, IT Change Manager for Kirklees Council, detailed how the council used ChromeOS devices to expand digital outreach. Over 1,500 ChromeOS devices are now used in public digital hubs (libraries, courthouses) and through loaner programmes, significantly increasing digital access for residents and supporting digital inclusion initiatives.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5dcd1b1d-ef26-4813-8821-885f9c9b280f','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority has secured £746,000 in funding to create a digital inclusion programme that will help people and communities across the region. The programme will use our community-based approach to digital inclusion as the template to develop local digital inclusion initiatives in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees and Wakefield. Programme activity is expected to start in April 2024.','Digital Inclusion West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHS_5ZcKdsNIwbPuJ9oI1TK4IVE0IEomHnDd3IzjO-yzJZBanUQZ1WH0PAEEEaVtdl3ehQwJDf1ZOxX_OPtIBdZD6BRMGyPEVkMEciG3FM8gEW6IYyBkcMjKD97j0QmQNhzw-Jav27z4jmKTCPNTH27bN_Rt-I_lDz60ulFq8MN7Kc_aVGw4eKpJOnpMICFyZdSVTVKEOs==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority secured £746,000 in funding for a new \'Digital Inclusion West Yorkshire\' programme. This initiative, building on the successful \'100% Digital Leeds\' model, aims to launch local digital inclusion efforts in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield, with programme activity expected to commence in April 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5de99b93-a597-4632-bcc6-ba82b299f782','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-star-multi-academy-trust-monk-fryston-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.364','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme opened for applications on 6 October 2021 and closed on 3 November 2021. The Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme provided £553m in government grants to 160 public sector organisations across the country to install 217 clean heat and energy efficiency projects. It will provide £1.425b of grant funding over the financial years 2022/2023 to 2024/2025.','Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme Phase 3a: Application Window Closes','GOV.UK / Salix Finance','2021-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-phase-3/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-grant-recipients','Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme, which provided £553 million in government grants for public sector organisations to install clean heat and energy efficiency projects, closed for applications. This scheme aimed to fund heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures over the financial years 2022/23 to 2024/25.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5df11d02-db34-4fc1-a8a2-daaa2312d4ca','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield residents will be able to benefit from support to improve home energy efficiency, thanks to a funding boost from the council. Homeowners are being given the opportunity to make their properties warmer, more energy efficient and save money on their bills, at no cost to them. Wakefield Council has £1.5million to spend on installing a variety of measures in homes that are eligible under the Home Upgrade Grant scheme. Free insulation, air source heat pumps or other forms of electric heating are available, along with energy efficient light bulbs and solar panels. Eligible homeowners in Wakefield will be able to apply for a grant to improve the energy efficiency of their home. Funding for 35 households for this year and 40 households for 2024, allocated on a first come, first served basis. Interested residents are urged to apply now.','Find out how Wakefield homeowners can apply for funding to get free insulation, solar panels and electric heating upgrades','Wakefield Express','2023-08-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE7MwJqlnLOqYwpKpjaZ2fICmlJH2ePZ2AaOwakWqTnE9WFM8Sm4sexuKldZYo0o5hDw8ey-TF51fVJJXXWHQ68wbN31kJ-V5AOsCaTlBE7W39D-gEPNV_bVxLsCEzoGQ1moOCQ5f85GywwdhzUyEtmy_n7Z_1DB-YHd4kcSwLI--Du0Rc-G3aXszdQiTgFLJ6mxAzzPT3JmTmqIc3uKCz3wOEH4tOnyIACz7VF6F_ZpLhPn2klzjfFxVgGJp6r5ZTwcOZ-_7hHSjHrHea9sbBEJugqlllZNMINr01GJY8JMTeRAwnbDOcuKFAszg==','This news article details a £1.5 million funding boost from Wakefield Council for home energy efficiency improvements under the \'Home Upgrade Grant scheme\'. It offers free insulation, solar panels, and air source heat pumps to eligible homeowners who do not use mains gas, have a low household income, and an EPC rating of D-G. The article mentions funding for 35 households for 2023 and 40 for 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5e0aa028-ce5b-4897-b81b-5c884baeb0c3','infrastructure-bp-pulse-stourton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.422','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'bp pulse is the most utilized electric vehicle charging operator in the UK with one of the leading ultra-fast and rapid public EV charging networks. Globally, bp pulse is expanding its network of high-speed charging for cars, light commercial vehicles, and trucks, supporting bp\'s ambition to be a net zero company by 2050, or sooner. bp is backing Britain with plans to invest up to £18 billion in the UK energy system by 2030. This includes up to £1 billion for EV charging infrastructure – a step forward towards bp\'s global ambition of having more than 100,000 chargers installed worldwide by 2030.','Sparking change: M&S and bp pulse to bring EV charging to customers (Broader Context)','BP News and insights','2022-12-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.bp.com/en_gb/united-kingdom/home/news/press-releases/sparking-change-m-and-s-and-bp-pulse-to-bring-ev-charging-to-customers.html','This press release details BP Pulse\'s broader commitment to expanding its UK charging network, including plans to invest £1 billion in EV infrastructure by 2030 and installing charge points at M&S stores. While not directly about Stourton, it contextualizes BP Pulse\'s strategic expansion in the UK.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5e261ce9-856b-4704-a3ea-0a848051813e','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A raft of car parking charge increases will be introduced in Calderdale after senior councillors approved pricing changes amid a bitter backlash from residents, businesses and political opponents. ... This seemed to refer to the issue of residents parking permits, which had been proposed to be £30 for a first permit (up from £25), £60 for a second permit and £90 for a third permit. Coun Lynn said these would be amended to £30 for a first permit, £40 for a second permit and £60 for a third permit. ... To make the changes, there will be £64,000 capital costs involved but income from charges is expected to £441,000 annually plus another £30,000 from residents\' and visitors\' permits.','Furious backlash as Calderdale councillors give go-ahead to car parking charge changes across district - Halifax Courier','Halifax Courier','2023-06-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFmR-2mAxCZ3bu4qiKIqrn3mwDnBvKPeTtvo_Kdp0MH13tPVebGp3WIR9IOjax_e0H6wUY2vO0TVey3GHHcfpbyU8pz6pjW_srPfNASN9RKY4InVohFjCCTvOM9AEAxkC8j2fjvj9lmcSsElgHiQuSKoBaIyEpm-w==&docid=4132338240406859737&q=Calderdale+Council+resident+parking+scheme+consultation','This news article reports on the approval of car parking charge increases by Calderdale councillors, including changes to resident parking permit fees. The first permit increased to £30 (from £25), the second to £40, and the third to £60. The article mentions capital costs of £64,000 for these changes and anticipated annual income from charges, including residents\' and visitors\' permits.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5e56097e-3c82-4433-a17f-1cf9d8697a0d','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council announced a public information event held on September 20, 2018. This event was designed to update the community on the progress of the £30 million scheme, which was expected to be completed by Winter 2019. Works highlighted included new flood walls, the relocation of Caldene Bridge, and river channel widening.','Drop in to find out about construction of Mytholmroyd flood defences','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2018-09-10 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/drop-in-to-find-out-about-construction-of-mytholmroyd-flood-defences/','Calderdale Council announced a public information event held on September 20, 2018. This event was designed to update the community on the progress of the £30 million scheme, which was expected to be completed by Winter 2019. Works highlighted included new flood walls, the relocation of Caldene Bridge, and river channel widening.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5e64bc5b-b472-43a1-b320-0b46430e2d4c','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The following information was presented between 22 June - 18 August 2022. UPDATE: Our consultation has been extended and will now open until 11.59pm on Thursday 18 August 2022. Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is looking to make it easier to walk, cycle and use public transport in the city centre. This is the second round of consultation and we would like your feedback on the updated proposed plans. [2] The plans will reshape Bradford city centre by improving walking and cycling routes, removing traffic from some roads and introducing new green outdoor spaces for people to enjoy. Providing an accessible, attractive and cleaner alternative to car journeys is at the heart of the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund (TCF). [2]','Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements: Second Round Public Consultation','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-06-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/bradford-city-centre-walking-cycling-improvements','A second round of public consultation for the Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme was held between June 22 and August 18, 2022. This consultation presented updated proposed plans, incorporating feedback from the first round, with the aim of reshaping Bradford city centre through improved walking and cycling routes, traffic removal from certain roads, and the introduction of new green outdoor spaces. The project is funded by the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5e75d249-c50c-4e2a-a60b-f160ca012f40','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority, made up of representatives from local councils, has proposed a number of major road and infrastructure schemes across the region in thecoming years. At a meeting early in December, members will likely be asked to push ahead with two Bradford schemes. ... The Bradford Interchange Carriageway Works is a major scheme to repair and refurbish the bus carriageways at Bradford Interchange Station in the citycentre.','Road widening scheme and bus carriageway works to be discussed','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2019-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGP9gh6W7RnKnORUkV4UjzZdfv7QEDU21dvy7r9RKObM0xQ8l2slOC9N4DqRCiPTcBdiS8auwSJtW0vMHsS5K0wmC72ktTNFRMGyFHB2-4qPjl3iXSocEu0hudteg1rGCv1Gn8LBJJWB4IjZDqKxDVuaic3nJfvN_xzMSpOBy2mHc6pJN9cRtVAjslWLPMSPhTuiJhNfGqfEBwVWUuquehGbJLOWgg=','West Yorkshire Combined Authority proposed major road and infrastructure schemes, including the \'Bradford Interchange Carriageway Works\' for essential repairs, renewal, and resurfacing of bus carriageways. The work would be phased to keep the bus station operational and was set for discussion at a December meeting of the West Yorkshire and York Investment Committee. [6]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5edc25b7-b469-4a8a-8114-7433ade2aadf','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---ling-bob-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.178','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Proposals to reduce traffic and build a safe and healthy environment for people of all ages to walk, cycle, rest and play in the streets around Ling Bob and Christ Church Schools. Funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Active Travel England. Current status. Concept In Progress. Development Pending. Construction Pending. Evaluation Pending. ... May 2022. [10]','Pellon routes to school - Project Page: Concept In Progress','Calderdale Next Chapter','2022-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/projects/pellon-routes-to-school/','This project page introduces proposals to reduce traffic and create a safer, healthier environment for active travel around Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Pellon, Halifax. It indicates that the project is funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Active Travel England, with a \'Concept In Progress\' status starting around May 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5efe0b75-9ef5-4243-9b34-435bef5186db','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council has just announced that it has bought the almost 50-year-old shopping centre for £15.5m with a view to demolishing it in the coming years as part of its long-standing plans to create a “city village.” Once the brutalist Kirkgate Centre is flattened, its place will be taken by a green space, housing and small commercial spaces. The planned City Village will have up to 1,000 homes, and will include the Kirkgate site, Oastler site and Chain Street. This move will enable the council to double the size of City Village.','Bradford Council purchases Kirkgate Shopping Centre for £15.5m to build \'city village\'','Asian Standard Newspaper, UKREiiF, Show House, Inside Housing','2022-09-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQECHS6jyWBPO6boV4XLHuJivhaSznHiMPYKhiw43cxDvYxZsGD3xvl9qvP3SnkJRMSeryCcp_KpZ_gnkkhcnNwquwuRpCzp7DEENX7JBXtJjEYdFi-0r-tE_rgUAdasN3XpXjA5O7a5Wkc3Y0gd9y0V51eeZTE4Ih_V8VLNYoDfPxpFrfIfCmL9yCCiqG3A0oEv9s9kd1-uEb5OeeGb6S9zZdIs9cXIIXzxIcaWSSXflBTvFFB9K8BSbmNWaGGNOVc, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHYHThezgMWAZ2Cm8s9VA_bKlSubKUKJN_3ndz1w65rNMucdlEYadRV6ovG9fDlqCS1eYYmRaPE07fQRZjJy4OlN-kS2jGhY2hDK7zbx4V3JzlQFfNNhuOBgJY2EY_wOYgLws16y4rZzCJlo2DR_MpexdDd-1mImCpWnmBCew, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG6inI3yifUyIU3FjPooRbyjHS5oFfYF4OKN7EtOfnI2n5AHHuNLCK4BMn84AkGLoz7C7kgBpYwvRDsONaeH-ZrY2hnlLyZB0Ph3geuV6R2mpPUa3TwrWrnVMI2MbQWt1euYNbS_hO-Y-JZPov8BG_SGzrvpoCiH9GqroDhKM2d-IIu0dTGcuPD5r3eVnV4Vu8K_ETzZ4nnYF20z4-Iw1hOD_L11JTgThBJGH1-6YVctwB7OzFv_EKZnJX2Usw, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEPRkmsq6LCei2vEUJgRKSGhavunjcGiqjuEFp5NJhgmgCWyffZLo68SC6bMM9GH5CkcxsHTrZjbIL1Dm0r122c_lsBof0EFtJx5H8HrUsjiUmpcbWuLGhowYZ9AbWBgqL1C0kqpqlm44s3hqEeG1Hss7Jmpl6MbVl8CjJ4NzvX0WOgLWan-FI0TYU6pZat78kCJLT7sMOlRllmfuNtxiAqKog','Bradford Council announced the purchase of the Kirkgate Shopping Centre for £15.5 million. This acquisition is a foundational step for the \'City Village\' plan, which involves demolishing the almost 50-year-old shopping centre to make way for a new urban village, including housing and green spaces. The move is intended to address a shortage of quality housing and reshape the city centre. Primark, a key tenant, will relocate.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5f50334e-8f9f-4a5f-84a4-7eb0aba38378','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Another 15 School Streets are to be introduced across West Yorkshire, funded by Active Travel England (ATE). This will add to the 33 School Streets implemented in the region since 2019. Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin said the schemes will help make school journeys safer, healthier and more enjoyable. Another compelling reason for more School Streets is they would help improve air quality.','More School Streets to be rolled out across West Yorkshire','TransportXtra','2024-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEiLPkFp80Sm-k6xTFqlxSewec1_rRICBavx4m2tKDa7jphvzsCa1Ke5mhe8uXIOpB6c0tVKPWvZkuPrIO_VycRbywGsRZs6-Dm2DX_AakfR_EAM62pCm0e9Rpro399QLMTyM4PJr7YIrev_gzrEvP9pyPjvgfO8uhXTVKbMMSWKJF9v9o5kCNyQH_IgVg5f0_jrHydFl6Bm_qBFcLQat0CG_owXMpjsLEvbbcMgebh4MF2PS1TgD-6wqesPgnME7ALCgo==','TransportXtra reported that another 15 School Streets were to be introduced across West Yorkshire, funded by Active Travel England, adding to the 33 already implemented since 2019. West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin emphasized that these schemes aim to make school journeys safer, healthier, and more enjoyable, encouraging active travel and improving air quality.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5f56fd0c-e1a5-43eb-84a3-dc8e2c282431','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Community Shop Knottingley will provide eligible members of the local community with access to high-quality, low-cost food and household products, as well as giving wrap-around support through its life-changing personal development programmes that deliver real change for individuals and communities. The store, which is being opened thanks to the support of long-standing partner, The Coalfields Regeneration Trust, will be located on Hill Top on Pontefract Road in Knottingley (WF11 8EE) and will open to members on 15th December. Community Shop Knottingley is also supported Coca Cola Europacific Partners, Ocado, Bakkavor, Wakefield Council and WDH who have generously provided funding to help kick-start the new store.','Community Shop expands with Knottingley store set to open','Company Shop Group','2021-11-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFGw51I9W35JyoQVOkhUDbUXxSEYvWBiPRJ8q2W26yf0etkY4eRs1aj0hn1R3GrYxASHbkFIXXGOM4YAPEubyXFLKcbgVaNUZ2U6xOPY-WurW-x2biKTOwf5-FPMtNuZaRySsXHKqTsaQTD5RpXK29E2PNLo5jSFAXdATwGso5wxkwRQwpeiYiyRnc6GoT6GS1O1VAlfWgwGd6pCe0=','Announcement of the opening of Community Shop Knottingley, located at Hill Top on Pontefract Road, on December 15th. This social supermarket provides high-quality, low-cost food and household products to eligible members, alongside a Community Hub offering personal development programmes. It is supported by the Coalfields Regeneration Trust and Wakefield Council.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5f87992b-33d7-40dd-b538-8ad22e77baca','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Final approval has been given for a flooding alleviation project in Halifax. ... They also heard work on the £19m Brighouse scheme was now underway. The town\'s two parks in which flood water storage areas are being created – Wellholme Park and Whinney Hill park – should see work there completed by spring 2026. Coun Howard Blagbrough (Con, Brighouse) said: “Things are really progressing – it\'s good to see it coming forward, people will see the actual scheme out there, work is taking place.” Coun Blagbrough added communications had been good over the scheme. Senior Environment Agency adviser Paul Swales told flood alleviation programme partners it was hoped the scheme for Hebble Brook in Wheatley would start in late spring or early summer. Realigning the water course and improving access are the preferred options, said Mr Swales.','Halifax Flood Project Approved and Brighouse Scheme Underway','Halifax Courier - Flooding in Calderdale: Halifax flood project approved','2025-04-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFlLFE78Ixqz1Alz04klPeTtx5G4N5NVlY8Q3H93OMjB5enCN3hvi5msOD-DABanrZo7fT5fCrw0kzsaWDCzDAMfKU4dzMNFMcl7pGHiRCfBU0j0yxSDai_B4JaVTjn6cOHsHRWmfUb8iZ8qpq1mU3zGddWM2t2Qds28yGuKIIGeY_ZXsznWLJJTVwfkF1GALehVOeQHaxwtCkydvb8R5ML5xNkmlP4QYUdNw==','As of April 2025, final approval has been granted for a flood alleviation project in Halifax, and the £19 million Brighouse scheme is underway. Work at Wellholme Park and Whinney Hill Park in Brighouse, creating flood water storage areas, is expected to be completed by spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5f8fd19d-063d-4286-9131-4333fc447cea','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans (LCWIPs) are a strategic approach to identifying walking and cycling network plans and priorities, that have been led by WYCA in collaboration with each of the WY districts. ... LCWIP Phase 1 was published in 2019 and after that we worked on LCWIP Phase 2, again a WYCA-led process which will be consulted on and adopted in due course, and WYCA are currently working on the timescales for that alongside their LTP4 work. ... Unfortunately, this scheme will therefore be pipelined following submission of the Outline Business Case anticipated in Winter 2024 until new funding opportunities arise and can be secured. ... In the meantime, LCWIP Phase 3 has commenced, and this will be taking a wider look at the entire network and priorities across West Yorkshire, building on the evidence gathered from the previous phases, which is still valid.','Slow Progress on a Cycling & Walking Network in Kirklees','Cycle Kirklees','2024-10-07 00:00:00.000','https://cyclekirklees.org.uk/2024/10/07/slow-progress-on-a-cycling-walking-network-in-kirklees/','This article from Cycle Kirklees discusses the slow progress of Kirklees LCWIPs, noting that Phase 1 was published in 2019, Phase 2 was completed in August 2023 but remains unpublished, and Phase 3 has commenced. It highlights concerns over funding issues leading to the indefinite pausing of key cycling schemes, such as the A629 Wakefield Road project, despite LCWIPs aiming to set priorities for future investment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5fd80a13-0aa7-453f-9ff1-766441483c9a','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council\'s new Darley Street Market to lead district\'s green regeneration. ... The engineers and architects have integrated green transport into the market\'s design. Cycle storage facilities will provide space for 6 bikes and two 50Kw rapid charging electric vehicle points will charge vehicles\' batteries up to 80% in 20 minutes. Showers and lockers will be provided to encourage active travel. The project will create 400 new jobs including 157 jobs in construction, 16 work experience placements and 136 weeks of apprenticeships.','New Market to Lead District\'s Green Regeneration','Bradford Markets Website','2021-05-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.bradfordmarkets.com/news','Bradford Council announced that its Darley Street Market project would champion green regeneration within the district. The market\'s design incorporated sustainable transport solutions, including dedicated cycle storage facilities and high-speed electric vehicle charging points. This initiative was anticipated to generate 400 new jobs, with demolition work for the market commencing in June 2021.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('5ff699a6-f977-448c-9965-53a23eae4160','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On April 29, 2025, Calderdale Council announced it had secured £900,000 from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, funded by Active Travel England, to improve routes and access for active travel to and from five schools in the borough. These improvements will include new road layouts, wider pavements, and safer crossing facilities, with work scheduled for summer 2025. [6]','Funding supports better access to Calderdale schools for active journeys','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-04-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF3PkPw6QLM8vj58ye70vAseFvRoPUdC3UQNhM-xqCs1KESxfRKzySbcPxliIeS5qIYjVCPajNuLCdMlWwMEsd1x0Fk_65KBGjIJk8nKHeX7i_eldDigCwIcdQMUD9W7v-OZYancGnuN_lPdk_S4M14BOVaeVmMTgrtjyWVW6fwhLmfQS06M9hF3GmRgEtsdg==','Calderdale Council secured £900,000 from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, as part of Active Travel England funding, to improve routes and access to five schools across the borough. The funding will be used for improvements such as new road layouts, wider pavements, safer crossing facilities, and landscaping, with work due in summer 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('60a7dcf5-5f10-48e5-81b4-d000b75e0c55','infrastructure-home-bargains-garforth-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.429','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The £3m-plus scheme is part of an effort by West Yorkshire Combined Authority to improve the county\'s air quality by encouraging the use of electric vehicles. The combined authority hired the Leeds-based company ENGIE to install, own and operate the new charging points after a successful bid for £2m of funding from the Government\'s Office for Low Emission Vehicles (OLEV)... West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the partnering local authorities – Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield councils – are also providing a further £1.2m of match funding for the scheme. [5]','West Yorkshire Launches Region\'s Largest Electric Vehicle Charging Network','Energy Live News / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-08-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGlVAdAGWqrfcKz5oam8g7RiP66O35_qUmc_uPsPOsKS9t7rWj4S6L2zCKDLwmfR4i7d-G5mF1yFXeDA9pkixavZa0Hxl5JaFfZ95OXKFGizaAGnEJIsdOKP6_zK7-mamKDegWfpYpLKGC-6cnug5eDqc3JZK2H6o1osl44BUHpG5GK5u3Lg2e7NIflclvRlPDstTAT0F34khK_PNYDUlxl5emGd9QLXDoGExvJEx1gUQE','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) launched a £3 million-plus initiative to install 88 new electric vehicle charging points across the region, including Leeds. This scheme, funded by the Government\'s Office for Low Emission Vehicles (OLEV) and local authority match funding, aimed to improve air quality and encourage EV adoption. The charge points were initially free to use.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('60c04294-5a10-4514-89bd-0c0d11d17145','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'If plans are approved, demolition of the Oastler site is expected to begin later this year, ahead of work beginning on Phase One in spring 2026. [6]','Demolition of Oastler Market expected to begin','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / Anita Morris Associates / Yorkshire Live / ECF - the English Cities Fund / Muse / Build News / Yahoo News Canada','2025-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEVhq9UGIvB0p7yAgeJn4kELgygHFh1GxF7qtHPkeswE9PrrgSUqKjqE33YSHCKamz1v4dafg-Kw9OAuI8T8HBILaWbccHufh2d7376Zz8Fm_g1zuNFayNRe7y3q7MVzG-a1Yzm6c1Ng1SiUYF5zbmY-s4gf1nZGkkHIdKqbNtJaP4nFG9gm0-tb45pQMtPwCjLjOK7H6mHynJmIEHOd9dkPnaX_g==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGXicfvbS5QWladcRnFtAnA0XPU_kZxhkxPsVkbEqWke3-pOdpdcwFobB7RENNbC_MIugiXDbmU9hsSf2XaTBmxA_OdS1Jl0-Ghf1YjXUyxskCGQsSblodQdZdB8Ra61Lajsz3EDL5zG_AwSiA2wuzAN4-wQ9X5iSoC8HP389jtRCoRFeeO4pDiXsbhavqd_UBxyJGPSvSOCiPJFl2t1_rHbtdlrmwqRGq9F3Ka0t3ry_M8pZlr21mZpiJDsg==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEXx0EMxAaPul_v2rTjBwQWD-i4QvnlBdMyKgbOIDKj1OszA-L__rND53g1UtMqMnIBg4f0nfx5M2Y0PP4qu5PLuozL0vDAdqD5knog_okLbj4pSg-7k_IlebY5ZzPUPnhuUtUTeZntpH1AaMO1V9e4GILXYI49HI1HVyC3U3alONuhVQLH6z1PP6EszpxAtQIFVIu9Q, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEmC_ORZC80BnQMcUFIWYURYJtGW6WfVRinbFvXjTnLBUyU1gVh2TKrNPkEWABWO3xb_GcQSxUE3RHrE-SEAYij9-fttf2hiXTKV6cMdDsInDijZg6QKIUhr8K3Yn4dxQO32pS_Hcg7hPn7_K2ucgRJVcRrtZVzlbMFXM8PZm_KMZ-b_wHxXHeGdQFRGVQ, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHw9Whmn_Olx4WvrDIf6E75ucwUrzZydVmjhnXC5MQ1z2T8a17tysul8FWjr4sHN_6rj4qRvb3ZF6JcxvDghlJM3qS1HeYhP3hf0K7XKGOkr8FM_O1Af_AYHHWvy3RiXKr57g1_fjdWwb2bLTdRS1ENCjOz0pWFVd-8lGSIemTqfssF2YEIK_4WflDSi_6JPzWs, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGcPrx5tnmphsyYcbgQKENvxA-enewmjaqAWrfHeCpBSDKIqKMjq7rzy9A_ZhS3xo-7ZR1hklkVufGfha85GtK0l_uZBFgKTcLrtujYGJLe9dG65FR93I3r046LamOxq1NBo5rF8PS4k_QvrI2cXAfqJdcyIIU1pnOl7rUIjC9IEMzQjxcq60CHUuAcaBGXACaXXCY9qM01SIC6rofZm8-j_QHhInorflmrwTMzCwdMkHPlT_dw, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH0wZzcuTAO98qI52znkhUurioiNCj32rjczy9vdL5a0KgGg7q8gVHtbKFet5vNXrePSL6STj2SWzMPW_lnhv12OgKIlZktG_LelypGsBFAz5k05bnSV8BWonNRABdmD71r0umUZydcG5xWQ2TCNoDZkahe-yOIApb0qHpNJNU1eSiTfqUZwtnB9gyv5A==','Following the submission of planning applications, the demolition of the Oastler Market, a key site for the City Village regeneration, is anticipated to commence in Autumn 2025. This significant step clears the way for future construction, including the Southern Oastler site apartments. [3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 12, 16, 18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('60d2cd31-73ef-4cbb-80ad-28e32b272920','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to build tram lines in Leeds and Bradford are set to move to the next phase. Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million for ongoing detailed planning and development work on Mass Transit, which will see a line run through West Leeds. [5] The work will include further technical and environmental assessments on phase one tram route options, as well as progressing the business case and preparing the plans to go before government decision-makers in the coming years. [5] More than 5,000 environmental surveys have been carried out as plans for a new tram line between Bradford and Leeds gather pace. West Yorkshire Combined Authority aims to have “spades in the ground” on the new mass transit system, which will feature numerous stops between the two cities, in 2028. [6]','Mass transit: Detailed planning and development to keep mass transit on track for 2028 start','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/mass-transit-detailed-planning-and-development-to-keep-mass-transit-on-track-for-2028-start/','West Yorkshire Combined Authority is set to approve £40 million for detailed planning and development work on Mass Transit, including further technical and environmental assessments for phase one tram route options. Over 5,000 environmental surveys have been conducted across 869 sites for both the Leeds and Bradford lines, confirming progress towards a 2028 construction start.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('60f8537b-32f7-4da6-bce4-dd4cdb68cf4f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council introduced the idea of shared transport hubs in the Upper Calder Valley area in November 2022 with an initial consultation. The earlier consultation asked for views on potential locations for shared transport hubs – Hebden Bridge and Todmorden were the preferred locations. Respondents were also asked which facilities they thought were essential, nice to have, or not needed at all. The proposed Calderdale shared transport hubs are part of a wider, West Yorkshire-wide programme to look at where the introduction of shared transport hubs, also known as mobility hubs, would benefit people, and what facilities would add value.','Calderdale Shared Transport Hubs - Hebden Bridge and Todmorden (Initial Consultation)','Calderdale Council / Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG7o_nvoYqgv01HSVueveMBUVGMY_2U-PdV14yaqMtStDN5RYZn16nG9ZBm_dTC7NA_cvf_yDg0kaNKl-i3B8F7zADa0KLexDPLSPoARAEu6eI5iwWnW01VZJPi4nVWFbbPMd6j_XNXSagmXAjK-R-pZUMHpuvoxjM5SGK0VqSAI2qz2v96U1yrb8mQ7qwZeQdYfEhoFrH4Xu7OEalM0gqM8Q==','Calderdale Council, as part of a wider West Yorkshire programme, launched an initial public consultation in November 2022 for shared transport hubs in the Upper Calder Valley, specifically identifying Hebden Bridge and Todmorden as preferred locations. The consultation gathered views on potential sites and desired facilities to encourage sustainable travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('61012ba9-a933-4d2b-ab93-0c271d0c1ee1','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'LEEDS City Council says it has been in \'ongoing discussions\' with Leeds Bradford Airport (LBA) about tunnel works that got underway last night. The southbound carriageway of the airport tunnel in Victoria Avenue, in Yeadon shut from 7pm yesterday until 6am this morning for resurfacing works. These overnight works will continue until 6am on Sunday. A huge diversion route is in place for anyone wanting to head south, via Harrogate Road, Pool Bank New Road, then Leeds Road/Otley Road and onto Horsforth to get through to Rawdon. [7]','\'Ongoing discussions\' with Leeds Bradford Airport for works','Wharfedale Observer','2024-10-10 00:00:00.000','https://www.wharfedaleobserver.co.uk/news/24641611.ongoing-discussions-leeds-bradford-airport-works/','Leeds City Council was in \'ongoing discussions\' with Leeds Bradford Airport regarding overnight resurfacing works in the southbound carriageway of the airport tunnel on Victoria Avenue, Yeadon. These temporary works required significant diversion routes, highlighting existing challenges with road access and congestion management around the airport.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6104da50-ac25-4c2c-a9c8-35b634bd3511','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This consultation has closed. The responses are now being analysed and the outcome report will be published once completed. Key Dates: Consultation Ends. 06 April 2025. What happens next? Timeline: 4 March - 6 April 2025 Public Consultation. May 2025 Bradford Council will review the feedback and incorporate any changes into a... [3, 4]','Have Your Say - A650 Connect: Wakefield Road and Tong Street - Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Consultation Ends)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-04-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a650connect/haveyoursay','This page confirms the public consultation for the A650 Connect scheme closed on April 6, 2025. It outlines the next steps, stating that Bradford Council will review the received feedback and incorporate any necessary changes into the proposals in May 2025. This marks the end of the initial public engagement phase and the beginning of the feedback analysis and refinement stage.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('612161c7-d7c9-49f2-9cf0-a2277147ee2c','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'enfinium has opened its new £500m Energy-from-Waste plant at its Skelton Grange facility in Leeds. Designed and built by global green technology company Kanadevia Inova, enfinium says the Skelton Grange facility will divert up to 410,000 tonnes of unrecyclable waste from landfill every year and generate up to 49MW of homegrown energy... Skelton Grange will play a key role in building a more circular economy by turning unrecyclable waste into homegrown electricity and heat to supply nearby businesses and homes across Leeds.”','New £500m Energy-from-Waste facility opens in Leeds','Circular Online / enfinium / letsrecycle.com','2025-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHs3vEEaGlY0NxNNUOhcq2AD1IgSvqoV73S6WI_J0cv_7ApImjnXJZAJyZXmFZyJE3K2ZIxuyQH1yvlNY8YnDHoXNvSvfILwzQQF2ep-1XpQFArwohVhfQ9xrWF2vgeuZTXDQelSGR02bRwqbrP-Ud8n3Zk_1ImXWD_ExdsiO0Jbj77o9qZks1NGXJI7t6sPFbCOyaiZw=','enfinium officially opened its new £500m Skelton Grange Energy-from-Waste facility in Leeds. This facility is the central heat source for the Aire Valley Low Carbon District Heating & Electricity Scheme, now operational and capable of providing heat and electricity to nearby businesses and contributing to West Yorkshire\'s net-zero targets.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('612d8213-89f8-478b-b990-7e38eb18daed','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Today (Thursday 3 April), the regional mayor and five district leaders of West Yorkshire cemented their commitment to the long-term prosperity of Bradford by approving funding for its City Village scheme, pending final business case agreement. If agreed at the final business case stage, the £13,166,409 grant will come from the West Yorkshire Mayor’s £89 million Brownfield Housing Fund, and will support the first phase of the scheme. [18]','City Village Bradford could be pledged over £13 million - Telegraph and Argus','Telegraph and Argus','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQECNmX9fe_BoQiTkqOgMOSbXgr6xhwyEXLbsJbKIVe3eQMGKpucdqspc_xXmXew-sB4mg_7kzal8JZt3mgyK4JzPHo6w2jf4JPf-JHSc6DKy6Rf6VapJSp8ze4XiP8sD687KtKUK_7NvUz0Q4rVdl6CkmRGjz9U7no1Tny8DkBLKm5o92LdcfmrExvZf02jr8ttNwwT-JFNGUo=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) considered and later approved a pledge of over £13 million for the Bradford City Village development. This funding, from the Brownfield Housing Fund, aimed to de-risk the site and build confidence in central Bradford\'s housing market. Phase 1 was projected to cost £33,066,838, with WYCA\'s funding supporting Phases 1 and 2 of the ambitious regeneration project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6148b067-02bb-4b5f-a4a1-85db5e24c204','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Completion of construction of the scheme was officially marked today with a celebration event at a new flood storage area by the riverside near Calverley in Leeds hosted by the Leader of Leeds City Council Councillor James Lewis joined by representatives of project partners the Environment Agency, BAM Nuttall and Mott MacDonald, along with technical advisors AECOM, Bradford Council and other key stakeholders. ... After more than a decade of work and an investment of £200million including the use of state-of-the-art engineering and infrastructure, the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme led by Leeds City Council in partnership with the Environment Agency offers dedicated flood defences to help protect more than 4,000 homes and over a thousand businesses along the River Aire catchment in Leeds and neighbouring communities. [6, 8]','Construction of Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Completed','Leeds City Council News / BAM Nuttall','2024-11-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE8Qtm2_u82CVQ84DWXxyC4yWAKXX27rELf-Bc3d9-eFyYZjMLf-k_w8IwvJZvFu68tA-C78ea4LuYTMThYGNSOvivmv7WI0cx8oK_xVGzmNabrE3QjvnNnv2_8yE4hD22UrRfUjvv1sKYtN0X-cuNwIxH1ucMCSjVdLWlbYFmEIiBN5Y_Im_1e7IuU1DdAnT_b2K3z7pZ6yGJmor7VkXQhQylM9y9tLu7w4-sghXGI-D1MiyIAsNLYeYia_7g7rfqkYtmD','Construction of the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme, including Phase 2, was officially marked as complete on 22 November 2024 with a celebration event near the new flood storage area in Calverley. The £200 million scheme, led by Leeds City Council and the Environment Agency, provides a 1-in-200-year level of protection plus climate change allowance along the River Aire, protecting over 4,000 homes and 1,000 businesses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('615c2dda-8551-40e9-bf50-30bbe314aeab','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradley Park is a council owned strategic housing allocation in the Local Plan and will deliver around 2,000 homes. Over the last twelve months, work has focussed on completing technical work on highways and progressing negotiations on strategic acquisitions required to support access to the site, including a number of properties. The focus on this site is on delivering a Phase 1 of development of around 500 homes. Looking forward, for 2025/26 the focus of the project will be on securing a master developer partner and progressing the strategic property acquisitions required to deliver the scheme.','Housing Growth Update Meeting: Growth and Regeneration Scrutiny Panel','Kirklees Council','2025-03-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHg0sBGQg4Ve8hIx0Q4yKvN0tMygxAdfBAGxxFTTRhDwketft0WASl9oZoHHO5kK0ZGZv6aRO67KaE7W0tulBKeWr-5q2uM8BnZiohit7SDMFb6lLb9VxGmJ5rr0f9K_wUJ41SEh462XLI9CufAWa2j0TmDAw141GJunHX41V5VkJg_kMPMi7Y-N_G1tpdb0UAElAYG1HCJXA==','A Kirklees Council report to the Growth and Regeneration Scrutiny Panel provided an update on housing growth, confirming Bradley Park as a council-owned strategic housing allocation for around 2,000 homes. The focus for 2025/26 for Bradley Park is on securing a master developer partner and progressing strategic property acquisitions for Phase 1, which aims to deliver approximately 500 homes. Technical work on highways is also progressing.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('617fdd8f-a281-4cc6-b6fb-97cda6e85435','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Numerous user comments on PlugShare confirm the operation of Pod Point chargers at Kirkstall Bridge Shopping Park from March 2019 onwards. Details include 2x7kW chargers, network affiliation, and user experiences regarding availability and parking. [4]','Pod Point EV Chargers Operational at Kirkstall Bridge Shopping Park','PlugShare','2019-03-03 00:00:00.000','https://charge.pod-point.com/address/kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-rn2w','Electric vehicle charging points from Pod Point have been operational at Kirkstall Bridge Shopping Park since at least March 2019, as indicated by user check-ins and comments on PlugShare. The site features 2x7kW chargers and is part of the Pod Point network. Users frequently report on the status and availability of the chargers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6196dd49-52d4-4b18-99e9-961e4fb66b0d','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £51.9 million scheme to reduce waiting times and introduce a raft of road improvements at Dawsons Corner and along Stanningley Bypass has moved a step closer to reality. A council report has revealed the final design layout of the scheme, and given the go ahead to submit a final business case to the Department for Transport to inject funds into the major highways project. Work is expected to start in summer 2024, subject to the Department of Transport agreeing a final business case to fund the scheme. There will be an 18-month construction period, with completion scheduled for winter 2025/26. [17]','£51m Dawson\'s Corner scheme: Work \'could start in summer\' after final business case submitted','West Leeds Dispatch','2024-03-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFlIKljyUHTsHJu0E7WwZd0aiJ6zgiU-SEOwdBpk1OuJCH5ueBRLE5bPTfZZX3VZXSST54EOCI0UwcYx5al9zgojFhp0sdmw3r1nHLgTnoUCGlcyvoyZMpWSKXYNLkcCZnEfukBh4JfHW8cUUicMFFE7mphcRvHWpCY1ULNWdxCAfiyBqWGhoBXKwoL6EC9','A council report revealed the final design layout for the £51.9 million scheme and gave the go-ahead to submit a final business case to the Department for Transport. Work was expected to start in summer 2024, subject to funding agreement, with an 18-month construction period.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('62134533-c5a2-46e4-aac6-9897c7dcc9df','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The North Yorkshire Council website details that the Transforming Cities Fund is a major programme of transport infrastructure investment covering the Leeds City Region, including the North Yorkshire towns of Harrogate, Selby and Skipton. These projects were part of a bid for funding from the Department for Transport by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, which was approved in March 2020. The £44.6m programme in North Yorkshire includes new or improved cycling and walking infrastructure, improvements to bus and rail stations and improved public spaces. Harrogate\'s project is £12m, Selby\'s £25.4m, and Skipton\'s £7.2m. Project development is ongoing from April 2020 to Summer 2024, with Full Business Case approval in March 2024. Construction for Skipton and Selby is projected from Spring/Summer 2025 to Summer 2026. [12]','North Yorkshire Towns Benefit from Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund Bid','North Yorkshire Council','2020-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEt_GD0aEDm1Pl3evaTvvaHt8t7QMblL7xFz-DnF72pN2u33QjO07vOTWZLG5F6gFVueh3j6h7hcEJw7v5IvvLFgRlKjLWIqf2G9Y6aYDBTCUytVYfT4gXGlCAcxAyfEAo8l5rmHBlcXVx3uHFHqV1ODF8STbG_7DdVSALFiGjHg3QxyHZbA73Yu9Uoq1H6kLicINdegU0CE56LlgMyJpPbXPdEA22rmPYWHMqTIXJWWVrUJe3VqzZZvNnDg9OgSEFnXK4ss0PB_4PLfA0vNAGVow==','While primarily focused on West Yorkshire, the Leeds City Region\'s successful Transforming Cities Fund bid, led by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, also extends to projects in the North Yorkshire towns of Harrogate, Selby, and Skipton. This £44.6 million programme in North Yorkshire includes new or improved cycling and walking infrastructure, upgrades to bus and rail stations, and enhancements to public spaces. Specific projects include a £12 million initiative in Harrogate to boost access to its rail and bus stations, a £25.4 million project in Selby to connect the rail station with new housing and employment via active travel routes, and a £7.2 million project in Skipton to better connect its rail and bus stations. The Leeds City Region bid approval was in March 2020, with construction for Skipton and Selby commencing Spring/Summer 2025 to Summer 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('621eb8f9-0d8b-45ca-a682-d144ae795e25','infrastructure-west-bradford-junctions-improvement-scheme-a6177-ring-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.879','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first phase of public engagement for the West Bradford Junctions Improvement Scheme took place from 18 February - 29 March 2019. A report has been produced that includes all the comments received during the phase 1 engagement period (18 February – 29 March 2019). [6, 7, 10]','West Bradford Junctions Improvement Scheme Phase 1 Public Engagement','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-02-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/westbradford','The first phase of public engagement for the West Bradford Junctions Improvement Scheme took place, inviting public feedback on the initial proposals for the three key junctions on the A6177 Outer Ring Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('62262417-af28-4059-95b3-615482ad8c7d','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BT\'s demonstration vehicle is also doing a tour of 12 towns and cities through August: ... 15th and 16thAugust: Wakefield, Morrison, WF2 9BY. [13]','BT\'s Digital Voice to rollout across Yorkshire and The Humber - ThinkBroadband','ThinkBroadband','2023-08-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFfr5cc-L95843U1YhUujHHeVr_1cqJ8kR-aG9Prc1LZ5Mzy2kdPQVzBVtv_QyACjXd2dew9rOdp0T2m1mIWb0BYiYYYDJ62N6Oq22JF9doc3JJCtQAL57c0VsBpr97X1yKwdv9p364LZLjY56jMazwPsjVp_w4ZCuc1jfohm37Y1K0p53WI0KDvq80fS5d_B9E759yNT8gfQcfmBlb5hSWQw==','BT announced the rollout of its Digital Voice service across Yorkshire and The Humber. As part of this, a demonstration vehicle toured 12 towns and cities in August 2023, including Wakefield, to inform customers about the upcoming digital landline switchover.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('62463441-6a10-4782-b1aa-cfddc92faa27','infrastructure-five-towns-leisure-hub-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.669','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work has begun on a £20.8m leisure centre in Pontefract in West Yorkshire. The Five Towns Leisure and Wellbeing Hub will be owned by Wakefield Council is due to open in late 2020. Wakefield Council has appointed Willmott Dixon to build the centre, which was designed by GT3 Architects. ARCADIS Design & Consultancy has been appointed project manager. [2]','Work underway on £21m Pontefract leisure centre – will become region\'s largest','Construction Enquirer','2019-08-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEETMTPJY8EgATkpk43Ov_BJ9Ok26_8M8T9hvu69_u-NyFBIXqPnBhYaFezGp-LuawL-dry4H_oDXcflY6sbprnn5Lk4FwdfjVyUul9QGMbo4nWbtB22JCnnPT7mopabt5QjtBaoedvGlsx2LPFTIHkHxUUPtl0EdKmRMqpf4PRlihOJtBX7k3zUOrb2mOAw3Z4Fww=','Work officially commenced on the £20.8 million Five Towns Leisure and Wellbeing Hub in Pontefract, West Yorkshire. Owned by Wakefield Council, the hub was designed by GT3 Architects and project managed by ARCADIS. The facility was still expected to open in late 2020 and would be the largest of its kind in the Wakefield district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('62786a0b-987b-4bc1-b1e7-7f2b692ded2c','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The preferred option is a realignment of the Hebble Brook watercourse to improve the fluvial approach to the culvert. This will help reduce undercutting of the steep sided embankment and provide much improved access for Calderdale Council maintenance teams to safely clean the screen if it becomes blocked with debris in high flows. The planning application has now been submitted for this project and we are looking to commence early works in Summer 2022.','Flood Risk Reduction Schemes - Hebble Brook Watercourse Realignment Planned','Eye on Calderdale','2022-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHtnyNGvNYX9dksUbYbE6BZgOxwrzb75THF-KMlEH3IGClh7O_YRWjIk4QzzaqGn3QsCBAWeHEQVi1b-m6dGsWDwPGTHZqR6Vn2ZGgGU1HGFXIgXhtv7H3ojoOA4v5ww1Xw9lAkiCLtrWD5UE4wx6b-G2hryQ==','Calderdale Council\'s \'Eye on Calderdale\' reported on flood alleviation schemes, mentioning that a planning application had been submitted for a Hebble Brook watercourse realignment project. This project aims to improve the fluvial approach to a culvert, reduce undercutting, and provide better access for maintenance, with early works intended for Summer 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('630c664a-1619-40a7-92db-75a7228b5e0d','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Go-Ahead will enter the West Yorkshire bus market on 23 February. From that date it will operate three vehicles on tendered service 571 between Halifax and Shelf, with the group having indicated that it expects to bid for franchise contracts in the region in due course. A new timetable is to be introduced on the route, which is currently run by Arriva Yorkshire. [6, 18]','Go-Ahead to enter West Yorkshire bus market ahead of franchising - RouteONE magazine','RouteONE magazine','2025-01-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH0TGa-6AoGnhRWuLnlT3muoLFeWC_X9YNOHUSb-7f2TscOm_vOqEywsjF22Ag_7ke1YqwcYDKr1MrxTTam0VA086faH0EUcdR0Tmw1Q2jRdulp5Yj2QV-ojh_k9INSz5ZBZLJ8d888RTi5uLubFU4vR2qFtzrjvQJYK4euE6GFv-WNyIHeujb0Ez6bxkGdCZoMfK4GpI2DKlFlEg','Go-Ahead announced its entry into the West Yorkshire bus market by securing the tendered 571 service between Halifax and Shelf. The company was set to begin operating the route from February 23, 2025, with a new timetable, replacing the previous operator Arriva. [6, 18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('636c6c98-88cc-4b45-aecf-0c383d3e32a5','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A LONG-AWAITED link between Bradford\'s two railway stations could be made a reality if a plan for a new \'tram-train\' in Bradford takes off. ... Now it has emerged that a plan to introduce a tram-train line between Bradford and the Leeds-Bradford airport could involve a link-up between Forster Square and the Interchange. ... Councillor Val Slater, executive member for transport at Bradford Council, said while there was \'no hope\' of constructing a heavy rail link between the two stations, it could be possible to connect them as part of this tram-train plan. [5]','Tram-Train scheme could link Bradford\'s two railway stations','Telegraph and Argus','2014-08-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/11405206.tram-train-scheme-could-link-bradfords-two-railway-stations/','Following the \'One North\' report, it emerged that a plan for a new \'tram-train\' line between Bradford and Leeds-Bradford airport could involve a link-up between Bradford Forster Square and Bradford Interchange. Councillor Val Slater, executive member for transport at Bradford Council, indicated that while a heavy rail link was not viable due to cost and engineering, a tram-train system offered a potential solution.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('63aa5844-a442-4e4f-a554-d020d2706249','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Improvements that have already been delivered in Hebden Bridge as part of the A646 Corridor Improvement Programme include better pedestrian facilities outside the Fox and Goose pub on Heptonstall Road, and the removal of limited waiting bays on Market Street to improve traffic flow.','Moving forward to transform travel in and around Hebden Bridge','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2025-02-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEFEdp6Wg-PnkEQcN0QJO9VnXHyXy--JlzceeypNwM3sFDZZtwO-Ugsqiz6AID1Ye-RwKEYxvknqigu2wZ--w7384F4t_rxClJ9nnOu5iqkF7odmZsJNdN88DGVosnwbOOfZRBtLiR1mm9X5El0iPjnx628NPbKGp25JSDkMgfnxHVbN20zqS7Kz_Wkah7s3WhVdxJWRAsKu90=','Calderdale Council\'s news centre re-confirms that improvements, including better pedestrian facilities outside the Fox and Goose pub on Heptonstall Road, have already been delivered as part of the A646 Corridor Improvement Programme. This serves as a further official statement on the completion of the junction improvement project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('63df2358-721d-45ea-9549-a7b414c0904e','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \'Your Voice\' platform details the consultation for its Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy, which commenced on 25 July 2024. The strategy focuses on enhancing the EV charging network across the region and includes the LEVI program. [15]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Launches EV Infrastructure Strategy Consultation','Your Voice (West Yorkshire Combined Authority)','2024-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/electric-vehicle-charging-for-west-yorkshire','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) launched a public consultation on its Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy. The strategy aims to build a comprehensive network of public EV charge points across West Yorkshire, focusing on increasing coverage, reducing inequalities, and ensuring the right chargers are in the right places. This includes participation in the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6428713a-95a0-4761-91a8-9a3561618af9','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Invest in flood risk improvement schemes in Walsden. Measure ID: 0204104024. Location: Walsden. Flood Risk Area: Todmorden, Humber (RoFRS). Timetable: 2027. Responsible authority: Environment Agency. Other responsible authorities: Calderdale Council. What is the status of the current measure? Ongoing. By 2027, the Environment Agency and Calderdale Council will invest in flood risk improvement schemes in Walsden to reduce the risk of flooding and manage coastal change in the Todmorden, Humber Flood Risk Area.','Ongoing Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme with 2027 Target','Defra data services platform','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://data.gov.uk/dataset/c4b8e8b0-a0a9-4b68-80f0-c11c210d7a04/flood-risk-management-measures-national-register','The Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme (Walsden FAS) is an ongoing measure by the Environment Agency and Calderdale Council. Investment in these flood risk improvement schemes is targeted for completion by 2027 to reduce flooding and manage coastal change in the Todmorden, Humber Flood Risk Area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('64570ee8-84cf-4287-9546-115fbade40f0','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Our Sustainable Future case study: Bradford City Village. ECF – our partnership with Legal & General and Homes England – is working together with the City Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to deliver Bradford City Village. Bradford City Village will transform the city\'s former retail heart into a bold new community. It\'s a plan which leverages 25ha of council- owned land, including the Oastler and Kirkgate shopping centres, to deliver a dynamic new neighbourhood. Including as many as 1,000 new homes – including affordable homes – the plan encompasses three new community parks, alongside shops, cafes, restaurants, and workspaces. Importantly, Bradford City Village is one of fifteen places identified in the Strategic Place Partnership between West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Homes England. Already, Homes England has committed nearly £30 million of investment – via the Brownfield Infrastructure and Land Fund – to enable the masterplan to be delivered. The engagement has informed our approach, with five distinct principles now guiding our approach: a green neighbourhood, a range of housing types, a range of community amenities, a sustainable community for the future, and respecting heritage.','Muse highlights Bradford City Village as a sustainable future project','Muse','2025-03-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHfmbFQcEFiEAa8IcPBEsMP591ckvbsoRGYDm2ZX0mdbmadSFLMhpsFkmUUdJoSniJS6cw1ClhkXIlLarhrsHxg-JDJuWLH_LMT6kdPAG50TQ2xSfa-bhizNPeH4MWSOSfSGfy66bHe_wVyODS5r70BzoDOX3brdVJDch9v3IttJJSiBE0Y7G1cZ4izJxeKDTVQSA','Muse, a partner in ECF, showcased Bradford City Village as a case study for sustainable urban regeneration. The report highlights the plan to transform 25 hectares of council-owned land, including the Oastler and Kirkgate shopping centres, into a new neighbourhood with up to 1,000 new homes, community parks, shops, and workspaces. It emphasizes the project\'s adherence to five guiding principles for a green and sustainable community. [14]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('64b31225-ef32-4314-8bdc-21637d50680a','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Comments from the public objecting to the development of Bradley Park Golf Course (Site H1747) for housing. Reasons include concerns about traffic, loss of green space and leisure facilities, and building on a former tip. The site is described as the only public golf course in Kirklees and a valuable community asset. The comments date from November 2015 onwards, following the draft local plan.','Draft Local Plan Allocations and Designations - Site H1747 (Bradley Park Golf Course)','Kirklees Council','2015-11-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG_MJfUw3vsSbxQQ3l7azWmXcs2m6EWLm3vqNBqDSsn2p1i5rQKaBCv7_MUaVlekrWBichB310h5XH9UkonP02yTAEG22Jf4MsN8VYjaUp245Na4pT8ICIuvHWI6Qg-4JFVbpOopHLM5PuOfhNF8FAOQAze8xI8JPhcFzDHBvnyOF3587aag3aggPuvd1s8cnPxmiH_m78ElHVvOB-n8Y0CaAXeMatJaJoAA1IuT51lWNWb3jh0j5yR5DdMsu4WneSRV1DavA6TTdJEpQUUtw==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG60GqNI34pbmEm7jzkx0nw6uxGg7c4rV3srNqLBxEhVhkN6TrNkcCjKhQrQrl5TeIXOsGsZfngPBCbZGi4OQL1D8GB4YCCh0XqXlHPj142YX5SzPDwi6IF023p4Lz36UrOqYPP8uf-Z5HByUs6poOlMlvDsx0hk6M_RY7AbYwX2qLyPxzRqUdVOQ0Ci-vfn144J38XN1a0UFPesn0K447GDc3VLo3x7TOZzje1cgRNtRzRbLHy3adP98uDovvhWe1khYF3QPBHCoXbPVSOQUbJInOW_LoUVw==','This evidence comprises public consultation responses from late 2015 regarding the proposed allocation of Bradley Park Golf Course (Site H1747) for housing development in the Kirklees Draft Local Plan. Numerous objections were raised, primarily citing concerns about increased traffic congestion, loss of a vital public golf course and green space, and the unsuitability of building on a former refuse tip. These objections highlight early community engagement and significant public opposition to the scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('652e2339-0128-4091-8a96-c24d9e582ae4','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The scheme to transform Bradford\'s historic former Odeon building received £4 million from the Government\'s Northern Cultural Regeneration Fund. This funding, along with a £12 million loan from Bradford Council and NEC Group\'s operating partnership, meant the project was \'almost fully funded\'. Internal demolition works were expected to start soon, with an anticipated opening in autumn 2020.','Former Bradford Odeon secures £4million Government funding','Bradford Civic Society / NEC Group','2018-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFJGKUbM9W5xyvek5Js7w1lxQH9IJoOYoayoWzEWq3bAV4U6TxOO7zzBHshTLty2MfKk-QaRBMFOK7PI4uheotfwAt-jzueRtaSD--DYdGHb1YuVznvwK6zBihj3wWpSph6yDN52bPLkTTa1CIiEApsrnk6TF4snPifYpRFAUYcD_LHzd2qpFnNZn-xywOUfH6C8JCybUYo4K6gBh_IGBXs_81q0JU=','The scheme to transform Bradford\'s historic former Odeon building received £4 million from the Government\'s Northern Cultural Regeneration Fund. This funding, along with a £12 million loan from Bradford Council and NEC Group\'s operating partnership, meant the project was \'almost fully funded\'. Internal demolition works were expected to start soon, with an anticipated opening in autumn 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('65949b7f-65cc-4369-a6f7-628151140f31','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2018-10-26) The A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill transport scheme is entering its final stages with the completion of work at Dryclough Lane ... The work on the A629 scheme has been funded through West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund. The £1 billion West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund is being invested over 10 years in more than 30 transport infrastructure schemes across West Yorkshire and York, designed to create around 20,000 new jobs and add £2.4 billion a year to the economy by the mid-2030s.','What work is still left to be done on the A629 Salterhebble scheme','Halifax Courier','2018-10-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGU0Psiq6AiQOMyIpO_9lfmptcJhgdAtsRtDoeTK8B2hN8jDKj9Wx83-wtrlbSt8kmtMU4GHQbJFagaNX9OnWhYKMPthtqoeYGEnw8k88I8AesxnqAVo5JNEq6pI5D3g1Gb-5eYQnTIdedx1ofX6RvYAlcRsES1_sjgrHCEF72_bCJdFcow_eh0Dp7KEfrpravXx7hGKFUvR8nY5ijbwPDdC3uozHJYE5YQwAM3HUYSzyPSS_Tx21FVNQ39L1DC','This article from October 2018 indicates that the A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill transport scheme was entering its final stages with the completion of work at Dryclough Lane. It highlights that the project was funded through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund, a £1 billion investment programme across West Yorkshire and York.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('65d03a00-8789-4f5d-8223-18c6dcfb78ee','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'YORKSHIRE Water has issued contract notices, valued at approximately £3 billion, to help the utility deliver its proposed AMP8 capital investment programme. The organisation is looking to procure an Alliance to deliver its significant stormwater programme, which will deliver £1.3 billion of investment in the next ten years. This ambitious programme will deliver on the organisation\'s drive to make substantial reductions in sewage overflows into watercourses. Alongside this, Yorkshire Water is looking to procure two non-infrastructure framework agreements, focusing on complex solutions and on more minor works. These two frameworks will look to deliver £1.5 billion of water and wastewater asset investment over the next 10 years, ensuring continued service to customers and protection of the environment. Partners will be required to provide expertise, guidance, support and resources in design, planning, management and delivery of assets. Andy Clark, head of commercial at Yorkshire Water, said: “We are currently working with customers, stakeholders and regulators to finalise programmes of work to be included in the AMP8 period, which will form part of our largest-ever environmental investment programme. “We are looking to hear from organisations with the expertise to deliver our ambitious goals over the AMP8 period and beyond.” Interested parties are invited to attend a supplier briefing hosted by Yorkshire Water on Monday, June 5, 2023. Business · Environment · Bradford · West Yorkshire. [19]','Yorkshire Water aims to deliver massive investment programme','Telegraph and Argus','2023-05-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/23508493.yorkshire-water-aims-deliver-massive-investment-programme/','Yorkshire Water issued contract notices valued at approximately £3 billion to help deliver its proposed AMP8 capital investment programme (2025-2030). This includes £1.3 billion for the stormwater programme, aiming for substantial reductions in sewage overflows, and £1.5 billion for two non-infrastructure framework agreements for water and wastewater asset investment over 10 years. The announcement seeks partners with expertise to deliver ambitious goals for AMP8 and beyond, ensuring continued service and environmental protection.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('65e76cb9-b129-4eed-b296-1958a2093fb7','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2019-11-28) • Transform Wakefield City Centre through removal of traffic at the Northern and. Civic Quarters, enhanced high quality cycle infrastructure and storage and a range of measures to reduce congestion and improve air quality. This will support the city\'s wider regeneration objectives, making the most of the city\'s heritage to enhance connectivity and drive growth. Complemented by bus quality and cycling/walking infrastructure on the A61 and A639 corridors towards Leeds, this represents a comprehensive package of measures to encourage shift to ... city centre and creating a healthier, more liveable environment. Programme milestones: Strategic Assessment – Nov 2019. Strategic Outline Case – Apr 2020. Outline Business Case – Sep 2020. Full Business Case – Jan 2010. Construction Commences – Mar 2021. Delivery Complete – Dec 2022. Key risks. Risk. Mitigation. Disruption to public and businesses during the development phase of the project. Effective Scheme.','Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-11-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHxDiDiJafvRlOJb7Bzc6kxPAo2jwZzmwC13nkBkbFGvjC4Op4V1GW67f563Z400m-HIFa8voqV8kFcI_HaJsY4ka9P_Km4vCRxeelzTLUbuk0yen0KWWFNj0E8wNbV0-CWKwn3cfn6I_BlUPhXsAIkneMaawbbv8edp1iy','This document outlines the initial vision and submission for the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund. It includes specific plans to transform Wakefield City Centre by reducing traffic and enhancing cycling and walking routes, complemented by bus quality and active travel infrastructure on the A61 and A639 corridors towards Leeds. The submission also laid out aspirational program milestones, including construction commencing in March 2021 and delivery complete by December 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('66024e30-0c56-4842-850f-21398b475d9e','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Crosland Moor CLC has been a part of the Kirklees Digital Hubs Loan Scheme since the first Covid19 Lockdown. This is a project that loans a Chromebook and/or MiFi to a resident for 3 months to enable the resident to access the internet, increase their digital skills and improve digital & social inclusion.','Digital Hubs and Learning Support - Crosland Moor Community Learning Centre','Crosland Moor Community Learning Centre','2020-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH4wEGMbop_9z1OJEsIR9jSSGOtujpVWGB0d5h6-HaC03ICyedGXXcgKxQbQzy35uLwdg6HACXsuxNSF02bnzGoXesi2HtoQCn-7kc7Enmv-7XmOk8Tv7NueyNFlExzzyQQ0SkHoM7ItaT8qQDDRqXgMeqUVzYq0ZbKCFBRAnMI','Crosland Moor Community Learning Centre has actively participated in the Kirklees Digital Hubs Loan Scheme since the first Covid-19 Lockdown. The scheme provides Chromebooks and MiFi devices to residents for three-month loan periods, aiming to enhance internet access, digital skills, and overall digital and social inclusion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('661eefa5-a5a5-46f8-a6db-6e6f05c48c35','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for the redevelopment of the Bradford Interchange entrance and \'public realm\' were officially submitted. The application was for a multi-million-pound revamp of the area outside the transport hub to provide a pedestrian \'plaza\' between Hall Ings and the Interchange\'s entrance on Bridge Street. Proposed works included the demolition of the taxi rank and access ramps to facilitate a ramped pedestrian walkway from Hall Ings to Bridge Street, and partial demolition and replacement facade of the basement-level car park. The scheme, funded by the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund, aimed to deliver significant economic, social, and environmental benefits, and improve accessibility and safety.','Bradford Interchange redevelopment plans are submitted','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2023-08-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFAtJt3RWHOU2lVP1OBGTfekRkoueo58qmgCbM4qcLvJSRiK2kkvp3tfZSBOCnGTO20Vxe2Ut138lIPSEAGy-uxTC7_J7jNfUsnL1b60rXuYO3IdLEcmEPK3J3Wz0hAMuHH8cvR4rFNl-3x1Wl9jKSc1tfSUL0_fR16xDqHC3Mc5vKhyV0TgTnBta8X11ErGea2MKjNhk_AX7tj3Vrw5IOhWsY3','Plans for the redevelopment of the Bradford Interchange entrance and \'public realm\' were officially submitted. The application detailed a multi-million-pound revamp to create a pedestrian \'plaza\' between Hall Ings and the Interchange\'s entrance on Bridge Street, including demolition of the taxi rank and access ramps. The scheme is one of four funded by the Government through its Transforming Cities Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6666d467-5344-4c83-94e3-a5b7adfd7efb','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The next stage in the transformation of Leeds City Rail Station\'s main entrance and surrounding area will begin next month (March). The Leeds Station Sustainable Travel Gateway scheme will create a much-improved and more people-friendly environment which can accommodate growing rail passenger numbers, and ensure people can enter and exit the station safely. A total of £46.1 million is being invested in the scheme, which is being delivered by Leeds City Council on behalf of Network Rail as the landowner, and in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [12]','Transforming Leeds City Rail Station: next stage of works to begin','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2023-02-27 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/transforming-leeds-city-rail-station-next-stage-of-works-to-begin','Leeds City Council announced that the next phase of the Leeds Station Sustainable Travel Gateway scheme, a £46.1 million investment, was set to begin in March. The project aims to create a more people-friendly environment at the station\'s main entrance and surrounding area, including pedestrianising New Station Street, relocating the taxi rank, installing passenger lifts, and enhancing cycling infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('666b0e8d-46f2-4f38-b383-f93d612d5559','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Chargepoint with electric car chargers in Leeds. The EV location have 2 outlets with max capacity 7 kW. This charge point is part of the charging network Pod Point. ... This is an open charge unit installed at the Benfield Motors - Leeds site in 83-85 Kirkstall Road. Free Charging. © 2025 - ChargeFinder. ... Showing 1 Pod Point charge point at Lookers Nissan - Leeds, select the unit name below to begin charging your EV here. ... Connector A. Up to 7kW; Type 2 socket. Available. Connector B. Up to 7kW; Type 2 socket. Available. Location. 83-85 Kirkstall Road.','Pod Point EV Charging Facilities at Lookers Nissan Leeds','Pod Point / ChargeFinder','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.chargefinder.com/charge-point/lookers-nissan-leeds-pod-point-56360','Lookers Nissan Leeds provides 7kW EV charge points that are part of the Pod Point network. These chargers, with two Type 2 outlets, are located at the dealership\'s 83-85 Kirkstall Road address, and the ChargeFinder platform lists them as free to use at the former Benfield Motors site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('66ccb3c7-3204-4a11-a3f3-5935399c1357','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WHAT IS YOUR PROPOSAL? Brief outline of proposal and the overall aims/purpose of making this change: To implement the first phases of developing for infrastructure and housing at Dewsbury Riverside urban extension, south of Ravensthorpe Road, Ravensthorpe. Including allotment, mosque and playgroup relocation, alongside the construction of new highway infrastructure. (See Source [16] for full context).','Dewsbury Riverside Integrated Impact Assessment Stage 1','Kirklees Council (Integrated Impact Assessment)','2020-01-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/council-and-democracy/pdf/agendas/cabinet/2020/january/integrated-impact-assessment-dewsbury-riverside-stage-1.pdf','An Integrated Impact Assessment (Stage 1) was conducted for the Dewsbury Riverside urban extension. The assessment covered the proposal to implement the first phases of developing for infrastructure and housing, including the relocation of allotments, a mosque, and a playgroup, alongside the construction of new highway infrastructure. It referred to the Kirklees Local Plan and the endorsed Dewsbury Riverside Masterplan for mitigation of impacts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('66e86c6d-f850-4b3b-ae04-4f280f5445a5','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In 2022 the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 (FAS2) continued to progress at pace, with construction work officially started across each of the 12 zones. Ground has been broken at the Kirkstall Bridge Inn, Kirkstall Meadows, the area around Kirkstall Abbey and Apperley Bridge. ... So far 288 hectares of soil aeration have been successfully carried out, with a further 218 hectares currently being delivered, or in the pipeline. Over 410,000 trees have been planted in the catchment and there is an ambitious target of over 100,000 trees to be planted between October 2022 and March 2023, with a further planting season to start in late 2023.','Significant Progress in 2022 and Natural Flood Management Efforts','Leeds City Council News','2023-02-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGA02wcHLMLuam_mpEDvVnI-lfDga0ScKfmHuNb9tc40lGF3dxitXZW8M3iIitBL4u_GPbAPlaD-_KHRnubVlxZeN37YqvBjvaBMlLy43B2OsP2fXpvfH5GLE3wG5JJaSkQ0XV_lwFWN5tXj65QGIQsEPq1Rka1rd3NEtOgcPlCC1CpVA7czkvX7QrV6vMVkeRjiKhAfwE','Leeds City Council reported significant progress in 2022 for Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2, with construction officially started across all 12 zones. Natural flood management measures were also well underway, including the planting of over 410,000 trees in the catchment area, with ambitious targets for further planting.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('66ef93a3-995d-4a02-993f-8f3ecfee860b','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Members of Bradford Civic Society\'s new \'place panel\' met with the design team behind Bradford\'s proposed new markets relocation project in early February as part of a pre-planning consultation period. The meeting began with a presentation by architects from Greig & Stepenson who shared their updated plans for a new food-led market building on Darley Street, which is now to feature a brand new civic square on the site of the soon-to-be-demolished Burton buildings. ... A planning application for the demolition of the former M&S building (along with others on Darley Street) and the creation of a new market building and public square is due to be submitted in late February. It\'s anticipated that demolition work could commence later this year, with the new food-led market set to open in 2021.','Civic Society consulted on city\'s new market plans','Bradford Civic Society','2019-02-15 00:00:00.000','https://bradfordcivicsociety.co.uk/','Members of the Bradford Civic Society\'s \'place panel\' met with the design team for Bradford\'s proposed new markets relocation project in early February as part of a pre-planning consultation. Updated plans for a new food-led market building on Darley Street, including a new civic square, were shared. The project involved the demolition of the former M&S building and others, with the new food-led market anticipated to open in 2021. Feedback from the Civic Society was presented to Bradford Council.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('66fa6c15-9876-4230-bac2-60b363602b89','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The £41 million Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme was officially opened on October 4, 2021, providing enhanced protection for around 400 homes and businesses in the village. The scheme, developed by the Environment Agency in partnership with Calderdale Council, involved the construction of new and raised flood walls, the relocation of Caldene Bridge, river channel widening, and flood proofing of buildings.','Mytholmroyd\'s new flood defences officially opened','GOV.UK / Calderdale Council – News Centre','2021-10-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/mytholmroyds-new-flood-defences-officially-opened','The £41 million Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme was officially opened on October 4, 2021, providing enhanced protection for around 400 homes and businesses in the village. The scheme, developed by the Environment Agency in partnership with Calderdale Council, involved the construction of new and raised flood walls, the relocation of Caldene Bridge, river channel widening, and flood proofing of buildings.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('67103c93-6937-47ee-9a65-dc2d2c9aef31','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Thorpe Park Rail Station project received Outline Business Case (OBC) approval in October 2021, marking a significant step in its development.','Thorpe Park Rail Station Outline Business Case approval','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2021-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/thorpe-park-rail-station','The Thorpe Park Rail Station project received Outline Business Case (OBC) approval in October 2021, marking a significant step in its development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('671859b1-2e85-4cf1-9985-1b28625cba9f','infrastructure-a629-halifax-to-huddersfield-corridor-improvement-phase-4-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.884','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for the fourth project in the £120m, A629 improvement programme between Halifax and Huddersfield are moving forward, following approvals by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee. ... At the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Investment Committee meeting in July, members approved funding for land acquisition and to develop the project proposals to a detailed design stage. To help shape the detailed plans for the scheme, a public consultation was held during February and March 2019. Overall, feedback for the project was positive, with the majority of respondents expecting that the proposals would improve journeys for all modes of transport.','A629 Huddersfield to Halifax project making progress - Calderdale Next Chapter','Calderdale Next Chapter / Calderdale Council','2019-07-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEtcfj8BG-z-04qVf6SkHah1b6GIl3riiAgHb7qtzU6Q6iLMMHLKvEbjiexQ4WphpGAbVOjVsJkqYszJN_fb1CXtlA_G0iboYBjmXi7bufJAkYn_UCBR2lnliAwCBG_6tOV2G0kGzHZ3b8jGM3huWYAoilEnr27Ca0DAK3nij-sG7KC7UEN-LccEh9Mxig2g4uGooXkbQ==','This news article announces that plans for Phase 4 of the A629 improvement programme are advancing. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee approved funding in July 2019 for land acquisition and to develop the project proposals to a detailed design stage. A previous public consultation held in February and March 2019 provided positive feedback that will be incorporated into the detailed designs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('673e737a-0698-4b69-a5c5-a471f60ca77c','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A new development aimed at bringing some exciting new businesses to Halifax town centre is well underway. As these photos show, \'Westgate Phase II\' – an expansion of Westgate Quarter – is taking shape. O&C Management Services are leading the project and said earlier this year that the core and shell finish of the development is due in May or June, and tenants should be able to move in after a fit-out later in the year. [7]','What are they building in Halifax town centre: New \'high-end shopping and leisure destination\' for Halifax taking shape','Halifax Courier','2025-04-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF-ch30Pc05v1zOvMg9Cr4-xZINAoAJOLmive9zAehe1uYqy2WXxT_YQvmLX9FpeVBtq_UJv8qZ38oX9X0T3dbJSYmaYCBzf-WSvId4wSB32Kh0ubq1MPLKMaXZw075Y348s6F-W2E05i-nJEkctqbV21tVitbl1LahiRXVbUIcpVtKSpGuYzUdHGojoiG40PTUMKfMx8Rz4yrWSq82-5IbSkcB3LIdD7bMCftuOEiPPmevBoLHGKQmdwiAGdwhypQUI9uJrkkP8tVWVQSrq1QQ_WB3DtoNdYGWYfHYEJUgt7s=','This Halifax Courier article provided an update on \'Westgate Phase II\', noting that it was taking shape. O&C Management Services indicated that the core and shell finish was expected in May or June 2025, allowing tenants to move in for fit-out later in the year. The development, replacing Horton House, is a three-floor \'high-end shopping and leisure destination\' with 12 new premises.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('674cc7ad-57a9-450c-bf10-e43c30be9353','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'2018-04-22T18:52:56Z. PlugShare User. Successful Charge. [8]','Earliest Public EV Charging Activity on Whitehall Road, Leeds (Citipark)','PlugShare','2018-04-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.plugshare.com/location/166549','User check-ins at Citipark Whitehall Road EV charging stations indicate that public charging infrastructure was operational on Whitehall Road by at least April 2018. While not explicitly an EVBox charger, this demonstrates early EV charging presence in the immediate vicinity of the specified project. [8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('675b84ca-2bfa-4a80-a726-500d030e34af','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In January, Ingenious Real Estate Finance, a London-based stretched senior and bridging finance specialist, provided a £19 million (€21 million) loan for the construction of new homes at what it said will be the UK\'s largest sustainable residential development. The loan will fund 120 new apartments and houses at the Climate Innovation District – on the north bank of the River Aire in Leeds by locally-based developer Citu.','Ingenious Real Estate Finance Provides £19m Loan for Climate Innovation District Homes','PropertyEU','2021-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG7aPDuZ-Lo38bhpmLfSV77gV714U-kAM2nNCL31znsuC_xcSkoW2j2yNeu8zR0_uDy2CrY6d37Eg8moMRH3HuMYygAqX4Ou1WmHb3hCfF5tBujRWpAsIoLFgFyBjsFlX6EVfbjqRRPdDDYy2wKRu_gWS3rEyCFfyvrV09inz9xvu4YPC_E40hBfN1pSYiuRK3UFnd7wFfk9g==','In January 2021, Ingenious Real Estate Finance provided a £19 million loan to Citu to fund the construction of 120 new apartments and houses on the north bank of the River Aire within the Climate Innovation District, supporting the development of sustainable residential properties.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6762779b-c401-4f7b-be95-12f915fe4c1b','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Knottingley Skills, Business and Services Hub Project focuses on the refurbishment and repurpose of the existing Kellingley Miner\'s Welfare building to become a centralised community hub that supports skills and employability within the local area. The total outturn cost is estimated to be £3m. This is based on the pre-tender estimated build costs of refurbishing and repurposing the Kellingley Social Club building. The Getting Building fund will provide £1 million towards the scheme. WYCA funding to be spent by 31 March 2022. The scheme is expected to be complete by 31st December 2022.','Knottingley Skills Hub Scheme Summary','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-02-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFuJ4vIj90S0qrSjGObFGURYzsPuo6lr2p917iSUmgeECu5eItjQ34pjIN1DjF5aCqdAVEBvDSSs2s3hIlGcR8b6mMaodvgfPrPmG2WPG8_naHZMJZRphidSwPkhD3fms7NgSmAsdYR9tvZ8zf_RbkRyXSFCMzZf0u2C53YqV2lI5OdakkRMDhbvE5RUcIaPg==','This document outlines the project to refurbish and repurpose the Kellingley Miner\'s Welfare building into a centralised community hub. The total scheme cost is estimated at £3 million, with £1 million from the Getting Building Fund (West Yorkshire Combined Authority) and £2 million from Wakefield Council. The project aims to support skills, employability, and health and wellbeing, with a forecasted completion date of 31 December 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('676e086e-97f9-4131-9f51-0b327fd91014','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In March 2022, as a result of soaring inflation and instability in the construction sector, the Combined Authority \'paused\' the scheme. ... In 2021 the cost of the A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme was estimated at £75 million. ... The estimated cost of the A62 to Cooper Bridge scheme has hit £94 million and Kirklees Council says that\'s unaffordable.','A62 to Cooper Bridge scheme \'paused\' due to soaring costs','Huddersfield Hub','2022-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH276YHRWQ0nC3hHCL-rR_BkJOwlrShh2NPt17pnOzO8gPFMmaQsyvxTyeOe8GzV8x08NAEm-Prhx54ydHH5PiC9p-Ll0OnYy-3PnRX_KUWlJSjm4N4_Hr7xAQf5n9Pf3pIw_ZS9AhCSps7Vp1t7JMx1g95sLOap44NTAIC0YsKc4HlJYX0R0_Bh9suD5EPt62hc_AtlXoKkPNp6GFY4Egj_HGG7FklqA==','In March 2022, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority \'paused\' the A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme. This decision was made due to soaring inflation and instability in the construction sector, with the estimated cost having increased from £75 million in 2021 to £94 million. [9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6774707b-cac1-4941-9983-12f996f852b9','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious plans to bring trams back to West Yorkshire, and deliver a multibillion-pound boost to the economy, have secured a major funding boost from the government. The Chancellor Rachel Reeves today (Wednesday 4th June) announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to get spades in the ground on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. The £2.5bn mass transit programme will have spades in the ground by 2028, with the intention for the first trams to be operating before the mid-2030s. The project will improve local transport for over 675,000 people and benefit those in some of West Yorkshire\'s most deprived communities. Last year the Combined Authority asked for the public\'s views on different route options, with 4,845 individuals and organisations in total having their say. More than two thirds of those surveyed in West Yorkshire backed the Bradford Line plans, while more than three quarters supported the proposed Leeds Line.','Major funding boost secured for West Yorkshire trams','Unknown (likely a regional news outlet or WYCA press release via Google Search Snippet)','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHMgD34AE0gRQ5jTheDJ2uCCT5fFy6xB1JaB_LH1VRKlWNB-CSNF942ua4k8bsFuI_uU-WTy3nsAdkd_Vztw7640KZ7ZeDQnparEqXyuNheDDU79ZVpE0MTCnVWkl96I_Av-vXOYp88mmhnCRKN2GuMQauoPj3ZIUw5Vu-yGknxcLB-hVZ6fsITbqrjz_tYIslPCHwlPG4WrYdRmxktMCbmSDNH','Chancellor Rachel Reeves announced the allocation of £2.1 billion in local transport funding to West Yorkshire, specifically for the tram project. This funding aims to enable construction to begin by 2028, with the first trams operating before the mid-2030s. The £2.5 billion mass transit programme is intended to improve transport for over 675,000 people and benefit deprived communities. Public consultations in 2024 showed strong support for the Bradford and Leeds line plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('67760279-85bf-4e19-8265-7d6be9a79006','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Balfour Beatty was appointed to deliver a series of Transforming Cities Fund projects in Bradford, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. These projects, with a combined value of £55 million, are part of the City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council\'s aspiration to become the UK\'s leading clean growth district and to prepare for the City of Culture 2025. Specific projects include the City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme (creating new pedestrian spaces, green areas, and sustainable urban drainage systems), the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension (a segregated cycle route between Bradford city centre and Thornton village, built in two phases), and South Bradford Targeted Bus Measures along the A641. The active delivery of these projects is implied to be ongoing, with the City of Culture 2025 as a key milestone. [20]','Balfour Beatty Appointed to Deliver Transforming Bradford TCF Projects','Balfour Beatty','2023-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHaZXoOranThtnXhSG9_GrpXvdmN2S-iERqVj6_Ar7aRqe4vcaTERu6aV2gHMMm-WTrCE-lrucfg10ljDbVmKcxm4YeaDnPyTX2BLmufZr122OkaA7gQoaxA75dpEoiCr5lgO6gi_4w6kK1XaV_UfzSC6MwZOyE8nDcEt65NZINlVhI','Balfour Beatty has been appointed via the SCAPE Civil Engineering framework to deliver a series of projects in Bradford funded through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund programme. With a combined value of £55 million, these projects are crucial for modernising Bradford\'s transport infrastructure and city centre environment, aligning with the goal of becoming the UK\'s leading clean growth district and preparing for the City of Culture 2025. The schemes include the City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme, the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension (designed in two phases for City of Culture 2025 readiness), and South Bradford Targeted Bus Measures along the A641.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('677bdca9-6b2e-40f6-ae9c-dcef6a69e87e','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'New zebra and puffin crossings have been installed in the town centre as part of £5 million worth of road improvements on the A646 from Todmorden to Halifax. ... Calderdale Council\'s Assistant Director for Strategic Infrastructure, Adrian Gill, said that as part of the A646 Corridor Improvement Programme, zebra, puffin and toucan crossings are proposed at a number of locations in the borough. ... The deadline for representations on all the pedestrian crossings as part of the Corridor Improvement Programme is Friday, June 2, 2023,','\'Retrospective\' Consultation on New A646 Pedestrian Crossings in Todmorden','Halifax Courier','2023-05-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGf5ZG9gUzmIDpaNXMCFWXDLHF1G1SmJng5FfyYOBez7bMSLMVjLkBZwW29Chh0WLbGZ1GDljL5CfrAQptAFwY-6fC5zIkRY18hGduBXRhP53vwYqjUq0TqnFiYAupcuhGk04zz0wwXhGmNBFei3O0LRyfQJmTgKoEzq0m0cZkGgFzdo70W00Xvg4vAhP6bamHeKhactGepnRyfTkhNRiiJ3j5_56NMob5lFXRPEzRHkWRYOxVfAy1Ykvr48n83zWfKVHtC5uHA64rILJm_iJGiJoU=','The Halifax Courier reported on a \'retrospective\' consultation regarding new zebra and puffin crossings that had already been installed in Todmorden town centre as part of the £5 million A646 road improvements. Calderdale Council confirmed the legal requirement for public notice, with a deadline for representations set for June 2, 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('67e43990-5b84-4217-ac06-358c11487105','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'ECF – our partnership with Legal & General and Homes England – is working together with the City Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to deliver Bradford City Village. Bradford City Village will transform the city\'s former retail heart into a bold new community. It\'s a plan which leverages 25ha of council- owned land, including the Oastler and Kirkgate shopping centres, to deliver a dynamic new neighbourhood. Including as many as 1,000 new homes – including affordable homes – the plan encompasses three new community parks, alongside shops, cafes, restaurants, and workspaces. [24]','Our Sustainable Future case study: Bradford City Village','Muse','2025-03-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.museplaces.com/work/bradford-city-village/','A case study by Muse highlights Bradford City Village as a key project contributing to Bradford\'s renaissance. It details the vision to transform 25 hectares of council-owned land, including the Oastler and Kirkgate shopping centres, into a dynamic new neighbourhood with up to 1,000 new homes, three new community parks, shops, cafes, restaurants, and workspaces, driven by five guiding principles including a green and sustainable community.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('67e9590f-aa54-4e95-ac4f-0c9892885dff','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The information below was presented during the public consultation between October 17 2022 to January 16 2023. What is our Mass Transit Vision 2040? Mass Transit is a large-scale public transport system in a metropolitan area. Typically, Mass Transit would use one or more of modern, high-capacity buses, trams and tram-train vehicles. Our Mass Transit Vision 2040 shows how Mass Transit will help make West Yorkshire\'s public transport network more accessible and more inclusive, while also helping us achieve our aim of net zero carbon emissions by 2038. What has happened so afar... A statutory consultation was held between 17 October 2022 to 16 January 2023 on the revised West Yorkshire Mass Transit 2040 Vision ahead of the final Vision being formally approved and implemented. We invited statutory consultees, key stakeholders and members of the public to share their views on the revised Vision. We received 240 survey responses and numerous letters and emails. We are currently analysing these responses and an outcome report will be publish on this page once available. [22]','West Yorkshire Mass Transit Vision 2040 | Your Voice','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice)','2022-10-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/mass-transit-vision-2040','A statutory public consultation was held on the revised West Yorkshire Mass Transit 2040 Vision, which outlines the long-term plan for a region-wide mass transit system, including the connection between Bradford and Leeds. Feedback received from statutory consultees, key stakeholders, and the public helped shape the updated Vision.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6820c62a-302f-4405-9ded-d3081eba3e70','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'People living in the Stubbing Holme Road neighbourhood of Hebden Bridge are being urged to drop in to an event to find out more about proposals to protect their properties from flooding. This is the proposed first phase of work carried out by Environment Agency, in partnership with Calderdale Council, to design and construct a flood alleviation scheme for Hebden Bridge. ... Members of the local community are invited to the drop-in event, from 3pm until 7.30pm, on Wednesday 8 August at the Hebden Royd Methodist Church, Bridge Lanes.','Plans to protect Stubbing Holme Road neighbourhood from flooding','HebWeb News','2018-07-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.hebdenbridge.co.uk/news/2018/2018076plans.html','People living in the Stubbing Holme Road neighbourhood of Hebden Bridge were urged to attend a drop-in event on August 8, 2018, to learn about proposals for flood protection. This marked the proposed first phase of work by the Environment Agency and Calderdale Council to design and construct a flood alleviation scheme for Hebden Bridge, specifically aiming to protect properties along Stubbing Holme Road. Proposals included replacing and raising riverside walls adjacent to the River Calder and measures to prevent flows into an old mill goit.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('684d7502-7dfd-47f6-aa8a-bff6258a2b10','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Corridor Improvement Programme - A639 Park RoadBeechnut Lane junction. Options have been developed to handle existing and future traffic levels to allow for better overall traffic flow and more active travel. Funding for this road scheme has not yet been secured. West Yorkshire Combined Authority is paying for the development of a business case which will be used to apply for funding to deliver the scheme. [4]','Corridor Improvement Programme - A639 Park Road/Beechnut Lane junction details','Wakefield Council','2024-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/roads-and-transport/transport-projects/corridor-improvement-programme-a639-park-road','Wakefield Council\'s detailed page on the A639 Park Road Corridor Improvement Programme highlights that options have been developed to manage existing and future traffic levels. Proposals include replacing the Pontefract Park roundabout with a traffic light junction, options for additional bus or traffic lanes, bus priority at the A639/Park Lane/Beechnut Lane junction, and improved cycle paths. It notes that funding for the road scheme itself has not yet been secured, but WYCA is funding the business case development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6860f1e2-8649-42c2-ac0c-97f3c0d29b39','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale NFM Grant Scheme provides funding to farmers and landowners to install natural flood management measures on their land. The Scheme is managed by Calderdale Council and supported and funded by the Environment Agency. It is unique to Calderdale and was developed with local partners to help build Calderdale\'s resilience to flooding. To date, 52 natural flood management projects have been funded through the NFM Grant Scheme. ... Four rounds of funding of the NFM Grant Scheme have been delivered since 2018. Through the Scheme, over £850,000 has been allocated to 52 projects in Calderdale delivering a range of natural flood management measures: 10,483 trees planted. 492 leaky dams built. 77,926 metres of cross-contour hedging planted. 26,963 m3 rainwater temporarily stored in attenuation basins.','Natural Flood Management Grant Scheme Launched, Funding 52 Projects','Eye on Calderdale - Natural Flood Management (NFM) Grant Scheme','2018-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGSQlnkWuzHDH4jRcimj1s7NvjpIuJ7MkTBj7dZSEwxo7BIqhmNcm4_y7_57d5CJw4tJfJFrfw_YtzYa8TL2hOaQiMggqwUvoTP8qSCzQKWXaQfnD8G4VtoIChI6NRgBJ6CpUpa3m-xLf1TPX4Myw==','The Calderdale Natural Flood Management (NFM) Grant Scheme, managed by Calderdale Council and funded by the Environment Agency, has been providing funding to farmers and landowners for NFM measures since 2018. To date, over £850,000 has been allocated to 52 projects across four rounds, implementing measures like tree planting and leaky dams.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('68b1e391-34df-4f51-bd4a-04de7d75c075','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority declared a climate emergency in June 2019 and then pledged to be carbon neutral by 2038. To meet this target, it identified: The need for better housing stock data. Pathways for achieving net zero. Estimated costs and savings. Alternative funding models to finance decarbonisation. A targeted list of projects that local councils could focus on in the next five years. [18]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Energy Saving Trust: Housing Stock Data and Retrofit Strategy','Energy Saving Trust','2024-10-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGeRNKXW6WKe6CCdFIx8KvVokDYiBD-DImlyHlPjwADPczQhSihxL8xLYJxW6DzJLymP0n9pj9X3rRhr4fa_80OYJlW9KFhFlXH7-t5MfZrqBiPA7J4GlhwOtqk3MQM9q8ZKK12qyGsS5v43Ap2Oy4WXQ02ZS1hKF_Y7Ee44FYziN2-wPI9wnvbIg==','In October 2024, Energy Saving Trust provided housing stock data, scenario modelling, and service analysis to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and councils including Bradford, Calderdale, and Wakefield. This project aims to inform their climate change strategy and future decarbonisation efforts by identifying energy efficiency characteristics and optimal retrofit strategies for residential properties from 2022 to 2038.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('68c01834-3c09-4bdd-8e5e-b4e852b4ceef','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'During the Bradford Showcase event, held alongside the UKREiiF regeneration forum, Bradford Council revealed that global consultancy firm Arup has been appointed to develop a comprehensive master plan for the ambitious Southern Gateway project. ... Located in the heart of the city, the Southern Gateway spans key corridors along Manchester Road and Leeds Road. The area is set to feature high-quality, high-density office spaces, commercial hubs, and residential developments, all integrated with new public spaces and green areas. Over the next 12 months, Arup will craft a detailed master plan that outlines specific proposals for the site.','Bradford City Centre Expansion Takes Step Forward with Arup\'s Masterplan','Public Sector Executive','2025-05-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHYrVaZTgmfSgtomR-drGJ3yah0fpESuk1KdUv85eT_ev1DcIBVUWtcUyE2XjdulUQBCMD34OC5LCPk9U1I-Iv7F4hlJO6e_TtFW1_48B3dOVKo1A4SXgkCKpcVGRQ8Wa6lP9tKUsn4cAjpXYGO9TmcF_Ba_AZpL2NcKytcSGgDdsAQoTSYU2K2BXOLRUQHD5eB36fO68g31PmiWB6R0HUioo1uefsO','Further details emerged following Arup\'s appointment, outlining that the Southern Gateway project, spanning key corridors along Manchester Road and Leeds Road, will feature high-quality office, commercial, and residential developments, alongside new public and green spaces. The comprehensive master plan is expected to be developed over 12 months.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('68ce9ecc-480c-4455-afe9-b93fe8bc4e17','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Starting in April 2024, the next phase of works will take place on Hall Ings, Bank Street, Market Street, Little Horton Lane and part of Bridge Street. This phase will see these roads pedestrianised and new public spaces created. [3] Since July 2023, our team has been working on making changes to the outer roads in the city centre. Now these works are nearly complete, these improved roads and junctions will create a dedicated public transport corridor enabling buses to flow around the city centre rather than through it. [3]','Phase Two Construction Begins on Bradford City Centre Pedestrianisation','Future Bradford','2024-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.future-bradford.co.uk/construction/phase-two-construction','The next phase of construction for the Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements scheme, Phase Two, commenced in April 2024. This stage focuses on pedestrianising key city centre roads such as Hall Ings, Bank Street, Market Street, Little Horton Lane, and part of Bridge Street, to create new public spaces and transform how people access and use these streets. Prior to this, work on outer city centre roads for a public transport corridor was nearing completion since July 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('690e1b39-98cf-4d48-8378-65bbab2329a3','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A YouTube video by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority showcased the region\'s plans for a new Mass Transit system. It stated that £200 million has already been allocated by the government to develop the case and undertake initial consultation and development of plans for a mass transit system between now and 2027. The Mass Transit system is described as a large-scale public transport system that typically uses modern high-capacity bus, tram, or tram-train type vehicles to connect cities and suburban areas. Construction of phase 1 (Bradford to Leeds and St James\'s to White Rose lines) is expected to start in 2028, with first services in 2031 and completion by 2040.','West Yorkshire is gearing up for a new Mass Transit system','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (YouTube)','2024-02-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J3W1_N_7a8A','This YouTube video from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority discusses the region\'s ambition to create a new Mass Transit system. It highlights that £200 million has been allocated by the government to develop the case and undertake initial consultation and development plans between 2022 and 2027. The video emphasizes that Mass Transit will be a significant, transformational investment for West Yorkshire, aiming to connect communities, drive economic growth, and create a greener, fairer, and healthier region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('69d86719-c715-4992-930a-8a502a08c925','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In February and March 2024, Archaeological Services WYAS undertook a trial trench evaluation at Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works comprising the excavation of 56 trenches targeting anomalies detected by a previous geophysical survey and apparent \'blank\' areas. ... A probable Neolithic barrow, based on its form, was observed in Area 3, but no artefactual remains were recovered to confirm its date.','Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works, Huddersfield, West Yorkshire: Archaeological Excavation','Archaeological Services WYAS (via Archaeology Data Service)','2024-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHfwh6YpLgUBI0IzUGFZaw5K6cPiRYFqdjNrDHQuakpMdiZhcBNK2CivR10fctNe5RB2oYn_Opf63H2IZHGyRliVxLCV4rJBcjkkIO1k-7tUi_hqMXGA3yOUigARLE1AEqPiwH_lf6VhPw-d-TkSWCVroVc0GMP347l_Qxxq3WCwqjj8cMDufjkjuCH99cEJrHiDAldgLYXaHbHnHKN40DK4H62Tw==','Archaeological Services WYAS undertook an archaeological excavation, comprising three open areas and 56 trial trenches, in February and March 2024 at the Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works site. The excavation aimed to investigate previous geophysical survey anomalies prior to the construction of the new integrated wetland. A probable Neolithic barrow was identified, but no dateable artefacts were recovered. Evidence of extensive mining and post-medieval/early modern farming was also found.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('69fdd68c-793a-4d42-849c-6d8551a2606b','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.902','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A Public Inquiry was held on March 4, 2025, at Halifax Town Hall concerning land acquisition and the use of Compulsory Purchase Powers for the A629 Phase 2 Corridor Improvement Scheme. This inquiry also addressed the \'Borough Council of Calderdale (Halifax town centre) (Highway improvements) (West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund, A629 Phase 2) (Side roads) Order 2020\'.','Public Inquiry for A629 Phase 2 Compulsory Purchase Orders and Side Roads Order 2020','Calderdale Council','2025-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/streets-and-transport/transport-improvements-and-initiatives/a629-phase-2-public-inquiry-2025','A Public Inquiry was held on March 4, 2025, at Halifax Town Hall concerning land acquisition and the use of Compulsory Purchase Powers for the A629 Phase 2 Corridor Improvement Scheme. This inquiry also addressed the \'Borough Council of Calderdale (Halifax town centre) (Highway improvements) (West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund, A629 Phase 2) (Side roads) Order 2020\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6a0b931a-9f75-4669-af26-6a9c2c338c49','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A PLANNING application for one of the biggest developments in Bradford city centre has finally been submitted. Plans for a new office development on the site of the former Tyrls Police Station in City park have been in the pipeline for years. The 56,000 sq ft office building is expected to cost around £35m, with some of the money coming from the Government\'s Getting Building Fund. The plans are supported by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Bradford Council. Yesterday the planning application for the development was submitted - revealing more details about the proposals. It says around 450 jobs will be based in the new building, and that the development will \'complete\' City Park.','Plans for multi million pound \'One City Park\' finally submitted','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2021-07-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFhuYsmGlDFZTKXlKBeA2Zs5jH6s1TLCXmibyV3Y5S_mYHG99ouMoSnqzC5_8jcU39LQDWoMAZPQq6qCMhbS_3A_L1nqUvCiKvjn-SIhhqfU_1lA_2OJVEtgCnqQV63OAT2cip6BoSuHOFx2LxuvLv-mB7TPtJzboK-zKfxG2GM9gPnEbdJIAgHaOmkf71DbuwfXG6TqqJbgRjFp8Zivbz2ayCWhyGevIkV','A planning application for the One City Park office development on the former Tyrls Police Station site in Bradford city centre was officially submitted. The £35 million project outlined plans for a five-storey office building with ground-floor retail or leisure space and the creation of new public realm, projecting approximately 450 new jobs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6a1a3672-157f-4a01-9782-fc8db574836c','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The transformation of Bradford\'s former retail heart into a vibrant new sustainable community known as \'City Village\' has taken a further step forward with the launch of the final phase of public consultation. Detailed plans for phase 1 of the neighbourhood, which ECF, our partnership with Homes England and L&G, is delivering in partnership with Bradford Council, were revealed today (Wednesday 21st May) as part of Bradford Council\'s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock, which is running alongside this year\'s UKREiiF regeneration forum. [15]','Community Conversation Launched on Final Phase of Public Consultation for Bradford\'s \'City Village\'','Muse','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.museplaces.com/news/community-conversation-launched-on-the-first-phase-of-bradfords-game-changing-city-village/','The final phase of public consultation for Bradford City Village was launched, revealing detailed plans for Phase 1. This phase includes the creation of 33 townhouses on Chain Street and 64 townhouses on the northern Oastler site, alongside supporting infrastructure and green spaces, ahead of a planning application submission.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6a2168dc-f051-4dc6-9cd6-ee3ab5e692ce','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced a new Digital Inclusion West Yorkshire programme with £746,000 in funding. This programme will extend the successful 100% Digital Leeds model to Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield, fostering digital inclusion across the region. The aim is to help digitally excluded people get online and confident with technology.','Digital Inclusion West Yorkshire Programme Announcement','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2023-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/growing-the-economy/business-and-skills/digital-inclusion-west-yorkshire/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority secured £746,000 in funding to launch a digital inclusion programme, building on the success of 100% Digital Leeds. This programme aims to develop local digital inclusion initiatives in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield, helping people and communities across the region get online and be digitally included.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6a586a47-7449-492a-88e4-ef92e1db578d','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water is three quarters of the way through a £27.8m programme that will reduce the frequency and volume of storm overflow discharges at 41 of its wastewater treatment sites across the region. When complete, the investment will see over 13,000m3 of storm water storage capacity, which will hold 13 million litres of wastewater, added to the network by April 2025. Of the 41 projects, there are 24 in North Yorkshire, seven in West Yorkshire, four in East Riding and four in South Yorkshire. This programme is focused on increasing storm water storage and is in addition to a further £180m investment to reduce storm overflow use and improve water quality in our region\'s rivers by April 2025.','Yorkshire Water makes progress on county-wide £27.8m storm overflow scheme','Doncaster Free Press','2024-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/yorkshire-water-makes-progress-on-county-wide-ps278m-storm-overflow-scheme-4860228','Yorkshire Water is three-quarters through a £27.8m program to reduce storm overflow discharges at 41 wastewater treatment sites, adding over 13,000m3 of storage capacity by April 2025. This initiative is part of the broader £180m investment, with seven projects located in West Yorkshire, contributing to improved water quality across the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6a9691bd-a89b-48b8-a942-c71b49eb0926','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The programme will also enable improvements to the Kings Road corridor to create high quality public transport and cycle lanes linking Five Lane Ends and new developments in Bolton Wood to Bradford city centre.” Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin said \'he £830 million investment will… New bus priority measures and cycle lanes will be introduced on Kings Road and Canal Road from January 2026.','Major Bradford road schemes to pedestrianise big chunks of city centre - Yorkshire Live','Yorkshire Live','2022-08-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4CEZcqwlBO9hGIvvp7mjEnDCE7hmzolVdiuB6q5xaLAG5pMgdjzJ_D7ZlJ_KhuEch-PxE0BxHG_vk_RybQYKiOYfjLtz2_U1ipeytMJBq96dpF5n5EzDxHXalegsve7T2gYQk1yHDQpxa7kh_aoqf1qb-19sFA6UDY-dUOkQGEQ6OcIdCZyzCv-jlVPi57IPoZ4iV9D_rnJyDk81Fvb2J_zUVRoM=','This article details the initial announcement of the £830 million City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) for West Yorkshire. It mentions that this funding will enable improvements to the Kings Road corridor, creating high-quality public transport and cycle lanes linking Five Lane Ends and new developments in Bolton Wood to Bradford city centre. It also indicates that new bus priority measures and cycle lanes on Kings Road and Canal Road are expected to start in January 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6aa9227f-30d7-4508-a42b-e30256e2a606','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority has released a consultation report which indicates that more than two-thirds of people, surveyed across the region, are supportive of plans to create a tram system. The system would initially cover Bradford and Leeds. The feedback will help the Combined Authority select its preferred scheme later this year, before consulting on a detailed version of the preferred route in early 2026. The route options consultation for phase one of the West Yorkshire Mass Transit scheme took place during summer and autumn 2024, and saw 4,845 individuals and organisations have their say. [24]','Consultation report reveals support for West Yorkshire trams','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-02-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGUAUKtmCDp7fUjiHLlSpzWckp_XyT_Fgwey2lOYQKx4aSLjkDIMxJgG5UblQhbXJPQRDnJ2VDIikFNe-cTXD4KHeaCXdIDzW1WwuAsqkKSb4F2Gy7NoXSOphRSVI8tx1cN5FAYfUzyJfWAPt8paIpCtDZ_gsX2kMAefUqBeK--8_vPlOkdFvFmENPAqqaH4M-sI7r_wtiNmWHpd60-9sxCg3qqqsociAp7','A consultation report released by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority shows strong public support for a new tram system, initially connecting Leeds and Bradford. The consultation, which involved 4,845 individuals and organizations during summer and autumn 2024, found that over two-thirds of respondents in West Yorkshire supported the plans. The feedback will guide the selection of a preferred scheme later in the year, with detailed route consultations planned for early 2026. [24]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6acb88cb-143c-495c-87ef-7a4758537c9b','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Live, with architect Aedas Arts Team, submitted a planning application to Bradford Metropolitan District Council for the transformation of the former Odeon Cinema into a 4,000-capacity live entertainment venue. The project aimed to restore the building to its former glory while modernising facilities, anticipating £10.4 million annual economic impact.','Bradford Live submits planning application for former Odeon','Access All Areas','2018-12-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHcFzQH9z9F5hlJ4uDk3wpVZkBXR-VvwVZm_KOus7uwJpA8Sc7H1KBtUZO47bex5h3rOdPQxUZiy1QNHbiRJSDr0hkdQMT9m_UlFHSJ3mFB66Qr9XDj3G3lSDCTusmHBwH7QpsdOWlUedEVeTpj_P8Nq1HMRZ5W80aPGzRAh7n2077-OOaoWXJgbdXWNWE=','Bradford Live, with architect Aedas Arts Team, submitted a planning application to Bradford Metropolitan District Council for the transformation of the former Odeon Cinema into a 4,000-capacity live entertainment venue. The project aimed to restore the building to its former glory while modernising facilities, anticipating £10.4 million annual economic impact.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6ae51ec0-3776-4938-beb5-f800a5d74630','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Landowner Emma on how she allowed natural forces to block Hebble Brook and flood the adjoining field. Where – Old Fulling and Worsted Mill site on Hebblebrook North Halifax. When – Approximatley 2022. Design and implementation – No specific design but natural tree fall and river debris allowed to build up to cause a blockage to slow the flow. This was left to work in its own way. The adjacent field is allowed to flood as necessary and the mill pond inflow was cleared to facilitate natural filling of the mill pond (usually dry) by the brook, to retain more of the water. The overall effect of this is not measured but it is the intention of the land owner to continue to allow a more natural slowing of the water and hopefully some planting in the flood plane area to help absorb some of the water/moisture.','Case Study at Old Fulling and Worsted Mill site on Hebblebrook - Natural Flood Management','Slow The Flow','2024-12-06 00:00:00.000','https://slowtheflow.net/case-study-at-old-fulling-and-worsted-mill-site-on-hebblebrook/','This case study describes a natural flood management initiative at the Old Fulling and Worsted Mill site on Hebblebrook, North Halifax. Starting around 2022, natural tree fall and river debris were allowed to build up to slow the flow, allowing the adjacent field to flood. The landowner intends to continue allowing a more natural slowing of the water.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6b052b76-33fe-4e46-8d45-fb61aa60f188','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Almost 5,000 individuals and organisations took part in a consultation with West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) back in February. Two-thirds were in favour of the proposed route for the tram. The to connect the city to Leeds city centre covering areas such as Thornbury, Laisterdyke, Pudsey, Armley and Wortley. The WYCA is using consultation feedback to help select the preferred options for the tram system. [20]','£2 Billion West Yorkshire Tram Network Serving Leeds & Bradford Takes Step Closer','Time Out (reporting on WYCA consultation)','2025-06-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.timeout.com/leeds/news/2-billion-west-yorkshire-tram-network-serving-leeds-bradford-takes-step-closer-060225','Following the summer 2024 public consultation, almost 5,000 individuals provided feedback, with over two-thirds expressing support for the proposed Bradford to Leeds line. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is now using this feedback to select the preferred route options for the tram system.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6b5b7baa-19eb-4279-a971-8112c7b2fbc2','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £55m+ heat network project is proposed in the South Bank area, one of Europe\'s largest brownfield redevelopment sites. This may serve as an extension to the existing Leeds PIPES network. LCC secured £24.5m from the GHNF in December 2023. The network plans to connect to 28 buildings, with up to 8,000 residents and mixed-use customers benefitting from connections. The project aims to use waste heat from a glass factory and water source heat pumps, utilising the River Aire. Air source heat pumps and electric boilers will provide peak heating and backup. A significant portion of construction and spending is planned for 2025/26. [14]','Heat Network Zoning Opportunity Report - Leeds','GOV.UK','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEoMYdudKkHkTSXCw1MgRGYzJR5nuZipIU00hmIbegFuuZrWRCsS799J-fPfiXoCsuFY3qywhpwnrz53UZ6MacLH4MQeGf30bZwhgYHfmzjY3M47LsWmVTR8g0Id_EYd9Rj3f22QWBTf_ohWNS_GiE1Iq-rFRmFhZNZhcsKKn6nzeM7k149N-R3VDWwxIS5ycyVO7cFEwWtb4_fD-FNuNyca2Y0cBUlQCRpRdKWEamG0Qs','This GOV.UK report outlines a proposed £55m+ heat network project in the South Bank area as a potential extension to the existing Leeds PIPES network. It confirms Leeds City Council secured £24.5m from the GHNF in December 2023, with plans to connect 28 buildings for up to 8,000 residents, utilizing waste heat from a glass factory and water source heat pumps, with significant construction and spending planned for 2025/26.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6b76139c-fe62-400c-b364-211e8c125ef0','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This annual report by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) details the progress of the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) programme for the period 2023 to 2024. It indicates that programme governance was established and embedded, with 24 CRSTS business cases approved and 28 projects (including 20 maintenance sub-programmes) starting on site. The Leeds City Square pedestrianisation project was completed. The financial spend for FY 23-24 totalled £96.3m, which was £6.7m (6.5%) less than the £103m baseline, due to underspending in a few sub-programme areas. The main challenge identified is the deliverability of projects by the March 2027 deadline. The programme\'s benefits-cost-ratio was updated to 2.32, remaining high value for money.','WYCA: CRSTS annual report 2023 to 2024','GOV.UK','2025-03-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/west-yorkshire-combined-authority-crsts-annual-report-2023-to-2024','This document provides a progress update on the West Yorkshire Combined Authority’s (WYCA) City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) programme for the financial year 2023 to 2024. Key achievements include the establishment of programme governance, the approval of 24 CRSTS business cases, and 28 projects (including 20 maintenance sub-programmes) being on site. Notably, the Leeds City Square pedestrianisation project has been completed. The report also highlights a slight 6.5% underspend against the baseline and identifies deliverability by the March 2027 deadline as the main programme challenge.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6bbe9590-6983-4bc2-b3eb-84abeed3a39c','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point located at Snowhill Starbucks, WF1 2UZ is part of the EV On the Move network. There are 2 devices and 2 connectors available at this charging location. ... Updated: 14th September 2025.','Snowhill Starbucks EV charging point, Wakefield - Zapmap','Zap-Map','2025-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHyplQBkwhYLqaAQXLBbKrmh0Cn0LahLbJI5bJxRAG_M5EtMrIIbZ7wjnYN6PXLtPfgx7p6gzh-eINkyXXe2h-I7JbOD_79t_HL5Lp9Cvb_oVtmQnx1N6qGSGBee7h9ous7CgS6vzHid6Zp491S4giMMvk','Zapmap lists EV charging points operated by \'EV On the Move\' at the Starbucks located on Snowfield Avenue (WF1 2UZ), near Snowhill Retail Park. This indicates additional EV charging options in the immediate vicinity of the retail park, distinct from the Osprey hub or the Aldi Pod Points.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6c435ffb-7af6-4e74-bd4a-1cd3621fbdf6','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-enquire-learning-trust-buckingham-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.379','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Enquire Learning Trust, Wakefield, School / Academy, £310,393. [3]','Enquire Learning Trust Listed as PSDS Phase 3a Grant Recipient','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: grant recipients - GOV.UK','2025-04-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHG2Eo_VRg1BXDYjFCuja06VKs4Rr6OTkKxbs7tQJxFXTJ1kDRh1xMNR0ElmTRxze6lsFktumXJRoeLi_x8kxsFcmumt-Ih1GeK0dRlyGLjT79KuNruEPJ3hJxbo_hnGD80TrBP_UYO04TwKzXFUc5bnxpun3WV7diyR1yWJlJggbcRKUGkbjHnAnfyWa6phgKEmWouoQIreQtzjMgw5tCF5KHLWgXVb3lNAKf-GCeq1wKy_vIERzrsnHezLJlW6rWZdRHcrPaf56l2B3uUpmS8Uak=','The Enquire Learning Trust, identified as a School / Academy in Wakefield, is officially listed as a recipient of a £310,393 grant under the Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. This confirms the trust\'s involvement in the government\'s decarbonisation efforts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6c5501c9-9945-458f-8b2e-b8a5f58615e7','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On March 20, 2025, a press release from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the Mayor of West Yorkshire announced new £5.1 million proposals for the \'West Yorkshire Places scheme\'. This multi-million-pound project aims to improve walking, wheeling, and cycling facilities across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield, with proposals including new street crossings, lighting, and traffic calming measures. Public feedback was sought on these proposals. [4]','New £5.1 million proposals to improve active travel across West Yorkshire','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH0dNvYixyRomRfPmSeknt5yEe18crZup-vE7qtz3h4fSEyIOSICTx7t_FCqMZV9IZkx1eMsZSvYbijUJPEVlbE9ZUCupbnR7kWwBgiCwIZZHQJ5vmq5_s7oGEJu8LtAapJdHiYmhAdnBE6UopsA1xKlmxbIOeKHkN4x9dkCd4dy3ukquWKEt6EsK_P1t8WkSqRvhNvk-oIFHT1-MpPHPSymwyT','West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the Mayor of West Yorkshire announced new £5.1 million proposals for the \'West Yorkshire Places scheme\', aiming to improve walking, wheeling, and cycling facilities across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield. The announcement marked the opening of a public consultation for views on measures such as new street crossings, lighting, improved green spaces, and traffic calming.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6c6f8706-4095-47d3-a6d0-95f1596d46b3','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Luminate Education Group is celebrating a key milestone in the transformation of Mabgate Campus, as the £27 million development reaches its topping out stage. [17] Delivered in partnership with GMI Construction Group, the project is turning a once-derelict site into a flagship centre for adult education in the heart of Leeds. [17] The new facilities will replace outdated buildings, providing cutting-edge spaces for University Centre Leeds and Leeds City College adult students. [17] The new development will provide 70,000 sq.ft of high-quality, sustainable learning space. [17]','Luminate Education Group celebrates Mabgate Campus \'topping out\' milestone','Luminate Education Group','2025-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE-PI_jJz8M9zpsgHS6JRkVKW7Hoju6n79HBM7UBshPmQV1_yo_IPaVrLzdktFMMXKtFSylH7sAW9j_PieUaW7mSZR202zfwgxjYdCTyMWkC2JGY5uBsXl09XV9Pfg3DAKQsRynGiXg1MYeugPwc09AkxBoTXgcgjiVOtHy9c6wsd5tFs0hkhlbaXrXDb9UgkGxi1gDQSkvZI0GKL_Os6I8lPBtmN3Gt5vntEX_zZ8ZuR1NN7tupEZT','Luminate Education Group, in partnership with GMI Construction Group, reached the \'topping out\' stage for the £27 million Mabgate Campus development. This signifies the completion of the structural framework for the new five-storey campus for University Centre Leeds and the purpose-built space for Leeds City College adult students, transforming the site into a flagship adult education centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6cc26783-30a0-4f61-9ec4-10bbb4bc35d9','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-weaver-network',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.799','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracey Brabin, has set out a new West Yorkshire Local Transport Plan, which details how future improvements will be prioritised through a vision for an integrated Weaver network, bringing together buses, trams, trains and walking and cycling routes. A 12-week consultation is underway, with views sought from Leeds residents on a draft of the plan, which has been developed in partnership with the region\'s five local authorities. ... an ambition to get spades in the ground on a mass transit system by 2028. [17]','West Yorkshire Local Transport Plan Consultation Launched with Weaver Network Vision','Dailymotion / Public Sector Executive','2025-07-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x8zt4b3','Mayor Tracy Brabin initiated a 12-week public consultation for a new West Yorkshire Local Transport Plan. This plan outlines how future transport improvements will be prioritized, centered around a vision for an integrated \'Weaver Network\' that encompasses buses, trams, trains, walking, and cycling routes, aiming for a mass transit system by 2028.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6cf59655-019d-438f-9eba-64cb411a0629','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The latest proposals for improvements to the eastern side of Halifax town centre are now available, showing how travel around this part of town will be transformed. Calderdale Council is delivering the A629 phase 2 Halifax town centre project, an ambitious regeneration project which is fully funded through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund. Details of the proposed changes to the Traffic Regulation Orders (TRO), show how the new layouts will work on the eastern side of the town. Amongst the proposals, the old route along Church Street to the eastern side of the former warehouses known as the Hughes Corporation building, will be reopened as the main road east of Halifax town centre. A new public space will welcome visitors arriving from the rail station, with new crossings providing a safe walking and cycling route into the town centre. Comments can be submitted until Friday 14 March 2025. This is part of an informal engagement ahead of a formal Traffic Regulation Order consultation later this year. [10]','Have your say on proposals for the east of Halifax','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-02-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/news-articles/have-your-say-on-proposals-for-the-east-of-halifax/index.jsp','Calderdale Council launched an informal engagement on the latest proposals for improvements to the eastern side of Halifax town centre. These proposals include reopening Church Street as the main road, creating a new public space as a gateway from Halifax Rail Station, and new crossings for active travel. The consultation ran until March 14, 2025, ahead of a formal Traffic Regulation Order consultation.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6d02c55a-6371-4034-8724-b670909c54d4','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council has partnered with charge point operator Believ to rollout a series of fast and rapid electric vehicle (EV) charge points across the district. Charge points will be installed across several council owned car parks and publicly accessible sites, helping to deliver a low-carbon and affordable transport network, create a series of EV destinations throughout the city and support the council\'s transition away from the reliance on fossil fuels. [18]','Leeds City Council rolls out series of EV charge points','GreenFleet','2024-10-31 00:00:00.000','https://greenfleet.net/news/31102024/leeds-city-council-rolls-out-series-ev-charge-points','Leeds City Council partnered with Believ to install fast and rapid EV charge points across the district, aiming to develop a low-carbon transport network and support the city\'s net-zero ambition. This provides context for the broader EV infrastructure development in Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6d537309-d834-4243-8752-9a91f7f4d885','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-06-09) Plans to bring trams back to West Yorkshire have secured a funding boost from the government. The Chancellor Rachel Reeves is to confirm the allocation of £2.1bn of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to start works on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. ... The funding will also support other transport infrastructure projects across the region including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield...','Government to confirm £2.1bn transport funding for West Yorkshire','Wakefield First','2025-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH9BYwkjMMhajiO7MygZTHnfzzeCXoicrADtdqkII5yQfmoWDRnGGkf8XFjnHJ_7U_jbIUG31wPzaO2gZAyrpHgWCWrqLpzvfcaGNrAO1xHKL5jnMi-4kgLCE9isokRGd_dbt7WCPaMeshJDz0P5OlObx5K8zQIojKQR-msiwP39CwIoiNw9nuiCok4LZhUOZhb9oHoR5Wpt4KnOuyNWDQ=','The Chancellor Rachel Reeves is set to confirm a £2.1 billion allocation of local transport funding to West Yorkshire, enabling the Combined Authority to commence work on a new tram project by 2028. This funding also supports other significant transport infrastructure projects across the region, including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield, extensive bus priority measures and cycleways on other corridors, and access improvements to unlock regeneration. This highlights the ongoing significant investment in West Yorkshire\'s transport infrastructure, of which TCF projects are a part. [19]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6d590dcf-4983-4eab-9001-2752d1d79484','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The cost of the new Huddersfield Bus Station has risen again – to £28.7 million. The new cost for the much-delayed bus station has emerged as Kirklees Council has granted planning permission. ... The modern new facility will include a new curved entrance canopy with a \'living roof\' filled with pollinator-friendly plants. The Henry Street entrance will be improved and bus bays inside the station will be reduced from 25 to 21. There will also be a cycle hub with secure bike storage, better shop fronts and improvement to the public space around the bus station. New facilities include a Changing Places toilet with extra features to meet the needs of people with disabilities. Environmentally-friendly measures include solar panels and an air source heat pump. ... The improvements are being funded through the Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund with money coming from the Government.','Planning permission granted for new Huddersfield Bus Station as cost rises to £28.7 million','Huddersfield Hub','2025-03-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFrP3_1MWmzbFy2xaEZKAMp4o2yk8jfW_3yB51QDoc86xw2_FWHR1l7EmYr5Fy73LCkw4RxZkf8leH99VR-NJdctOndlACZMxYVPBT8eNtqJz8nV19rxCl0CKvRD5kRsJHIJBMhwa1mvFAEtA5gzaRhdnLJZJfif4ssCbsEMBRAPLu1GqvTmxE28pHy72mcuREeqIINOhDZezrFMjgvIefatctcLP0QmjCoFWbJ-EmS0e0Rc4A=','Kirklees Council granted planning permission for the Huddersfield Bus Station upgrade. The project\'s cost has further increased to £28.7 million. The modern facility will include a new curved entrance canopy with a \'living roof\', improved Henry Street entrance, reduced bus bays, a cycle hub, and a \'Changing Places\' toilet. Environmentally-friendly measures such as solar panels and an air source heat pump are also planned.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6db82ff4-b6ee-4a89-9f4d-91bd8b491da6','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first phase of major resurfacing works on the A62 Leeds Road, Huddersfield, is now underway with drivers facing up to eight weeks of disruption and lengthy diversions. The works began last night (Mon) with highways chiefs closing Leeds Road at Bradley, from the junction with Bradley Road to the Kirklees Council boundary at Cooper Bridge. Work costing a total of £1.65m will also take place on Sunday between 8am to 6pm - but workers will down tools on Saturday. Other roads affected at Bradley Junction are Bradley Road, Lower Quarry Road, the A644 Huddersfield Road and the B6118 Colne Bridge Road. The works \'provide the foundations for the A62 to Cooper Bridge Improvement Scheme\'.','Huddersfield A62 roadworks and road closures as eight weeks of disruption begins','YorkshireLive','2021-10-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE84t6JM5Lb4zEX4hacJpXIv0e-E2ykaKMaJ1dA8sb_kVnY3sxlKdbFdqTeOUwLAaT2cfo8CN6XQT-CDG-6oHnx1NzPu7q3sBn2f3GrtTySobe4Ny_QgxCY6XYR-zqRTwEqwIgx9ZNI85zQW8zI4jaXlLLSqrZj5GqyrPch1oJfPAXU0Az4HKKeIf2t7z2ECBHd_HsdWU4TTnaiHc1Rek8Bq9g_Og==','A two-month scheme to resurface the A62 Leeds Road, from Bradley traffic lights through Cooper Bridge to Stocks Bank Road, began in October 2021. This resurfacing work, costing £1.65m, was stated to provide \'the foundations for the A62 to Cooper Bridge Improvement Scheme,\' highlighting ongoing preparatory infrastructure work in the vicinity of the Bradley Park housing project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6dfa95e4-207a-4348-bc61-a8ccdbe3b8f7','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Works to pedestrianise key areas in Bradford city centre continue to \"progress well\", according to project bosses. [4] New paving has been laid down on much of Market Street to the western side. Work will now concentrate on the eastern side, where more paving, to provide wider footway space, and planting areas will be installed. [4] On Bank Street, work is continuing to prepare the area for more paving to be laid between Market Street and Broadway. The installation of new bollards will continue near to the junction with Hall Ings. [4] Transformation works also started on Bridge Street a few weeks ago, with new paving for the future service vehicle route being laid on the City Park side of the road. New paving has now been laid on the other side (beside the Ginger Goose pub) to widen the footway for pedestrians. [4]','Bradford city centre pedestrianisation \'progressing well\'','Telegraph and Argus','2024-06-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24419912.bradford-city-centre-pedestrianisation-progressing-well/','A progress report from June 2024 indicated that works to pedestrianise key areas in Bradford city centre were \'progressing well\'. New paving had been laid on much of Market Street, and work was concentrating on the eastern side for wider footway space and planting. On Bank Street, preparation for paving continued, and bollard installation near Hall Ings was ongoing. Transformation works also started on Bridge Street, laying new paving for service vehicle routes and widening footways for pedestrians.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6e74e8fa-dd9b-4cb0-bb68-b398df2a46d8','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Throughout December 2023 and January 2024, we began a conversation with the local community around our early-stage vision for Bradford City Village and asked for feedback to help shape the plans going forward. In response to the feedback we received during our visioning engagement, we developed a set of principles that are guiding plans for Bradford City Village.','Bradford City Village - Visioning engagement with local community and businesses','Bradford City Village Website / News Articles','2023-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF9KXpPoQOrGKno-_MI6C-XPS-jRstKGPi7YvwOxbeDmgbwg6hBnKKuIz36lnwYCOTT8C2wsMq6CaoaxdK1NYA2iucY9nHoitQDCr7v8fOe9buf2j_Usz6yOfQDEY4W7eC8LCH3014ub6ZS2UZUk1j620ntkG2oBKsmwWDmZzj1MA','Bradford Council and ECF initiated early-stage visioning engagement with the local community and businesses to gather feedback for the Bradford City Village masterplan. This initial consultation helped to shape the evolving plans for the regeneration project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6e82af27-507c-45cb-8de9-015ae0a8bd9c','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious plans to make it more pleasant to walk, wheel and cycle around Todmorden have now been revealed. The £2.56million Active Todmorden project aims to create healthier communities by enabling everyone to walk, wheel or cycle for everyday journeys and improving access to the town\'s attractions. The improvements will be seen from Rochdale Canal at the south of the town, to Centre Vale Park, and will include: Improvements to the towpath along the Rochdale Canal between Todmorden town centre and Walsden, resurfacing \'tipside\' between Hallroyd Crescent and the town centre (part of National Cycle Network Route 66), new cycle parking, improvements in and around Centre Vale Park, and improvements around Todmorden CE J, I and N School.','Step forward for Active Todmorden plans','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-06-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/step-forward-for-active-todmorden-plans','Calderdale Council revealed ambitious final plans for the Active Todmorden project, now stated at £2.56 million, aimed at enhancing walking, wheeling, and cycling. The plans include improvements to the Rochdale Canal towpath, resurfacing \'tipside\' of National Cycle Network Route 66, new cycle parking, and upgrades around Centre Vale Park and Todmorden CE J, I and N School. This followed engagement with the community in November 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6e8ace16-e8c8-4223-81e9-7730da825d56','infrastructure-five-towns-leisure-hub-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.669','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Progress is well underway at the new Five Towns Leisure Centre, with walls, ceilings and windows in place - and even the swimming pool beginning to take shape. The Leisure and Wellbeing Hub, which is officially known as Aspire@ThePark, is under construction at Pontefract Park. It had initially been expected to open this year, but the finishing date was pushed back after the site was hit by a major flood last year. New video footage of the site reveals that construction reveals that work is well underway, with power to the building and work almost complete in the tennis courts. The £20.8m Leisure and Wellbeing hub will feature a 10-lane swimming pool. [8]','Video shows work underway at new £21m Five Towns Leisure Centre in Pontefract Park','Wakefield Express','2020-10-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFP7JBCtt1ySJpcVEDsUJGJQN1MqpWxYeOZpQ3uBZkH6IkoFfWzH2Orv7mTpFteVk3PCeY-HL9hon_1XlJu1hxNeeFrgQGxVYMoGhyGX6_342wSvcKbA3imtyAklXjrdiVKseuw8uGx_6_qnJqmgl7nhKLEj9BFv-xWrhdi7fwpL4NlxHaVixRo6fBZetMlHfE-SssM4dKB8dXX8ZLh6hzysnsr4Cl3y40NP48Vkqn383LUBwDkCj3D1yD5xHv1m5ByuuArYCnN','New video footage revealed that construction was well underway on the Leisure and Wellbeing Hub, officially known as Aspire@ThePark, at Pontefract Park. Despite the earlier flood-related delay, the project was still on track for an early 2021 opening. The £20.8 million hub was progressing with walls, ceilings, windows, and the swimming pool taking shape.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6ea0c1fc-a20a-4916-b75c-017995060667','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford city centre is on the brink of one of its most ambitious transformations in decades. Backed by over £40 million in funding, the City Village project will reimagine the “Top of Town” area into a thriving new neighbourhood of homes, parks, and community spaces. At the heart of City Village is the creation of 1,000 new homes, a significant proportion of which will be allocated as affordable housing through partnerships with Incommunities. The development will feature two- and three-bedroom townhouses, complemented by 400 modern apartments on the Kirkgate Market site and more than 300 apartments on the southern Oastler site. Funding includes £13.2 million from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and £30 million from Homes England, alongside private investment from partners including Legal & General and Muse. The regeneration will unfold over a 10-year period, with demolition of outdated structures beginning later this year and construction starting next spring.','Bradford\'s \"City Village\": £40 Million Urban Regeneration to Create 1,000 Homes and a Greener City Centre','UK Estates','2025-09-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHSJRaQeYpT5S-zrlyudlW3MW9wJBleLtWeIyK-okVfI0BEUjLAvsEv7F23X_NVsbPJULfryjWGHD8cXrwMAhTf2U5gw3n_H-TsHhVWkAXIyE2WYeNr2-Wi0-W4B7G-QEbZhp0FoEIiqS9MpRUdd3rgmXznzdIwVmB2RussI4K4xGjN4JTezSvL41y4XZlrnN25Famc28mRJFrjoZJPcQGWz123rTifiN2ZRLKkgJulmb19K2s=','A comprehensive overview of the Bradford City Village project highlighted its scale and funding. Backed by over £40 million in funding (including £13.2 million from WYCA and £30 million from Homes England), the project aims to create 1,000 new homes, including affordable housing, across the Oastler, Kirkgate, and Chain Street sites. Specifically, 400 modern apartments are planned for the Kirkgate Market site, and over 300 for the southern Oastler site. The regeneration is expected to unfold over a 10-year period.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6efddd22-a8ab-449b-b7d3-a1b4c9e71c73','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Kirklees Council are developing Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans for West Yorkshire. ... Phase one of the LCWIP for Kirklees includes plans to improve walking in Dewsbury town centre, and to improve cycling provision in east Huddersfield. ... Further stakeholder engagement was undertaken in winter 2019 to get feedback on the proposals.','Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans: Kirklees | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2019-09-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/cityconnect/local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-kirklees/','This details the Phase One LCWIP for Kirklees, a collaborative effort between West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Kirklees Council. The initial phase concentrates on walking improvements in Dewsbury town centre and cycling provision in east Huddersfield, laying the groundwork for future active travel investment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6f0a200e-6b9b-4821-94ed-2a4ea950d15f','infrastructure-manchester-road-bus-improvements-scheme-south-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.869','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'\'In summer 2021, we consulted on proposals for a full Park and Ride scheme.\' This consultation explored proposals including a fully segregated, two-way bus expressway along the middle of Manchester Road. The cycle route was originally proposed as a segregated cycleway along the length of Manchester Road itself. Due to feedback and inflationary pressures, these plans were later revised and broken into stages.','South Bradford Park & Ride and Bus Expressway Scheme - Initial Consultation','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (referenced in 2023 consultation documents)','2021-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEtNmk1z-0hET_zqMXQVknb2Qk9MaXL9tHqYne_jU4C8A7WVkFJXk9B8nDiPLzcp3D0_fdDA6KsuABc21_GMZYZOIS1amevOOQx_9Etk_qkwuCMYnVcfYEDdo04zDSY7a55-MyNyfsum5wFv_7UIeTpkCJQ5fIj','This evidence references the first consultation on the comprehensive South Bradford Park & Ride and Bus Expressway Scheme. The scheme initially proposed a fully segregated, two-way bus expressway along Manchester Road and a comprehensive cycle route. Feedback from this consultation led to revisions in subsequent proposals due to inflationary pressures and public comments.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6fbe342e-dc68-4046-af44-612bd5fba1e2','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Storm overflow spill data released by the Environment Agency has shown how many times wastewater flowed into waterways in North Kirklees in 2024. A total of 68,164 spill events were recorded across the Yorkshire Water network in 2024, and the average number of spills per storm overflow was 31.4. This was 9,595 total discharges less than in 2023 (a 12 per cent reduction), and a 17 per cent reduction in the amount of time Yorkshire Water discharged to watercourses. In Kirklees, some of the EDMs that recorded a high number of spills compared to the rest of the area included, Warwick Road No 2 Combined Sewer Overflow (CSO), which spilt 70 times for 173.25 hours into Batley Beck.','Yorkshire Water announces progress on reducing storm overflow activity as new Environment Agency data shows sewage spills in Kirklees waterways in 2024','Dewsbury Reporter','2025-03-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.dewsburyreporter.co.uk/news/environment/yorkshire-water-announces-progress-on-reducing-storm-overflow-activity-as-new-environment-agency-data-shows-sewage-spills-in-kirklees-waterways-in-2024-4573177','New Environment Agency data for 2024 shows a reduction in sewage spills across Yorkshire Water\'s network, including in Kirklees waterways. This is part of a 12% overall reduction in discharges attributed to a drier year and the company\'s £180m investment program. The report highlights progress in Kirklees specifically, despite some individual overflows still showing high spill counts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901');
