	('6fc30721-1e31-46f6-a9fb-f1748c7580a8','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The development of Dewsbury Riverside is a key priority in delivering housing growth in Kirklees, being the largest housing allocation in the Kirklees Local Plan (Site reference HS61) and contributing to alleviating the significant housing needs across the district. The Housing Growth Team are working alongside Homes England, West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) and Network Rail, to progress funding and delivery partner options. Finalisation of Collaboration Agreement terms with the Savile Estate, negotiations with relevant landowners, the Homes England bid and securing a master developer are the key next steps to progress Dewsbury Riverside. This report updates Cabinet on the collaboration agreement and decisions required for finalising the agreement. In July 2024, community engagement consultants AR Urbanism were appointed by Homes England to develop a series of place-based indicators for Dewsbury Riverside. Notice of proposed decision first published: 11/06/2025. Decision due: Not before 9th Sep 2025 by Cabinet. (See Source [8] for full context).','Dewsbury Riverside Housing Delivery Update - Future Cabinet Decision','Kirklees Council (Council and Democracy)','2025-06-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/council-and-democracy/council-meetings/meeting-details.aspx?id=43939','A future Cabinet meeting, anticipated for June or September 2025, will determine a \'Housing Delivery Update\' for Dewsbury Riverside. This report will update on the collaboration agreement terms, negotiations with landowners, a Homes England bid, and the process of securing a master developer. It also highlights ongoing community engagement efforts, including the appointment of consultants in July 2024 to develop place-based indicators.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('6fe25059-a8f2-46d9-ab26-5d1b3db44c10','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'New images of a planned entrance to Bradford Interchange were released as the next stage of a public consultation began for the £16 million scheme. The scheme involves replacing the Hall Ings NCP car park with a \'pocket park\' and a new walkway, linking to the pedestrianisation of Hall Ings. Other planned improvements include relocating the taxi rank to Bridge Street, improved waiting areas, new baby changing, multi-faith room, Changing Places facilities, a new entrance to the underground car park, and a new cycle hub. Both schemes, carried out by Bradford Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority, were expected to be completed by late 2024, funded by the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund.','Plans outlined for new entrance at Bradford transport interchange','Business Live','2022-11-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEObnKuQyXjHQe8ouW0EvdDk4das_1_rs98LrO2D9EDJP73NvS3ZsdsVyHBvLZWfqEwfJzHYp3scKjNT1e0JlCAnOxppOATGroaTaXuASdq9CNCOk3o8pqscXGmY_fUS_yQ14EAjVD_Fz-FZPvsseUKsHNer5w22NtVJDTa_vtRLGHSkBcvdMbz-ebC9Nw7ejzuo_07run8SmP-Ql4v','A public consultation began for the £16 million scheme to create a new \'gateway\' at Bradford Interchange. New images showed the Hall Ings NCP car park being replaced by a \'pocket park\' and a new walkway. Other changes included relocating the taxi rank to Bridge Street, improved waiting areas, and new facilities. The scheme, funded by the Transforming Cities Fund, was expected to be completed by late 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('70812f03-2fa5-47bf-9ad9-c7396e90c1b3','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The following comments relate to the detailed plans and documentation which were submitted on 7 and 20 April 2020 as part of the above planning application for the demolition of existing structures, construction of new cafe & cycle hub, new taxi rank, public realm enhancement works including hard & soft landscaping, improvements to the cycle, pedestrian & multi-modal interchange arrangements and installation of new access lift at Bishopgate Street, New Station Street & Mill Goit, Neville Street and Dark Neville Street in the Leeds City Centre. [16]','Planning Application 20/02048/FU Leeds Station Entrance COMMENTS OF LEEDS CIVIC TRUST','UK Parliament Committees','2020-04-07 00:00:00.000','https://committees.parliament.uk/publications/4426/documents/45564/default/','Leeds Civic Trust provided comments on the planning application for the Leeds Station entrance improvements. The application involved demolition, construction of a new cafe & cycle hub, new taxi rank, and extensive public realm enhancements including landscaping, paving, and improvements to pedestrian, cycle, and multi-modal interchange arrangements at New Station Street, Bishopgate Street, Mill Goit, Neville Street, and Dark Neville Street.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('70e0d22b-7846-44f4-86d4-c361df1ac956','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The construction of the David Oluwale Bridge and the work on Meadow Lane and Crown Point Road is being jointly funded by the council, section 106 developer contributions and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, with the latter\'s share coming through the Government\'s Getting Building Fund. [19] The newly opened David Oluwale footbridge connects the development to Leeds train station by just a short walk. Those travelling by bike can now do so safely and efficiently as Leeds embarks on its mission to implement safer cycle lanes around the city including key routes on Meadow Lane and Crown Point Road. [28]','Construction Underway on David Oluwale Bridge and Key Road Sections','Leeds City Council News / Aire Park','2022-03-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEWDqYdwU4c2CwhR3nMQTmoOx82uIzvH80M3wpUF4nv3S7E7pK5zHlQDZRjge-cys_gg-x1EQ8MtqnD6Ieq3DDhH_NV8dRuaI2wy1d8TGIVT73_VQmDhEMLrEMAiIzdSLKxEHFdeV8yWah0MZhE7FZKT48Pea3V5pAia9UAeYHOm2WnvXTkC5Cn4G0eWhA4ZEm_tRRJDY2wNLA3hwd5jQ [19], https://airepark.co.uk/location [28]','Work commenced on the David Oluwale Bridge and improvements to Meadow Lane and Crown Point Road. This infrastructure is vital for connecting Aire Park to Leeds train station and enhancing pedestrian and cycle routes, funded jointly by Leeds City Council, developer contributions, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Getting Building Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('70eb8dad-9e17-489f-a46f-95a4b1108bb1','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Road users are being urged to prepare to plan ahead as works begin next month to make improvements to the B6157 Dawsons Corner junction, as part of the £44.179m Dawsons Corner and Stanningley Bypass improvement scheme. For six weeks between Monday 8 September to Friday 17 October, there will be a 24/7 lane closure on Bradford Road towards Stanningley (the eastbound lane of the Dawsons Corner roundabout) and vehicles will be diverted along the ring road. [16, 22]','Plan ahead: Dawsons Corner and Stanningley Bypass improvements upcoming lane closures','Leeds City Council News / Leeds City Magazine','2025-09-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFYyO0UZxPOeMLQvpfJL5aI8P7qMeG4ifCYNBZzTVrfvyKUOiXdFEa-B4SP6niJWPWlXnTWcD5SlfzBHudzYcJdU9wuYPLGBlTET7lKbHA8tuT-2DIZZBb_BYW55qdyAW88xhD7NJIausx5ncpMDCR9NNMfdxE8qmuD3vBdQoB4dRwhQ4U-sfmfPQLOM_axtDXrvNblkwvYq0w9t1EeyKwHnHb1jZ400GrZFnA0crc','Leeds City Council announced upcoming 24/7 lane closures on Bradford Road towards Stanningley (eastbound lane of Dawsons Corner roundabout) from Monday, September 8 to Friday, October 17. These works are part of the £44.179m improvement scheme and will facilitate junction realignment, new footways, and cycleways.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('70f8e593-1dfd-47bc-8671-4526c506e6e1','infrastructure-enfinium-skelton-grange-energy-from-waste-facility',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.539','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In February 2025, it was announced that the Aire Valley Heat and Power Network, an innovative low carbon heating and electricity scheme in Leeds, was awarded £19.5 million in funding from the Government\'s Green Heat Network Fund.','Aire Valley Heat and Power Network awarded £19.5 million from Green Heat Network Fund','enfinium, letsrecycle.com, theenergyst.com','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHs6t8YxNOHH0OUzaWM9H1oVnmMYXVBozYAV4G7CVJMoodDWJe-l77ADaQ0y8tlfiCKSfigVCVKf1GqBRe2NE7zpz6iHZ6HB2qrOAP_wbff1JCVVues6yr2HVGuO2rbo5RHsrH1Pw5Qgden-f-v1QblRvKLoO-aOsKYkoUz87DvANsGvWbYwiQdclw=','In February 2025, the Government\'s Green Heat Network Fund awarded £19.5 million to the Aire Valley Heat and Power Network. This scheme will utilize heat generated by the Enfinium Skelton Grange facility to provide sustainable heating to local businesses in Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('710ae54c-9330-41d9-889c-c118cdffe283','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Seven projects make up the Todmorden Town Deal and in addition to work at the Town Hall, the programme also includes improvements to active travel and public spaces; the redevelopment of the Hippodrome Theatre; improvements at Centre Vale Park and Todmorden Community College; and the creation of a new Enterprise Centre at Ferney Lee. Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet Member for Regeneration and Transport, Coun Sarah Courtney, said: \'Through the Todmorden Town deal, we\'re reinvigorating the building, preserving its heritage whilst making sure that its facilities are suitable for modern-day use.\'','New bar and new toilets at Todmorden Town Hall as part of landmark\'s transformation','Halifax Courier','2025-09-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/new-bar-and-new-toilets-at-todmorden-town-hall-as-part-of-landmarks-transformation-4780521','While primarily focused on the redevelopment of Todmorden Town Hall, this article mentions the Active Todmorden project as one of the seven key initiatives within the broader £17.5 million Todmorden Town Deal. It serves as a recent update reinforcing Active Todmorden\'s ongoing status as part of the town\'s regeneration efforts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('715d8327-2066-444a-92ba-771361870fcf','infrastructure-zapmap-ring-road-middleton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.435','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'After securing funding from the Government\'s Office for Zero Emission Vehicles (OZEV), the West Yorkshire Combined Authority appointed EQUANS to deliver 88 new charge points across West Yorkshire, all using 100% renewable energy. EQUANS provided free charging at all charging points for the first two years as a further incentive for residents and business users. The scheme has seen huge successes, with over nine million free miles provided to drivers since the launch in 2019. After securing almost £2 million from OLEV for the project and with £1.2 million in matched funding from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and its district partners, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority awarded EQUANS the contract to install and operate 88 new charging points across West Yorkshire. This network would be the largest rapid electric vehicle (EV) charging infrastructure in West Yorkshire, providing 100% renewable electricity supplied by EQUANS, using EQUANS\' own GeniePoint Platform EV charging technology.','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Equans: Installation of 88 new charge points','Equans','2019-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFqOx48uuib0uXtoY-F_lPIqa_8dgzXrQ83fYn0gs67YMYsjJtKQsemWeNbZeQn7s4NhcO-9FIEI0P0mT6hFOXKTXcsY7dwT528_7LJ4nH86DxazsmmYerH6JOUW_946HFmM3rgh0Pd','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) appointed Equans to deliver 88 new electric vehicle charge points across West Yorkshire. This initiative, launched in 2019, aimed to improve air quality and support the region\'s goal of becoming a net-zero carbon economy by 2038. The project received almost £2 million from the Government\'s Office for Zero Emission Vehicles (OZEV) and £1.2 million in matched funding from WYCA and its district partners.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7177c426-0b79-4d7a-8c22-13ed25698476','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Virgin Media O2 has today launched hyperfast gigabit-speed broadband for small businesses – offering the fastest widely available business broadband in the UK. Voom Fibre from Virgin Media now provides even more flexibility for small businesses, giving them a greater choice of download speeds: 400Mbps, 600Mbps, 800Mbps and 1Gbps. Voom Gig1 also offers small business customers 99.9% reliability, as well as 4G back-up from O2 and automatic fault reporting. [8]','Virgin Media O2 launches hyperfast Gig1 broadband for small businesses','Virgin Media O2 Business Press Release','2022-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFEt5zi5GAKUVihvDZQIxO57CCZvqAIEK6BFKQ183xqKm-uPlR65yfanP8fwmokK0IR8Zv3hz7TkLabUFZzzbKsxFfIWtHFUpE4GDpcH67gfEKwEC7Ygbo9UHT0p6ItKu3tDvcYvkJ-ooDuOTBncLOVIE-vH7njoH0c3UPpd4UCOs7vXGrEw6xvk6Lm5Rsd0IOyJmHm4w-0LM9iJThFqACTBfaS','Virgin Media O2 launched its hyperfast Gig1 business broadband across its entire UK network, offering speeds up to 1,000Mbps. This service, designed for small businesses, includes high reliability and flexible package options, providing the foundational product for initiatives offering free business broadband to VCSEs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('717a926a-d570-444e-97c8-e107f1cee162','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'ii) Northern Entrances – it is proposed that City Square and Bishopgate Street will be transformed and act as principal high quality entrances to the Integrated Station. Both will be predominately pedestrian spaces, with general through traffic removed. New Station Street is to be pedestrianised with existing structures removed to extend the space along to Bishopgate Street. This will create a new piece of major public realm at the front of the Integrated Station, whilst permitting access for taxis and public transport in the immediate environments. [17]','LEEDS INTEGRATED STATION MASTERPLAN','GOV.UK','2017-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/660144/Leeds_Integrated_Station_Masterplan_-_Nov_2017.pdf','This masterplan outlines a vision for the transformation of Leeds Station, proposing the pedestrianisation of New Station Street, the creation of principal high-quality entrances at City Square and Bishopgate Street, and the removal of general through traffic to create new public realm. It sets a blueprint for developing the integrated station and surrounding areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('71a6a502-dd00-4eaa-9c45-611ac06fbd8a','infrastructure-pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.548','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust has been awarded government funding for heat pumps and other energy projects to help reduce emissions from its estate. The grant – worth £0.8m – has been provided by the government\'s Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme, which has supported projects aimed at decarbonising public sector estates since 2020. ... This includes the installation of heat pumps, roof insulation and solar panels, together with upgrades to building energy management systems. [10]','Trust wins funding for green energy projects','Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust','2023-04-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.midyorks.nhs.uk/news/trust-wins-funding-for-green-energy-projects-7389','The Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust was awarded an £0.8m grant from the government\'s Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme for various energy initiatives, including heat pumps, roof insulation, and solar panels, across its estate to help reduce emissions. This indicates broader decarbonisation efforts that would encompass projects like the Pinderfields solar farm.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('71d25efc-31c2-4f20-bf84-a277ff380d9b','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council\'s cabinet is set to discuss transport improvements around the borough on Monday including the major work on the A629. According to the council, the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction project is “progressing well”. The project aims to improve road safety and journey times between Huddersfield and Halifax and will include improved facilities for pedestrians, public transport users and cyclists. Work is due to be completed by summer 2024 although some elements will be open earlier, such as the new link bridge. West Yorkshire Combined Authority is funding the project via its West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund. In late 2022, the combined authority and local councils carried out a review of the transport projects it had planned, outlining a number of changes to the programme to address inflationary pressures and to reduce overprogramming. The agreed position included funding increases to the first two phases of the A629 project, which also includes improving pedestrian and cycle access into and within Halifax town centre. The council estimates work on this phase will begin in early 2024. [18]','Photos of latest work on A629 between Halifax and Huddersfield and when the road improvement project is due to be finished by','Halifax Courier','2023-10-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/transport/photos-of-latest-work-on-a629-between-halifax-and-huddersfield-and-when-the-road-improvement-project-is-due-to-be-finished-by-4357908','An article reporting on the progress of the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction project (Phase 1b), stating it was progressing well with a completion target of summer 2024 for most elements. It also highlighted that funding increases were agreed for the first two phases of the A629 project, which includes improving pedestrian and cycle access in Halifax town centre (Phase 2), with work on this phase estimated to begin in early 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('71dfb189-32d1-4ea7-9b81-d695ae8ed803','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At PARKdesigned, we are pleased to be continuing our involvement in the delivery of the Aire Valley Energy Centre, a pivotal project that forms part of Leeds City Council\'s long-term sustainability strategy... We are now progressing the Stage 4 Building Regulations information in collaboration with the wider design team. This stage includes detailed coordination with structural and services engineers to ensure full compliance with regulatory standards and to refine the design for construction. Construction is anticipated to commence later this year...','Delivering Design and Efficiency at the Aire Valley Energy Centre','PARKdesigned Architects','2025-07-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFhDtUHl7hXGgGys8zKQmLeSdc9T4ZKv09-tSG4wy17x1bLLhWxbtWJrqFORWicdQKu_Hj33VkRW7tdYSODtwXDkR-r6vI_c32As-OpFAdEJ7nfpZINKPIVb21vBL94JgQhKsgJEH8qhrrEDFbE8YmJvvYkqrymY_95rxS-lLemRxil99mN0g5LZwi9KcaxWplI9AVYdKpYQG8N','PARKdesigned Architects announced their continued involvement in the Aire Valley Energy Centre project, which is a key component of Leeds\' district heat network. They are progressing the design to Stage 4 Building Regulations, with construction anticipated to commence later in 2025, indicating significant progress in the physical infrastructure development for the scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('71e24fcd-81e8-4539-ae59-10e2e9897186','infrastructure-west-bradford-junctions-improvement-scheme-a6177-ring-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.879','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Land assembly and supporting formal legal orders were sought by means of a Compulsory Purchase Order (CPO), and this was confirmed on 25 January 2021 and brought into operation. A link to the confirmed order and other documents can be found on the Great Horton Road and Horton Grange Road Compulsory Purchase Order page. [2]','Great Horton Road and Horton Grange Road Compulsory Purchase Order Confirmed','Bradford Council','2021-01-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.bradford.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-transport/major-highways-schemes/west-bradford-junctions-improvement-scheme/','The Compulsory Purchase Order (CPO) for land acquisition necessary for the Great Horton Road and Horton Grange Road junction improvements was confirmed on January 25, 2021, and subsequently brought into operation, allowing for the formal acquisition of land and rights.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('71fb580c-841e-4f02-9e8e-a64fc35a3dab','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Objections are raised as Hebble Brook runs across the bottom of this area where there are already businesses and housing near to Old Lane. This land is not suitable for development. Such an extensive greenfield is needed to soak up run off and run off from the existing roads and buildings at of the Boothtown areas. However, the site is likely considered to be developable and mitigation could secure the area from flooding. Mitigation could be secured through green and blue Infrastructure on site such as SuDS and green roofs to reduce the infiltration rate of precipitation as well as provide storage for storm water run-off.','Local Plan Initial Draft 2017 - LP1229 Near Royd, Ovenden - Comments on Hebble Brook flood risk','Calderdale Council','2017-09-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/sites/default/files/LP1229-NEAR-ROYD-OVENDEN-SA-REPORT-130917.pdf','Public consultation comments on the Calderdale Local Plan Initial Draft highlighted flood risks associated with Hebble Brook running across the bottom of the Near Royd, Ovenden site. Concerns were raised about properties being affected, pollution, heavy surface run-off, and the unsuitability of the extensive greenfield land for development due to its role in soaking up run-off.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('72166257-0726-4769-b6b2-2c22373436c8','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Flooding hotspots along the Calder Valley include Walsden, Ramsden Clough, Todmorden, Cornholme, Callis, Hebden Bridge, Cragg Vale, Mytholmroyd, Luddenden, Luddenden Foot, Sowerby Bridge, Copley, Elland and Brighouse. Surface water flooding has also been an issue across Calderdale with such incidents reported along the Calder Valley at Walsden, Hebden Bridge, Midgley, Blackshaw, Todmorden, Callis, Mytholmroyd, Luddenden, Sowerby Bridge and Brighouse.','Adopted Flood Risk and Drainage SPD - History of Flooding','Calderdale Council','2016-09-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEyb_iEfe8Aya8WyTVdzcAUkHbXa_5y3OcvHEORxYUnyoMMJ6Tu5R6Ao_LPp3oyfsBjHqWsLO-ecR1Rp2mRkWzL8HGu6ikDYGAVuSlwM2srBXarEzAtS1Rh_uVI6WmlBc-kwlHc23Kd3UaJjcqNqJxwQZA2HhgqmTBxNGt1Ov1OXGW-I5TPuUkfeCFSgLNYR0sThY-Z-fN1UQcvP1V8vmhsHt7lGHbRu_sJBwPtQlg8Er8gRKPVHHkX9rUt5IkY746AUOHwjy1Hh3osp-ktp0zn66r6Lg==','This Supplementary Planning Document from Calderdale Council details the history of flooding in the area, identifying Luddenden and Midgley as flood hotspots. It explains that runoff from steep moorland and sedimentation in drainage systems are major contributors to flood problems, underscoring the necessity of flood alleviation measures.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('721a97cd-3097-4463-9d57-71f1f387edd8','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire and York Investment Committee provided an update in January 2018 regarding transformational schemes, including \"Bradford Interchange redevelopment\" as Bradford Council\'s priority. It was allocated approval of £0.5m for the next stage of development. The interchange, built in the 1970s, needs investment to achieve a high quality contemporary gateway and arrival point to the city centre. A masterplan is being developed to modernise Bradford Interchange. Work on the scheme could start in September 2019, with completion by December 2020. Consultation will take place with Interchange users, including passengers, travel operators, taxi firms and businesses.','Plan for better links at Bradford Interchange gets green light','TransportXtra / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2018-01-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGnnMijhSc7QfRiMSadbXVW7iYvksC8_kgv8tjLl3n6K0ORVILFFsNASt0P0ltllOpWoIVC61c_NG9cr7PMnrvTEhOhf9q-GNBpQKUyGGBuUFjP2MxqTKXVsIlIjXFP6IGYAAkpVO7oAWAZMVgHBKuDkztsNBwSQYR2-KEFH2I5nhPLdTes9DBqzl84E0lfMTHgKp7ab1WUcXZMn23UdPfZ3mOkgEplLEehzY5nTvtaA_ou4d3RKrrRsNyijCLe4ug5LK0LH1a5','West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s West Yorkshire and York Investment Committee approved £0.5 million for the next stage of development for the \'Bradford Interchange redevelopment\', with a masterplan being developed to modernise the interchange. The overall project aimed to address poor quality design and functionality, creating a high-quality contemporary gateway. Work on the scheme could start in September 2019, with completion by December 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7227d818-99bb-4d53-a63e-862337534c58','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of the wider A646 Corridor Improvement Programme, work started on Friday 12 May to improve safety on this busy road, with work taking place between Stubbing Holme Road and the junction with Heptonstall Road. This involves the widening of footways and improvements to Heptonstall Junction. To carry out this work safely, it is necessary for temporary traffic lights to be in place.','Update on works around Hebden Bridge - A646 Corridor Improvement Programme','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2023-05-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHDfZkmzmsw8Lo1RCfD35aEn7MeJBGPl2RdzUeyvUFCv_Uqk5rOHSw3Dn9yAhaTIqK603M580O4SXlfZJmGyAPKchPlNZe-briowC2shWClntsHn9Sm5eCg72r8-44SB7gOzyhla96DAukC20ZfIs_KwW_GUIvirdNu0LbG12hg','Calderdale Council announced that work started on Friday 12 May 2023 as part of the A646 Corridor Improvement Programme. This specifically involved widening footways and making improvements to Heptonstall Junction between Stubbing Holme Road and the junction with Heptonstall Road, requiring temporary traffic lights.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('722b6f85-c9ee-4ba5-8b38-66c0dd1204e3','infrastructure-zapmap-ring-road-middleton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.435','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-08-01) Aldi Middleton charging point. This electric car charging point located at Aldi Middleton, LS10 4TQ is part of the Community by Shell Recharge network. There are 1 device and 1 connector available at this charging location. To plan your route or see the latest status info for this charge point, download the Zapmap app or go to the Zapmap web map. ... This electric car charging point is located at Ring Road, Middleton, Leeds, LS10 4TQ and it has 1 devices. This charging point is part of the Community by Shell Recharge charging network.','Aldi Middleton EV Charging Point on Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQET0Cvtmq-zOdqkwWpCofL7ERipXoul-x8-YorLj9KTLyIBxCJeQhvLQgOtZdQ1kWiCAPiv4wa4b2-5BCEvKi2WrLGjz2q8PXBUXQ-yccl_jTLeFsCRdFkLqnGd60C6v7Z-L0CRY6l5Cect2T4MtQ==','Zapmap lists an operational electric vehicle charging point at Aldi Middleton, located at Ring Road, Middleton, Leeds, LS10 4TQ. This charger is part of the Community by Shell Recharge network and features one slow device with a single connector. The listing was last updated on August 1, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('725f12bf-a64b-47ca-be4d-ddea6e21d860','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-transforming-cities-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.795','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Regional leaders are set to approve £40 million in funding to progress detailed planning and development for Mass Transit and bus franchising, two of the West Yorkshire Mayor’s top transport priorities. The investment will support the next phase of the Weaver Network – an integrated system connecting bus, tram, train, walking, and cycling routes – with the goal of breaking ground on the first tram route by 2028. At the West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting on 18 September, council leaders will review how the funding will: Advance technical and environmental assessments for phase one tram routes; Develop the business case for government approval; Prepare the scheme for entry into the Government’s Major Projects Portfolio (GMPP). The Combined Authority is also progressing plans to introduce a fully-franchised, publicly-run bus network in three phases between April 2027 and October 2028. [30]','West Yorkshire Mass Transit System Plans Progressing with £40 Million Funding','Public Sector Executive','2025-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.google/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEreUX1hGlOB1aPd0dhZDGVzzApSjdauIy6vPgTKRvsA-_8_YjunZ5vdFIg5HSxio_rvN7RjCnlcYOOw2yPIHnbbNQgV9UYtV6Uq4AmnCIjKkAgJ_7ZEar2aUaBo_yCBGmxM0b5U7a58gkZ1YsY2o_QeSzQ-AU2ajRg1P0Uxq_rWw8j08RHQV9g6aSdnW3CS680-lwy4zPG5ZgT','Regional leaders in West Yorkshire are set to approve £40 million in funding to advance the detailed planning and development of the Mass Transit system and bus franchising, key transport priorities for the West Yorkshire Mayor. This investment will support the next phase of the \'Weaver Network\', an integrated system connecting bus, tram, train, walking, and cycling routes, with a target of breaking ground on the first tram route by 2028. The funding will be used for technical and environmental assessments for phase one tram routes, developing the business case for government approval, and preparing the scheme for entry into the Government\'s Major Projects Portfolio.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('72638f75-2635-4c96-9300-ee35e518b79a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious plans to bring trams back to West Yorkshire, and deliver a multibillion-pound boost to the economy, have secured a major funding boost from the government. The Chancellor Rachel Reeves today (Wednesday 4th June) announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to get spades in the ground on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. [8] This substantial investment will also support other vital transport infrastructure projects across the region, including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield, extensive bus priority measures and cycleways on the A641 and North Kirklees transport corridors, and access improvements aimed at unlocking regeneration across six key neighbourhoods bordering Leeds City Centre. [12]','Major Government Funding Boost of £2.1 Billion Secured for West Yorkshire Trams','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / West Yorkshire Trams Project','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/major-funding-boost-secured-for-west-yorkshire-trams/ ; https://westyorkshiretrams.org/news/west-yorkshire-trams-project-secures-major-government-funding-boost/','Chancellor Rachel Reeves announced the allocation of £2.1 billion in local transport funding to West Yorkshire. This significant investment is earmarked to enable the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to commence construction on the tram project by 2028 and support other vital transport infrastructure projects across the region, including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield and improvements in Kirklees and Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7270ab50-69ec-4201-ac89-62077df42739','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Digital Hubs programme, part of the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, launched its first funding round for community organisations. The call for applications for capital grants up to £5000 opened in March 2023, with £20,000 available for the 2022-23 funding year.','UKSPF Digital Infrastructure Capital Funding - Year 1 Round 1 Opens','Kirklees Council / Third Sector Leaders Kirklees','2023-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.tslkirklees.org.uk/funding-news/digital-access-and-skills-training-uk-shared-prosperity-fund/','Kirklees Council\'s Digital Hubs programme, funded by the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, opened its first round of capital grants. Community-based organisations could apply for up to £5000 to improve their digital equipment or infrastructure, with an initial funding allocation of £20,000 for Year 1 (2022-23).','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('72732e02-a938-41c9-9023-edc90b3ed0f8','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Iqbal, Aisha. (2016). £125m \'eco village\' plan for Leeds. Source link [Accessed 7 October 2020]','£125m \'eco village\' plan for Leeds announced','Urban Nature Atlas (citing Aisha Iqbal)','2016-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFpWPvH1q_RSavFBFHFQXArIMWrd57eh0p3Xygr_Fbw_E4mFNdowbpLTJyy0J0hpoHLmy-hlQzTDTDbGg7Vs-cDPdu3Az_OJuQ0GcwZdTnIfDwYUwrk3jIMIr0KDIIms7fQ9Lq_CdUXXecpgvU5xkl9TA==','An early news report announced a £125 million \'eco village\' plan for Leeds, highlighting the vision for a sustainable development. This marked an early public declaration of the Climate Innovation District project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7298a15f-f92e-4cf4-8912-f43b2abab0d5','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for a tram system running between Leeds and Bradford have been set out today by West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin. The project will be subject to a full business case and approvals process. The mayor said work on two lines, serving Leeds and Bradford, could begin in 2028 with Government backing. The submission of the Combined Authority’s “strategic outline case” document to the Department for Transport is set to be approved by members of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on March 14. [17]','£2bn Leeds to Bradford tram plan unveiled','Construction Enquirer News','2024-03-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2024/03/07/2bn-leeds-to-bradford-tram-plan-unveiled/','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin set out detailed plans for a £2bn tram system running between Leeds and Bradford, marking a significant step towards the region\'s mass transit ambition. The Strategic Outline Case was to be approved by WYCA on March 14, 2024, for submission to the Department for Transport.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('72d401a9-56fc-4c3f-bd5c-1e544f256d6e','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Since 2018, local planning policies have required new charging infrastructure in all new developments with parking. [6]','Leeds City Council Implements Planning Policies Requiring EV Charging in New Developments','Leeds City Council news (referenced in various news reports)','2018-01-01 00:00:00.000',NULL,'From 2018, Leeds City Council\'s local planning policies mandated the inclusion of electric vehicle charging infrastructure in all new developments that include parking. This policy laid the groundwork for the expansion of EV charging facilities across the city, including potential locations like Whitehall Road. [6, 10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('73c753a0-40a5-43da-bcd9-3011d66eab21','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Specialist real estate finance provider Maslow Capital has announced the successful completion of an £18 million development finance facility to support Citu, a pioneering developer known for delivering sustainable, high-quality residential schemes across Yorkshire. The funding will facilitate the completion of a 87-unit residential development, District Lofts, in the Climate Innovation District, Leeds, one of the UK’s most ambitious low-carbon regeneration projects. Construction of District Lofts is underway, with completion anticipated in Summer 2025.','Maslow Capital Provides £18 Million Development Loan for District Lofts Apartments','Maslow Capital / Place Yorkshire','2025-02-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG8qU38cCgcMZ4WfxppRoWRPZQG0o4TwhkeaMT2nOUYudyrDFaQJ0g8F7Cj9ULNv21LjXjmC-JFEvKw7du3My72Yd1rH5wgs5vrETzLqAz3E9mYpfOkBnt76EnZa6kZIKjed3qOFlMt-mExuXHq-W3bgPOJD9gDkqmMWz4ojgqoHPqHSfxUlGGQ5QTDGqGRlAXfmpZ7uRJLNdvzQx3Ct28J9MZhLB0RFseGRR-_qQkzd4F0CxyPthhn9k1Rd5EbIyAlWjN5NRuFBN2YwYTJL-dc8gnHfAqmQljQRatd2w7dGwt5wVHznXIkLBozYgk8T48ybJ8PnfgpSpPyLrrgbPiczNvRrPRQaLkNRQ==','Maslow Capital provided an £18 million development loan to Citu to complete the 87-unit District Lofts residential scheme, part of the Climate Innovation District. This development includes a mix of one, two, and three-bedroom apartments, with seven designated as affordable, and is anticipated to complete in Summer 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('73c87f16-500c-482b-861e-27c3dc9f1dc6','infrastructure-north-halifax-streets-for-people-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.173','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The information below was presented during the public consultation between Monday 15 March to Sunday 25 April 2021. [6] \'I\'d just like to tell you a little bit about a project we\'re working on in North Halifax. which improves the streets for people in the area. and how you can get involved in helping us shape. it. more people have been enjoying the benefits of walking or cycling. recently this government funded scheme will allow us to make improvements in North Halifax. so people can enjoy a better experience around the areas they live and work... The project is still in its early stages which means we are developing the ideas for what to do and where to do it. it\'s really important that we get your input to ensure we are making the right changes in the right. places. so we are in a six week public consultation.\' [11]','Public Consultation on North Halifax Improved Streets for People (Round 1)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority, Calderdale Council YouTube Channel','2021-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEGyK3N5uP4L-1XsxSUs9cFq5J8-eRAURfkh9Lms721LqPNApIDCSDacSVikbfQPckRs1gZyEt0EcvLNRy0BRVnxZB_Cq35RM14-U2Mvo8ESjf3KgWX8aHOsy9zJd19XDT9gJKjsyGLpNu8X6_DwCMhIcg=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHRN2bqdUQfXWBfjw_Zf-_pQV3MgvFZNnP-zHnR0lHsZMJC_1UpbFccyOurnAiWFshFLVMbrbnU2I4T1m4it9eoWEk6I8UUMGas3jJrfn4fEp4kDKXvU96-w84raOl0uRWo3Kz09uuOV4BAaYdmDcsVlTQORZUEAVZ14uDCIvVgnh4M8OimNJyTcTc=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGDxFpIeIyRh508UwUW607n5DbIV7mOVomqP4DjUQGQ3xO0yYIPlcJwXJJwbPdX9VbHmSCmAB602qC6xhhy8zuGaC9nYgMioGFOV51HwBhhfcyKXySCV9Vmx7oh_jKWXRH6j6o4tK4=','Calderdale Council, in collaboration with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched an initial six-week public consultation from March to April 2021. This consultation sought public views on early ideas for enhancing walking and cycling routes and access to public transport in North Halifax, including plans for a new cycleway to Halifax town centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('741c56ea-fd2c-4678-bbe3-57f0c0bedbfd','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Lichfields, together with its partners Gillespies and Systra were instructed by Wakefield Council to prepare a forward thinking, visionary and sustainable concept for the rejuvenation and growth of the Knottingley and Ferrybridge settlement in West Yorkshire. The Knottingley and Ferrybridge Masterplan is an ambitious plan for regenerating both towns in a sustainable and unified way over the next 15 to 20 years. This is part of the Knottingley Action Plan which includes over 90 projects to achieve the shared Knottingley Vision of residents and businesses, developed in partnership with the Council. Its content were informed by a public consultation held in late 2020.','The Knottingley masterplan','Wakefield Council','2022-03-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQESi1MCqPLw0L5nIWaPwnqIYTTi6eLyIS802Xec9Xqx0Ih0WYoRXYVU0nvyGwrBqZ4ONEVpF-8aTcyKT8MKbqQqQKIo1ZxVO4MmnamPc8QOQMhZDl9uAi4yLVU6P-xnfmX46gwk31QSXnFwyC1qnsJHQede4a2EEUIPl_53lbhlv8b6I2qmxEVTF2vF6I5chNCEjA692AMNweHPd2MmaZcYeL95pzQ=','A comprehensive masterplan for the regeneration and growth of Knottingley and Ferrybridge, prepared by Lichfields and partners for Wakefield Council. It proposes significant developments including new homes, employment spaces, a new road, and improvements to the town centre. This masterplan informed the emerging Wakefield Local Plan and was developed following a public consultation in late 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7429c43a-2940-4c8c-9530-335747928579','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'To demonstrate support for Mass Transit to the Department of Transport, all West Yorkshire authorities were asked to agree the West Yorkshire Mass Transit Vision 2040 (August 2023). Kirklees Council signed up to the vision and is named in the document. However, it should be stated, that the adoption of the vision only commits the council to supporting the scheme in principle subject to further detailed work to be undertaken.','West Yorkshire Mass Transit Vision 2040','Kirklees Council - Issue details - Joint West Yorkshire Mass Transit Spatial Development Framework Development Plan Document','2023-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHhoWS26UtxwpoFzJZG70oSrmnZpi1DSN5iyg614Pqo0kZczRLwCEe6qeYy4rpLopd7ptI01WkEOQb_9SBv921_U1fb-5Q9kaBS_zIvm7-TOW3VWAMoFOLmhXMEdjQXxQmVHSZ7ydSm9vGhLhmbBrCdTaSJcFuwkFkq1FKoBdU=','All West Yorkshire authorities, including Kirklees, Bradford, Calderdale, Leeds, and Wakefield Councils, were asked to agree to the West Yorkshire Mass Transit Vision 2040 in August 2023. This vision outlines an ambitious and transformative plan for a new Mass Transit system to enhance urban mobility, drive economic growth, and address environmental challenges across the region. While supporting the scheme in principle, the adoption of the vision commits councils to further detailed work.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7495017a-7728-438f-b7d7-57fce060e0bc','infrastructure-bp-pulse-stourton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.422','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Successful Charge reported by a user on 2020-08-09T18:24:34Z, indicating the charger was operational. The station is described as having 1 Electric Vehicle (EV) Charging Station maintained by bp pulse UK and located at 53 Pontefract Rd, Leeds LS10 1SW, UK.','BP Stourton Service Station on PlugShare (User Activity)','PlugShare','2020-08-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.plugshare.com/location/269177','User reports on PlugShare confirm successful charging sessions at the BP Stourton Service Station as early as August 2020, providing evidence of the EV charger\'s operational status at that time.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('74f431a5-4815-4216-b011-ac16768aea35','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Huddersfield Bus Station (Phase 2) Biodiversity Net Gain Assessment Willmott Dixon Construction Ltd - Kirklees Council. ... Under the Environment Act 2021, developments are required to achieve 10% Biodiversity Net Gain (BNG) to ensure that biodiversity post-development is greater than that present pre-development (enforceable from February 2024 for most sites). ... The proposals comprise the transformation of the bus station, including interior concourse building refurbishment and reconfiguration, changes to the bus circulatory area, improvements to the approach to the bus station off Henry Street, and construction of a new canopy area adjacent to Upperhead Row.','Huddersfield Bus Station (Phase 2) Biodiversity Net Gain Assessment','Kirklees Council','2024-07-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFrpu5NnNlMP8hTJ8DUOC-t2S5FeIz3--MQkuocPe9PDuyUIOdEFs86YDMK1BDi8lVBRany8GpZ2VzlX2RSUgm5iKoZa7JQLweUO6-Q37UcS_K4oQYn8ApNXDPyzJvitAOaM5M8X5k4sLd5tMfmfRixpumQ-wch5fore0uBPRFH6fB57udf_f9nGe7g2bXXQy1gXRKL99mU2svfK8U6ryIXpOdCgVjuif5Og4rEIQvxTL3TmjhvAWWLEIyA5do8aFgPgbCdv-lEMPDaqHctkSV0_QiL9xGZ8lmKK8UaWwuDx1Z1K2vTc68L2FeCoYQ=','This assessment by Willmott Dixon Construction Ltd for Kirklees Council outlines the Biodiversity Net Gain (BNG) calculations required under the Environment Act 2021 for Phase 2 of the Huddersfield Bus Station transformation. It details the proposed changes to the bus station, including interior refurbishment, reconfiguration of the bus circulatory area, improvements to the Henry Street approach, and a new canopy, aiming for a 10% BNG.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('751369bc-e64e-412b-9109-9b84e11a18b8','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A 2km (1.5m) section of the Spen Valley Greenway will close from today (Monday) for six months as major improvements commence. The off-road path between Tesco supermarket, Cleckheaton, and Knowler Hill Tunnel, Liversedge, will have a smooth rolling surface, wider path, improved lighting and signage, and better access points to the route installed, which Kirklees Council said would make it “more accessible and safer for walkers, wheelers and cyclists of all ages and abilities.”','Spen Valley Greenway: 2km section between Cleckheaton and Liversedge to close for six months as it undergoes major improvements - Dewsbury Reporter','Dewsbury Reporter','2025-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.dewsburyreporter.co.uk/news/transport/spen-valley-greenway-2km-section-between-cleckheaton-and-liversedge-to-close-for-six-months-as-it-undergoes-major-improvements-4659427','This news article confirmed the six-month closure, starting June 9, 2025, of a 2km section of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton\'s Tesco and Liversedge\'s Knowler Hill Tunnel. The closure is to allow for major improvements, including a smoother, wider path, enhanced lighting and signage, and improved access points to make the route safer and more accessible.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('751b7d56-e051-47ca-ac92-675cadb987ba','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Sustainability leads Huddersfield\'s bus station redevelopment. ... Plans for the bus station include a 120m long green roof and solar PV canopy. The plans are being submitted by Stephen George + Partners (SGP) in conjunction with AHR. The bus station transformation is a partnership between Kirklees Metropolitan Borough Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority. ... Plans were submitted on 13th August to Kirklees Metropolitan Borough Council and show a biodiverse roof, which includes a sedum green roof covering, 148 solar photovoltaic rooflight panels and mansafe access points. ... If planning is granted, work is expected to start on site in the Summer of 2025.','Sustainability leads Huddersfield\'s bus station redevelopment','NewStartMag','2024-08-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG9xCGScGqHp8iD08jCCeoniP9ziTa6dgbeW1iFDegu-nZgyulL80LWzF6rrlnKsTA13Nyv-D9uAH0fWhqxIF9WWLoi5pvKRMb2S7oJOOpzmaXTtr_Ej7Rgb7pGYP5FwQuDFkctoCaGNV2hK0eofPD5YCmO6Ukv9WV_8AFtYhkTU39sZ4XregpAgDPI3_bliir5p04DGkj6Rpk94w==','Stephen George + Partners (SGP), in conjunction with AHR, submitted plans for the Huddersfield Bus Station redevelopment, emphasizing sustainability. The plans, submitted on August 13, include a 120m long green roof with sedum cover and 148 solar photovoltaic rooflight panels. The unique roof canopy design is inspired by the Yorkshire landscape, and work is expected to start in Summer 2025 if planning is granted.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('75535966-2d47-41fd-8295-1e627838262f','infrastructure-proposed-highway-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.142','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans are moving forward to transform travel in and around Hebden Bridge, to help make it safer and healthier for people to get to the town, and to support local businesses. Following the pause to the Fallingroyd part of the £5 million A646 Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP), Calderdale Council has now agreed a way forward. In the near future, the pedestrian crossing on Station Road will also be improved and the speed limit between Mytholmroyd and Hebden Bridge will be reduced from 40mph to 30mph.','Moving forward to transform travel in and around Hebden Bridge through A646 Corridor Improvement Programme','Calderdale Next Chapter','2025-02-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHnx3h8hk1wSEIhKgbxyF2SqeBKr5Rtjtx7MHJqwK-zO6yQiOuGKwVDkCFlg-Qx89wGMQO462WYGAQzfcL9S9ArH4grTRI4vz-6kKbvM-8_xnfq0UvDWnLzUtyqKP3chpdhqTrKYxC8xpvTtE_NIU8yS8Knj-jcg6lHiXEVzUUu0r6r5JS6-GYN4MBx7z5CQZzOHMyu8m_0wVnMxUc=','Calderdale Council has agreed a way forward for the A646 Corridor Improvement Programme in Hebden Bridge, focusing on improving road safety, journey times, and promoting active travel. This includes revised plans for the Fallingroyd section, improvements to the pedestrian crossing on Station Road, and a speed limit reduction between Mytholmroyd and Hebden Bridge.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7568ade9-129c-4607-83bd-d67759725229','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'New images have been released showing how work around Halifax town centre will transform travel, with new safer ways for people to get around and welcoming areas into and around the town centre. Calderdale Council is delivering the A629 phase 2 Halifax town centre project, an ambitious regeneration project which is fully funded through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund. New images illustrate how the project will create new public places, routes for safe and efficient travel, and new cycle routes. Work on the project has been progressing well, with the first phase of work focused on the west of the town. Construction work is being carried out by Galliford Try. Work will be completed in three parts; western, eastern and central; with work on each section to run consecutively to minimise disruption. [12]','Images Of How Revamped Halifax Will Look','Calderdale Forum 50 Plus (referencing Calderdale Council)','2025-01-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdaleforum50plus.com/news/images-of-how-revamped-halifax-will-look/','Calderdale Council released new images illustrating how the A629 phase 2 Halifax town centre project will transform travel, create new public spaces, and establish new cycle routes. The project, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is progressing well, with initial work focused on the western side. Construction is being carried out by Galliford Try, with work planned in western, eastern, and central sections consecutively.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7685a7c5-d489-423b-bf4f-ce0c6ce4e0c2','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Our consultation findings. We consulted on three possible options to improve transport links to Leeds Bradford Airport. These plans included building a new parkway train station for the airport and increased road access. Plans for a new train station received support during the consultation. However, none of the road proposals received clear backing. We have also since declared a climate emergency and committed to becoming a carbon neutral city by 2030. Due to a lack of support for the road plans and concerns about their environmental impact, we\'ve decided to create a new plan which promotes more sustainable travel to the airport. A report on these proposals was taken to the Leeds City Council Executive Board on 7 January 2020. [17]','Leeds Bradford Airport and North West Leeds Employment Hub: access improvements - New, greener plan','Leeds City Council','2020-01-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/connecting-leeds-bradford-airport/airport-and-north-west-leeds-employment-hub','Following a lack of public support for previous road proposals and increasing environmental concerns, Leeds City Council announced a new, greener plan for airport access. This revised strategy prioritises sustainable travel, including a parkway station, park and ride facilities, and active travel routes, while reducing impact on green belt land, shifting away from major new road construction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('76ae8a54-f211-4d25-8a80-656da58b7c08','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Providing an accessible, attractive and cleaner alternative to car journeys is at the heart of the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) - a major new programme of transport infrastructure investment secured as part of the West Yorkshire devolution deal. The programme, which is being delivered by the Combined Authority in partnership with local authorities, will be funded through £317 million from the Department for Transport (DfT) plus local match funding up to £140 million. Communities across Bradford, Calderdale, Craven, Harrogate, Kirklees, Leeds, Selby, Wakefield and York are set to benefit from the schemes.','Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) for West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/transport-projects/transforming-cities-fund/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority secured £317 million from the Department for Transport\'s Transforming Cities Fund, supplemented by local match funding up to £140 million. This major programme aims to deliver transformational infrastructure, dramatically improving access to walking, cycling, and public transport across communities in West Yorkshire, including Wakefield, to connect people to jobs, training, and education.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('76bdb609-87f7-48a4-9324-556d0b1bee8c','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Business owners on Sowerby Bridge\'s historic high street can take advantage of a new funding scheme to support improvements to the look of their property. ... The Sowerby Bridge Shop Front grant scheme can fund up to 80% of costs to improve signage, stonework or other heritage restoration works to business properties along Wharf Street / Town Hall Street... Approved works will commence in April 2023, and must be completed by December 2023.','Enhancing and preserving the heritage features of Sowerby Bridge | News Centre','Calderdale Council News Centre','2023-01-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFJYU9t0LrTbnb2NY8Wt0S2V0OvH3hAv7bv6fdyy05nCgMk3NqTz5H0Z2ifSSir_-htrLqpkTt0eP_dn7GItZEK-lMztenYk0UAxiDYLhj8wkxiM1tisVeqWV7N5MlkfZhDU-dQh6xvL3Jr1ZXFsU15j7M7NQwYu0zJc2jj9Qtac355cnZiEZySPZBwwthnimbpWddU1PaBbjKm','Calderdale Council launched the Sowerby Bridge Shop Front grant scheme, offering up to 80% funding for businesses to improve the aesthetics and heritage features of properties along Wharf Street and Town Hall Street. This scheme, part of the High Streets Heritage Action Zone programme, aimed to enhance the high street\'s visual appeal, with works scheduled for April to December 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('76f6e896-f020-4aab-9286-0f8ca1d9c0e7','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As well as established regular opening hours of between 10am and 2pm on Mondays and Fridays, it is now open on an additional day – Thursdays, between 3pm and 7pm. People can also receive copies of updates about progress with the schemes by sending the word “subscribe” by email to HebdenBridgeFAS@environment-agency.gov.uk. If the plans are approved, the multi-million pound scheme could take around four years to complete, it is estimated. The proposed scheme aims to reduce the risk of flooding from both Hebden Water and the River Calder, and includes repair and reconstruction of river walls, building new walls within St Pol Square Car Park and vertical-rising flood barriers on Bridge Gate and Old Gate which would be raised when needed.','Environment Agency extends hours in flood-hit Calderdale town as defences plans go in','Halifax Courier','2025-09-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/environment/environment-agency-extends-hours-in-flood-hit-calderdale-town-as-defences-plans-go-in-4790074','On September 13, 2025, the Environment Agency\'s Flood Information Centre in Hebden Bridge extended its opening hours, adding Thursdays from 3pm to 7pm, in response to the submission of defence plans. The proposed multi-million-pound scheme, estimated to take four years, aims to reduce flood risk from Hebden Water and the River Calder, including river wall reconstruction, new walls in St Pol Square Car Park, and vertical-rising flood barriers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7762f321-4a39-49f2-8d5f-d0b20dd9ac1f','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the English Cities Fund (ECF), is inviting the public to play a pivotal role in shaping the future of Bradford City Village, a project poised to deliver 1,000 new homes and breathe new life into the former retail hub of the city centre. This visionary initiative, set in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, including the sites of the Kirkgate and Oastler shopping centres, aims to create a sustainable neighbourhood at the heart of the city centre. [21]','Public Consultation Unveiled for Bradford City Village Masterplan','UKREiiF','2023-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://ukreiif.com/news/public-consultation-unveiled-for-bradford-city-village-masterplan/','Bradford Council and the English Cities Fund (ECF) launched a public consultation, inviting residents, businesses, and stakeholders to contribute their insights to the Bradford City Village project. This initial phase aimed to gather feedback on the masterplan to deliver 1,000 new homes and revitalize the former retail hub in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('77920066-992c-4fd5-b8c8-beac56a58884','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Proposed scheme: This scheme includes changing routes around the town and creating welcoming gateways for people as they enter and leave the town centre at Bull Green and Ward\'s End. We will change the layouts of roads and junctions to make walking, cycling and public transport routes easier and safer. Proposals include improving key junctions which will link with traffic signalised junctions. Bull Green roundabout will be taken out and replaced with a signalised junction and enhanced pedestrian environment/gateway to the town centre from the west of Halifax. There will be the introduction of a cycle lane along the key route to/from Halifax. The subway at Cow Green/Pellon Lane will be infilled and replaced with signal-controlled pedestrian crossing. Additional elements of the proposals have now been made and come into force on 20th May 2025. [20]','A629 Phase 2 – Halifax Town Centre (Western Corridor)','Calderdale Council','2025-05-20 00:00:00.000','https://calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/projects/a629-halifax-town-centre/a629-phase-2-halifax-town-centre-western-corridor','This page details various Traffic Regulation Order (TRO) updates for the A629 Phase 2 project\'s western corridor, including proposals to remove the Bull Green roundabout, introduce a new signalized junction, enhance pedestrian environments, create cycle lanes, and infill the Cow Green subway with new signal-controlled crossings. The latest TRO updates came into force on May 20, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('77a4bba6-f0c1-4d98-b508-1a4e17f52a19','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The estimated cost of the Bradford Live project increased to £22.7 million, up from £15.6 million in 2016. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) approved an additional £32,500, increasing their total contribution to £357,500. The project, including a £12 million loan from Bradford Council and NEC Group investment, was then expected to open in Autumn 2020.','Cost of Odeon transformation now predicted to be £22.7 million, with West Yorkshire Combined Authority increasing funding','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2019-01-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEGCEhx7Apf8-A0bM5nsP2r8jAxJpiT8eRiURiD7oBPXEyyg6DlCWVmqpESxx9CtlXbNMULKfQsZI5If-xtyGXFCDBwhGFvtopZnZ2s-NdDt1IJUfSsinH0ItPNmOIT5fsCGLn-0yjuVSDTUWqkU7QFJVThGo61ae5aS4KiPfuaKW-gb3CNVWa8lPGXM2teo8_Xwl3_zyau5Jfl8cjlw3Hydz_oC_eTWkEpJBZetXXzh5ed3WZI6v4OP2u2N5HOCqGiDZhjvXnyITSYIGOITV_TLZcBm2tQBN9c4w==','The estimated cost of the Bradford Live project increased to £22.7 million, up from £15.6 million in 2016. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) approved an additional £32,500, increasing their total contribution to £357,500. The project, including a £12 million loan from Bradford Council and NEC Group investment, was then expected to open in Autumn 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('77a92633-742c-4e7b-b92d-3daad74ecb5e','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Between Monday 14 September and Friday 16 October 2020, a period of engagement took place where the public and other interested parties were asked to participate in a baseline engagement survey. The survey aimed to understand current travel behaviour and perceptions of walking and cycling, including identification of barriers and changes to streets that could encourage more walking and cycling journeys. Over 500 people participated and following this, data from the survey and people\'s comments have been analysed.','Initial Public Engagement Survey: Calderdale Streets for People (North and West Halifax)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF587wf7BYOZVLGxq2D33fvvPSzNtdikwOrPt_SYobO450T5SRgwhLvNZZopFzp-ExlsDKPTUbj6r3R5fAz-6oCMlgicK0Xek9s8VqyedibJddncbE3QSeFXfylVPNzXZoKA_dfzbS9_WWgeZ0fe4YLRDeEjFjAr8Kfnb4-NLQ=','Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, undertook an engagement survey to understand current travel behaviour, perceptions of walking and cycling, and barriers to active travel in North and West Halifax. Over 500 people participated, and the feedback informed the early development of schemes aimed at improving the street environment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('78191003-9a58-4291-b916-8ac4eeba3dfc','infrastructure-outer-ring-road-a6120-junction-improvements-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.973','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2018-02-09)... Preliminary work will begin on the junctions which are located on the existing outer ring road west of Red Hall; the A6120/Roundhay Park Lane junction and A6120/A61 Harrogate Road junctions. This will be followed by similar work to the A6120/King Lane and King Lane/Stonegate Road junctions at a later date. ... This project will support a wide range of tree planting and habitat improvements being made across Leeds that will make the urban streetscape greener and more attractive. This includes an emphasis on tree planting in association with planned highway improvements as part of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \'Green Streets\' initiative and as a contribution to the newly promoted Northern Forest. [19]','North east Leeds ring road junction improvements to commence later this month','Leeds City Council News / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2018-02-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH8dh1949qIkZnUNgA9U0Tbq7KdTazvsosheuT5UFLDMQ4v3FYnCBXkx8EkrQfDaJCvK5NBP1c11AJr9qVmtW_tJI1_ZtLetwWkePU9N8pmQZLZ4dlqiaCBJ0pHeV3ckM-eHbXNu113lqbUDByoLX-gNq6Dlu6V0W-rznwDLApV6uPIo2_mdQX6t2pDbEdhexRDVEQXQegc3LNjKrvxA==','Preliminary work for infrastructure and environmental improvements to three outer ring road junctions in north east Leeds was announced. The work targets traffic congestion, air quality, and new pedestrian and cycling infrastructure at the A6120/Roundhay Park Lane and A6120/A61 Harrogate Road junctions, with future plans for A6120/King Lane and King Lane/Stonegate Road junctions. This project is part of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \'Green Streets\' initiative. The works started in late 2017 or early 2018. [8, 19]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('78282ee4-7322-4502-bd2f-62a5c8e67741','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The School Streets scheme aims to reduce car usage and air pollution; promote walking and cycling; and boost road safety, health and well-being. Christ Church, Pellon on Sandbeds Road had access restrictions become effective from 14th September 2023.','School Streets - Halifax','Calderdale Council','2023-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE7olmZbn2MXZpDTmIWrCc8G2Fj2HoaMLQXJ0nK76p2VfGVCt56un37DSAiJsFJguFUs7iM14zHQdxheDbgMTraFArI17lRAdCuiKVFf8rZj-T15U5Ut039_ionXnEKvJ6C2BsovpjDPsbSd5wX3r2WRyART8FHt0mzG1UeMYimDhnMbFdZvqSU4VUyQhgCrOTQnWw==','Calderdale Council implemented \'School Streets\' access restrictions outside Christ Church Pellon Primary School on Sandbeds Road, effective from September 14, 2023. This initiative aims to reduce car usage, improve air quality, promote active travel (walking and cycling), and enhance road safety, health, and well-being around the school during drop-off and pick-up times.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('784b7860-5d1c-4931-b5e0-a75ad6a88041','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'UP to £45 MILLION could be spent improving roads to the South of Bradford, and members of the public are being asked for their views on the proposals. The work will apply to a 3.6km stretch of Wakefield Road and Tong Street, and see areas of road widening, new bus lanes, improved crossings and cycle routes. The proposals cover the A650 from the junction with Croft Street in the city centre to the Tong Leadership Academy School. A public consultation on the plans has now started, and runs until April 6. [8]','Have your say on £45m plans for two major Bradford roads','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-03-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE5p0caBt_uHNKWj5BUwf1asnN_HlTtVTzuQlNLGLfZ5rUVIKXHXHqXA_AlzU4sJuxOfpUCLK9oEJllYSpWqYi_YAiJI2ADdHuiIcuysrltZQ3nGC7jX9hlYt62IziQAiZYxSOSEOQPdKxLmQq8tysoKs83oaq6ZhBSeGLasFsI_OOPYhHEWuJTZtoJF_fbe72n_cOA_0f9','A public consultation was launched for plans to improve a 3.6km stretch of Wakefield Road and Tong Street (A650), with an estimated total cost of up to £45 million. The work will apply to this section of the A650 from the junction with Croft Street to the Tong Leadership Academy School and will include areas of road widening, new bus lanes, improved crossings, and cycle routes. The consultation points out that a significant portion of residents along the route do not own a car.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('787df8f6-ba55-479c-a3e6-341540696f36','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Hundreds of children across the region are benefiting from a safer journey to school thanks to a partnership between parents, schools, local councils, and the West YorkshireCombinedAuthority.\n\nFollowing a successful pilot in 2019, the Combined Authority has invested over £600,000 into the School Streets programme – which sees streets outside schools become safer and cleaner by reducing traffic and addressing dangerous parking.\n\nHaving already delivered 33 \'School Streets\', 15 more are now being planned across the region through funding from Active Travel England.\n\nMayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin, spoke about the success of the programme at the School Streets North Conference in Bradford last week (Friday 15th March).','Nearly 50 schools across West Yorkshire to benefit from a cleaner, safer school run','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news/nearly-50-schools-across-west-yorkshire-to-benefit-from-a-cleaner-safer-school-run/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced an investment of over £600,000 into the School Streets programme, having already delivered 33 School Streets since a 2019 pilot, with 15 more planned. This update was given by Mayor Tracy Brabin at the School Streets North Conference in Bradford on March 15, 2024, highlighting the programme\'s success in reducing traffic, improving safety, and promoting active travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('788f63ba-dec5-4816-bd14-c56ad980b05e','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Located on the outskirts of Leeds, Thorpe Park Hotel & Spa offers a luxurious retreat with a strong focus on relaxation and well-being. For EV owners, the hotel provides charging stations so you can keep your vehicle powered while you unwind. [5]','Hotels in Leeds with EV Charging for an Eco-Friendly Stay - Evist','Evist','2024-10-14 00:00:00.000','https://evist.uk/blog/hotels-in-leeds-with-ev-charging','An article highlighting hotels in Leeds with EV charging facilities, featuring Thorpe Park Hotel & Spa. It states the hotel provides charging stations for EV owners.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('78b148be-4593-4b32-b441-87f83f18372c','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept the grant from West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of measures designed to achieve net zero targets. WYCA has been allocated more than £14m of government funding as part of the local electric vehicle infrastructure (LEVI) scheme. ... Wakefield will receive a total £1,520,938, based on a University of Leeds study into EV charger requirements for the region.','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for EV charging points across city after study from Leeds university - Yorkshire Evening Post','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-10-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/council/wakefield-council-to-get-ps15m-for-ev-charging-points-across-city-after-study-from-leeds-university-4822709','The Yorkshire Evening Post reported that Wakefield Council\'s cabinet formally approved a recommendation to accept a £1.5 million grant from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA). This funding, part of the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) scheme, is designated for the installation of additional public EV charging points throughout the Wakefield district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('78d28bf4-3751-43b3-9076-b5328d6f4866','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On August 23 planning permission was granted to create the main access road into the site and deliver the first 350 homes. The application also supports the delivery of high-quality pedestrian and cycle facilities connecting to the new signalised site access junction at the existing Forge Lane / Lees Hall Road junction, as well as the ability to connect to the new Ravensthorpe Railway Station which is part of the Transpennine Route Upgrade.','Dewsbury Riverside Development takes positive steps forward','Kirklees Together / Business Kirklees (referencing update)','2023-08-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHUPUufsjKFo6OLWtBjSA4ktvRHmvkqo-Uzmqq4e9vqbqCT5ONaLQ4xiAa7FjsbAtiIzGlBZkmIg0BV6i5XWrr7MnvNVuoZbkRQek_7OXLrAULZ_tUji7pdNOYPZRIegigyWC7EXAhxpuz3vw==','Planning permission was granted on August 23, 2023, for the main access road into the Dewsbury Riverside site and for the first 350 homes. This approval also supports the provision of new community facilities and high-quality pedestrian and cycle facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('79012c5c-7b65-4877-a810-642855a04a18','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'re starting a home energy revolution in West Yorkshire to help you make energy-saving upgrades to your home. Our Home Energy West Yorkshire service offers advice, low-interest loans, solar panel installations, and information on grants for extra financial support. We\'ll help you make cost-effective choices, reduce your carbon footprint, and make your home more comfortable. Our partner councils: Bradford; Calderdale; Kirklees; Leeds; Wakefield. Coming soon. We\'re creating a one-stop shop to offer advice and install energy-saving measures in homes across West Yorkshire. Launching in 2025.','Home Energy - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEUVJt-EiMdFIpKOXH6Jr0z0ogENb8btmyrVX02n2AmWEFk7gj62JCdc-Qzl02MsDBlb5HWb9lCq1mDoPeICWQh5-5PJS9f511mp_ei_vwzDpzjlaPh7BC63WJlMjBx6Wte4TlzjBgKwcv_fKgmcjeDRWK1DujOwz9SiPjNDFisi6-sVNlXchlxW5vdlrquHhU0WEgPCOpy9IH7AHcisp9oD57ApeZ2Pe7GCxa-ony69eHVRkqRBwWVHgNQIw6szCbg88_BEx9XhpnlhfZv8uVryutopwPd0Q18C6XuuoVvrFckWH0BGvRQa3pFvdK8tpoNNj3al549AnqnvJQ4iKnTiO06sKZA==','This page highlights the \'Home Energy West Yorkshire\' service, a regional initiative by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) to support energy-saving upgrades. It mentions advice, low-interest loans, solar panel installations, and grants. Wakefield is listed as one of the partner councils offering various schemes to help residents. A \'one-stop shop\' for energy-saving measures is launching in 2025. This shows the HERO scheme\'s alignment with broader regional goals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('792dd344-4d43-401d-a2af-992036fcd1c6','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Between Monday 14 September and Friday 16 October 2020, a period of engagement took place where the public and other interested parties were asked to participate in a baseline engagement survey for the Calderdale Streets for People initiative in North and West Halifax. The survey aimed to understand current travel behaviour and perceptions of walking and cycling, including identification of barriers and changes to streets that could encourage more walking and cycling journeys. Over 500 people participated, and their feedback was analysed. [12]','Calderdale Streets for People (Park Ward and North Halifax) Public Engagement','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2020-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE_msCa4oDZzPc97zKYmSGDgiR0a26ZMmzmw87JtEvUf3jLFpSFmetuHvOpYj7avBe5-aUY3xnzzDi0qXEf196-gi_Z4TfpNwQF196w3n-55KGwr3KqQ7-x3JuhWtZ0kGAh4e1SAgLLDcMfI1RyUZ9GVcN9RBlLL_XZfrZqtIA=','Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a public engagement survey for the \'Streets for People\' initiative in North and West Halifax. The survey aimed to understand current travel behaviour, perceptions of walking and cycling, and identify barriers or changes that could encourage more active travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('79e7d34c-be8c-4dcd-8517-e53ef1bcfabb','infrastructure-toby-carvery-leeds-aberford-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.388','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'bp pulse Charging Station. 2 Aberford Road. Toby Carvery Leeds Leeds LS26 8EJ +44 800 464 3444. Get Directions. Charging bays Open · 24 hours. 1 of 1 chargers available. CHADEMO IEC_62196_T2 IEC_62196_T2_COMBO. CHAdeMO (DC 50kW Max). 1/1. Type 2 (AC 14.2kW Max). 1/1. CCS (DC 50kW Max). 1/1. Get fast, rapid, and ultra-fast charging with bp pulse. This EV charging station, located in Leeds, LS26 8EJ, is part of the bp pulse network.','Leeds, 2 Aberford Road - bp pulse Charging Station','bp pulse','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://chargers.bppulse.com/charge-points/leeds-2-aberford-road','The official bp pulse website confirms an operational EV charging station at Toby Carvery Leeds, 2 Aberford Road, LS26 8EJ. This 24-hour station provides CHAdeMO (DC 50kW Max), Type 2 (AC 14.2kW Max), and CCS (DC 50kW Max) connectors, with one charger currently available. It highlights the continued functionality and accessibility of the charging point.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7a4eeb19-27ae-4c5e-b21f-513d96f116c8','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public consultation on proposals for new stations at Thorpe Park and White Rose, including park and ride facilities at Thorpe Park. The consultation ran from July 2nd to July 27th, 2018.','Public engagement on new rail stations for Leeds gets underway','Leeds City Council News / TheBusinessDesk.com','2018-07-03 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/public-engagement-on-new-rail-stations-for-leeds-gets-underway','Leeds City Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public consultation on proposals for new stations at Thorpe Park and White Rose, including park and ride facilities at Thorpe Park. The consultation ran from July 2nd to July 27th, 2018.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7a525c2d-5192-4cfb-9b0b-7236b319bc9d','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Regional decision-makers are set to approve £40 million for ongoing detailed planning and development work on mass transit, as well as a technical consultation on how cross-border and other special services, such as shuttle buses for sporting events and concerts, can run alongside franchised services in a single bus network. Mass Transit and bus franchising represent two of the West Yorkshire Mayor\'s biggest priorities, and will form a key part of an integrated Weaver Network connecting bus, tram and train services as well as walking and cycling routes. ... At a full Combined Authority meeting on September 18, West Yorkshire council leaders will hear how the extra £40 million of funding would support key works to keep the mass transit project on track for spades in the ground by 2028.','Mass transit and bus franchising plans set to accelerate after £40m funding boost','Yorkshire Evening Post','2025-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/mass-transit-and-bus-franchising-plans-set-to-accelerate-after-ps40m-funding-boost-4786415','Regional leaders are set to approve £40 million in funding to accelerate detailed planning and development work for both the mass transit system and bus franchising in West Yorkshire. This funding will support technical and environmental assessments, business case progression, and preparation for the scheme\'s entry into the Government\'s Major Projects Portfolio.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7a528bba-dea9-4e7e-8bfa-45d2539e1c27','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work is due to begin on a new town square for Sowerby Bridge, providing a flexible and welcoming space, with improved facilities for pedestrians. The new Sowerby Bridge Square will be built on the site of the old market building and will include landscaping, with tree planting and rain gardens. ... Construction work on the square will begin on Thursday 1 August and will last around six months. ... Once the new square is finished, the car park will be resurfaced and will include two electric vehicle charging points, additional motorcycle parking and new cycle stands. Sowerby Bridge Square is part of the A58/A672 Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP), a programme of work which is worth over £5million and is being delivered in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','Starting work on new community space for Sowerby Bridge','Calderdale Council News Centre, Calderdale Next Chapter','2024-07-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE89PXY-TLFrOAX82gN0yneXlF0ueMiHzRRqiqWfhwxb0KxA2KOh6K05VUnzyfkR3QJLY4LrMvH1u09tn2hLpw5M24LgR4NbGzjJTTqTKxeTgpJD6fiWtnTb11cgJTPqU3aHAF8u-QFid8sUCi3Ay-GCv63avJ329W_6JT3GsHNF-SOdNqW4YqaXWAasSaLOPcK','Work was announced to begin on August 1, 2024, for a new town square in Sowerby Bridge, located on the former market building site. This six-month project includes landscaping, tree planting, rain gardens, seating, and enhanced pedestrian and bus stop facilities on Wharf Street. The adjacent Tuel Lane car park will be resurfaced to include EV charging points, motorcycle parking, and cycle stands, funded by the A58/A672 Corridor Improvement Programme and HAZ funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7a65da6b-cba5-4e8c-a7f5-f76428382905','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In February 2020, £1.9 million was approved by Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee to help start a £27.2 million scheme in Hebden Bridge being led by the Environment Agency which will reduce the risk of flooding from a 20% risk to a 2% risk in any given year. This project will reduce the flood risk to 231 commercial properties and move 180 commercial properties to a lower flood risk band, directly safeguarding approximately 700 jobs. In addition, the scheme will better protect 183 residential properties and move 130 to a lower flood risk band and improve the resilience of the A646 road. [11]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Approves £1.9M for Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/growing-the-economy/our-investment-themes/flood-alleviation/','In February 2020, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee approved £1.9 million in funding to support the initiation of a £27.2 million flood alleviation scheme in Hebden Bridge. This Environment Agency-led project aims to substantially reduce the risk of flooding in the town, safeguarding 231 commercial and 183 residential properties, and improving the resilience of the A646 road. [11]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7a86aea4-ee6d-409b-bd92-90837059395b','infrastructure-cornholme-a646-active-travel-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.620','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) programme is aimed at providing a more integrated and inclusive transport network across West Yorkshire. The programme is made possible thanks to the West Yorkshire Mayoral devolution deal and is being delivered by the Combined Authority in partnership with Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield Councils. [11]','Active Travel projects in West Yorkshire funded by City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/active-travel','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s active travel projects, including those in Cornholme, are supported by the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) programme. This programme aims to provide a more integrated and inclusive transport network across West Yorkshire, delivered in partnership with Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield Councils.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7a8f331f-e4fb-437d-bd0e-3ddcecee985b','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A new operator has been found for the 571 between Halifax and Shelf. Councillor Thornham said the new operator will be Go Ahead and the buses will run more frequently than previously. The new 571 timetable includes an improved 30-minute daytime frequency (currently hourly) which is very welcome! The increased frequency from Go Ahead is being funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Bus Service Improvement Plan. [4]','What is happening with Halifax buses: \'Welcome news\' as Halifax bus service saved from the axe','Halifax Courier','2025-01-18 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFy0a8vhcjM0TZths06VuaRcvHsu6bfZx1NaLnBcL8sx-JytuNNbHeaHoZ8OayV05pMugOih-TWS4GEBtESXdAiA5urcx0biKoW9WfMavanqiuoyjaQb1jBrFiMJg9Xl454kXEsiXjdEMLU0QBrjGjHZC3LWhLZIrEsKvodpc5YUMIHrjKK-vbebHwaUACW5EJnYBGyTRT9lNw32Bdt5fFsMVnjW33AfGxR70kDsrgWxnESSTbsSh7HQ-j3hSkMCX5TryqPqZg18_KcuUxV2Tw','A new operator, Go-Ahead, was found for the 571 bus route between Halifax and Shelf, alleviating fears of the service being dropped after Arriva\'s withdrawal. The new timetable includes an improved 30-minute daytime frequency, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Bus Service Improvement Plan. [4]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7acaa390-cc42-41c1-90ae-ee073309febc','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Virgin Media O2 has today announced it has connected more than 10,000 homes in West Yorkshire to its ultrafast network, bringing the benefits of gigabit broadband to tens of thousands more people for the first time. As part of its \'Project Lightning\' network expansion programme, Virgin Media O2 is expanding its network to bring ultrafast broadband, TV and phone services to more residents and small businesses. [22]','Thousands in West Yorkshire connected to Virgin Media O2\'s ultrafast gigabit network','Virgin Media O2 Newsroom','2022-01-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGFzl3sZ3tUhZKArzDLWEIQTDD-v2ZdmHhJlgCNVg8zoPnf7oesIQXQS_HPpKLLn_IzV2X1vzbmfwOO4eLtMSQmjvZRcDjW92AlkM_TgNGaJJ2XvDDCD7CvBFHjMQMDlzE8vnbCQ2c9aeR8bUvhtLXOJra1RD2yqnv1KM_ohRapGpbsoJndnxJ76aaNmKcZYjdXu8vq0p9OIAr75ZPLOriAFw0rjNL9eqhJaZY3lZg7Ug==','Virgin Media O2 announced it connected over 10,000 homes in West Yorkshire, including Otley, Menston, Burley-in-Wharfedale, and Guiseley, to its gigabit-speed network. This expansion, part of \'Project Lightning\', signifies a significant infrastructure upgrade in the region, making ultrafast broadband services more widely available for residents and small businesses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7ad9b503-5b1d-40b1-b13e-2f8d8bd7910a','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On June 29, 2022, Calderdale Council announced its intention to start a discussion about how to improve streets in Skircoat, making them better for walking, cycling, resting, and playing. Initial engagement gathered feedback, revealing that 1 in 6 people did not feel comfortable walking in Skircoat. The project is funded by £2.4m from Active Travel England and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [20]','Skircoat Your street matters: Initial Engagement','Calderdale Next Chapter','2022-06-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFzFcOaEsx2PlD1WeadX7Z9zhFeqZkmH7TMm7DqrO5AhoC0yhQTQyuCqM2G4q2Gp4U9PFy_wSfEr1JpRtb0ACFCoO77qPWB797hVM4CvTnICzQ5dwEeXTGH1o-m5NQ5IIzGuh-2uvKUmGDBey4NP90FtLYkO1Lk8O2rV4VA7_-3Zdqkcw=','Calderdale Council launched an initial engagement to start a discussion about making streets around Skircoat safer and more enjoyable for walking, cycling, resting, and playing. This initiative is funded by Active Travel England and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7b06086b-692e-4250-bb4a-cd11dff2b372','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'I understand that they will be stored for 7 years. I understand that they will be shared with Virgin Media (the service provider) so they can install broadband and monitor their Corporate Social Responsibility contract with Kirklees Council. I understand that I can withdraw or update my details at any time. For more information about how we store your data and how you can request your right to withdraw consent to use your personal data later please read privacy notice for Digital Hubs. [5]','Apply for free business broadband - My Kirklees Account','Kirklees Council','2022-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGv7rgTLE4p3eoOlixgS4jha304ZQxeok4GoG2sbGkzAuvF7qRKFKJrAoNwPopkF1M_I5h24cNN3Y5JYuY-A9mQyVJTcUvwcK7oGr-xfs0PXusGYcJ92Y6naFyBH0YDNAPwcIdB7ei8kCJd4zgykXdLAMG2gkywv2IQd_bCgZ4yqVmeRc_Kwk_MGI0Yx7FlhZ25Tq0PMYve6m3Ynx6GD9qWD7vp0yUAWpdDzYcvcCUQUHDE8zDcIdA5l0msLna_iz3RgOOWDMDHOW9XbPi5Gmu4dX2Kqt2th-PwnvhQBpmRRt0Nmnp4n3R9HyiNW-oBcLIK1ZM9dZkJ_0MIkbZUf10ytxZnTz7cvbrq21l8-z01BgW0afIwUIjUCaZz8ZPzITpjPYluPnDSRjM3FWSayt8=','This active application page on the Kirklees Council website confirms the existence of a Corporate Social Responsibility contract between Kirklees Council and Virgin Media O2 to provide free business broadband. While a specific launch date for this program isn\'t stated on the page, its functionality confirms an ongoing offer for eligible organisations in Kirklees.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7b2589fe-028b-4649-aae8-53e772ae653e','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Some of the schemes we\'ve seen today are part of our 180 million pound investment which will be complete before April 2025. This is just the start of our plans to improve performance in October 2023.','Yorkshire Water // The Science Behind // What we\'re doing to reduce storm overflows','Yorkshire Water (YouTube)','2024-05-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kYJz2J_s3oQ','This YouTube video from Yorkshire Water explains their efforts to reduce storm overflows, detailing the various schemes and part of their £180 million investment program, expected to be complete before April 2025. It highlights different approaches, including upgrades to wastewater treatment works, sewer lining, and phosphorus reduction schemes, which contribute to the overall goal of improving water quality and reducing storm overflow use.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7b45b67d-381f-4efa-9223-639cb4f238a0','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In February 2020, £1.9 million was approved by Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee to help start a £27.2 million scheme in Hebden Bridge being led by the Environment Agency which will reduce the risk of flooding from a 20% risk to a 2% risk in any given year. This project will reduce the flood risk to 231 commercial properties and move 180 commercial properties to a lower flood risk band, directly safeguarding approximately 700 jobs. In addition, the scheme will better protect 183 residential properties and move 130 to a lower flood risk band and improve the resilience of the A646 road…','West Yorkshire Combined Authority approves funding for Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/corporate-information/publications/reports-and-strategies/investment-committee/item-7-leeds-city-region-growth-deal-funding-allocation-flood-alleviation/','In February 2020, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee approved £1.9 million to help initiate the £27.2 million Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme. This project aims to reduce flood risk from a 20% to a 2% chance in any given year, protecting 231 commercial and 183 residential properties and safeguarding approximately 700 jobs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7b8dc808-b36b-45b2-845a-a2fc121c728e','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On behalf of the Board, I am delighted to introduce our 2024 Annual Report and Financial Statements. ... During the last year alone, we invested £75.4 million in delivering more new affordable homes and improving homes through our investment programme... Our Sustainability Plan 2020 to 2025. ... Key achievements include the following: ... Installation of more than 500 solar panels on the roof of our head office, Merefield House. ... Achieving a reduction in our carbon footprint of more than 17%.','WDH Annual Report and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 March 2024','Vico Homes (WDH Document)','2024-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFnhVG7syBXxGEhufLKZlkJALaZF-A5meLxB4WIj9MtWM-PZ6mGM1oaR6L3qKsZek8QA2C1hsHtcQHlEK8zlbksL5WFrYp6hFC_pJSddOA3jvdtmSwJey32joamLZt_sFsnFu4Frezo0uUP8XbhHwzrCs_NIndmwKxvm2iFp0IeiXeJTFgaM_26fMvqY8LlS1s3QucrYPtImks','The Wakefield and District Housing Limited (WDH) Annual Report and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 March 2024 highlights their strong financial position and continued investment in improving homes. The report mentions their \'Sustainability Plan 2020 to 2025\' and key achievements, including the installation of more than 500 solar panels on their head office, Merefield House, and a 17% reduction in their carbon footprint.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7bc7b577-a8d8-4d5e-af6d-15bac67ac0f0','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire will benefit from a multi-million-pound investment to improve walking, wheeling and cycling routes in the region, it can be announced today. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority will receive £17.07 million to help make active travel a more attractive option for short journeys. ... A total of £12.86 million has been awarded for 2025-26 by Active Travel England (ATE), with £4.21 million allocated for 2024-25. It follows previous rounds of funding which are already being used for schemes like improving the Silsden to Kildwick towpath in Bradford, traffic management measures around Ash Green School in Mixenden, walking and cycling improvements to the Spen Valley Greenway, and new cycle routes along the A660 Otley Road, and from Fitzwilliam Rail Station to Ackworth.','West Yorkshire to benefit from £17 million funding boost for active travel','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-02-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news/west-yorkshire-to-benefit-from-17-million-funding-boost-for-active-travel/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced it will receive £17.07 million in government funding from Active Travel England (ATE) to enhance walking, wheeling, and cycling routes across the region. This funding, allocated for 2024-25 and 2025-26, will support various projects including new cycle lanes, towpath upgrades, traffic management, and school-area improvements, demonstrating ongoing investment in active travel infrastructure identified through plans like LCWIPs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7be296d5-f9cb-4cf9-891f-83ff34b6c312','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2022-02-24) This public consultation report has been prepared by Mott MacDonald on behalf of Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council (CMBC) and Kirklees Metropolitan Borough Council (KMBC) for the proposed A629 Phase 4 Scheme (the Scheme) public consultation. ... The Scheme complements the four other A629 Schemes and will provide active travel options along the corridor. The other four Schemes are: ○ A629 Phase 1a Salterhebble to Shaw Hill.','A629 Phase 4 Public Consultation Report','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice)','2022-02-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG3Pr_7yvVaHWZ13ki3bWTeqxwThifzaWTksXxFm-o-LPH_utFFCT2ls44HHoP0u9Uh8RqQI3dShJyDogD4BUXMWA0Gd4mCzMnIv7-ed2-3tkd5mou2I2dTKjb9ZLdrTQaTaGvhUtDzTw8y5ijRHlBWoIc_cUWtkhSXUvx2kYPcToBNlAG28O0c','This public consultation report from February 2022 for the A629 Phase 4 Scheme explicitly lists \"A629 Phase 1a Salterhebble to Shaw Hill\" as one of the other four complementary A629 Schemes. This places Phase 1a in the broader context of the A629 corridor improvement program, emphasizing its role in a series of interconnected projects aimed at enhancing accessibility in Halifax and Huddersfield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7c25b48f-d35f-43d1-acc3-4f79473ee288','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) was approved in Summer 2020 and the Halifax Park Ward (Streets for People) and West Halifax Bus Improvements will now progress to develop an Outline Business Case (OBC). At this stage we will continue to define the scope of the project to identify the locations and type of improvements required in order to achieve the benefits.','Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) Approved for Halifax Park Ward (Streets for People) and West Halifax Bus Improvements','Calderdale Next Chapter','2020-07-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGMCRr-5nNbaKxKlTEEvHLf80V3Is3ys3r3IJdlls2pzCQZAyUqkAcxM8UUuLUAHjbhYhY2FhLZ7bXrFxT0TL3HjR29IxngMarPbKYifX4L-oom-iwfPI4ssyJm5c-uA6U8_bhK_6j_dL9kCtPka4Il0d8dlz2s7YCmvUwLmgBjMeE0yV2vkVSWrk4EvG4vqqc','The Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) for the Halifax Park Ward (Streets for People) and West Halifax Bus Improvements was approved, allowing the projects to progress to the Outline Business Case (OBC) stage. This stage involves defining the scope of improvements for bus access, walking, and cycling in West Halifax as part of the Transforming Cities Fund program.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7c4ed038-fb8d-46c2-b275-eb64ed2ab389','infrastructure-calderdale-corridor-improvement-programme-phase-1-a58a672-and-a646a6033',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.888','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The next steps for road improvement plans which aim to improve journey times, reduce collisions and encourage the use of public transport, are being discussed by Calderdale leaders. Calderdale Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority are developing a series of improvements to the road network along the A58 / A672 from Junction 22 of the M62 to King Cross in Halifax and the A646 / A6033 from Todmorden to Skircoat Moor. [11]','Next Phase of Improving Journey Times and Reducing Crashes on Two Major Calderdale Roads','Halifax Courier','2020-04-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHAtELcnvuSESrjpilFlVksE0QsJiswt1cy8viC-S7SdvrMF_QLE--qOnpkSHkbGdb2G9vuqQiZdbohpK3cldbZ3pVAXT83FolfnIoyAqUSe1BEfgoyFBHVIm4vn5rNbUtv2Jr-ggd7VkazrOpTxUWxIRI-xwLm47AK5gJIRAUQpvq_dFvo4ZyN3EYWffC27-uAiOCljbiQlU4RZrkbdfx9O94vptPI6OmpE32I6tqDJSeBVc8Arf41nb0e3DVxsZtfE6JqDj_lskmG8PU=','Calderdale Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority discussed the next steps for the road improvement plans, emphasizing economic, social, and environmental benefits, and mentioning updates following public consultation, including additional pedestrian facilities and car park plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7c80f683-b9bc-49c4-b341-358b13f72eed','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The plans got a huge boost on Tuesday when the Government announced funding to allow Bradford Council to plan for a new £2 billion station in the area – expected to be on the current site of St James\' Wholesale Market. Detail of the gateway is included in Bradford\'s draft Development Framework, which is out to public consultation until Monday. ... Around 2,500 new homes are planned for the area.','Government Announces £2 Billion Funding for New Bradford Rail Station','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2023-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFt1Eyd3Qm156w2TyWiBi42YPIy8xz71BR37CW5mcHLVxsnlDhpQyBv9u7Y6Fw4nXH3DSrcA4tYkr44tvx3r-KeonFB9In33IDb_MZKobMZ1KceiZqyPaYyh0_iKn_h386otA2pEWNy8_3cBJUwXXjJ12GiokhQLfshREe7RTiD6VepeFcwN-l0ZouwXv-eJ_Qm20s83CEmYEWuH9rMHlAgzg9m','News reports indicated that the Government announced £2 billion in funding for a new rail station within the Southern Gateway area. This announcement was a significant boost for the project, with the station expected to be located at the current St James\' Wholesale Market site, as detailed in Bradford\'s draft Development Framework.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7d17c58a-dc97-4202-8531-7625fafbd783','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At the Bradford Showcase event it was also confirmed that Bradford-based affordable housing provider, Incommunities, has been selected as ECF\'s preferred funding partner to deliver the first phase of townhouses for sale and rent at Bradford City Village, subject to a final legal agreement.','Incommunities Selected as Funding Partner for Phase 1 Townhouses','Place Yorkshire / Bradford Council','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHe_d4KhPq6J2AlfNAcNAQK7R1Z_9NE75pKu7YaeHGR-LHOfcgy4sRKvCoYRmrFTu0_1iIs8MeMq6mjIzc1uDYfVy72kiRkd1NhWDkl8MFvdO-YkaDbfLkZU6TMfZK7lF9vgMZwZXrEbvJZqtgAtlrW9PdRSUa7v493dyTwht013IrYwtY1','Bradford-based affordable housing provider, Incommunities, was officially selected as ECF’s preferred funding partner to deliver the first phase of townhouses for sale and rent at Bradford City Village, subject to final legal agreement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7d45cfc2-73e3-4f02-b90b-34e1bb42009b','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin has unveiled proposals for a new tram system that will run between Leeds and Bradford, with a later extension to Dewsbury also a possibility. Subject to being agreed at a final Combined Authority meeting this week, this will represent a major step forward for the area’s proposed mass transit scheme. The first phase is planned to begin construction in 2028 and begin operation by the early 2030s. [14] The submission of the combined authority\'s \'strategic outline case\' document to the Department for Transport is set to be approved by members of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on 14 March. The document will then be sent by the Mayor Brabin to the government for approval to continue with the development of the scheme. [21]','West Yorkshire Mayor Unveils Tram Plans and Strategic Outline Case Submission','Air Quality News / Build in Digital','2024-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.airqualitynews.com/2024/03/13/tram-plans-announced-for-west-yorkshires-mass-transit-system/ ; https://www.buildindigital.com/west-yorkshire-sets-out-vision-for-mass-transit-boom/','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin unveiled proposals for a new tram system connecting Leeds and Bradford, marking a significant step forward for the mass transit scheme. The Strategic Outline Case (SOC) document was approved by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) for submission to the Department for Transport to continue with the project\'s development. Construction for Phase one is aimed to begin in 2028, with operation by the early 2030s.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7d5b8c69-7468-4717-89bb-b02982409d98','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BDUK awarded supplier Quickline a £60 million contract to provide around 28,000 hard-to-reach premises in West Yorkshire and parts of North Yorkshire with access to gigabit-capable broadband. The contract was signed in February 2024. Communities to be connected include those surrounding Selby, York, Bradford, Kirklees, Leeds, Wakefield, Harrogate, Skipton, Ripon, Keighley, Calder Valley, Stamford Bridge and Pocklington. [4, 5, 8, 16, 17]','BDUK awards broadband provider Quickline a Project Gigabit contract for West Yorkshire and parts of North Yorkshire','BDUK, Fibre Provider, Business Live, Quickline Communications','2024-02-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFkoYW7YkcS7ZqZr5Ag4X1H3FPZ19SsJbT_cWOVg2pPviQeU5z8CD7ItXQWsksgMNq8EbMBp9OpeOxrNUKWg77qbVrIC2JL3buuDJYeq1oEVnxeKTmdIu7MLI3OzJIE8xXblPXogt9EDauyHrx4P-I-tFNIQ9ET7IDq3S9n3OTvN0CmExxHdTgHAKz1UKgbdesm6GfCu_gBqWymf8HG0AnQbCvDOb2CR7Jg','Building Digital UK (BDUK) awarded Quickline a £60 million contract as part of Project Gigabit to deliver gigabit-capable broadband to approximately 28,000 hard-to-reach premises in West Yorkshire and parts of North and East Yorkshire. The contract was signed in February 2024, with the first premises anticipated to have access in 2024. This includes communities around Bradford, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7da8c6bd-454e-4965-9df6-a4584286fae2','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of the ongoing transformation of Leeds City Rail Station\'s main entrance and surrounding area, the northern section of New Station Street (from the station\'s main entrance to City Square) will be closed to pedestrians from Thursday (24 August). Pedestrians must use the other side of New Station Street (towards Boar Lane), station entrances on Aire Street and Wellington Street or the Southern entrance which is open between 6am and 10pm. The closure of New Station Street is necessitated by Network Rail\'s Mill Goit Works which is essential maintenance work to reinforce the underground structure below New Station Street that supports much of the station above it. [8]','New Station Street update: northern section closes to pedestrians','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2023-08-23 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/new-station-street-update-northern-section-closes-to-pedestrians','An update from Leeds City Council announced the closure of the northern section of New Station Street to pedestrians from Thursday, August 24, 2023. This closure was necessary for Network Rail\'s Mill Goit Works, which involves reinforcing the underground structure beneath the street, alongside progress on the Leeds Station Sustainable Travel Gateway scheme. The scheme aims for pedestrianisation, a relocated taxi rank, and improved accessibility.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7e11a3f8-73da-4dda-978f-91113b1ce8eb','infrastructure-frizinghall-station-revitalization',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.032','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford, UK – May 19th... A key development is the recent inauguration of a new platform at Bradford Forster Square... Complementing this strategic investment, a heartwarming local effort has seen Frizinghall station revitalized through the dedicated work of schoolchildren and community partners. This initiative, a collaborative effort, saw Network Rail personnel, Bradford Council enforcement officers, and the specialist company Railscape, join forces with pupils from Frizinghall Primary School. The collective endeavour focused on a thorough clean-up of the station environs, particularly targeting litter and illegally dumped waste (fly-tipping) behind the Shipley-bound platform and along station approaches.','Bradford Rail Upgrades: New Platform & Community Spirit - Railway News','Railway News','2025-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFIIKAdX3jxDxowBwO7CA6z3q0bE8qYP4I9Z4OSQ_tqGzlOSNNrwJxsRlff4DFzJYLp1ZlM8QklM0l916T_snXdxsdYIP6HV8U89LXzZeFsgn44aWe8vUL08hbrfXk2E3csub2SfmyA15U4XPJgq14W1-h06CLmmb9KJOrPe3678phBGXSmtdspiMwrSeNu_lM==','This article details a community engagement project at Frizinghall station around May 19, 2025, where Network Rail, Bradford Council, Railscape, and Frizinghall Primary School pupils collaborated on a clean-up effort, addressing litter and fly-tipping. It frames this initiative as part of broader railway improvements and Bradford\'s UK City of Culture 2025 celebration, emphasizing local ownership and civic pride.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7e6fbd69-5b7a-4077-9939-6ebbd764bdc5','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a638-doncaster-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.598','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This contract has been undertaken as a Direct Award under the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Framework Agreement; Ref: CA1550, Title: Transforming Cities and Other Funded Programmes; Lot 2: Highways Schemes and is for the production of a fully completed and compliant Full Business Case submission to WYCA, building on the original option appraisal outcomes already defined for the Outline Business Case. ... A Contract Award Notice by WAKEFIELD COUNCIL. Source: Contracts Finder; Type: Contract (Services); Duration: 10.5 month; Value: £641K. Sector: CONSTRUCTION; Published: 09 Feb 2024; Delivery: 02 Feb 2024 to 15 Dec 2024. [10]','Contract Awarded for Full Business Case Development','bidstats.uk (Contracts Finder)','2024-02-09 00:00:00.000','https://bidstats.uk/tenders/2024/W6/869584443','Wakefield Council awarded a contract for the production of a fully completed and compliant Full Business Case (FBC) submission to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) for the A638 Doncaster Road scheme. This contract, valued at £641,000, was published on February 9, 2024, and is part of the \'Transforming Cities and Other Funded Programmes\' framework, with a delivery period from February 2024 to December 2024. [10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7e7cd5b9-851e-477c-a05a-75e53b7f53f8','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Vastint UK, the developer behind Aire Park, has submitted its planning application for the final masterplan phase of the 24-acre mixed-use district on Leeds\' South Bank. [...] The developer\'s plans for the second phase feature 502 homes, including affordable housing, over 20,000 sq ft of flexible, ground floor space for leisure use, including cafes, restaurants and cultural activities, and a 353-space multi-storey car park. The application also details the final hectare of the development\'s park set to become the largest new city centre green park in the country. [17, 20, 21] A consultation was carried out in April. [20]','Planning Application Submitted for Final Masterplan Phase (502 Homes, Car Park, Park Extension)','TheBusinessDesk.com / Place Yorkshire / Vastint UK','2024-07-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGQphN5i-fl1iv5c5uKr8LVB7QMd2gUdYkY5dQmYB7bjANVHy9VsQXkVzMJ8VRlky9lzDDC1Cfgx1JscGoQ7XWPNToYTKY15omD1TzuSkuPoQx_TTvFs42G6Zd87V0R47aUgKztN5PNFeoiPoBn-fxCcx10IsjzZxUoYl0bhaDfIeVjdh_5mv7JEOLei6Bz0cMfyUiCDF-TuTn7XeSY15z7NRMZXTwMU-GaLfjmN0U [17], https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGbQ_bxVWaxewLbebmNIBZa-F7LMiCJYz7DeKHq_N9IOSOgS2nUed5D29Vzzztw58MmUciygklpcN8qAxI-jYH2KUbHI_Ma2npR2RGj2Esp3M0w1QpQrncLEsLeA1sZHU3vg5s5yxh4wqucCcpE4iKOkrSJKTkH_S4g0HDYX0a-3KxOe9jSdJMEUg [20], https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFWBfDFxH0Fz_Onj3pQDOmI6kxef_elIECWXlr5Y2DZxTbkFkhuK2qDoH4z5j_L7wIfpE2mEs7KFYFSA5h1ymuHCNDn6kIy1nx4FFZkff2G-q9NVqNil9xL-qq2ULl-KJ8VfG_-uPd8h3U-PbYx6fptN2uGbS8xSEwJqEXBy-QnQTQNGaORK3Ex-x2zByFxrJYqT9yVaAtnOTk25LP0zA== [21]','Vastint UK submitted a planning application for the final masterplan phase of Aire Park. This phase includes plans for 502 homes (including affordable housing), over 20,000 sq ft of flexible ground-floor leisure space, a 353-space multi-storey car park, and the final hectare of the public park. This application follows a public consultation held in April 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7e8c1a95-6911-4ba0-b282-73a83081d38a','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Homes at phase I of the district were released for sale in November 2017 and the first residents moved in early 2019. The £800m Climate Innovation District in Leeds, part of the city\'s major South Bank Leeds regeneration plans, draws on Scandinavian best practice and harnesses the latest technology to deliver new low-carbon homes alongside manufacturing, leisure, offices, a care home, primary school and climate resilient public realm.','Phase I Homes at Climate Innovation District Released for Sale','Housing Design Awards','2017-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFfSpf2wOlTVmx0kgHo49aXSdIjmUTSN0Dwrn6GsrKr4V55YZ2fIcVuUlSxu6qK5yz1uP8tg2ij748LyCnIt_Ezoc8eVvXlHdUc_nVIpwW9nOiD5vGrWxaDFVfmj19kyva8XPdGBb_RDBd2Q-cDYG1lCRJ9','The first phase of homes in the Climate Innovation District was released for sale in November 2017. This marked a significant step in the project, which aims to deliver new low-carbon homes as part of the South Bank Leeds regeneration plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7ea89a93-f7a1-4661-ac1e-421885530069','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'ROSE, M. (2023). Watching Brief at Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works. Archaeological Services WYAS. ... A total of ten ground investigation pits were monitored in advance of a programme of works involving updating the existing pipework and pump station, as well as the construction of a new integrated wetland in the undeveloped fields directly to the north of the sewage treatment works, Clayton West, Huddersfield. One pit exposed a stone-built culvert type land drain. No other archaeological features or remains were identified within the limits of the works.','Watching Brief at Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works','Archaeological Services WYAS (via Archaeology Data Service)','2023-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFjpgmPL7Ztq5hnK3pF6V0v3I_OisMq1W3FaMEaLFJWWGAeTrH2ChzwJLDU9Iaqpd1H5cN74Ki6BnkIXdU8TWUUqpeyN8CiBLIGX3MPs9gI1XzITtGTiVQke1M4JL4aIQj9sPLQznM4Qwt9UDoMZwWcTG0s88IeDYOmsQkd1gewevPmX5gqassO9Bm6lh5EMr811OdE_nWzEUgnizrV1flunK27-Q==','Archaeological Services WYAS conducted a watching brief in advance of works at Clayton West Sewage Treatment Works, which included updating existing pipework and pump station, and the construction of a new integrated wetland. Ten ground investigation pits were monitored, revealing no significant archaeological features other than a stone-built culvert, indicating a long history of agricultural land use.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7ed5107c-9f80-44e1-9b67-c7ee26ee0bad','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'re proud to celebrate the transformation of Leeds City College\'s Mabgate Campus a £27m regeneration project that blends heritage, innovation, and community impact. [11] Recently nominated for the Constructing Excellence Yorkshire & Humber Award – Regeneration & Conservation 2025. [11] At the heart of the scheme is the restoration of Studio 24, a Victorian Non-Designated Heritage Asset, now reimagined as a landmark entrance to the campus. Alongside it, two new five-storey buildings, College House and the Enfield Centre, provide 6,800m² of purpose-built learning space for over 1,500 students and staff. [11] This project is a showcase of sustainable and forward-thinking design. From post-tensioned concrete floors that cut embedded carbon by 20%, to a pioneering battery-powered crane system that slashed diesel use by 90%. [11] The Mabgate Campus is coming in spring 2026, offering a brand new building providing an innovative, vibrant place for adult learners. [4]','Project Spotlight highlights Mabgate Campus transformation ahead of Spring 2026 completion','Adept Consulting Engineers / Leeds City College','2025-07-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH5Zg9NeX4WCEJKJ2P-K0I_2XKkrBmu82ksK8NJC6ATmE9gWSuuTkXvbKEShJnm4m-WNkE3ZZWWMWBcA7rbUTNbxhToWd3I48NJUA6OPv3gQGYfge0nvqF7uaqM5b5vutre6vZLiKMG6KpRXPesh9NNc-kwiz9aMwl7q8iADdfhFlB40qkQEbuQL-bIXA==','A project spotlight highlighted the ongoing transformation of Leeds City College\'s Mabgate Campus, a £27 million regeneration project. It details the restoration of Studio 24 and the construction of two new five-storey buildings (College House and the Enfield Centre) providing 6,800m² of learning space. The campus is expected to be completed by Spring 2026, featuring sustainable design elements like post-tensioned concrete floors and a battery-powered crane system. The project was also nominated for a Constructing Excellence Yorkshire & Humber Award – Regeneration & Conservation 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7f533183-b072-47f3-8a91-3d094ed9af68','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Innovative plans to create a vibrant riverside village in Dewsbury have been approved. What is it all about? The Dewsbury Riverside Masterplan, approved by Cabinet on 19 March, sets out a vision to develop up to 4,000 quality homes, supported by new schools, roads and a local centre. It will be located on a 160 hectare site in South Dewsbury, on land to the south of Ravensthorpe and south-east of Mirfield. What will be in it? The innovative scheme will have a large public park at its centre, with six neighbourhoods around it, connected and surrounded by woodlands, walking and cycle routes, bridal paths, allotments and natural play areas to encourage residents to live healthy lifestyles.','Plans to create Dewsbury Riverside village','Kirklees Together','2019-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGID9ln-vApl5cK9zCHNtPPKalvbnWQuk5rGwS-u7x0sHA0JD-eD25UVyDXka_cru0bGQfmys0tHRqZ63CTtU6WB6-e4YMozA4DokJjEQ9k268ksspzIp5VnRS4mOq6Jax-DTgzG4xQ4lbTDdLwzKGxX8sCfnyP-X_n6bGolXZcqFgJ2jyFM8iQbraLFXn_UEw=','The Dewsbury Riverside Masterplan, outlining the vision for up to 4,000 homes, schools, roads, and a local centre on a 160-hectare site in South Dewsbury, was approved by the Kirklees Cabinet. The plan incorporates a large public park and six neighbourhoods with green spaces.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7f5deafc-4efa-400e-b2c8-390958bad517','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'To combat this, we worked with local community centres to establish Digital Hubs – designated spaces across Kirklees where anyone can learn basic digital skills and access technology in a safe way. Through these Hubs, we also offer access to devices and data for adults who don\'t have this at home. Our Green Hubs will repurpose unwanted laptops, desktops and tablets passing them to Kirklees residents who are digitally excluded. If you know someone who is digitally excluded, you can refer them to our Chromebook loan scheme.','Donating your unwanted IT equipment could change someone\'s life - Kirklees Together','Kirklees Together (Kirklees Council news)','2022-01-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHTHsdpczZtQMmh5AtMMTqRW87EuamCvorszt2AYTL_fHHejmww2RjN7Vfv3LKJLPN3cZVQt6a7QqrzD79CH80oU2oBxTKQhYG4pk1NJBYWoxQYG6A-zCpr4qM2DlSDp35Wlp00MXGh9PBcuc0XGhg5wWQqnniNZZjVfDVyctfaOK33ov-tsPJ8ZbrbbD5aK851ZyLGdTX33l1HAomCA5IYiPjl3Q==','Kirklees Council launched a \'Green Hub\' initiative in collaboration with community centres. This program encourages residents to donate old or unwanted IT equipment, which is then securely wiped, refurbished, and repurposed. These devices are provided to digitally excluded Kirklees residents through the Chromebook loan scheme and Digital Hubs, promoting both digital inclusion and environmental sustainability by diverting e-waste from landfill.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7f85f624-43d4-4e40-a6bf-b71f3043be04','infrastructure-moving-traffic-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.124','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On 5th July 2024 we submitted our application to the Department for Transport (DfT). This was to grant Calderdale Council the powers to enforce moving traffic contraventions under Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004. We are waiting for the DfT to approve our submission.','Moving Traffic Enforcement - Halifax - Calderdale Council (Application Submitted)','Calderdale Council','2024-07-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/moving-traffic-enforcement','Calderdale Council formally submitted its application to the Department for Transport (DfT) on July 5, 2024, seeking the powers to enforce moving traffic contraventions under Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004. The Council is currently awaiting approval from the DfT for its submission.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7f961207-89d1-4361-a3bf-85e56c2d296e','infrastructure-proposed-highway-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.142','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Surface improvement work is taking place on over 120 roads across Calderdale this summer. Calderdale Council has identified roads across the borough which require surface dressing. Each road will shortly be subject to maintenance, with bitumen and stone chippings applied to the road surface. This important work seals the road making it more waterproof, improves surface texture and prolongs the life of the road by many years. Road closures to prevent through traffic will be in place for the works around Cross Stone Road, Todmorden; Height Road through to Akroyd Lane in Mytholmroyd; works around Scammonden Road in Barkisland; Toothill Bank and Toothill Lane in Rastrick; and Garden Road and Blackburn Road in Brighouse.','Road surface improvements planned across Calderdale','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHpo3P8vFy4u8Qz8PBVEGsFiuQBJlzJSpMOJvs6woksBEpskCX_Gc8nIw707z6hr00U9VthX_JaHUrxFNGG4oaKPFY6Sjh3R6WzKQCnUX1x2B80Yrzqgvx4HICm76aAI_ICjK8F1-Mgk00HXDgka-nBSlGHZqZavNUGsmhEJzHCTVBc25w0CM1aQK7S-jBS','Calderdale Council announced a program of surface improvement work across over 120 roads in the borough during the summer months. The work involves applying bitumen and stone chippings to seal the road, improve surface texture, and extend its lifespan. Specific locations like Cross Stone Road (Todmorden), Height Road (Mytholmroyd), and Toothill Bank (Rastrick) are mentioned.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7fcd1e08-113d-4b3d-be2d-10b87d33158f','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'So we\'re here in the center of Bradford where over the last 12 months our teams have been transforming the city into the beautiful surroundings that you can see before you. We\'ve been appointed by the Scape Civil Engineering framework to deliver three interlinks projects: the City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements, the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension, and the South Bradford Targeted Bus Measures. We\'ve delivered these as an integrated program of works. We\'ve had pedestrianizations of some of the busiest streets in the city. We\'ve been able to create this green natural environment which is a benefit to the well-being of the residents.','Bradford transformed: From vision to reality (Balfour Beatty video)','YouTube (Balfour Beatty)','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UqQc8n4yRjY','Balfour Beatty, the contractor, released a video showcasing the completed transformation of Bradford City Centre. The video highlights the pedestrianisation of busy streets, creation of green natural environments, and improved public transport, cycling, and walking infrastructure, delivered as an integrated program of works, including the City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements, West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension, and South Bradford Targeted Bus Measures.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('7ff0dd4d-3f53-48b1-a96a-395ed544f08e','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council initiated a review of safe and active travel to school, including school crossing patrols, 20mph zones, and \'School Streets\'. The aim was to identify the best ways to encourage more children to walk and cycle, informing sustainable travel programs and infrastructure improvements, also considering impacts on health and air quality.','Calderdale Council aims to boost number of kids walking and cycling to school','Halifax Courier','2021-11-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFO_Q6-GF1FyupQRIQbjFxDeUdG9rM6_k-MAl724P5W1XbmmSU6wYwV4lLDEATr0IPf5Xf6gHYeX4s9KrMsz68mQYRflzCsjM9BIWUacsgTQ7iDkVmiiEMKsu1svHjsRkWQh_cBgThr1CpxlAL81QSgNzyt_N7ydiDhEQiezqtzOKymoUHY2QEM3ShXgyR3ZuBwgZykhGRrneQLJp-I_tF4lx941oVLhsbvXUH9xK1JtgA299Bok_Gto5dpGQ==','Calderdale Council initiated a review of safe and active travel to school, including school crossing patrols, 20mph zones, and \'School Streets\'. The aim was to identify the best ways to encourage more children to walk and cycle, informing sustainable travel programs and infrastructure improvements, also considering impacts on health and air quality.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8034ae09-ca94-4a57-bcdc-bcba2725c9c4','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Over £180m of investment in West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund schemes in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield is set to be approved at tomorrow\'s meeting of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. All of these schemes, which have been designed to support economic growth and the generation of new jobs, progress roads, rail facilities and infrastructure development across West Yorkshire and the City Region. Schemes, which were supported by the Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee earlier this month include the development of an outline business case for a new station at Elland. Bradford\'s Forster Square Station is set to be re-developed as a high-quality, facility providing a significantly enhanced gateway to the city. [16]','Combined Authority backs over £180m of investment for West Yorks Transport Fund schemes','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2017-06-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEDZigdgg1CQSQ9sfqI5BSWH8_FSLoWthoaYangtTE-PeVEulV37Y0GVyDkfNc_jdhVHlyJAsrqQsnFd_zMrr6t9-_XXetRkEQeZPgjbuDew3BuFqN-A4LdH0440aTmVqYdaGD7nuUNaiFjMI3TsSxRToLLouWGkwMiEcLCB4GaypYwusy9zX0DGSQEWAC99EQ7IL6xz63xeVX1FkhsrDPU_zKn-SrymNoxNRhOkvvafJg=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority approved over £180 million in investment for West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund schemes across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield. These schemes aim to support economic growth and job creation through improvements in roads, rail facilities, and infrastructure development. Specific projects mentioned include a new station at Elland, redevelopment of Bradford Forster Square Station, expanded park and ride facilities, and the A629 Halifax to Huddersfield Corridor Improvement scheme. [16]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('80a07ea9-f551-4e75-bccf-772d1e60c757','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Growing Resilience Natural Flood Management (NFM) Upper Aire Project was a 2 year project with a budget of £388,000 which delivered hundreds of small individual interventions spread across a large area. ... Final total delivered: • 23 Landowners engaged. • 284 Leaky Dams. • 20 Leaky Bunds. • 8 Ponds. • 12,000 trees planted. • 7.76km riparian/ hedge/tree fencing. • 2.9km new/ restored hedging. • 120ha farmland aeration. [24]','Growing Resilience – Leeds City Region Natural Flood Management Programme - The Upper Aire Project (Final Report/Summary)','The Upper Aire Project (document/report)','2021-10-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHQzoIrgj6I16jzyCau7KjM_9402xFId92YgB9knl7KCZoTtC38LNkOaSwi5d4w8b5ldtg12ulpYl7uZ88sxNdbMUFQ9M_jn8Kpl6L8aglab7UD6EkNnIJ42WQWG1uqFjh5kUJ2koHM5HLVMidLipcM_OJUMFiUafNckNRGStTfR8=','A detailed report outlines the achievements of the £388,000 Upper Aire NFM project, including the construction of 284 leaky dams, 20 leaky bunds, 8 ponds, 12,000 trees planted, and 120 hectares of farmland aeration. The project successfully engaged 23 landowners and involved multiple partners and volunteers, contributing to flood resilience and habitat enhancement. [24]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('80d641da-e6df-4834-bb43-5f1af1e23cec','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'2020 was an especially hard year because of COVID-19 straight after flooding, but joint work has continued on the recovery and future resilience. “As we approach the one-year anniversary of our latest major flood, we want to say a big thank you to everyone in our communities for their continued support to reduce flood risk and tackle the climate emergency.” Adrian Gill, area flood risk manager at the Environment Agency said, “Storm Ciara had a devastating impact on many people, homes and businesses across the region. It also made life incredibly difficult for flood agencies, who immediately began work on emergency repairs and recovery activity, whilst working through the challenges of the pandemic.”... The Council has been ramping up its work with groups like Slow the Flow, Moors for the Future and Treesponsibility on nature-based solutions to flooding (Natural Flood Management), including planting trees, providing flood attenuation ponds, restoring moorland and installing 309 leaky woody dams through its landowner grant scheme. Grants from the Council and the Environment Agency in 2020 have helped to complete 15 natural schemes, with a further four in progress.','Updates on Flood Recovery and Natural Flood Management a Year After Storm Ciara','HebWeb News 2021 - One year on from Storm Ciara','2021-02-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEqAJH-SHRGwNf4fiWB35iAf8vNig4zaL0n_uc_Ic2Vmo8qkztHFVvngYXfoHpLTzqyTcoX22zW_yV9LGeyhoI7o0NBym97AMbvt3817Yw3prjPQ6jcpo8qQaB3mZ_Na7tzA7E1O3RxjVCzoeE=','A year after Storm Ciara (Feb 2020), updates in February 2021 highlighted continued joint work on flood recovery and future resilience in Calderdale. This included ramping up work with groups like Slow the Flow on nature-based solutions and the completion of 15 natural flood management schemes, with four more in progress.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('80e2b38d-dab6-44e7-9d3e-1b09f5a30884','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-places-scheme-cornholme-a646-active-travel',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.168','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A multi-million-pound project to improve walking, wheeling and cycling facilities in West Yorkshire is taking a major step forward. The new £5.1 million West Yorkshire Places scheme includes proposals such as new street crossings and lighting, improved green spaces and traffic calming measures. People are now being asked for their views on the West Yorkshire Combined Authority initiative, which will help encourage more people to choose active travel and make local neighbourhoods safer and more attractive across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees and Wakefield. Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin said: “Everybody in West Yorkshire deserves to have access to low-cost, sustainable travel options. ... In Cornholme, proposals include new footway links along the A646, new pedestrian crossings, and a one-way system on Greenfield Terrace.','New £5.1 million proposals to improve active travel across West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGUxwvbC65Bs6Tqby17s0O8Kv0AG_m1fkIA1SDfxST7ZVWObze46Blrq2zjepJgSeH4cegQCUGh2xlVHrceDWz74gRA2op5nDa5bMBEE-wY--I7TKkZJIpAPcCgoBWzjpH4PkdFsENfNCBdlyyj57aG8NXfv45Y5GY8yEnD8M1KX4admOslldF58JOV5I8ujbIoDyuMpwV9bw79P_BjdZLcinHt_DVtNIB6dG3FE7IBcB90','This article highlights the launch of the £5.1 million West Yorkshire Places scheme. It details the overall aims of the project, including new street crossings, improved green spaces, and traffic calming across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield. Specifically for Cornholme, it reiterates proposals for new footway links along the A646, pedestrian crossings, and a one-way system on Greenfield Terrace.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('811a6cf8-a9aa-4690-b14d-69eba6059b29','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The £35m Grade A office development on the edge of City Park - delivered by Muse in partnership with Bradford Council - was recently completed. Now, it has been confirmed that contracts have been exchanged with a corporate anchor tenant. The building\'s first tenant is due to be named in the coming weeks. The building has now been formally handed over to Bradford Council as the owners.','Bradford\'s One City Park secures \'high-profile\' tenant / One City Park scheme celebrates completion and letting','Telegraph and Argus / OneCity','2023-12-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHAV_qK-7G9Zn63MzpTMbhFHariHjzgcxiwKkCcaVB7qTvuU8xI5zNKzdO51QWKuUHAzGg-DZHNy_IqvvTyd7VyrJ-oNwP18DOvPnalSCBGkjzkOQpLrBJRAevL2kxJLQYCyVJFOMkS_x5JCdP7gcFzE19y7n29Zw-E6fXlevem4hKEhjMWRtQfRrQ3Qa-U2wQpWwGyrotZQQyJnmr74k3oHyeW','The £35 million Grade A office development, One City Park, was officially completed and formally handed over to Bradford Council. The project secured a corporate anchor tenant, later revealed to be PwC.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('816bcc2f-67d5-464c-8924-33bd70ec2c39','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-places-scheme-cornholme-a646-active-travel',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.168','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Key Dates: Engagement start date. 19 March 2025. Drop-in - Vale Baptist Church. 02 April 2025. Webinar - Zoom. 09 April 2025. Drop-in - Cornholme Old Library. 23 April 2025. Engagement end date. 30 April 2025. ... All survey answers, comments and suggestions are being considered before developing the final designs. Please find the Outcome Report available at the top of this webpage or by clicking the button below. Outcome report. We will publish a \'You Said, We Listened\' in October which shows how we have considered and responded to your feedback on the proposed changes. We will show you the preferred measures and explain our reasons for selecting these. We will then take these decisions forward to the detailed design stage with a view to begin delivery in March 2026.','Cornholme pedestrian improvements - Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Key Dates and Delivery)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice platform)','2025-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHQbBY3CDeX7hEFdUK_vtYVSdD9Ce_n9xxUUpEMCO-rEtUVsjonNOkkeThwlBppiTo_ybj820khGUASAxWeidDViRP5JFzJQC-7Slo8Qv1R-y97jDRKNC0Dg5NEjpY_Qp3GOnV1wXQbRYc3T7aSXxJV5wFY-KrMPXc=','This section of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s consultation page for Cornholme provides a timeline for public engagement and project delivery. It states the engagement period ran from March 19 to April 30, 2025, with drop-in sessions and a webinar. It also indicates that an \'Outcome Report\' will be available, a \'You Said, We Listened\' report will be published in October 2025, and delivery is projected to begin in March 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('817d2081-2ee6-4b41-a92c-124069cc69f1','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Stubbing Holme Road FAS will consist of: • Raising and strengthening river walls along. Stubbing Holme Road. • Strengthening walls along Rochdale canal overflow at the Vale Centre site. • A flood mitigation solution at Longstaff Court. • Improving protection to riverside properties. Construction work is currently programmed to commence in 2023. Look out for invitations to face-to-face public meetings and virtual zoom meetings where we will share the proposals with you ahead of planning submissions and provide an opportunity to ask questions and speak to the project team. In the meantime if you have any questions about any of the flood alleviation schemes, members of the project team will be available in Hebden Bridge Town Hall every Monday throughout August and. September from 10am – 2pm.','Keeping You Informed - Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme (August/September update)','AWS (Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme update)','2022-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://environment-agency.s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/Hebden-Bridge-FAS-Keep-You-Informed.pdf','An update for the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme indicated that construction work for the Stubbing Holme Road FAS was programmed to commence in 2023. Project team members were available in Hebden Bridge Town Hall every Monday throughout August and September to discuss the schemes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('818b3508-f2d0-489c-978c-87f00cfd1f02','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In Group B, the strategic outline business case for Hebble Brook (Dean Clough) has been approved. ... Calderdale Council has implemented improvements to access and telemetry at the Hebble Brook screen, aimed at preventing screen blockages and potential flooding.','Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Update: Hebble Brook SOBC Approved & Screen Improvements','Calderdale Council','2024-09-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG8WpyuN3HoT1VA2X_fFMdkMrv_SZ_hWRAISdUch5l5iys666CpWuaNrmai1FsvWQDGWgr8y-uIDmXZsQRKVo043wWvhbpWnwDbDs9TNWCwPihweR4U4qsPWolxaUBsHY6vBt2xIaMW86w4al5C9ijwUy44qebLc5Vx-nXJESh0M9PseG7YDb3wpXPljJPB5g==','An update on the Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme reported that the Strategic Outline Business Case for the Hebble Brook (Dean Clough) scheme had been approved. Additionally, Calderdale Council had implemented improvements to access and telemetry at the Hebble Brook screen, aimed at preventing blockages and potential flooding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8191ba52-b74b-4cb1-8548-816cee62c730','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This commission will look to secure external consultancy support to develop the mobility hub programme. This will consist of two principal tasks: -Task 1: Business Case Development (Mobility Hubs phase 1) Support the development of Phase 1 of the Mobility Hubs programme in Calderdale including developing the outline business case (OBC). ... It is intended that the outline business case will be submitted on 22nd May 2022 for consideration at a June PAT meeting.','West Yorkshire Mobility Hubs – Business Case Support - EU Supply','EU Supply','2022-05-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGWR8v3AnlI7mtzN6udwrsJkPNLK4OEC2XBpDNHgmypO5hVXqjbfzU8TorUfgcTsklrKyEyfGplu6oolCRKSrXrV3QSRrTIZoQmaCiV4u9EcR40_6MrP7kry_yJmqz-e01_487I4cOFQMnvWS9xwYRIllur1mxVi1mJFz1sqv2WbXhFt8xTjoYlzRn756iQWnJNFDB8gfbiwGPtdmj','A procurement notice for external consultancy support to develop the mobility hub programme. This commission specifically focuses on supporting the development of Phase 1 of the Mobility Hubs programme in Calderdale, including the creation of an outline business case (OBC). The OBC was intended for submission on May 22, 2022, and also includes developing a prioritisation framework for future phases.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('81e48149-0c4d-4aca-8447-a9ad24fddfa4','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Feedback from local people and organisations is being used to help shape plans to improve walking and cycling provision in north and west Halifax. Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is working on two projects which focus on a number of changes to roads and facilities around the areas of north and west of Halifax. ... The Full Business Case incorporating these updated proposals will soon be submitted to the Combined Authority and pending further approvals, construction is expected in late 2024/ early 2025.','Feedback Shapes Improvements in North and West Halifax','Calderdale Council News Centre','2023-12-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGQOpPCFBB7uvq9sjrU2c44acUBoF1TM6ax6oJTaigp3xZbh8GjINB_itvZjtr5JKxyvb7-NxAq6On4qBKFiv-CPStYrPvC3jRFn2ZrHOK_-5J5LSTj-NOZKklVTL7vBrhSrjNHUj5p1lOi912vDdc81w2Pi2pUj0vrWeo48hql8KfLjWnc03IXHj5BdW2klKCC','Feedback from local people and organisations gathered during early 2023 has been used to shape plans for improving walking and cycling provision in North and West Halifax. The Full Business Case for these projects, incorporating the updated proposals, is expected to be submitted soon, with construction anticipated in late 2024/early 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('82515208-0282-4a05-85b2-4b3690502007','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Residents and businesses are being asked for their views on proposals to invest up to £22.5 million in two key roads connecting Leeds and Wakefield – the A61 and the A639. Residents and businesses are being consulted on the proposals between Monday, July 4 and Sunday, August 14. [7]','A61 and A639 scheme: Public consultation to be held on new bus and cycle route plans for key Leeds to Wakefield roads','Yorkshire Evening Post / West Yorkshire Combined Authority Your Voice','2022-07-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEvtoZhNEk0HKuN3bt0JfdaRAiYv-eykSKD6prmPYLmNT7akRDIYu_oVLXrHj7snilIH4cOy6eSnyhp1Fgzyb_6QWbBOucBxJw45lLPYLSWWQBufgUIka8RgJdYl2PEX4rhlQZ1DwsGfn73iDNq6MSJq25TjW_wRJEV0Q-xA2qdhbN7KmvXL7Trf4rXu3hW08igOySCToypjT7iFsKdzBFcjVQVqzGDALG-gj7qsvUt8BfF31hk46NZqi8PGmznjtsk5Qxthyv7OzrNdAvRcBg-NzIfiyb5QLKS_oYh4zEMzxxyKsuSGPNj-0zlx2x0','A public consultation was launched on July 4, 2022, inviting residents and businesses to provide feedback on the initial proposals for the A61 and A639 improvements. The consultation, which ran until August 14, 2022, detailed plans for dedicated bus and cycle lanes, new crossings, wider pavements, and smart traffic lights to enhance travel between Leeds and Wakefield District. [7, 8, 11]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('825fb173-5dfe-4f3a-9424-f253cd610976','infrastructure-home-bargains-garforth-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.429','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with the 5 districts of West Yorkshire, carried out a public consultation on the LEVI fund proposals. The consultation opened on 25th July 2024 and ended on 11th September 2024. [4, 9]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Opens Public Consultation on LEVI Fund Proposals','Your Voice West Yorkshire','2024-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFrX9QpIdRmBFYkkE0vCphsxIqChtbrFS63KBAG2vbEalU7PS0UEXtm3mJJRTeYsMlt4tYvguV8ojhYdboJ1wMzhpeJ28w-zd3rcyuK9j8AGM_OxSmA4QW6uO223LdmBLX3FdE9Gyc9CQ','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in collaboration with its five districts (including Leeds), launched a public consultation on July 25, 2024, regarding proposals for the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) fund. This sought feedback on plans to install public charge points in residential areas for residents without off-street parking, concluding on September 11, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('82e86ed8-46d3-4bf0-888e-f2b2455ca687','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The new Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme is now available across the district to help qualifying private households install free solar power, insulation and other measures. ... HERO is a £1.5m Wakefield scheme which is part of the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme. And applications are now being taken. ... The measures available could include: • Solar PV electric panel systems • Loft insulation • Cavity wall insulation • Air Source Heat pumps • High energy efficiency electric storage heaters. ... The HERO scheme is available until March 2028, but funds are restricted each year and will be allocated on a first come, first served basis so interested residents are urged to apply now.','Council launches new scheme to provide free home energy improvements (HERO Scheme)','Wakefield Council','2025-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHTnNBj_-wAGY9aPK_SajnRhqUS6v4lKdVr_oqLlq6oxVOwi-XOTj4MsT-DXILtCMmIGHpPgR8xXnvFpfo9b8ek8t3S0uJHOoC-y-pK7WUoNDc4SbU_jNbEtre89IZhzHAqmFZiiXUtG9lQi4Vg32jPbvxDgXDOqqObzrH4_uiZcGjgvZZvx3oVlpBs1zP0Tq1S0w6HWmwQJADAn4Z90gfyQGNK0Q-UDj1bGQ==','Wakefield Council launched the Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme, a £1.5 million initiative funded by the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme, to provide free home energy improvements to qualifying private households in the district. Measures include solar PV electric panel systems, insulation, and heat pumps. Applications are being taken, and the scheme is available until March 2028, with funds allocated on a first-come, first-served basis. This scheme, while for private households, contributes to the overall energy efficiency and carbon reduction goals in the Wakefield district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8321b351-7500-401d-aa81-0133d5892399','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We have launched a public engagement on proposals to improve roads at four busy routes to the south of Huddersfield. The scheme, known at the \'Huddersfield Southern Corridors\', has been developed by us in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and would be funded through the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund. It outlines improvement proposals to roads at Lockwood, Longroyd Bridge, Folly Hall and Queensgate that all aim to better manage traffic, reduce queues and improve conditions for cyclists and pedestrians. The public can view plans and have their say from Monday 30 September to Friday 25 October 2019. [6, 7, 9]','We have opened engagement on improvements to Huddersfield\'s southern corridors','Kirklees Council / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-09-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/news/archive/2019/southern-corridors-engagement.aspx (similar content in [6], [7], [9])','Kirklees Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public engagement on proposals for road improvements at Lockwood, Longroyd Bridge, Folly Hall, and Queensgate, aimed at better traffic management, reduced queues, and enhanced conditions for cyclists and pedestrians. The scheme is funded through the West Yorkshire-plus Transport Fund and the Leeds City Region Growth Deal. The engagement period ran from September 30 to October 25, 2019.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('83a8d9b6-1c27-40cc-9f4b-b252ef999919','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-02-04) The second stage of consultation has launched today to improve two key roads linking Leeds to Wakefield and Pontefract. Run in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, the consultation aims to make it safer and more accessible to walk, wheel and cycle, as well as improving bus reliability. ... For the A61 in Lofthouse, the proposals focus on two key junctions which have known safety concerns, lack of safe crossing points for school students and pedestrians, and cars travelling at speed – the A61 Jumbles Lane junction and the A61 Carlton Lane junction. ... If the proposals were to go ahead, a £9.14million funding pot from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund, ringfenced to transport schemes, would be invested to carry out the works - £2m for the A61 and £7.14m for Pontefract Road.','Consultation launches on travel improvements to A61 junctions and B6481 Pontefract Road','Leeds City Council News','2025-02-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHmVveYLwLyBRtc_nJkhayRRz8J7gGaeQkZmXROVfYUYvi5R2L9HT897NMSsOGsfxk-oK7cSpAzhoejL6ak-tfeHgp-VkuCT0rJRwt-VRwZhjViKHgdzyV4Pos9fkyDWH1PzThNLEB03N1Rzk9zIf5GuPwob8q2v9QCtA1MIn35Vi3zIUl6lbMNnfwpOSzzgS8PsYDgAcJwpN7NDT3n9rfvtwbKqUYsBvnM6xZCYEOGHQXE=','Leeds City Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a second stage of public consultation on February 4, 2025. This consultation focuses on further improvements to specific sections of the A61 in Lofthouse (Jumbles Lane and Carlton Lane junctions) and the B6481 Pontefract Road, linking Leeds to Wakefield and Pontefract. These proposals, funded by a £9.14 million pot from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund, aim to enhance safety and accessibility for active travel and improve bus reliability. [18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('83cfd46e-ad3d-4723-ab18-6a2a342e9026','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Fenay Lane site was identified as part of the council\'s housing growth strategy and following a land sale process, Kirklees Council has appointed the developer to deliver the West Yorkshire site. The homes will be made up of private market and affordable homes, and once constructed Yorkshire Housing will manage the latter. Design work has begun and Vistry is expected to submit a planning application at the end of the year, with the aim of construction starting in late summer 2026...','Vistry Group to build 150-home Almondbury scheme','Place Yorkshire','2025-03-27 00:00:00.000','https://placeyorkshire.co.uk/vistry-group-to-build-150-home-almondbury-scheme/','Place Yorkshire also covered the appointment of Vistry Group by Kirklees Council to deliver the 150-home scheme on Fenay Lane. The article reiterates that the site was part of the council\'s housing growth strategy, and the development will include private and affordable homes, with the latter managed by Yorkshire Housing. Design work is underway, with a planning application expected at the end of 2025 and construction slated for late summer 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('84053da9-8b09-4165-bcd9-2486dfccd45e','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A letter from the Secretary of State, Grant Shapps, to Mayor Tracy Brabin confirmed the finalised delivery plan for West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) for the next five years. The letter acknowledged the work to finalise outstanding details of the delivery plan. It stated that WYCA has local flexibility in managing the programme to deliver against agreed outcomes, but should not expect additional HMG funding to meet any cost overruns. The Integrated Rail Plan for the North and Midlands had committed £100m to start work on the West Yorkshire Mass Transit System.','Finalised City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement: letter to Mayor Tracy Brabin','GOV.UK','2022-07-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/city-region-sustainable-transport-settlements-confirmed-delivery-plans-and-funding-allocations/finalised-city-region-sustainable-transport-settlement-letter-to-mayor-tracy-brabin','This letter from the Secretary of State to Mayor Tracy Brabin confirms the finalised programme delivery plan for West Yorkshire\'s CRSTS. It builds upon the initial funding confirmation in April 2022, acknowledging the significant work undertaken to reach this stage. The letter grants local flexibility in managing the programme to achieve agreed outcomes but reiterates that no additional government funding will be provided for cost overruns. It also references a £100m commitment from the Integrated Rail Plan for the North and Midlands to start work on the West Yorkshire Mass Transit System.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('841eb7ea-68d0-42cf-816f-e805076edf59','infrastructure-a629-halifax-to-huddersfield-corridor-improvement-phase-4-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.884','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We have objected to this new planning application for Halifax Road – for improvement and widening of the A629). It does not include provision for dedicated cycling paths or alternatives. In part, that was meant to be provided by Phase 4 – but this has been sidelined indefinitely. We cannot support this scheme until it is either redesigned to incorporate cycling, or Phase 4 is completed in line with the government guidelines (in LTN 1/20).','Halifax Road (A629) New planning application, we object! | Cycle Kirklees','Cycle Kirklees','2023-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHtYYdy--WKEitgzO0EKZrf4-UPGAv-2_NteT3pfBVCIftRSGlTR22rY0-0t6IQjYFbnuz9Jmu8ubHRqPpJ3Rf4hLww7XkLybCHB79F1E3MYQPZe6Tr8VE1k6OEwgJyuQgXeyS_WGMMFv8OYd0cbOl-noHL86bwVEeln8TBH6KQjGJ-U2jHpmqRJQcAYEs=','Cycle Kirklees lodged an objection to a new planning application for A629 Halifax Road (Phase 5), stating that Phase 4, which was intended to include dedicated cycling paths, has been \'sidelined indefinitely\' due to the project\'s pause. They argue that any major road scheme must comply with LTN 1/20 standards for cycling infrastructure and cannot support the current Phase 5 design without such provision or the completion of Phase 4.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('844376c7-7614-4c98-9132-93984c47407d','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A NEW tram-train link across the district could be constructed as part of a plan to turn the north into an \'economic powerhouse\' to rival London, it has been revealed. A major report was unveiled today calling for up to £15 billion of investment in transport links across the north of England. The report, called \'One North\', was compiled by the cities of Liverpool, Manchester, Leeds, Sheffield and Newcastle, with input from Bradford Council and West Yorkshire transport authority Metro. ... The report says within Bradford, there is a need for a \'north-south link such as a tram-train or similar\', which could be developed by 2026. It is understood that this would likely be a light-rail link between Bradford Forster Square station and the airport, first suggested some years ago, with a possible extension down to the Euroway Industrial Estate south of the city. [15]','Bradford train-tram link proposed as part of £15bn transport plan for the north','Ilkley Gazette','2014-08-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.ilkleygazette.co.uk/news/11406180.bradford-train-tram-link-proposed-as-part-of-15bn-transport-plan-for-the-north/','A major report named \'One North\', compiled by northern cities including input from Bradford Council and West Yorkshire transport authority Metro, unveiled a proposal for a new tram-train link across the Bradford district. This link, envisioned to be developed by 2026, was understood to be a light-rail connection between Bradford Forster Square station and Leeds Bradford Airport, with a possible extension to Euroway Industrial Estate. Chancellor George Osborne welcomed the plans, committing new money for infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('84e77aa7-fc6a-4177-9d33-fa73821a6fac','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford\'s new Darley Street Market is more than a shopping destination, it\'s a vibrant hub of food, culture, and community. From Thai satay to Sri Lankan curry, live music to rooftop views, it\'s drawing visitors from across Yorkshire. ... Set across three bustling floors and an outdoor courtyard, Darley Street Market is a bold addition to the city centre. It\'s a space that doesn\'t just sell things; it brings people together.','Darley Street Market: Bradford\'s bold new space is buzzing, but can it go one step further?','RFM Photography / Yorkshire Post','2025-08-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/','One month after its grand opening, Bradford\'s Darley Street Market has established itself as a bustling hub for food, culture, and community, successfully attracting visitors from across Yorkshire. The market\'s diverse array of food stalls and lively entertainment options are contributing to a positive shift in public perception of Bradford, highlighting its success as a dynamic social venue.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('84ed7380-2844-4003-9704-92e67e189759','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Funding for this project was secured from the Future High Streets Fund in May 2021. Westgate phase 2 and Palatine Chambers. Support for a local developer to bring derelict land and buildings back into use. This scheme will provide high quality spaces for local business. The work will create a public realm that complements Westgate phase 1. It will provide visual links with Borough Market and the Piece Hall. [3]','Halifax Development Board | Calderdale Council - Westgate phase 2 and Palatine Chambers','Calderdale Council','2021-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEYWmnMs3ZEmsqPAtv-eCE8IxaQ074vERmz0VPeaui7wZG3Sm0pQoEwQ0vMbGv6T8saB-OEL77TrIOPOCDbFj1ot_jp6AgU7PrZg87SHsNU4tg4mB2aJ9t_BzpK2O3F2iFzqrzAzOQDK9jeA1cf55abFKhATKLSvyQVY9yi4RQyoP2RuxImY55z29A=','This Calderdale Council page mentions that funding for the Westgate phase 2 and Palatine Chambers project, which aims to bring derelict land and buildings back into use for high-quality business spaces and public realm improvements, was secured from the Future High Streets Fund in May 2021.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('851fef62-d89e-45d8-8bf1-73afed4aafd4','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point located at Tingley Wakefield, WF3 1TB is part of the Project EV network. There are 2 devices and 2 connectors available at this charging location. To plan your route or see the latest status info for this charge point, download the Zapmap app or go to the Zapmap web map. Address: Tingley Wakefield. 12 Upper Green Avenue, Tingley. Wakefield. Yorkshire and the Humber. WF3 1TB. Network: Project EV. Sources: Zapmap. Updated: 16th June 2025.','Tingley Wakefield EV charging point, Wakefield - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-06-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHt9KylAH3H01HS0k0MigFVqs8NMV6ETqK3wozoxLbTqUltSZnTe6hJDldtVprqMTSOr-t8HI580-AEnIK_lRo2CXwRShTysjttKiTYokvVyzQimd_ee6wnVpymRd_5TrM_mzJlpVZcfh-QSm8DHVPN7ww=','A Zapmap listing, last updated on June 16, 2025, confirms the presence of an electric vehicle charging point at 12 Upper Green Avenue, Tingley, Wakefield, WF3 1TB. This charging point is part of the Project EV network and features 2 devices and 2 connectors.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('85f1a0a1-bfb4-479b-9c12-ae07f1a0b722','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A report to the council\'s Cabinet on Tuesday January 23 says that £75 million had been allocated for the A62 Cooper Bridge scheme but phasing it would mean that £22 million could be used to re-start other schemes. ... This will mean a phased approach to the scheme – which will see improvements at Cooper Bridge roundabout delivered during the first phase, and the remaining improvements delivered over a longer period of time (subject to more detailed evaluation of the project).','Kirklees Cabinet Approves Phased Approach for A62 Cooper Bridge Scheme','Kirklees Together / Dewsbury Reporter','2024-01-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEjTbCB6hCcgAm2IzIlKVSJxLpVd1XEYNcTqFNdrtD3oiM9-u7oh4G9r0swU1V20cLbSPqfbWb8BCzjc3VTINnXy3rsC-QhT5RaYx2ctus1_OUXau7cpido23OxhnMpWxGsqkmzyJMBP4-qCsFQLpFZVJdvUYCl88peYbPp9OxoetjJy7VULrbf9gM0jcsXF_wLjuwP6-URkZc8pirxLFE=','On January 23, 2024, Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet agreed to a new strategy for the A62 to Cooper Bridge scheme, adopting a phased approach. The first phase will focus on improvements at the Cooper Bridge roundabout with a budget of £53 million, allowing some funding to be redistributed to other projects. [9, 11, 12]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('85f608b2-f61e-4f6f-bf6c-86adf42a62d1','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A planning statement submitted as part of the application said: “The refurbishment and bringing back into active use a building which currently detracts from the surrounding heritage assets and wider area. This will assist with the wider regeneration of the site and provide employment opportunities to existing and future residents of the Holbeck area.” Permission is being sought to refurbish the building, including the re-organisation of internal space to create 85,000 sq ft of space – mainly for office use which could be for a single or multiple occupants. A new cafe is also planned and the main entrance will be moved to a more prominent location. [3]','CEG Submits Office Development Plans in Leeds - Temple Works','Insider Media Ltd','2020-09-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.insidermedia.com/news/yorkshire/ceg-submits-office-development-plans-in-leeds','CEG submitted planning applications for the refurbishment of Temple Works to create 85,000 sq ft of office space, including a new café, improved exterior, and internal hub facilities, aiming to bring the derelict building back into active use.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('861c6cdb-3ae4-43f6-baf6-b72f48b19302','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Progress. The project was completed at the end of November 2018. Final milestones included the seeding of the innovative living wall, the reopening of Dryclough Lane, and the resurfacing of the 3km of highway from Salterhebble to Shaw Hill. The first project paves the way for further improvements in the next major part of the scheme – the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction. ... The project saw Salterhebble Hill widened to four lanes, new traffic light technology installed and improved facilities for pedestrians, cyclists and public transport.','A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill project completed','Calderdale Next Chapter','2018-11-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHZZp4BxNz3rD4M_BDWg9sl45_EeKq36mO2s-8XjjFwMEn5Pksm502z9Hqal95Ep723tpoJT65-qAqNgYuT9frGkciPzwrfHPMg_2jkoMoCNSw0xM7Fynyzm1-2JqcVykclBpIIvryAKpKJVwTFccMPT0Jc2mbvlymBBCkBHr_ioU1PqA==','The Calderdale Next Chapter project page for the A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill improvement confirms the project\'s completion at the end of November 2018. The project involved widening Salterhebble Hill to four lanes, installing new traffic light technology, and improving facilities for pedestrians, cyclists, and public transport, including a dedicated bus lane and end-to-end cycle lanes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('86573f8e-83e7-4057-b26a-35386806c67c','infrastructure-halifax-future-high-streets-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.256','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Out of those 57, five in Yorkshire are included in the list. They are: Elland - £6,310,812; Northallerton - £6,085,013; Rotherham - £12,660,708; Halifax - £11,762,823; Barnsley - £15,624,456.','Five Yorkshire towns set to transform their high streets thanks to £52m cash injection from Government','YorkshireLive','2020-12-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQER_973XZZNIcv85yvkL0NtFLaNiGaB6fqRCccdlWmJvTQyY4m3LTLmFKTXS0TABrlI9NxqkKthTKObJv-dzcGaDWIsOPt51xaY7Bpg5Od-_jXvJboA8P-XOITE16dbkTXz8vuMqrge8UJ_NOC2X3oIGmntnp77iSWWg8Y6RnME4Loair488nizZgzjG7gcWNKBs9irMbY=','This article announces the provisional funding offers from the Future High Streets Fund. Halifax is provisionally allocated £11,762,823 as one of five towns in Yorkshire to receive funding as part of the government\'s £830 million investment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('868e754b-bdc7-4da5-b217-afc34c12918d','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Prime Minister Keir Starmer has re-committed £30m worth of Government support to a project intended to transform parts of Bradford city centre. Last year it was announced that the City Village scheme would get around £30m funding from Homes England. The project will see housing, offices, cafes and retail space, and green areas built on three different city centre sites. The bulk of the development will take place on land currently occupied by the Kirkgate Shopping Centre and Oastler Market – both of which are due to be demolished in the coming years. Around 1,000 homes will be developed as part of the project.','PM Confirms £30m For Bradford City Village Scheme','Great Yorkshire Radio','2025-02-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG7IAqGcM8NfJ0ZFUWzTZvlHJh_mAXI4kSbV3es4U76VXI1bQDtynaT95n42ROAMp6jqOnvH-xFb9NBLP2FFgWdqJfFV9cIw07Sn3QtYH7SluWQNoMa8oW395WKHVDv1hmQ7hPQbI-WXejUVhfIu1dknJjPYWfHZeThATfedbm0L-b2lRP1hNVeYZreBAavphirR3h3UKM1ybE','Prime Minister Keir Starmer re-committed £30 million in government support for the Bradford City Village scheme from Homes England. This funding is part of efforts to regenerate areas and use brownfield land, supporting the development of around 1,000 homes, offices, cafes, retail space, and green areas on three city centre sites, including the Kirkgate Shopping Centre and Oastler Market.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('86f9c4fd-9199-4370-8594-9d12d5dc824c','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The South Bank Planning Statement, adopted in October 2011, proposes an overall vision to transform the South Bank of Leeds City Centre into a distinctive, vibrant, well connected, sustainable business and residential community which has at its heart a new City Centre Park. This park will act as a catalyst for regeneration and place-shaping, improving connections to surrounding communities and contributing to the Aire Valley Urban Eco-Settlement. [20]','Adopted October 2011 - Leeds City Council South Bank Planning Statement','Leeds City Council','2011-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/docs/Adopted%20South%20Bank%20Planning%20Statement%20October%202011.pdf','This document outlines the vision for the South Bank area of Leeds City Centre, aiming to transform it into a distinctive, vibrant, well-connected, sustainable business and residential community with a new City Centre Park at its heart. It serves as foundational planning for regeneration in the wider South Bank, which the South Village project contributes to.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('870a1c65-d951-46aa-bcfc-015c06658fb5','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On August 7, 2024, new plans for Bradford Interchange were announced. The exterior plaza at the Interchange entrance will be significantly improved, with new paving, planting, public art and seating in place of the taxi rank. Passenger access to the rail station will be upgraded, including opening up the escalator and a lift, as well as providing a refreshed waiting area and visual improvements to the space. The existing toilets will also be reopened and made free of charge. The project draws on some of the £22 million of funding previously set aside for improvements. The Combined Authority\'s planning application will be considered by a Bradford Council planning committee.','New plans for Bradford Interchange due to investment','WYMetro','2024-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGfG3RzBMFF1E9G0bPdaKo1TZN9B8isTSYu2Ns4vRrXONB-uQ9lpVNMFQrUC9wOVEIuILzqCyiKrDnFJyOUn6hAzIt85bNSGkjfIz2k-CM2D5YkX9nmNdkc4nG9fpfxC3EvaJlZJcX1mAsRWDfN2d7_JlPc18mJ0QWezeKd91RZAi1Gi2goGMeT3boG-o0fqdaNwjpX28B1WJQjKRY89hSS','New plans were announced for the Bradford Interchange, focusing on upgrading passenger access to the rail station, refreshing waiting areas, and improving the exterior plaza with new paving, planting, and public art. These works draw on some of the £22 million previously set aside for Interchange improvements, with a planning application submitted by Bradford Council. The project addresses the ongoing bus station closure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('871b4ce2-9d46-47dc-be01-f3a20ba3dd41','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Osprey Charging Network opens EV charging hub in Wakefield at Snowhill Retail Park. ... Yorkshire residents, businesses and visitors\' EV charging access improved this week with the opening of a hub of four new EV charge points at Snowhill Retail Park in Wakefield.','New hub: Snowhill Retail Park, Wakefield. - Osprey Charging','Osprey Charging','2025-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEEEHJ0-fPf_qx6vU31rFFPy_f1VfOAw9RJy8r6omnJoaMSVauxY7ficAcIoGEasYPmLFIERM0FfhlHZrRaJeCHvYIxyEYgMgBdvfpxjL4Auwi5MRFVagDYeyRLghku00bcyKplkUM7fUirjXVeTgoEjYnXnA2ejYw1nyyYXA','Osprey Charging Network officially announced the opening of its EV charging hub at Snowhill Retail Park in Wakefield. The hub features four new super-fast 300kW chargers, capable of adding 100 miles of range in 15-20 minutes, significantly improving EV charging access for residents and visitors in Yorkshire.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('877bbd38-3e68-49f2-aaec-f46a092f60e8','infrastructure-halifax-future-high-streets-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.256','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Halifax is building a national and international reputation as a place of culture. A programme of physical infrastructure regeneration is in place across the town including a new sixth form centre. ... The FHSF investment will also unlock private investment in the second phase of the privately-owned Westgate Quarter project.','Halifax Future High Streets Fund - FULL BUSINESS CASE (FBC)','Calderdale Council','2020-05-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGj5rG5onFSMGSRiyB5rygrfgUDU4uDAc8jWvim6g1PGx2Ekwt1BGqa0lOGGXir0XMWvNgbaaecq3J0bP42R0QHgEfVJDJltwZ_ORwok6l2eA4Lp-E6RajITpUDc98MPQ-dtGk2fwDXE5rgKqlHO5aBAKwGGknQRIM7x26zHZ4hDsB2DmC4baRbYkgrf_M=','This document outlines the Full Business Case for the Halifax Future High Streets Fund, detailing the vision for renewing Halifax town centre. It focuses on revitalizing key historic buildings, improving connectivity, creating new event spaces, and enhancing public realm, stating a requested funding of £17,382,215 from FHSF.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('87dec204-a6e5-408c-a209-aa3bfa033bf8','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council has a number of schemes in the City Region WY+TF package. Focus is now firmly on delivery of a number of these schemes by 2021. The report details the progress made to date on our West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund (WY+TF) scheme programme and introduces governance arrangements for the processing of grants and funding. [20]','West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund Scheme Update (Kirklees Council)','Kirklees Council – Council and democracy','2018-11-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHottqo0xvMGVGcFsuw_ckYhrZheF7QNYeFTiqUB08X8Lcr4ogvGVBr3k0ZxZnJa-jZhCnYMCzK4yVGO4BwGDpn-aFXqh2Ncw95-T9nZPayeDlen-kqyOBI92ae1pCYSlF7hHuovetzKfOZjK5nE2zlP73n2ykz6sl-FKk=','A decision report from Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet notes the progress made on the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund (WY+TF) scheme program and introduces governance arrangements for processing grants and funding. The report emphasizes the focus on delivering several schemes by 2021. [20]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8816d8db-f2ff-4503-aff2-58407212c08c','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'EV Rapid Charging Station, Wakefield. Stanley Road, Wakefield, WF1 4LH. Opening hours. Monday Open 24 hours. About Wakefield Hub. Visit our 120 kW DC Electric Vehicle (EV) Rapid Charging Station in Borehamwood, a short distance from the A61. [Note: Text incorrectly refers to Borehamwood in description, but the address is clearly Wakefield and the context is \'EV Rapid Charging Station, Wakefield\']. EV Charge Station Details. Lcp Stnly Rd 1. Connector: CCS2 Combo. Max Power: 120kW. Connector: CHAdeMO. Max Power: 60kW. Services on site: Tesco Express.','InstaVolt EV Rapid Charging Station, Wakefield (Stanley Road)','InstaVolt','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://instavolt.co.uk/locations/ev-charge-point-wakefield-2/','InstaVolt operates a 120 kW DC Electric Vehicle (EV) Rapid Charging Station at Stanley Road, Wakefield, WF1 4LH. This station offers CCS2 Combo and CHAdeMO connectors, with maximum power outputs of 120kW and 60kW respectively. It supports contactless payment and is open 24 hours, with Tesco Express services on site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8861404b-5f41-4b2c-a1fd-8f2bc05c5e9e','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Todmorden Town Hall, Calderdale Council, £1M Town Deal Funding. ... Published: Wednesday 14 th December 2022. Related project: Public Places in the Heart of Todmorden. Todmorden Town Deal Board is delighted to share the news that in the first phase of government approvals, five of the key projects proposed in the Town Investment Plan have received the go ahead for investment from the Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities.','Investment Secured for First Phase of Todmorden Town Deal Projects','Todmorden Town Deal Board / Calderdale Council','2022-12-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG-j_k-JdHwzQuRZkE-PYVkumdJwrExpW1nvuITzCwy4j2MbNpftisO4GEBHIG2NmUcE4Tvydtxy0MIAeokO-04l6DfNgezCvTtMu0oP5c3hb_S7-QTR9XpckCbsKKQi-YlBqDSd8zveE1KpGfb8H-2klXe_Jj_UNhCUHVG51YImOWXg2UOR2-AuZNEGQxFuYwXEaQI3NVnlyTGrU44RDuORIgXk8nB47Tj','Todmorden Town Deal Board announced the approval of £10 million for five key projects, with £1 million specifically allocated to Todmorden Town Hall improvements. This funding, from the UK Government\'s Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities, aims to develop the local economy and enhance the town.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8864232f-1e90-4e85-a300-def6882b4420','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Leonardo and Thoresby student accommodation buildings and St James\'s Hospital are the latest buildings to have started using heat from the scheme.','Hundreds of tower block flats to get cheaper heating as Leeds City Council scheme extended','Yorkshire Evening Post','2023-12-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/council/hundreds-of-tower-block-flats-to-get-cheaper-heating-as-leeds-city-council-scheme-extended-4444317','The Yorkshire Evening Post reported on the extension of the Leeds PIPES district heating network, noting that the Leonardo and Thoresby student accommodation buildings, along with St James\'s Hospital, were among the latest to have started using heat from the scheme. This expansion aimed to provide more affordable and low-carbon heating across the city.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('88acf116-ec83-408e-86c2-5d73d828b2c4','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Proposals to reduce traffic and build a safe and healthy environment for people of all ages to walk, cycle, rest and play in the streets around Ling Bob and Christ Church Schools. Funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Active Travel England. Current status: Concept In Progress. Development Pending. Construction Pending. Evaluation Pending. Plans include Junctions and road layouts, Improvements to snickets, Green space. The page lists a date \'April 2024\' within its timeline/plans section.','Pellon routes to school','Calderdale Next Chapter','2024-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGqBSkwHdTakaKDPdwEsVbKT9zilNYuLDbem146P9y96-n2aNX2pHpCFm24xOHTd8nPOq6GbvTX32pJ_stv5ZoGftT_hfbuS8jPM3j3xca4juM1lMiLaXl7LB-_JYuIqEuLyr0wRwb64YvF5d3_-Q==','Calderdale Council\'s \'Pellon routes to school\' project outlines proposals for improving streets around Ling Bob and Christ Church Schools in Halifax for safer walking, cycling, and other active travel. Funded by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Active Travel England, the project includes junctions and road layout changes, improved snickets, and new green spaces, with various stages of development from concept to pending construction. The page mentions \'April 2024\' as a date in the \'Plans\' section, indicating planning or initial development activities around this time.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('88baf04b-58ab-439d-8cd1-46705c38f8cd','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-05-19) Roadworks are planned on the A629 Salterhebble Bypass in Halifax, due to start on 2nd June 2025 for 16 weeks, finishing at the end of September 2025. ... Heffernan Utilities will be undertaking works to lay essential cabling along Salterhebble, Dudwell Lane and Godfrey Road to the current A&E entrance at CRH. This will support the construction of the new Multi-Storey Car Park and Clinical Building at CRH.','Planned works on the A629, Salterhebble Bypass starting Monday, 2nd June for 16 weeks','Calderdale and Huddersfield NHS Foundation Trust','2025-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEZzJeEzcof1JW1JKtXmrh8IK8Y0f5EE9mJf-uDx29KxoQor34XuFD8plS0AcU04J59Flb0uFa2mLV7Ufr27R1NXXvFoNhJdPYLFfraCbq8zxGa7KKcKyzIoWplIUmRakT8kIXNr2n88dfVkVVbQ5UZZlJXNLiRRMiSSxzU6RILi572li2I9ATiU0tdKswz1jqlnJxZTcRt_OuZfshiDaE3dsAxGCu3uUAPOO4ag38EswEhuZcRThgdM0kjiswbWOuf6WyJzvZ7zCazpfcHqpnuvo5dUMLcJvjqJLhpN7OAVARbv4vn4Zg==','This announcement details planned roadworks on the A629 Salterhebble Bypass, scheduled from June 2nd to the end of September 2025. Heffernan Utilities will lay essential cabling to support the construction of a new multi-storey car park and clinical building at Calderdale Royal Hospital, indicating ongoing infrastructure development in the Salterhebble area, though not directly part of the A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill Corridor Improvement (Phase 1a) itself.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('88c22efa-3831-414b-b15f-1c86ea58e16a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Earlier this year (January 2024) we introduced the idea of a shared transport hub in Otley. ... Taking your feedback into account, we\'ve now developed a proposal for facilities on Nelson Street. ... This proposal is part of a wider pilot scheme to explore the benefits of Shared Transport Hubs across West Yorkshire. This consultation runs from 20 August until 22 September 2024. ... Under the latest plans, the transport hub would be located on Nelson Street, opposite the bus station, with facilities for secure cycle parking, access to shared e-bikes and a bike repair stand. Real-time public transport information screens and extra signage for directions are also included.','Otley Shared Transport Hub | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice)','2024-08-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFlJZiGqQBN7e4lqqS-Z_Rp9d3msVBAYKz_Jr3Y8GKYMmEZ5DYqjsGeWTsuItJ6woU2-HEpgWmx_dvFeQx3OJnBEJW8nP6ZBQOiTNkC3XPj4Hcc896OE5dhGJQwk0iPJ57CNEAKa_trhhwLnwbs','Following an initial consultation earlier in the year, an updated proposal for the Otley Shared Transport Hub on Nelson Street was put forward for public consultation. This new plan, developed by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, Leeds City Council, and Otley Town Council, includes facilities such as secure cycle parking, access to shared e-bikes, a bike repair stand, and real-time public transport information screens. The consultation for these refined plans ran from August 20 to September 22, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('892ed6d5-592e-44dd-9c0f-f7d16d193ad6','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A contract notice was published on August 30, 2023, by Kirklees Council for \'UKSPF Digital Hubs (the \'Services\')\'. This procurement aimed to find up to six suitable delivery partners from the VCSE sector to operate digital hubs, with contracts valued at £134,640 and running from October 2023 to March 2025.','GOV.UK Contracts Finder: UKSPF Digital Hubs in Kirklees Services Procurement','GOV.UK Contracts Finder','2023-08-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/notice/a60e9d6d-29c4-44b4-a212-085e5461c6b5','Kirklees Council issued a procurement notice on Contracts Finder to establish a programme of services for UKSPF Digital Hubs. They invited quotations from local voluntary, community, and social enterprise (VCSE) providers to operate as Digital Hubs, with a total value of approximately £134,640 for contracts commencing around October 2023 and ending March 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('894f23af-c5b1-4286-8c1e-1820ef6b8ff2','infrastructure-a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction-improvement-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.993','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This engagement has now closed, thank you for taking part. Your feedback has been analysed, the outcome report can be found here. In 2021 (A639 Park Road, Pontefract - Corridor Improvement Programme) you gave us feedback on options to improve transport provision on the A639 Park Road, Pontefract. We listened to your feedback and are excited to share our updated proposals. These improvements will enhance cycling, walking facilities, upgrade the existing bus network infrastructure, and improve traffic journey times for local trips along the route. Through the funding from the Department for Transport (DfT) this project has been awarded £12.4m for this work. Engagement Starts: 14 November 2024. Engagement closes: 11 December 2024. [5]','A639 Park Road, Pontefract - Improvement Scheme | Your Voice','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/A639parkroad','This West Yorkshire Combined Authority page details updated proposals for the A639 Park Road, Pontefract, following feedback from the 2021 consultation. The project, awarded £12.4m funding from the Department for Transport (DfT), aims to enhance cycling, walking, bus infrastructure, and improve traffic flow. It outlines a public engagement period from November 14 to December 11, 2024, with drop-in events to gather feedback on the finalised plans. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8950cccd-9d76-494c-b9a0-1579ae151f92','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The feedback survey will be open to gather your feedback during the consultation period from 12.00 p.m. on Monday, July 15, until 23.59 p.m. on Monday, September 30, 2024. [16]','West Yorkshire Mass Transit Phase One Public Consultation Concludes','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2024-09-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/masstransitphaseoneconsultation','The public consultation on the Phase One route options for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit System officially closed on September 30, 2024. This marked the end of the period for the public and stakeholders to provide feedback on the proposed tram lines for Leeds and Bradford.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8972fd82-1bd5-403d-8bee-cd1d5cad8886','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, has today launched the second phase of public consultation on more detailed plans for a new high-quality cycleway in the city. The West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension is an ambitious proposal to extend the existing Bradford Leeds Cycle Superhighway to Thornton village by building a new, largely segregated cycle route along Thornton Road. [4]','Bradford Council launches second phase consultation on Thornton Road Cycleway','Bradford & Keighley News','2022-08-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGXclIrsN8TKEnQ91UhcftJCdIrNQVZSVT7yAQ8zsD8wp9JHbAQb3SdUCQa6jV9VyOt0Nvm34LLoSnBbfXG5aIN2h6m6VHaZyYHuQCECz0vJHX7ZGPBR_JNpic24EnWeWnfpYHnt-A6Lr6YjcOBZMCM_668Owmf_mdpLKFAQj2oqrqL15Y-pwAwICOW17uHEuiuIh20aNtnmDKWT39uVZ0-Abl3qFmCZYe6','Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched the second phase of public consultation on more detailed plans for the West Bradford Cycle Superhighway Extension. The proposed route would run along Sunbridge Road and Thornton Road, extending to Thornton village.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('899f957c-c024-4199-ab59-0be7d8654795','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'MORE than 5,000 environmental surveys have been carried out as plans for a new tram line between Bradford and Leeds gather pace. West Yorkshire Combined Authority aims to have “spades in the ground” on the new mass transit system, which will feature numerous stops between the two cities, in 2028. Land access for 869 sites across the Leeds and Bradford lines has been agreed, and over 5,000 surveys covering bats, birds and badgers have been undertaken. [4], [6], [16]','Bradford to Leeds tram line update to be given at meeting','Telegraph and Argus','2025-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24584218.bradford-leeds-tram-line-update-given-meeting/','Over 5,000 environmental surveys, covering bats, birds, and badgers, have been completed as part of the plans for the new tram line between Bradford and Leeds. Land access for 869 sites has been secured, and noise and air quality modelling has begun, with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority aiming for construction to begin in 2028.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('89a17446-db71-443b-906d-9368ef8d9802','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More details of the planned transformation of Bradford Interchange were revealed through new documents submitted by SLC Property on behalf of Bradford Council. A \'screening opinion\' was submitted for the £13.2 million scheme, part of the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund package. The plans include the demolition of the existing Hall Ings NCP car park and the creation of a new Hall Ings entrance. The documents stated that the interchange was of poor-quality design and functionality, lacking a \'gateway\' sense to the city centre and serving as a physical barrier.','New documents reveal more details of £13.2m Interchange redevelopment','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2021-10-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEGzIYxJkhXvqaBE_OwPIZbttVCC3gD5AhQmUIcW0LLE_8odt2KjxtT9N18rOnfxOgrSC55uSaALYwggfK9mk5lm64TVGfMd09ZfLgoHykWlZOJcaHcUPCjTaud7rjU9QvCpnX5oSajoW92Ty321QYYrk128DJWPXMRUw7bRDnNRZE1CKB1rjbPVZ8ZqZNNJ1wz8RwR6vp9SqsbdhxGmnGnVCbSHhG3ESB_1aE5pw==','New documents, submitted by SLC Property on behalf of Bradford Council, provided more details of the £13.2 million scheme. A \'screening opinion\' was submitted, outlining plans for the demolition of the NCP car park and the creation of a new Hall Ings entrance, aiming to address the interchange\'s poor design and lack of \'gateway\' feel. The work is part of the Transforming Cities Fund package.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8a5299a6-b3a0-44e0-8bf8-b22bb0ba978c','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Almondbury site is on a plot of council-owned land and will see 157 homes built by 2030. At Cabinet last November, approval was granted for disposal of the site to a Homes England Registered Provider through a competitive land sale. Such providers exist to provide and manage affordable housing, with a percentage of affordable homes on site to be “significantly above” the Kirklees requirement of 20 percent. Aside from the above developments, a further 253 homes will be contributed by town centre living projects at Huddersfield and Dewsbury...','Kirklees\' biggest housing projects explained as 2k homes to be built by 2030','Yorkshire Live','2024-03-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/local-news/kirklees-biggest-housing-projects-explained-28876483','This article details Kirklees Council\'s major housing projects, confirming that the Almondbury site on council-owned land will see 157 homes built by 2030. The approval for disposal of the site was granted by Cabinet in November 2023 to a Homes England Registered Provider, with a commitment to a \'significantly above\' 20 percent affordable housing. Initial funding of £800k was released for preparatory works.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8a73ec5b-5b98-4a3e-96a1-2d7f9addfc5d','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford\'s new Darley Street Market officially opened on Thursday, 10 July, marking the beginning of a fresh chapter for the city\'s retail scene. ... The new market features a fresh food hall, a lifestyle hall, and a vibrant food court offering international cuisines, including Mexican, Greek, Italian, and Thai. With the closure of both Kirkgate and Oastler markets on 28 June, the sites will be demolished as part of a broader regeneration initiative to develop new homes in the area.','Darley Street Market opens with new offerings and an exciting weekend celebration','Business Link Magazine / Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-07-10 00:00:00.000','https://www.businesslinkmagazine.co.uk/','Bradford\'s new Darley Street Market officially opened on July 10, replacing the long-standing Kirkgate and Oastler markets. The market features a fresh food hall, a lifestyle hall, and a vibrant food court offering a diverse range of international cuisines. Its opening marks a significant step in the city\'s regeneration efforts, with the former market sites slated for demolition to make way for new housing developments.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8a7fc219-55e1-414c-9d6d-46b459cb0f01','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Last year, the network saved 5,945 tonnes of carbon and it has continued to expand this year, with connections completed at Leeds Conservatoire and the former Technology Campus Student Residential development. [9]','Leeds City Council to extend the PIPES heat network','Air Quality News','2024-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://airqualitynews.com/2024/09/24/leeds-city-council-to-extend-the-pipes-heat-network/','This article discusses a £24.5 million grant to Leeds City Council for extending the PIPES network. It confirms that connections have been completed at Leeds Conservatoire and the former Technology Campus Student Residential development, highlighting the ongoing expansion of the network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8a948904-4aa9-477d-acce-03f07869ceae','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The largest slice of the GHNF’s latest investment has been allocated to the Aire Valley Heat and Power Network in Leeds, which will receive £19.5m of commercialisation and construction funding. Led and majority funded by SSE Energy Solutions, the scheme aims to deliver low-carbon heat to a large industrial and commercial area of the city using waste heat from the Skelton Grange Energy Recovery Facility, which is currently under construction.','Further £34m awarded under Green Heat Network Fund (including Aire Valley Heat and Power Network)','Renewable Energy Installer / The Energyst / BusinessGreen News / Triple Point Heat Networks Investment Management','2025-02-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHA9ZRXO4YtgopAq69hj9y7sCX12VLNxP86rx13a7lNQrWfUsyLvsVQekXcKOu6qIGRs7MvkMz6T6f09b9BXEGmkSvMIKwOQcP0WMS3R546GSdeVFzstuNO-HxyHwd_gl6jJgPg6AapKQRY2XOsM67jbSG534utuglIM9C2AQ-sk2qLLSBSqpt1GTuEwqWee-jjUmhQT5vA4ez_rIPz1_pfQ55IA56weRIpCI8u_CQAQoMIKyg=','The Aire Valley Heat and Power Network in Leeds, led by SSE Energy Solutions, was officially awarded £19.5 million in commercialisation and construction funding from the Government\'s Green Heat Network Fund (GHNF). This significant funding aims to further develop the scheme, which will utilise waste heat from the Skelton Grange EfW facility to provide low-carbon heating and electricity to local businesses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8aa35381-889c-4f02-8939-4ae9f7b4922e','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The four latest buildings, including the first private-sector residential developers, which have confirmed their intention to connect to the network within the next 12 months, are: ... Leonardo and Thoresby buildings on Gt George Street, developed by McLaren on behalf of Arrow Leonardo.','Further expansion revealed for city\'s £62m heating network','TheBusinessDesk.com','2023-08-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/further-expansion-revealed-for-citys-ps62m-heating-network','TheBusinessDesk.com reported on the continued expansion of the Leeds PIPES district heating network, confirming that four new buildings, including Leonardo and Thoresby student accommodation, were set to connect within the next 12 months. The article highlighted the network\'s role in providing affordable, low-carbon heat and its government funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8b04953b-eaf7-4d3f-8b32-fcd4088e85f6','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work to begin: January 2022. Huddersfield Southern Corridors – Cost: £13.5m. Aims: to improve four busy routes to the south of Huddersfield town centre: at Lockwood Bar, Longroyd Lane, Folly Hall and Queensgate. Kirklees would pay £3.15m towards the total cost of the project. [10]','£200m to be spent on improving roads across Kirklees','Dewsbury Reporter','2021-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.dewsburyreporter.co.uk/news/transport/ps200m-to-be-spent-on-improving-roads-across-kirklees-3164923 [10]','An article reporting on significant investment in Kirklees roads, including the Huddersfield Southern Corridors project. The scheme was stated to cost £13.5m, with Kirklees Council contributing £3.15m. Works were projected to begin in January 2022 across the four key locations: Lockwood Bar, Longroyd Lane, Folly Hall, and Queensgate.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8b052553-3c59-4b1a-9780-4299fbd855e1','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A detailed planning application for Phase One, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site, has been submitted. ... Later phases of the City Village neighbourhood will include more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site, alongside approximately 400 apartments on the Kirkgate site. [6]','Bradford city centre housing plans submitted for 1000-home mega \'city village\' / Plans submitted for Bradford City Village','Yorkshire Live / ECF - the English Cities Fund / Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEXx0EMxAaPul_v2rTjBwQWD-i4QvnlBdMyKgbOIDKj1OszA-L__rND53g1UtMqMnIBg4f0nfx5M2Y0PP4qu5PLuozL0vDAdqD5knog_okLbj4pSg-7k_IlebY5ZzPUPnhuUtUTeZntpH1AaMO1V9e4GILXYI49HI1HVyC3U3alONuhVQLH6z1PP6EszpxAtQIFVIu9Q, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEmC_ORZC80BnQMcUFIWYURYJtGW6WfVRinbFvXjTnLBUyU1gVh2TKrNPkEWABWO3xb_GcQSxUE3RHrE-SEAYij9-fttf2hiXTKV6cMdDsInDijZg6QKIUhr8K3Yn4dxQO32pS_Hcg7hPn7_K2ucgRJVcRrtZVzlbMFXM8PZm_KMZ-b_wHxXHeGdQFRGVQ, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHjXtasWKm0qf76PXxjrqOZZue6zQFQ-nE6he2ss5sUkEdtgFomStmYjUD8qBRfOZY62PhGn8a2i8uOa7JnvKbb8ENggRlqKt70LCbePL_4bBH8CnBfUWy8Z4AZmPXaT3HGRMqgo8QA6VPyqW2fh92razPesf_bdTga70TN_Td5D4SFTMUEgXGogs1Yo52ZeNhCGaboGYJdb0-DKGai309m','A hybrid planning application was officially submitted to Bradford Council for the City Village project. This includes detailed plans for Phase 1 (97 townhouses on Chain Street and northern Oastler site) and outline plans for the remaining phases, which encompass around 903 additional homes, including over 300 apartments on the southern Oastler site and approximately 400 on the Kirkgate site. [5, 6, 16]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8b2762f7-b88c-4e16-b522-b516f9129ee0','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Initial information on options for improved road access to Leeds Bradford Airport has been released today. The information issued by Leeds City Council outlines three options to improve access to the airport, which has been identified as a key transport need to boost the future Leeds economy, as well as tackling existing congestion issues in the local road network. Of the three proposed options, two would see the creation of a new link road while the third consists of widening existing roads and upgrading junctions. The scheme to improve road access to the airport is to be funded through the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund with Leeds City Council leading on its planning and delivery. [3, 18]','Information released on Leeds Bradford Airport road access options','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2015-09-29 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/information-released-on-leeds-bradford-airport-road-access-options','Leeds City Council released initial details on three options to improve road access to Leeds Bradford Airport. Two options proposed new link roads from the A65, running either east or south-west of the airport before joining the A658. The third option involved upgrading existing A65 and A658 junctions and local road widening around Rawdon and Yeadon. These proposals were ahead of a full public consultation.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8b35c90e-4dda-477c-b90a-2384081fa5ad','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The second phase will include a higher density of homes - more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site, currently occupied by Oastler Market, and about 400 apartments on the Kirkgate Shopping Centre site. [14]','Model of planned City Village on show in shopping centre','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-05-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHKKi_Fg3KodyLejoJWCINen7oFcbFvFChnrBvR7SvqKgboBbyRof65jlYW2o0FP4BsILNp-6JGmb3O1BHalPxxZWIPXN79aGQYfjM-S1IeWaUf7SzqFAB-CsmFKOxd0VxJw58AkOUSS_f7XzBu6QY6OntFPhlirO30VWF7pAZMqOubwUFXITt_QOWMOOSIuFa8_fDHpuKG7UZMiCbvcIK0','A 3D model of the proposed City Village was put on public display in the former Samsung unit at Kirkgate Shopping Centre as part of an ongoing public consultation. This allowed the public to visualize the detailed plans for Phase 1 and the broader vision, which includes over 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site. [14]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8b471114-097d-46ae-b76d-ce223219105f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'TRAMS are the most likely form of transport that will be used in a planned mass transit system linking Bradford to Leeds. The long-planned public transport system will link all the major destinations in West Yorkshire – with a Bradford to Leeds line being among the first phase of the work. A new report into the plans has now been published and reveals that the first two lines being built will be the Bradford Line and the Leeds Line. This phase of the work is expected to cost around £2 billion, and work is due to start in 2028. [26], The Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin, has announced plans for a tram system between Leeds and Bradford which will revolutionise the region\'s transport network. [11] The Bradford Line would run from Leeds city centre to Bradford city centre and would also link Bradford Forster Square station with the new Bradford rail station, in line with plans to regenerate the city\'s southern gateway. [11] The submission of the Combined Authority\'s “strategic outline case” document to the Department for Transport is set to be approved by members of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on March 14. [31]','Plans for West Yorkshire tram system in Bradford and Leeds announced','Rail Technology Magazine','2024-03-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/news/plans-west-yorkshire-tram-system-bradford-leeds','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin announced initial plans for a tram system between Leeds and Bradford as Phase 1 of the Mass Transit system. The Bradford Line would connect Leeds city centre to Bradford city centre, linking Bradford Forster Square station with a proposed new Bradford rail station. The strategic outline case was expected to be approved by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on March 14, 2024, with construction hoped to begin in 2028.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8b8255b0-5e4d-442a-91cf-87ffff4ed200','infrastructure-zapmap-ring-road-middleton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.435','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy sets out how the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, and the region\'s five councils, will collaborate in an effort to ensure there are enough places to charge cars and vans in public where people need them. The strategy, which was agreed by members of the Combined Authority\'s transport committee on Wednesday, April 16, outlines investment priorities, design guidance, and an action plan.','West Yorks Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy agreed by Transport Committee','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-04-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHENQwOZQMvuoi40jop70pzlW60Euun7w4HLZyYBFrARQE_VZ8xVTQX7Oiwcb4a-jitmuGt0deLhbfonA5gx_W1J7Pg18Is4XUV0dwQzzcdTtV2gRvojVcXaj4B0gJVH86k7PDoO1oOu8k7vGGDKwi7a4z2RWliWAfDvzOxSYKjs90h7flMNPU7batFEUIyUI4QxfUouR8rKsRsg3dnEu3-D-M8zOKXd6W9DGI=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s transport committee formally agreed upon an Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy on April 16, 2025. This strategy details how WYCA and its five constituent councils will collaborate to ensure an adequate public EV charging network across the region by outlining investment priorities, design guidance, and an action plan.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8be143ad-22b3-42d6-a4fe-a1da5d8e1d36','infrastructure-huddersfield-southern-corridors-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.921','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The construction of Folly Hall and improvements on Queen Street South began in 2021 and were completed in 2023. Works included improvements at the junction to Colne Road and St. Thomas Road, to help reduce peak time traffic and improve journey times. The right turn out of Colne Road was removed, and an alternative route created along Queen Street South. This phase was completed with resurfacing of the highway and footpaths. [11]','Huddersfield Southern Corridors (HSC) - Kirklees Council (Folly Hall and Queen Street South Completion)','Kirklees Council','2023-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/major-transport-schemes/huddersfield-southern-corridors.aspx [11]','Works on the Folly Hall and Queen Street South sections of the Huddersfield Southern Corridors scheme, which began in 2021, were completed in 2023. These improvements focused on the junction with Colne Road and St. Thomas Road, aiming to reduce peak-time traffic and improve journey times.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8bf7cc0a-8801-4164-a2d9-8d8d2248e0ec','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The completion date for Bradford Live was pushed back again, with the venue now expected to open in early 2024. Delays were attributed mainly to the extensive work required for floor installations in the building, as well as previously unforeseen issues like asbestos removal and a fire.','Why Bradford Live completion date has been pushed back again','Telegraph and Argus','2023-03-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHLLvcKtuUwAJNFghRXYnOPx8E6PcsE5WhyCqoDAZnPAevoGRltbnTR6sFm0D8rhc5hHaOrLiEcRVtEBq9-7z4SQ-lAgNFVqnJZokIotsMn5oUW6uS3xXZ_mC87xPsQxRfnhmx0mQ3ZiMQpCfzFw6k3EvaxvN37yEAHH_IBVP2aPycxAJj34-XoBPd2H59M7NPdHMkDjLnXenM=','The completion date for Bradford Live was pushed back again, with the venue now expected to open in early 2024. Delays were attributed mainly to the extensive work required for floor installations in the building, as well as previously unforeseen issues like asbestos removal and a fire.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8c1beaf9-83c5-4e86-b3fd-11c026890fd6','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council\'s response to a major consultation on how buses are run in West Yorkshire will be discussed at its Cabinet meeting on Monday 11 December. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is asking people and organisations across the region to have their say on the proposed reform of bus services. The consultation is open until 7 January 2024, and Calderdale Council is one of the organisations that will formally give its views. ... Cllr Jane Scullion, Leader of Calderdale Council, said: “Good bus travel, that\'s inclusive and accessible, is really important to our communities, especially those in rural or more deprived areas. ... We back the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s proposal to create a better-connected region by bringing buses back under public control, simplifying fares, providing greater certainty over services and customer information, and having greener buses.”','Council has its say on bus services','Calderdale Council','2023-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/news-articles/council-has-its-say-on-bus-services','Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet discussed and prepared its formal response to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s bus reform consultation. The Council expressed support for bringing buses back under public control to improve services for communities, particularly in rural and deprived areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8c7feb98-2899-4656-bf5c-4249bbe08ed5','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As a result of funding through four Registered Providers and an additional £5m investment from the Combined Authority, West Yorkshire social housing tenants will benefit from reduced energy costs through solar PV & battery storage installations, alleviating the impact of fuel bills and reducing carbon emissions. ... Being the largest of the Solar PV and Battery Storage programme\'s workstreams, this project is aimed at delivering up to 1500 solar PV and battery storage installations on social housing properties across the region... The Business Case was approved in early December 2023, with delivery to commence March 2025. ... Project Status, Delivery to commence April 2025.','Solar PV and Battery Storage - West Yorkshire Housing Partnership','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGIJzaoGnz4DajCmd1nOADRvMie_egPmcGD9LBg4X1iCRx5ENBcwJkEovDuo1vjDjPzs7ajDBK0fi9YqbF9aydEGxOz7bQqDJiu_BreNEpx2ng8VsUoDZ9Fx0oWWMIQQSbjq3KLZBcbcVolxHJzsBg1pcDxagIs8c4Q7X9bHyM8c3TcmqfDhsuXEuKd3iJSV32dGyeJ_lG4AhX2SEAQs2fDwnUkwdZzGQAgfYErHT-7dwDoWE2D','The West Yorkshire Housing Partnership, with £5 million investment from the Combined Authority and funding from four Registered Providers (including Wakefield and District Housing), will deliver up to 1500 solar PV and battery storage installations on social housing properties across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield. This project aims to reduce energy costs for tenants, alleviate fuel poverty, and contribute to climate emergency outcomes. The business case was approved in December 2023, with delivery scheduled to commence in April 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8ccb3da7-3cf0-4b11-b845-9baecc5922fa','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'23.5 Degrees Limited (T/A Starbucks) operate the drive thru on Plot 2, and have been trading successfully for over two years. ... Plot 2: Full planning permission was granted for the Starbucks Drive Thru on 16th February 2018. The planning reference number is 17/00893/FUL. Click here to access the Wakefield Council planning portal to view the consents. ... Prominent location at the corner of the Doncaster Road and Wakefield Relief Road to the east of Wakefield town centre.','Planning consent for Starbucks Drive Thru on Plot 2','Howie Property (property brochure)','2018-02-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&rct=j&q=&esrc=s&source=web&cd=&ved=2ahUKEwjG4KjC29eFAxWDgkGBHUuQDTkQFnoECB4QAQ&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.howieproperty.co.uk%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F10%2FHeathlands-at-City-Fields-Wakefield.pdf&usg=AOvVaw2I19m0V78kE7zGf6Vq6UjM&opi=89978449','A property brochure for \'Heathlands at City Fields\' in Wakefield details that full planning permission for the Starbucks Drive Thru on Plot 2, located at the corner of Doncaster Road and Wakefield Relief Road, was granted on February 16, 2018. The planning reference number is 17/00893/FUL. This establishes the initial site development where the EV chargers would later be installed.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8cefd33a-430b-4bf8-94c7-d987ecbf8db6','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Located at the Lookers Nissan dealership in Leeds, this EV charger is situated at 83-85 Kirkstall Road. The charger is accessible to the public, however, a membership is required in order to use it. The charger is equipped with a Type 2 socket, making it compatible with a variety of electric vehicles. It has a charging capacity of 7 kWh, providing a decent charging speed for those in need of a quick top-up.','Wattly Listing and Public Access Details for Lookers Nissan Leeds EV Charger','Wattly Your Local Charging Community','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://wattly.co.uk/chargers/lookers-nissan-leeds/','Wattly, a local charging community platform, lists an EV charger at the Lookers Nissan Leeds dealership on Kirkstall Road. It describes the charger as publicly accessible but requiring membership, equipped with a Type 2 socket and offering a 7 kWh charging capacity, operated by the Nissan UK Dealer Network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8d225311-cde7-4bf7-a2a1-f970fcd9b93b','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Thousands of people across West Yorkshire, as well as leaders in business and education, have come out in support of plans for a region-wide Mass Transit network. It comes as West Yorkshire Combined Authority releases a consultation report showing more than two thirds of people surveyed across the region are supportive of plans to create a tram system initially covering Bradford and Leeds. [19] The consultation feedback will play a key role in shaping the preferred scheme, set to be selected later in 2025, with a further detailed consultation on the chosen route scheduled for early 2026. [17] The route options consultation for Phase One of the project was conducted during the summer and autumn of 2024, with 4,845 individuals and organisations participating. [17]','Thousands Support West Yorkshire Mass Transit Network','Railway-News','2025-03-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.railway-news.com/support-revealed-for-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-tram-network/','A consultation report released by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority showed that thousands of residents, business leaders, and education leaders across West Yorkshire supported the plans for a region-wide Mass Transit network. Over two-thirds of those surveyed backed the plans for a tram system covering Bradford and Leeds, with feedback guiding the selection of a preferred scheme later in 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8d349dc3-091e-4fff-a203-fab7a0e9d9a7','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point is located at 18 New Road, Leeds, LS19 7SE and it has 2 devices. This charging point is part of the Osprey charging network. ... Updated: 27th August 2025.','Zapmap Listing Update for Woolpack Inn Leeds EV Charging Point (Osprey Network)','Zapmap','2025-08-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQENAsyHsnY5le_bt6BVsgYvozf2RwzzOf1ZcmBQ3wlvXodSa-kg1Z63wlTbgQf1Eotn2LLIGCL9bYebt3H7aenCjzO39m1NUOB1ozI4wfIAV2WaWAG25qBi_tDCttZHS10lwLca0XFTZMMtK8qT','The Zapmap listing for the electric car charging point at Woolpack Inn Leeds (18 New Road, LS19 7SE), part of the Osprey charging network with 2 devices, was last updated on this date.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8d3932b5-87c9-4d12-81f3-c475307e78e4','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council are set to unveil £12m plans to improve travel along the A639 Park Road in Pontefract for all road users. [9]','Wakefield Council unveils £12m plans for A639 Park Road improvements','Wakefield Council','2024-11-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/news/news-archive/2024/plans-unveiled-to-improve-park-road-in-pontefract','Wakefield Council officially announced its £12 million plans for A639 Park Road in Pontefract, detailing improvements to enhance journey times, reduce bus delays, and create facilities for walking and cycling. The announcement highlighted the integration of feedback from a previous consultation and invited further public comments through drop-in sessions and an online survey running until December 11, 2024. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is funding the work.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8d7003d8-958d-40c0-b022-a4eba47379a7','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council and its community partner, Sowerby Bridge Fire & Water, are delighted to reveal they have been awarded a £90,000 grant from Historic England as part of the Sowerby Bridge High Streets Heritage Action Zone (HSHAZ) to create and deliver community-led cultural activities on the high street over the next three years. ... Nearly £2 million was secured in 2020 from the Government\'s HSHAZ programme, to help create more things to attract people to Sowerby Bridge during the day and improve pedestrian areas to make the high street a more pleasant place to spend time. This will include repairing and refurbishing a number of historic buildings in the town and revitalising the marketplace as a multi-purpose space for a variety of activities and events.','Sowerby Bridge high street awarded £90000 for cultural programme','Halifax Central Initiative','2021-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH7eiIV0YiP8NthkM9aP6Y_35f1cHzsPNjJ1veGp2UxDSMm8Jvu2LDzbTIbPshS59sLWilFO34iy3JBau0QlUaYpaUrf5GegjNTlal_jIoUDj481uxacZnD_0mB0lkikSi8f0OOpqDw88zDFEzbA0Av4v2ZqHQ-tyG83RlgLUxxt-OaiFrycDQzto-stkD5FbP3-4M9Riwr2nMCj99Vf-E=','Calderdale Council and Sowerby Bridge Fire & Water received a £90,000 grant from Historic England as part of the Sowerby Bridge High Streets Heritage Action Zone (HSHAZ) cultural programme. This funding, part of a broader £2 million secured in 2020 through HSHAZ, aims to support community-led cultural activities, local artists, and revitalize the marketplace.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8d779212-0fc9-4775-b778-4aa052e4db94','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work started at the Vale Centre site, Stubbing Holme Road in April this year to repair the dilapidated wall, relocate the flood warning siren (which is now fully operational) and facilitate installation of the canal overflow. The Stubbing Holme Road FAS will consist of:- • Raising and strengthening river walls along Stubbing Holme Road. • Strengthening walls along Rochdale canal to pass flows to the Hebden Bridge FAS canal overflow at the Vale Centre site. • A flow diversion solution at Longstaff Court to return water to the river. • Improving protection to riverside properties. Construction work is currently programmed to commence in 2022.','Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme Newsletter (referencing Stubbing Holme Road FAS)','AWS (Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme Newsletter)','2021-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://environment-agency.s3.eu-west-2.amazonaws.com/HB_FAS_Newsletter_02_15_11_21.pdf','A newsletter from the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme mentioned \'early works\' starting at the Vale Centre site, Stubbing Holme Road in April 2021, to repair a dilapidated wall and relocate a flood warning siren. This was in preparation for the main flood alleviation scheme and specifically referenced the Stubbing Holme Road FAS.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('8da02808-d8d2-44c4-bfab-2e3f61de3d2d','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to speed up the delivery of new electric vehicle chargepoints across West Yorkshire have been agreed by the region\'s leaders. The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy sets out how West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the region\'s five councils will work together to ensure there are enough places to charge cars and vans in public where people need them. The strategy outlines investment priorities, design guidance and an action plan, and was agreed by members of the CA\'s transport committee on Wednesday 16th April. As of January 2025, there were 1,345 publicly accessible chargepoints in West Yorkshire, with the majority of these in built up and urban areas. Modelling suggests that the region will require between 15,180 and 17,080 EV chargers by 2030.','More electric vehicle chargepoints planned for West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority News','2025-05-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news/more-electric-vehicle-chargepoints-planned-for-west-yorkshire/','West Yorkshire leaders approved the Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy, setting out a collaborative plan between the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the region\'s five councils to accelerate the delivery of new public EV chargepoints. The strategy, agreed on April 16, 2025, addresses investment priorities, design guidance, and an action plan to meet the projected need for 15,180 to 17,080 chargers by 2030.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
