	('93c90b58-2fd0-4ebc-ab37-9e877896d8dc','infrastructure-bus-lane-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.094','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Automatic number plate recognition cameras will soon be in use to catch \'cheeky blighters\' gaining ground by using bus lanes in Calderdale when they aren\'t supposed to. ... The committee were told in an officers\' report that a three-camera trial scheme would cost around £115,000. Ultimately a capital cost of around £295,000 would be required with another estimated £140,000 needed annually for running costs for a full eight-camera scheme. ... At present Calderdale has six lengths of bus lane. They are at the A629 Skircoat Road (Free School Lane to Caygill Terrace), Halifax, ... A629 Huddersfield Road (Spring Hall to Stafford Square), Halifax, ... A629 at Ainley Top (Huddersfield Road to Ainley Top roundabout), ... A646 Burnley Road (Trimmingham Lane to Warley Road), Halifax, ... A646 King Cross slip road into the King Cross district centre, Halifax, ... and Wade Street, Halifax.','\'Cheeky blighters\' to be slapped with fines for using Calderdale\'s bus lanes','Halifax Courier','2018-08-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/cheeky-blighters-be-slapped-fines-using-calderdale-bus-lanes-1-9273760','Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet backed proposals for the introduction of automatic number plate recognition (ANPR) cameras to enforce bus lanes and access restrictions in Halifax. The proposal included a three-camera trial scheme costing around £115,000, with a full eight-camera scheme estimated at £295,000 capital cost and £140,000 annually for running costs. Specific bus lanes identified for enforcement included A629 Skircoat Road, A629 Huddersfield Road, A629 Ainley Top, A646 Burnley Road, A646 King Cross slip road, and Wade Street.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('948cd168-0bbf-4127-b030-adb79d3036f9','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Stubbing Holme Road Flood Alleviation Scheme will improve protection for approximately 56 properties and will consist of increasing flood protection from River Calder and Rochdale Canal. The planning application is currently expected to be submitted later in 2023.','Flood information centre opens in Hebden Bridge','GOV.UK','2023-08-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/flood-information-centre-opens-in-hebden-bridge','The Environment Agency opened a new Flood Information Centre in Hebden Bridge. The announcement stated that the Stubbing Holme Road Flood Alleviation Scheme would improve protection for approximately 56 properties and was expected to have its planning application submitted later in 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('948fe03a-a44b-42aa-8c34-a54b33f29dba','infrastructure-a629-halifax-to-huddersfield-corridor-improvement-phase-4-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.884','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This public consultation report has been prepared by Mott MacDonald on behalf of Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council (CMBC) and Kirklees Metropolitan Borough Council (KMBC) for the proposed A629 Phase 4 Scheme (the Scheme) public consultation. This report has been prepared to provide an account of the non-statutory public consultation, which was undertaken from 26 October to 23 November 2021, provided an opportunity for stakeholders, members of the general public and interested parties to provide feedback on the proposed Scheme.','A629 Phase 4 Public Consultation Report - Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice)','2022-02-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHA5NXb8wH-htdRZrVM6eBa8pMmb-0qbK-vj--lDoOIdpmCOfh4BgYX7jFLcmzGLmrdIejBv3gqJMHLJ-B1EY21l9jfeFdYBMenVrw09C9kyGxQWEMbh1YrlaDQbeJXwL4dW1dUEilA_71cGh4guYLoGrsWCTO7McYKvCHi7fRIYhkJ8pwMmaRI','Prepared by Mott MacDonald for Calderdale and Kirklees Councils, this report details the non-statutory public consultation for the A629 Phase 4 Scheme. The consultation ran from October 26 to November 23, 2021, providing stakeholders and the public an opportunity to provide feedback on the proposed improvements for walking, wheeling, cycling, and bus travel along the route.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('95004742-b75c-4b7a-86dd-b9756a8a5401','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of its Bradford Showcase event, which is running alongside this year\'s UKREiiF, Bradford Council confirmed that consultancy Arup has been commissioned to create the masterplan for the future of Southern Gateway. The Southern Gateway has been earmarked as one of the biggest regeneration sites in the UK, powered by £4.5bn in transport upgrades, including Mass Transit and a new Bradford railway station.','Arup Appointed to Develop Bradford Southern Gateway Masterplan','TheBusinessDesk.com','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEjJ1HgWO3HSYFUw0bXVekgX4pRYrJ72-MNGxADk5KQzPSjsvyPH-KDbB98teSZciaiq-gj34LiZmjZKsmhE84RBtRDg_aEcKu4Z-GVzQyYoQFN1cJpNbqCLzNv3Fr50EubKFLVwRXSnSTG3nEgYdG7IlG4Jp8g8wtg_Ym-FnZ0N3TCkkI3zl2UiSDyvQwjbGizEbZoAWOsGgEihBAW5PuSswPcMMwh7gR8e4_UQaV6OOs=','Bradford Council officially confirmed the appointment of global consultancy Arup to create the comprehensive masterplan for the Southern Gateway project. This initiative, valued at £4.5 billion for transport upgrades, aims to significantly expand and regenerate the city centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9515f081-c40c-4d17-96c1-cb7bc556db9e','infrastructure-a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction-improvement-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.993','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A survey to gauge the public\'s reaction to proposed improvements to the A639 Park Road, Pontefract will close on August 4. Issues identified include poor walking and cycling facilities, traffic congestion with queues and delays at junctions especially during evening peak times and weekend events. [9]','Last chance to have your say on improvements to Park Road, Pontefract','Wakefield Express','2021-08-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/transport/last-chance-to-have-your-say-on-improvements-to-park-road-pontefract-3331773','A news article from Wakefield Express urging the public to participate in the consultation for the A639 Park Road improvements, which was set to close on August 4, 2021. The article highlights identified issues such as poor walking and cycling facilities and traffic congestion. [9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9523ed2a-3bc0-4709-a353-ba32f1840c9f','infrastructure-toby-carvery-leeds-aberford-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.388','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We are also supporting work by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to develop a regional strategy for increasing the number of public chargers. These are usually installed by commercial partners in locations where people already park such as supermarkets, car parks, leisure and retail settings, or in residential areas such as local car parks. Find out more about our approach, read the Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030 (PDF, 507KB).','Electric vehicle charging in Leeds | Leeds.gov.uk','Leeds City Council','2022-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/sustainable-travel/electric-vehicle-charging','Leeds City Council outlines its approach to electric vehicle charging infrastructure, including supporting commercial partners for public chargers and its own \'Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030\'. This strategy underpins the development of EV charging points in the city, aligning with the installation at Toby Carvery Oulton.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('953aa9b8-f896-40ca-8622-c0c950e9da73','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-places-scheme-cornholme-a646-active-travel',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.168','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Published: Thursday 20 th March 2025. A multi-million-pound project to improve walking, wheeling and cycling facilities in West Yorkshire is taking a major step forward. The new £5.1 million West Yorkshire Places scheme includes proposals such as new street crossings and lighting, improved green spaces and traffic calming measures. People are now being asked for their views on the West Yorkshire Combined Authority initiative, which will help encourage more people to choose active travel and make local neighbourhoods safer and more attractive across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees and Wakefield. Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin said: “Everybody in West Yorkshire deserves to have access to low-cost, sustainable travel options. “Through initiatives like this we are making it easier and safer to walk, wheel and cycle, which help improve the health and wellbeing of our communities. “This will play a key part as we build a modern, integrated transport network and a better-connected region, so your feedback is invaluable.” The Combined Authority is working in partnership with Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees and Wakefield councils to deliver the scheme. A similar project called \'Healthier Streets\', which is also funded by the Combined Authority, is already underway in Leeds. ... In Cornholme, proposals include new footway links along the A646, new pedestrian crossings, and a one-way system on Greenfield Terrace. Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet Member for Regeneration and Transport, Cllr Sarah Courtney, said: “We want to make it easier for people to choose active travel methods, like walking, wheeling or cycling, for everyday journeys. The proposals for Cornholme will make it easier and safer for people crossing the busy A646 road, improving connections within the village centre and supporting access to the local junior and infant school.”','Cornholme features in proposals to improve active travel across West Yorkshire','Local news outlet/West Yorkshire Combined Authority press release','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFooi0D-Ddn6P0k3PrkBakxF7xlf4lY1v-Hg6BAyqX-b7wvDvxHIr6riLPHw_IqCSxsm_xaNWnOt6bqKzPqNGBgtIYUdsd69s-g-UVV0J0ZJiD_KOhKOSb6ObsK7FHqMjz5ll54OKWrJe4OQhCtWG60EGAh-kUw2Tc_ab-Yb7f-ON16DE0Fv9Wpe7XOcOvWDIyW_0p4i6eWG-JqWaXFL19FjGjNBFTfm0TIqHSc47apYA==','This news article announces a major step forward for the multi-million-pound West Yorkshire Places scheme, which includes proposals for active travel improvements in Cornholme. These include new footway links along the A646, new pedestrian crossings, and a one-way system on Greenfield Terrace. The scheme is a West Yorkshire Combined Authority initiative in partnership with local councils.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('963e39ef-5126-49c5-b1b8-c44fe64692b0','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first major piece of news from today\'s announcement is that we now know West Yorkshire will be served by a tram, with our potential options discarded. The first two sections to be built will connect Leeds city centre to Bradford and to the White Rose centre south of the city, with both lines going onto St James\' Hospital to the north. The mayor later said the first two lines had an estimated cost of £2.5 billion, with £200m already provided by the last government. Work is less advanced on connecting other parts of West Yorkshire - Kirklees, Calderdale and Wakefield - to the network. And Ms Brabin told reporters later that the completion of the whole network would be \"decades away\".','\'Football\'s not coming home but mass transit is\' - what next in major plan','YorkshireLive','2024-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE0MZtsFN0m_ezhj_ZLlydua6gQbj7Sn8298GrhyLlKNUB4ae4nfhkIUun19_dvULjobC4EfAh2hmqvkZyP3eaxxZS2vwQIQfbog1ijW3smALo8JwzD4UUpcjtTJYW9KyuSY7yaOMEUl_PnWsfV1ZOJKJuRvFZjiF02cYtJ1eJz4TkfBSp0MRkZwv-MlJzMjuvNqN9TStafvlXJ','A public consultation on initial route options for the first two tram lines (Leeds city centre to Bradford, and Leeds city centre to White Rose centre/St James\' Hospital) was launched. West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin stated that while these first lines had an estimated cost of £2.5 billion, work on connecting Kirklees, Calderdale, and Wakefield to the network was less advanced and the completion of the entire network would be \'decades away\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9651ed10-f257-4a31-ab52-a01643688fbc','infrastructure-leeds-to-micklefield-rail-upgrades-transpennine-route-upgrade',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.980','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Network Rail has submitted its TWAO to the Secretary of State and anyone can submit their comments or objections to the proposals. Micklefield Parish Council has submitted its comments and objections to the Secretary of State for Transport. Posted: Fri, 25 Aug 2023. The proposals include closing Peckfield level crossing and diverting the route of the bridleway and footpath; closing Highroyds Wood level crossing and diverting the route of the footpath; demolishing the grade II listed railway bridge on Ridge Road and building a new one; and putting a temporary works compound on Phoenix Avenue. [8]','Micklefield Parish Council Submits Objections to TWAO','Micklefield Parish Council','2023-08-25 00:00:00.000','https://micklefield-pc.gov.uk/news/network-rails-transport-and-works-act-order/','Micklefield Parish Council submitted comments and objections to Network Rail\'s Transport and Works Act Order (TWAO) proposals for the Leeds to Micklefield upgrades. The proposals included closing Peckfield and Highroyds Wood level crossings, demolishing and rebuilding Ridge Road bridge, and establishing a temporary works compound on Phoenix Avenue.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9672b55c-5ec9-4701-95fe-6f9774b256da','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A new town square being built where a Calderdale market was demolished is still not ready – but progress is being made. ... Councillor Adam Wilkinson has given an update on the project... In April, Coun Wilkinson said the project should be finished by June. In his update today, he has posted: “Progress continues on the new town square... flagging is now complete, with some snagging across the site; bollard installation along the top elevation is finished; lighting and electrical connections have been successfully commissioned; and the site cabin has now been removed. Cycle racks have been delivered and will be installed once the car park surfacing is complete... On Wharf Street, the road layout will be changed, with Calderdale Council relocating the bus layby, adding disabled parking spaces, adding a new loading bay, adding a parallel crossing for pedestrians and cyclists, widening the footpath, and removing on-street parking.','What is going on at Sowerby Bridge market: Residents \'thanked for their patience\' as work on new Calderdale town square still not complete','Halifax Courier','2025-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGO3G8d3LVaYzmK6hXRsHUTPk7BYjfw4sfyLJWumXAV30giacp-YqHLuErPF_x04P3iu1gMahQrVqlMMZ_dr4bvWZ_R6lBt11Tsb9NTCy_YEiuu_J_m-JuSVA4OF43xc_TLgAlsQ5ou868OOAZjwz8TtfoxF7JITLXCEsJwibD_8SGQgDcUld8QOYEHm3t1ve8LXQL5i2-sKVKuyk9L38So9ywtXlI_V6W6SrTo6Rtw0QH19KjijjKOH-KNKP6UNor_jUpa0DDX_ZztkkE-tQ7VOyhXipGN60kccVacX9EqealfPRwZ3ITojJWS_n76Jh9h5w8J2Xvikr5LvfA=','In mid-July 2025, the new Sowerby Bridge town square remained incomplete despite an earlier June target. Councillor Adam Wilkinson provided an update indicating progress with flagging, bollard installation, and lighting, while car park resurfacing was pending. Significant road layout changes on Wharf Street, including a relocated bus layby, new disabled parking, loading bay, parallel crossing, and widened footpath, were still underway due to ongoing logistical and material challenges.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('96c72755-bd84-46ef-a872-fa9b459f2d6f','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The history of Todmorden Town Hall has been brought to life in a new guidebook featuring the many stories that the building holds. ... The guidebook has been funded by the Heritage Lottery Fund as part of the Todmorden Town Hall: Telling the Story project...','A guided history of Todmorden Town Hall','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2016-11-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFZYtQHemjzeF88RIiH4eL6G0yY2Afx2zD7jVDeFtVPQmu4vsvWDTBPW6cSKGgen-P59tdivqmEkMJlz4eggAfPirKMqzpMsUhUd50FkdHuAOqAA2Wp7G8T8u1c10K7DxV9br_n3J7TBCy6UvPmoaSR2RytRMGrxQ2PBxrtm3ODFp0','This news article from Calderdale Council announces the launch of a new guidebook detailing the history of Todmorden Town Hall. The guidebook was funded by the Heritage Lottery Fund as part of the \'Todmorden Town Hall: Telling the Story\' project, highlighting earlier heritage-focused activities and funding for the building.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('96ceb397-2ae1-464d-8429-ddbab2d52f5c','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Detailed proposals for Aire Park, a landmark for Leeds, and the largest new city centre green space in the UK, have been officially approved by Leeds City Council\'s plans panel today. Developer Vastint UK put forward the plans as part of its major redevelopment for the former Tetley Brewery site with public space at its heart. [...] The news follows the announcement that £8.6 million from the governments Getting Building Fund will be committed to deliver additional park space and infrastructure around the development as part of West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s mission to boost economic growth and aid the recovery from the Covid-19 pandemic. [13]','Detailed Proposals for Aire Park Approved; £8.6 Million Government Funding Secured','Leeds City Council News / Yorkshire Evening Post','2020-09-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEZ-NvpDctkBubCt2yWxxSNf-ylEhuj0rEzf8hoRm6alKK-AQehB1b7nLSU8k7sHLBVNeKsb72LfoEOfzw6M40yZAmuK2qomIYQdrv0z7fzPS6jAa5qvdauYzuy32noBDGHQhnWRzzuuf9s9lfricWaPFuA3dIe0ckEiI9gP_wSmcV6hKFWprK5IleFmrMCocOdL5ovXvsU4YGlJNajaj0TAbjiv17C [13]','Detailed proposals for Aire Park were officially approved by Leeds City Council\'s plans panel. Concurrently, an £8.6 million grant from the government\'s Getting Building Fund was committed by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to deliver additional park space and infrastructure, boosting economic recovery and regeneration in the South Bank area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('96f7681a-3038-4a70-a984-6369336ae2f4','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'MORE areas in Bradford city centre have reopened following the completion of paving works. [15] This week, a large area of paving has been laid on Broadway, between Landmark House and Britannia House between the new planter structures. This area will soon be open to pedestrians once works on the planters allow the space to do so. [15] Further progress has been made at the southern end of Market Street, where new paving is being completed in the pedestrian areas on the east side, around the ground level planter areas. [15] A period of overnight works started on Monday, September 2 on the inbound section of Leeds Road, near the Broadway Shopping Centre. This work will facilitate the realignment of a kerb line to widen areas for the new cycleway. [15]','More areas in Bradford city centre reopen as works continue','Telegraph and Argus','2024-09-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24571932.areas-bradford-city-centre-reopen-works-continue/','In September 2024, more areas in Bradford city centre reopened to pedestrians following the completion of paving works. Significant progress was reported on Broadway, with a large area of paving laid and new planter structures. Further paving was completed on the east side of Market Street around ground-level planter areas. The Future Bradford newsletter also detailed ongoing overnight works on Leeds Road to realign a kerb line for a new cycleway.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('97565128-84ce-428c-9c79-c8c77b109910','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3 of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme was launched by Salix on behalf of the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero in 2021. The Phase 3a application window opened on 6 October 2021 and closed on 3 November 2021, providing £553m in government grants for 217 clean heat and energy efficiency projects.','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme launched and application window closed','Salix Finance','2021-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.salixfinance.co.uk/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme','Salix Finance announced the launch of Phase 3 of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme in 2021, with the Phase 3a application window opening on 2021-10-06 and closing on 2021-11-03. This phase provided £553m in government grants for clean heat and energy efficiency projects across the public sector, including hospitals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9757b454-c96a-4d48-a537-947740768ee2','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'PRIME Minister Keir Starmer has re-committed £30m worth of Government support to a project intended to transform parts of Bradford city centre. Last year, it was announced that the City Village scheme would get around £30m funding from Homes England. [22]','PM re-affirms £30m of Government support for City Village','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-02-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF7F9neU_WJYczfbzomE213n6ks9NRgKen5DYgtpW7N_fPSJhBWdIDDdOfPsGOmwFSveZTJbfy-ll6EqL8XagDRYe-l_ct90FKW2iHsehcQ3enZ0Gu4oNS6OqSgZSt1f9U6l_N51_bY1J0TUlfkuHyh3h6bSIDngN_3ByfDQE-sMvcJNquzaTSSmVCbQrSLp6bMGjx5uji_jdiUXMJ-LmzBG7c=','Prime Minister Keir Starmer re-affirmed £30 million of government support from Homes England for the Bradford City Village project. This funding is aimed at regenerating brownfield land to create around 1,000 homes, including on the Oastler Market and Kirkgate Shopping Centre sites. [22]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('977783bc-2e9d-4e26-8de9-8f575047bae0','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Completed. ... June 2024. ... Additionally, the building is seamlessly integrated into the district heating system, tapping into Leeds City\'s low-carbon resources for heating and hot water generation.','Leonardo & Thoresby Student Accommodation, Leeds - Completed','Robertson Group','2024-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.robertson.co.uk/projects/leonardo-thoresby-student-accommodation-leeds','Robertson Group, involved in the construction of Leonardo & Thoresby Student Accommodation in Leeds, announced the project\'s completion in June 2024. The development, comprising 476 student bedrooms, notably integrated a \'fabric first\' strategy and was seamlessly connected to the Leeds City district heating system for low-carbon heating and hot water.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('97d1771f-0e68-464d-99a4-0c5a5a49e31e','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin has unveiled detailed route options for the region\'s future mass transit tram network. The public is now invited to provide opinions on the proposed routes for the first phase of the project, which will connect Central and South Leeds and Bradford and Leeds. ... The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is running a public consultation on the proposed routes, which will continue until 30 September. [23] This video provides an overview of our plans of the phase one West Yorkshire Mass Transit route options consultation. ... the consultation is now open it will close on Monday 30th of September 2024 at 1 minute to midnight. [24]','Public Consultation Launched for West Yorkshire Mass Transit Phase One Route Options','Railway-News / West Yorkshire Combined Authority - YouTube','2024-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.railway-news.com/west-yorkshire-proposes-route-options-for-mass-transit-network/ ; https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X6u_2y_oI28','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched an 11-week public consultation on the proposed route options for Phase One of the Mass Transit system. This phase focuses on tram lines connecting central and south Leeds, and Bradford city centre to Leeds city centre. The public was invited to provide feedback on 10 route options.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('98209285-fd21-4e62-b6f2-6c198a31f4c2','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As landlines in Kirklees make the switchover to digital as part of a UK government wide initiative, the BT Digital Voice team, will be making a truck stop in Kirklees to answer any questions you may have about the industry-wide changes. ... Visit the BT Truck at the Co-op Crown Bottom Car Park in Holmfirth on Thursday 6 March from 10am – 4pm or drop into Dewsbury Library on Railway Street on Wednesday 26 March from 10am – 2pm. [6]','The digital home phone switchover - Kirklees Together','Kirklees Together','2025-03-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFuVRZZTCstMkDvW6YMrTgx7Nj3YZtnX3ZkhgbBhCu42hM58Rb4InCoozv1742Hl7djcg1iqUYQUM4zo2SeMLDIqR9dqnOTuMmBAqFSTCZht47vBXIEg_uDg8-MJJh4h7K8bae2dUBiQftl1_PKNpTuRvMfXUXsadlvtf954NrCTp9-1LNXbjo=','Kirklees Council provided an update on the digital home phone switchover, noting that BT\'s Digital Voice team would be making truck stops in Holmfirth and Dewsbury in March 2025 to assist residents with the industry-wide changes. The article confirms the national switchover to VoIP technology is set to be completed by January 2027.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('983077f9-a973-4091-8fb1-f14bd3cb45da','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Charging station with fast-chargers for electric vehicles (EV). 2 outlets, max capacity: 50 kW. Network: E.ON ... Lookers Nissan Leeds - E.ON. 83-85 Kirkstall Road, Leeds. LS3 1HS, Leeds, United Kingdom.','E.ON Rapid EV Charging Facilities at Lookers Nissan Leeds','ChargeFinder (E.ON)','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.chargefinder.com/charge-point/lookers-nissan-leeds-e-on-59439','The Lookers Nissan Leeds dealership also hosts E.ON rapid charging stations, offering 2 outlets with a maximum capacity of 50 kW for faster electric vehicle charging, catering to drivers needing a quick top-up.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('983bafda-0fc9-4c5d-9e5c-b61b83579489','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Metropolitan District Council\'s Regulatory and Appeals Committee unanimously approved planning permission for the Bradford Live refurbishment. This allowed developers to proceed with transforming the former Odeon into a 4,000-capacity entertainment venue, with demolition of 1960s additions already underway and original 1930s decoration being preserved.','Planning permission for Bradford Live granted','Sports Venue Business (SVB)','2019-03-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGXDOR_VGOhxb3FrZbqIEWEPy8c3Pe5q5le43ZDZ2aQn6bYmC7G3g6fVqnPTYnGF4fjtQ5h5ySGMgMAgJ53JLbmdCrfw-FrLUPOA5-W-a8HotB0Dv-mOURe_Ofk3SdOfyVfwTOtd4pKPTmp1CvEKmsoRSsG5KP_JQXY_Vwss6PVD5K6FRuJbo6JM5dtVgKjgqH4_l8=','Bradford Metropolitan District Council\'s Regulatory and Appeals Committee unanimously approved planning permission for the Bradford Live refurbishment. This allowed developers to proceed with transforming the former Odeon into a 4,000-capacity entertainment venue, with demolition of 1960s additions already underway and original 1930s decoration being preserved.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('99064269-000a-4cda-9779-e7bea415e6a8','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Separately, senior councillors have recently approved an application for up to £20 million of grant funding that, if successful, would enable two major new extensions to the existing network. ... A second new extension, located in the South Bank of the city centre, would see approximately 7 km (4.3 miles) of low carbon heat network installed from Clarence Road to Sweet Street and eventually connecting to the existing Leeds PIPES infrastructure. Subject to funding and final approval, construction of the extensions could begin as soon as 2024 with works completing in 2026. [12]','Plans to extend Leeds PIPES network into new areas of the city revealed, as four more buildings set to connect','Leeds City Council News','2023-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHfR0buXL8fAtz0sOuokXsmkA8spVEbT9xBmQQ41pe6rLssFrCDtrFzny1U37NBZRJjJhxfVKyDQEEbIEtHAZLbffPESQr2-9So_zfMjZgc5ZQzqSArzg8-KuDdeCLHTMeO-C1dQbTLxru-vWbU8hJyFbH4CoF8MFLfWShF-XKM7MjJnCokgkvwRk2d6rdLxuHcVZiHd7EaOjqOyglhBruJ_Y763mXM7e1i0CaQeirXpQEEjzxYjvOyp9J5tzVOBi2vtd2vYy0nHw','Leeds City Council announced that senior councillors had approved an application for up to £20 million of grant funding. This funding, if successful, would enable two major new extensions, including approximately 7km of low carbon heat network to be installed in the South Bank area, from Clarence Road to Sweet Street, with construction projected for 2024-2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('994f1675-4406-496a-bdc5-75df40fcb840','infrastructure-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-corridor-improvement-phase-1b-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.863','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council say installation of huge beams for new bridge and link road are a major milestone for Salterhebble improvement works. [...] The bridge lift marks a major milestone in the progress of phase 1b of the A629 improvement project and I\'d like to congratulate those involved in successfully completing the beam lift works. [10]','Huge Bridge Beams Lifted into Place for A629 Salterhebble Improvement Works','Halifax Courier','2023-02-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/council/calderdale-council-say-installation-of-huge-beams-for-new-bridge-and-link-road-are-a-major-milestone-for-salterhebble-improvement-works-4017326','Calderdale Council announced on February 6, 2023, that the lifting of huge bridge beams marked a major milestone for Phase 1b of the A629 improvement project at the bottom of Salterhebble. This complex engineering task is part of the scheme funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, which aims to transform the road layout and improve journey times and safety. [10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('996cca13-0443-49b3-a97f-fc0a6a487a55','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A transformation of Bradford\'s former retail heart into a community known as “City Village” has advanced with the launch of the final phase of public consultation. Detailed plans for phase one were revealed today – 21 May – as part of Bradford Council\'s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock, which is running alongside this year\'s UKREiiF. Phase one will include: Creation of 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces. [13]','Detailed plans unveiled for first phase of \'City Village\' transformation','Bradford Council / ECF','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEMN5ElcT99gFGmXTRYK--K2A2hkce4AWspTN9-wmdWpC6B1Xo06nRsbvHD6ghnnQP7rSr9wIQxvBUE_WO0R11BJc7dKzuXmMFtWT6pzYdAOTD80cWyexgBv93l1RigodlXKwNnvuzDPlpRrNB59FJWNwVitdAL67olEBsMlPUbJCNGB4F4VFzsO8WSJF-yDdm8BAOHfhaPwsZ0jttaL3lA','The final phase of public consultation for Bradford City Village was launched, revealing detailed plans for Phase One. This included the creation of 33 townhouses on Chain Street and 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around courtyards and green spaces, along with supporting infrastructure. The consultation ran until June 18, 2025, ahead of a planning application submission later in the summer.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('99d19597-47a6-4aed-bfa4-e6da32151aeb','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Digital Switchover is coming to Kirklees and here\'s what it means and why it\'s happening. ... The BT Digital Voice truck will be making a stop in Huddersfield to answer people\'s questions about what it means for them. The team from BT will be located at Huddersfield Bus Station on Thursday August 17 and Friday August 18 from 9am to 5pm. The advice below has been put together by Kirklees Council. What is the Digital Switchover? The Digital Switchover is a nationwide initiative backed by the UK government. The switchover from copper lines to digital lines started in 2020 and is expected that all homes and businesses will be moved across before the end of 2025. [5]','The Digital Switchover is coming to Kirklees and here\'s what it means and why it\'s happening','Huddersfield Hub','2023-08-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFvv1XjmoN_TCsMyp6pmF_71DYW5wErbTfeP6bxluBZajCYt5f8CssMKLRixdTsoioHaJ-nd5ydX7owX9ij-ScqESo5ThihQJME6dHuDmW6VtimglPaiGmYHnChLXuIBp3dWqlLUPWLbKlYZCDJiWTU73lF8Zk4VlHOk2Ns36wrJH_8YZUmTDm5yEWZh7_E1_toZy51_fOd8-4S_PnUc8l2ihyAOC51ip7JMlZ3xzpv2RHrvgA=','Kirklees Council announced that landlines in Kirklees are being switched over to digital as part of a UK-wide program by BT. A BT Digital Voice truck visited Huddersfield Bus Station to answer questions from residents about the switch. The nationwide program aims to switch all residential and business landlines by 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('99dc575c-53f1-4c64-9a97-b3aafc840725','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'McLaren\'s property arm has got the planning green light to build a 45-storey build to rent tower and two lower-rise office blocks to the west of Leeds city centre. ... Designed by architect Howells, the Wellington Square scheme will be located on the city skyline by the landmark hexagonal-shaped residential block which will rise to 141m and provide just over 460 flats. Two adjacent office blocks of 14 and 15 storeys will provide around 435,000 sq ft of space next to the main block of flats. All buildings will have terracotta facades. The build to rent tower will be clad in white tiles while the office buildings will be red, drawing inspiration from the local red masonry buildings of Leeds. ... Prior to work starting, the site bounded by Wellington and Lisbon Street next to the A58 gyratory will also require demolition of existing buildings.','McLaren gets green light for 45-storey Leeds tower','Construction Enquirer News','2024-04-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGgwcxQHers6Rva1jCYTlDDeD5ibt_U3L57CBFXAnmwQgMm2lkd_UikpLd1Fp6HIoYxilNQBuykEzGdMmIpWBilPida7Y-ceUgEN7aMH-NhCptY4HsmzrDfqEhpj2hOVsiTXGtXxQBaW3p7-_SaZ4x5MO2ufffVZad8FtR8OhjjSJrLDrnL5tOaYDO96psivM_F8znKSzW9OgF17e_aOw==','McLaren\'s property arm secured planning permission from Leeds City Council for the Wellington Square development. The scheme features a 45-storey build-to-rent tower (known as \'The Hexagon\') with over 460 flats and two adjacent office blocks (14 and 15 storeys) providing approximately 435,000 sq ft of space. All buildings will have terracotta facades, with the residential tower clad in white tiles and office buildings in red. The site is bounded by Wellington and Lisbon Street, requiring demolition of existing buildings. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9a146a24-afc0-40bc-bf56-601be0a448f7','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Mobile operator O2 (Virgin Media) has signed a new multi-year partnership with UK tech charity Jangala, which aims to help get thousands of people affected by data poverty online by introducing free WiFi hotspots via the roll-out of 5,000 broadband-enabling “Get Boxes” to homes, community centres, refuges, and homeless shelters. [9]','Free WiFi for families and communities in need from Virgin Media O2 and Jangala','Virgin Media O2 Newsroom (via ISP Review)','2023-09-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHLoGRS2is019ancDhqYIMccUxJ7KcVNg9LXhyRZZRWV5s143VQ0EvPl4LN4-cWvIT-Hd6TL459FgV7U4UFd6LM3jcTXpM77TpQg-sPbyU1E9DbG9oSnACdwlnMk4wyVugBCujQrpMH6ZThCUiJt5XBvwFb9mb5HvoWlkdV4vfNOs44H1uWED_RkU4pABIsoEDG-X-hz-qlU5VkWcS-LUb7ADglI_7YKyJlsWxO','Virgin Media O2 partnered with technology charity Jangala to roll out 5,000 \'Get Boxes\' across the UK, providing free WiFi to thousands affected by data poverty in households, community centres, refuges, and homeless shelters. This initiative, powered by O2 mobile data from the National Databank, directly supports community organizations in connecting vulnerable people.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9a4b8b83-0cd4-4f64-895f-f24981521c87','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-places-scheme-cornholme-a646-active-travel',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.168','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The borough council of calderdale (cornholme junior, infant and nursery school) (greenfield terrace and other streets) - experimental traffic regulation order 2022. This Order is made on an experimental basis and will remain in force for a maximum period of eighteen months. Interpretation 3. 4. ம் 5. 6. 7. The Interpretation Act 1978 shall apply to this Order as it applies to an Act of Parliament. Where a provision of this Order is in conflict with a provision contained in a previous order, the provisions of this Order shall prevail for the period that this Order is in force. ... South west side - from its junction with the projected south eastern kerb line of Greenfield Terrace for a distance of 10 metres in a south easterly direction. ... Both sides - from its junction with the projected north western kerb line of A646 Burnley Road for a distance of 10 metres in a north westerly direction as measured along the centre of the carriageway. Both sides - from its junction with the projected northern kerb ... North side - from a point 10 metres west of the projected western kerb line of Greenfield Terrace to a point 6 metres east of the projected south eastern kerb line of Greenfield Terrace. ... iam 13 904 GREENFIELD TERRACE Co DRAWING No. 72/1288/01.','The borough council of calderdale (cornholme junior, infant and nursery school) (greenfield terrace and other streets) - experimental traffic regulation order 2022','Calderdale Council (likely a PDF document on their website or a legal gazette)','2022-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHXZCWwDWaaDRvgUIDVRJKARtTDJmyPoPHMIZF5RQZSCnNmbXhBLk-u0mUmm_XUZzUBiFfjyeRi8YGshfTFVu8CBX4pwkH_G99Uh0BHR2vI7wFvd8tT0Ol-qlaQSNgwqdnSa2lA2qMMUuJC7jl9RRDHd_FccRQjSk5GrX4NdjO0tdwp9BqJz1Bj3le3V622BahjGs1Wg0_9wRWM9qo1lDVF9dPOc4AO_Q0tNVI74VG64g==','This document details an Experimental Traffic Regulation Order (ETRO) made by Calderdale Council in 2022 concerning Greenfield Terrace and other streets around Cornholme Junior, Infant and Nursery School. It includes provisions for a one-way traffic system on Greenfield Terrace and restrictions on waiting, indicating early planning or implementation of traffic management measures in the area related to the broader active travel goals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9a5cdc20-8fa2-49ca-b9f6-b5e06bb4e92a','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Borough Council of Calderdale (Waiting and Loading and Parking Places) (Todmorden) (Consolidation) Order 2008 (Variation No.1) Order 2010. This Order may be cited as The Borough Council of Calderdale (Waiting and Loading and Parking Places) (Todmorden) (Consolidation) Order 2008 (Variation No. 1) Order 2010 and will come into operation on 17 January 2011. ... The items in Table B to this Order are to be added to Schedule 11.01 of the Order and the effect of this will be to introduce Resident Parking place all days all hours on the streets listed in the said schedule. ... Person Authorised to use Parking Place. Column 2. Column 3. Column 4. Position in which vehicles may wait. Classes of vehicles. Wholly within the limits of the parking place as marked on the carriageway in accordance with a road marking as indicated by diagram 1028.4 in Schedule 6 of. The Traffic. Signs. Regulations and General. Directions 2002 permitted to use. Parking Places. All classes of motor vehicle other than vehicles in excess of 3.5 tonnes gross weight. Column 5. Column 6. Column 7. Days of. Hours of. Maximum operation of operation of period for. Parking. Place. Parking. Place which vehicle may wait. A person whose usual residence is at premises, the postal address of which is Osborne Place,. Cambridge Street,. All Days. All Hours. Not. Applicable. Cambridge Place,. Industrial Street,. Sackville Street,. Roomfield Street,. Hazelwood Street, Hey. Street, Sanworth Street,. Anchor Street, or odd numbers 121 to 139. Halifax Road,. Todmorden or any person to whom a special parking permit has been issued by the Council for use in that behalf.','The Borough Council of Calderdale (Waiting and Loading and Parking Places) (Todmorden) (Consolidation) Order 2008 (Variation No.1) Order 2010','Traffic Penalty Tribunal TRO Library','2011-01-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF2Fr-U_hnZRG6Feg0LCxI6FQfvwRjh6eXAsrgvxi6Xc3qCF8cedRcDw4VSXyirObl9JG-8kAJowee56NTpz4yiLg7PGhxHLFqjn5DgvfXvACAbmCWMpE_7idm9_8vYplqBD_8lKXqWtzgx03czSy7Z12dc0cKmHe_7eBzXAg==','This legal order details the introduction of Resident Parking Places, operating all days and all hours, on specific streets in Todmorden. It outlines the authorized parking areas and the classes of vehicles permitted, as well as the residents eligible for such permits on streets like Sackville Street, Osborne Place, and Halifax Road. This is a foundational document for an RPZ in Todmorden.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9a768198-4c75-471a-8588-64992f4a1c13','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A spokesperson said: “Fink Hill update: resurfacing between Fink Hill and Bank Avenue was successfully completed last weekend. Lane closures will remain in place to make sure that footway and signalling works can be completed safely. The project is on track to be completed before Christmas 2023.” Leeds City Council has issued a key update on resurfacing works currently underway along the A6120 Horsforth route. Since June, the A6120 Broadway between Fink Hill and Horsforth roundabout has been closed intermittently to traffic, to allow for the first phase of carriageway resurfacing.','Update on Fink Hill Resurfacing Completion','Yorkshire Evening Post','2023-09-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHuOfbQ3SdaAN_6sNcREi3m5szyIGcatbHNrp1aPrYL-UVnHxloON412sl2GdYDYbVC1yFlWm-zN5wcnZcRnVqApczXJt8EVJhvg4PXBqZqll7sUMqGp2nieWenPhsJlf3TA3_McWAgLYvHn6wDy7cEKvt1-yRYfhFcXVCoJd2buI-TcUc2OveW0uMm1o2_0Aaz6_C6N8dppaFJjPMryL6pM2RVb24qeqfgfShIx08UjsVgOhFN-vuKRffV4Xrrk5WIlE_qX2_4FaIIaMYG-TKK9vjnNlALVALGYPM=','By September 11, 2023, resurfacing work between Fink Hill and Bank Avenue was successfully completed. Lane closures remained in place to facilitate footway and signalling works. Leeds City Council confirmed the project was on track to be completed before Christmas 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9ab9a6a0-2b1a-4f9b-b981-ac6576e0f064','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Works to improve Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton and Liversedge will start in early June 2025. Closures will be in place from 16 June 2025 until mid-September 2025 between Tofts Road (Tesco) in Cleckheaton and Knowler Hill tunnel in Liversedge. ... The works will create a smooth rolling surface, a wider path, improved lighting and signage and better access points to the route, making it more accessible and safer for walkers, wheelers and cyclists of all ages and abilities.','Spen Valley Greenway - Sustrans.org.uk','Sustrans','2025-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.sustrans.org.uk/find-other-routes/spen-valley-greenway','Sustrans announced that improvement works on a section of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton (Tesco) and Liversedge (Knowler Hill tunnel) would commence in early June 2025. This includes creating a smoother, wider path, installing improved lighting and signage, and enhancing access points. The section was scheduled for closure from June 16, 2025, until mid-September 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9ade45ad-233a-4cd8-9b99-1592c872d9ca','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A detailed planning application marks the first construction phase of Bradford City Village... Further phases are planned to deliver over 300 apartments on the southern Oastler site and approximately 400 apartments at Kirkgate... Subject to planning approval, demolition of the Oastler site is anticipated to begin later this year, with construction starting in spring 2026. The Oastler South site would feature around 380 apartments in a mix of one- and two-bedroom homes within buildings rising up to 10 storeys... We are now introducing detailed plans for the first phase of the project and are once again inviting community feedback before we submit a planning application later this year. May - June 2025 Consultation on Phase 1 plans. The deadline to submit feedback on our detailed plans for Phase 1 is 18 June 2025.','Public Consultation Launched with Detailed Plans for City Village, including Southern Oastler Apartments','Build News / Bradford City Village (ECF) / Telegraph & Argus / Place Yorkshire','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHT4ueISlnq0YaKeEGppbhjTRqCD9zGXLgipQQsC2We5_AlcLc7I_g17QPq2oWJBrc1KF3LVYFv2dI-Sa7lM0IZEznI-NBy_X1Qi9O3lETnEow_69pTdl34McqlKkNTciEFCaAY2Va8vTGPmL7z4obHoE-Ajrm1pN8RZJGMPz68HD2jxj0bDHNMqrOLqiQsI6yVhUjs6G7NSQFXdSRj8gk4EFbtaA','New images and detailed plans for the Bradford City Village project were released as part of a public consultation, running until June 18, 2025. The consultation explicitly detailed that \'later phases will include over 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site\' (or around 380 apartments), with demolition of the Oastler market anticipated for Autumn 2025 and Phase 1 construction starting Spring 2026. [3, 4, 5, 8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9b12c86e-35d9-439f-95b9-3bbbf8830bc8','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority will utilise a collective buying scheme to enable £5 million of leveraged private sector investment, providing residents across West Yorkshire with a reduction in the cost of Solar PV & Battery Storage installations, resulting in reduced carbon emissions, energy use and fuel bills. ... The project aims to install panels on an estimated 811 privately owned homes equating to around 3.2 MW of solar power, CO2 savings of 762,000kg per annum and estimated total bill savings of £506,400 per annum. The contract is projected to be awarded in May 2024. ... Project Status, Delivery to commence in June 2024. Start and end dates, July 2024 – March 2025.','Solar PV Residential Collective Buying Scheme - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGgRJT0bYBirzUsbaLAeIXhVj2tVLXnJEDyzzhx-bE5yKcfokTditYS0ZXpS38nult6LI6TONY67qfBR_oDnWJ7AKHJ3-PhBK8rw2_7VYJUUkgbDD4RoqYSb4nOIKXEF0z-GKL1tZvzjqialNm_npgX4hWXWP-2kX0SK_nwUL5193RqQ4ySblwZkLh5M0yGkuhmIp-oOrStudKtCJ1kQSz7B45W','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) is launching a collective buying scheme for solar PV and battery storage installations, aimed at \'able to pay\' residents across West Yorkshire, including Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield. The scheme, which is projected to commence delivery in June 2024, aims to make solar installations more affordable through economies of scale, reducing costs by approximately 30% compared to market price. It targets 811 privately owned homes, expecting 3.2 MW of solar power and annual CO2 savings of 762,000kg.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9b55bd2b-48ce-4a5f-8d8a-a2cd0c3dc8e3','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Together Housing Association(THA) working with The West Yorkshire Combined Authority are seeking to appoint contractor(s) to carry out retro fit Solar PV and Battery installations across West Yorkshire region. These works are in partnership with other west Yorkshire registered providers of social housing: • Yorkshire Housing • Wakefield And District Housing • Leeds Federation Housing • Connect Housing. ... The procurement is related to a project and/or programme financed by European Union funds: Yes. Identification of the project. Framework for Solar Pv and Battery Installations In Conjunction With The West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','Framework for Solar Pv and Battery Installations In Conjunction With The West Yorkshire Combined Authority','Find a Tender (Gov.uk)','2025-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFqU4KDA521X7R4bZTTYMPPJNdS-x9MgQvYZ-pGy8ZSpKmVAGHtwKs9IVCPc81zudCv8iF8-Cj451xVYUHqjvcYBGwdHi9LfN2FdduAWX4INAdP6LrgC9hAIklt4xdMysKwfp80wHsprR8vGnApEb4yt_YnrQ==','Together Housing Association, in collaboration with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, initiated a tender for contractors to carry out retrofitting of Solar PV and Battery installations across the West Yorkshire region. This framework explicitly names Wakefield And District Housing, Yorkshire Housing, Leeds Federation Housing, and Connect Housing as partners. This procurement is related to a project financed by European Union funds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9c0e4e7f-a044-4729-8f2c-9470fd89f463','infrastructure-elland-rail-station-and-access-package-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.897','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In June 2017, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) allocated £20 million towards re-opening the station, with planned opening date in 2022. [11]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority allocates £20 million for Elland Station re-opening','Wikipedia','2017-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elland_railway_station','In June 2017, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) allocated £20 million towards re-opening Elland station, with a planned opening date in 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9c3b4d8f-70f9-455a-b236-c5aa7fb9dd3f','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Construction work on Armley Gyratory highways phase one was completed Winter 2023. Phase two footbridge structures work was completed and open to the public in spring 2025. If you live nearby or use the junction, we would encourage you to sign up for latest news updates.','Armley Gyratory highways improvement scheme','Armley Gyratory - Commonplace','2023-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHQFOMKa-8ijMkURQEnAMILKtOYu71OoLgDK8sYFr7IO5Mjht3omjF1rfXVmw0dpOSWbU_srqkw-Rquy5ZiLXYbKJD2WbVEL-7xw_lOXqaIfBYRnATrSO505T8zXvF9xXTO','Construction work on Phase One of the Armley Gyratory highways improvement scheme was completed during Winter 2023. This phase focused on remodelling the gyratory to improve vehicle throughput and was part of wider transformative highways works aiming to remove through traffic from the city centre, mitigate environmental issues, and encourage sustainable travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9cab8c73-9b3b-418c-9fe3-8682a2971448','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been drawn up for an electric vehicle charging station on the site of an old community pub that was once earmarked for a McDonald\'s restaurant. The White Bear, off Tingley Interchange, was demolished in 2017 after closing around six years earlier. Now BP Pulse, the electrical arm of the petrol giant, wants to set up a facility for electric vehicles to be recharged on the site. Under proposals submitted to Leeds City Council this week, the station would feature 18 chargers, as well as a shop. A design and access statement attached to the plans said: “By its very nature, the proposed EV charging hub seeks to encourage the take-up of electric vehicles providing ultra-rapid chargers in a highly accessible location.','White Bear Tingley: Former Leeds pub site could become home to new electric vehicle charging station - Yorkshire Evening Post','Yorkshire Evening Post','2023-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGHYL0Wd5i_u9dsOZ4uoO4muWPWf7sui5ULLPAydL62LZqb48HQYBNSIDPQ5FNDKbbbkeryItaWPilEswBuYhsIduCLVPOKE4DrSy-0gk07FbJuSqLhicC6cZ9n0vnTMsTSqZodIP4R4hZ00UklwqtcOB3rgJOaX_wqMXamr--o0V8ZMgvVM-kG00egvXbVG1Xj57P8tfGy-o0daJWRHXXmU5N7Ur827-657C1WgB8N6nuk7aWPSly5wzTbJ-VbaGzMVxoXd_1C0b6Emc10G_gPKyDK','BP Pulse submitted plans to Leeds City Council for an electric vehicle charging station on the site of the former White Bear pub in Tingley, near the Tingley Interchange. The proposal includes 18 chargers and a shop.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9cfd5f8f-6b24-4bf6-bd47-214278526b39','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Big Four accountancy has agreed terms on around 27,000 sq ft at Muse\'s grade A office development in Bradford\'s Centenary Square as it looks to build its presence in the city. All of PwC\'s Bradford staff will relocate to the space, across two floors of the building, by June 2024, allowing the firm to build towards 500 employees over the next few years. Designed by Sheppard Robson, One City Park was completed late in 2023.','PwC to anchor One City Park - Place Yorkshire / PwC celebrates success in Bradford with new 27,050 sq foot office space at One City Park','Place Yorkshire / OneCity','2024-01-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFjTLif-Xbd4In2nTved_gR-dBe5sB30UiYD5ylxwMiuZ8MKVhOjm2YFyM0YpvVNkhvJfBZA2nh2QW3EoM9HuDTa9rV8oeIP73ryPxsG4K-4uYlWB7v8djH0QZ0h3JYX2t-ydPmqtfXkjFgiCBhIlRgiyZjD1soWQ==','PwC announced it had agreed terms on approximately 27,000 sq ft at One City Park, becoming the anchor tenant. All of PwC\'s Bradford staff were set to relocate to the new space by June 2024, with plans for the firm to expand to 500 employees over the next few years. The building, designed by Sheppard Robson, was completed in late 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9d187206-3d3c-447c-8148-7d187eff47f0','infrastructure-leeds-city-centre-public-realm-improvements---new-station-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.649','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of the next stage in the transformation of Leeds City Rail Station\'s main entrance and surrounding area, New Station Street will be closed from Friday 19 May to all traffic (except service vehicles and emergency services). Due to the closure, the station taxi rank will be moved to Princes Square. Friday 19 May will also see the northern section of New Station Street, from the station\'s main entrance towards City Square, closed to pedestrians to allow works to be carried out. [4]','Transforming Leeds City Rail Station: Date of New Station Street closure announced','Leeds City Rail Station - Commonplace','2023-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://leedscityrailstation.commonplace.is/proposals/transforming-leeds-city-rail-station/updates/transforming-leeds-city-rail-station-date-of-new-station-street-closure-announced','As part of the ongoing transformation of Leeds City Rail Station, New Station Street was scheduled to close from Friday, May 19, 2023, to all traffic (except service and emergency vehicles). This closure facilitated major works on the station\'s main entrance and surrounding area, with the taxi rank temporarily moved to Princes Square.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9d7ea3ef-81aa-468c-ab69-c40133834125','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-star-multi-academy-trust-monk-fryston-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.364','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A Leeds primary school that has pledged to become net zero by 2030 is inspiring the community to take action in the pivotal \'climate decade\'. In 2019, Monk Fryston Church of England Primary School formed a project with other community buildings in the village to achieve carbon neutrality. After successfully securing a grant of £170,920 from Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme, it was able to set to work on installing a ground source heat pump as the preferred heating and hot water solution. The school also upgraded its lightning to LED to increase efficiency and reduce electricity usage. This project has resulted in annual carbon savings of 15 tonnes in addition to significant financial savings.','Monk Fryston Church of England Primary School Inspires Community Decarbonisation','Salix Finance','2023-07-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.salixfinance.co.uk/case-studies/monk-fryston-church-of-england-primary-school','Salix Finance published a case study on Monk Fryston Church of England Primary School, highlighting how a £170,920 grant from Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme enabled the installation of a ground source heat pump and LED lighting. This project resulted in annual carbon savings of 15 tonnes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9db7a6e6-df82-4dbd-b909-c7271824757e','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Earlier this year, over two hundred and fifty council properties in Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers were set up to receive heat from the network. This year, connections have been completed at Leeds Conservatoire and the former Technology Campus Student Residential development and both sites are now receiving heat from the network.','Leeds low carbon heat network set to expand to thousands more residents','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2024-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/leeds-low-carbon-heat-network-set-to-expand-to-thousands-more-residents','Leeds City Council announced further expansion of the Leeds PIPES network. The update confirmed that \'Earlier this year, over two hundred and fifty council properties in Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers were set up to receive heat from the network,\' indicating the connection became operational during 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9dce155a-f313-4dbb-9d88-d9b6fc26fc99','infrastructure-enfinium-skelton-grange-energy-from-waste-facility',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.539','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first waste delivery took place in March 2025, comprising of around 200 tonnes of residual material from six suppliers.','First waste delivery at Skelton Grange Energy from Waste facility','letsrecycle.com','2025-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEa30ZvLlWMQrAn68cAKFEziF7vY-Le2EaBzZUtsImVwbdYBKTjBZKTfBtf8ubCs4J9qgd67q_iI0uOZ8Zzne4UipvTWH2sLxD4y_jX1vn7KleG0cyvazJktm9c_XANd-3EHWQ3gXojRHds7CXP5R26Iiv14lzyTKml678oZAus0iMogq48YnL-RJIXMj2tGSB_tXg6','The first waste delivery, comprising approximately 200 tonnes of residual material from six suppliers, took place at the Enfinium Skelton Grange facility in March 2025. This marked a significant step towards the facility\'s full operational status.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9de5cce1-dd14-4d22-b25e-78da21478a78','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for a tram system running between Leeds and Bradford have been set out today, as the West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin aims to revolutionise the region\'s transport network. ... The Bradford Line would run from Leeds city centre to Bradford city centre – also linking Bradford Forster Square station with the new Bradford rail station. This line supports Bradford\'s plans to regenerate the city\'s southern gateway, which includes the new Bradford rail station. ... It is hoped that spades will be in the ground in 2028 when construction of the early stage of the project will begin. [22]','Mayor sets out plan for West Yorkshire tram system to better-connect region','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-03-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/council/mayor-tracy-brabin-sets-out-plans-for-west-yorkshire-tram-system-to-better-connect-region-4547463','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin announced plans for a tram system, a \'Mass Transit\' network, for the region, with spades hoped to be in the ground by 2028. This includes a dedicated \'Bradford Line\' that would run from Leeds city centre to Bradford city centre, specifically linking Bradford Forster Square station with the proposed new Bradford rail station (near the Interchange site). This marks a significant step forward in the formalization of the Bradford cross-city link as part of a larger regional system.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9e10a657-621a-46a3-b385-11bbd13d9a2b','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Minister visited several landmarks and connections on the network including the Recycling & Energy Recovery Facility (RERF), Cross Green energy centre and St James\'s Hospital where he met members from the NHS Estates and Facilities team. Lord Callanan also visited Shakespeare Towers to meet residents connected to the Heat Network. ... A second new extension, located in the South Bank of the city centre, would see approximately 7 km (4.3 miles) of low carbon heat network being installed from Clarence Road to Sweet Street and eventually connecting to the existing Leeds PIPES infrastructure. Subject to funding and final approval, construction of the extensions could begin as soon as 2024 with works completing in 2026. [11]','Minister Visits £62m Leeds PIPES Heat Network Project','Vital Energi','2023-08-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEl4GfcnM3ltHnswR3yTELAJUftLsATXfzBE1YJFvIwi07vNlQQ7OHgyqOLsQwEn-gTl9AFRi7nxNTunp8FD88UZNxCraMrDtqtwAys7Iozla0-cNdM3nTHG4sovg05PmwfsjhmqiDCiRWQVaiTLzl2tr-Qsor7sEThxcF45WGzIl0vGfBWXaRK_hpLHfmQT34etyUPA0HsfiawqyghQgI50NJz','Lord Callanan, Minister for Energy Efficiency and Green Finance, visited the Leeds PIPES network. The visit highlighted government backing for the expansion plans, including the proposed 7km South Bank extension from Clarence Road to Sweet Street, with construction expected to begin as soon as 2024 and complete by 2026, subject to funding and final approval.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9e21b65d-9afe-458f-b04c-ad7494ebf86c','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Diocese of Leeds: South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School, School / Academy, £354,418.','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: grant recipients','GOV.UK','2025-04-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-grant-recipients','This GOV.UK publication provides a list of all organisations that received grants under Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. It confirms the Diocese of Leeds: South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School received £354,418 as part of the Yorkshire and the Humber region allocations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9e9501bc-6278-4b18-9ac3-134b752b8b9c','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale councillors are on board with regional proposals to develop a mass transit system for West Yorkshire. But representatives have to make sure it brings benefits to the borough, they said, and a councillor asked “why are we bothering?”. West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) and Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin, are backing ambitious plans to develop mass transit travel in the region. At a meeting of the full Calderdale Council councillors agreed to joining the others in West Yorkshire – Bradford, Leeds, Wakefield and Kirklees – in starting shaping a framework for how it will be realised. Recommending the proposals, Leader of the Council, Coun Jane Scullion, said initial proposals were developing a tram system between Leeds and Bradford, and it developing from there. The government has allocated an initial £200 million to develop West Yorkshire\'s Mass Transit plans including some design and consultation work.','Councillors on board with proposals to develop mass transit system','Telegraph and Argus','2025-08-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF_A-BoSf6tH-zzR3z8NyHM6kUyT2xt1qSI9dIbhSyfTgU_Oz1DTLA1CLWgJrmpaSDJRyCrAtIzDnq3-H1550Xb2dGqhBGbiptPv7QLnhZHKRzZXbNVhQqqqUHX6XHoNjmMn6NY9Nz9qEIkhvSbaNmwHcaFwQ3lfn2DY1-wyqf_kf4BpmMLfUuoxPalDryo0yBqooGp7B1PhPVDbGLaC5P8QkjerL4REO4=','Calderdale councillors expressed their support for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit System proposals but stressed the importance of ensuring the project brings benefits to Calderdale, not just the initial Leeds-Bradford lines. Concerns were raised regarding potential mayoral control and funding distribution, with councillors advocating for Calderdale\'s specific needs within the regional transport plans. The government has allocated an initial £200 million for design and consultation work.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9ebcb8e1-3018-4162-8556-a8dcbdf7d376','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A new flood information centre has opened in Hebden Bridge, to help keep the community updated with progress to reduce the risk of flooding in the town. From: Environment Agency; Published: 29 August 2023. The Environment Agency has opened its new Flood Information Centre at 4 Hardcastle House, Valley Road in Hebden Bridge this week. The centre will be open on Mondays and Fridays from 10am to 2pm, where people can stop by to speak with members of the project team and view information about the flood alleviation schemes for Hebden Bridge Town Centre, Stubbing Holme Road and Erringden Hillside. The Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme will improve protection for approximately 400 properties in the town and will consist of increasing flood protection from Hebden Water and River Calder, improving the drainage of surface water with a series of gully systems and a pumping station and construction of a canal flood overflow. The planning application is currently forecast to be submitted in early 2024.','Flood information centre opens in Hebden Bridge','GOV.UK (Environment Agency)','2023-08-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/flood-information-centre-opens-in-hebden-bridge','The Environment Agency opened a new Flood Information Centre at 4 Hardcastle House, Valley Road, Hebden Bridge, on August 29, 2023. The centre provides updates and allows the community to meet the project team for the Hebden Bridge Town Centre, Stubbing Holme Road, and Erringden Hillside flood alleviation schemes. The Hebden Bridge scheme aims to protect approximately 400 properties, with the planning application forecast for early 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9ecc686c-a599-463c-bc57-77f3e6379f3d','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.902','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'New images were released on January 6, 2025, showcasing how the A629 Phase 2 project will transform Halifax town centre with new public spaces, safer travel routes, and cycle paths. Work is progressing well, with the first phase focusing on the west of the town, including the removal of the Bull Green roundabout for a new junction. Construction is being carried out by Galliford Try and will be completed in three parts: western, eastern, and central.','New images released showing revamped Halifax town centre and construction progress','Calderdale Forum 50 Plus (citing Calderdale Council\'s Next Chapter website)','2025-01-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdaleforum50plus.com/Images-Of-How-Revamped-Halifax-Will-Look','New images were released on January 6, 2025, showcasing how the A629 Phase 2 project will transform Halifax town centre with new public spaces, safer travel routes, and cycle paths. Work is progressing well, with the first phase focusing on the west of the town, including the removal of the Bull Green roundabout for a new junction. Construction is being carried out by Galliford Try and will be completed in three parts: western, eastern, and central.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9ece90f3-e933-43ef-bb87-28b74a87b719','infrastructure-calderdale-corridor-improvement-programme-phase-1-a58a672-and-a646a6033',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.888','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Corridor Improvement Programme received decision point 2 approval (case paper) from the Combined Authority on the 29th June 2017 for the programme as a whole. Following this approval, Calderdale Council appointed a development partner to identify key issues along the network, develop a long list of proposals, short list of options, feasibility designs and an outline business case for the A58 and A646 schemes. [10]','Corridor Improvement Programme Decision Point 2 Approval','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (FAQs)','2017-06-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH-d6Yh0PjMpoD6ZyoZn7uXD45VeoEHb0Fx3taDDCxZe8PbTZ4-SZNEACy7n2Ya2OACLa3YXrUUMMMUwr035qtWnN8f7miUB0nbNBAsrkHPowX6PQ7jspDYc5Pw4PCL6ZHtgZcFIJQCCBaGj4jsjA==','The Corridor Improvement Programme, which includes the Calderdale Phase 1 schemes, received Decision Point 2 approval (case paper) from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. This signifies the formal approval of the programme\'s strategic direction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9ed80206-855d-4edc-a6b8-bea33ea97dcf','infrastructure-calderdale-corridor-improvement-programme-phase-1-a58a672-and-a646a6033',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.888','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority are developing a series of improvements to the road network along the A58 / A672 from Junction 22 of the M62 to King Cross in Halifax and the A646 / A6033 from Todmorden to Skircoat Moor. Financed through the WYCA\'s Transport Fund, the two programmes cover the congested routes through Calderdale. Here we take a closer at what is being planned on the A646 corridor which will cost £5.09m. What are the aims of the A646 Corridor Improvement scheme? [7]','A Closer Look at the £5m A646 Corridor Improvement Plans','Halifax Courier','2020-01-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFU4rnW8dPVufTBkHfYGTB6Dv__IXB9Vi1j5uzOhMU55mqIJY7H2F6RVY3qZ82Br54Y-lX9CH127jbIbh2R4FHKitNRnNfkgSmUg8JYSLjtCahGJ2IMHQ0XP9gwjO9LvJnedZPZcV1IZ5TN9t-MC1kd_cw79o1LPbreZs_1Yu16wuJ9Vi1W97DvBfGmERzkf9SPaJ6M3poPFpf26HGvLx4yr9NFLESCOw1EHzU9ig-0gePh1TtQzjVL618O_1olOY1Tq2YxlVa7dHGZxFlxLBk=','The Halifax Courier provided a detailed overview of the planned £5.09 million improvements for the A646 corridor, highlighting aims such as addressing pinch points, improving resilience, and encouraging modal shift, with specific interventions in towns like Todmorden and Hebden Bridge.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9f0f42b7-832a-48a4-a066-cb5da45a3564','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The transformation of Bradford\'s former retail heart into a vibrant new sustainable community known as \'City Village\' has taken a further step forward with the launch of the final phase of public consultation. Detailed plans for phase 1 of the neighbourhood, which ECF, our partnership with Homes England and L&G, is delivering in partnership with Bradford Council, were revealed today (Wednesday 21st May) as part of Bradford Council\'s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock, which is running alongside this year\'s UKREiiF regeneration forum. [21] It will create up to 1,000 energy-efficient homes including affordable housing, as well as independent retail and leisure opportunities, business spaces and new high-quality public realm, including three new green spaces. [21] Bradford-based affordable housing provider, Incommunities, has been selected as ECF\'s preferred funding partner to deliver the first phase of townhouses for sale and rent at Bradford City Village, subject to a final legal agreement. [21]','Community conversation launched on the first phase of Bradford’s game-changing ‘City Village’','Muse Developments','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.musedevelopments.co.uk/news/community-conversation-launched-on-the-first-phase-of-bradfords-game-changing-city-village/','The final phase of public consultation for Phase 1 of Bradford City Village was launched, inviting feedback on updated plans ahead of a planning application submission. Incommunities was announced as the preferred funding partner for the first phase of townhouses. The project, delivered by ECF and Bradford Council, secured £13.2 million from WYCA and £30 million from Homes England.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9f12fb39-b12c-49fd-b655-8efd96d5aeba','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'First of 3,500 leaky dams installed for National Trust and Yorkshire Water joint conservation scheme in the South Pennines. In early October, contractors arrived at the Yorkshire Water moorland landholding around Baitings and Ryburn reservoirs and began stacking up stones to form leaky barriers. By partially blocking the flow of water through moorland ditches or channels, they act to slow the flow of rainwaters during heavy rainfall. By gradually releasing water slowly over a longer period, instead of allowing it to rush downhill, they can help to limit flooding downstream, saving homes and businesses from damage. The Landscapes for Water project is installing 3,500 leaky dams across five main areas of the South Pennines over the next four years.','Leaky dams installed in landmark Natural Flood Management partnership project for South Pennines','Yorkshire Water','2024-10-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirewater.com/news-media/news/leaky-dams-installed-in-landmark-natural-flood-management-partnership-project-for-south-pennines/','In early October 2024, contractors commenced the installation of the first of 3,500 leaky barriers around Baitings and Ryburn reservoirs as a key component of the Landscapes for Water project. This natural flood management technique is crucial for slowing water flow on moorlands, rewetting these areas, and thereby protecting downstream communities in the Upper Calder and Colne catchments from the impacts of flooding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('9f24097f-3191-4307-86a0-a8e579ca5b26','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The \'William Parkin Way Link Road\' opened in 2019, which includes a new bridge over the Leeds-York rail line and provides a connection to the M1, enhancing accessibility to Thorpe Park Leeds.','William Parkin Way Link Road opened at Thorpe Park Leeds','Leeds.gov.uk','2019-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/east-leeds-extension/thorpe-park','The \'William Parkin Way Link Road\' opened in 2019, which includes a new bridge over the Leeds-York rail line and provides a connection to the M1, enhancing accessibility to Thorpe Park Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a05aac8e-40ba-4450-83de-9392e482864f','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Caddick Developments website for South Village, Leeds, outlines the key elements of the approved project: up to 1,925 homes, 650,000 sqft of commercial space, and significant landscaped areas, including a \'village green\' the size of a professional sports field. The project, located off Meadow Road, is designed to meet high environmental standards and improve city connectivity. [7] While the page doesn\'t have a specific publication date, its content reflects the status post-planning approval and Homes England MoU, hence the May 21, 2024 date is used to represent its current details.','South Village, Leeds - Caddick Developments (Project Details)','Caddick Developments','2024-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://caddick.co.uk/residential-developments/south-village-leeds','Caddick Developments\' official project page for South Village details the approved scheme, including up to 1,925 homes, 650,000 sq ft of commercial space, and significant landscaped areas centered around a \'village green\'. It emphasizes the project\'s design for high environmental standards and improved connectivity.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a06791d6-42d7-46a5-83b5-4474093b27fd','infrastructure-a660-holt-lane--otley-road-junction-improvements-adel-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.964','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of the \'Connecting Leeds\' scheme, improvements were proposed for the A660 running from Adel to Leeds, with traffic signals proposed at the Holt Lane/Otley Road junction. [8]','Connecting Leeds: Adel to Leeds (A660) plans - Leeds Cycling Campaign Response','Leeds Cycling Campaign','2018-07-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG96VAE0cATnHn8-YyzebHbpHn576TOxZ65KHSQRnML6tqIJP2EdnW1IozwEPTMN99cnUHUVoK2ooSqxd0-dsuJ4IvDdCQbIFyBZpGtwwa0Bb5j4oElI8mPpjJecaGJl8GFTgW0XAdghuSEpjI9Hn_oCLY3DkaEBg==','This article from the Leeds Cycling Campaign, dated July 2018, discusses proposed improvements for the A660 route from Adel to Leeds, specifically mentioning traffic signals at the Holt Lane/Otley Road junction and advocating for separate signals for cyclists.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a0a0553c-2686-406f-8e39-56da2d71b23a','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'2017-11-04T15:42:23Z. ... Charger situated to the left of the showroom in the main customer car park. There is one post with two mennekes type 2 charge points, and one chademo rapid post. Ask at reception if you need to use the chargers. There is an emergency 7kw pod point unit in the back of the dealership.','Earliest User Check-in at Lookers Nissan Leeds EV Station (formerly Benfield Motors)','PlugShare','2017-11-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.plugshare.com/location/101869','A PlugShare user successfully checked in and charged an EV at the Lookers Nissan Leeds dealership (then operating as Benfield Motors site), indicating the charging facilities were operational and publicly accessible by this date. The station featured one post with two Type 2 charge points and one CHAdeMO rapid post, along with an emergency 7kW Pod Point unit.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a0a48da2-acf4-4f29-a72e-bf4f66507cb0','infrastructure-a629-halifax-to-huddersfield-corridor-improvement-phase-4-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.884','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The public consultation ran from 4th February to 31st March 2019. The aim of the consultation was to promote the project proposals, give people the opportunity to review and feedback on our outline business case proposals and gather views to inform the future development of the scheme. Overall, feedback for the project was positive, with the majority of respondents expecting that the proposals would achieve our strategic aims and would improve journeys for all modes.','Delivered in partnership with Kirklees Council, the consultation for the A629 Halifax to Huddersfield - Calderdale Next Chapter','Calderdale Next Chapter / Calderdale Council','2019-02-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGe7s4sd8jOGTV51GkPDUDo54sZx0IA386J9ttTGsBbBOrBEUUiZHTqgWTOd5fqWKxEFtyYqB1iKrqj5lGZM9gUmtm9tzaYC9jQVBxOy0Gj3UuywBeMw5CLJIv-f193zG3uuXYDgNHS5NEws8SpZGHDuNJBL79TsJRU0ir5h-EK5wPv0mT-Hyb1xtZ6DqZkmmwbi5_nDj7lWAeOzgKSSk8a92qiCoeAU23dlcM8WIHj0cNX5FYmN836s988nvtOMt6kBvAiVirNuJPgwsEe1KDe66UX3_I6YC9uUsV5dYc=','This document outlines the public consultation for Phase 4 of the A629 Halifax to Huddersfield project, which ran from February 4 to March 31, 2019. The consultation aimed to gather feedback on the outline business case proposals, and overall feedback was positive, with respondents expecting improvements in economic growth, sustainability, safety, journey times, and the environment. The project is delivered in partnership with Kirklees Council.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a0a4dccb-3d7e-400b-913b-c065fd941da7','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In response to a parliamentary question, the Department for Transport confirmed that Thorpe Park Station received £7 million funding from the New Stations Fund 3 in 2021, and reiterated the expectation for the station to open in 2024.','Department for Transport confirms funding and projected opening for Thorpe Park Station','Parallel Parliament','2023-02-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.parallelparliament.co.uk/lords/question/2023-02-17/151703','In response to a parliamentary question, the Department for Transport confirmed that Thorpe Park Station received £7 million funding from the New Stations Fund 3 in 2021, and reiterated the expectation for the station to open in 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a0a983d1-a1a3-480d-9f2e-fbe9f8c68094','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The scheme, with a value of £86.7m, was approved by the Environment Agency (EA) in December 2018 to provide protection from a 1% Annual Exceedance Probability (AEP) flood event. It is led by Leeds City Council (LCC), supported by the EA. The approval was based on a “nationally preferred” option of a 1.33% scheme with additional Defra and local funding being secured to improve the level of protection to a 1% AEP scheme. This is now in construction and LCC wishes to pursue an opportunity to raise the protection further to 0.5% AEP.','Accounting Officer Memorandum: Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 - Initial Approval','Parliament.uk','2018-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHiJleEDjiNL5mS4jQMz4vOFPDln1d_IuZiaRbu46TuRqRtbXN3UHEI71tSh_BI3c7JXYJaO9ClYSBNZh-YWozGc4nGlXehoiuBJiXqggLKgcgP-QMWTPQ3HAlLiGvuS5iBu4_G_7PZ_93iE4bft7SeT5x8mbn5_LXUyEpy4pr3PPx3hvZqgyeArfcYDH3xH3BmpDnpIyKyfhmpZDIXh03uaQR0BKL6fcgZHy-bLD2QFfkISFwnBWo1APnmqcbHNhT3eIcozvEQ8nlPLk0ZcyMn','The Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 was initially approved by the Environment Agency in December 2018 with a value of £86.7 million, aimed at providing protection from a 1% Annual Exceedance Probability (AEP) flood event. Leeds City Council leads the scheme, supported by the Environment Agency.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a1068830-545f-4ed6-a02e-a5ea7d0b204c','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Tech Lending Community scheme, established in 2022, aims to tackle digital exclusion and electronic waste by providing second-hand devices to people in need, while also giving tech a second life, preventing it ending up in landfill. [17]','Virgin Media O2 and Hubbub show charities \'TLC\' with £400,000 tech lending scheme','Virgin Media O2 Newsroom','2022-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFxqbSQTIKIVHckkybqlL6VAgpKdr1CSxCaqkBcmP_BP0NAXaEaMYsHBGvkBvalwaSvaWzq70ETAAHrxQUzESa8B-Ow0iYVB78_3QoosnRY4kKiICQWQ3MB6ZoYrDaV2xqcS6yw5OjZ-mn6LtfjJcZlDBaQNrSI3vUMf3Us_pWZXS1qZXoSBaAHabNX7-5hZEL1K3ekSmId0rTqlF5AHOWwq40WV47QqWcynA==','Virgin Media O2, in partnership with environmental charity Hubbub, launched the Tech Lending Community scheme in 2022. This £400,000 initiative tackles digital exclusion and e-waste by providing refurbished devices with free O2 mobile data to people in need, showcasing Virgin Media O2\'s broader commitment to supporting charities and digital inclusion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a183556e-a151-4dbe-adfa-0a0ac8e693ac','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The LEVI Fund supports local authorities in England to plan and deliver charging infrastructure for residents without off-street parking. West Yorkshire has been awarded £1.5 million of LEVI Pilot funding and £14.3 million of further LEVI Capital funding to install close to home residential chargepoints. This is in addition to over £1.5 million of Capability funding to support officers working on EV programmes. ... Updated Dec, 2024 (from Carbon Copy reference to WYCA LEVI program).','Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) Fund - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/transport-projects/local-electric-vehicle-infrastructure-levi-fund/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) details its participation in the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) Fund. West Yorkshire has been allocated £1.5 million in LEVI Pilot funding and £14.3 million in Capital funding, along with over £1.5 million for Capability funding, aimed at installing residential chargepoints and developing a robust EV infrastructure strategy across the region. The commitment reflects a goal to build a reliable, safe, and easy-to-use network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a185aeb0-bdd2-4d28-9efe-4cc7df7f92ea','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Project Partner, Calderdale Council, Invites Residents to Have Their Say on Updated Plans for Walking & Cycling Routes as Part of Their Active Todmorden Town Deal Project. On 16th Sept Calderdale Council published a Press Release on its website inviting residents to have their say on updated plans for walking and cycling routes as part of their Active Todmorden Town Deal project. The £3.2 million Active Todmorden project is one of the eight projects which make up the £17.5 million Todmorden Town Deal programme, which is funded by the UK Government and overseen by Todmorden Town Board. Todmorden residents are invited to have their say on updated plans for walking and cycling routes through the town, with public events scheduled for Thursday 24 and Saturday 26 October 2024.','Calderdale Council Announcement on Active Todmorden Project - Invitation for Public Consultation','Todmorden Town Deal / Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.todmordentowndeal.co.uk/news/calderdale-council-announcement-on-active-todmorden-project','Calderdale Council published a press release inviting Todmorden residents to have their say on updated plans for walking and cycling routes as part of the Active Todmorden Town Deal project. This announcement indicated the project\'s initial £3.2 million budget as part of the wider £17.5 million Town Deal regeneration programme. Public engagement events were announced for October 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a28d0f03-3eaf-4e93-a134-4ae7feb8815c','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Muse Developments, leaders in town and city-centre urban regeneration, in partnership with Bradford Council have officially launched One City Park, today (Tuesday 17th May) - a BREEAM \'Excellent\' 56,403 sq. ft office building in the heart of Bradford city centre. The development, to be built on the former police HQ site, is the first Grade A office scheme delivered in Bradford city centre for 20 years and will directly address the need for high-quality offices, with flexible options now available to secure off-plan. More than 300 jobs will be created throughout the construction of One City Park, with Yorkshire-based Caddick Construction named earlier this year as the scheme\'s contractor. A further 450 jobs will be based in the building once completed.','Muse Developments officially launches One City Park in Bradford','Bdaily','2022-05-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFezryMhbSy185Br0nSSJNTSYIisUolRhnMNa-GJRGes1Mg6mmZCMBepPXvsThlrX0QJEo76hvyEWT88GwGYoCupF5VAgtW_XkmqamytO409oQW7pejcN7OO8jAjjxN95TeaYJEUFEx6Ue7dfq52nkKZ-EBqKYkn46pfkbr7u7bN5NnsDe7nADk62bgddA0M7icIAdk96aNieptzb3Ff6hV_rU=','Muse Developments, in partnership with Bradford Council, officially launched One City Park. This BREEAM \'Excellent\' 56,403 sq ft office building is the first Grade A office scheme delivered in Bradford city centre for two decades. The project was expected to create over 300 construction jobs and 450 permanent jobs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a2b1216b-8d78-412a-a3d5-d04ccdc7a4e9','infrastructure-huddersfield-rail-station-connections-phase-one-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.936','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This project is in the construction phase. The project aims to make it easier for everyone to make their way between the railway station and the places where we live, learn, work or visit in Huddersfield town centre. Currently, the town centre is dominated by motor vehicles, low quality pavements, lack of cycle lanes and busy junctions which are difficult for users. Public transport facilities and connections between the town centre, train station and bus station need significant improvement. This project is funded by the Transforming Cities Fund and supports the council\'s blueprint project and Our Cultural Heart, an ambitious investment with families and culture at the centre of Kirklees. Huddersfield Town Centre continues to be a place for people to enjoy with a vibrant open market, outdoor events and leisure and retail experience. Plans. Northumberland Street. Improved cycling provision making it safer for cyclist to join the carriageway. Widening of the footways along Northumberland Street to improve urban infrastructure and accessibility in the area. New Zebra crossing making it safer and more accessible for pedestrians. Reversal of Byram street to be made one way in the opposite direction to help improve local traffic circulation and safety. Trees to be planted on both sides, creating a green, urban landscape. Traffic calming measures. Trinity Street. Upgrades to traffic signals and installation of new cycle and pedestrian crossing points. Additional cycle route across the Trinity Street junction. Provision of a shared cycle/pedestrian footways at key crossing points. Amendments to the Henry St/Westgate junction at the corners to allow shared cycle use. St John\'s Road. New cycle route between Fitzwilliam Street and Beck Road to connect the National Cycle Network on Willow Lane with the town centre. Wider and improved footways and pedestrian crossings to make walking easier. Upgrades to the traffic lights improving traffic flow and allow cyclists to cross safely. Making Fitzwilliam Street one-way ... Huddersfield Rail Station Connections will complement the Transpennine Route Upgrade, a Network Rail project which will bring more trains, quicker journeys and better links between Huddersfield, Dewsbury, Leeds, Manchester and York, improving connectivity and supporting economic growth in the north. [7]','Huddersfield Rail Station Connections - Kirklees Council (Construction Phase)','Kirklees Council','2025-08-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/transport-roads-and-parking/transport-schemes/huddersfield-rail-station-connections.aspx','The official Kirklees Council project page confirms that the Huddersfield Rail Station Connections project is in its construction phase. The project, funded by the Transforming Cities Fund, aims to improve transport links and public spaces around the station. Detailed plans include widening footways, adding cycle lanes, new pedestrian crossings, and traffic calming measures on Northumberland Street, Trinity Street, and St John\'s Road, directly addressing the project\'s public realm and active travel goals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a2d5883e-5b59-430f-aa36-6ba4b44e218b','infrastructure-a629-calder-and-hebble-junction-corridor-improvement-phase-1b-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.863','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This Instrument may be cited as the Borough Council of Calderdale (A629, Southern Section, Halifax) (Highway Improvements) (West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund, Phase 1b) (Calder and Hebble Navigation Bridge) Scheme 2020 Confirmation Instrument 2021 and shall come into force on the date on which notice that it has been confirmed is first published in accordance with paragraph 1 of Schedule 2 to the Highways Act 1980. [...] Signed by authority of the Secretary of State. Simon Connick. A Senior Civil Servant. in the Department for Transport. 18th November 2021. [19]','Confirmation Instrument for Calder and Hebble Navigation Bridge Scheme','Legislation.gov.uk (likely)','2021-11-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2021/1317/made','The Borough Council of Calderdale (A629, Southern Section, Halifax) (Highway Improvements) (West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund, Phase 1b) (Calder and Hebble Navigation Bridge) Scheme 2020 Confirmation Instrument 2021 was confirmed on November 18, 2021. This legal instrument authorized the Council to construct a new bridge over the navigable waters of the Calder and Hebble Navigation as part of the project. [19]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a32d3198-e5fe-4025-92b0-67ef610d18de','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The LEVI Fund supports local authorities in England to plan and deliver charging infrastructure for residents without off-street parking. West Yorkshire has been awarded £1.5 million of LEVI Pilot funding and £14.3 million of further LEVI Capital funding to install close to home residential chargepoints. This is in addition to over £1.5 million of Capability funding to support officers working on EV programmes. Our ambition is to build a network of public electric vehicle (EV) chargepoints in West Yorkshire. LEVI will be delivered in several phases – Phase 1, funded by Pilot funding and then subsequently Phases 2a and 2b, funded by the Capital allocation.','Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) Fund - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/transport-projects/local-electric-vehicle-infrastructure-levi-fund/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority outlines its Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) Fund strategy, which supports local authorities in England to deploy residential charging infrastructure. West Yorkshire has been awarded £1.5 million in LEVI Pilot funding and an additional £14.3 million in Capital funding, along with £1.5 million for capability, to significantly expand its public EV charging network, especially for residents without off-street parking.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a34afe40-12b3-4d19-a97e-939ee40dca5d','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'New buildings are regularly being connected to the system, with some existing customers including some student accommodation buildings, Leeds Conservatoire (formerly the College of Music) and St James\'s Hospital already connected. [14]','Low carbon heat network for Leeds','Public Sector Executive','2023-12-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.publicsectorexecutive.com/articles/low-carbon-heat-network-leeds','Leeds City Council announced the expansion of the Leeds PIPES district heating network, benefiting hundreds more households. The article explicitly states that Leeds Conservatoire (formerly the College of Music) is among the new buildings regularly being connected to the system, having already joined as a customer.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a363cc14-de4f-43a2-8467-4e96e319cf49','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious plans to bring trams back to West Yorkshire, and deliver a multibillion-pound boost to the economy, have secured a major funding boost from the government. The Chancellor Rachel Reeves today (Wednesday 4th June) announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to get spades in the ground on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. [10] The first phase of West Yorkshire\'s Mass Transit network will create two tram lines - a Leeds Line, running from St James\'s University Hospital through the city centre to the White Rose, and a Bradford Line, connecting Bradford and Leeds city centres. [10]','Major funding boost secured for West Yorkshire trams','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-and-events/news/major-funding-boost-secured-for-west-yorkshire-trams/','Chancellor Rachel Reeves announced the allocation of £2.1 billion of local transport funding to West Yorkshire, empowering the Combined Authority to begin construction on the tram project by 2028. This substantial investment is earmarked for the initial phase of the Mass Transit network, specifically including the Leeds and Bradford Lines.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a36a75d1-5be4-4c62-9e49-31247498a7cc','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point located at Thorpe Park Hotel and Spa, LS15 8ZA is part of the Powered by E.ON Drive network. There are 3 devices and 6 connectors available at this charging location. ... Updated: 08th September 2025. [4]','Thorpe Park Hotel and Spa EV charging point, Leeds - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.zapmap.com/charge-points/thorpe-park-hotel-and-spa','Zapmap confirms the electric car charging point at Thorpe Park Hotel and Spa, LS15 8ZA, is part of the Powered by E.ON Drive network. It has 3 devices and 6 connectors, with an update date indicating recent information.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a412fc9e-b24e-4d67-ace6-83b31ce8843d','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Network Rail began a project on Monday 22 October 2018 to extend platforms three and four at Bradford Interchange railway station as part of the Great North Rail Project. Network Rail and Northern are extending the platforms in readiness for newer and longer trains which will call at the station. To minimise disruption to passengers, the work will be carried out overnight. The upgrade was expected to complete on Friday, 7 December 2018.','Network Rail begins improvements to Bradford Interchange railway station today','Network Rail','2018-10-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFxBJtCKqkxeD_45MYmbnY20q5vKg2nWvvfsWXG8YGW4X2lc-45v1dO8SsdlN723ZYjOnInxedWOHgeA2MBkC_XzFtlaFsVJKWb9HKkHXUgh4fn_oUkECbKVr6m_WcSk3tSbfeWqWmCoSRpGXaUrlT5luIrzZ--WIpdUXf9jXEJBiIH95sLPIVRlyR6N84FPkyYTwtRn7EQsl73_w40zHrhotrfQlP6TYSp9Nkpso0y6z-1fzCjlResDcNmPXTEA6QUnnUDulYgKeVWysLbYKXiPTYZ1yo=','Network Rail began a project to extend platforms three and four at Bradford Interchange railway station as part of the Great North Rail Project. This work was carried out overnight to minimise disruption and was set to complete by Friday, December 7, 2018, to accommodate newer and longer trains.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a48f5069-e204-4eca-a668-417a6daf1a9e','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Tomorrow\'s Active Todmorden engagement event at Todmorden Market is cancelled. See the latest plans and share your feedback online through the Todmorden Town Deal website.','Active Todmorden engagement event at Todmorden Market is cancelled','Calderdale Next Chapter','2024-10-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/projects/active-todmorden','An engagement event for the Active Todmorden project, scheduled for October 25, 2024, at Todmorden Market, was cancelled by Calderdale Council. The announcement directed people to view the latest plans and share feedback online through the Todmorden Town Deal website.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a5a482a0-bb5a-4bd2-966d-4027d1db0661','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first pictures have been released over plans to create a new £15.4m bus station in Halifax. Following the public drop-in events, people will also have the opportunity to review the exhibition boards at Halifax Central Library from Sunday February 2 to 13 2020. Plans for a new Halifax Bus Station were submitted as part of a West Yorkshire package to the Department for Transport’s (DfT) competitive Transforming Cities Fund bidding process. A funding decision is expected from the DfT in March 2020, with all projects needing to be completed by March 2023. The Combined Authority plan to use public and stakeholder feedback to help shape plans and benchmark user satisfaction with the bus station. The redeveloped bus station will be an important transport hub and gateway into Halifax town centre, making changing between transport modes simple and improving connectivity with near level walking routes to key destinations across the town centre, such as Dean Clough, The Piece Hall and the new Halifax Sixth Form College. Councillor Jane Scullion, Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet Member for Regeneration and Resources, said: “Good connectivity and effective public transport solutions are essential in allowing more people to travel into town and cities quickly and affordably. \"The Halifax bus station redevelopment will complement other Calderdale Next Chapter projects including the transformation of Northgate, just next door, featuring a brand new sixth form centre, high quality office space and retail units. “I would encourage people to get involved and have their say either online or at the events, to ensure we can deliver a bus station that meets the needs of existing and future passengers.” People are being asked to comment on the plans for the new facility which is due to be completed by 2023. [23]','First look at £15.4m design for new state-of-the-art Halifax bus station','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-01-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQENwcTullqIryZoqeEKDsEXiwloguPR_ywu9hDilLiZuAZ22SIBpOvBFNDDfrjZiamF4VozeyaNkcMKavFTNDd6-KlDWdyMj3VdSrtIObppQdAk10UUBIq3yrb1dOE3nn1HHW3eyvkxwvjgeNMX6hNPoNlAm4_4wHUloMupbvHzJDsUCyWOIeDljQmJgfULuOLzLSTqk_sNvbBrzpxfjv5agF2cZ6ZX5hqIyzSuDhW12kc=','First pictures and plans for a new £15.4 million Halifax Bus Station were released, with public drop-in events scheduled for early 2020. This redevelopment is a significant regeneration project for the town, creating an important transport hub and gateway that will serve as the starting point for the Art and About Trail.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a5c1e353-4361-4118-bdbf-b9b7505d3ee1','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme has been in place since the flood events in 2012. It brings together a range of partners that include: Calderdale Council; Environment Agency; Canal and River Trust; Local Flood groups; Yorkshire Water; Network Rail; the voluntary sector and others. Its aim is to reduce the impact of flooding in Calderdale. Also, it is to work with local communities to build resilience against future events. [4]','Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme Established','Calderdale Council','2012-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/environment-and-planning/flooding/calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme','The Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Programme was put in place after flood events in 2012. Its aim is to reduce the impact of flooding in Calderdale and work with local communities to build resilience against future events.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a5da5cfa-ac2a-4ae3-86e2-038ee872e7d1','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We issue a number of permits for use in Calderdale for residents, non-residents and commuters. These are: Contract permits. ... Resident permits. For use in Resident Parking Zones (virtual permit.) Visitor permits. For use in Resident Permit Zones (paper permit). ... Virtual permits. These are now available for some permit types. They are quicker and easier to apply for and are more flexible in how you can use them. The benefits. Easier to apply for a permit. Manage, renew and pay online anytime, with no need to contact us. ... Our enforcement team can check if a vehicle has a permit by putting the registration number into their handheld device.','Parking permits | Calderdale Council','Calderdale Council','2025-01-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHLQ2hquDuxc2JTxPRjsRES2Jx0pSe8pXKpSbmtPArfI_SUuXZ5x2dGalnX11xtWpR2cVjqHptduWrWU-apbVuw4OIVGbXzWgBI5x7RCzXZdZ8oV1TCRQwXqg79n6Xuy7EcG3pHALK_m5Q==','This official page from Calderdale Council outlines the different types of parking permits available, including Resident Permits specifically for use in Resident Parking Zones (RPZs). It details the virtual nature of many permits, the online application process, and the benefits of virtual permits like easier application and real-time information for enforcement. It serves as a guide for residents on how to obtain and manage their parking permits.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a60e65c6-1491-49fa-aae1-9d608241b858','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At a full Combined Authority meeting on September 18, West Yorkshire council leaders will hear how the extra £40 million of funding would support key works to keep the Mass Transit project on track for spades in the ground by 2028. The work will include further technical and environmental assessments on phase one tram route options, as well as progressing the business case and preparing the plans to go before government decision-makers in the coming years. [5, 7] Regional leaders are set to approve £40 million in funding to progress detailed planning and development for Mass Transit... At the West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting on 18 September, council leaders will review how the funding will: Advance technical and environmental assessments for phase one tram routes; Develop the business case for government approval; Prepare the scheme for entry into the Government\'s Major Projects Portfolio (GMPP). [11]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority to Approve £40 Million for Mass Transit Planning and Environmental Assessments','West Leeds Dispatch / Wakefield Express / Public Sector Executive','2025-09-18 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/mass-transit-detailed-planning-and-development-to-keep-mass-transit-on-track-for-2028-start/ ; https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/combined-authority-to-discuss-extra-ps40-million-funding-towards-new-mass-transit-and-bus-franchising-project-4790013 ; https://www.publicsectorexecutive.com/articles/west-yorkshire-mass-transit-plans-set-for-green-light','Regional leaders are set to approve an additional £40 million in funding at a West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting on September 18, 2025, to advance detailed planning and development work for the Mass Transit system. This funding will support further technical and environmental assessments on phase one tram route options, progress the business case, and prepare the scheme for entry into the Government\'s Major Projects Portfolio, aiming to keep the project on track for a 2028 construction start.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a6af6040-6154-4cc9-88ec-a2aeff12ca1e','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Improved services and reliability on the Penistone line and between the five towns in the district of Wakefield as well as securing more and better rolling stock. ... The previous government already committed £48m of investment on the Penistone line but we need an additional £69 million to deliver half-hourly services between Huddersfield and Barnsley. ... Provide more frequent and quicker journeys between Huddersfield, Barnsley and Sheffield. [20]','Our requirements - West Yorkshire Combined Authority Rail Strategy','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-01-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/media/7933/wyca-rail-strategy-appendices-a-c-web.pdf','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Rail Strategy outlines key requirements for rail improvements, including enhanced services and reliability on the Penistone Line, with an additional £69 million needed to deliver half-hourly services between Huddersfield and Barnsley, beyond the already committed £48 million.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a6c74067-58f0-4134-94cd-45242de2792c','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield\'s Eastern Relief Road was \'built for housing\'. Paul Davis said: \'It was never a relief road, it was built purely to unlock all that land for building.\' Many said that traffic was already becoming an issue (Source 16).','Wakefield\'s Eastern Relief Road was \'built for housing\'','Wakefield Express','2021-09-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFdEKhHIoTfsVhpYIdm7mR4No4rsa41aSwuKSP5UMEokrv0TEIt9I3xcuNmVVi-Fyf_yj44siSCraOjJvmInuGF0tdhtCmWIa_X2ScDYxSC7OBWClmS50BGre3BKNlerokIaP2S2LObdeMGynFORYnfysnrbRtLHBb6gi0ylTu_0vg6J_MSX5TpXHK8BNHOowjoaHUUk5ZxcdAMrJZ_H7TpwbNLkZYts4CiCr3oPDG-0PJSIea1hokm_bXXCTnEEW8E8xV537o-e4zfM=','An article from September 2021 reflected on public perception of the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road, with some residents claiming it was primarily built to unlock land for housing development rather than solely for traffic relief. Concerns about existing congestion on the road were also raised.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a760a010-a391-485d-b53c-3f353a76e2eb','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Item 10g Development Committee Meeting 2 February. 2022. A646 Consultation - Email. Dear sir/madam. Proposed Highway Improvement Schemes - A646/A6033 Corridor Improvement. Programme. Calderdale Council are proposing a package of improvement measures on the A646/A6033 to improve traffic flow, reduce congestion, reduce accidents and stimulate economic growth. Some of the proposed measures in this area require new Traffic Regulation Orders and/or amendments to existing ones. ... I would welcome any comments or observations you may have by 31st January 2022.','Todmorden Town Council Meeting Discusses A646 Highway Improvement Proposals','Todmorden Town Council (Development Committee Meeting Document)','2022-02-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFhAAUUI73CELu201kxKKuRAxu6Ru1BHZMoHBuzuvXI5p1HDjwc_RbzMu8lXokWECQBkYem48GaQGTc7qH591SM7Lryw2r8Klm5ofb3E1Tr2E7508ASp45n8Tih4b529G9TNOlLP7wLpnVYif_45GftaJp5xik3knljgiuEi0r-wYW9-qb3i6YmQ5_JIovtRxv8LyZOj2gMavupiNmjbbFgVw8HFL2qch-zlSI-z35Yb3KLmQ==','Todmorden Town Council\'s Development Committee discussed proposed highway improvement schemes for the A646/A6033 by Calderdale Council. These included changes to bus and taxi lay-bys, waiting restrictions, a new zebra crossing near Castle Hill Primary School, and traffic regulation orders for various streets. Comments on these proposals were welcomed by January 31, 2022.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a804b7a1-cf48-4eee-b2b7-7beba97e0f91','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The latest stage of the Castleford Growth Corridor scheme is now underway, with the demolition of buildings on Aire Street to allow for the construction of a separate cycle way and pedestrian route along the entire northern side of Savile Road from the roundabout. It will also provide an additional pedestrian crossing and allow modification to the existing junctions on the roundabout. [4]','Demolition starts in Castleford as part of growth corridor scheme','Wakefield Express','2024-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/demolition-starts-in-castleford-as-part-of-growth-corridor-scheme-4559491','Demolition of buildings on Aire Street in Castleford began as part of the Castleford Growth Corridor scheme. This phase aims to create a separate cycleway and pedestrian route along Savile Road and modify existing junctions, enhancing connections between Fryston, Airedale, and Castleford town centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a83f049d-6227-4293-a311-8a875cdf0bdc','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority in collaboration with partner councils are developing a mass transit system... The purpose of this commission is to undertake Environmental Impact Assessments and produce an Environmental Statement to support the West Yorkshire Mass Transit programme. Jacobs (London) was awarded a contract valued at £10,000,000. [25]','Environmental Impact Commission (Mass Transit) [Award]','Find a Tender / WEST YORKSHIRE COMBINED AUTHORITY','2023-08-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.find-tender.service.gov.uk/Notice/025313-2023','West Yorkshire Combined Authority awarded a £10M contract to Jacobs for undertaking Environmental Impact Assessments and producing an Environmental Statement to support the West Yorkshire Mass Transit programme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a842e133-190f-4582-9298-e67d84c8ff40','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Hundreds more households will soon enjoy more affordable, reliable, and lower carbon heating with three tower blocks set to become the latest to connect to the city\'s flagship Leeds PIPES district heating network. Two hundred and fifty-nine council properties in Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers will be set up to receive heat from the network within the next six months. The new connections are expected to reduce the city\'s annual carbon footprint by 279 tonnes, supporting efforts to end the city\'s contribution to climate change by transitioning to \'net zero\' emissions. Leeds City Council estimates that the network, delivered in partnership with Vital Energi, is helping existing customers to collectively save nearly half a million pounds (£490,000) in reduced energy costs this year alone.','Hundreds more households in Leeds to benefit from low carbon heat network','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2023-12-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/newsroom/housing/hundreds-more-households-in-leeds-to-benefit-from-low-carbon-heat-network','Leeds City Council announced that 259 council properties in Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers were set to be connected to the Leeds PIPES district heating network within the next six months. This expansion aims to provide more affordable, reliable, and lower carbon heating, reducing the city\'s annual carbon footprint by an estimated 279 tonnes. The project is delivered in partnership with Vital Energi.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a8573f29-513e-427c-93b5-7ebb3c365763','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'March 2024 We\'ve appointed local artist Talya Baldwin to create the illustrations for the Art and About Trail map. We\'re working in partnership with Everybody Arts to develop public art commissions for the trail. As part of this project, they are working with the local community to design a new moquette fabric to be displayed at Halifax Bus Station. [5]','Art and About Trail - Halifax Future High Streets Progress Update (March 2024)','Calderdale Next Chapter','2024-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE52u-ZW_XL3oBA49P5C3370IQ3e1mQVcB0nsT2QCAeWna-dZn7CLZHRsBdX3ENPfhJj8Wv68nvPMV6M93GHaFoB1FSLJBGHNpAo25UDUZhyupShunGGmYW9qPBGCSXCOp9rRYYE7jGxbDff__pnlTfXFjA53SedgPzwgNK3jBs2NsBPKdFiQpoRdx1rm6GxZHHU3arbQ8M','An update on the Art and About Trail project states that local artist Talya Baldwin was appointed in March 2024 to create illustrations for the trail map. This update also mentions the ongoing partnership with Everybody Arts to develop public art commissions, including a new moquette fabric designed with community input for display at Halifax Bus Station.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a8ad47a2-2db6-4301-afc6-7a5c25270f5b','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A popular section of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton and Liversedge is set to undergo major improvements this summer. The project is funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund. Kirklees Council and the charity Sustrans will work together to upgrade accessibility, lighting and surfacing on a 2km (1.5-mile) section of the Greenway between Tesco supermarket, Cleckheaton and Knowler Hill Tunnel at Liversedge. ... Work is due to start from Monday 9 June and is expected to take around six months to complete.','Spen Valley Greenway gets the green light for exciting upgrade - Kirklees Together','Kirklees Together','2025-06-04 00:00:00.000','https://kirkleestogether.co.uk/2025/06/04/spen-valley-greenway-gets-the-green-light-for-exciting-upgrade/','An announcement from Kirklees Together stated that a major upgrade to a 2km section of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton and Liversedge would begin on June 9, 2025. The improvements, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund, include resurfacing, widening, improved lighting, and better access points, with the section expected to be closed for approximately six months.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a8c1151f-4dfb-49fc-8f68-7069f392fbcb','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'GMI Construction Group has secured a £27m contract to expand Leeds City College\'s new Mabgate campus. The project will transform the once derelict site into around 70,000 sq ft of educational space. [9] Partial demolition of existing buildings fronting onto Mabgate is underway to make way for the construction of the five-storey campus for University Centre Leeds and a new building for Leeds City College\'s English for speakers of other languages (ESOL) centre. [9] In addition to the construction of the new facilities, GMI will also undertake the refurbishment of the historic building, Studio 24, which is a popular arts and events space located within a former industrial building. [13]','GMI Construction secures £27m contract for Mabgate Campus expansion; demolition begins','Construction Enquirer News / GMI Construction Group Ltd','2023-11-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFJtKDKNMb-iie9MGmro3W27MIEwDBqOv6O7PdmqWxIna9k-xHsKKE9IxVYdkhaV5xsrxKB_A_NTTSFmJFd89YMPpu1LYRhtl_v5uvdsoUso6kU0GlZIuh7bChNy4LIXt4M8eJ2IGN1KHbitTXjJgsUNKzk1oaIZ3__DL2-M3ZuVTsuYz5qRcrxYEwilorcty0Z','GMI Construction Group Ltd secured a £27 million contract to expand Leeds City College\'s new Mabgate campus. The project involves partial demolition of existing buildings to make way for a five-storey campus for University Centre Leeds and a new building for English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL) provision, along with the refurbishment of Studio 24. Works commenced in November 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a8cdc383-c888-4c1a-bdb9-1563b8bf778f','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'shed7 said: There is also a pre-app for a huge 400,000sqft+ 17+ floor office on Wellington Street. It states 18 storeys which would be massive. The developer is McLaren Property. \"It is likely that the building would be heavily glazed within an elegant brick grid presenting a balanced, high quality, elevational treatment.\" :cheers:\n...New thread for this major office proposal. Pre-application presentation to be made to the planning panel on 6th Dec 2018.','Wellington Square | Residential and office | 139m | 45fl, 15fl, 14fl | 23/00608/FU','SkyscraperCity Forum (referencing Leeds City Council documents)','2018-12-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEejppQdeScDkWkTx9E3q5wZFrY7O3unXsyDv-3Jurx1FC5952Vsh6axSHCQucyZVhweqaBoIJIsNxi-JkoRxdTD0qtNixw3Q1kxoyOeiK6FZwuel0RMKSfUdDekKGN1qfwJJeI5PdccAcLeE2asuLfHSt7EPk3Xc9obgZ3JKITdJHOsdlQJMZF-C9qdamMYQABwsHCBNZWoNhPt2rQVOIoeLSCioiGtbX773bvOR8ZYesh-w==','Early forum discussions referenced a pre-application presentation to be made to the Leeds City Council planning panel on 6th Dec 2018 for a McLaren Property development on Wellington Street. This indicates initial concepts for a large-scale mixed-use development, including a tall office building and later a 45-storey residential tower in the area. [10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a8e93bf9-1ff6-4d64-8d69-5ae942ae9090','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bus franchising could be introduced in West Yorkshire from June 2026, with a decision on whether such an avenue will be followed due to be made by Mayor Tracy Brabin on 14 March 2024. ... Details of the franchising proposals are within documents including a consultation that were published by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) on 10 October. It believes that reregulation of services in the conurbation is the best way to deliver improvements. ... The consultation closes on 7 January 2024.','West Yorkshire bus franchising plans revealed as consultation is go','RouteONE magazine','2023-10-11 00:00:00.000','https://route-one.net/news/west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-plans-revealed-as-consultation-is-go/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) launched a public consultation on its bus franchising proposals, running from October 10, 2023, to January 7, 2024. This marked a significant step towards potentially re-regulating bus services in the region, with the intention of a mayoral decision in March 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a8f25a49-4b45-4a8b-8745-cf662f683040','infrastructure-a638-doncaster-road-corridor-improvement-programme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.997','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Council is proposing improvements on the A638 Doncaster Road between Chantry Bridge and Heath Common to improve travel for all along this key corridor linking the city with the eastern areas of the district. Benefits: Better journey times and improved reliability for buses. More people using public transport. More people walking and cycling to encourage healthier lifestyles. Reduced carbon emissions from vehicles and improved air quality. Easier access to education, employment and skills-based training facilities. Proposals: Bus lane improvement, A655 Black Road/A638 Doncaster Road junction at Heath Common. Provide new lay-bys for bus stops on Doncaster Road. Better access to selected bus stops from nearby residential areas. New \'Toucan\' crossings at Sugar Lane and near the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road. New or improved cycle route from Agbrigg Road through Belle Vue to the riverside. Progress: A consultation is to be held from 21 June to 18 July 2021. The results will be published in September and, subject to Cabinet approval, works will start in 2023 and be completed in 2024. Funding: Funding of £6.7 million has been allocated by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','Corridor Improvement Programme - A638 Doncaster Road - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2021-06-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/transport-and-streets/transport-plans-and-programmes/corridor-improvement-programme-a638-doncaster-road','Wakefield Council detailed its proposals for improvements on the A638 Doncaster Road between Chantry Bridge and Heath Common, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. The plans aimed to enhance journey times and reliability for buses, encourage walking and cycling, reduce emissions, and improve access to amenities. A public consultation was scheduled from June 21 to July 18, 2021, with results due in September 2021 and works projected for 2023-2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a999a814-ca6c-456c-a64c-e97d5f8afc89','infrastructure-north-halifax-streets-for-people-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.173','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'11 December 2023. You can now read the North Halifax Improved Streets for People public engagement report 2023 to find out about our last consultation, what people told us, and how we\'ve responded. [4, 5] Revised plans for the North Halifax Improved Streets for People project will be on display at a community information event on Wednesday 13 December 2023 from 3 - 7 pm at Forest Cottage on Cousin Lane. [4]','North Halifax Improved Streets for People Public Engagement Report 2023 and Community Information Event','Calderdale Next Chapter - North Halifax Improved Streets for People, North Halifax Improved Streets for People public engagement report 2023','2023-12-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHSGqBROegSMIkY6t3wjo-PoPYWhsFZ8FkhXGNJz6aVcRqhkJI5ATkqf8LoQNu78z5TjD2E3er-JOG2El0Rh2JOIe4kvHb8QzRbdMUr6iC1gnE8y4LKSCIRY2YjhfQHv6K2aoC8O-DVqokCxs57IqWoqQBhY1-F78k5OdQLLcpx-7ARjaSP60TIh-njK2BQNv0, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE8V9bcUaJYK97bxJSeaNHz1CfZzfc0hzXlAHxxiVagS_iJf-O4RMdV1-V2Z8aQxEXSBRRmSLl1wx7An22hUAznpmY7J5JaWSR9tyTWGiFE95qpN4uZEWnVq4uCf_Cz3ERDQ95nZOeW_g6xCkWOqj6G39cchC6QDUISrWCMaCjB95-YIUashgHoSCmtvma-iB-zxKokgx3NJCyHvBMBnTyxz7UDDI30f7Ckogs=','On December 11, 2023, Calderdale Council released the North Halifax Improved Streets for People public engagement report for 2023. This was followed by a community information event on December 13, 2023, where revised plans, incorporating feedback from previous consultations, were displayed to the public.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a9d1159b-a1cc-4571-90a8-18f46d744a6f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (CA) has opened its \'dynamic market\' for potential franchised bus services. The technical procurement process sets out criteria for any bus companies looking to bid to run services throughout the region. ... A newly-proposed, West Yorkshire-wide franchised network will aim to see bus fares, routes and timetables set by the CA, with bus operators accepted and registered onto the dynamic market invited to bid for contracts to run services. ... The CA has stated it hopes the first contracts will be awarded in Spring/Summer 2026, with a start in 2027.','West Yorkshire CA Opens Dynamic Market for Franchised Services','Bus-News','2025-08-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.bus-news.com/news/west-yorkshire-ca-opens-dynamic-market-for-franchised-services/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) officially opened its \'dynamic market\' for bus companies interested in bidding for contracts to run franchised services across the region. This technical procurement process is a crucial step in implementing the new publicly controlled bus network, with the first contracts expected to be awarded in Spring/Summer 2026 for a 2027 start.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('a9e6fdfb-a710-456e-8f40-01c813f4bc66','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-calderdale-future-phases',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.114','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to spend around £200m on bringing a mass transit system to West Yorkshire are set for approval. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority has not localised route, expected to cost more than £2bn and be fully operational in 2040, or decided whether tram-trains or prioritised routes of electric buses will be used. The organisation, run by West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin and council leaders, is expected to sign off plans to invest £199.9m on “development and initial delivery” over the next five years. If approved, the money will be taken from the £830m City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, provided by the Government. The combined authority is also working on a business case and aiming to submit it to the Department for Transport before the end of the year. It is currently exploring plans for a network, consisting of nine lines, that links towns and cities across West Yorkshire, including Leeds, Bradford, Halifax, Huddersfield and Wakefield. The Government reaffirmed its commitment to the project and said the first services will be “operational in the second half of this decade”.','West Yorkshire mass transit: £200m for \'development and initial delivery\'','Halifax Courier','2022-03-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHfUvlx9skMvNhyZClsgISqaA99NpYc7hzGOF5__BPabQT6kZIEGIRACgUBLfid3qJ80BoaxnNT88Lqw8Pa95HKoVkj34y6legAv1-KWgw_l4Te8WxpdGQxFExL_sYu-mVARZ9ukHgyEhSIYnCiokB8TwgYwg2GEBxPMgyZzpUH7MDC-Jv-nqgMPFaOaGX4vZrLgbVuVcFlNokaX7UBCV5Mkw8Ld13ENbU_F__Cuw-ZkibP0fvo7DorxfE','Plans to spend around £200m on bringing a mass transit system to West Yorkshire were set for approval. This initial funding, from the £830m City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, was allocated for development and initial delivery over five years. The project aims to link towns and cities across West Yorkshire, including Leeds, Bradford, Halifax, Huddersfield, and Wakefield, with a full operational target of 2040. The exact routes and mode (tram-trains or electric buses) had not yet been finalised.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aa1dfbde-46dc-49c1-aabe-186d66b5b303','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to transform travel and public spaces in and around Halifax town centre are moving forward, with Calderdale Council appointing the construction contractor to carry out the works. Read: Contractor appointed for major Halifax town centre improvements. 13 November 2023. Back in February and March 2023 the public were invited to examine proposals for changes to traffic regulations as part of the A629 phase 2 Halifax town centre project. [9]','Contractor appointed for major Halifax town centre improvements','Calderdale Next Chapter (Calderdale Council)','2023-11-13 00:00:00.000','https://calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/projects/a629-halifax-town-centre','Calderdale Council announced the appointment of a construction contractor for the A629 phase 2 Halifax town centre project. This milestone followed public invitations in early 2023 to examine proposals for changes to traffic regulations as part of the project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aa20d47f-79d5-4b40-90a4-47105e6918dc','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A group of operators in West Yorkshire, including the three largest in Arriva, First Bus and Transdev Blazefield, have come out against bus franchising proposals for the region and instead put forward a plan for reform that they term Enhanced Partnership Plus. The operators are campaigning under a tagline of The Best for West Yorkshire to oppose long-expected reregulation plans. Those include a formal consultation and were published by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) on 10 October. [19]','Operators propose EP Plus to deliver West Yorkshire bus reform - RouteONE magazine','RouteONE magazine','2023-10-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFZyoamgOnjf7-1A50bapsBUhOfp7RaOlWjEZNW62WasvEk3_hqu1nv9N9zmKnkk8omMLyQwOWiEGQm4kdgC-ufpENoEUdf3HjVrKqUWlpx4RJJd8aKwIZ0aT-1XavQ_aHKBqi2wN_wVCclcSCd7oAwipLI-OyiyhgJAKxoUbQGcWWwJZhmWg_sNP8VHMPPJnlTXJ7Qu_sHDlQ','A group of bus operators in West Yorkshire, including Arriva, put forward an \'Enhanced Partnership Plus\' proposal in opposition to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) franchising plans. This document outlines the alternative strategy for bus reform, aiming for quicker improvements and less financial risk compared to franchising, ahead of Mayor Tracy Brabin\'s decision on bus reform. [19]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aa468b68-0716-44b1-9f4e-6fb04efb79da','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The information below was presented during the public consultation between Monday 15 March to Sunday 25 April 2021. Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, are working together to deliver improvements to walking in West Halifax which aim to benefit residents, businesses and visitors alike. Options being considered include traffic calming measures, and general improvements to pavements and public space, which will help make streets in West Halifax greener, healthier and more attractive.','First Public Consultation on West Halifax Improved Streets for People Proposals','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEgs4bS06bSbnYtT8lRz2h_dPFqCcM5XwbhDy-EeBelfelztQeXHwJPN4kCR1iLfaWJ_tQ93c4ZzpMF7RV0j6cVx1GxJbg2bSmnjkQ_C1uy-cSe6jLgRh_azbu-mR8NoDaeOgLiLB6USOU5BVNqV7lQ1vHQ==','Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, held an early public consultation to gather feedback on initial ideas for improving walking, cycling, and public transport access in West Halifax. This consultation aimed to shape the development of more detailed proposals, considering options such as traffic calming, pavement improvements, and public space enhancements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aa5a1c84-e486-461d-8720-2a5aa5c07f30','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BT\'s Digital Voice Roadshow comes to Bradford. Throughout August, BT are heading to towns and cities across Yorkshire to speak to people about what Digital Voice is, why the change is necessary and what it means for customers. ... Come and speak to the team at their drop in sessions in Bradford: Dates: 21th, 22nd & 23rd August. Venue: BT Truck – Bradford – City Park, BD1 1HY. [7]','Digital Voice - BT\'s new home phone service - Cost of Living Bradford','Cost of Living Bradford','2023-08-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGYm_e7S4xzmpKLV-yuTP7267jymYOGb2xv0pktsQtp9xtBZZGYFfXoDA9NnHQHDnApMO3HTjpHxiF8wvcF-gVEiRThJqnvP7we_sI3hQN43yLNmUO41hc7WZ5ei6BpVvzNz3yACo3Qis2Qxcwrim1Aeh2exBGozzOf_0qnVu70qCHsOFsr7uGpxF61ysAS_erw5Q==','BT introduced its new home phone service, Digital Voice, in Bradford. As part of a regional roadshow across Yorkshire, BT\'s truck visited Bradford\'s City Park to explain the changes to customers. The analogue network is being switched off by 2025, with the new service running on broadband.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aa7e2ce8-e65a-4620-ab5a-e17577a93cdd','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water has appointed seven contract partners to its new complex non-infrastructure works framework, worth £850m, which covers the 2025 – 2030 delivery period (AMP8). The partners have been selected across the framework to deliver on the utility\'s increased investment in non-infrastructure clean and wastewater assets over the next five years. Partners selected onto the framework are Barhale, Galliford Try, Glanua, Kier, Mott MacDonald Bentley, Tilbury Douglas, and Ward & Burke. [18]','Yorkshire Water appoints seven contractors for non-infrastructure works','H2O Global News','2025-01-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.h2oglobalnews.com/yorkshire-waters-850m-non-infrastructure-framework-2025-2030/','Yorkshire Water appointed seven contract partners to its new complex non-infrastructure works framework, valued at £850 million, covering the 2025-2030 (AMP8) delivery period. The selected partners (Barhale, Galliford Try, Glanua, Kier, Mott MacDonald Bentley, Tilbury Douglas, and Ward & Burke) will provide civil engineering, mechanical, electrical, instrumentation, control and automation, and building expertise to support increased investment in clean water and wastewater networks.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aaa70a7a-7ac3-4bdf-b51c-4a7f53f11f8b','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Address: Moor Lane, Netherton, Moor Lane, Huddersfield, West Yorkshire, HD4 7HF. Local authority: Kirklees (382). ... Diocese: Diocese of Leeds (ce).','South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School - GOV.UK','GOV.UK','2025-02-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/107734','This is the official GOV.UK page for South Crosland C of E Voluntary Aided Junior School, providing details such as URN, address, local authority (Kirklees), and diocese (Diocese of Leeds). This confirms the school\'s identity and its affiliation with the Diocese of Leeds, which is the grant recipient.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aae13124-5367-4c1e-b306-c04594d408eb','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council plans to install more electric charging points across the district after recent data showed existing rapid chargers have been used almost 9,000 times in the last year. The council has already installed 10 rapid chargers in the district so far, with a further six planned this year. ... The £3 million programme is the result of a successful bid for £1.98million funding from the Government\'s Office for Zero Emission Vehicles (OZEV).','Wakefield Council to install more rapid chargers after high demand - Transport + Energy','Transport + Energy','2021-04-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4DqGQv6irAzwNksxF9ozK0bWSD0N2XEHHjd8qa-R_ScGtWwU5NL9xUNfarLo03mghZUxpX06ZChJrWePCBBt_qBMv8zFVU9Kt3Z56OD4FjN83dcb6ZvvQ0d0GNLqniClPUGR9IGSKL4312OO7IjSS7MyAonfzNNAONyD62hEsb42VZctepYenTsHO36LicxvgQ1viKCUJ_5fVuERTtsQwz7JNLUsExiQ','Wakefield Council announced plans to expand its network of rapid EV charging points across the district, in partnership with West Yorkshire Combined Authority and ENGIE. This followed significant demand for existing chargers, with a £3 million programme aimed at increasing accessibility.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ab97000f-5d5a-400a-9aba-437ab334fcdf','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-places-scheme-cornholme-a646-active-travel',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.168','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Go straight to Cornholme pedestrian improvements on Your Voice to share your feedback on the proposals for Calderdale. ... The information below was presented during the public consultation between 19 March to 30 April 2025. ... About the scheme. The West Yorkshire Places project aims to help create safer, healthier and better-connected streets in Cornholme. We have identified current issues along the A646 Burnley Road with a lack of safe crossing points, long stretches without a footpath and unenclosed livestock in the village. This has created a difficult environment for walking, cycling and wheeling ... This is particularly the case around Cornholme Junior and Infant School and Vale Baptist Church. ... This scheme suggests installing new crossings, creating new stretches of footpath along Burnley Road and potentially installing a new cattle grid. These measures would improve connectivity and safety across Burnley Road.','Cornholme pedestrian improvements - Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Consultation Launch)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice platform)','2025-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHQbBY3CDeX7hEFdUK_vtYVSdD9Ce_n9xxUUpEMCO-rEtUVsjonNOkkeThwlBppiTo_ybj820khGUASAxWeidDViRP5JFzJQC-7Slo8Qv1R-y97jDRKNC0Dg5NEjpY-Qp3GOnV1wXQbRYc3T7aSXxJV5wFY-KrMPXc=','This is the official consultation page for the Cornholme pedestrian improvements as part of the West Yorkshire Places project. It states that the consultation for Calderdale (including Cornholme) launched on March 19, 2025. It outlines the project\'s aim to create safer, healthier, and better-connected streets by addressing issues like a lack of safe crossing points and footpaths along the A646 Burnley Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ac0250ea-f5e7-4e78-870d-f8fdeaa857b2','infrastructure-north-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.153','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'To help us understand why people don\'t choose to walk or cycle, in September 2020 Calderdale Council asked people in North Halifax to fill in a \'Streets for People\' engagement survey. It asked how people felt about getting around the streets in their area, and hundreds of people took part. [3]','\'Streets for People\' Engagement Survey in North Halifax','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Your Voice / Calderdale Next Chapter','2020-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE_IuYxvpcbgj-96HFZRrmod8s1dDnpHYSzYQaMnKRZFEUARqy1_26oeH_DJQANRSesS3F8vTcCWvpxaIaRb4O5-yhoJCel7UwHyhPVg6TiTrFG0QP1BBZR3yrYJwKXXIZaj9olUIVzhrHDqbQkZnrow1c=','Calderdale Council initiated a \'Streets for People\' engagement survey in North Halifax to gather residents\' views on barriers to walking and cycling, aiming to inform the early development of the project. Hundreds of people participated in this survey. [3, 6, 8, 10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ac06d68a-35ef-43f1-8e96-457f1db27644','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-enquire-learning-trust-buckingham-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.379','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme opened for applications at 2pm on Wednesday 6 October 2021, with scheme guidance published on Wednesday 8 September 2021. The Application Portal closed four weeks later at 2pm on Wednesday 3 November 2021. [5]','PSDS Phase 3a Application Window Closes','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme - Salix Finance','2021-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEmzZpEK9xAa7UShbWbQjAxMzmLbrRrtnTsK9VirinZmaBGSP9v-g-F4VPuTB88jBWmD40rbif9EWpuld8YqERlMkwGPhWU_qpQvjmJqLny5fVDluIpe3y4qh2S0RRf17LDWkTN56kCSxOjz7uN2_ZHUzSAQ6x1uFA7LtW_Csti8Usxidz_3rqlcgcUbPmsnof867BxnOxMvtHVZqdqdA==','The application portal for Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme closed on 3 November 2021, marking the end of the submission period for projects seeking funding for heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ac41a3d9-e04d-444f-8e9e-b8ffe119ab4c','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet has just approved the sale of land in Almondbury for housing development, despite objections from 84 residents. The land, on Fenay Lane, is owned by the council and has the capacity to deliver around 160 new homes. The site was allocated for housing in the council\'s Local Plan in 2019 and was identified in the local authority\'s housing growth strategy, which was approved by Cabinet in November last  ...','Council ignores 84 objectors to sell off Almondbury land for 160 houses','Yorkshire Live','2024-01-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/local-news/council-ignores-84-objectors-sell-28503886','Yorkshire Live reported on Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet approving the sale of Fenay Lane land for a housing development, despite 84 resident objections. The site, allocated in the council\'s Local Plan, is expected to deliver around 160 homes, contributing to the council\'s target of 2,000 new homes by 2030. Concerns from residents included loss of green space, flood risk, and traffic issues.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ac8b564d-0e66-4bdf-bf25-edb66f3c08e8','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle (EV) charging points are set to be installed across the Wakefield district after senior councillors agreed to accept £1.5m of funding. The project supports local authorities in England to install public charge points for residents without access to private parking. It also aims to improve the roll out and commercialisation of local charging infrastructure. Wakefield will receive a total £1,520,938, based on a University of Leeds study into EV charger requirements for the region. Jack Hemingway, the council\'s cabinet member for environment and climate change, said: “The number of electric vehicles on our roads continues to grow as people opt to make the switch to greener vehicles. We need to make sure there are enough publicly available charging points across our district to meet this need.”','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for EV charging points across city after study from Leeds university - Yorkshire Evening Post','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-10-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHvfsXDuMPjepiKKZ9yP-hs2ExUCwiC6TApRFxI3bItrTXFbPWKyuCwAXWmo0XSjDrf8h9Puah69GCtNyCavFV02JYmfwg-K7ysd_BY3oKd0ZMW3nzKxYEn5TGtLq9-aLx3oqbk9066qVhmYemurN7m5CeyXpvQjUevmmQWUWfq5vJ5pyzMsxUoy7jvZhNnbxwiR8roM6F5jjFTHViLGXbY63iJ7vGPs2c9vcDeXvR0NVu2DAK4PF-v4uPZD_YrP5506Hpl61uqEuCTxU6dhHVYO_yaha8yIx7rWlkA','Senior councillors in Wakefield agreed to accept £1.5 million in funding for new electric vehicle charging points across the district. The grant, from the LEVI scheme, will support local authorities in installing public charge points, particularly for residents without private parking, and improve local charging infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ac916da5-5c78-4373-a3ba-781702a4fd84','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The SimpsonHaugh Architects website for \'Leeds City One\' (now South Village) lists the project start date as 2020, with completion \'TBC\'. This refers to the masterplanning and initial design phases for the regeneration project. [19]','Leeds City One | SimpsonHaugh - Project Information Start Date','SimpsonHaugh','2020-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.simpsonhaugh.com/projects/leeds-city-one','SimpsonHaugh, the architect for the development, indicates the project\'s start date as 2020 on their project page, referring to the initial conceptual and masterplanning phases for what was then known as City One.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ac9a12c5-7e40-4fd6-8b64-270e99e6c9ff','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BAM Construction commenced the development in May 2021 on behalf of CEG and is set for full completion this summer. [8], Working for developer CEG, BAM has completed its 37,800 sq ft seven-storey office development on Globe Road, marking the first new build office to be delivered in Leeds this year. Globe Point provides next generation workspace for over 400 people and its striking flat iron design offers spectacular views across the city from the roof terrace gardens. [15]','BAM Construction Commences Globe Point Development','South Leeds Life / BAM Construction','2021-05-01 00:00:00.000','https://southleedslife.com/holbecks-globe-point-tops-out/','BAM Construction began the development of Globe Point, a seven-storey, 37,800 sq ft office building designed by Feilden Clegg Bradley Studios, marking a significant step in the Temple district\'s regeneration.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aca5b8ec-5006-4f8d-8602-e675c5095bf5','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust (LTHT) is taking another step closer to its ambition to achieve net zero carbon emissions by 2040, with support from law firm Bevan Brittan. A new heat supply agreement between the Trust and Leeds City Council will enable the supply of low carbon heat from the Leeds PIPES district heating network to the Trust\'s internal low-carbon network providing low temperature hot water to 17 buildings at St James\'s University Hospital.','St James\'s University Hospital to expand connection to Leeds PIPES district heating network','Bevan Brittan LLP','2023-05-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.bevanbrittan.com/news-and-insights/news/2023/low-carbon-network-development-at-st-james-s-university-hospital-to-be-connected-to-leeds-pipes-district-heat-network/','A new heat supply agreement between Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust and Leeds City Council, advised by Bevan Brittan, will enable the supply of low carbon heat from the Leeds PIPES district heating network to 17 buildings at St James\'s University Hospital. This builds on earlier connections and further supports the Trust\'s net zero carbon ambition by 2040.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('acb21958-c469-4329-b0a7-c9fefef6566d','infrastructure-calderdale-active-travel-programmes-general',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.183','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In February 2023, the \'Active Todmorden\' project, a £3.2 million initiative, received the go-ahead for investment from the Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities. This approval enabled the project to move forward to its design stage, with the goal of creating healthier communities by facilitating walking, wheeling, and cycling for everyday journeys and improving access to local attractions. [17]','Active Todmorden Project receives investment go-ahead','Calderdale Next Chapter','2023-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFem1d75ZnZEXV9EfWXS9u95REg87UyL3GG8g8LItpEx6x-BJGogxckAs_hfnKLGNW00YwwpYJNKdtSezt3eSXPxvL6mxxn1Tq7KXWNxRCbk8QoKysZuM6dL_o6KjiRVKwXc0EccoQ3tT2e6qLDdQQYQrNr0hooSeio6DzL','The £3.2 million \'Active Todmorden\' project received investment approval from the Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities, allowing it to proceed to the design stage. This project aims to make walking, wheeling, and cycling easier and more pleasant around Todmorden.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ad189ce8-a765-4881-91ea-16222070ba8f','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, has so far developed early-stage proposals for the Bradford City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements scheme, as well as for three other Transforming Cities Fund schemes. We want to understand the public\'s views on the proposals before progressing to the next stage of design. [8] Under the Bradford City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements proposals, new green public spaces would be formed in the city centre… To facilitate the formation of these spaces, a number of streets would be pedestrianised, removing through traffic to create a pleasant and pollution-free environment. Norfolk Gardens would be expanded out to create a major new green space, and Hall Ings would be pedestrianised from Jacobs Well roundabout to Bridge Street. Jacobs Well roundabout would be removed to allow easy crossing from the east of the city centre to the west for those who walk and cycle, linking key cultural destinations to the city\'s core. [8] The removal of Jacob\'s Well roundabout was first consulted on in 2021. [10]','Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements scheme consultation (Round 1)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-07-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/bradford-city-centre-walking-cycling-improvements-scheme','The first round of public consultation was held on early-stage proposals for the Bradford City Centre Cycling and Walking Improvements scheme from July to September 2021. The scheme aimed to reshape Bradford city centre by improving walking and cycling routes, removing traffic from some roads (e.g., Hall Ings, Market Street), and introducing new green public spaces. It also proposed the removal of Jacob\'s Well roundabout to improve pedestrian and cyclist crossings. This initial consultation sought public feedback before progressing to detailed design.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ad304a2a-22c5-4ec7-ac8d-2223c5ba149b','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Up to £22.5m could be invested in two roads connecting Leeds and Wakefield – the A61 and the A639. Leeds City Council, Wakefield Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) have developed plans to improve the two roads by: Making them easier and safer for people travelling by bus, bike or on foot; Creating faster and more reliable bus journeys; Reducing congestion and delays for car users; Reducing air pollution; Improving green spaces along the two routes. [6]','A61 and A639 could get £22 million investment to connect Leeds and Wakefield','Highways News / TheBusinessDesk.com','2022-07-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHXPqiKmKnkPJin0Sc5QTJpatCQxTdN-FBxO_ywc_FtHnws3KZ75t7qnxI2GCL1PtPyD-yNYU-tWitOFpPH-2c5t26mTkUVK5g5xDNC7Db1kaEkq7o7e9dypBWmtnwVQQb6tifAU02G1ioHtZdtlNHok9Oq2wEQ3Mn3uGLYY7hAA6UOdjkz1e0UvJiKBcN9-F91Pok9pfgWnUf6lZqe8mQI3Q==','Leeds City Council, Wakefield Council, and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced proposals for an investment of up to £22.5 million into the A61 and A639 roads. The plans aimed to make these routes safer and easier for bus, bike, and foot travel, reduce congestion, improve air quality, and enhance green spaces. This specific project funding is part of the larger Transforming Cities Fund. [6, 9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ad61fc4e-64ec-41f4-9f87-5ba658f54294','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-to-leeds-line',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.043','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Detailed proposed routes for the first phase of a new West Yorkshire mass transit network have been revealed... People are now being invited to have their say on a choice of proposed route options that will connect central and South Leeds; and Bradford with Leeds. The Bradford Line will connect people between Bradford city centre and Leeds city centre with the proposed route options aiming to connect areas like Thornbury, Laisterdyke, Pudsey, Armley and Wortley. This consultation will run until 30 September. [26], [28]','Public invited to have their say on proposed routes for West Yorkshire\'s mass transit network','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (via Unlock Net Zero)','2024-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://unlocknetzero.co.uk/blog/plans-for-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-network-launched/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched an 11-week public consultation (July 15 - September 30, 2024) on proposed route options for phase one of the Mass Transit network, including the Bradford to Leeds line, inviting feedback on connections between key communities like Thornbury, Laisterdyke, Pudsey, Armley, and Wortley.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('adc94604-743b-4ed2-8d6d-753844c6ddec','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water\'s PR24 business plan (2025–2030) centers on improving water and wastewater services across the Yorkshire region, with significant investments in environmental performance (e.g. storm overflow reduction, treatment upgrades) and customer service. As a major regional employer and investor, Yorkshire Water\'s plan will have a significant economic impact in Yorkshire. The company estimates that its 2025–2030 investment program will create around 6,000 jobs in its supply chain. [6]','Workforce Implications of UK Infrastructure Business Plans 2025','Yorkshire Precision','2025-06-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireprecision.com/green-jobs-skills-for-net-zero/workforce-implications-of-uk-infrastructure-business-plans-2025','An analysis of Yorkshire Water\'s PR24 business plan (2025–2030) highlights its focus on improving water and wastewater services, particularly through significant investments in environmental performance like storm overflow reduction. The investment program is estimated to create around 6,000 jobs in its supply chain, demonstrating a commitment to local employment and skill development within the Yorkshire region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ae63e99c-f093-4388-99d3-ef220992324b','infrastructure-home-bargains-garforth-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.429','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The strategy, which was agreed by members of the Combined Authority\'s transport committee on Wednesday, April 16, outlines investment priorities, design guidance, and an action plan. [15]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Agrees on Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-04-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGpqwKOhim6EkxY7D1nlataryKOz_-umcko7WNzcLuwT_Hn9j5RkkffnekzoqZH6ryi7UTTYeXMhk6Qxfa43VeVruQrUN3VUXE7G0EQchNxvgHaMok3BUGpc58snC6lldF4SYA8LuK2Wa6NxLMHsUg048qlpEsUjQ6nIDW7bnUu0VJw_szGTMQ1fW0DPl7A4i3anxttm89u1UMK3Jd7YDX0uVwK-_H7hFLzepo=','On April 16, 2025, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s transport committee officially agreed on its Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy. This comprehensive strategy outlines how WYCA and the five regional councils will collaborate to ensure a sufficient network of safe, reliable, and easy-to-use public EV charge points to meet future demand and support the region\'s net-zero carbon ambitions by 2038.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('aeb2fffa-1ebd-4acb-b5f4-e40407fe3e21','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £40m scheme to widen a main route in and out of Leeds is \'critical\' to cutting the number of vehicles passing through the city centre. Planned improvements to Armley Gyratory include widening roads, replacing footbridges and better signalling. The scheme, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), will be split into two phases and should be completed next year. The authority\'s finance committee agreed to release £28m to begin work.','Armley Gyratory plan critical for Leeds city centre','BBC News','2022-01-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHyGd8CEyxvESBCm-GtCVuHEgNFgkYFVfO2aaD3Fs73rdkN_-l0l4m0wuuQzS4Bw80mssv0IoOjJAsibBASeQ9sPWpD8exDiqmh2sO63fhsr7G2GVfTfKufoV9t1nW6gX-m2be9TY_Te_MHJyXCMLIEv7w=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) finance committee agreed to release £28 million for the Armley Gyratory improvement scheme. This £40 million project, funded by WYCA, was deemed critical for reducing traffic in Leeds city centre by improving the gyratory\'s capacity and routing traffic away from the city center, particularly in anticipation of closing City Square to through traffic. The scheme involved widening roads, replacing footbridges, and enhancing signaling, with completion expected by late 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('afa92ee9-4a71-4f9f-a47f-891aa6fc06fe','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Leeds City Region has won the biggest share of the Government\'s latest round of Transforming Cities Fund grant, which was announced in last week\'s Budget. The Government has awarded £317m to the Leeds City Region covering the council areas of Leeds, Bradford, York, Wakefield, Calderdale, Kirklees, Craven, Harrogate, and Selby. [15]','Transforming Cities Fund grant awards announced','TransportXtra / West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHto8oDrdc8Sp1GTD1wwaLarBrZ8wKiz2dKqPH1PiDxs8n-AIcagBK2JzWbWed_mn9bR39FkOYC3eixV2VqnD4Nb9IB_7hoQvzQyvz-RC54Aok4-Rs2VgEPsgQ34mpr3htYEKyutQopJ_wOP6R3-5sxF-qDMNbHHCPS29lA83Bde7i27QiS_mG8hHLvmV42nMhjRFAVPhXZDH0KwXaDFNJyN9ecyjVNQxNaPqY65uQBfyx8WvnB2FM=','The Leeds City Region, which includes Wakefield and Leeds, was awarded £317 million from the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund. This substantial funding underpins various transport infrastructure projects across the region, including the A61 and A639 improvements, aiming to provide accessible, attractive, and cleaner alternatives to car journeys. [15, 17]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b00e1d3f-e159-4e58-87ec-709445b069b5','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As a result of the feedback, we are focusing our efforts on developing the proposals, and as a result we have reorganised the scheme into 7 corridors which are: Lister Court; Model Village; Gibbet Street; Queens Road; Parkinson Lane; Beech Hill; Pellon Lane. There will be a public information event on Monday 20th March 2023 at the Elsie Whiteley Innovation Centre, Halifax HX1 5ER, 3-7pm, to give you the opportunity to learn more about the current scheme plans and ask any questions you may have.','Public Information Event and Reorganisation of West Halifax Scheme Corridors','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2023-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFFYOa-bPMxSqltxErYg-uE_VSOFQ9tWymRcDnV-d3Tk-LeK5qQtnC8FZiVzDpZ-614wpDnat-nyZJLVSWI4riPjMIRbaHTJpI0B9H-K6memLSfMFupxzYe1PVSLQWMgiBJso5VWqDIBbIsYbErhPlgUVaF','Following feedback from previous consultations, the West Halifax Improved Streets for People scheme was reorganised into 7 corridors: Lister Court, Model Village, Gibbet Street, Queens Road, Parkinson Lane, Beech Hill, and Pellon Lane. A public information event was held to update stakeholders on these updated plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b0b7f180-d19a-4a17-abd3-85fd3bdfa810','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Digital Enterprise has secured £4.6m funding from the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund (UKSPF), to encourage businesses in West Yorkshire to invest in digital. As the new round of funding is now live, the clock is already ticking for businesses to access the  [6]','Seven-figure funding to boost digital enterprise for West Yorkshire businesses','Bdaily','2023-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://bdaily.co.uk/articles/2023/11/01/seven-figure-funding-to-boost-digital-enterprise-for-west-yorkshire-businesses','Bdaily reported that Digital Enterprise secured £4.6 million in funding from the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund for its third program (DE3). The funding, now live, aims to encourage West Yorkshire businesses to invest in digital. The program offers Digital Accelerator Grants (up to £10k) and High Impact Grants (up to £35k) and is scheduled to end in March 2025, urging businesses to apply swiftly.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b0c8e917-87f3-4a50-b51f-decad7bc0a62','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'1 Electric Vehicle (EV) Charging Station at EV On The Move Starbucks Snowhill. Stations maintained by EV Chargers and located at Snowfield Avenue, Wakefield, West Yorkshire, WF1 2ZE, UK. ... gps_fixed. 53.696062, -1.504548. ... (2) EV On The Move 22kW ( 2 sockets )','EV On The Move Starbucks Snowhill | Snowfield Avenue, Wakefield, West Yorkshire, WF1 2ZE, UK - PlugShare','PlugShare','2021-09-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.plugshare.com/location/312061','PlugShare lists an Electric Vehicle (EV) Charging Station at Snowfield Avenue, Starbucks, Wakefield, WF1 2ZE. It specifies 1 station with 2 devices (22kW), part of the EV On The Move network, with payment options via Fuuse App or Octopus juice. The listing date on PlugShare is September 19, 2021, confirming the operational status of these chargers by this date.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b0f4dad9-9c8a-403e-87bb-27a4102af810','infrastructure-normanton-golf-club-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.339','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Normanton Golf Club charging point. This electric car charging point located at Normanton Golf Club, WF3 4JP is part of the Alfa Power network. There are 0 device and 0 connector available at this charging location. ... Network: Alfa Power. Address: Normanton Golf Club. Aberford Road, Stanley. Wakefield. Yorkshire and the Humber. WF3 4JP. ... Updated: 14th July 2025.','Normanton Golf Club EV charging point, Wakefield - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-07-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGQqkUNDv5s57A5f90wbJQrVJ3h03_ZRkUb8IW_gbuuMlMMhVzYFsZXF1CRI2X_2YUXHhRmw3w0qto5hsJKiFzX15s6YpY1HQKE8XnvmDAwkMKsxKLxKnave4s8jSq_Sz8H7Dbr9dIlJ7rJNsvJMOENTrM=','Zapmap lists an electric vehicle charging point at Normanton Golf Club, Aberford Road, Stanley, Wakefield, WF3 4JP, as part of the Alfa Power network. The listing, updated on this date, confirms the presence of EV chargers at the golf club, though it currently indicates 0 devices and 0 connectors available.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b123ea1e-23c0-4e8c-9ae6-56cf34dbc9b1','infrastructure-one-city-park',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.090','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Muse Developments, one of the UK\'s leading names in town and city-centre urban regeneration, has today (Thursday 21 October) received full planning consent for One City Park, a BREEAM \'Excellent\' 56,403 sq ft office building in the heart of Bradford city centre. Earlier this year, Bradford Council secured £7.5m of funding from the government\'s Getting Building Fund through West Yorkshire Combined Authority, to accelerate the delivery of One City Park. The development will create more than 300 jobs throughout construction, with a further 450 jobs based in the new building once complete. The estimated total project costs amount to £28.8m with £21.3m match- funding committed by the Council subject to the GBF grant. £7.5m GBF grant is requested to fund the remaining project costs and enable the viable delivery of the scheme.','Green light for Muse Developments\' landmark One City Park in Bradford / Bradford One City Park Scheme Summary','UKREiiF / Bradford One City Park Scheme Summary','2021-10-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHSq1BjdslxzJr4HqkXh63xlUW74ycAaTvZJxqViuRYhC7mREOy4_peWk0enDqxtRFzSnaiDUYqqg_c7lUc0ehVS_ySeEzjwene0CZ0Bx-QnOig8WA7m9JaJt6kDmND1-GoUGEsh5VH5MHhU0nc4GyogPpd3kivfG0ewO8AhPcU6wyC','Muse Developments received full planning consent for the One City Park project. Bradford Council had secured £7.5 million of funding from the government\'s Getting Building Fund, channeled through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, to accelerate the delivery of One City Park. The overall project costs were estimated at £28.8 million, with Bradford Council committing £21.3 million in match-funding. The development was anticipated to create over 300 construction jobs and 450 permanent jobs upon completion.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b168408a-f379-419f-97da-f0dc6e85b985','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A partnership project between the National Trust, Yorkshire Water and the Woodland Trust has announced a landmark programme of work to restore and improve the UK\'s uplands. The \'Landscapes for Water\' programme will focus on restoring five areas in the South Pennines, from Hepstonstall Moor in the north to Marsden Moor in the south, including planting 350 hectares of native trees in the small valleys, or \'cloughs\'. As well as the benefits for wildlife, the new woodland will capture carbon, improve water quality and provide flood protection for homes in the South Pennines by slowing the flow of water across the landscape. The trees will form part of the White Rose Forest. There are also plans to install 3,500 leaky dams across the five areas, which will further reduce flood risk by encouraging water to soak slowly into the landscape.','Landscape-scale programme to restore South Pennines uplands announced','Yorkshire Water','2023-03-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirewater.com/news-media/news/landscape-scale-programme-to-restore-south-pennines-uplands-announced/','A partnership between the National Trust, Yorkshire Water, and the Woodland Trust officially announced the \'Landscapes for Water\' programme. This ambitious initiative aims to restore five areas in the South Pennines, including planting 350 hectares of native trees and installing 3,500 leaky dams in the Upper Calder and Colne catchments. The primary goals are to reduce flood risk, improve habitats, enhance water quality, and capture carbon for climate resilience.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b1c087bf-babe-4cf6-adb9-2a9c00b7e8a4','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charging point located at Morrisons Wakefield, WF2 9BY is part of the GeniePoint network. There are 1 device and 3 connectors available at this charging location. Network: GeniePoint; Address: Morrisons Wakefield; Morrisons Wakefield, Dewsbury Road; Wakefield; Yorkshire and the Humber; WF2 9BY. Payment: Zap-Pay, Web App, Mobile App or RFID card; Pricing: 83p/kWh. Sources: Zapmap; Updated: 04th September 2025. Devices. Device 1 GP14195. CHAdeMO (50kW); Type 2 (22kW); CCS (50kW).','Morrisons Wakefield charging point - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-09-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.zap-map.com/charge-points/morrisons-wakefield/','This Zapmap entry provides current details for an electric car charging point at Morrisons Wakefield, Dewsbury Road, WF2 9BY. It is part of the GeniePoint network, offering one device with CHAdeMO (50kW), Type 2 (22kW), and CCS (50kW) connectors. The page was last updated on September 4, 2025, providing up-to-date information on the operational status of the charger.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b1f1d1fa-1976-4fca-b8a1-bd74908b3d6a','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds\' South Bank is set to benefit from more affordable and sustainable heating solutions after securing £24.5m in funding to extend the Leeds PIPES district heating network. This significant expansion will potentially connect up to 28 buildings, impacting around 8,000 residents and various commercial entities. This marks the largest single investment in the project since it began. [5]','Leeds\' Heat Network Expansion to Reach Thousands More with Low-Carbon Solutions','Leeds Star','2024-09-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGcllfx-WXJm_y0VbL7VrYT1wwE6VyE5e7DJuRn_NUBxzM8AC5cnMVOZEGZmD4kXfEMSIkBd90Hz3zv9Mb4NabWJc789oAH_M-G8a4Z9MDx_7cVzLOycTFSIpVtywilze6kyuJK0mw_02aSNy3HMZb31aAD5qNQXtGApgZIGLnEOcMbYqGaSruGjXc9T2892jOSDTWPCT_Qpa7iERGlq4x6zrMMofQu4g','This news article reiterates the secured £24.5m funding for the Leeds PIPES district heating network expansion in South Bank, emphasizing the project\'s aim to connect up to 28 buildings, benefiting around 8,000 residents and commercial entities. It highlights the use of heat from the city\'s non-recyclable domestic waste and its contribution to carbon emission reduction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b24386dc-bc57-49cf-876e-32fe2d6c8759','infrastructure-elland-rail-station-and-access-package-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.897','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council approved a planning application for the Elland Rail Station Access Package project on 7 November 2024. [9]','Planning approval granted for Elland Access Package','Calderdale Next Chapter','2024-11-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdalenextchapter.co.uk/projects/elland-access-package','Calderdale Council approved the planning application for the Elland Rail Station Access Package project on November 7, 2024. This package includes walking and cycling improvements and two new pedestrian and cycle bridges.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b2657f2b-aa9e-43d1-b2a2-4fbb35b80036','infrastructure-cornholme-a646-active-travel-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.620','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The consultation for Wakefield, Bradford and Calderdale launched yesterday (Wednesday 19th March), with Kirklees starting on Tuesday 1st April, each lasting for six weeks. ... The information below was presented during the public consultation between 19 March to 30 April 2025. About the scheme. The West Yorkshire Places project aims to help create safer, healthier and better-connected streets in Cornholme. We have identified current issues along the A646 Burnley Road with a lack of safe crossing points, long stretches without a footpath and unenclosed livestock in the village. [6, 7]','Public consultation launched for Cornholme pedestrian improvements','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/cornholme','The public consultation for the Cornholme A646 Active Travel Improvements, part of the wider West Yorkshire Places scheme, was launched. This initiative invited residents to provide feedback on proposals aimed at creating safer and better-connected streets, particularly addressing concerns along the A646 Burnley Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b2cc0267-bf9a-4a12-bb04-80b26e4d92ce','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In addition, a successful bid in 2024 to the Department for Transport (DfT) resulted in the council being allocated £500,000 from the Green Light Fund (GLF) for traffic signal improvements which is focussing on the A62 Corridor at Cooper Bridge.','Highways Capital Plan 2025-27 Includes A62 Cooper Bridge Traffic Signal Improvements','Kirklees Together','2025-05-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEvSmb4HHd0ffkiPf6eEU6gInVPQiKlukFe5d7AnoVhfUTD4199QhLII15RwQTawQLVK6_dcbxadDsOV7xkZkiyjAUBZfQUX_bsp-XPyX0SB0IipyfM67IZNyEWuLRRqVfaWbihswfzfOxCu7l5N6_jJ4RO0xxQAEuYjoFKyfK4gbBFjDVS2hmIM-aZzo63UXRZm9l5zgrn0w==','Kirklees Council\'s Highways Capital Plan for 2025-27, approved in May 2025, includes an allocation of £500,000 from the Department for Transport\'s Green Light Fund (GLF) specifically for traffic signal improvements along the A62 Corridor at Cooper Bridge. [15]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b2ce9e69-b023-4b73-918f-5715e4875f47','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A statutory consultation was held between 17 October 2022 to 16 January 2023 on the revised West Yorkshire Mass Transit 2040 Vision ahead of the final Vision being formally approved and implemented. We invited statutory consultees, key stakeholders and members of the public to share their views on the revised Vision. We received 240 survey responses and numerous letters and emails. We are currently analysing these responses and an outcome report will be publish on this page once available. [19]','West Yorkshire Mass Transit Vision 2040 Statutory Consultation','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2022-10-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/mass-transit-vision-2040','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority conducted a statutory consultation on the revised Mass Transit Vision 2040. This consultation aimed to gather feedback from statutory consultees, key stakeholders, and the public on the long-term vision for the mass transit system before its formal approval and implementation. Responses were used to shape the updated Vision document.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b31055bf-40dd-42f7-b21c-2899704c4fed','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Our Flood Action Plan sets out the actions that we will take to recover from past floods, reduce the impact of flooding and build resilience for future events. The Plan, initially published in October 2016, is a dynamic \'living document\' that has undergone multiple updates to incorporate completed, revised, and new actions. [5]','Calderdale Flood Action Plan Initially Published','Calderdale Council (Eye on Calderdale)','2016-10-31 00:00:00.000','https://eyeoncalderdale.com/calderdale-flood-action-plan','The Calderdale Flood Action Plan, a dynamic \'living document\' outlining a comprehensive program of work to help the area recover from past floods and build resilience, was initially published in October 2016.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b318c767-10d3-4e87-9d3b-a6603d13095e','infrastructure-bus-lane-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.094','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Civil enforcement of Calderdale\'s bus lanes, resulting in fines for drivers breaking the rules, will be going ahead. ... It is intended capital costs can be funded through the West Yorkshire Transport Fund.','Bid to halt Calderdale Council bus lane camera plan fails','Halifax Courier','2018-08-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/bid-halt-calderdale-council-bus-lane-camera-plan-fails-1-9304958','A challenge to Calderdale Council\'s decision to implement civil enforcement of bus lanes, including the use of ANPR cameras, was unsuccessful. The plan, which aims to improve traffic flow and encourage public transport use, was confirmed to be going ahead. Capital costs were intended to be funded through the West Yorkshire Transport Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b34059b1-5474-4355-8269-f85a4425680d','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kings Road Connect. This consultation has closed. The Kings Road Outcome Report has been published and you can read it here: Kings Road Consultation Report. About the scheme. Kings Road is an important part of the Bradford district\'s transport network. It connects communities such as Five Lane Ends, Swain House and Ashbourne, providing access to schools, shopping and amenities along the route and access to Bradford city centre via Canal Road. The scheme is expected to cost around £35 million and, if approved, would be funded by the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) to transform this vital 2-mile route. Key Dates: Consultation opens. 03 February 2025. Proposed measures include: New bus lanes and bus priority at key junctions to keep buses moving and improve journey times and service reliability, while keeping general traffic flowing. Improvements to bus stops with new shelters, upgraded seating and real time information to help people travel with comfort and confidence. New segregated cycle lanes for better connectivity to other cycle routes in the Bradford district, making cycling more attractive, reliable, and safer. Widened pavements and new crossings for pedestrians, making walking and wheeling safer and more enjoyable. Reduced speed limits from 40mph to 30mph to create a consistent speed along the route, improving traffic flow and road safety for all.','Kings Road Connect | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Consultation Open)','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice)','2025-02-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEt0AZS1G9kfBi0x2KmhmMp5KbvteaImcEi8v7t63wWgbzYJncuTVIN24P1LkrhWS0l82J2qDgF4aL0Wy1sLBTTzGLHki27vtbuaWXgUtndFQHjYwlVvnHHSi5ZCftsa2HezHPlf7UQ4CCFCo4fa_bAheW3ls0Xug==','This is the official consultation page for the Kings Road Connect scheme. It states that the public consultation opened on February 3, 2025. The scheme aims to improve public transport, walking, wheeling, and cycling along the route between Five Lane Ends roundabout, Kings Road, and Canal Road. The page provides details on proposed measures including new bus lanes, improved bus stops, segregated cycle lanes, widened pavements, new crossings, and reduced speed limits from 40mph to 30mph on sections.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b34f8505-84c2-4126-a748-a71e66569019','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A MULTI BILLION pound plan to create a new mass transit system linking areas of West Yorkshire could use abandoned rail routes. ... The full network could eventually include a line linking Bradford to Baildon, Guiseley and Leeds Bradford Airport, one linking the city to Halifax, Elland and Brighouse and one linking Bradford to Dewsbury - as well as the direct Bradford to Leeds link. At a briefing by West Yorkshire Combined Authority this morning, members acknowledged that it was a long term scheme - the document says the plan is a vision for 2040. [9]','Multi billion pound mass transit system to link up West Yorkshire','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2021-01-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/18991206.multi-billion-pound-mass-transit-system-link-west-yorkshire/','Details were revealed about a multi-billion-pound mass transit scheme for West Yorkshire, presenting a vision for 2040. The full network could eventually include a line linking Bradford to Baildon, Guiseley, and Leeds Bradford Airport, as well as connections to other towns. This indicates the \'Bradford Crossrail\' and LBA link concept is being considered within a broader, long-term regional mass transit strategy, though the exact technology (tram or new technology) was undecided at this stage.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b36a0ed2-7bc9-423f-b36e-4b5eaeabd834','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-star-multi-academy-trust-monk-fryston-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.364','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A village school is taking steps to ensure they have a greener future with an overhaul of their heating system. Children at Monk Fryston CE School near Selby are to learn first hand about the benefits of renewable energy. The school has been awarded a grant from the government\'s Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme to remove the existing fossil fuel gas boilers and install a greener ground source heat pump. Work on the installation of a heat pump at the primary school should commence at Easter and will be finished in time for the start of the new school year in September.','Monk Fryston CE primary school near Selby is going green with government grant','The York Press','2022-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/20038896.monk-fryston-ce-primary-school-near-selby-going-green/','Monk Fryston C of E Primary School was awarded a grant from the government\'s Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. The project involves removing existing fossil fuel gas boilers and installing a ground source heat pump. Work was expected to commence at Easter and be completed by September.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b36bcfc5-eca5-427f-8a6b-53361187970c','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Electric mobility has taken another huge leap forward thanks to significant investment in the UK\'s charging network that will make it easier than ever to own and run an electric car. As part of the £37m scheme, the UK Government has announced that it will contribute 75% to the cost of an installed charger at a home address anywhere in the UK. As well as the home charging bonus, the Government has announced some other major benefits for the entire charging network. ... The announcement comes with production of the 100% electric Nissan LEAF and a new lithium-ion battery plant set to launch at the company\'s record-breaking Sunderland Plant this spring. John Martin, Nissan\'s Senior Vice President for Manufacturing in Europe, said: \'We are at a crossroads in personal mobility. Nissan is proudly pioneering zero emission technology through our UK operations and we are delighted that the UK Government shares our commitment to the transport of the future.\'','Nissan UK Welcomes Government Investment in EV Charging Infrastructure','Nissan UK','2012-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://unitedkingdom.nissannews.com/en-GB/releases/release-130456-nissan-welcomes-the-uk-governments-commitment-to-electric-vehicle-charging-infrastructure','Nissan UK issued a press release welcoming the UK government\'s significant investment (£37m) in the electric vehicle charging network. This commitment included contributions for home and public chargers, establishing Nissan\'s early strategic focus on EV mobility and the supporting infrastructure across its dealership network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b3724bbf-04c4-4d71-aa79-e8d38aeb8644','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Sowerby Bridge is set to benefit from a share of £95m of government funding to improve its Historic High Streets. ... This £95 million will help breathe new life into high streets all over England, benefiting businesses, supporting our much-loved buildings and helping to make our communities more attractive places to live, work and visit.','Calderdale town to get share of £95m to revive its historic high street','Halifax Courier','2019-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEXptdLMQ0c-sihsJbV8yDKM6NplgWYx-jPHYA-BbzyJScDFKNIUBfgB0_Y_XY_kypEmqlHCRZBb59bLiHDyKGz9BbvYklKeNx-04xirG7AgGur110wFR4N2td9B9Zr03qNWmGe7vJLCgjZOkfgoX_-ZJnR0RsYyJIZFICqXVUEBR-SZ0d1IAgZQKbj4Nee2dSvRqOkh4G2esAVodbOFfRodwv8WMJbJtMPvt4tyUZYV7Bz99-EqV7F','Sowerby Bridge was selected to receive a share of £95 million in government funding through the High Streets Heritage Action Zone (HSHAZ) programme. This initiative aimed to revitalize historic buildings and areas within the town, combining funds from various government departments and the National Lottery Heritage Fund to support regeneration and a cultural program.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b373951f-aecc-4fc9-906c-3decd8a6016b','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water has started a £2m project on Oak Road, Bradley to reduce storm overflows into the Huddersfield Broad Canal. The work, which is being carried out by Morrison Water Services, includes the construction of a new surface water sewer in the green space off Oak Road and along Bradley Road. Highways drains in the area will be disconnected from the combined sewer and redirected into the new sewer. The surface water sewer will also take rainfall from the roofs of properties nearby. The £2m project is expected to be completed in November and will reduce discharges into the Huddersfield Broad Canal by 61%. Omair Khan, project manager at Yorkshire Water, said: “Constructing a new surface water sewer will reduce the amount of rainfall entering the combined sewer during periods of heavy or prolonged rainfall.” This project is just a small part of a £180m investment we\'re making across the region by April 2025 to reduce storm overflows into Yorkshire\'s watercourses.','£2m project underway to reduce storm overflows into Huddersfield Broad Canal','Yorkshire Water','2024-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirewater.com/news-media/2m-project-underway-to-reduce-storm-overflows-into-huddersfield-broad-canal/','Yorkshire Water has initiated a £2 million project on Oak Road, Bradley, Huddersfield, to reduce storm overflow discharges into the Huddersfield Broad Canal. The project, delivered by Morrison Water Services, involves constructing a new surface water sewer to separate rainfall from the combined sewer system. This is expected to reduce discharges from the Oak Road storm overflow by 61% and is anticipated to be completed in November.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b422cb36-cf81-4820-92df-f6f0669b87d8','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wellington Square is a new mixed-use destination with two tech-hub workplaces and a 45-storey residential tower. ... Working with McLaren Group, the new neighbourhood will be integral to the sustainable regeneration of the area, helping to unlock growth in the west of the city. The tech buildings, wrapped in red glazed terracotta tiles, will cater to the emerging green tech industry and collaboration with research institutes. ... Future workers will find homes in the form of a distinct build-to-rent tower, the \'Hexagon\', soon to become the city\'s tallest landmark. The tall and elegantly proportioned building will house unique homes with a democratic central core and exclusive hallways shared by no more than four apartments. ... Further shared amenities include co-working space and a conference hall at the base and crown of the Hexagon.','Wellington Square, Leeds - Howells','Howells Architects','2024-04-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE_DKGvtShfHIR3156xCKU2bI5xzgsfv_Sp33vm_yjpwa-wGvHqTXu6wSiNx3fCdqRLud-iSDT_-VKa3A8-SIS3VHYjPzqSB9-ZOv_NCiG-7UcV8_rYhXjP0PgAd6xFlqxketjcCOdHSSK8WLE=','Howells Architects, the designer of Wellington Square, describes the approved project as a new mixed-use destination integral to the sustainable regeneration of Leeds\' West End. It features two tech-hub workplaces and a 45-storey residential tower (\'The Hexagon\') with 464 build-to-rent homes. The tech buildings will be wrapped in red glazed terracotta tiles, while the Hexagon provides unique homes with significant amenities including a sky lounge. [6]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b42ea486-dd55-454f-8e9f-4943c36900fc','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds School Streets pilot scheme launches on Monday, 1 June, with up to six Leeds primary schools taking part. Pudsey Primrose Hill Primary School, Pudsey; Ingram Road Primary School, Holbeck; Cross Gates Primary School, Cross Gates; Thorpe Primary School, Thorpe; Clapgate Primary, Middleton; and Lane End Primary, Beeston are the first schools to take part in the pilot scheme. School Streets make roads outside schools into pedestrian and cyclist only zones at the times displayed on the signs and only during term time. This helps to reduce air pollution and keep children safe from traffic.','Council to introduce first \'School Streets\' in Leeds','Leeds City Council (via Leeds Star)','2020-05-29 00:00:00.000','https://leedsstar.co.uk/leeds-council-introduces-first-school-streets-in-leeds/','Leeds City Council announced the launch of its School Streets pilot scheme on June 1, 2020, involving six primary schools. The scheme restricts motorised traffic outside schools during pick-up and drop-off times to improve safety, reduce air pollution, and encourage active travel. Residents within the zones were issued permits, and the initiative was part of the council\'s wider response to COVID-19 to create more space for walking and cycling.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b4339796-2202-4ddc-a428-4ebedcc3d6fc','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Safer routes to schools and improvements to greenways and towpaths form part of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority’s ongoing commitment to get more people walking, wheeling and cycling in the region. The Combined Authority recently received a £12.8 million funding boost from Active Travel England – and now regional leaders have approved the schemes it will be used for. Projects include making streets around schools safer and easier to get around, with improved footways, green spaces and junctions near to Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax.','Improved walking and cycling routes for Leeds schools among plans for £12.8m Active Travel England funding','Yorkshire Evening Post','2025-08-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEwNsfcqyZbsKPlMeEdbUwMsCIU54-lzxuCvFHZ1dv2LGwJXDH0_84F1Pl3oLlrzqEKZKRbGW-5uD3G5KIQeEBRfsF7P4Z5r21PznbZSr1PAgXenQqTSDhljtiWVFixUg2cCwt3gzjNcyj7ugQvBloZgfFd6LWWXoWHbYA3xKc4jVmADVUgCeXGpP0ZqkUz0iXrnKphOeNs2L57Hu5usNHWA0Mkyj1o5-_NtD1N9asn-A==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority received a £12.8 million funding boost from Active Travel England, with regional leaders approving schemes to improve walking, wheeling, and cycling. Among these proposals are safer routes to schools, including improved footways, green spaces, and junctions near Ling Bob Primary School and Christ Church Primary School in Halifax, as part of a region-wide commitment to active travel.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b43a4330-11a3-4b13-be49-bdbd39151276','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The CMA has responded to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority Bus Reform Consultation led by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA). The CMA is a statutory consultee on bus franchising proposals in England. Franchising has the potential to deliver significant benefits to the WYCA region, the CMA\'s response explores these benefits as well as highlighting potential competition risks and mitigations to WYCA\'s proposals. The response to this consultation builds on the CMA\'s views set out in its responses to the Greater Manchester Combined Authority and the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority bus franchising consultations.','CMA response to West Yorkshire Combined Authority Bus Reform Consultation','GOV.UK','2024-01-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-response-to-west-yorkshire-combined-authority-bus-reform-consultation','The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA), a statutory consultee, published its response to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s bus reform consultation. The CMA acknowledged the potential benefits of franchising for the WYCA region while also highlighting potential competition risks and suggesting mitigations to WYCA\'s proposals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b43ca60e-68dd-4ecf-b443-6ea1d000d03a','infrastructure-ionity-leeds-skelton-lakes-ev-charging-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.372','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Electric vehicle (EV) charge point provider Ionity has installed a high-power 350kW charging station at the Leeds Skelton Lake Services, located on junction 45 of the M1. It enables EV drivers to charge their electric cars in less than 20 minutes, depending on their vehicle\'s charging capacity, using renewable energy from the Ionity High Power Charging points. The 350 kW UK charging network is future-proofed, powered by 100% renewable energy... [4]','IONITY Leeds Skelton Lake: High Power Chargers and Renewable Energy Source','AM-online','2020-04-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.am-online.com/news/ev/2020/04/14/ionity-installs-350kw-ev-charger-in-leeds','The IONITY hub at Leeds Skelton Lake Services offers 350kW CCS rapid chargers, designed for ultra-fast charging. The facility is powered by 100% renewable energy, reinforcing IONITY\'s commitment to sustainable e-mobility.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b44fab24-26f5-4603-b060-e0c55e31f577','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Quickline Communications... today unveiled the full list of communities set to benefit from its full fibre rollout over the next three years, bringing fast and reliable, gigabit-capable connectivity to a further 360,000 premises across thousands of rural communities. The programme comprises locations included in the UK Government\'s Project Gigabit rollout, which Quickline is delivering in four regions... They span West Yorkshire and the York area... targeting more than 170,000 hard-to-reach homes and businesses. [13, 25]','Quickline reveals three-year rural broadband rollout plan across Yorkshire and Lincolnshire','Quickline, Future Humber','2025-06-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGfpsnFxMQt8yRmliBb-1KipzuS4hB7iR7S5buywb9LrJfwOQpTFZ7_WTW1IJyUZktkkkrPJOXzZmwcVfNjB1qNSmNrF69NwTmRb3wryTdMmlPDDT8CmNdwynJ6iVFXRu9HvAB2siKDN_jwm7WjjiZQGc7MbXYmW3O1zlgV379oHFTQyqeIk9CFHhnkWi78hW6fGcAhsAZN-mhOsjShTOfFePCA8E16jWpz-FX6WI8l5J75lbv0n0CJ8rTxH0ycio_iaI2MnIn9aNguyuqjTuoRRBX7OIxasZ66','Quickline unveiled its comprehensive three-year rollout plan, aiming to bring gigabit-capable connectivity to 360,000 premises across thousands of rural communities in Yorkshire and Lincolnshire. This plan includes locations from the UK Government\'s Project Gigabit rollout in four regions, including West Yorkshire and the York area, targeting over 170,000 hard-to-reach homes and businesses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b4a48b68-b855-4ff7-ae3e-e077e92413c0','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin unveiled plans for a tram system, with Phase One focusing on Leeds and Bradford, aiming for construction to begin in 2028. Future phases are intended to extend to Wakefield, Kirklees, and Calderdale, supported by a £1 million development fund for the Dewsbury Line.','Mayor sets out plan for tram system as Wakefield, Calderdale and Kirklees to be part of mass transit network','Halifax Courier','2024-03-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHFz7R07gsRdfja4JKNXMD3tht8Rr0MDKRlKjqq-NW3BCE3CLyUaJf3VJZRxLwfAxnn0aO_q6XLTbspllXmOaSD7txoPhItf3ZUjo9Ohp4UaCQykK3TxzIKPZwxeIAoMjnAu-w_EE0YH-1-5U_-yJnu2T1678e7d3fjm5-rI4jGbpSI4DhedWthAi-7jICMLvW0Ngs4x5OueGjv-CYKSJl0MNyr-AnF6M3SpsTGd-ACcGRQbVJFgwFS_H8Wm_ggSx_wvPOGdrAfXeebZXC5xwG-GvP8wvMx0OkWCGUBtbZA','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin unveiled plans for a tram system, with Phase One focusing on Leeds and Bradford, aiming for construction to begin in 2028. Future phases are intended to extend to Wakefield, Kirklees, and Calderdale, supported by a £1 million development fund for the Dewsbury Line.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b50c783b-0af6-44bb-affb-34e2c4b3145e','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Get full details on planning application 24/05382/COND in Leeds, including status, dates, case officer, agents, documents and comments ... Discharge of Conditions. Wellington Plaza, Wellington Street, Leeds, LS1 4DL. LS1 4DL. Full Proposal.','Planning Application 24/05382/COND Details','Leeds City Council Planning Portal','2024-07-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG-5sFb79e3iP58pwJVsgXOT0w4rnEjGHrvx2BqQWPfUPoi_jkZJoZDoyaQHytYb2XOf-wk4z4HBFGwbgQ_lAz7CMkDWeANBO6JVlZW6zhUo6nSzPUT_ml-36Q54RDHd3Bya0eXtExFcx2rDxPmFhFNgHXx7VLCaw==','An official planning application (24/05382/COND) related to \'Wellington Plaza, Wellington Street, Leeds, LS1 4DL\' for the discharge of conditions, with an \'application received\' date of 2024-07-20, indicates ongoing administrative progress following the main planning approval. This likely relates to the Wellington Square development, given the location and project scale. [13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b545626e-e4ba-4b38-92c4-74f38f568207','infrastructure-north-halifax-streets-for-people-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.173','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The information below was presented during the public consultation between Thursday 4 November to Sunday 30 January 2022. Please note - the below consultation has now closed. [12] The scheme has previously been through three rounds of consultation in 2020, 2021 and 2022. [5]','North Halifax Improved Streets for People - Round 2 Consultation','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-11-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFKqXX6DERrmN2448hORm8M2aIvg-VE4PAeFfIqSQX90JRxREbZeCit5_BQ6RB6o3a9Ez_8ZP2urWCvKYcGi_ou1TKYJ5ffKJ4zSZDjtLrHzCkn9fYT8Qmo2W7DrFY3ZJfbspBZLwneGQKh9qTTA0KCALYKFia3TbCAiIM=','A second public consultation was launched from November 2021 to January 2022 for the North Halifax Improved Streets for People project. This consultation provided an opportunity for the public to review and offer feedback on more detailed plans and proposals for the scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b5f69f74-268e-45e3-8ea4-8ff117b2091b','infrastructure-home-bargains-garforth-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.429','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Department for Transport (DfT) are providing local authorities funding to deliver publicly accessible charge point infrastructure through the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) fund. As a result, West Yorkshire Combined Authority has been awarded grants of £15.83 million from the LEVI fund. [6] (Also referenced in [5, 7])','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Awarded £15.83 Million LEVI Funding','Kirklees Council - Council and Democracy','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH2m3kdhQwUQ8KOo1Q2ROSbcdzxBQtxInraHojmXEiguG3Kab9AyoYixMfr6li1Wa0vABfkfpEHYQzxpTebqXeU63Rox0LS252W-f8Fa6RQ4FGNg_gkKzUrOsPoaN-XWrVZw1WCZJUBXPU4j9sB4qNmc6xZhW6VNbxEcyBKXHipuVy-nA==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority was awarded grants totaling £15.83 million from the Department for Transport\'s (DfT) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) fund. This funding, announced in April 2025 (with the notice of proposed decision first published on April 3, 2025), comprises £1.5 million in Pilot funding and £14.3 million in Capital funding, designated to deliver publicly accessible charging infrastructure across West Yorkshire\'s districts, including Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b64d4482-f9d8-4522-99db-080c6b90cd5f','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Quickline was awarded a £60 million Project Gigabit contract covering 29,000 rural premises in West Yorkshire and parts of North and East Yorkshire. [15, 18, 23]','Quickline awarded second Project Gigabit contract, referencing West Yorkshire progress','Quickline, Business Up North, Growth Yorkshire','2024-04-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEngE6xxfsyzOKxl4t8ohWjAtOveH2F7c4gv7vPMres4Fike6bK5v7lOwilO_anKeHZop0bJa1Ap7Czd_SooOZ11vj9knQwNfc15hlGcwA205TIrIhcRsNOZ5wNNUxjZMGS0hS8iS1_904l2vfCdEP9vG-UFxST_pjonhH7ppREkA1R0pPR3C9kAslJiCq-pJyPgHPdDoZkBmwTdO-UNb3vUsBNpifuTYZDNA5nXg2lrXxgXGkCvLbrc5cDN5b7FT6PFjCF8j8','Quickline Communications was awarded a second Project Gigabit contract worth £44 million for South Yorkshire and parts of East Yorkshire, North Lincolnshire, and Nottinghamshire. This announcement came weeks after the £60 million West Yorkshire contract, bringing Quickline\'s total premises covered by Project Gigabit to over 60,000.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b6ae114c-f366-466d-b2c9-299e2d6bd94c','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'An outline planning application submitted by Vastint was approved in principle by Leeds City Council\'s City Plans Panel in October 2017, which provided for a phased development of up to 850 residential units, business and hotel uses, and a city park with a minimum of 2 hectares (4.9 acres) of public realm. [2]','Outline Planning Application Approved in Principle for Aire Park (formerly \'city park\')','Wikipedia / Vastint UK','2017-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aire_Park','An outline planning application for the development, including up to 850 residential units, business and hotel uses, and a city park, was approved in principle by Leeds City Council\'s City Plans Panel. This marked an early key approval for the large-scale mixed-use scheme on the former Tetley\'s Brewery site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b6dca06f-be53-4afa-a103-3fbecaa7a963','infrastructure-active-todmorden-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.275','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans are underway on a £3.5m scheme to give the town a makeover. And there are plans to create more walking and cycling routes in Todmorden. The Active Todmorden project will include new cycle parking spaces throughout the town; improving pedestrian access - including links between Todmorden Rail Station and the town centre; and upgrading the existing crossing at Centre Vale Park. The benefits, says Calderdale Council, will be reducing the number of car journeys and ease traffic congestion to improve air quality and boosting the economy.','Todmorden: How council plans to revamp Calderdale town centre and make it more \'attractive and vibrant\'','Halifax Courier','2025-01-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/todmorden-how-council-plans-to-revamp-calderdale-town-centre-and-make-it-more-attractive-and-vibrant-4467140','An article in the Halifax Courier detailing various regeneration plans for Todmorden, including the Active Todmorden project. It highlighted specific improvements such as new cycle parking spaces, enhanced pedestrian access (including links to the rail station), and upgrades to crossings at Centre Vale Park, aiming to reduce car journeys and boost the local economy.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b72d7661-1824-41c8-8c60-fd87db6ab9da','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'LCC has recently completed phase 3 of the Leeds PIPES networks which extends the network by 2.5 km. Phase 3 adds several connections including St James\'s University Hospital, Leonardo/Thoresby student residential accommodation, Old Technology Campus student residential accommodation, and Lovell Park multi storey flats. ... Phase 3 commenced construction in October 2022, and is due to completed early 2024.','Heat Network Zone Opportunity Report - Leeds','GOV.UK','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/heat-network-zone-opportunity-report-leeds','A GOV.UK report on Heat Network Zoning for Leeds, dated February 2025, confirmed that Phase 3 of the Leeds PIPES network, which extends the network by 2.5 km, was completed in early 2024. This phase added several connections, explicitly listing \'Leonardo/Thoresby student residential accommodation\' among them, demonstrating its official integration into the broader heating infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b732a226-93d9-4fb7-809e-3ee743093a90','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On May 21, 2024, Caddick Group signed a memorandum of understanding with Homes England to accelerate the delivery of the 1,900-home Leeds masterplan, South Village. The agreement is a step towards infrastructure works starting on site before the end of the year, allowing the first plots to emerge in 2025. [9, 15, 27]','UKREiiF | Caddick, Homes England tie up deal to kickstart £1bn South Village','UKREiiF','2024-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://ukreiif.com/news/ukreiif-caddick-homes-england-tie-up-deal-to-kickstart-1bn-south-village/','Caddick Group signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with Homes England to accelerate the delivery of the £1bn South Village scheme. This agreement aims to expedite infrastructure works, with the first plots expected to emerge in 2025, marking a significant step towards implementation.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b811dc4c-48ef-4e34-af11-aabe392cfb10','infrastructure-a638-doncaster-road-corridor-improvement-programme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.997','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans which could see more than £6m of funding being made available to improve travel on a \'torturous\' have been approved. The scheme, which was approved by the council\'s Cabinet, proposes a range of improvements along the A638 between the junction of Black Road, at Heath Common, and Chantry Bridge. The council is will receive an initial £1.09m of funding from West Yorkshire Combined Authority to fund a full business case and detailed designs of highway improvement works.','Plan approved for £6m scheme to improve \'torturous\' stretch of A638 Doncaster Road in Wakefield','Wakefield Express','2022-06-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/transport/plan-approved-for-ps6m-scheme-to-improve-torturous-stretch-of-a638-doncaster-road-in-wakefield-3733074','Wakefield Council\'s Cabinet approved plans for over £6m of funding to improve the A638 Doncaster Road between Heath Common and Chantry Bridge. Councillor Matthew Morley emphasized that the scheme, aiming to improve conditions for pedestrians, bus users, and cyclists, would receive an initial £1.09m from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority for detailed designs and a full business case.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b86718ad-8fe5-47eb-a448-8a4131075a59','infrastructure-cornholme-a646-active-travel-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.620','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A multi-million-pound project to improve walking, wheeling and cycling facilities in West Yorkshire is taking a major step forward. The new £5.1 million West Yorkshire Places scheme includes proposals such as new street crossings and lighting, improved green spaces and traffic calming measures. ... In Cornholme, proposals include new footway links along the A646, new pedestrian crossings, and a one-way system on Greenfield Terrace. [5, 6]','New £5.1 million proposals to improve active travel across West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news/new-51-million-proposals-to-improve-active-travel-across-west-yorkshire/','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced a new £5.1 million \'West Yorkshire Places\' scheme to enhance walking, wheeling, and cycling facilities. This multi-million-pound project includes specific proposals for Cornholme, such as new footway links along the A646, new pedestrian crossings, and a one-way system on Greenfield Terrace.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b8daa2ff-a3ac-44f7-b46e-8d52a4f5d433','infrastructure-toby-carvery-leeds-aberford-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.388','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been been agreed regarding new electric vehicle chargepoints across West Yorkshire. The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy sets out how the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, and the region\'s five councils, will collaborate in an effort to ensure there are enough places to charge cars and vans in public where people need them. The strategy, which was agreed by members of the Combined Authority\'s transport committee on Wednesday, April 16, outlines investment priorities, design guidance, and an action plan.','West Yorks Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy agreed | Bradford Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-04-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24299902.west-yorks-electric-vehicle-infrastructure-strategy-agreed/','The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy for West Yorkshire was officially agreed by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s transport committee on April 16, 2025. This strategy details how the Combined Authority and its five constituent councils will collaborate to provide sufficient public EV charging points across the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b94bb3e4-76cb-4fdb-a783-8686faab7d47','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Changes are coming to the technology which provides our telephone lines in Calderdale (and the rest of the UK). This will involve anyone who currently owns or uses a traditional phone line (which are often referred to as “landlines”). By 2025, the various companies who provide our current telephone network (companies like BT) will have replaced all traditional phone lines (which have used copper wiring and similar technology for over a century) with a new system which uses broadband technology. ... Vulnerable Citizens Telecoms providers have signed a Charter committing to protect vulnerable households, particularly those using personal alarms, known as telecare, which offer remote support to elderly, disabled, and vulnerable people. [14]','Digital Telephone Switch Coming To Calderdale','Calderdale Council','2024-12-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE--XmuUdqXSscICKRPpB7pNXRdHQ2Z7xwkXYWiwH719e7_WTV61AgcpkB9GvTeyikZpLixewZsrYS6PuAEPN3MPbL_jtkY_KrUnESEujfaugtSNBG6FoxOG_JmPXSZrnzgYtmXtP3_rPF5WJbP6fObJoij_0fQpU2rmg-mZk1GWXI5iDpaNeech0gKKGI_IiSZB0bb6j9f6RI-ctG0nhbX','Calderdale Council issued an announcement regarding the national digital telephone switchover, indicating that traditional copper landlines would be replaced by broadband technology by 2025. It highlighted that vulnerable citizens, particularly those using telecare alarms, would be protected by a Telecoms providers\' Charter.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b951e8ea-2529-4b24-a561-3b6a5d5446b9','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Today the Department for Transport has given the green light of £35.709 million funding to enable Leeds City Council to make improvements to the Dawsons Corner junction and complete joint replacement work on the Stanningley Bypass. This forms part of a £42.679 million total package with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority funding of £6.970m and contribution from the council. Changes to the junction will reduce congestion and delays, helping to support economic growth across Leeds and Bradford. The reduction in congestion will also lead to a better environment in terms of improved air quality. Improvements are also planned to see better traffic flow, with bus journey times also reduced and improved safer crossing facilities for cyclists and pedestrians. [8, 9, 10, 14]','£35.709 million green light for major A647/A6120 Dawsons Corner / Stanningley Bypass scheme','Leeds City Council News / West Leeds Dispatch / Bradford Telegraph and Argus / Major Funding Boost for Leeds Infrastructure','2025-02-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG_n6PeoxH3MWyx0dI8zKOF98zhl-c3ejvND10MXKxTGPt3zrc6EmfF-855Orr5imIhIbFtThM-9yU_lpLjQVx7iZBz1p3xaz5jectjiD7jBs38aKA0VXuCKVJi8Q8gSp1Z9vSp-IZbev5VBSqF6c1Kvme4bihw1k7eRprafyrHWJAIxA59qLdwCNHCy2ugO_B2snTpZtB7DgDLhF-nY7naZSKfOzr5sPamQk0Q4ecX6R60VEdh','The Department for Transport officially approved £35.709 million in funding for the Dawson\'s Corner and Stanningley Bypass improvement scheme. This forms part of a £42.679 million total package, with contributions from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Leeds City Council. The announcement detailed plans to reduce congestion, improve air quality, and enhance active travel facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b9766552-eb39-4871-88d9-56be4f8e6087','infrastructure-frizinghall-station-revitalization',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.032','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Litter is a major problem at the station. Fly tippers use the area for no good reason. Travelers using the station drop litter and mustn\'t be proud of their local area as this picture shows. The railway company can\'t be bothered to clean up! Shame on them! The local council has paths and by-ways passing the station that are in a dirty state. Time they did some enforcement and cleaning-up. Bill Bryson, author and president of the Campaign to Protect Rural England have published a guide on complaining about litter. ... Network rail blame the public saying \'railways are a prime target for litter and illegally dumped rubbish by members of the public.\'','Frizinghall and It\'s Mucky Railway Station - God\'s Own County','God\'s Own County (blog)','2016-09-02 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGqHZ2V3SYky82vkLT59cNXvmbK63CeqhadM2NcqCgVbs2Q0Nu_B2hiD-A1q2W70B5_eQJR6avN1lpVBQTvJ0CdF1H6xGoLZESd9p7LloX-FSOrbWe4lzAqt9QfcXG7AL5v4fQ6l-6p0kKntZYsbgbpzAq0Bk3mx0xDDXXXLBykWp7ilCSM_gVeEk-o1oi5Ug==','This blog post from 2016 highlights the significant problem of litter and fly-tipping at Frizinghall station. It expresses frustration with both the railway company and the local council for not adequately addressing the cleanliness issues, providing a historical context to the station\'s environment before recent revitalization efforts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('b9eed742-c5ba-4dca-9487-b40388abec3f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-plus-transport-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.788','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This report provides feedback on work to revise the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund programme and a matching funding profile including increased local contributions. The Growth Deal funding previously announced would have funded a £1bn programme over 20 years. The proposed programme has a value of around £1.4bn (outturn prices) and an anticipated delivery programme of 11 years. Approval is sought for the revised programme and increased local contributions. The approach was recommended by the WYCA Investment Committee. The report seeks approval, in principle, to the initial additional resource needed to deliver the fund programme. ... The outputs suggest that by the mid-2030s the revised transport fund package would deliver at least an additional 18,500 new jobs, 10,500 new homes and £2.45 billion of GVA (per annum) across West Yorkshire and York. ... The overall impact of the Fund\'s interventions would be carbon neutral at the package level. [4]','West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund - Programme and Cost Review Report Summary','Bradford Council','2014-12-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGddEkzL2ty52Zntm7B8-5bJKGqr0lZgcIIbg9JOW-thLIPYF8DeqvFnLLkWrx66pngS1Pmy8vgYU5m-H0fGApFsJHrM0sJ4aRgFgd2-xOis6eGa0-L1S-kafvCqsaX1efuYHofCzJFaRSE-ByjLpyJrVr89xwH-MqHvs2g4tzkrelBSbAYX5jsOTk-lNFVC7oXSsUtEF62geaR8BONf3Xlrk_YdvKr5BHwhj9_2aFyWY7ecX3DdAw073hXGg1VkP8qfiv7_paUyWwVAuDSwZSHVo4mtzO8hrQlYpr2xybtPYFO39yRse6fdV4r8Nan2KH9DAXfhzblKdLE','A report providing feedback on the revised West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund programme and its funding profile. Initially, a £1 billion program over 20 years, it was revised to around £1.4 billion over an anticipated 11-year delivery period. The report seeks approval for the revised program and increased local contributions, aiming to deliver at least an additional 18,500 new jobs, 10,500 new homes, and £2.45 billion of GVA annually across West Yorkshire and York by the mid-2030s. It also sets an objective for the Fund\'s interventions to be carbon neutral at the package level. [4]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ba290654-b945-4e62-88e4-d8cf312e33b3','infrastructure-halifax-future-high-streets-fund-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.256','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Demolition of the public toilets at George Square will start on Monday 28 October 2024. This work will prepare the area ready for construction which is expected to begin in summer 2025.','Demolition of George Square public toilets to start in October 2024','Calderdale Next Chapter','2024-10-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEpPIw7yBdBQ5XEvxcZxg9FRpfNmsa8GaA8OBNSwVhGJ3YHlTP7p__5xWHL71-WP9PTWrvz0BZzXP9KTjbfPuNlyxOZc7R1IG5oUgNI3v3Gky-gI6UmbtJdR3tUmIL1P0RCayd-SJcCT2izt3NVO_0e7Uuya8Id2WGbCZXbwPZbKnjbeAvhL-ro6_RtqrJHk-d9Hw==','An update on the George Square project, part of the Halifax Future High Streets Fund. It announces the demolition of public toilets starting Monday, October 28, 2024, to prepare for construction expected in summer 2025. This will create a new social space, wider footpaths, and greener areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ba632025-23f2-4bb7-9e86-84cbe8879f7f','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In March 2015 The Northern Sparks report was produced by a committee of Members of Parliament from all parties focusing on economic benefits of electrification in the North. The Calder Valley line in its entirety was number one priority. This was reiterated in 2018. [7] Top-ranked route on business, economic and environmental criteria was the full Calder Valley Line from Leeds via Bradford and Brighouse to Manchester (via Rochdale) and Preston (via East Lancs). The assumption was that planned schemes for the Huddersfield (TP Route Upgrade) and Midland Main Lines would have already gone ahead. [8] The first phase was to be a 5-year plan over the 2019-24 control period, covering 12 routes. [8]','Northern Sparks report: North of England Electrification Task Force','Transport for the North (originally, cited in various articles)','2015-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHRU4w_HAoVrWrGKFsZo6uErMKBNeiij_Z5rPK08k02TyEU4SQhApGBYM-YFe86ZhZqTzCg3l69Mjp6AiX_n9M4oL01o1uLN4Gb1ibK_4w0_HCHfFvjsNS5DWwVSVcECzOduSakFz7Wt0ZDB9NIU1emm5xdan_pQfb48IoygADasH9Le310f5-YSWhHtLMUzaeECXpjrFSabio6xeWl1pmHb-q1','The Northern Sparks report, produced by an all-party committee of MPs, identified the full Calder Valley Line electrification as the top priority among 12 schemes for its economic and environmental benefits in the North. It was the highest-ranked recommendation for a 5-year plan over the 2019-2024 control period.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ba91548b-6b71-4bd3-aa3d-af88627bb5b8','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to create an enhanced rail gateway at Bradford Interchange using part of a repurposed £22 million funding pot have been set out by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Bradford Council. This commitment follows the closure of the bus station on January 4, 2024, due to drainage issues and widespread water leakage. The investment plan is to deliver essential improvements for rail passengers in the short-term. An update report on May 31, 2024, (and June 3, 2024, in WYMetro) revealed the bus station would remain closed until September for in-depth surveys to determine its viability.','Bradford Interchange rail gateway to benefit from investment while solution for bus station is found','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / WYMetro','2024-05-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHCVBFe3purAhQX4y6p6Oy7-krmbRYWoz9LJIybzHG0JUxq2eekyQBqiFs7qO5idspIbT26BHpzVx0ohXkxsYFcZrtQgyre4o8rgsdgZely6q_4qQz1uI_OQ-yS_xr3UfHuzkeIVg0wI5iuKd7tqqWa5bb7Acnyw-pHmZr34KT1E2W-9YcKNuHD8l8AoTZXZHkO6S1D0DShxU9uODEauSAuzMGfBG7zPEUS3-mrCMsg_OkvyCREFrojlbXrJ53GdiUKrWm04fT8dgDpwv1zTdfAe9wsHA==','Following the closure of the bus station in January 2024 due to safety concerns, West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Bradford Council announced plans to create an enhanced rail gateway using a repurposed £22 million funding pot from the Transforming Cities programme. The investment focuses on short-term improvements for rail passengers, with in-depth surveys ongoing for the bus station\'s future.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bacef124-7209-4b75-8c7d-7fbbcb3faa78','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Our proposals for Armley Gyratory have changed since we consulted on them in autumn 2019. This page explains what the changes are and why they have been made. The updated design has since received planning approval in December 2021. Leeds City Council have appointed a construction partner to undertake works on the Armley Gyratory. How will the work affect you? • Planned highway works will begin on 10 January 2022.','Have Your Say Today - Armley Gyratory','Armley Gyratory - Commonplace','2021-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE2QbL9TNT1Lbjccv_pHhUL6Rq0G1qyZORcvvJz36IryssLSF7KixoSU2wOosQZtflUtNqVSkYYKG4Yp7a7lTni46V_gaXEug-jU_byb5G4387VhcMpI_Q5tw0EqqPUb6iIiDOBG7GsB0vAozkZ6ceGGL6do14XZiken8tpqZuxfWf0n5clJZ70sD4k0tw=','The updated design for the Armley Gyratory improvement scheme received planning approval in December 2021. Leeds City Council appointed a construction partner to undertake works, with planned highway works commencing on January 10, 2022. The scheme aimed to provide appealing routes for pedestrians and cyclists, increase safety, improve traffic flow, and enhance the local environment through new landscaping.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('baf3a85c-e073-44a1-be00-bf411ee4cc24','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WORK to pedestrianise some of Bradford city centre\'s main roads began yesterday, and it is hoped the work will “encourage people to spend more time in the city.” The closure of Hall Ings, Market Street and other city streets to traffic was first announced in March 2020, when Government awarded Bradford millions from its Transforming Cities Fund. [6] Hall Ings\' four lanes of traffic will become a new city centre park, while Market Street will become a pedestrian street that can host stalls, events and bring more “café culture” to the centre. [6] The overall scheme will cost £43m, and recent releases by Bradford Council have highlighted that this Department for Transport cash “cannot be used for other purposes, such as delivering day to day services or other projects.” [6]','Why are roads in Bradford city centre being pedestrianised?','Telegraph and Argus','2024-04-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24250262.roads-bradford-city-centre-pedestrianised/','A Telegraph and Argus article in April 2024 highlighted the commencement of work to pedestrianise major Bradford city centre roads like Hall Ings and Market Street. Part of a £43 million scheme funded by the government\'s Transforming Cities Fund (TCF), the project aims to create a new city centre park on Hall Ings and transform Market Street into a pedestrian-friendly area for events and \'café culture\'. The article explains the rationale behind the pedestrianisation, including reducing congestion and pollution, improving safety, and aiding city centre regeneration.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bb0b6c6f-69c2-47cd-80d0-3eff9fa24c9d','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'PEOPLE in Otley are being given the chance to have their say on new transport services for the town. In a bid to get people to ditch their cars, “Shared Transport Hubs” are an initiative being launched across West Yorkshire. ... Otley is the first of five areas to invite the public to have their say on what these should look like. ... West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Leeds City Council, is asking the public for their views on the proposed location of the new hub — at North Parade Car Park or Courthouse Street Car Park — and on what services residents, businesses and other potential users would like to see.','Have a say on new transport plans for Otley as consultation starts | Wharfedale Observer','Wharfedale Observer','2024-01-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHGvgdahIIrvAANx54SmmYCvoe-5pj8WuBKX7r9YS_reIsPgkxPUW4rvTBoDuXF2OfLKm3VTE_No0N82IWW3qtcQ2m-j_OONkDd38fuKYguDJCs59SZ5DstbXy_7gJuwhVkC66CX1E7Akkc7tSh-4MotS8R4ajURERjqYCKbyLM_siAKZYm7FniUvvoAB2pImF-_f7yeFTq1VbjcxLDMNJ1','An article announcing the launch of a public consultation in Otley, Leeds, for a new \"Shared Transport Hub.\" This is presented as part of a wider West Yorkshire initiative to reduce reliance on private vehicles by creating a single point for various transport services. The consultation, led by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Leeds City Council, sought public views on potential locations like North Parade Car Park or Courthouse Street Car Park and the types of services residents would like to see.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bb593619-42a5-4c6d-a9a4-f19ee648c4d2','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Castleford growth corridor scheme that provides new cycle lanes, pedestrian facilities to the north of the town centre. Castleford. 30/09/2023. 01/08/2024. [17, 20]','CRSTS_Delivery_Plans_for_City... (West Yorkshire Combined Authority delivery plan)','Cycle Sheffield (document hosted on)','2024-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.cyclesheffield.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/CRSTS_Delivery_Plans_for_City_Regions.pdf','A West Yorkshire Combined Authority delivery plan document mentions the Castleford Growth Corridor scheme as providing new cycle lanes and pedestrian facilities to the north of the town centre, with a stated completion date of August 1, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bbbe4b3c-f125-4729-bd58-6419eb7fa095','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Drivers of plug-in vehicles will soon find topping up their mileage even more convenient, thanks to 84 new plug-in vehicle fast charging bays being installed in Leeds. A newly announced partnership between Leeds City Council and EB Charging will see 84 new \'fast\' charging bays installed at 15 locations across the city—with the first 30 bays at six locations already live. [6]','Leeds City Council Partners with EB Charging for 84 New Charge Points','Leeds City Council news release (reported by Charged EVs)','2023-03-21 00:00:00.000',NULL,'A new partnership between Leeds City Council and EB Charging was announced to install 84 fast charging bays at 15 locations throughout Leeds, with some already operational. This initiative significantly boosts public charging options in residential areas. [6, 10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bbfb309a-4f5e-4367-80a8-63c09ca67a10','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire and the Humber will benefit from 108 flood schemes totalling £59.5 million protecting homes and businesses, boosting the local economy, and creating construction and infrastructure jobs, the Environment Agency has announced. ... Here is a list of Calderdale schemes to be invested in between April 2025 and March 2026: ... Stubbing Holme Road.','List of Calderdale flood schemes to receive a funding boost, the Environment Agency has announced','Halifax Courier','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/environment/list-of-calderdale-flood-schemes-to-receive-a-funding-boost-the-environment-agency-has-announced-4089943','The Environment Agency announced a £59.5 million investment for 108 flood schemes in Yorkshire and the Humber, including Stubbing Holme Road. This funding is set to kickstart or progress construction of schemes between April 2025 and March 2026, providing protection for homes and businesses.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bc25e013-7d9f-4c1f-9731-8b3d3c084056','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This Order gives effect to the Borough Council of Calderdale Permit Scheme. The Borough Council of Calderdale Permit Scheme is designed to control the carrying out of works in specified streets in the Borough of Calderdale by imposing an obligation to obtain a permit from the Borough Council of Calderdale before undertaking the works. The scheme came into force on 31st March 2015. [14]','The Traffic Management (Borough Council of Calderdale) Permit Scheme Order 2015','Legislation.gov.uk','2015-02-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2015/121/made','This statutory instrument formally established the Calderdale Permit Scheme, designed to control and manage works on specified streets within the borough. It requires obtaining a permit from Calderdale Council before undertaking works, aiming for better overall network management and reduced disruption.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bd2acb2a-2cce-4e45-9348-e8f8c348025b','infrastructure-kirkstall-bridge-shopping-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.411','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A GOV.UK press release from 13 July 2025, details a £63 million government investment to supercharge the UK\'s EV infrastructure, with a significant portion allocated to local authorities to increase charging access. [20]','Government Announces £63 Million Boost for UK Electric Vehicle Infrastructure','GOV.UK','2025-07-13 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-63-million-boost-for-britains-electric-vehicle-revolution','The UK government announced a £63 million investment package to enhance Britain\'s electric vehicle infrastructure. This includes a £25 million scheme for local authorities to expand access to cheaper at-home charging, particularly for households without driveways, and aims to support the deployment of an additional 100,000 public chargepoints.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bd46fed3-b9e8-4f5b-9afb-2dfd0d29b3c4','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The unique heritage and culture of Halifax will be showcased as part of a new trail around the town\'s centre, mixing existing landmarks with new art installations. The \'Art and About Trail\' is part of Future High Streets Fund work in Halifax, funded by the Government and being delivered by Calderdale Council. The trail is being created in partnership with local arts organisation, Everybody Arts (formerly Artworks) and will showcase brand-new art installations along with existing points of interest such as the Borough Market and the Victoria Theatre. This will create a trail taking in 21 locations around Halifax with works inspired by the town\'s history, but with modern techniques and influences. Artists are now invited to submit their ideas for two of the locations on the trail, at Hatters Fold and George Square. [6]','Artist call-out for new cultural trail in Halifax','Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGcAxnfttnx2QVN3hcQhztAVd1EiIx8x3vprIXeeQ6Vrw7kHIv-D-zB37BK5LH1S6bGlbzRAQdXojFUzZ4BES0JmeFfgxF8Qm_XRPUZZ5GzhCdHcSXuTJR3nIKOsGKUfx6taqJl7SEOqXu5qe9cNMYo2cbD-iulWprzM_2poR95mSsD_3mMMwI0xhXaqvDo','Calderdale Council, in partnership with Everybody Arts, announced a call for artists to submit ideas for two locations on the \'Art and About Trail\' – Hatters Fold and George Square. This project, part of the Future High Streets Fund, aims to create a trail of 21 locations with new art installations and existing landmarks showcasing Halifax\'s heritage and culture.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bd47bd53-576e-4626-9407-b32827c93ed7','infrastructure-calderdale-corridor-improvement-programme-phase-1-a58a672-and-a646a6033',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.888','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Name of scheme: CIP A58 A672 Corridor. Lead organisation: Calderdale Council. Approvals to date: Decision Point 3 Outline Business Case: August 2018. Change Request September 2019 – extension to delivery timescales. Decision Point 4 Full Business Case: September 2020. [15]','Scheme Summary Report - A58/A672 (Decision Point 4 Full Business Case)','Calderdale Council','2020-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHt4-_dxoSEAVWKV01q3lgLM6YogmJLMpK7VYf7wfkau7udo7MJ5BCI7m_HZM7V8KAr4h7WE-8hnEhKvQ4Tl7t30-QA9Ur7STKHQT90ARJnCocM3mfND0X4vEIZN3M7u7qKZGpFpwmF0JgFpTQiWbMBsrHgfaSlP0-_jmK5mmmFLAbrFSLVlZxERGRoCleCFMhhsWhOjoI=','This report details the full business case for the A58/A672 scheme, part of CIP Phase 1, outlining interventions to improve highway efficiency, including junction improvements, bus facilities, pedestrian crossings, and cycle infrastructure. This milestone marked the approval for the full business case.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bd9152f9-fbaf-484f-b1e4-a9906fe450ed','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'GOV.UK announced the opening of the new Caldene Bridge to motorists and pedestrians on May 18, 2020. This event marked a major milestone for the Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme, with the new bridge featuring an area beneath nearly twice the size of the old one to significantly improve flood resilience.','A new bridge opens – a major milestone for Mytholmroyd flood defences','GOV.UK','2020-05-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/a-new-bridge-opens-a-major-milestone-for-mytholmroyd-flood-defences','GOV.UK announced the opening of the new Caldene Bridge to motorists and pedestrians on May 18, 2020. This event marked a major milestone for the Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme, with the new bridge featuring an area beneath nearly twice the size of the old one to significantly improve flood resilience.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bdad0ae8-4e91-40f8-a5eb-214c3a222470','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Vastint UK the developer behind Leeds\' 24-acre Aire Park, on the site of the former Tetleys brewery, is set to welcome leading global law firm Eversheds Sutherland as the first tenant of its latest commercial building. Due to move in early 2027, following the building\'s completion, Eversheds Sutherland will occupy nearly two thirds of the building, taking a lease on floors three to five, and part of level six. [9, 30]','Global Law Firm Eversheds Sutherland to Relocate to Aire Park\'s Kellstone Building','South Leeds Life / Business Link Magazine','2025-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHPRZ64RdBx7HNnVTtkRrpT2_-nERNO7MCqgs_urUqcNoneBSIzjePjko0V7ccu5tNHNuqL7W_nRnHRrqxwZqQGqud71qJsdsPs8ap-gYOxWRDRvQFdupMilhJLVv5R5ms7hRF-owlyJIpUQDBDPGtAaCLEOzQBI9TfKPX5kmalNSQ [9], https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEhnd7gP2iIsYSCdoylmhXZ7gOqmi0s0IReX8CWkUQvh1V5r77cpboKwRZDb603igl7X9GusXBRiO5U9r0HShqqR0EWzs3WguHIqurIohb8evbTSgwg4sMW1amA-WQbqK0HO_-oGnbRTvAbYgCSNzHO4E7XkUjyBZp_HK6GYToYbMVyeQ [30]','Leading global law firm Eversheds Sutherland confirmed its relocation to the Kellstone building, Aire Park\'s latest commercial offering, in early 2027. The firm will occupy nearly two-thirds of the 75,000 sq ft Grade A office space, contributing to the growing community of businesses at Aire Park.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bdb23577-60bc-4507-a20e-d55ad8f41921','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been formally submitted for the first phase of City Village, a new sustainable community set to transform Bradford\'s former commercial core into a thriving city centre neighbourhood. Bradford City Village, which is being delivered by ECF (our partnership between Homes England and L&G and Muse) and Bradford Council, is proposed to be built across the \'Top of Town\' area, which includes the Oastler, Kirkgate and Chain Street sites. A detailed planning application for Phase One, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site, has been submitted. Plans for phase one include: – The creation of 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. – A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces. – Supporting infrastructure including safer roads, landscaped public spaces and active travel routes.','Plans Submitted for First Phase of Bradford City Village Regeneration','ECF - the English Cities Fund','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFiRsZghHbqe98yVdJe1snoW-VJi_Tdy5E8r07E3cwJxxWYJfB_epLR2XeMM4-itCxqHrPW06ZhPhyjws1CDOCJ2gMtIJnFwj4pPRC3qYOpC-znoxVnF0e13djnMfdwB1OF0VBZOjsvLFMwKLgWlKVfy5MD-CCWHUq2M_Lj4-H7mCRXWbrMvMB5xQL7XU4=','A detailed planning application for Phase One of the City Village, along with an outline application for the remainder of the site, has been formally submitted. Phase One includes 33 townhouses on Chain Street and 64 on the northern Oastler site, plus supporting infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bdb54ef1-1010-40fa-b10b-30e52b080825','infrastructure-hebble-brook-halifax-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.231','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Final approval has been given for a flooding alleviation project in Halifax. Senior Environment Agency adviser Paul Swales told flood alleviation programme partners it was hoped the scheme for Hebble Brook in Wheatley would start in late spring or early summer. Realigning the water course and improving access are the preferred options, said Mr Swales.','Flooding in Calderdale: Halifax flood project approved','Halifax Courier','2025-04-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGVkPcCIB2mi_zYfQ_lOZSts2hlvgZdzZJREGEYnuIOeFNkKgzRpEiEzCDN1lU61DhCQWqOoPJkXW0wVPCkUdUMJDGR1YvnqAlV641mv6omW8Yjiu6ubDgbPF3hXAR7kk5WwGUSAZYeWw6AWlSrMQ1UilG6enevos6BsVDYx-NsUwSeLpo1DCqPinhZP8JIOQ_679P5T5U09okzoWd19HLnomnt0EV3MmQUFw==','Final approval was granted for the Hebble Brook flood alleviation project in Wheatley, Halifax. Senior Environment Agency adviser Paul Swales stated that the scheme, which involves realigning the water course and improving access, was hoped to start in late spring or early summer 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('be401e9b-3800-46ab-8247-4f0fcaf44e1e','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WESTGATE ARCADE TO GET BIGGER AND BETTER... We are proud to announce that Westgate Arcade will be starting it\'s Phase II Expansion in mid 2022. The Phase II Expansion sees a new and exciting chapter in this successful shopping centre story and includes 12 new commercial premises. [12]','Westgate Arcade to get Bigger and Better! - YouTube','Westgate Arcade (YouTube channel of O&C Management Services)','2021-08-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEXEAJVi3-1v6gowZ3gHkeqI_d_1BcOzfmQ3g7ZsVPfHUe1rElhnacvnLxl_mc8VuifJz0jRird7LhlDq_hvHcGc2JbbC4Q5oE-VmViEJXA8s5GP7TCVLZHxDg9sg_HYIRcNNyBKA==','An announcement video from O&C Management Services proudly declared that Westgate Arcade would begin its Phase II Expansion in mid-2022. This expansion is set to include 12 new commercial premises, enhancing the shopping centre\'s offerings.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('be57b46a-2f25-4637-afd2-7df5a347a56c','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Diocese of Leeds has been awarded £354,418 to decarbonise South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School by replacing the existing oil boiler with an air source heat pump.','Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: project summaries','GOV.UK','2025-04-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-project-summaries','This document from GOV.UK specifically lists the Diocese of Leeds project for South Crosland Church of England Voluntary Aided Junior School, detailing the award of £354,418 to replace an existing oil boiler with an air source heat pump for decarbonisation purposes. This is a direct confirmation of the project and its funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bee777e8-6626-4915-a038-00c10fefffb2','infrastructure-lookers-nissan-leeds-kirkstall-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.392','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Drivers no longer need to submit planning applications to install electric car chargepoints, helping them save up to £1,100 a year. ... from today, it\'s now quicker, simpler and cheaper to install EV chargepoints at home or at work, thanks to new government changes cutting red tape. The move means that many drivers and businesses no longer need planning permission to install public and private EV chargers, as confirmed by Future of Roads Minister, Lilian Greenwood.','UK Government Relaxes Planning Permissions for EV Chargepoint Installation','Carwow','2025-05-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.carwow.co.uk/blog/no-more-planning-hassles-for-ev-chargepoints-uk','The UK government implemented new rules to simplify and expedite the installation of EV chargepoints at homes and workplaces by largely removing the need for planning applications. This policy change, effective from May 2025, aims to accelerate the national EV rollout and reduce barriers for businesses and individuals installing charging infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bf110927-5533-4aa7-ab8d-7aa6e2f9a4c2','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Views sought on multi-million-pound revamp of Huddersfield Bus Station. Huddersfield Bus Station is set for a multi-million-pound refurbishment – and the public can have their say before designs are finalised. West Yorkshire Combined Authority ... Plans for the £27 million revamp, delivered by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Kirklees Council, aim to provide passengers with a more accessible, energy efficient and modern bus station. They include a new entrance canopy, cycle parking and improvements to the public space around the bus station. Proposals also involve better shop fronts, real-time bus and rail information to help with onward journeys, improved safety and security measures, and a \'Changing Places\' toilet with extra features to meet the needs of people with a range of disabilities. A \'living roof\' covered in plants, and energy saving features such as solar glass, are also part of the plans. ... The public can find out more about the plans and have their say before 11.59pm on Sunday 17 August by visiting http://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/huddersfield.','Views sought on multi-million-pound revamp of Huddersfield Bus Station','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-07-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFZLmY8PQhOaNK6rX4dErVFetnU75N1-HNWrJNVj2SCxiziAvVo9fwSFrDZivvZaOv9CaXW0d8zUF47SAWxZ6oTVl_UH4kXj_SzzXhhJU9A_nhXyJ6h4-4NBKO4rBc0V0v0YRV5C6PQrv2BxGWYRqSs4Z7DbdetwyBBYiPNsVwciZSEL2Jh4lxhd3fL28ML0ZN2VEvMpca6Jdtvmnmua4QL5AONx6XY_fZXNpVwB37LwWcQWU2C','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Kirklees Council launched a second round of public consultation on the £27 million refurbishment plans for Huddersfield Bus Station. The plans aim to create a more accessible, energy-efficient, and modern facility, including a new entrance canopy, cycle parking, enhanced public spaces, a \'Changing Places\' toilet, and a \'living roof\'. The consultation was open until August 17, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bf69f3c3-64cd-4b1f-97e6-43d67751b913','infrastructure-frizinghall-station-revitalization',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.032','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A primary school has been helping to clean up a north Bradford train station. Pupils from Frizinghall Primary School have been hard at work tidying up the approaches to Frizinghall station, close to their school. They took part in a project with Network Rail, the council, and Railscape to remove litter and fly-tipped waste from around the Frizinghall station area. ... Mrs Victoria Merriman, headteacher at Frizinghall Primary School, said: \"Taking pupils out on visits is an integral part of our school curriculum, and we plan visits to places which are accessible by train. ... The clean-up at Frizinghall station is part of wider efforts to improve the appearance of this section of railway. Bradford is currently celebrating being UK City of Culture 2025.','Frizinghall Primary pupils help clean up railway station | Bradford Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-05-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGs6E-CDGbtE7itEPqrs3FGQNFI3IvuDxhpYwM0_I_O3t651uwZofXCEDio2l_Rbx496sDHmloCIXzzb_pG4G1WpeJninF7JPV974ShSMTtzN8GskzzS3qV3Pqk-b4CT0ZdK3ITvqrOWuUq7yBZzMr8DGXEsI8YiV66aAjD2dRNM4EB1cvqBp4aM41gbngQ-QjNWnuqqHcnH4etIBU3q9QJYApIbSWr','This news article reports on Frizinghall Primary School pupils\' active participation in a clean-up project at Frizinghall station. Collaborating with Network Rail, Bradford Council, and Railscape, they removed litter and fly-tipped waste, showcasing community involvement as part of broader efforts for Bradford\'s UK City of Culture 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bfe270cf-b788-48ab-8532-5e47256555cb','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council has hit back at criticism over the nearly-complete walking and cycling improvements - stating that the city centre is now \"easier, safer and more pleasant.\" [5] Council bosses said the scheme had brought about safety improvements for people who “no longer have to dodge traffic” after streets once dominated by vehicles were pedestrianised as part of the £43 million scheme. [5] Market Street has been pedestrianised. [5] The scheme is being delivered through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund programme, which is a capital grant transport fund, provided by the Department for Transport and cannot be used for other purposes. [5]','Bradford pedestrianisation improves safety, says Council','Telegraph and Argus','2025-02-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24135519.bradford-pedestrianisation-improves-safety-says-council/','In February 2025, Bradford Council responded to criticisms regarding the nearly-complete city centre walking and cycling improvements. The Council asserted that the city centre is now \'easier, safer and more pleasant\' for pedestrians, wheelchair, and mobility scooter users, as streets once dominated by vehicles have been pedestrianised, removing the need to dodge traffic and navigate multiple kerb levels. This £43 million scheme, delivered through the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund, has brought about significant safety improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('bfe945fb-08bc-4b23-b612-b3123a86c2cb','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ten schools in the borough have had colourful new cycle and/or scooter storage installed to support and encourage active travel and complement the School Streets initiative. Calderdale Council is working with schools to encourage more active ways for children and young people to get to and from school, such as walking and cycling. ... The initiative has been funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority after a successful Council bid, supported by Active Calderdale.','Calderdale youngsters being encouraged to scoot and cycle to school','Halifax Courier','2020-11-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/education/calderdale-youngsters-being-encouraged-to-scoot-and-cycle-to-school-3041934','Ten schools in Calderdale received new cycle and scooter storage, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, to complement the School Streets initiative. This aims to further encourage active travel among children and young people, supporting the council\'s efforts to create more active and sustainable journeys to school.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901');
