	('c00b75f7-1cd7-4a32-86ff-efac64da8b65','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This scheme started on 4th March 2020 with the intention of: Less disruption on the road network. Better to overall network management. Less delays to the travelling public. Less costs to businesses caused by delays. Promotion of a safer environment. Lower carbon emissions. [10]','Calderdale Council Permit Scheme','Calderdale Council','2020-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/businesses/road-works-and-permits/calderdale-council-permit-scheme','This page details Calderdale Council\'s Permit Scheme, which began on 4th March 2020. The scheme aims to minimise disruption and delays from highway works through better planning, scheduling, and management of activities on the road network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c02de1ee-853b-4437-8a18-aeb6a44bb810','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More than 200 Calderdale homes will be better protected from flooding once a scheme is finished, says the Environment Agency. ... The Rishworthians section is now complete, with piles installed and backfilled with material and grass seeded, while the Copley Lane section has piles installed earthworks started ready to give gardens back to residents. ... Piling of the section leading up to the railway viaduct was now taking place and it is hoped will be complete by next February, they said.','What is happening with Copley flood alleviation scheme: Environment Agency gives update on work to protect more than 200 homes in Calderdale village','Halifax Courier','2024-10-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG8qJRyivl0sZAiLTpjZb2vvONr7VP0T-J1MY7Cgvj6HSSt0c11SsLNoMOZsySQSotBBWMYRlXNmbSQSAnrJPDqvYT8dfRztqI343adgTeIvmw0adGJ-1ySQEvhoK3yPIBkz22cElg3x4RlgjaR1SDSf-hf9GVqjvLCNkorx8Ys07Hr7LUY-L6siv93XrFodIPR6JLoXnWKSycpH72P4b5xU4mXdzstGJiOorYShC97QmjqbPB0v3UChJ5_7aWc_N2Xtk9dizcIMXPGXHa1GRGd68ffe6_KoPdUNjCYWMtIqQWvoOJyltzu_vibhy_JENLZJfZfZAcgea34JMqlSlc4bvxZCrBhJpHv','An update from the Environment Agency stating that over 200 Calderdale homes will be better protected by the scheme. The Rishworthians section is now complete, with piling ongoing for the Copley Lane and railway viaduct sections, aiming for completion by February 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c05b5b35-ecad-42c5-9695-0b36f3292084','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The UK Government announced its commitment to accelerate the construction of new rail stations at Thorpe Park and White Rose, aiming for construction to begin by the end of 2023. At this time, the Thorpe Park station was anticipated to be operational by summer 2024.','Government pledges to \'accelerate\' Thorpe Park and White Rose Rail Stations','Yorkshire Evening Post','2022-09-23 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/government-promise-to-accelerate-thorpe-park-and-white-rose-rail-stations-just-reannouncements-of-existing-schemes-claims-leeds-council-leader-3855661','The UK Government announced its commitment to accelerate the construction of new rail stations at Thorpe Park and White Rose, aiming for construction to begin by the end of 2023. At this time, the Thorpe Park station was anticipated to be operational by summer 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c05e7b48-23ca-4240-bcc3-19a71cb77f34','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water has initiated the tender process for two significant framework agreements valued at approximately £2.8bn (US$3.6 billion), reports Construction Enquire... These two frameworks aim to facilitate water and wastewater asset investments over the next decade, aligning with Yorkshire Water\'s objective of significantly reducing sewage overflows into watercourses. The proposed works will span the AMP8 regulatory period, commencing from April 2025 until March 2030, with potential extensions to AMP9. Throughout this comprehensive 10-year duration, Yorkshire Water intends to allocate £1.5bn... The Stormwater Overflow Alliance can anticipate an investment of £1.3bn, with £500m designated for AMP8 and an estimated £800m for AMP9. [8]','Yorkshire Water invites firms for £2.8bn infrastructure projects','Smart Water Magazine','2023-12-07 00:00:00.000','https://smartwatermagazine.com/news/yorkshire-water/yorkshire-water-invites-firms-28bn-infrastructure-projects','Yorkshire Water initiated the tender process for two framework agreements worth approximately £2.8 billion to facilitate water and wastewater asset investments for AMP8 (April 2025-March 2030) with potential extensions. This investment aims to significantly reduce sewage overflows. The frameworks include £1.5 billion for Non-Infrastructure partners and £1.3 billion for a Stormwater Overflow Alliance, with £500 million designated for AMP8.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c067b23c-8bef-4570-bd6b-18cfd718d38b','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'McLaren Living\'s new Build-to-Rent tower is the latest scheme to be given the green light by planners. The development, known as Wellington Square, will transform a 2.47-acre site into a gateway to Leeds city centre. G&T is providing Cost Management services...Designed by Howells Architects, the 45-storey BtR tower – The Hexagon – will become one of the city\'s tallest landmarks providing 464 homes ranging from one to three bedrooms, with a sky bar offering panoramic views on the 45th floor. Residents will benefit from about 10,000 sq ft of shared amenity space, including a concierge, post/parcel storage room and a lounge on the ground floor together with a fitness and wellbeing space on the first floor.','Plans for new scheme in Leeds\' West End Approved','Gardiner & Theobald','2024-04-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHmZXrFVFU6VwFqrmK9BOGdvrZL-z4CWuG4qAq-sMDKRGpH7K6htbz40HcOTLVNFYFBtrnnDy-TMfrf7HvQPPvV39topueuh4cXRcEu4v1jIQOS3EUEa4AIRPo9Zbv8Ughfmea1nsn8-zdmsq1Qn2wx_175fdhcmjVj1vf9VXrvlc94tIeoPqRvH730AHcg8s4=','Gardiner & Theobald confirmed the approval of McLaren Living\'s Wellington Square development by Leeds City Council. The 45-storey build-to-rent tower, \'The Hexagon\', will provide 464 homes, with a sky bar on the 45th floor. The project aims to transform a 2.47-acre site into a gateway to Leeds city centre, and Gardiner & Theobald are providing Cost Management services. [8]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c10a7ae5-29a4-41a4-94b3-e9c2855f558b','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A well-loved stretch of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton and Liversedge is set to undergo significant improvements this summer, thanks to a major investment from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund. The 2km (1.5-mile) section of the off-road path, which runs from Tesco in Cleckheaton to Knowler Hill Tunnel in Liversedge, will be closed from Monday 9 June for approximately six months while work is carried out. Kirklees Council and the charity Sustrans will deliver the project together, with signed diversions in place throughout the construction period.','Major Upgrade for Spen Valley Greenway Set to Begin This Summer - KLTV','KLTV','2025-06-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.kltv.co.uk/major-upgrade-for-spen-valley-greenway-set-to-begin-this-summer/','KLTV reported on June 7, 2025, that a 2km section of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton and Liversedge would close from June 9 for approximately six months to undergo significant improvements. The upgrades, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transforming Cities Fund and delivered by Kirklees Council and Sustrans, include a smoother surface, wider path, improved lighting, and better access points.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c120ee5e-ea3d-4c0f-932a-b1aa53f14607','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council are set to unveil £12m plans to improve travel along the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. [8]','Plans unveiled to improve Park Road in Pontefract','Wakefield Express','2024-11-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/transport/plans-unveiled-to-improve-park-road-in-pontefract-4835624','Wakefield Council announced £12 million plans to improve travel along the A639 Park Road in Pontefract, based on previous public consultation feedback. The plans include road widening, carriageway realignment, new crossings, and cycle lanes. Public drop-in sessions were scheduled for November 21 and December 9, 2024, with public feedback accepted until December 11, 2024. Funding is provided by West Yorkshire Combined Authority.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c1426e0f-4399-4f88-b4dc-d610dd368a23','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford city centre is on the brink of one of its most ambitious transformations in decades. Backed by over £40 million in funding, the City Village project will reimagine the “Top of Town” area into a thriving new neighbourhood of homes, parks, and community spaces. The regeneration will unfold over a 10-year period, with demolition of outdated structures beginning later this year and construction starting next spring. Funding includes £13.2 million from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and £30 million from Homes England, alongside private investment from partners including Legal & General and Muse. At the heart of City Village is the creation of 1,000 new homes, a significant proportion of which will be allocated as affordable housing through partnerships with Incommunities. The development will feature two- and three-bedroom townhouses, complemented by 400 modern apartments on the Kirkgate Market site and more than 300 apartments on the southern Oastler site.','Bradford\'s \'City Village\': £40 Million Urban Regeneration to Create 1,000 Homes','UK Estates','2025-09-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHNEEbo58GMKSNk_sLx74KvZ8sE9MZkeBtWJQ9zoHUC9bmbXL7or21xFHAjYNkiohrLCR5wZwDd-WeHMxTQfcTevsHs3JdFGV-jotuQh0xNFGD9e0doAGW5LBd3Ml8B6ANzX03CxnbDM8gVAfbSMuzSIN8VPJfoM2o33VFylN7uBX24gbfmBuuSWPaJ8bywFNwK6ScsepzvWTKVL3BPzCxpsWtyi0IwkTzOCWno76lknRfWKZ8=','A news report highlighting the Bradford City Village project as a significant £40 million urban regeneration backed by £13.2 million from WYCA and £30 million from Homes England. The scheme aims to create 1,000 new homes, parks, and community spaces over a 10-year period, with demolition starting later this year and construction in spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c144ed4d-2474-440a-af0d-01382355ad7b','infrastructure-wakefield-cathedral-square-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.682','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The project forms part of a £24.9m government Town Deal award given to the council in 2019 to revamp the city centre. [5]','Wakefield Council Awarded £24.9m Towns Deal Funding','UK Government / Wakefield Council (reported by Yorkshire Post, Wakefield Express)','2019-12-31 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/council/plans-submitted-for-new-city-square-next-to-wakefield-cathedral-4382583 [5], https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/plans-submitted-for-new-city-square-next-to-wakefield-cathedral-4381898 [12]','Wakefield Council received a £24.9 million grant from the UK government\'s Towns Deal program in 2019. This funding is allocated to support various city centre regeneration projects, including the ambitious Cathedral Square regeneration, aiming to revitalize the area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c15c960c-1bf5-4562-a514-aa389c06b7d3','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Brighouse residents and businesses are being invited to discover and discuss the latest designs for the future of the town as work continues on the Town Deal which will see £19.1 million of investment over the next three years. The latest plans will be on show from Monday 15 May on the Brighouse Deal website with a chance for everyone to have their say, see the designs and give feedback for three weeks until Sunday 4 June. [15] The project to has been nearly six years in development and, in that time, there have been consultations, open days and workshops in July 2020, May 2021, October 2022 and May 2023. [21, 37]','Public engagement on latest Brighouse Deal designs','Calderdale Council News Centre, The Brighouse Deal','2023-05-10 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/brighouses-19-1-million-town-deal-investment-discover-and-discuss-the-latest-plans/, https://www.brighousedeal.co.uk/the-timeline/','In May 2023, Brighouse residents and businesses were invited to discover and discuss the latest designs for the Town Deal projects. Public open events were held, allowing feedback on plans for public realm, a new market, and community spaces.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c1631f01-7393-45a6-94d5-72085886c61e','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Later phases of the neighbourhood will include a more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site alongside approximately 400 apartments on the Kirkgate site. The final phase of consultation launches today – inviting feedback on updated plans for the neighbourhood ahead of a planning application to be submitted in late summer. It will run until Weds 18 June. [12]','Detailed plans unveiled for first phase of \'City Village\' transformation / Community conversation launched on the first phase of Bradford\'s game-changing \'City Village\'','Muse / Bradford City Village Website / Bradford Telegraph and Argus / Anita Morris Associates','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHGmvmJaLLAIY6FqNDwN10ukjzcXHCx0AF9TYi0bH8UhAMpWb7SIFSnmuG8od1q2FyT-scbAmjYd59p0seGFp3c_SC3NANGLAfyA5MjE8qTACmOtpnm-Lj8BxyA8H1KY4fnJbJhSrv858u5SamH-RpWY4iHYTU_n2Jl8He4HeXj2OU=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEQTEx8DZzBrlx9vyepTD8xqq3nyDcNc_DW-al9Ocd9Bhn7lURdeIiXcUZBrookG4zy_zay4SyZmUogYohWqn2OAKx5j7G876vi7Psc3Aejze6J1uB_fOjQc6tpNgDgI8cmNnLEk9v3cFjIIDwhhXJou_wFqsusIWAJ-yc1sM51HYYDWRcDxBazKLYr2lBgVTYETZy5mf7YOgZrkpDz5cXZUhOctpzC7QxpSWkoTDqmJBO2pCkiWRhw, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGcPrx5tnmphsyYcbgQKENvxA-enewmjaqAWrfHeCpBSDKIqKMjq7rzy9A_ZhS3xo-7ZR1hklkVufGfha85GtK0l_uZBFgKTcLrtujYGJLe9dG65FR93I3r046LamOxq1NBo5rF8PS4k_QvrI2cXAfqJdcyIIU1pnOl7rUIjC9IEMzQjxcq60CHUuAcaBGXACaXXCY9qM01SIC6rofZm8-j_QHhInorflmrwTMzCwdMkHPlT_dw','ECF and Bradford Council launched the final phase of public consultation for the City Village project. Detailed plans for Phase 1 (Chain Street and northern Oastler site townhouses) were revealed, and outline plans for later phases, including over 300 apartments on the southern Oastler site and approximately 400 on the Kirkgate site, were confirmed. The consultation was open until June 18, 2025. [2, 3, 11, 12]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c23ea416-7ceb-4faa-87ee-2c5ca7b77fad','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is working to bring more electric vehicle chargepoints to the region through its £17 million Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme. West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin is urging people to have their say on where they should go – to ensure the right chargepoints are installed in the right places, particularly in neighbourhoods where driveway charging isn\'t an option. The consultation runs until Thursday 12th September, with people able to feedback at various drop-in sessions, webinars, online at https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/levi, or by post.','Consultation to improve electric vehicle infrastructure in West Yorkshire launches','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/media/7650/consultation-to-improve-electric-vehicle-infrastructure-in-west-yorkshire-launches-1-august-2024.pdf','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a consultation for its £17 million Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme. This initiative aims to increase the number of EV chargepoints across the region, including Wakefield, to support the transition to electric vehicles and improve air quality. The consultation ran until September 12, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c2966b6f-0006-4889-a147-b2c9017c71ea','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council has approved £1.3 million funding to buy digital carephone devices for 3,500 residents ahead of the analogue switch-off in 2025. The funding is designed to keep vulnerable telecare users safe as the council implements a national digital switchover.','£1.3m investment will ensure council residents can access digital telecare services','Government Technology','2022-06-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFin1A3ACvd0ysNrF39i_ijSXTZp2ngke3-06uARXHaBGe2xj3QG9iqYcTmtBZ1wr2wDfKxn_RxCRmgArYiHF7y6T5SXqSvDtIV_zGeH2KnXZWztb8V8rasVmSNmVRI8rUnmgIkJ1t56pC38NgAEiq_NHRkLfotAkWbFYEPzFX0t_JoGLQAZ2M-DlfstKOjdZNuDtMtcma7tk_JBgwS_B6aaUVcVw==','Kirklees Council committed £1.3 million to procure digital carephone devices for 3,500 residents. This investment ensures that vulnerable telecare users can maintain access to essential support services, safeguarding them ahead of the national analogue telephone network switch-off planned for 2025, which will affect existing analogue telecare equipment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c2b76d72-f762-4470-ac84-784dcbcc0b6d','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Corridor Improvement Programme received decision point 2 approval (case paper) from the Combined Authority on the 29th June 2017 for the programme as a whole.','Corridor Improvement Programme receives Decision Point 2 Approval','West Yorkshire Combined Authority: Your Voice','2017-06-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE0zZffFPM5GkhDwL76t4cmoawutC1tS_eIAeG_3ByWtjb9DNPCSmu9tlsSLBgT1HHvCb_gJoZ2L6tCqBx96hd2hfKjY7UEC0OPM9QG7D8Vg4hoNtE55IYqUWnYNQ3OJiCyK5RNpquPdBV5bUa','The Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP), which includes the A646 Todmorden to Skircoat Moor scheme, received Decision Point 2 approval from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, marking a key milestone in its development. This approval enabled further planning and development of proposals for the scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c2f30e00-2f67-4c16-a7f3-588b545cacca','infrastructure-wakefield-cathedral-square-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.682','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'June 2022 – The scheme\'s Business Case was submitted to the Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities in June. [4]','Cathedral Square Regeneration Scheme\'s Business Case Submitted','Wakefield Council','2022-06-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/cities-towns-and-villages/wakefield/wakefield-city/bread-street-cathedral-square [4]','The business case for the Wakefield Cathedral Square regeneration project was formally submitted to the Department for Levelling Up, Housing and Communities in June 2022. This marked a key milestone in moving the scheme forward.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c335583d-2551-46ec-97f0-f3d91878e1c3','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2021-10-19) A major project, using innovative, \'natural\' measures which protect the environment, improve biodiversity and boost wildlife, has also reduced flood risk to 865 homes and 53 businesses in West Yorkshire. The two-year £388,000 Growing Resilience Natural Flood Management (NFM) Upper Aire project has also created 145 hectares of high-quality green infrastructure. The project, led by Yorkshire Wildlife Trust, aims to reduce dangerous flooding on a stretch of the river between Keighley, Steeton, Skipton and Malham. It has been funded by West Yorkshire Combined Authority via the Leeds City Region Growth Deal. ... This Growing Resilience Natural Flood Management (NFM) Upper Aire scheme has now been completed and a project closure report has been approved by the Combined Authority. ... This Growing Resilience Natural Flood Management Project in the Upper Aire, is the sister project to one successfully led by The National Trust in the Colne and Calder valleys, also funded by the Combined Authority via the Leeds City Region Growth deal and recently successfully completed. [18]','Project reduces flooding risk and boosts environment in West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-10-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHun4hO8Nv0k0zlcdS0Dw4VBQEjMocmpHlRuv53msYEm32-Xw3HcbDbHedZ3dO9lA7B-p1iYAKINyt7yaqC4-SvQNabClwBcddmf6d6PvYKBiW41X8s4-xHuO6oO_U_SKe2J5brSovdl0RPn9KDUvf-kauj-KUWeV_AHaFb12M6GzuDNbnJ5KSSRk90-ebXlyzjU1MVTZFQeOS5EJTQpeSxxP3EPHzMxQIl7gvHHYyVYhwtEVom','West Yorkshire Combined Authority reported the completion of the \'Growing Resilience Natural Flood Management (NFM) Upper Aire project\' (led by Yorkshire Wildlife Trust, £388,000) and its sister project in the Colne and Calder valleys (led by The National Trust). These projects, part of the £1.7 million investment, collectively reduced flood risk for 865 homes and 53 businesses, delivering significant environmental benefits over two years. [18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c335e364-1544-4b75-bdc7-42a2a0827970','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The A646/A6033 Corridor Improvement Programme stretches from Todmorden to Skircoat Moor, near Halifax and is being delivered in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. ... Work is currently taking place around Hebden Bridge, to improve safety on this busy section of highway. ... “These works will bring long-term benefits to the people of Calderdale – making it easier to walk, wheel, cycle and use public transport.','Transforming Travel Around Hebden Bridge with CIP Progress','Calderdale Council News Centre','2023-07-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFDP_lR7CHe9Wx2DYTSRIGnrf3919Shmfz8lIdhatYDTwPnU4s8wE2h6oxhKyiirDMZB7dmNUxxxWRizd-3ZdRGe5dSTRY9Q4b80HuwWxrzqVrri3q78R6ksLA8fb_bGO58fyN_B508mtYr3MoFUx0O-TpdNglcNir1KgZTmtO80l9q','Calderdale Council provided an update on the A646/A6033 Corridor Improvement Programme, delivered in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. The program aims to address congestion, improve facilities for pedestrians and cyclists, and reduce bus delays. Work was specifically noted as ongoing around Hebden Bridge, aiming for long-term benefits.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c37bf96c-a186-4b39-a3e4-2cc276b43630','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Highways England has concerns over Kirklees Council\'s plans for up to 2,000 new homes in Bradley, it has emerged. The body which looks after the country\'s major road network, including motorways, has fears over the impact of extra traffic on the M62 junctions at 24 and 25. Highways England\'s potential objection was revealed at a meeting of Kirklees Council\'s Strategic Planning Committee on Thursday. Councillors were told that the council\'s original \'Bradley Masterplan\' was drawn up in 2017 and much had changed in that time including plans for a re-modelling of the Cooper Bridge roundabout and traffic flow changes on the A62 Leeds Road at Bradley.','M62 congestion fears over plans for hundreds of new homes at Bradley','Huddersfield Hub','2021-07-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEu-Ph1d8nTvDUT-VVQEEiAtWy2LoZgX_KrRUTwKe49i4yBV5HnetWnWfRbUttlm_BZaci2_w-0DBzUKqvlJaToNsZck532_S18qeCQDGCmIrJlfRn1SZpkJuy_7LKuZOwiCjBk2w-Rs_2DvhrZHqaTEeB2gBiqqd9ovLg25-Y67iBqvIX_1Eb98dKc2uH_NGUtRzzPeTQ2Z77EYhNbOecA==','Highways England expressed concerns about the impact of up to 2,000 new homes in Bradley on M62 junctions 24 and 25, raising potential objections. This concern was revealed at a Kirklees Council Strategic Planning Committee meeting. The article highlights that the council\'s original \'Bradley Masterplan\' was drawn up in 2017 and mentions the need for improvements at Cooper Bridge roundabout and A62 Leeds Road traffic flow changes, vital for the wider development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c3abe040-175f-4cd1-ac06-d3be3d9c77af','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-hubs-programme-ukspf-capital-grant',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.294','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Digital Skills Plan, dated November 28, 2022, highlights the importance of digital skills and access. It specifically mentions \'Kirklees Digital Hubs\' as providing free Wi-Fi and a space to access technology in a safe environment, along with a range of free learning courses. It also details a scheme for free device or data loans for up to three months.','West Yorkshire Digital Skills Plan','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-11-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/media/7057/west-yorkshire-digital-skills-plan.pdf','This plan outlines the strategic ambitions for digital skills across West Yorkshire, including efforts in Kirklees. It mentions Kirklees Digital Hubs as providing free Wi-Fi, technology access, and learning courses for residents aged 19 or over, and device/data loan schemes. It sets the broader context for digital inclusion initiatives in the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c3e48ea8-ff9a-4d33-b479-ee728ed2dd5f','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Structural design problems have severely delayed a new £1.3 million market square for Sowerby Bridge. ... Construction was to have started on a new town market square being put in place off Wharf Street this spring. But due to the problems that have arisen, it is likelier it will be spring 2024 before the new square is in place. ... The issues are to do with the levels that they have used and the gradients between the canal at the back and Wharf Street at the front of the site.','Severe delay means work on Sowerby Bridge market square will not be finished until next spring','Halifax Courier','2023-09-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE13NQBPLX6dF0Z9eJJre8PiT5xQcKveBpxlehRXZTN-bBE2y0DIqU78V0mubKTIXY_x2mNp5Tw_CJvUD39wQvaiCswTny_UjBNnvPQMP4y-ojijk0Or2ibwqWfNbrWZBV9fb0K-v2fthTiXiswUda5otVLL0QGld73HEuTo7lolYBpprlZDwP_Ty_6tAljhgnFFvJZ4e3MkRCRBt_1pZCvTsPH8H_gXT2OMytt0t2CSWlL_VROfwGCDlIWCJa3CUWSQc1CuIbbPotDkrgkNOn5ShZj','Construction of the new £1.3 million town market square off Wharf Street, initially slated for Spring 2023, faced significant delays due to underlying structural design issues. These problems, related to the levels and gradients between the canal and Wharf Street, pushed the estimated completion date to Spring 2024, possibly by April.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c3e8fd7a-9b1f-4913-bdce-8c8fbafd98f5','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'enfinium, a leading UK energy-from-waste operator, today announced that its Skelton Grange facility in Leeds has received its first waste delivery — a key milestone as the project moves toward full operations in 2025. Around 200 tonnes of unrecyclable waste arrived at the site from six suppliers, marking the latest commissioning milestone in the project\'s delivery.','New EfW facility in Leeds accepts first waste delivery','enfinium / Circular Online / letsrecycle.com','2025-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQElpeUCux7jbS5T2trBNWuHlicUt7EVjvinstoLuyfT6V9PZu8wr197bOrv-ImwZzbhU7U6HKQscz0ptN5RQUsWn3sZ_00Kl1SJZpr60LiOeXaZVJu5dKTB0vx3zwuVpeJLz2hqclSkXtOlBCiL8Vhk6Tz0QKeZJkrzBpuYOxQzpRRuaJELYHkYuidlRkqr','enfinium\'s Skelton Grange Energy-from-Waste (EfW) facility in Leeds received its first waste delivery, marking a key milestone towards its full operation in 2025. This facility is crucial as it will serve as the primary heat source for the Aire Valley Low Carbon District Heating & Electricity Scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c41b7ad5-5a7e-4c70-ab07-dc6c37fe3812','infrastructure-home-bargains-garforth-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.429','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A newly announced partnership between Leeds City Council and EB Charging will see 84 new \'fast\' charging bays installed at 15 locations across the city—with the first 30 bays at six locations already live. 54 bays at nine more locations are due to go live by the early summer. Each of the new bays will be easily located on services such as Plugshare or Zap-map when live. [11]','Leeds City Council Announces Partnership for 84 New EV Fast Charging Bays','Leeds City Council News / Business Motoring','2023-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEaumzBIajMw8ByK8PAtfcpOA29Tle8JY45CuTAM71UJx9hn5edx4WHRZRzJ5WDzeErSRSCPcecuWssXY-Cb-zo1vcIDmFXWyAETsxzEb_I9VOQ_l6yksyCkudxGta_JNEgXeZ7qISoaGCtwNW03p3dR5sLFyFmI3RJpN1VNL5Ck6mtEIEjH7k9P-mha4r8TCARbHBXF5ljhxDPI','Leeds City Council, the local authority for Garforth, announced a partnership with EB Charging on March 21, 2023, to install 84 new \'fast\' charging bays at 15 locations across the city. This initiative aimed to improve access to local vehicle chargers for residents, particularly where off-street parking is limited.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c48e0f32-642f-4668-b6bc-1f720ca327db','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'People are being asked for their views on the latest proposals to create three \'shared transport hubs\' in Todmorden and Hebden Bridge. Shared transport hubs are one-stop shops for transport services, with plans in Calderdale including facilities for car club vehicle parking locations, electric vehicle charging, secure cycle parking, access to shared e-bikes and bike repair stands. ... Under the latest plans, the three hubs would be located at Hebden Bridge market place car park, Todmorden College, and School Lane in Todmorden. ... The consultation will run from Tuesday 5th November to Monday 2nd December 2024.','A new way of providing transport services could be coming to Calderdale as plans take another step forward | News Centre','Calderdale Council News Centre','2024-11-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEO7ZQDVKLnn6viBjyFQBbtkUatqUdNxS6Cxa5pwlD_UhqSXr1DG_9TwiUVX04zwrpauQBmGLYlLM-G3S92uk4qIfVsj6hRTUjq-MemRgaugY4UshSiFn8v_9XJAVm1UqLMjQp58GJl330ZYwL7AOG5tscuv1PAvjP2Zwfy3jSesozqjdhvVngECl9fSsdg6o2W1_j-6goTiOtA-N7NHia48CSOhcXAOC6Z3lzK5WbbPWEo8hBu44GBky1oLfLL5WtOc2y6IHE==','Calderdale Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced a public consultation on updated proposals for three shared transport hubs in Hebden Bridge and Todmorden. The proposed locations include Hebden Bridge market place car park, Todmorden College, and School Lane in Todmorden. These hubs are planned to offer facilities like car club vehicle parking, EV charging, secure cycle parking, shared e-bikes, and bike repair stands. The consultation period for these proposals ran from November 5 to December 2, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c4904028-d1f3-4891-9e8d-2f7733661bc2','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Kirklees council have been awarded £1.5million by the government to upgrade their Penistone rail line between Huddersfield and Sheffield. Supported by neighboring councils and local MPs, in 2023 they managed to secure million in leveling up cash. ... The plan for this upgrade is to increase the speed along the Penistone line and improve the rail infrastructure. This will allow two trains to travel along the northern section of the line every hour, in both directions. ... By the end of this project, Journey times between Huddersfield and Sheffield will be reduced to less than an hour in travel time. [18]','1.5 Million awarded to Kirklees Council to upgrade Penistone rail line','Media Hud','2025-05-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.mediahud.co.uk/1-5-million-awarded-to-kirklees-council-to-upgrade-penistone-rail-line/','Media Hud reported that Kirklees Council received £1.5 million from the government to advance the Penistone rail line upgrade. This funding is for the detailed business case following the initial £48 million Levelling Up award in 2023. The project aims to improve connections, increase speed and frequency (two trains per hour), and upgrade stations between Huddersfield and Sheffield, reducing journey times to under an hour.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c4c7bde2-1066-45bd-9d0e-952cde3c2a0c','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The final round of public consultation on the ECF-backed project is underway, while new CGIs of the neighbourhood have been released. A detailed planning application for phase one will be submitted later this summer, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site. Incommunities has also been selected as ECF\'s preferred funding partner to deliver the first phase of townhouses for sale and rent at Bradford City Village, subject to a final legal agreement. Work on phase one is expected to start in spring 2026, while demolition of the Oastler site should go ahead this autumn. [5]','Phase one of Bradford City Village advances - Place Yorkshire','Place Yorkshire','2025-05-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH8fhBxHS80a940CPI9AZkEkAM2GvExaFeGyx7Ni7soGOY61hq-Pw35wsxzeMAyCtXLCc0ZDnDmF1K1JMVi28pBmcWgUJSBe7vDi_MRhJPCwuGDoOLWnAfveEUzLd7Yg_RL_jFnoTHOHUO2bKqXahIwLuHcGcQDAhYB5-mqtS6AX120LVfxWA==','This report confirmed the final round of public consultation for the ECF-backed project and the release of new CGIs. It reiterated that Incommunities had been selected as ECF\'s preferred funding partner for the first phase of townhouses. Work on phase one was expected to start in spring 2026, with demolition of the Oastler site slated for autumn 2025. A detailed planning application for phase one was to be submitted later that summer.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c66aa5cf-d9f7-4696-8b37-20e400af5d84','infrastructure-yorkshire-water-amp8-infrastructure-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.595','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water have announced a huge £7.8bn investment into their system over a five year period. The plan, which has been submitted for approval by Ofwat, focuses on improving water quality and protecting the environment. £3.1bn will go towards improving the resilience of the pipes in the network. £1.9bn will be used to reduce the use of storm overflows and to protect the environment. [11]','Yorkshire Water plan £7.8bn investment between 2025 and 2030','The Northern Echo','2023-10-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/23825827.yorkshire-water-plan-7-8bn-investment-2025-2030/','Yorkshire Water announced a £7.8 billion investment into its system over the five-year AMP8 period (2025-2030), with the plan submitted to Ofwat for approval. The plan focuses on improving water quality and protecting the environment, allocating £3.1 billion towards improving network pipe resilience and £1.9 billion to reduce storm overflows and protect the environment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c678eb92-d706-4374-94c1-8be57c35934c','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At their meeting next week, Wakefield Cabinet look set to approve plans to improve the charging infrastructure for electric vehicles (EV) across the district. The council\'s new strategy outlines its vision for EV charging so that residents and businesses have enough access. Coun Jack Hemingway said the number of electric vehicles on the road is expected to continue to grow exponentially, demonstrating the need to provide sufficient charging infrastructure. “We want our charging network to be high quality, open and accessible to everyone, which will of course also contribute towards a greener district for all.” Cabinet members are expected to approve the strategy at a meeting on Tuesday March 21.','Wakefield Council set to introduce electric vehicle charging plan across the district','Wakefield Express / LCRIG','2023-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFdtuIMqU1IuMDXiyPBrD7Eb896QxfB0HogammaB34PJdq6hihtKGd1rsbLj8jZ5VX_TaLSf6IUDeWcnqgZGgkrL5hfnzlt1AXWN1XHwIPUCtZo3xgYnJGMeH5-I75JsChmCXqC7tuejglnHfkakCkwGhHVRgPdrSGkOl6JJQezmOFusOSf1BNGsMpX0vZDD_zn9pY8qmO5iNNl66CEkIlC4ODBEODITdbLmL0mwVEQ2SaYMsh3cXa5XpoTrTYsPYHhYVyNh_jZbA==','Wakefield Council\'s Cabinet was set to approve a new strategy on March 21 to improve electric vehicle charging infrastructure across the district. The plan aims to increase access for residents and businesses, addressing the growing number of EVs and contributing to a greener district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c692e3e8-1257-48c3-853e-397529e9402e','infrastructure-kirklees-bradley-park-housing-scheme---phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.749','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme concept is a series of highways improvements at the Cooper Bridge and Bradley Road junctions and surrounded by roads. The future development growth includes employment and housing growth with the Local Plan highlighting 31,140 new homes to be delivered over the plan period (2031). This includes a number of site allocations within the vicinity of Cooper Bridge. The most significant of which is land north of Bradley Road (HS11) which allocated 1,950 additional homes. Why are you not building the preferred option presented in 2021? Whilst there was support for the proposal in 2021 which included a series of highway improvements to the Bradley and Cooper Bridge junctions, this is no longer deliverable due to escalating costs. Our proposal is still at a conceptual stage, but we propose to build on what we have learnt from the previous engagement in 2021 by reducing the impact on trees and introducing sustainable drainage.','FAQs | A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme - second consultation','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-05-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHhANkWVrf_xztWP8FG-kIJDBHwvjDWN_jzqn_GCy0XGDfRIUAmxuJvoWO0ftPa37F2jw7MfI8CtnWkUY2RHol13ogKO4k1unuqTLm21rb89uPfZ76XnyBo27FjyV1EH0Vs68m9u-adXHnELzSEeLugGnU96IVG==','This consultation explains the need for highways improvements at Cooper Bridge and Bradley Road junctions due to existing congestion and future development growth, including 1,950 homes allocated north of Bradley Road (HS11). Crucially, it states that the preferred option from 2021 for the A62 to Cooper Bridge scheme is \'no longer deliverable due to escalating costs,\' necessitating new proposals that reduce environmental impact.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c69dbb87-6c6a-4e4d-abc5-5b7ffb628083','infrastructure-manchester-road-bus-improvements-scheme-south-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.869','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WORK on a Park and Ride scheme in Bradford is expected to continue, despite the fact there is no funding available for the car park. The proposal would see an almost 700-space car park created near the M606 with a new bus hub and improved bus routes down Manchester Road. On Friday West Yorkshire Combined Authority is expected to approve £1.5m in funding to develop a full business case for the scheme. Phase 1 (bus priority measures) is to be delivered through the Transforming Cities fund. Phase 2 (Active Travel Cycle Route and Park and Ride) is currently unfunded and will not be delivered at this time.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority to approve funding for South Bradford Park and Ride Full Business Case','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-05-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHhMAgs18kKPZeyNBlBls7Aw6BEgO1z3mesqPHiTEi1v1GVfnQ9ocHzQIdnJjnUx3pHdixj4WAHAe05--d3xIoY7BsPryRO--1mHKhtqvHX86DmFBlj44j_V4YmcWcWVK7J0SUuL31zGbXTqmidkxaxBtK_OMqtHDrluaBN3at0dnsL8RjVFVgC9Cyn1Pifa72LHWN51yllGiafljI=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority was expected to approve £1.5 million in funding to develop a full business case for the South Bradford Park and Ride scheme. This indicates continued progress for the wider project, even though the park and ride aspect itself was currently unfunded, with an emphasis on bus priority and active travel measures along Manchester Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c6fdd111-a8ed-45c3-988e-d72addcbc016','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with ECF (formerly the English Cities Fund), is developing plans to unlock the potential of what was the former retail and trading heart of Bradford city centre. City Village will involve the delivery of up to 1,000 homes in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas. We first shared our early-stage ideas during a phase of visioning engagement with the local community and businesses in Winter 2022/23. We carefully considered the feedback received to help inform the evolving masterplan, which we provided an update on in Summer 2024. Since then, we\'ve continued to refine the plans. We are now introducing detailed plans for the first phase of the project and are once again inviting community feedback before submitting a planning application later this year.','Initial Visioning Engagement for Bradford City Village','Bradford City Village Official Website','2023-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHLprD_YvMLCwXrHRLQSRbgSXOy4TZusoyCckqivFwRIGmHOb67iWkUg6x3swvu4qhad7O0_C8NjlC_7pGSwrYBPADAU0Ax9HpJuugbAaI5xyh2dxe0nIqDZ_WZFlpf0w==','Bradford Council, in partnership with ECF, began early-stage visioning engagement with the local community and businesses to gather feedback for the Bradford City Village masterplan. This initial phase helped to shape the evolving plans for the regeneration area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c71a35a3-ed36-41d1-84a0-0df59c17e806','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Highway widening to A6120 west of Horsforth roundabout along with new cycleway and footway construction starts Wednesday 24 July, until scheme completion in summer 2025. There will also be new and improved pedestrian and cycle facilities between the two roundabouts linking to the facilities at Fink Hill, and those currently under construction between Rodley and Dawson\'s Corner.','Highway Widening and Cycleway Construction A6120 West of Horsforth Roundabout Commences','Leeds City Council','2024-07-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFEkLEGx2GJQzl1t5dfHHbXJ0VesMn1rWpdef4sdMtT6519ptgB8OrSdBTkfm5FNhImd9I1M68MIXyGDt5FGcBqCtG7iGIq41Zd-CTul2CrCye3qCDEyfowbVrkBiwSXuSyZvPtPN4aKo1L5_skzoxQUh47f556Esk1Ld-U3ycwDuLL8s2qPwfQvuAO2rAGJIKsQyOCxT2mGztwkzs=','Highway widening to the A6120 west of Horsforth roundabout, along with the construction of new cycleways and footways, began on Wednesday, July 24, 2024. This work is a crucial part of the segregated off-highway cycle path from Horsforth roundabout to Rodley roundabout and is scheduled for completion in summer 2025. This phase includes creating new and improved pedestrian and cycle facilities linking to those already in place at Fink Hill.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c7246c20-4647-4df3-befd-e4df375cc093','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ambitious projects in Sowerby Bridge are progressing well as part of the £2 million programme to revitalise the high street. The Old Town Hall and the Fire & Water complex are two of the key schemes benefiting from £2 million from the Government\'s High Streets Heritage Action Zone programme. ... Further projects in the Sowerby Bridge High Street Heritage Action Zone programme include ... a high street shop front improvement scheme, which is now open and offering businesses and property owners on Wharf Street up to 80% contribution towards improvement works.','Significant progress made to transform historic Sowerby Bridge high street','Calderdale Council News Centre','2022-10-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH4CHrQsJZzw9JqNObbQMf7y9BsbEFuxhX25yci91BsYHT-CKb-FSZSs0AfoGQwRIyCfmcvCJcRMq0z2zZq5CVZMESm9hI1H8qO9sjx1dCXL0HuZ0KHmtwmefeteRJOg7MODsu57BKtx2Tc4sgdS1nacTZYqkunZkZBfVY-jiBu03aasw3_rHAUm10junokg-TU2nIK_kL7oeSkCnsttf5u41Avhg==','Calderdale Council reported significant progress on various projects in Sowerby Bridge, funded by the £2 million High Streets Heritage Action Zone programme. Key achievements included works on the Old Town Hall and the Fire & Water complex. Additionally, a new shop front improvement scheme was launched for businesses on Wharf Street, offering substantial funding for facade enhancements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c8302510-afa2-42a2-8f52-c847cf8b8ab7','infrastructure-enfinium-skelton-grange-energy-from-waste-facility',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.539','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Engie has inked a three-year deal to purchase power from Enfinium\'s Skelton Grange energy from waste facility in Leeds, which is expected to start turning hundreds of thousands of tonnes of residual waste a year into low carbon heat and electricity from this summer. Under the Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) announced today, Enfinium is set to supply 390GWh of electricity a year from the combined heat and power (CHP) plant to French energy and services operator Engie over a three-year period, beginning this year.','Engie inks three-year deal to secure power from Enfinium Skelton Grange plant','BusinessGreen, Energy Live News','2025-06-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGOfwLsA2EvsUlWSx1dkx2uSsvqmB2K7rQiq5p9fzqcdLv-WsCOoHskJgaKLjfACY2VoTxD8kWLlE2ZUTu8jsrQkyW0Xkgy0ruAK06b2v_vt71vJa04nHMR3qZYdlp9zEOrkg3uAMgxskr5UOJNh-l-w49rh9zoPdNFzffE5v0mHt056zqRnUhiq7NZLWX3fKgwRzqImybpzRHNLnjC','In June 2025, Engie signed a three-year Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) with Enfinium to secure approximately 390 GWh of electricity per year from the Skelton Grange facility. This agreement, beginning in 2025, will supply low-carbon electricity to residential and industrial customers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c8636c03-447b-486e-bde7-b3102b7ec93c','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Early enabling activity at Dawsons Corner has started in earnest with the construction of a \'bellmouth\' entrance off Bradford Road for the primary site entrance, and the arrival of a heavy duty bulldozer. Pedestrian and cycle routes have been diverted to permit this work, conducted mainly at night to minimise traffic disruption. An information event at Pudsey Civic Hall on 15 May was attended by some 150 members of the public and the expected timetable was published. Enabling works are proceeding as planned. Completion of the full scheme is expected in Winter 2026, around 18 months away. [21]','Dawsons Corner reconstruction steps up a gear with early enabling activity','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-05-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFQS0C3oPcyAO6tvDQQwvk3bGhzeWGkHcPMpGU2g6noBpaaagmyzMYw2cL4b8r6kIe4haCrfj8IJGETIkq90b_miIDaXYxVq6WXWWNXe-O2JvXNdgFJyuOSsOiYcIxh6BNkfH99UtLYDUKswQMVdFMnPwgg188VEx60TJFfxzNHpdP-jvTAx3U','Early enabling activity for the Dawsons Corner reconstruction began with the construction of a \'bellmouth\' entrance and the arrival of heavy machinery. Pedestrian and cycle routes were diverted. Completion of the full scheme is expected in Winter 2026, marking the start of physical works on site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c8f63bbe-8ed2-4094-983c-a00f04443f2d','infrastructure-tingley-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.342','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for a new electric vehicle (EV) charging hub near Leeds have been submitted to the city council following \'overwhelming\' public approval. A recent consultation saw more than three-quarters of the 157 respondents (76%) say that they are in favour of BP\'s proposals for 18 covered ultra-fast charging bays on the site of a closed pub on Dewsbury Road in Leeds. Along with bays for disabled users, 13 vehicle parking spaces and a 323 sq. m retail unit are also proposed as part of plans to regenerate the site, which has been vacant since the pub closed in 2018. If the project gets the green light, it will see residents benefit from convenient access to new services and facilities as well as drivers on the Bradford Road and Dewsbury Road and the nearby M62 motorway, say planners. It will also address the lack of EV charging facilities in the Leeds area, enabling people to charge their electric vehicles in under 30 minutes.','Leeds EV charging hub receives \'overwhelming\' approval','LAPV','2023-05-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEDoN7fQVH-bcYF9w2aQT-NPANhBF_RcoTYsfCK8nDZrrzK8xnEZgIHlksX7lF6ypit4LbhnCnEJ6Wp46GtPorYwPLp1Y5GDNUYAP04wdGOWPAHBFRCe8AvtAOYKotLRf7e9MGb6oExUbVZydsEUUQ73hCiKmmDTW6ptbhWb3bk0b-xHP0KdgkoomKpeg==','Plans for a new electric vehicle (EV) charging hub on the former White Bear pub site in Tingley, submitted to Leeds City Council by Lichfields (on behalf of BP Pulse), received overwhelming public support. A consultation showed 76% of respondents were in favour of BP\'s proposals for 18 ultra-fast charging bays on Dewsbury Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c9351b8e-5476-41cd-a873-5b671837cdad','infrastructure-virgin-media-o2-free-business-broadband-for-vcse-organisations',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.305','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Virgin Media O2 has continued to act on its pledge to invest over £10 billion pounds to upgrade the UK, with over £188 million spent across Yorkshire in recent years. Through the company\'s Project Lightning programme, ultrafast broadband has been made available to over 324,000 additional homes and businesses in the region. That includes 24,500 premises in North Yorkshire, 128,600 in South Yorkshire and 171,100 in West Yorkshire. The investment has seen over 900 jobs either created or secured, as well as additional contracts with local firms, to help build the required infrastructure to keep the region connected. [24]','Virgin Media O2 invests millions to upgrade connectivity, jobs and digital inclusion across Yorkshire','Virgin Media O2 Newsroom','2022-12-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEeBnRUNZRMfgsln6PGWrrB8VeZFojMn10c_clr_v3P4RpdsiygVU8dNjnO0JRGgHBVv9YG5Odxg8b0br4lZYV5o8Ztk-GU3b52hUzoJGjub33F9cOVNr2FpX685Z-urF7JNMUDQ6BiTFGUg2i3hjLF5HgX_SeWgfXRgbuQphTfnNk6G2CNtrs6o9LYy90JuF6EtxlJPiPTUdtY5VAG_ixmogAohYUEH-MkTnkwr2Q4Ph6Jh9QVWkGO6-FYSrdFdZ2kkGW708Nx41BWMlCcJ__8gfqi9XRz0IkC7xSsszZKkOMOeFJLdrQJtBYfOM0hufZ6DJA==','Virgin Media O2 pledged over £10 billion to upgrade UK connectivity, with over £188 million spent in Yorkshire. This investment led to 324,000 new ultrafast broadband connections for homes and businesses in the region, including 171,100 in West Yorkshire, and supported digital inclusion initiatives with Good Things Foundation.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c984227f-242d-42b1-97e2-ee576e8ae4f0','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Works have officially started on-site for the first two plots of the Mabgate Masterplan in Leeds. The first phase sees the development of College House and Enfield Centre, two major teaching buildings for Leeds City College. [10] Together, these buildings will accommodate over 1,500 students and staff across a combined 6,800 sqm of innovative learning space. [10] The development transforms and creates around 70,000 sq ft of high quality facilities, office space for staff, and residential properties, while contributing to the regeneration of the area and providing community resources on a site which was underutilised for some time. [8] The project commenced in November 2023. [8]','Phase 1 of Mabgate Masterplan construction commences on site','Cartwright Pickard / Mason Clark Associates','2023-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGYOVthXaLXPe4eoYTFkg0Oyp0rirbBgV6bWeh2uPzx1z09W7-nhn_oKJoQbl3u8JTV25g371W2DlE38ybwyXYl3uqjpMtLKgAIlthELv2s5Yk0DVOpfBW4aBSlfHnQ0hENWq6lrg3hdy49A11JUX8bhHsHfL4ty-JpXD81IIBMDg==','Official on-site works began for the first two plots of the Mabgate Masterplan. This phase focuses on developing College House and the Enfield Centre, two key teaching buildings designed to provide 6,800 sqm of innovative learning space for over 1,500 students and staff, marking a significant step in the campus redevelopment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c98f2e12-3e25-4424-b443-4080b409c2d2','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water has embarked on a series of major investments to reduce storm overflows and improve water quality across the region. These projects form part of a £180 million program slated for completion by April 2025, with an additional £1.5 billion planned between 2025 and 2030 to reduce storm overflows and improve water quality. Yorkshire Water has more than 2200 overflows in its network, and is working to reduce how often they operate to keep rivers healthy, focusing on the overflows that operate most frequently.','Yorkshire Water invests in reducing sewer overflows across its service region','Water & Wastewater Treatment','2025-01-21 00:00:00.000','https://wwtonline.co.uk/news/yorkshire-water-invests-in-reducing-sewer-overflows-across-its-service-region/628038.article','Yorkshire Water is undertaking major investments to reduce storm overflows and improve water quality, as part of a £180 million program completing by April 2025, with an additional £1.5 billion planned between 2025 and 2030. The company aims to reduce the frequency of overflow operations by focusing on the most active sites, employing various solutions like increased storage and sustainable drainage systems.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('c9d77340-6d34-403e-bb00-64513a0655c5','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Meanwhile, Leeds Conservatoire (formerly Leeds College of Music) has become the thirteenth non-residential customer to have signed a contract to connect. The new connections are expected to reduce the city\'s annual carbon footprint by 279 tonnes, supporting efforts to end the city\'s contribution to climate change by transitioning to \'net zero\' emissions. [8]','Hundreds more households in Leeds to benefit from low carbon heat network','Ener-Vate','2023-12-13 00:00:00.000','https://ener-vate.co.uk/news/hundreds-more-households-in-leeds-to-benefit-from-low-carbon-heat-network/','This news release announced that Leeds Conservatoire (formerly Leeds College of Music) had become the thirteenth non-residential customer to sign a contract to connect to the Leeds PIPES district heating network. This expansion was expected to reduce the city\'s annual carbon footprint by 279 tonnes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ca0cdaae-7115-47ae-a0d5-deb0eec24bc2','infrastructure-west-halifax-improved-streets-for-people',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.150','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This report details the engagement activity undertaken by Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council (CMBC) between March and May 2023, to inform the final detailed designs of the West Halifax Improved Streets for People scheme. This period was not a formal public consultation, as the aim was to share the updated proposals based on the feedback received in previous rounds of consultation.','West Halifax Improved Streets for People Public Engagement Report 2023','Calderdale Council','2023-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHbhU9EbIl2G86xwlCpp8FbxJrO-68LUADdkGqE8eWNIQwfzbVsnGLTGC_1cZSk_DtiVddLD5U4VOn8iEIOf9K85RxtuXRY90bIPEwgQf9sghQc1WvyOXM1J620NTIryTfIiSPFGh9Syw_R1QOWAeoKqmpe4Hi4puFWmLSPvJnNi7OLATCKFAraKnWdPGLTjlZ8KY_67nNVLP5U1Wky-nwjF4Na','Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council undertook a period of targeted public engagement between March and May 2023 to update stakeholders on the current scheme plans for West Halifax Improved Streets for People. This report details the activities and feedback received, which aimed to inform the final detailed designs based on previous consultation rounds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ca10d3dc-fba9-4e14-a749-5d6644084c41','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield is now benefitting from new technology that will tackle cable theft and ensure continued reliability for EV drivers in the city. The UK\'s largest ultra-rapid EV charging network InstaVolt, is introducing CableGuard™ to its EV charging points - and it\'s now in Wakefield which has been identified as a hotspot for cable thefts. The technology was first introduced in April 2025 as part of new measures to protect InstaVolt\'s EV infrastructure and is now being rolled out across the country. InstaVolt has also implemented a suite of enhanced security measures across its network including AI-powered CCTV systems capable of identifying suspicious activity in real time and monitored around the clock by security teams, including a team of on-site patrols led by ex-military operatives.','New tech targets cable cutting in Wakefield','Wakefield Express','2025-05-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/crime/new-tech-targets-cable-cutting-in-wakefield-4650578','InstaVolt deployed its CableGuard™ technology in Wakefield to combat cable theft at EV charging points. This innovation, a protective sleeve for cables, was introduced in April 2025 and is part of enhanced security measures including AI-powered CCTV and on-site patrols.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ca884b18-63a2-42f8-b7e8-9aa22beded0d','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Digital Enterprise is being delivered by Leeds City Council and is funded by the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund (UKSPF). In West Yorkshire, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority leads the implementation of the Fund as part of the Mayor\'s ambition to make West Yorkshire the best place to work, learn and live.  We can support your business if you\'re focused on growth, have been trading for a minimum of 3 years, you\'re based, or have operational premises, in West Yorkshire, whether that\'s Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds or Wakefield, and your annual taxable turnover is £100,000 or above. We\'re focused on supporting businesses with 5 – 100 full-time equivalent employees (FTEs) as they scale their operations. For projects costing up to £25,000 or between £25,000 – £100,000, we can offer match-funded grants to support digital projects that will have a significant and transformational impact on your business. [7]','About | Digital Enterprise | Invest in Digital','Digital Enterprise','2023-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.digitalenterprise.co.uk/about/','The official \'About\' page for Digital Enterprise confirms it is delivered by Leeds City Council and funded by the UK Government through the UK Shared Prosperity Fund, with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority leading implementation. It states the program supports growth-focused businesses in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, or Wakefield, trading for a minimum of 3 years, with £100,000+ turnover and 5-100 employees. It highlights the availability of match-funded grants for digital projects.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cb60f0be-23c7-4d4c-ac5b-a35a54700bf4','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to overhaul a busy junction between Bradford and Leeds will slash congestion, highways chiefs believe. Dawson\'s Corner, in Pudsey, is ravaged by heavy traffic and delayed buses at peak times. Now, Leeds City Council has submitted proposals to rejig the four-way junction, with a view to widening the approach roads, installing new bus lanes and pedestrian crossings. A planning statement attached to the application said the road\'s current layout, “does not provide adequate capacity for existing traffic” and that “consequently congestion frequently occurs on the approaches” to Dawson\'s Corner. [12]','Plans to re-jig Dawson\'s Corner are revealed (Planning application submitted)','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2022-05-18 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFkRfMMPaDVqmp_2824oThu2H19uiP5H4jyPGTf39QcIduY6GDajWUeqtVwamqdV1VoqOcM9VHiYTYFTR0Tm2jePd0moTDAPCzuRH9sTRyEVMX_Je_ozBFslqGIpLniBcZmYQjMHP2wg9pwieMspFbGVCtUcJLOIXPGMW8yIQa5fwZ3M5q45JhGQHEB9j8_LV5W2RaOOg','Leeds City Council submitted proposals to rejig the four-way Dawson\'s Corner junction, including widening approach roads, installing new bus lanes, and pedestrian crossings, aiming to slash congestion. This marked a formal step in the project\'s development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cba13b4e-b00e-43a5-960b-da6b061f2d73','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Combined Authority has been reassured that while the structure has reached the end of its design life, it can remain operational for longer with a certain level of investment. In addition, work is now starting on a longer-term plan, capitalising on the exciting programme to bring Mass Transit to Bradford, with an alternative multimodal bus interchange facility in the city centre plan being drawn up in the coming months. A detailed report covering all aspects of the Interchange and its future will be brought to the October Combined Authority meeting for members to make a final decision, along with timescales for reopening.','Plans to safely reopen Bradford Interchange Bus Station drawn up ahead of final decision next month','WYMetro (West Yorkshire Combined Authority)','2024-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHaEpVNy-Eo39VJwfNVRKPTsvXC4liAb-R5Eq19DLMKD6HR4JoY-FVsZfhldF-z1KY-widTAjcVRiHs4XL6v04VKYzZbwz8OoQD-ZhLvd-uwOVD4YtuBhamKn4I95Ue3swMrhQ0lDgjsVVs34dP5d_KgxAq_cJ2cF1mAxqTvRCy_lIizqhSOEUqgqE98AE9PxSkYgMjTmnosvwyAIHQahghkqW-6iNMsRxhj4oxywVkjX6x_v1P6Y2uUzX3rzfojtu8f-oudihELLODT63_87jD','The Combined Authority is actively developing plans for the safe reopening of Bradford Interchange Bus Station, with a final decision anticipated at the October Combined Authority meeting. Experts have provided reassurance that, despite reaching the end of its design life, the structure can remain operational with targeted investment. Additionally, a longer-term strategy is underway to establish an alternative multimodal bus interchange facility within the city center. The lower concourse of the Interchange is expected to reopen by the end of October 2024. [15]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cc31f291-6bce-429c-b8ab-3e3ab4c46328','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Environment Agency gives notice that it proposes to carry out piling and improvement works to the flood embankment surrounding Copley Village, Calderdale. ... An Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) Screening Report ... was submitted to Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council in August 2023. A Screening Opinion was received in September 2023, confirming works are not likely to have significant effects on the environment and the scheme does not constitute EIA development. The scheme is likely to result in beneficial effects for biodiversity and flood risk and the water environment. Initial enabling works will commence in January 2024.','Copley Village, Halifax - Flood Alleviation Scheme. - Public Notice Portal (Environment Agency Announcement)','Public Notice Portal (Environment Agency)','2023-12-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF-8JLmgqKYzR6WKZzDnS-ZHeb00GTWP1w8l5A-2i6m6ZBlMWsx7qtgFtJQ7eiYNYs1CECd24BPsxlMQCg3y85WNVNxVf7CWJ-_Dr44CaoJFuk0-EWOlFGuNOfpHwVMc0otp8t0qWXvEncPoE1m9xKwzCmfua_nKLSbtF-quvyTaGTn','The Environment Agency issued a notice about proposed piling and improvement works to the flood embankment surrounding Copley Village. An Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) Screening Report confirmed no significant environmental effects, and initial enabling works were scheduled to commence in January 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cc556a60-d7e4-42d8-88db-f3d3e856abc5','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire and the Humber to benefit from £19.8 billion transport investment... nearly £4 billion through City Region Sustainable Transport Settlements ( CRSTS ) to ensure all 6 Northern city regions will receive more than double their CRSTS1 funding to improve connectivity in their areas, which could pay for schemes such as bus rapid transit corridors in Bradford and Leeds. ... £2.1 billion for West Yorkshire, including £800 from savings from HS2 . This includes a £500 million downpayment for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit. ... funding of £2.5 billion will ensure delivery of a West Yorkshire Mass Transit System for Leeds and the wider area, providing better connections to Bradford and Wakefield.','Yorkshire and the Humber to benefit from £19.8 billion transport investment - GOV.UK','GOV.UK','2023-10-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGtFAFC1idSUu2pK1ZWInpN2IkZw6NmVlWhGOyUQ7FUFKwTQl7-Iyez3MVJ_tykEDAukNQ_W1uMaoH74bP3lqL6cTACBLGczny9iXkMRHB1KIZcUBLtLjFFE7ThSzHaIdeD9EVFhBGCpFg88DGeAor39l4mbYmOufvXzGOXihvKk1AidONChQ45wih2GDBPf1whk6NE7eSceDzFZPDJh3Eb5SH7lucQnw==','A government announcement details a substantial transport investment package for Yorkshire and the Humber, including £2.1 billion specifically allocated for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit System. This funding, partially redirected from HS2 savings, is intended to support an integrated transport network, encompassing initiatives like bus rapid transit corridors in Bradford and Leeds, and a mass transit system with connections to Bradford and Wakefield, under which mobility hubs are envisioned as crucial components.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cc55a72d-e81a-45f4-b6da-eeac4e07e7af','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The second round of public consultation for the Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements scheme was launched. This consultation presented updated proposed plans to reshape Bradford city centre by improving walking and cycling routes, removing traffic from some roads, and introducing new green outdoor spaces. The plans were part of the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund.','Second Round of Public Consultation on City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-06-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements','The second round of public consultation for the Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements scheme was launched. This consultation presented updated proposed plans to reshape Bradford city centre by improving walking and cycling routes, removing traffic from some roads, and introducing new green outdoor spaces. The plans were part of the Leeds City Region Transforming Cities Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ccbc74c8-8af7-4cfd-93bc-93a2291003cb','infrastructure-bp-pulse-stourton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.422','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'STOURTON SERVICE STATION. Pontefract Road LEEDS LS10 1SW. ... Fuels: AdBlue, AdBlue Cannister, AdBlue Pump, Diesel On, EV Charging, Truck Diesel, BP Ultimate, BP Ultimate Diesel, BP Ultimate Unleaded 95. Features: Toilet, Jet Wash, Bistro, Cashpoint, Car Wash, Mobile Enabled, Open 24 hours. There is an EV charging point available within this station. Location Details. Lat / Lng. 53.77457, -1.5132.','STOURTON SERVICE STATION - BP Locations','BP Locations','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.bp.com/en_gb/united-kingdom/home/products-and-services/our-locations/stourton-service-station.html','BP\'s official website lists the Stourton Service Station on Pontefract Road, Leeds (LS10 1SW) and explicitly includes \'EV Charging\' among its available facilities, confirming its presence and official support.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cd1060c3-3043-4735-9f5b-6bbba368331f','infrastructure-stubbing-holme-road-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.220','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Council is working with the Environment Agency to create a new car park at Stubbing Holme once the flood defence work is complete.','Transforming travel around Hebden Bridge','Calderdale Council News Centre','2023-07-03 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/transforming-travel-around-hebden-bridge/','Calderdale Council reported on a major road improvement program around Hebden Bridge. The article mentioned that the Council is working with the Environment Agency to create a new car park at Stubbing Holme once the flood defence work is complete, indicating the ongoing nature of the flood alleviation scheme and its integration with wider infrastructure improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cd286dc9-15e8-48fa-a342-c9e050ab5253','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Residential developer Rise Homes has brought Spinners Yard, an 11-storey build-to-rent (BTR) development in Leeds city centre, to market. Contractor Clegg Construction completed work on the 185-unit scheme this month, with the developer set to host an open house on 7 June. Spinners Yard is a 185-apartment, U-shaped BTR scheme constructed on Regent Street in Mabgate in the city centre. The building is also connected to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, a £62M initiative aiming to reduce emissions in the city. Sarah Snape, Managing Director of Rise Homes, said: “Our Spinners Yard development has transformed the former brownfield site on Regent Street. Rise Homes is looking forward to welcoming our first residents and creating a thriving community.”','Rise Homes launches £40M Spinners Yard scheme in Leeds','Built Environment Networking','2025-05-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.built-environment-networking.com/news/rise-homes-launches-40m-spinners-yard-scheme-in-leeds/','Residential developer Rise Homes officially launched its 11-storey, 185-unit build-to-rent development, Spinners Yard, located on Regent Street in Mabgate, Leeds city centre. Construction was completed in May 2025, and the building is confirmed to be connected to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, contributing to emissions reduction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cda4d150-1999-4b88-9d52-4bf9826e0d9f','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'ECF\'s scheme for a regenerated city centre neighbourhood has progressed to the next stage with a detailed planning application for Phase One submitted by Avison Young. A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces, each with designated parking space. If plans are approved, demolition of the Oastler site is expected to begin later this year, ahead of work beginning on Phase One in spring 2026. [10]','Plans in for Bradford City Village - Place Yorkshire','Place Yorkshire','2025-09-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGA3m2tlhvVn4hYTEYkfuicvF3hhtIrKn83dHbime_gzSffWpdyZFrVnGZrFDrmuwuGTg48ivwnD_Luo1Km6k0EM2qwB5S-isSbcUfCFOuSKwv7eJI1cX06DCcXxDcwnahoihsgFmsTKpthSy7uNV26fIDJURwxVx7hsmmU6OEr','ECF\'s detailed planning application for Phase One of the Bradford City Village, including 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, was lodged. This report reinforced the project\'s ambition to transform the \'top of town\' area with 1,000 homes and new green spaces, with demolition of the Oastler site expected to begin later in 2025 and construction of Phase One starting in spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cdb56d49-9be7-4293-8c7a-aea49d82c8bb','infrastructure-leeds-to-micklefield-rail-upgrades-transpennine-route-upgrade',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.980','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Transpennine Route Upgrade (TRU) engineers have completed a series of work across 5 weekends between Leeds and York. Now, 7.5 km of wiring has been completed between Church Fenton and Micklefield. During the work, Station Road Bridge, in Cross Gates, was demolished and replaced to allow for the overhead line equipment to be installed. [14]','Completion of Wiring between Church Fenton and Micklefield, including Cross Gates Bridge Replacement','RailAdvent (Transpennine Route Upgrade Completes Series of Work)','2025-07-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.railadvent.co.uk/2025/07/transpennine-route-upgrade-completes-series-of-work.html','TRU engineers completed a series of work over five weekends, including the installation of 7.5 km of overhead wiring between Church Fenton and Micklefield. This work, which will enable electric trains, also involved the demolition and replacement of Station Road Bridge in Cross Gates to accommodate overhead line equipment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cddba025-76a6-4a1b-a757-ab886f061ca6','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle (EV) charging points are set to be installed across the Wakefield district after senior councillors agreed to accept £1.5m of funding. Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept the grant from West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of measures designed to achieve net zero targets. The project supports local authorities in England to install public charge points for residents without access to private parking.','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for more EV charging points across the district','Wakefield Express','2024-10-18 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/wakefield-council-to-get-ps15m-for-more-ev-charging-points-across-the-district-4821447','Further reporting confirmed Wakefield Council\'s decision to accept £1.5 million in funding from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) under the LEVI scheme. This initiative aims to expand the public EV charging infrastructure throughout the district, addressing the growing number of electric vehicles and supporting the transition to zero-emission transport.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cdde9d6e-7f86-46b4-a95d-2177c9dce95a','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---ling-bob-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.178','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council says it is looking at how it can encourage more youngsters to take a greener and healthier route. The review includes looking at school crossing patrols, 20mph zones and other projects such as \'School Streets\' - where access restrictions are put in place around school hours. [15]','Calderdale Council aims to boost number of kids walking and cycling to school','Halifax Courier','2021-11-11 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/calderdale-council-aims-to-boost-number-of-kids-walking-and-cycling-to-school-3453392','A review is underway in Calderdale to encourage more children to walk and cycle to school, exploring initiatives like \'School Streets\' and 20mph zones. The aim is to identify the best way to enable safe and healthy travel to and from school, and the findings will inform sustainable travel programmes and infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ce382521-35d8-46ec-a735-a59be104df17','infrastructure-wakefield-eastern-relief-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.001','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'WAKEFIELD\'S Eastern Relief Road (WERR) is nearing completion and is expected to be open this spring. The new £33m highway will reduce traffic congestion in the city centre and service a 2,500 housing development at the City Fields site. Work began in April 2015 and is expected to be completed by May 2017 (Source 5).','Wakefield\'s Eastern Relief Road Project Nears Completion','Yorkshire Voice','2017-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFslSIxbU7QN6VmQkk9_ePYHw5Ut4G_AkKC_Sey5Fwd6ZEDDjCRvARAD7ByHbWlBWvMGafnLd9-1wZhq8l7F_1QajiSaze5zexTY3znmRyrhkeaVwS1VjziQ2IjPSuTAI8XZagOXfo-EIuAAtHPz7mdFYms0KLD4BhaaL1dA7uZ66d9Q0X8vlUptpoLGH2tsa2Ht5tjkhdZB_IlEjiMC1FlC8gx6zzy4VmC5cA==','In March 2017, it was reported that the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road (WERR), a £33m highway, was nearing completion and expected to open in spring of that year. The road aimed to reduce city centre traffic congestion and support a 2,500-home development at City Fields.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ce5c5c9e-5ae1-474d-b80b-14d1794d8807','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---south-bank-extension-clarence-road-to-sweet-street',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.491','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds College of Building\'s North Street Campus is set to benefit from the latest expansion of the Leeds PIPES district heating network. The network uses heat recovered from non-recyclable domestic waste to provide heat and hot water to buildings in the city. Expansion into the South Bank area of Holbeck and Hunslet comes after £24.5m funding was secured to further the Leeds PIPES district heating network as Leeds City Council\'s aims to become a zero-carbon city by 2030. [10]','Leeds College of Building joins heat network','elemental','2024-11-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGYPtdIRmRxkiiOCcZc5tzy7YJq0_dFbPEx0JtEeYgxpnHr3wD-lHf_cE8JRGQVCH80Dtm6Iv6cWJBETH3ygfssYd57PK_EL-pjboQJDy_QufaWFTXeFocpNx8OL6dmRLGXWyd2ETs-zRqKIVU-C1imlfTNSZB2zRM6BYWvWfUHDZVjOzafuslIGBU','Leeds College of Building\'s North Street Campus became the latest connection to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, benefiting over 2,130 staff and students. The article mentions that the expansion into the South Bank area of Holbeck and Hunslet comes after £24.5m funding was secured.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ce8da1f5-83ae-4618-b6d8-b2466851b859','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A development in Halifax town centre with space for some brand new businesses is taking shape. \'Westgate Phase II\' – an expansion of Westgate Quarter – is well underway. O&C Management Services, who are leading the project, have described the new three-floor development as a “high-end shopping and leisure destination” which will be anchored around Westgate Arcade. The Courier understands one of the new tenants will be “home-from-home cafe bars” Loungers, who have made a licence application for two units at the new development. The Courier revealed earlier this year that Lounge was advertising for a general manager to run one of its restaurants in Halifax. [9]','Photos show progress of development bringing new businesses to Halifax town centre','Halifax Courier','2025-06-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFyL5Xb84nWh96pOjJ0RPUR7-0i5Xv0Y4SijB5RqqJ-JrDS9_0uKm_D1js2alXad9A9DZRlDBTeZckR8gVnt5y6QT3Lo7Z-q1ll-WNtuFxiph4pV-ioApdXS6_ntpN8Ji1GearW-lGwxqylRFv8EzAO9iRp_k8NLHAqi-Q1tHgsYNjb-nLxpbmauR1-wZjDf9QMHyPC0wgCtZIJAv62W2ttJT3UYKk8ezsf0ouZeX9njBD5cvhufxH0stBkEaVJsM-YXWrTkC52HcOa5V5gpmtv35GkxNPstr5AsZOE8pRe_hazgN2gJzHZ','The Halifax Courier published photos showing the progress of \'Westgate Phase II\'. O&C Management Services described the project as a \'high-end shopping and leisure destination\'. It was also revealed that Loungers had applied for a license for two units within the development, and their \'Lounge\' brand was actively advertising for a general manager in Halifax.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ceb0a0fa-ac01-4e66-81cf-e07851640d55','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 1 will replace the existing, outdated 1970\'s \'Oastler\' market hall, releasing the largely Council owned 3.5 hectare site, which will become the primary residential development opportunity within the City Village. Demolition of the Oastler market is expected to commence in February 2021 and be completed by October 2021 when construction of the new market should commence. The new Darley Street Market will be constructed by April 2023 and will be ready to open by June 2023. This \'10 year\' regeneration plan will create a new community friendly environment... by creating a new \'City Village\' which will be a green, healthy, and sustainable neighbourhood of 1,000 new homes.','Scheme Summary: Bradford City Village outlines initial plans for Oastler Market demolition','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFsPHNh8uSWtt9-4Uf-YGKdk4BF8LQbnv2vJp2YH-av8P9UXm5sjfGve7I6gfTB9cg31-xd2hflHZ8IIl16OkeZgisoilxHaQL0UVJSzCCzlzT7zJpdUk2q9Bky9ofDICOQRF8luBSoqDcafnaVWq0U8oQ617MLHn61zKWBcPPXyK-dHUbaXVXIML4haHjx','A West Yorkshire Combined Authority document details early intentions for the Bradford City Village scheme, outlining the replacement of the outdated 1970s Oastler market hall. This demolition was projected to commence in February 2021, freeing up the 3.5-hectare site for future residential development as part of a 10-year regeneration plan. [11]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cefb0538-db8f-4593-8418-2159796a0628','infrastructure-bradford-live-odeon-theatre-transformation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.098','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'NEC Group pulled out of the £50 million Bradford Live project with immediate effect, following months of speculation. Bradford Council and Bradford Live announced they would \'move at pace\' to find a new operator, aiming for the venue to be operational in 2025 for Bradford\'s UK City of Culture year. The overall cost of the project had reportedly doubled to £50.5m, with nearly £44m from the council.','NEC Group withdraws from Bradford Live project','IQ Magazine / Bradford Telegraph & Argus','2024-09-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGih-a0wWfpJVtp8VQgbrxToiEDjl_MvsaTuARe9aChBskUlWOh7f31p6D9_g2unN1PE_3qB3qc8bNdQTktT_TQtSiZniL-xnS-Iqdac7UiKVEnlr3MRUyQvfHRVlYtfxZ8VIGfDfbwZL3MfWFeYZCDJ8AffxuLkaFGGlpgBrd569iuzXVmFPma6MDA8Q==','NEC Group pulled out of the £50 million Bradford Live project with immediate effect, following months of speculation. Bradford Council and Bradford Live announced they would \'move at pace\' to find a new operator, aiming for the venue to be operational in 2025 for Bradford\'s UK City of Culture year. The overall cost of the project had reportedly doubled to £50.5m, with nearly £44m from the council.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cf0ffe9d-51e4-4aa0-8f6f-9c20a44a5d28','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Visit our 50kW DC Electric Vehicle (EV) rapid charging station in Wakefield. Delivering a rapid charge to get you back on the road quickly. Simple, contactless payment, no connection charge, no subscription. Just tap your payment card to start the charge and pay for what you use. Services on site: Bannatyne Spa offering premium facilities which include Cafe, Gym, pool and Spa area. EV Rapid Charging Station, Wakefield. Bannatyne Health Club & Spa Paragaon Avenue, Wakefield, WF1 2UF.','Electric Vehicle (EV) Charging Station – Wakefield (Paragon Avenue)','InstaVolt','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://instavolt.co.uk/locations/ev-charge-point-wakefield/','InstaVolt operates a 50kW DC rapid electric vehicle charging station at Bannatyne Health Club & Spa, Paragon Avenue, Wakefield. This hub offers simple, contactless payment and is open 24 hours a day, providing CCS2 Combo and CHAdeMO connectors. Services on site include a cafe, gym, pool, and spa area. This location aligns with the project description of a \'50kW DC rapid electric vehicle charging station in Wakefield\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cf39a259-25f0-44e7-a05c-6b6b668c9542','infrastructure-pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.548','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Pinderfields Hospital: Plan revealed to install solar farm on rooftop of Yorkshire hospital buildings. [16]','Pinderfields Hospital: Plan revealed to install solar farm on rooftop of Yorkshire hospital buildings','Yorkshire Evening Post','2023-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/leeds-inquests-first-look-inside-new-ps27m-wakefield-coroners-court-as-old-building-not-fit-for-purpose-4240755','This article, though primarily about a new coroner\'s court, is listed as a related story, indicating that plans for a rooftop solar farm at Pinderfields Hospital were already publicly known and being reported on by this date.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cf4c3b0e-0a40-4fc4-8218-0d7c25074a2f','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Alternative network operator and rural ISP Quickline has today announced that their new gigabit-capable Fibre-to-the-Premises (FTTP) broadband network has just gone live in three more West Yorkshire (England) villages, including Southowram, Clifton and Holywell Green. The local deployment means that almost 3,000 homes and businesses across these three villages can now place an order for Quickline\'s full fibre service. [24]','Quickline Puts FTTP Broadband Live in 3 More West Yorkshire UK Villages','ISPreview UK','2025-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEClLRH91ZfKBz8MOZAQnYz0sdLzMJ3HoubPqNWyAPyZc6-S-TsorISDXQz3MHSHuARhCnZGZXrSOiha7-5q6bryAeb6q33u-fiMdfIGEdb3hkJzJn_HADAmWX6BsXogReK_i-8Z6N_xKn5E29Rpq9dzSjvIKWzJS2T1D8Sb4GL6UQ-TLCluzwbYvIhiaKndUHtNXSrRMaVvcVlaWkS1mbK8-frcJ30POveJSnN8aL9LLWnGbQ','Quickline has announced that its gigabit-capable Fibre-to-the-Premises (FTTP) broadband network has gone live in three additional West Yorkshire villages: Southowram, Clifton, and Holywell Green, all located within the Calderdale district. This deployment provides almost 3,000 homes and businesses in these areas with access to Quickline\'s full fibre service.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cfc1ca8f-38fb-45eb-8d93-25dbdf8e65bb','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Parking charges may have brought Calderdale Council £1m surplus – but it will be swallowed up by highway and other related costs, councillors have heard. [...] Coun Silvia Dacre (Lab, Todmorden), cabinet member for Resources, said parking income can only be spent on parking services and the infrastructure for that, and on highway maintenance and infrastructure. [7]','£1m for council raised from parking fees swallowed up by fixing roads costs','Halifax Courier','2025-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/ps1m-for-council-raised-from-parking-fees-swallowed-up-by-fixing-roads-costs-4687595','This article further elaborates on the allocation of the £1m surplus from parking charges, confirming that it was absorbed by highway maintenance and infrastructure costs. A cabinet member stated that parking income can only be spent on parking services and highway maintenance, directly linking parking revenue to infrastructure upkeep.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cfc4be84-fe3b-4ac1-b64f-fab7c96741f7','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The new GBF Warm Homes Fund Scheme (the Scheme) builds on the successful track record. Wakefield Council has in delivering effective schemes that provide support for low income, fuel poor owner occupied households to: Switch from carbon intensive forms of heating, to efficient gas central heating, where no central heating is currently fitted; or. Upgrade and improve existing heating systems to more efficient, modern heating systems; Insulate properties identified as suitable for standard insulation measures. The target through this Scheme is to directly support 145 low income, vulnerable and fuel poor owner occupied households across the Wakefield district with 175 retrofit energy efficiency improvement measures (145 heating and 30 insulation) by the end of March 2022. The total cost of the Scheme that this FBC relates to, which is part of the wider programme, is £660,500.','Wakefield Warm Homes Scheme Summary','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG2scAvKVEfmghMe_hDedZbXhq5S9N7KWuY1nlnhSfNaO_4KWNfN301v4RiqePuLZLJVkIm3TN9xGlF9x3bt9sTg3wMyRAzXL1CFcSdA-6_Luz8YTGgCZ5dBGm9W_u-e617rkvEbNbPPmTQdTJ2qjOK4QFaJrHoH30fSBuGZogPhPkDmcoAZ69fsAMzbjE=','This document outlines the \'GBF Warm Homes Fund Scheme\' in Wakefield, a previous initiative aiming to support 145 low-income, fuel-poor owner-occupied households with heating and insulation measures by March 2022. It had a total cost of £660,500 and highlights Wakefield Council\'s existing \'Home Energy Efficiency Improvement Programme\'. This provides historical context for energy retrofit efforts in the district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('cfcaa586-bb3b-4b0d-9691-48c6fac07574','infrastructure-sowerby-bridge-town-square--wharf-street-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.915','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'An exciting new venture will bring an unused historic building in Sowerby Bridge back to life, as work gets underway on its transformation. The stunning, Grade II listed \'old Town Hall\' building on Town Hall Street will be revitalised, after standing empty for several years following the closure of the bankthat was previously located there. The project is thanks to a partnership between 22 The Square, Calderdale Council and Historic England. It will help to boost Sowerby Bridge high street as part of the Government\'s £95 million High Streets Heritage Action Zone programme...','New Lease Of Life For Historic Building In Sowerby Bridge','The Yorkshire Press','2022-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGVzVN-nC_xaDqSVtss7PaOnkf7xKfMwle3_lWkr_Lib-KYEMmefwjRyLMjnV5vhIKLiRpwcZK3J7g-s8lU-S2kfZXjxy2bd2khWLYHGF8eR5UD698vIE67MdOkaYp0--YF-YItRPQjwkkvkhpGMfthuRWy6_Y6jpA_x0SzqDCoQV_sYiwezFGjxplOBKJDLNXpA1CujedBp3g=','Work commenced on the revitalization of the Grade II listed \'old Town Hall\' building on Town Hall Street in Sowerby Bridge. This project, a collaboration between 22 The Square, Calderdale Council, and Historic England, falls under the High Streets Heritage Action Zone programme and includes external and internal repairs to bring the long-empty building back into active use.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d0661ce5-6f90-4411-9450-57e5a6d4e7e0','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This drone footage highlights the continued construction work in Copley as part of the Flood Alleviation Scheme. The work in Copley involves improvements to the existing flood embankment that surrounds the village, work at the cricket pitch to speed up the rate of drainage and also solutions to manage and reduce surface water.','Eye on Calderdale | Copley Flood Alleviation Scheme Construction Progress, September 2024 - YouTube','YouTube / Eye on Calderdale','2024-09-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFpxkNhV6vzcAWgDW_ZVBEd3w1ail6besVJWjKphYBsWwxHTg3lo51c-4Q_SB2edpm5xQKCvGXqIPD2-PpC8e02LsMJcd7nnOSfSvFtzigPj0rWufTyDX0HkWqMxaaH6QuScMioKx8=','Drone footage showcasing the ongoing construction work for the Copley Flood Alleviation Scheme, highlighting improvements to the embankment, cricket pitch drainage, and surface water solutions.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d08d309c-a6f5-4330-a4a2-8fccca458502','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £20 MILLION highways scheme will see new bus lanes, cycle lanes and pedestrian crossings on one of the main routes in Bradford city centre. On Thursday, West Yorkshire Combined Authority will discuss plans to create a \'sustainable transport corridor\' on Wakefield Road and a stretch of Tong Street – both part of the A650. The Wakefield Road scheme will create 4.3km of new bus lanes on the route, along with a 1.7km long two-lane cycle path. It involves a 2km stretch of Wakefield Road from Croft Street to Dudley Hill Roundabout, and a 500m portion of Tong Street from Dudley Hill Roundabout to Rook Lane. If the scheme is approved and moves ahead work will start in Summer 2026, and be completed by April 2027. [5]','£20m road scheme will see new bus lanes and cycle lanes','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-09-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEzrdqn6d7Qhms1HeAuAZiGaJrtAeSC49YZlRNcBLofDGkIm0S68EQX0SiCwZrRjbA4m_rUIBz1XtdKtb9aCeuIeyRfxY4vju3CbMmP0gHGP5GI09f4LBKcvCEMU2fNaY5SZ2tnwBtScXLN71exy6LLwTFQM0hOpp_VBoxoebOwhuhfD6X7L7F-bKCrQ6cxovHpP0OPxJJEfjEcmcjkBa3-bay8','A £20 million highways scheme is proposed for Wakefield Road and Tong Street (A650) in Bradford, including 4.3km of new bus lanes and a 1.7km two-lane cycle path. The West Yorkshire Combined Authority was set to discuss plans for this \'sustainable transport corridor\'. The article details the specific stretches of road (Wakefield Road from Croft Street to Dudley Hill Roundabout, and Tong Street from Dudley Hill Roundabout to Rook Lane) and mentions an estimated start in Summer 2026 and completion by April 2027.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d0e3ad81-ab6b-435e-94dd-f576e369bd42','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Businesses in the Leeds City Region are set to benefit from a major new support programme that will help them invest in new technology and learn new digital skills. Launching today, the £8.5 million Digital Enterprise programme will support eligible small and medium sized businesses (SMEs) to invest in digital technologies or advance their digital skills as they look to scale up and grow. Digital Growth Advisors will be on hand to offer advice and support to help businesses find the right type of investment that will help them achieve growth and raise both productivity and competitiveness. A Digital Growth Voucher of up to £5,000 will be available for eligible firms towards the cost of investment in digital or ICT solutions. The programme is part-funded by the England European Regional Development Fund as part of the European Structural and Investment Funds Growth Programme 2014 – 2020 and will be managed by Leeds City Council. The workshops will be available across the Leeds City Region and will cover a range of topics including social media, cyber security, digital marketing and web development. Small to medium sized business based in the Leeds City Region should visit the Digital Enterprise website at www.digitalenterprise.co.uk to see if they are eligible for a Digital Growth Voucher. They may also email any enquiries to; enquiries.DE@leeds.gov.uk. Alternatively, they can contact the LEP to find out what support is available to help them grow – 0113 348 1818. [18]','New digital support and funding for SMEs in Leeds City Region','Calderdale Council News Centre','2017-02-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/news/news-centre/new-digital-support-and-funding-for-smes-in-leeds-city-region/index.html','This news article announces the launch of the original Digital Enterprise Programme in the Leeds City Region. It details an £8.5 million program part-funded by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF), offering up to £5,000 in Digital Growth Vouchers for SMEs to invest in new technologies and skills. Leeds City Council managed the program, aiming to boost the digital economy and create jobs across the region including Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d0fd4c2d-2067-4e16-8dea-a47182d3a744','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The first phase of development on the proposed Dewsbury Riverside housing scheme could be a step closer. It follows the submission of a planning application by Kirklees Council for works to create site access from Forge Lane and Ravensthorpe Road to land it owns. Up to 350 homes are earmarked for this section of the overall scheme. The council\'s “hybrid” application has been submitted to its own planning department. It requests full planning permission for engineering works, drainage and utilities connection “for the provision of site access” from Forge Lane and Ravensthorpe Road. It also asks for outline planning permissions for up to 350 homes and a mixed-use development with community facilities. (See Source [10] for full context).','Planning Application Submission for First Phase of Dewsbury Riverside Development','YorkshireLive','2021-10-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/local-news/massive-dewsbury-riverside-4000-home-21757820','Kirklees Council submitted a hybrid planning application for the first phase of the Dewsbury Riverside housing scheme. This application sought full planning permission for engineering works, drainage, and utilities connections to create site access from Forge Lane and Ravensthorpe Road, and outline planning permission for up to 350 homes and mixed-use development with community facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d12fbbef-73ce-46d5-8640-cb8c32ffa7f1','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire LCWIP is made up of individual LCWIPs for the five West Yorkshire Partner Councils. They will function and act as standalone LCWIPs, and be brought together into the West Yorkshire LCWIP. ... This LCWIP identifies a proposed walking network, proposed intervention sites and a list of proposed infrastructure improvements for Harehills. ... The proposed cycling network and infrastructure improvements were also informed by data analysis (as described in the supporting analysis section) and additional expert site visits. This LCWIP identifies a proposed cycling network, proposed intervention sites and a list of proposed infrastructure improvements for North East Leeds.','Leeds Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan: Phase 1','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2019-11-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/media/7666/leeds-lcwip-phase-1-report.pdf','This detailed Phase 1 report for Leeds LCWIP, coordinated by West Yorkshire Combined Authority, sets out the strategic approach for identifying cycling and walking improvements. It includes a network plan, a prioritised programme of infrastructure improvements for future investment, and supporting analysis, with specific focus on Harehills for walking and north-east Leeds for cycling.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d14c1540-050e-4dda-881d-e6f64f84315d','infrastructure-ionity-leeds-skelton-lakes-ev-charging-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.372','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ionity has expanded its UK EV charge point network with a 350kW High Power Charging station at Extra MSA Group\'s recently constructed Leeds Skelton Lake Services. EV drivers at the facility, which opened in January, can now charge their cars in less than 20 minutes depending on their vehicle\'s charging capacity using renewable energy from the charging points. Located on the M1 J45, within two miles of Leeds city centre, Leeds Skelton Lake is Ionity\'s fourth station to be launched in the UK... [2]','IONITY Launches 350kW EV Charging Station at Leeds Skelton Lake Services','CiTTi Magazine','2020-04-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.cittimagazine.co.uk/ionity-opens-its-first-350kw-ev-charging-station-in-uk/','IONITY, in collaboration with Extra MSA Group, officially launched a 350kW High Power Charging station at the newly constructed Leeds Skelton Lake Services. This marked IONITY\'s fourth station in the UK and was highlighted as the first in the country to feature their new generation of chargers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d16d68a2-4e93-46eb-8d09-2748fb1a5813','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'O&C Management Services say Westgate Phase Two – the area that formerly housed Horton House, between Union Street and Horton Street – is due for a “shell and core finish” in November. It says some tenants will begin their fit-outs afterwards, potentially to open for the festive period. [5]','What is being built in Halifax: \'Almost there\' say firm creating space for new bars, shops and offices in Halifax town centre as they reveal planned finish date','Halifax Courier','2025-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEvrXIj8ZSP5hodDq5iiz6fmB0jaws9Sefe7JX0oGtojsgGWx15j8oQln9Vxp269HxenGXItKs8zPPDFNjyVIC7XHfxLEZjkHbtxPcfO6KEluTn7Cip4wiEd5K8Au8RwzkQVLs1a4CCxuQgsscHueHQhBS-YzK-oXCTWrwvatjQ8YyF2kJi62xdUfeXzfKTya2NM-r3pLIIFZWYMHXsRdXRMK5pjpI64pZyTTQYE-uw6j305u-dVTYg47U78zT4fbDizMksnIZl3czNQ0JBLKuEYliaXOgkTCkpyUdeqfigDlF_fmSj4OOQyKBEkhjyGy6HbAahEr_9ktheA30RdH_HNSuhORlxIOWO','O&C Management Services announced that Westgate Phase Two, located in the area formerly housing Horton House, is anticipated to reach a \'shell and core finish\' in November 2025. This timeline suggests that some tenants could begin their fit-outs shortly after, potentially allowing for openings during the festive period.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d17589b7-93e8-450b-b76e-67a06fb47e57','infrastructure-pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.548','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of this groundbreaking new funding, the Mid Yorkshire Teaching NHS Trust has been awarded £2.7 million to install solar panels at Pinderfields Hospital in Wakefield. ... Mid Yorkshire\'s solar project will involve the installation of approximately 3,000 rooftop PV panels – totalling just under 1MW of installed capacity – across the Pinderfields site. Once completed, it is expected to save around £250,000 each year through avoided electricity bill costs, which will represent a significant positive contribution to organisational finances. The project will also lead to a carbon reduction of approximately 200 tonnes of CO2 equivalent. This initiative, set to be completed within the 2025/26 financial year alongside our valued partners Consort Healthcare and Equans, marks a significant step toward achieving our net zero ambitions. [5]','Mid Yorkshire awarded solar panel funding','Mid Yorkshire Teaching NHS Trust','2025-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.midyorks.nhs.uk/news/mid-yorkshire-awarded-solar-panel-funding-7456','The Mid Yorkshire Teaching NHS Trust was awarded a £2.7 million grant from the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero via Great British Energy to install solar panels at Pinderfields Hospital. The project involves approximately 3,000 rooftop PV panels (just under 1MW capacity) and is expected to save £250,000 annually and reduce CO2 emissions by 200 tonnes equivalent.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d19573aa-086f-4845-a11e-58ca1bb3bae7','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The focus of this budgeted £23m construction project at Todmorden, West Yorkshire, is to reduce the frequency and severity of flood damage to properties together with reducing the risk of injury or death to the general public within the Walsden and Lower Todmorden areas. The scheme offers the majority of properties a 1 in 50 year standard of defence with the remainder still receiving 1 in 25 year level of defence. The challenge, therefore, was to set a realistic, robust budget very early in the project lifecycle (conceptual design), therefore an effective risk and value management strategy played an integral and vital role.','Todmorden & Walsden Flood Alleviation Scheme Conceptual Design Budget and Scope','WaterProjectsOnline','2005-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.waterprojectsonline.com/projects/Todmorden_and_Walsden_Flood_Alleviation.html','A conceptual design for a £23 million construction project aimed at reducing flood damage in Walsden and Lower Todmorden was in development. The scheme aimed to offer a 1 in 50 year standard of defence for most properties. This early phase focused on setting a robust budget and implementing risk and value management strategies.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d1d26391-cb88-400b-abfb-844772e03bd3','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Energy efficiency for private landlords. All UK residential buildings that are available to buy or rent, must have a valid Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) (GOV.UK). This gives your property an energy efficiency rating between A and G. It also shows the potential rating if certain improvements are made. [15]','Energy efficiency schemes | Calderdale Council','Calderdale Council','2025-01-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGQJizbQ80kZFrxHF05GISrHOFy3aPAlDrAvLFnrsrxbmwiSlY9H7ZYwjJf76nVBtTKGTA37J92uH3E0sd-vvR2T0i2o_snfFLYyTO6UFRvkrj_FheMIohtrmJXfwZu_HYRds4yvIbrrQ-NLLzqF7wqVx0diYQ_zkROxc2sDlCYWYpIoZNIz0nKh0rte10xdxA==','Calderdale Council provides information on energy efficiency schemes for residents, including private landlords. While specific interest-free loans for landlords are mentioned for low-income owner-occupier households if no subsidies apply, the page also directs landlords to the Home Energy West Yorkshire service (West Yorkshire Combined Authority) for low-interest loans and grants. It emphasizes the importance of EPCs and outlines financial support available through schemes like ECO.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d1e56318-4692-4840-a16f-2490d8b9009c','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-ministry-of-justice-leeds-courts-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.352','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Our vision is to reduce our Scope 1 and 2 carbon emissions to net zero by 2050. We will calculate our baseline Scope 3 emissions by the end of FY23/24 and will develop a comprehensive Scope 3 action plan by the end of FY24/25. We will take an active role in supporting the development and implementation of wider government policy on Scope 3 measurement and reduction. ... MoJ\'s Scope 1 emissions were nearly 170,000 tCO2e in FY22/23. Approximately 90% of those emissions were from the combustion of natural gas to heat our buildings and generate hot water. [10]','Ministry of Justice Net Zero Carbon Strategy 2024','GOV.UK','2024-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministry-of-justice-net-zero-carbon-strategy-2024','The Ministry of Justice\'s Net Zero Carbon Strategy 2024 outlines its commitment to achieving net zero carbon emissions (Scope 1 and 2) by 2050, with an interim target of a 41% reduction by 2025 compared to the 2017/18 baseline. The strategy highlights that approximately 90% of the MoJ\'s Scope 1 emissions come from natural gas combustion for heating and hot water in its buildings, making heat decarbonisation projects like the one at Leeds Courts crucial to their overall targets.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d1ff5234-49c1-43c9-a28a-efec1e7c3ccc','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a638-doncaster-road',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.598','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Council is proposing improvements on the A638 Doncaster Road between Chantry Bridge and Heath Common to improve travel for all along this key corridor linking the city with the eastern areas of the district. Proposals include bus lane improvement, A655 Black Road/A638 Doncaster Road junction at Heath Common, new lay-bys for bus stops, better access to selected bus stops, new \'Toucan\' crossings at Sugar Lane and near the Wakefield Eastern Relief Road, and new or improved cycle routes. A consultation was scheduled from 21 June to 18 July 2021, with results published in September. Works were expected to start in 2023 and be completed in 2024. Funding of £6.7 million has been allocated by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [4]','Corridor Improvement Programme - A638 Doncaster Road: Initial Proposals and Benefits','Wakefield Council','2021-06-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/roads-and-travel/transport-infrastructure-schemes/a638-doncaster-road','Wakefield Council outlined proposals for improvements on the A638 Doncaster Road between Chantry Bridge and Heath Common. These improvements aim to enhance travel for all users, particularly through bus lane improvements, new lay-bys for bus stops, improved access to bus stops, new Toucan crossings, and new or improved cycle routes. The page also mentioned an upcoming consultation from June 21 to July 18, 2021, with works projected to start in 2023 and complete in 2024, funded by £6.7 million from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [4]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d24dc3f0-2e50-4a3f-be7e-eb3d60ab2339','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On March 15, 2024, UKREiiF reported that Leeds City Council had given its unanimous approval for the South Village development, previously known as City One. The scheme, spearheaded by Caddick Developments, will transform the South Bank of Leeds into a vibrant urban community with up to 1,925 homes, 650,000 sq ft of commercial premises, and a \'village green\'. [8]','Leeds City Council Endorses 1,925 Homes Plan','UKREiiF','2024-03-15 00:00:00.000','https://ukreiif.com/news/leeds-city-council-endorses-1925-homes-plan/','UKREiiF reported that Leeds City Council unanimously approved the South Village development, formerly City One, which will bring up to 1,925 homes, 650,000 sq ft of commercial space, and a \'village green\' to the South Bank area. The project is spearheaded by Caddick Developments.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d29dcd88-459e-4461-8950-cd1cd5d20a18','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-star-multi-academy-trust-monk-fryston-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.364','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We are proud to have the Eco Schools Green Flag Award. In 2025, this was again awarded with Distinction. We have a team of Eco Warriors elected from each class from Year 1. They have an action plan and meet regularly to discuss their work towards Green Flag re-accreditation. Last year, they focused on: Energy – To find out more and tell people about renewable energy, and how they can cut their carbon. ... Eco Warriors are helping to monitor our energy usage and are looking at how our Ground Source Heat Pump and solar panels operate. We have counted our carbon usage and have identified ways in which we can cut this.','Monk Fryston C of E Primary School Achieves Eco Schools Green Flag Award with Distinction','Monk Fryston C of E Primary School (Eco Schools Page)','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.monkfryston.n-yorks.sch.uk/eco-schools','Monk Fryston C of E Primary School continues its commitment to environmental education, achieving the Eco Schools Green Flag Award with Distinction in 2025. This reflects ongoing efforts, including monitoring the ground source heat pump and solar panels, to cut carbon and promote sustainability.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d2e8f975-bc88-4eaf-a46b-55a198b234d8','infrastructure-a650-connect-wakefield-road--tong-street-upgrade-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.844','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is proposing to upgrade Wakefield Road and Tong Street as part of a strategy to improve major transport routes into Bradford city centre and around the Bradford district. The proposals aim to create a better-connected transport route that improves traffic flow, makes walking, wheeling and cycling easier, and ensures public transport is more reliable. Key Dates: Consultation Launches. 04 March 2025. Consultation Ends. 06 April 2025. [3]','A650 Connect: Wakefield Road / Tong Street | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Consultation Launches)','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a650connect','Bradford Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a public consultation on the proposed upgrades to Wakefield Road and Tong Street (A650). The proposals aim to create a better-connected transport route that improves traffic flow, makes walking, wheeling and cycling easier, and ensures public transport is more reliable. The consultation period was set from March 4, 2025, to April 6, 2025, inviting public feedback on the plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d3a47361-3f56-4708-a183-edc94e74a07c','infrastructure-dawsons-corner-junction-remodelling-pudsey-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.989','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Road users are now being urged to prepare as significant enabling work begins this month to make improvements to the A647/A6120 Dawsons Corner junction and complete joint replacement and resurfacing works on the Stanningley Bypass. This forms part of a £44.179m total package with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority funding of £8.470m. The council\'s appointed contractor John Sisk are set to construct the scheme, which is scheduled to take up to 18 months to complete. On Thursday 15 May 11am-7pm the council will hold a drop-in event at Pudsey Civic Hall. [6, 24, 26]','Major improvement scheme at Dawsons Corner and Stanningley Bypass planned to start this month','Leeds City Council News / West Leeds Dispatch / Calverley and Farsley Labour Party / Information event organised as \'significant\' Dawsons Corner work due to start','2025-05-09 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGVHR0F6vi8ufKZjOq0q3f5bq3YFXigX_onzzmpoThe2l-2Qq-r9kpsPyvL0uaSJD9nr4A_Prhzwp-atsjuh7a5FW8NXfR6rhNyyd9aKfxJTVupGMEfe6HLrpXm06yb6WXg9y7pUKDsdddkq1X6ylao7Dp9WBzlwtwd17ECRYmDdknSfExn16LDNSE4PXSoBKLy9CZ1mU8l-VZuxD4Gua33pINpGzKZZUJr_KSNW4xFvDX2-cxaMzw','Leeds City Council announced that significant enabling work for the Dawsons Corner and Stanningley Bypass improvement scheme was planned to start in May 2025. This £44.179m project aims to improve safety, connectivity, and bus journey reliability, with an 18-month construction period. A public drop-in event was scheduled for May 15th at Pudsey Civic Hall.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d3c27240-0799-4f93-aa23-cd5cb92df5d0','infrastructure-clayton-west-wastewater-treatment-works-investment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Councillors from Kirklees Council and Denby Dale Parish Council recently visited Yorkshire Water\'s Clayton West wastewater treatment site in West Yorkshire to see progress on a £14m nature-based wetland solution. The project, being carried out by Mott McDonald Bentley, has seen the installation of a 4.3-hectare wetland containing 13 interconnected ponds.','Councillors praise £14m Yorkshire Water wetland project nearing completion','Yorkshire Water','2025-08-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG3_6UMn0G2HzB5TtYW9_WEq2BA_Bv4W5KsBiKERnXfaw7fqJ7ISmcDux3ydnpFsV9dWNNe3XQa4kw6H9XB-8jbucr4E9BgAxnpByJRV7atGFZvYNwinpiQ_R6UVDREvmDmmE8GYqOC-_AHdzkYJ2KqN3jwKppTbH52beGUsmlSFEgpjXgbot1dnYzqIJQ1s66doulKrp1-mKWJKHoufvBSxFoktCLtgGS7xkQXozGOXs2xBlgTfPzAK7PzrTDLgGzJoDA==','Councillors from Kirklees Council and Denby Dale Parish Council visited Yorkshire Water\'s Clayton West wastewater treatment site to see the progress of the £14m nature-based wetland solution. The project, featuring a 4.3-hectare wetland with 13 interconnected ponds, is nearing its expected completion in late summer 2025. Local officials lauded the scheme for its potential to significantly improve River Dearne water quality and enhance biodiversity.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d3d1d98b-28b0-49eb-a964-dd9f845b17ca','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Find out more about our approach, read the Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030 (PDF, 507KB). [9]','Publication of Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030','Leeds City Council website','2022-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/electric-vehicle-charging-in-leeds','Leeds City Council published its strategy document outlining plans to expand EV charging infrastructure across the city between 2022 and 2030, reinforcing the city\'s commitment to supporting electric vehicle adoption. This strategy provides the overarching framework for EV charging projects. [5, 9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d3f05ec5-7819-4a74-8415-a00838ea951f','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-airport-southern-access-route',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.761','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Details of the initial public consultation to be carried out on options supporting the development of Leeds Bradford Airport through improved road access have been released today. The initial public consultation runs from Monday 23 November to Sunday 24 January 2016, and will see Leeds City Council seeking views on the three options outlined in September to improve access to the airport. The first option is estimated to cost up to £75million, the second up to £50million, and the third up to £15million. The scheme to improve access to the airport is to be funded through the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund with Leeds City Council leading on its planning and delivery. It is hoped the chosen scheme will be completed during 2023. [4]','Details of initial public consultation on improving access to Leeds Bradford Airport released','Leeds City Council Newsroom','2015-11-12 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/details-of-initial-public-consultation-on-improving-access-to-leeds-bradford-airport-released','Leeds City Council announced the launch of an initial public consultation, running from November 23, 2015, to January 24, 2016. This consultation sought public views on the three previously outlined options for improving road access to Leeds Bradford Airport, with estimated costs ranging from £15 million to £75 million. The chosen scheme was hoped to be completed by 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d41124c7-2640-4ff0-b554-2e5e6a93fe7a','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council has secured government funding from the Department of Energy, Security and Net Zero (DESNZ) to deliver home energy efficiency improvements across the district. We are only able to support homeowners whose properties are not heated by mains gas. Eligibility: your home does not have mains gas central heating; AND your household (or your tenants) have a combined gross annual income of up to £36,000 or you live in an area pre-identified by DESNZ; AND your property has an Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) Rating of D-G. Only homes within the Wakefield District are eligible for this funding. What could I had done? This could include: insulation (internal wall, cavity wall, loft and/or external wall) draught proofing. installation of new heating systems, like Air Source Heat Pumps. heating and hot water controls. ventilation improvements. renewable energy generation, like roof-top solar panels. HUG Phase 2 (HUG 2) is actively reporting and has allocated £630 million for delivery between September 2023 and March 2025.','HUG - Home Upgrade Grant 2 - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2023-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF3nznRlM1xDHqyO3ArQx_P-2RsfRCJOJWfwwuzy06QLHQIuuScMrdGTNBbOY21EdgCupk6zgOv3G1n9x40AWWZuLjTgNeJjh97hOHP5hTxhQGrla6aj2XmXfPlx53U2LE3K3TQPcOMjpXXoY4m9tV75aJpTi6ggdyNyTh5GhDMn0qyPe8=','Wakefield Council has secured government funding from the Department of Energy, Security and Net Zero (DESNZ) to deliver home energy efficiency improvements across the district. This scheme supports homeowners whose properties are not heated by mains gas and meet specific income and EPC rating (D-G) criteria. Measures include various types of insulation, draught proofing, air source heat pumps, and solar panels. The scheme runs from September 2023 to March 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d4d57d6b-9e38-4877-a857-9e466db05f82','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3a closed to new applications in November 2021. ... The Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme provides grants for public sector bodies to fund heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures.','Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: Phase 3 - projects awarded funding','GOV.UK','2021-11-03 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-phase-3-projects-awarded-funding','This GOV.UK page provides general updates and information about Phase 3 of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. It states that Phase 3a closed to new applications in November 2021 and that the scheme provides grants for public sector bodies to fund heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures. It acts as an umbrella page for PSDS Phase 3 information.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d4f93386-9ae5-4aee-a9f3-3a51ce34733f','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We are pleased to see the allocation of £29.9 million to Bradford Council through Homes England\'s Brownfield Infrastructure & Land (BIL) funding for its Bradford City Village project. The grant funding will be used to deliver around 1,000 new homes along with retail and leisure spaces including three community parks, right in the heart of Bradford city centre. [6]','£30m Allocation for Bradford City Village Development via Homes England','Northern Housing Consortium','2024-11-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.northern-housing.org.uk/news/30m-allocation-for-bradford-city-village-development/','Homes England allocated £29.9 million (approximately £30m) to Bradford Council through its Brownfield Infrastructure & Land (BIL) funding for the Bradford City Village project. This grant funding is intended to support the delivery of around 1,000 new homes, retail, leisure spaces, and three community parks in Bradford city centre.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d5082af7-a5cb-4f0d-a036-0d7de44db47a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mobility-hubs-rollout',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.839','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A multi-million-pound project to improve walking, wheeling and cycling facilities in West Yorkshire is taking a major step forward. The new £5.1 million West Yorkshire Places scheme includes proposals such as new street crossings and lighting, improved green spaces and traffic calming measures. People are now being asked for their views on the West Yorkshire Combined Authority initiative, which will help encourage more people to choose active travel and make local neighbourhoods safer and more attractive across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees and Wakefield. ... The consultation for Wakefield, Bradford and Calderdale launched yesterday (Wednesday 19th March), with Kirklees starting on Tuesday 1st April, each lasting for six weeks.','New £5.1 million proposals to improve active travel across West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEe2BzEukj-ndga4oCAf4MOicp6nEVKc0V9tAwTHqDm3tJbkeie3RO2IrmizZc-Um3rhSaQ-zw-TVSelF3ahseIPhcpbpYvRHpntsdvPHEi8PlfGvXo_JRPUP3WOsW51McwMmEZy6ymst-v8qCOG98JHfM6NT41J3KSvp-SmOYAOquK6Y-cBICeaNJ4jYIl3EUFw9ng9_en34r4kSUBxwgpTDB2k8wLVXqb34yOFBkY9gqW','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced the new £5.1 million \'West Yorkshire Places\' scheme, aimed at improving active travel facilities across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Wakefield. The project includes proposals for new street crossings, enhanced lighting, improved green spaces, and traffic calming measures. Public consultations for these proposals were launched in phases, starting in March 2025 for Wakefield, Bradford, and Calderdale, and April 2025 for Kirklees.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d52fccae-4ea2-413e-ab5c-ba5eef7160d2','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'NEW pictures show the latest progress on the City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme. On a former crossroad between Bridge street and Hall Ings is now a circular bench and \'square\'.','Pictures show latest progress on Bradford city centre transformation','Telegraph and Argus','2025-01-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24061291.pictures-show-latest-progress-bradford-city-centre-transformation/','New pictures provided an update on the City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme, showing a circular bench and \'square\' replacing a former crossroad between Bridge Street and Hall Ings, signifying the ongoing transformation towards green and public spaces.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d56793b1-1edb-489a-8d1f-9b903e9c8c67','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Flood Recovery and Resilience Board. Date of Meeting: 15 th. June 2018. Report: Pin Hill Scheme. Report of: Mohammed Amjid – Flood Risk Manager. Pin Hill is the name of a constructed Flood Alleviation Scheme in Midgley, Luddendenfoot, Halifax. The scheme is one of the Calderdale Council\'s Flood Risk Reduction Schemes (FRRS), Phase 1. The site is nestled between the villages of Midgley and Luddenden below Midgley Moor at grid reference SE 03818 26374.','Pin Hill Scheme Report','Calderdale Council','2018-06-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEx9zzV1fPZimgaZh0snAXTD65Bt8C5mHTMT0tVBrUoDqNgZvb8CdRE23VH7INnrhND0Ia4V-Dg5WBQ82nj0d1OXkX2YpmvUAUxpVZ5a88syOpfFyR9S1EBPbxlh-tGf_O1w-ezZyPaTV89k_FAnXg0Svwakg5A14NU7z6QSMyW1wlPgV4Cx_pni2JhbQxhZKO9gOc_Gg==','A report detailing the Pin Hill Flood Alleviation Scheme, located between Midgley and Luddendenfoot. This project, part of Calderdale Council\'s Flood Risk Reduction Schemes (Phase 1), aimed to collect surface water and direct flows to Luddenden Brook, demonstrating ongoing flood mitigation efforts in the immediate vicinity of Railes Close.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d58b662e-74f8-42d5-9cf1-ea20262dc4b1','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leonardo--thoresby-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.457','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The four latest buildings, including the first private-sector residential developers, which have confirmed their intention to connect to the network within the next 12 months are: ... Leonardo and Thoresby buildings on Gt George Street, developed by McLaren on behalf of Arrow Leonardo.','Plans to extend Leeds PIPES network into new areas of the city revealed, as four more buildings set to connect','Leeds City Council (via Place Yorkshire)','2023-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.placeyorkshire.co.uk/property-companies-join-leeds-low-carbon-heating-network/','Leeds City Council announced plans for further expansion of the Leeds PIPES district heating network, with four new buildings confirming their intention to connect within the next 12 months. Among these was the \'Leonardo and Thoresby buildings on Gt George Street, developed by McLaren on behalf of Arrow Leonardo\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d58bfd59-e3dc-446a-baf0-873cad49056c','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to regenerate Bradford\'s Southern Gateway with a new railway through-station could unlock 5,000 new homes and 27,000 jobs. ... The Mayor\'s in-principle investment of £13.2 million for Bradford City Village is another major boost for the UK\'s City of Culture 2025, after the Government committed £30 million of funding for the scheme, which will be delivered by Bradford Council working with ECF, formerly the English Cities Fund.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Approves £13.2 Million for Bradford City Village','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGDaQY-nB8j7pIOlOIy99Oe25i5XUzdv0Hxffgj04MSprmjAO3EB4l-rgv0DW4wNPBIC2tGOoGgboZZUTBpjPno59H_9UF1yjYZgaEyNCTSsxCqzkvu5I-O7RA3uKwGlqra7hoQ1YlfAmwxbBlFgJbj1bef4MKDTaOwtQ1SiQY95XX7jefPxSsbcOaXMZHQtI6Gptg_gTuHoCdnxp7JNQjsA9WqoYvz8MPKlHFSBvXpADzuh9YAK-_Z4GUUB10ryJnSuA==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) approved an in-principle investment of £13.2 million from the Mayor\'s Brownfield Housing Fund for Bradford City Village, a flagship scheme within the Southern Gateway. This project aims to deliver almost a thousand new homes and three new green spaces, complementing a previous £30 million government commitment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d5af55a5-5615-4fd9-9fab-d738f2c10bb2','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority discussed a report on a mass transit system, outlining a potential three-line network connecting Leeds, Bradford, North Kirklees, and the Wakefield district. The proposed transport mode (Bus Rapid Transit or Light Rail) was not yet confirmed, and a consultation was planned for early 2019.','West Yorkshire Mass Transit proposal shared','Proposed Railway Schemes','2018-11-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEk2x1UcGpDYCI15HSbNbTAKYwpl2Bumci94XjzvYmr8TmQz32uzZU4p4XqdntPb128bmtkncmzuOsqlm1as_QBf7DdkOmZ5foxfluXKwlyyxa8ofQfvZV0T1OoopBaQQceyMZ0nmjGMb029DqxGURwXOUQ893Q6xeUhoqlVaDYXtcBfTdQJgMS','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority discussed a report on a mass transit system, outlining a potential three-line network connecting Leeds, Bradford, North Kirklees, and the Wakefield district. The proposed transport mode (Bus Rapid Transit or Light Rail) was not yet confirmed, and a consultation was planned for early 2019.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d5bb2901-982b-47f8-b2eb-8b4f848cf26c','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Citu\'s Climate Innovation District – a low carbon development on the banks of the River Aire in Leeds, UK – has released a collection of four-bed townhouses. Once complete, the project will feature 955 low carbon homes underpinned by climate-conscious leisure and offices. Planning permission has also been granted for a multigenerational building that will include a primary school, care home and apartments in one space, with completion anticipated in 2025.','Climate Innovation District Progress Update: 955 Homes Total & Multi-Generational Building Anticipated by 2025','Housing Today','2023-06-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF15HdltJ5KF7Ju6VTUwMlJ8XSAECdYLRYhpTZB3F7Df7omHkiSSs0nGXhjqpeJ0esIoVGZpbrhFkORLvvzvAh9z-WH1Nf9ampMmmC7WcXuM7IiR78IsAHHhLPGuTVLeB5v7qKOkHjEfX__o5M2BJCht9LL8cOjusJT6jmh0Y8Z_uFR_Qnc8Y_tCV96hzCVOssSuMDE4ktyPgVq_OVdh0PeoHJUqZI89ASHq6LvqQJFSJNXGC0k08oDoOVaaiiE34A==','An update on the Climate Innovation District in June 2023 highlighted the release of new four-bed townhouses. The project\'s overall masterplan includes 955 low-carbon homes, with planning permission granted for a multi-generational building (primary school, care home, and apartments) anticipated for completion in 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d5d67837-e740-4955-a864-c757feef79d9','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A public consultation into a proposed mass transit system has shown a line running via Armley and Stanningley is the marginally preferred option to link Leeds and Bradford. A report from West Yorkshire Combined Authority shows more than two thirds of people surveyed last year are supportive of plans to create a tram system between Leeds and Bradford. [9] The route options consultation for phase one of the West Yorkshire Mass Transit scheme took place in during summer and autumn 2024, and saw 4,845 individuals and organisations have their say on plans for the region\'s biggest proposed infrastructure project in decades. [9] Line B1 (running from Leeds city centre via Armley, Stanningley, Thornbury and Laisterdyke, before arriving in Bradford city centre) had 55% of respondents supporting or tending to support it. [9]','Public support for Leeds to Bradford mass transit system','West Leeds Dispatch','2025-02-20 00:00:00.000','https://westleedsdispatch.com/public-support-for-leeds-to-bradford-mass-transit-system/','A public consultation into a proposed mass transit system revealed strong support for a line running via Armley and Stanningley as the marginally preferred option to link Leeds and Bradford. More than two-thirds of respondents supported the plans for a tram system between Leeds and Bradford.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d5da6e97-5348-436e-a795-e886a0194eb1','infrastructure-bus-lane-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.094','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On 5th July 2024 we submitted our application to the Department for Transport (DfT). This was to grant Calderdale Council the powers to enforce moving traffic contraventions under Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004. We are waiting for the DfT to approve our submission.','Calderdale Council submitted application to DfT for Moving Traffic Enforcement powers','Calderdale Council','2024-07-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/parking/moving-traffic-enforcement','Calderdale Council submitted an application to the Department for Transport (DfT) on 5th July 2024 to gain powers for enforcing moving traffic contraventions under Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004. This broader power includes the enforcement of bus lanes and aims to improve the borough\'s road network, road safety, and tackle congestion. The council was awaiting DfT approval.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d60179fa-2179-4cc9-938f-7d32bf699d2e','infrastructure-thorpe-park-railway-station-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.955','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A £14 billion masterplan, led by Lord Blunkett, was unveiled to improve Yorkshire\'s railway network over the next 15 years. This plan includes the delivery of new stations such as Thorpe Park as part of the investment proposed for the first five years.','£14 billion plan to improve Yorkshire\'s rail network unveiled, includes Thorpe Park Station','Yorkshire Post','2025-05-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/transport/ps14-billion-plan-to-improve-yorkshires-rail-network-unveiled-including-leeds-and-sheffield-station-expansions-4632426','A £14 billion masterplan, led by Lord Blunkett, was unveiled to improve Yorkshire\'s railway network over the next 15 years. This plan includes the delivery of new stations such as Thorpe Park as part of the investment proposed for the first five years.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d61eab65-c9ac-45cf-8973-72703e1ae8ad','infrastructure-five-towns-leisure-hub-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.669','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following Willmott Dixon\'s successful completion of Minsthorpe Leisure Centre for Wakefield Council, the company has also been successfully appointed by the council for a £17m contract to build Five Towns Leisure and Wellbeing Hub in Pontefract. Construction work on the hub, which is located in Pontefract Park, will complete in autumn 2020. [10]','Willmott Dixon back for second Wakefield leisure centre in a year','Willmott Dixon','2019-08-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHHkfV0Ey8Ego3J6at1QwOG-6XsWD_iZFK5UOXiXV32oqiX3yHGxxR8cUbdQK1Hv6KGIzzy3tjj430ltz7Sy2rGtutfzDtBNXxTQQ1spkY3JcyB17utwqvJ9dVrPd3qAdPE4TfAWrsvpAuq8VVjLp9S4ka0yjYbo8Y0ROe958E06tpapUAe1bZDvbbGdODl7xwtJT_Z32d-GJ26_JAjzgEW','Willmott Dixon was appointed for a £17 million contract to build the Five Towns Leisure and Wellbeing Hub in Pontefract Park. The project, located in Pontefract Park, was still slated for completion in autumn 2020, featuring a 10-lane swimming pool, gym, studios, climbing activity, café, and outdoor sports facilities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d62e5ede-4c3d-4a88-9bdb-df4c8ce9b27e','infrastructure-calderdale-corridor-improvement-programme-phase-1-a58a672-and-a646a6033',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.888','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Between 13 August and 27 September 2018, a period of engagement took place where the public and other interested parties were asked for their comments on the Calderdale CIPs proposals. Following this, the feedback was analysed and the plans were developed further. [4]','Public Engagement on Calderdale CIPs Proposals','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2018-08-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF2XxSz9rhEwJodGOu572Oj11yjAwivwmt-wklNFMQaAYBWusyp1--EP8boKhsrZLDYD5o5MN70bX9DdtC26R1pNyESJjin-9yBZ2g25gCG4fqfDDNW0oJoQgfgZoIkpb8eE9WGJyvI4AYglSD8w_dO5xqbJUYv--rB7scSX6ufP0c3ItmLMjkrM3898_8V7nw2YFzCrvRCtp0IYjn1DvjFHxY37YKKSJ841DeApdJYVL63RasqNQJDaSxP3_WG4EtCs1uuCMqYmFuVk7NxVdbPsAUW_w==','A public engagement period took place for the Calderdale Corridor Improvement Programmes Phase 1 proposals, seeking comments from the public and interested parties on the planned improvements for the A58/A672 and A646/A6033.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d67a36d3-8107-4323-9eb3-921d06cbc0b5','infrastructure-a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction-improvement-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.993','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is looking to make improvements to the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. The improvements are intended to encourage and enable more walking and cycling in the area as well as encouraging more bus use. We would like your feedback on the proposed improvements. This consultation closed on 4 August 2021. Following the consultation period, the survey results will be analysed, and your feedback will be considered. Feedback will help develop the proposals which will be submitted via the Outline Business Case (OBC) in October 2021. Please note that there is currently no funding allocated to deliver the identified improvements once the Outline Business Case document (OBC) has been submitted. The A639 Park Road corridor is on a “reserve list” if more funding becomes available. [8]','A639 Park Road, Pontefract - Corridor Improvement Programme','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-08-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a639parkroad-cip','Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, sought public feedback on proposed improvements to the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. The consultation aimed to encourage more walking, cycling, and bus use, and address issues like poor active travel facilities, traffic congestion, and inadequate bus infrastructure. This consultation closed on August 4, 2021, with feedback to be considered for an Outline Business Case submitted in October 2021. The scheme was then on a \'reserve list\' for funding. [8, 9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d6c79771-5aeb-4e34-aa48-a043f395d36c','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford TramTrain Proposal. Transforms train access to and through Bradford City Centre. ... Possible Solutions: 1. Underground tunnel between Forster Square and Interchange: prohibitively expensive, would not improve city centre access and would have a very long lead time before opening of at least 15-20 years. 2. On-street TramTrain connection between Forster Square and Interchange with new city centre TramTrain stop(s) extending Ilkley and Skipton trains through to Interchange. Much cheaper, shorter lead time to opening of 5-10 years, and greatly improves access to the city centre from 11 Bradford Council Wards. [6]','Bradford TramTrain Proposal','Baildon Town Council (document)','2023-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.baildontowncouncil.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/bradford-tramtrain-proposal-january-2023-1.docx','A detailed conceptual proposal advocates for an \'On-street TramTrain connection\' of approximately 1km between Bradford Forster Square and Bradford Interchange stations. The document argues this solution is much cheaper and has a shorter lead time (5-10 years) compared to an expensive underground tunnel, while greatly improving city centre access and extending existing rail services. It highlights advantages like higher frequency and closer station spacing.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d6d00e1a-73ca-461c-b8ea-bd5956617335','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme will also continue. This scheme aims to construct a new link road, improving the highway and reducing congestion in the town. [13]','Major Wakefield road improvement schemes and Outwood Railway Station redevelopment to be \'paused\'','Wakefield Express','2022-11-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/major-wakefield-road-improvement-schemes-and-outwood-railway-station-redevelopment-to-be-paused-3909772','Despite other transport schemes in the region facing delays and being \'paused\' due to inflation and rising costs, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) confirmed that the Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme would continue. The scheme aims to construct a new link road, improving the highway and reducing congestion in Castleford.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d7184340-4175-4ccf-82ff-734b9ccc863b','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-star-multi-academy-trust-monk-fryston-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.364','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Mr Newton said: “Recently the school has received a government grant to replace its ageing gas boilers with ground source heat pumps and its fluorescent lights with LED ones; and the community centre has a grant from The Community Lottery Fund to replace its gas heating with an air source heat pump. “Both organisations will share their learning and data with residents and other organisations. They are being recognised as exemplar community sustainable building projects.”','Two North Yorkshire villages are set to become carbon neutral','YorkMix','2022-08-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkmix.com/two-north-yorkshire-villages-are-set-to-become-carbon-neutral/','An article highlighting the Monk Fryston and Hillam Sustainability Project mentioned that Monk Fryston Church of England Primary School had recently received a government grant to replace its ageing gas boilers with ground source heat pumps and fluorescent lights with LED ones.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d71f817c-9444-4a2d-9a0b-f8d604a2026f','infrastructure-pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.548','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been submitted for a rooftop solar farm at Pinderfields Hospital as part of a government-backed green energy project. The £2.7m scheme involves placing panels on top of eight buildings within the site in Wakefield and would contribute to an NHS trust\'s “net zero ambitions.” Documents submitted to Wakefield Council said the total area covered by the panels would be 0.67 hectares. Planning regulations require applicants to request a screening opinion from a local authority if the size of a project is more than 0.5 hectares. A report said: “We request that the local planning authority adopt a screening opinion that an EIA is not required and that the proposal can proceed.” [4]','Pinderfields Hospital rooftop solar farm plan submitted','Wakefield Express','2025-09-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/environment/pinderfields-hospital-rooftop-solar-farm-plan-submitted-4767120','Plans for a £2.7m rooftop solar farm on eight buildings at Pinderfields Hospital in Wakefield have been submitted to Wakefield Council. The scheme, covering 0.67 hectares, aims to contribute to the NHS trust\'s net-zero ambitions and is part of a government-backed green energy project. A screening opinion has been requested to determine if an Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) is required.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d735776f-38f2-4599-8888-ff7f38e97c9e','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This engagement has now closed, thank you for taking part. Your feedback has been analysed, the outcome report can be found here. In 2021 (A639 Park Road, Pontefract - Corridor Improvement Programme) you gave us feedback on options to improve transport provision on the A639 Park Road, Pontefract. We listened to your feedback and are excited to share our updated proposals. These improvements will enhance cycling, walking facilities, upgrade the existing bus network infrastructure, and improve traffic journey times for local trips along the route. Through the funding from the Department for Transport (DfT) this project has been awarded £12.4m for this work. Engagement Starts: 14 November 2024. Engagement closes: 11 December 2024. [5]','A639 Park Road, Pontefract - Improvement Scheme Public Engagement','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-11-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/A639parkroad','West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \'Your Voice\' platform launched a public engagement for the A639 Park Road, Pontefract Improvement Scheme, inviting feedback on updated proposals. The project has been awarded £12.4m from the Department for Transport. The engagement includes drop-in events and an online survey, closing on December 11, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d7396e2e-71e2-4da2-8630-2818a9ec25b6','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---southern-oastler-site-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.552','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'ve submitted plans for the first phase of the new sustainable community known as \'City Village,\' which will transform Bradford\'s former commercial core into a thriving new city centre neighbourhood. A detailed planning application for Phase One, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site, has been submitted. Later phases of the City Village neighbourhood will include more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site, alongside approximately 400 apartments on the Kirkgate site. If plans are approved, demolition of the Oastler site is expected to begin later this year, ahead of work beginning on Phase One in spring 2026. A planning application detailing a major regeneration project in Bradford city centre has been submitted. The Bradford City Village scheme will create almost 1,000 new homes, a new public park and retail and community space, if it is approved by councillors later this year. The application, which follows a public consultation earlier this summer, states the project would create a \'green, healthy, sustainable and community friendly\' city neighbourhood. Under the first phase of the proposed scheme, 97 homes would be built across Chain Street and the northern half of the Oastler zone, where the 1970s-built centre is likely to be demolished next month.','Hybrid Planning Application Submitted for Bradford City Village','English Cities Fund (ECF) / Yahoo News Canada','2025-09-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGu3L4wLfIcmUOCI3EZh86hlQ9GyAtwe7g2qG-N2txW7e81b5OSNbCJxFDJYSckZDOgUg55B9Ku10TGEwUcPzq8_6YlrCRxL38OZIW6vjJ6G5Q9JpcBaeQqu20hPOCLLasXtV-yigvm_1SVuksbcw1KMTqgIpsmffQmWXyA2p8L3T7ECW6FDWmbsKoo9Ns=','ECF, in partnership with Bradford Council, submitted a hybrid planning application for the Bradford City Village. This includes detailed permission for Phase One (Chain Street and northern Oastler site) and outline permission for future phases, which specifically include \'more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site, alongside approximately 400 apartments on the Kirkgate site\'. Demolition of the Oastler site is expected to begin later this year. [7, 10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d7536cd3-f0b8-4c52-8b19-82b13e4451cf','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'COUNCIL bosses have released extra funding for to delayed Darley Street Market scheme – although the extra cost was not revealed in public. Bradford Council\'s Executive agreed to the extra funding for the market, which had recently been budgeted at £31m, at a meeting on Tuesday. But details of the extra money were discussed in a section of the meeting where public and press were excluded... During the meeting it was revealed that the market\'s food court is fully let, and would be a “new offer” for the city centre. ... He said the costs for the fit out were proving to be higher than originally budgeted, and urged the Executive to release money from a “contingency fund” to help finish off the development. ... She said while the market building was completed in June, and the food court was almost completed – and all tenants now signed up – the two market floors still needed to be fitted out.','Extra funding put towards Bradford\'s Darley Street Market scheme','Greatest Hits Radio (West Yorkshire)','2025-02-19 00:00:00.000','https://planetradio.co.uk/greatest-hits/west-yorkshire/','Bradford Council\'s Executive approved additional funding for the delayed Darley Street Market project, though the specific amount was kept confidential due to commercial sensitivities. The market\'s food court was reported to be fully let, but the fit-out for the remaining two market floors required more funds than initially budgeted, necessitating a release from a contingency fund to complete the development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d76943e4-2ab0-4f94-bb80-e59623117fd0','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'From late-spring, vulnerable customers will begin making the switch to Digital Voice, supported by free in-home visits from engineers and battery backup units to keep them connected during power cuts. Rollout schedule for vulnerable customers: Spring 2025: East of England, Northern Ireland, Wales, Yorkshire & Humber. [21]','BT Launches National Campaign for Digital Landline Switch - Rural Services Network','Rural Services Network','2025-03-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEWwyQ_sh88OovbEqOBEPp9pNVdXgAbxp-XPellg60rq5knfx_5Dy_0ljIH3Y54tASgugpSqaxHOJzfCP2RSFH5DPk5TulJEfhPhb7B_06nU77tgQ6q4srjAkfpX6E72mkfV1EMDf-veaLx6mQIKkN97J_A-yEiJipJpPsPdq8bP2o4JDS4PwfwdseFkQKxBeXf','BT launched a national campaign for the digital landline switch, with a specific focus on supporting vulnerable customers. The rollout schedule for vulnerable customers indicates that those in Yorkshire & Humber would begin making the switch in Spring 2025, with free in-home engineer visits and battery backup units provided.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d79c373e-7c6f-4234-bbb8-c9b60733635f','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin has joined forces with a local bus operator to take back and improve a Calderdale bus route. Passengers using the 571 service, which runs between Halifax and Shelf, via Brighouse, Southowram and Hipperholme, were seeing poor performance from the previous operator on the service. But the West Yorkshire Combined Authority has stepped up to not only retender the service to a new operator, Go Ahead Buses, but also to increase its frequency. A revised timetable – starting this week – was introduced for the service, paid for using money from the Combined Authority\'s Bus Service Improvement Plan. Daytime frequency of the service for the Halifax to Brighouse section of the route has now been increased from one every hour, to one every 30 minutes. [5]','West Yorkshire Mayor teams up with local operator to improve Calderdale bus route','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-02-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4Ga2P3SunLmPs8HQ5FUg16KPsLsODHN-gROAoCsH0q369bM6hnnPs_Fi4p2ec_YgZgKfDxX1-MP9nCndpmIOrJGrtoqW53Vbu48MRu67xoCTQSdNUMsowzDryVAHIMgBB9aKnLm8iJlCkUTGZknjwA4pd7-0jwUqf8s9U9IaOkJ5kNeFi6ABYyEINpDySfrh7SFNNHjE3kQb_G0H6fxcb_HeNQvnLbLB1twbf5AvE3pBXZSaddRjSkHcMB2E','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin confirmed Go-Ahead Buses as the new operator for the 571 service, and announced an increased daytime frequency to every 30 minutes for the Halifax to Brighouse section. This improved timetable, funded by the Bus Service Improvement Plan, began the week of February 26, 2025, addressing previous performance issues. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d7bc1c1c-17de-4de2-a18b-8fc4afcb9f5a','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'It is pleasing to see WYCA sticking to its guns and advocating electrification including the full Calder Valley. This and the government-proposed Leeds- Bradford electrification must seen as one scheme. The Calder Valley routes do require full electrification. Hybrid trains with multiple traction systems are heavier, waste more energy, and are potentially less reliable. By full we mean the whole route through Bradford and Brighouse to upper Calderdale. Manchester, Preston and beyond. [18]','Calder Valley and Halifax rail: time to plan upgrades!','Halifax and District Rail Action Group (HADRAG)','2024-07-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH9Gl6EVIcE0DKBAreUa25dtoxEmx5TC9xMo1lMTVSz6c4ZLb47mq5QqWGnJH7cNDKJ46Xh08_B9VV9MMcg1MF1sjevUkGy1rlCZOnTeVviFxyxFaicf9757TugRr8fQpEDhi2pPLZ_2ifEV8OMLVRpM9mcGE_MXLJUd1VBLtXBBHfn3pSIDSGKXhVzw3DC','HADRAG (Halifax and District Rail Action Group) highlighted that the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) is advocating for full Calder Valley electrification, viewing the government-proposed Leeds-Bradford electrification as an integral part of this larger scheme. They emphasize the need for full electrification due to the inefficiencies of hybrid trains and the heavy freight traffic on the line.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d7d3152a-a0ec-46ef-a168-ff113ae877cf','infrastructure-leeds-flood-alleviation-scheme-phase-2',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.562','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Step 1 (zones 10 – 13) – runs along an 8km stretch upstream of Leeds station, along the A65 Kirkstall corridor. Our works largely consists of raised flood walls or embankments in the Kirkstall area. Construction works relating to this step began in January 2020.','Construction Works Begin on Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 Step 1','Leeds City Council Flood Resilience / Commonplace','2020-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGXHbVn9lGY3uulpSGq4qK8QmgtBzbTNIMId0VIyoMWQmslKFrEvoj3NfZfTRLliskB92T6PbTrb7nN61y2A7XLLRJC4nQJX6Ufoi39N81hLjm491CW218T_j7rNtxQcyFPb2in-dN_dHg9YZKhF58cnbYfdkQVu29egUuziaG7z7d7hOiMHnPkncQ4wzSXRN8EYCZZu-KgKASoR1gCL5UZ9kOsZcqs','Construction for Step 1 of the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme Phase 2 began in January 2020, focusing on an 8km stretch upstream of Leeds station along the A65 Kirkstall corridor, involving raised flood walls and embankments. This phase aimed to provide a 1-in-100 year standard of protection.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d84d60da-de1e-4052-b54f-7daf1c98c34b','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Digital Enterprise has relaunched with a bigger and better grant scheme for West Yorkshire SMEs – and it\'s the most generous yet. This is a golden opportunity to supercharge your digital growth with match funding, but only if you move quickly. ... Who\'s Eligible: B2B businesses in West Yorkshire, 3+ years trading, £100k+ turnover, 5+ employees; Deadline: First come, first served – limited funds; Ideal For: New websites, rebrands, personalised AI marketing, eCommerce upgrades, and more. ... Digital Accelerator Grant (projects under £25k) – up to £10k; High Impact Grant (projects £25k-£100k) – up to £35k. [12]','New £35,000 Digital Grant Now Open for West Yorkshire SMEs – Here\'s What You Need to Know','Fleek Marketing','2025-07-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.fleekmarketing.co.uk/blog/digital-enterprise-grants-west-yorkshire-smes-2025/','Fleek Marketing, a digital agency, announced the relaunch of Digital Enterprise grants, promoting it as a significant opportunity for West Yorkshire SMEs to secure up to £35,000 in match funding for digital projects. The article details eligibility criteria (B2B, 3+ years trading, £100k+ turnover, 5+ employees) and the two grant types: Digital Accelerator (up to £10k) and High Impact (up to £35k). It emphasizes the competitive, rolling deadline and advises prompt application.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d85c6e06-6550-4573-8ba2-534da33f2a93','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Gillespies has developed a masterplan for Wakefield District Council which sets out proposals to regenerate Knottingley Town Centre and Hill Top, in support of a Levelling Up Funding application. The masterplan proposes... Creating a new leisure hub... will complement the existing Kellingley Social Club and sports pitches to create a community hub. While the £19m bid to the Levelling Up Fund Round 2 wasn\'t successful, we are continuing to work with the council to find other funding opportunities to deliver the project.','Knottingley Town Centre Regeneration - News','Gillespies','2023-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFbwJ1QOEkRnhm0VWPT-aY5NJarRZiPsXhuw9yTmSZ24fNAMLVEC-sQo0XDiWvAQF_Sv_7-rl_uvmY2NmG4A8v954Xn31OLIthqpetXYgF-wFfMFVrm1uMv4YLLn_NL3U_ysNYefDMg5VH4VxFzQgoZUd6y1oW003_zD-LCMxxYTMLJf58=','Gillespies developed a masterplan for Wakefield District Council for Knottingley Town Centre and Hill Top regeneration, which included creating a new leisure hub to complement the Kellingley Social Club. The article notes that a £19 million bid to the Levelling Up Fund Round 2 was unsuccessful, but work continues to find alternative funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d894f1d4-bbff-4048-bcdc-f9ecb40ba385','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Updated plans as part of work to transform Halifax town centre will be discussed by Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet tonight. The A629 Phase 2 - Halifax town centre project is fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and aims to improve pedestrian and cycle access into and within Halifax town centre. It also includes an upgrade of the highway network around the town and supports economic development of brown field sites to the east of the town. As part of the next steps for the project, Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet will discuss the process of acquiring land needed for the improvement work, with proposed changes to the alignment of the scheme on Church Street to incorporate land from the recently demolished section of Deal Street warehouse. Members will be asked to note these amends to the original design and approve the use of Compulsory Purchase Orders if required. [19]','Update to plans to transform Halifax town centre to be revealed','Halifax Courier','2021-10-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/council/update-to-plans-to-transform-halifax-town-centre-to-be-revealed-3407635','Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet was set to discuss updated plans for the A629 Phase 2 - Halifax town centre project. This included the process of acquiring land needed for improvement work, proposed changes to the alignment of the scheme on Church Street (eastern side works) to incorporate land from a recently demolished section of Deal Street warehouse, and the potential use of Compulsory Purchase Orders if required. The project aims to improve pedestrian and cycle access, upgrade the highway network, and support economic development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d8a592e8-a9d1-4575-ac27-0fc6d369c903','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-city-regional-sustainable-transport-settlement-crsts-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.783','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Rt. Hon. Grant Shapps, Secretary of State, confirmed the full CRSTS allocation of £830m to West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) for investment in local transport networks, following the previous announcement at Spending Review 2021. The funding is for investment in local transport networks in WYCA as outlined in your programme business case and delivery plan, with a capital grant profile across 2022/23 to 2026/27. Additionally, revenue grant funding for 2022/23 was confirmed to support the development of the CRSTS capital investment programme and build longer-term local transport planning and delivery capacity. WYCA is expected to make a contribution of at least 15-20 percent of the funding granted for capital enhancements. Any cost overruns must be met locally with no additional HMG funding provided.','Allocating City Region Sustainable Transport Settlements','GOV.UK','2022-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/city-region-sustainable-transport-settlement-allocation-letters-for-mayoral-combined-authorities/crsts-funding-settlement-letter-for-west-yorkshire-1-april-2022','This is a letter from the Secretary of State confirming the allocation of £830 million to the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) for the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS) programme. The funding is for investment in local transport networks over a five-year period (2022-2027), following the Spending Review 2021. It outlines the capital grant profile and additional revenue grant funding to support programme development and build transport planning capacity. The letter emphasizes the requirement for WYCA to contribute 15-20 percent locally and manage any cost overruns.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d8f01f85-df1e-4f39-a2de-9611698f2e63','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work to breathe new life into Todmorden Town Hall is progressing well, with the completion of the first improvements at the iconic building. ... To improve the visitor experience at events, new facilities are now in place on the first floor. This includes a new bar in the main hall, which has been created using materials repurposed from the court room ... A new warming kitchen has also been installed... New toilets and changing areas are now in place under the stage area in the main hall and a new accessible toilet is also due to be installed. ... The work is due to be finished later this year.','Investing in a thriving future for Todmorden Town Hall','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2025-09-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGmI_7fj65tkbf3ym0hZ-35qS5yrFHQjLcvtmSEmwBcWoeaOmbBGvHYtZkiIDTXVk4viwD-fFQv1Sojjs-0vz_A0kw-A8QjoN4eA03cnr6ZiTFQcWP4gxaFaOythmv2a7IgnuY2PKLJ4EgFFUCM1HlMe8GG2xtbgVAdlfydojumZMh9D9XMe6lQ2zlSKilMz9_x','Calderdale Council\'s news centre reports that work on Todmorden Town Hall is progressing well, with the completion of the first improvements. Details include new facilities on the first floor such as a new bar, a warming kitchen, and new toilets/changing areas. Further improvements like opening the grand entrance and changes to the courtroom are planned for later in the year.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d91240c3-09a8-4da6-b0fe-3864410e2b72','infrastructure-cleckheaton-spen-valley-greenway-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.625','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We are working with the charity Sustrans to upgrade accessibility, lighting and surfacing on a 2km (1.5-mile) section of the Greenway between the Tesco supermarket, Cleckheaton and Knowler Hill Tunnel at Liversedge. ... The scheme has received £15 million funding from the WYCA\'s Transforming Cities Fund. ... Work on the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton and Liversedge commenced in June 2025. ... Resurfacing and widening 2km (1.5miles) length of greenway, giving it a smoother finish for a better experience for everyone. New signage and lighting which will improve safety. Easier and more accessible access points on and off the greenway.','A638 Dewsbury-Cleckheaton Sustainable Travel Corridor - Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council','2025-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/traffic-transport-and-roads/a638-dewsbury-cleckheaton-sustainable-travel-corridor.aspx','Kirklees Council\'s project page for the A638 Sustainable Travel Corridor details improvements to a 2km section of the Spen Valley Greenway between Cleckheaton (Tesco) and Liversedge (Knowler Hill Tunnel). These upgrades include resurfacing, widening, new signage, improved lighting, and more accessible entry points. The page confirms that work on this section of the greenway commenced in June 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d939a8f5-89be-4ffe-987a-0b0dd458671a','infrastructure-a660-holt-lane--otley-road-junction-improvements-adel-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.964','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council launched a consultation on January 31, 2023, for improvements along the A660 Otley Road, Headingley Lane, and Woodhouse Lane. [18]','Consultation now live: A660 Otley Road, Headingley Lane and Woodhouse Lane','GovDelivery (Leeds City Council News)','2023-01-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGVeVEtzl6as4DVxk0qNm-eRIwfxb359Bb_Cv3YILe1tJCQCoqyHas7hsWDRRq9YowGucA67Dt3kIlPna8UFFk5yMFJXsSW-N2FXiXl4a_SGPLrYNqCMbt0w5WuFX3wN5dksg-i9L-0X1oiQg0zbWzosjmJPBgfJfOo1rSQ2Q==','Leeds City Council announced a consultation on January 31, 2023, for wider improvements along the A660 corridor, covering Otley Road, Headingley Lane, and Woodhouse Lane. While the Holt Lane junction itself was completed earlier, this shows ongoing strategic investment and planning for the broader A660 route, including sections of Otley Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d93db501-48e8-4d3c-a682-9b145f229e38','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme will benefit from the scheme with £6.7m, the A650 Newton Bar revamp project will receive £9.4m, and the Glass Houghton Southern Link Road will receive £1.8m. [11]','Wakefield Council is planning to invest £355 million in services and infrastructure to save our economy - this is where the money will go','Wakefield Express','2021-02-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/wakefield-council-is-planning-to-invest-ps355-million-in-services-and-infrastructure-to-save-our-economy-this-is-where-the-money-will-go-3140509','Wakefield Council announced plans to invest £355 million in services and infrastructure, with £6.7 million specifically allocated to the Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme. This funding is part of a broader economic regeneration strategy for the district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d95f7940-e876-42c7-8cdb-daaaabac6adf','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Works to pedestrianise key areas in Bradford city centre continue to \"progress well\", according to project bosses. Providing an update, the team overseeing the Walking and Cycling Improvement scheme said: \"New paving has been laid down on much of Market Street to the western side. Work will now concentrate on the eastern side, where more paving, to provide wider footway space, and planting areas will be installed.\" On Bank Street, work is continuing to prepare the area for more paving to be laid between Market Street and Broadway. The installation of new bollards will continue near to the junction with Hall Ings. Transformation works also started on Bridge Street a few weeks ago, with new paving for the future service vehicle route being laid on the City Park side of the road. The works to demolish the former NCP car park will create a new green space, linking to Hall Ings and Norfolk Gardens.','Bradford city centre pedestrianisation \'progressing well\'','Telegraph and Argus','2024-06-28 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24420846.bradford-city-centre-pedestrianisation-progressing-well/','An update indicated that works to pedestrianise key areas in Bradford city centre were progressing well. New paving had been laid on Market Street, and work was continuing on Bank Street and Broadway. Transformation works also started on Bridge Street, and the demolition of the former NCP car park was underway to create a new green space linking to Hall Ings and Norfolk Gardens.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d970528b-c20b-4b81-beca-1c8b10244976','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme was recognised for its excellence, winning the Centenary Award at the Institution of Civil Engineers Yorkshire & Humber Awards in 2022. The award highlighted the project\'s commitment to health and safety, its successful execution in a constrained environment, and significant community engagement efforts.','Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme wins Centenary Award at ICE Yorkshire & Humber Awards','Eye on Calderdale','2022-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://eyeoncalderdale.com/mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme','The Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme was recognised for its excellence, winning the Centenary Award at the Institution of Civil Engineers Yorkshire & Humber Awards in 2022. The award highlighted the project\'s commitment to health and safety, its successful execution in a constrained environment, and significant community engagement efforts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d99d8ff3-f7e3-41e6-97f5-223262e2326d','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Luminate Education Group has received £51m funding from the government to replace and upgrade some of its buildings. [19] Leeds City College, the largest member of Luminate Education Group, will begin new campus building works on its Mabgate site that will facilitate the development of new higher level technical and apprenticeship courses. [15] In addition to this new facility which replaces the College House building, a purpose built Adult education building will be built at the same time, replacing the existing Enfield Centre. [15]','Luminate Education Group secures £51 million government funding for building transformation','Luminate Education Group / FE News','2022-07-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFIrGkZwbeKpRmgLMiIR6Bg3WNBM6OZZlEa4bummHKFVXwSAko58uoHcg3yIpGl1Fb7xhajo6wfZK96qw8mhSHgHpJJGN05IZca8YcY-iOI-YZ623cjExG4S7fp5HvVwG_d0c3GEozeUogegehgS2lP82oG_bGe0IEeaGQLNVKNuRyUSqWh00PzOUFbqYSqSGus57yssuCYzQ','Luminate Education Group, which includes Leeds City College, received £51 million from the government\'s Further Education Capital Transformation Fund. This funding is designated for replacing and upgrading college buildings, with significant new campus building works planned for the Mabgate site to facilitate higher-level technical and apprenticeship courses, and a new adult education building.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('d9dd396e-6ca6-4caf-b8d6-d23e289dc3b0','infrastructure-a629-salterhebble-to-shaw-hill-corridor-improvement-phase-1a-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.874','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2021-12-15) Work is now underway to transform the Calder and Hebble junction corridor of the A629 near Halifax - the largest individual civil engineering project ever undertaken to date by Calderdale Council. ... This section of work will complement the earlier widening from Salterhebble hill to Free School Lane, completed in 2018. ... The £28.1 million project is funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority as part of the wider A629 improvement programme.','Progress update on £28m project to transform the A629 Calder and Hebble Junction','Halifax Courier','2021-12-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFSaRrE-q9xc7aXaQhlSDuSQGuP1oaE6tHChKaNpdNezaZaFGP6DOZWkJIxTKSZm-wdelKYqZjk_AlrbL57RvHHqoZyRaKmtn5qbEUUUUt1qpP3eUeiRtwRmBYSjTTSJOWDbd-zfaVfxXaOeoQw6bt9EGp6YwqJpkbEhQkabypXgkEn2lw113fuUlJP8o4kfWD0tINeWWIHwdgnrE6nZd5lJzLZ4M0TQJ0eOKWNFRIACXkKLIozAG2YClVCGELfg0mAXw51dA==','This December 2021 article provides an update on Phase 1b of the A629 improvement scheme, focusing on the Calder and Hebble Junction. It explicitly states that this phase will complement the earlier widening from Salterhebble Hill to Free School Lane, which was completed in 2018, thereby placing Phase 1a within the context of the larger A629 improvement program.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('da071a83-e462-45d4-9631-5cb37ea84f21','infrastructure-bradford-crossrail-tram-train-link-concept',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.040','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The consultants report recommends that to link Leeds to the airport a tram-train link be built from Horsforth. ... If a route from the airport to Guiseley could be built for tram-trains, then they could carry on to Bradford Forster Square station, thus giving Bradford direct access to the airport. [8]','Tram-Trains Recommended For Leeds-Bradford Airport Link (with potential to Bradford)','The Anonymous Widower (Blog referencing Global Rail News)','2016-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://anonymouswidower.blogspot.com/2016/03/tram-trains-recommended-for-leeds.html','A consultant\'s report recommended a tram-train link from Horsforth to Leeds-Bradford Airport. The article discusses the possibility that if a route from the airport to Guiseley were built for tram-trains, they could potentially continue to Bradford Forster Square station, thereby providing Bradford with direct airport access. This reflects ongoing discussions about airport connectivity and its wider regional impact.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('da0f9216-60b3-42a2-b343-ae07a5fd4e77','infrastructure-huddersfield-bus-station-upgrades-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.947','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Name of meeting: Economy and Neighborhoods Scrutiny Panel Date: 18 October 2022 Title of report: Progress Update on Huddersfield ... The response to this was overwhelmingly positive with most respondents, 76%, replying positively. ... Responsibility for the bus station projects is split between WYCA and Kirklees Council. WYCA are leading on Huddersfield Bus Station transformation and Dewsbury Bus Station. Kirklees Council is leading on Heckmondwike Bus Station and the canopy, cycle hub & public realm improvements and car park access to Huddersfield Bus Station. ... The scheme will install new seating, lighting, flooring and an information point in the concourse, and new signs will help people navigate in and around the bus station. New real time information boards will also be installed providing passengers with live bus and rail information. The scheme will also include a new roof with solar panels, cycle parking facilities, a Changing Places facility with a fully accessible toilet and generous space and equipment, and improvements to staff areas.','Progress Update on Huddersfield Bus Station - Economy and Neighborhoods Scrutiny Panel Report','Kirklees Council','2022-10-18 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGURLuGP9wIr2hnAzuLKKRjcOuHAK7mhAclmDqZvaIM-wQ7bTayZFSwHVEflRPUvvT2ghIs7kEDAX6XB27Ypv6fvozCqmw7f38p8O4SjiAADIfuBLwu8dU79sAp4eC3G7nxDEZy7z_PPrusB3OdWEFArJQoszwHmJHdJOA0MYAegUw1Q7oECLXD9hxRFkrgcPude_RMQoYSrA==','A report to the Kirklees Council Economy and Neighborhoods Scrutiny Panel provided an update on the Huddersfield Bus Station project. It detailed positive public consultation responses, with 76% replying positively, and confirmed that responsibility for the bus station projects is split between WYCA and Kirklees Council. The report also outlined planned interior improvements, new information boards, solar panels, and a Changing Places facility.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('da48692b-158e-4cd6-9e94-9bc7d7e45fe1','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the English Cities Fund (ECF), is inviting the public to play a pivotal role in shaping the future of Bradford City Village, a project poised to deliver 1,000 new homes and breathe new life into the former retail hub of the city centre. This visionary initiative, set in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, including the sites of the Kirkgate and Oastler shopping centres, aims to create a sustainable neighbourhood at the heart of the city centre. Local residents, businesses, and stakeholders are encouraged to participate in an online survey or attend a roadshow event where they can engage directly with the project team and contribute their insights to this transformational scheme.','Public Consultation Unveiled for Bradford City Village Masterplan','UKREiiF','2023-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFw8MFvXApGd7cUHwdnK6j-B8nf4EKK-bfsQz1hGlLR7muCQaWt3mZf9S0arO7J9STI6csDplGlZOvT3lK4MV5Gt-R8Zqs6hWlcJeghg3_R3KWMDGGH4L-0R-wbURKAxq8TuJxRLL9FdppgqFdJP4j5pCLnEI6FX7RlxQG0','Bradford Council, in partnership with ECF, launched a public consultation inviting feedback on the City Village masterplan, which aims to deliver 1,000 new homes and revitalize the city centre\'s former retail hub across Kirkgate and Oastler sites.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('da8d1a4f-cc75-4b6d-8a58-20bf4608a5c2','infrastructure-toby-carvery-leeds-aberford-road-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.388','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This electric car charge point located at Toby Carvery Leeds, LS26 8EJ is part of the BP Pulse network. Download the Zapmap app or view our interactive web map to see other nearby chargers and live status data. ... Sources: Zapmap. Updated: 04th September 2025.','Toby Carvery Leeds charging point - Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-09-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.zap-map.com/charge-points/toby-carvery-leeds-ev-charging-point/','Zapmap, a popular EV charging map service, lists an active electric vehicle charging point at Toby Carvery Leeds, located at 2 Aberford Road, LS26 8EJ. The charger is part of the BP Pulse network and offers Type 2 (42.78kW), CHAdeMO (50kW), and CCS (50kW) connectors. This listing was updated on September 4, 2025, indicating current operational status.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dab8bbed-076b-4371-a2b7-eccf07c8a7b2','infrastructure-leeds-city-college-mabgate-campus-redevelopment',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.659','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City College, part of Luminate Education Group, has submitted outline plans to deliver new education and sports facilities, as part of a proposed new college campus near the city centre on Mabgate, Leeds. The proposals which include high-quality education facilities, a sports complex, and a residential development are in response to the significant growth the college has seen over the last decade. The new campus could transform a currently derelict 275,957sq ft site, bringing investment and regeneration to the area whilst helping to provide much-needed community facilities. [7] An outline planning application, which establishes the principles of the project, has been submitted for approval to Leeds City Council. [3] Residents are being invited to visit www.leedscitycollegemabgate.co.uk, where they can learn more about the proposals and submit their feedback on the outline plans. The consultation will run from August 20th – September 7th. [2]','Leeds City College submits outline plans for new Mabgate campus','TheBusinessDesk.com / Yorkshire Post / Cartwright Pickard','2020-08-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGlXk8LwPKZfhFEBLkCCVjI7FOsZGHx6KWWXtPFhIRin6zmG9R3LStiRtsN_qwj-b-t_Gui_pStfb4UviZjulpuhJubHbYIHGzJfAfFl96cxLHw9E4v_K3DLxVN_387obaEnBvEUlurD0Nvs-smCJa-m5jdr-e1SG6E6jwUzHU81_bwMhiuOOboU27rGGse23I','Leeds City College, part of Luminate Education Group, submitted an outline planning application to Leeds City Council for a new campus on a derelict site in Mabgate. The proposals included education and sports facilities, office space, and residential development, aiming to address college growth and provide community facilities. A public consultation period was also announced.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dab97a0c-1aa5-4a11-9645-d40a8512a161','infrastructure-a660-holt-lane--otley-road-junction-improvements-adel-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.964','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The A660 Holt Lane / Otley Road in Adel scheme started in 2017. [6]','Road and highway improvements - A660 Holt Lane Project Overview','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2017-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEQZqfxYWI74RbED-OW8tifFWymi-yzVX8nimKlBY6oEhfoLb4s4Zy8IBCUtSbvPLoYqgpvKKyf3OQZ6YKQVYtzuHKJdTlTMOf6CGLVuYGOS0-rvRy7N5fh7TEecZf0bkNRsYmLGyMM1-uDR1kQjma0-aRvPhhmfRh0lIKYJ5_QPZvmKJgeUICgh3EXMNk4inZhgBTnA_HiynF9ozUfBOb6wZtToPyAtwJNaIzP393Q8exOVF2BtURI44AUqL5AqGI9Wfc=','This project overview from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority website states that the A660 Holt Lane / Otley Road in Adel scheme began in 2017. It details the funding from the Leeds Public Transport Investment Programme at £1,150,000.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dae2547b-32d0-4945-a93f-393623830da8','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Levelling Up funding application confirmed. October 2021. The overall completion of both phases is scheduled for winter 2024. £20m of the work is funded by the Government\'s Levelling Up Fund with the remaining £3.257m being provided by West Yorkshire Combined Authority. Funding for both phases have been approved by the Department for Transport.','Levelling Up Funding Confirmed for Connecting West Leeds','Commonplace / Leeds City Council News / BDC Magazine','2021-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFwJDRiydwrRXKsH9JOfoCgv6kxz108eOUPm8Th8QoiSlvEcHa0DyHUoniPPrbQv2HY5edpewXqhBLKwv5z6HsajNIV2aJIZ3NevhboYWLkUJTU7kSkzP4cGPa-5ZjSXUK7rni_TzCUTQIQwLPY2oqbztxR, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHEkvq1NWvHLg1OTDy6OiA3SOnAKl_QgRJx28X5nyB0q5_5MzZsfEZ46RhM9yXP5Nyqp9iqpqSk9aQ9r3dUEwMkMDeG1wuJErXEvw3Avz8BTK_oz5CMN3PSGrWc69rAOSZRsUq9dOWYZSfv817J5YrHFMJcXzw_65vf_QJOYIWqCeFQ2f--Hns0CKyd7Y-wxIlll1X0FM65I437TikLmWj7sJKw1qYOngUZgkQJNTV5','Funding from the Government\'s Levelling Up Fund was confirmed in October 2021 for the Connecting West Leeds scheme, which includes improvements to the A6120 Outer Ring Road, Fink Hill, Horsforth roundabout, and the Horsforth to Rodley cycle link. This secured a significant portion of the £23.2 million required for the overall project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dafb67fc-1a20-40a7-96a1-0b2225958dbf','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Mayor of West Yorkshire Tracy Brabin has decided to take control of the buses in the biggest shake up to public transport in the region for decades. In a landmark move, the Mayor decided to bring buses under local control - through a process known as franchising - as recommended by the Combined Authority at its meeting in Leeds today. Routes, frequencies, fares and overall standards for buses in the region will be set by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority – not private operators, who will instead be contracted to run services on the Combined Authority\'s behalf. ... The Mayor\'s decision follows a three month consultation which revealed that nearly three-quarters of the people and organisations which responded supported franchising. ... To ensure a smooth transition, franchising will be introduced in phases, with the first franchised buses up and running in parts of Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield from March 2027. ... WYCA has already laid out that transition and transition management costs for franchising will be over £20 million, and that depot and fleet investment of above £335 million will be necessary over 15 years for a combination of bringing those assets into its ownership, and the deployment of more than 850 zero-emission buses. [14, 17, 18, 25]','West Yorkshire Mayor takes buses back under public control / Bus franchising in West Yorkshire formally adopted as reform path','Metro - WYMetro / RouteONE magazine / Bradford Telegraph and Argus / Bus & Coach Buyer','2024-03-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGPdCSF7u1UE3_S3ZocL3MsJFRFz-FYjZ4fScMddwr43hB075c1ac68hvRz8xfdwo2YHDTcYrtym1ZmOH7D45vyYgbkchqAMOUI5ujRpV56_2wDUzltoNPNcfVxPaIRdeTEoZFytdP5fSgVqKTGTIJdyxn0LqCIOcm8XZCfsrqCJjyYkf0nqSG2jpwMkr_T_h4JtCgq-Y2CG-Dp79QQbU-To2RvizA=','Mayor of West Yorkshire, Tracy Brabin, formally announced the decision to introduce bus franchising, bringing services under local control. This \'landmark\' move, recommended by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) after a three-month consultation showing strong public support, means WYCA will set routes, frequencies, fares, and standards, rather than private operators. The first franchised services are expected to launch in parts of Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield from March 2027, with a phased rollout across the region. Transition and management costs were estimated at over £20 million, with a further £335 million needed over 15 years for depot and zero-emission fleet investment. [14, 17, 18, 25]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('db46b8a3-33e5-4216-b0cc-e07c5ea96bc5','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.902','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, invited public feedback on proposed changes to Halifax town centre as part of Phase 2 of the A629 Improvement Programme. This public consultation on a Traffic Regulation Order included changes to bus stops, taxi ranks, cycle and pedestrian zones, parking, and traffic rerouting. The consultation ran from February 6 to March 5, 2023.','People invited to give feedback on changes to Halifax town centre Traffic Regulation Order proposals','Telegraph and Argus','2023-02-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/23322100.people-invited-give-feedback-changes-halifax-town-centre/','Calderdale Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, invited public feedback on proposed changes to Halifax town centre as part of Phase 2 of the A629 Improvement Programme. This public consultation on a Traffic Regulation Order included changes to bus stops, taxi ranks, cycle and pedestrian zones, parking, and traffic rerouting. The consultation ran from February 6 to March 5, 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('db4d0594-cce7-440a-9ef0-15bcda5e57b2','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Now in its third iteration, Digital Enterprise (DE3) has provided West Yorkshire SMEs with up to 50% funding for projects that have boosted the area\'s economic growth. ... Suzanne Bradbury, Programme Manager for Digital Enterprise says “As funding for eligible DE3 projects is due to end on the 31st March 2025, applications will need to be in before the end of the year in order to complete in time. ... One business that has successfully accessed funding through DE3 is Bradford-based sign makers, Sign Focus, who will be speaking at this event. [19]','A Boost for Business in Bradford','Digital Enterprise','2024-02-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.digitalenterprise.co.uk/news/a-boost-for-business-in-bradford/','This Digital Enterprise news article focuses on the impact of DE3 in Bradford. It notes that DE3 has provided up to 50% funding for projects boosting economic growth in West Yorkshire SMEs, including those in Bradford. It highlights a Bradford-based company, Sign Focus, that successfully accessed a Digital Accelerator Grant. The article mentions the program is due to end on March 31, 2025, with applications encouraged before the end of 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('db83494b-a3eb-4d2a-8255-190317d45d54','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following an immense effort by our local councils, community groups, and fellow members of Parliament, like Mark Eastwood and Jason McCartney, it is brilliant news that our bid to upgrade the Penistone Line has been awarded £48 million. ... This investment offers a great chance to improve public transport links along the route, and to bring the sort of benefits to our towns and villages that are already enjoyed in other city regions across the UK. ... The £48 million investment in the Penistone Line will see: Upgrades to the track and signalling, improving journey times and reliability. Upgrades will also be made to our stations to integrate them with local bus services. Users of the Penistone, Silkstone Common, Dodworth and Chapeltown stations all benefiting from the improvemens; Delivery of important link between South and West Yorkshire, including connections to Leeds and Manchester etc. [23]','£48 million Penistone Line Upgrade | Miriam Cates','Miriam Cates MP Official Website','2023-11-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.miriamcates.org.uk/news/48-million-penistone-line-upgrade','Miriam Cates MP announced the success of the bid to upgrade the Penistone Line, securing £48 million from the Levelling Up Fund. This investment aims to improve public transport links, including upgrades to track and signalling, better journey times, reliability, and station improvements at Penistone, Silkstone Common, Dodworth, and Chapeltown.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dbda373a-6f19-43c2-b528-4d447f418acc','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'DETAILS of a £35 million scheme to improve a busy Bradford route will be revealed in the New Year. Earlier this year West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced a major scheme for Kings Road, which runs from Wrose to Bradford city centre. At the time it was said the changes would include 4km of bus lanes and over 5km of cycle lanes, as well as the creation of 10 new pedestrian crossings and improvements to 21 bus stops. The Kings Road Connect scheme is being delivered as part of the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, a £830m fund awarded to West Yorkshire by the Department for Transport in 2022. Plans for the works have been drawn up and will be revealed when a public consultation starts in the New Year. A spokesperson for WYCA said: “A preferred way forward has now been established which will be shared with the public in the new year as part of a six-week consultation period.”','Public to be consulted on £35m Kings Road scheme in New Year - Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-12-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGpjwiUEH_XC1uaVea3rqJiygbaNdMGF58_8dSYZ0jzlhWDGQAuqPXMUns4yCs-Asuc2EuMZoCRi2Xa0ascINtNHkw3WFzjIs61-tFE4cpEv6_CSChpwGShN9PcpqhISSWvb6ezcH9yedRfhReTdpENXaPLgqNdiWB7x9vCvUhcK5PHp2z6qLoL3YiPZlvJrKbtMZxjW_Q6ab75gdV0sux6','This article announced that details of the £35 million Kings Road Connect scheme would be revealed in the New Year, preceding a public consultation. The scheme, delivered as part of the City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, aims to address congestion and lack of provision for walking, wheeling, and cycling on Kings Road. A six-week public consultation period was planned to allow residents to provide feedback via the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s \'Your Voice\' platform and at drop-in sessions.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dd03dd4a-b433-474a-b0fc-e50889c73b96','infrastructure-proposed-highway-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.142','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work has started in Todmorden to install a new crossing point outside Lidl on Halifax Road. These works are expected to last until 28 June 2022. Work on the islands, kerb lines and footpaths near the roundabout at the junction of Rochdale Road and Halifax Road is underway. These works are expected to be complete by 20 July 2022.','Work starts on new crossing point outside Lidl on Halifax Road, Todmorden','Calderdale Next Chapter','2022-06-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHWPYB2x5OitEv42E_LIbTvRuqnMcrgOM8WnT1NkMTtlHYCrX89rcECPmzXh-rdSMOwyE_WpZKVrscKtOZrrJ0sg7sm9q1UD3OyBbZ_o6sf60V2djqH7D2WnOK70X68ElSjWpn3DcXTzh9McvwJfTeCV3C5RqpMTcYdXKnJRO6jAgXFDx_sxM0fSJvz88vu','Work commenced in Todmorden to install a new crossing point outside Lidl on Halifax Road. This initiative is part of broader improvements, with additional work on islands, kerb lines, and footpaths near the roundabout at the junction of Rochdale Road and Halifax Road.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dd2b226a-0d62-476d-8bea-c42511c3ba6a','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'ve pledged to become a carbon neutral council by 2030. This means having a net zero carbon footprint, and we aim to help the entire district achieve this goal too by 2038. Our Climate Change Action Plan was approved by cabinet in September 2020. We\'re building a dedicated climate change team and an extensive programme of work is well under way. ... To deliver this project we will: ... Install EV charging points across the district, and ensure this work covers the requirements of the corporate EV fleet.','Wakefield Council Climate Change Action Plan approved, including EV charging infrastructure','Wakefield Council','2020-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEJ0Z9zYUVEGiTM0bqxitWY-0_vCAHqVKjf2gVxqjy_h2pO1Q1P2g-UgOSJ9lZfcVWi8ZUBoJSxkyJ2_Cymvq0hi3Ar59q2XnYr8tnUb6xl2Lb4jULZrFifdUrmZiLLU7mtxVNkDYQsDvSTdOdm2cjWZvSlQUMDgfPXSgtcMDaWEjHeUI6_IVU1uLHvc9bgy60hD8zzRfFSgvbL-K8-DZGRsVjB','Wakefield Council\'s Climate Change Action Plan (CCAP) was approved by cabinet in September 2020. This plan includes a commitment to install EV charging points across the district, ensuring that this work covers the requirements of the corporate EV fleet and supporting the district\'s broader net zero targets by 2038.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ddab54d3-58c2-47c1-b85e-bf47622ad10e','infrastructure-proposed-highway-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.142','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A new combined council team is streamlining the process of dealing with issues arising from Calderdale\'s highways and Green Spaces. Duties the new team deals with takes in keeping neighbourhoods and town centres clean, maintaining parks and open spaces, looking after play areas, allotments, and sports pitches, repairing potholes, pavements, walls and drainage, protecting and and enhance the countryside, keeping the highway network open in bad weather and dealing with a range of highway-related emergencies round the clock.','Calderdale Council merges highways and green spaces teams','Highways Magazine','2022-03-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHmdjAWMGotb0DhoB_ir0wmRClrQRw8ynD7Gz4oGazNTS-5sGtoMyzv7pQAug8hHuuVLtOSRdWHxjigmPoAnfhQLsrhGK1qweH7bTu6yxhzXGAf2aHBtVuBPmz6gCZyhKckNs27sZBVrXcunIwk6BzG7CgceQ6gLMQj99VZZP6kHSFPWKj_Yv4p1AeKoABt-w==','Calderdale Council combined its highways and green spaces teams to streamline processes including pothole repair, pavement maintenance, walls, drainage, and street cleaning, aiming for more effective maintenance programs and engagement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ddff636e-9226-4717-9c2a-ce0f9138215f','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The ARGC MasterPLAN WAS adopted AS a material planning consideration in 2018. This was to provide a clear and transparent strategy for future growth around Castleford. The Council will work with local landowners and businesses to create sustainable housing growth and employment in the Aire River Growth Corridor. The goal is to make Castleford an attractive and environmentally friendly town for people to live, work, and spend their free time. This will be good for Castleford because it will create new homes and jobs. [7]','The Castleford masterplans - Aire River Growth Corridor (ARGC) Masterplan','Wakefield Council','2018-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/planning/policy/castleford-masterplans','Wakefield Council adopted the Aire River Growth Corridor (ARGC) Masterplan as a material planning consideration in 2018. This framework provides a clear strategy for future growth around Castleford, aiming to create sustainable housing growth and employment by making use of old industrial areas. This masterplan sets the strategic context for projects like the Castleford Growth Corridor Scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('de0b6e91-c97a-4014-8844-f552fc522225','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council is launching a public consultation on the next stages of the proposed Connecting West Leeds scheme, which would see a series of improvements to the A6120 Leeds Outer Ring Road between Fink Hill in Horsforth and Dawson\'s Corner in Pudsey. Phase 1 consultation on Connecting West Leeds, Horsforth Merge and Horsforth to Rodley Cycle Link (this consultation). The public consultation will run for four weeks, with a deadline for feedback by 12th December 2021.','Public Consultation Launched for Horsforth to Rodley Outer Ring Road Improvements','Leeds City Council News / Telegraph and Argus / Yorkshire Evening Post','2021-11-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF4T4liImnF7LZI6iUR3eGLTYl8U9P5faP_SRtP70qyzmBMBidPIlkhARUciHI7cuBoaeDBTdAS-_INvpP4kRYft2Hn0J7y9Jyk3scgrEw_VUUsl1eOlflrfvQIbEpsET98yfEhUeVi7tCPzEU2YJwVqHEOVgkOfIBZLbWkjodc_E2jLNFV33hV3PLM2znrZqv7Ku_x_A7NgqbZAySTZ5Op0EFy-C2c__AXCFg==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEDumxseeBN1Dmh4OXB8oi5wEKdMF7jek1vPSrYuBEFTEkgJpggCg4XYeIgbHOHyeqW0YORrOZTMb4QemAxj4Z-CaF8FEVDiYZ-NK6wURf18PAhsL9mMM3yjjdQsBgNNWPv5WGTtgVv27jGZFYBYxTXamwCGLJYPpdc9YpPSD0nmWSBEWRJXWZsEQVsp-jS8-pOj7cV7VHF6ozgp-NBcPdTkoTiCQ==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH2-gNinX-k6aBDNS4jmUQQwrbLxs2yQbFRpNl1oxsd7yUOHZdPN-i10tDnGmDdG_6q7yJTdFf4DopJPYgjwCubuZdNozLuL_-feualF1rIvkZX_uBT59k4j9aFVanuNJ2cSkq6X0X1NRO4lIV9oayCHlIwA_R1JC17AuBL9WTNVVhH3wH_Sg7-hGZ2nmu1OxZmLWFPaYN-ThNBKgRbU8ab4WTB7udO95N5tKnQRWfUn_1hLfEnKRO_s2SG','Leeds City Council launched a public consultation on November 16, 2021, for the next stages of the proposed Connecting West Leeds scheme. This included improvements to the A6120 Leeds Outer Ring Road between Fink Hill in Horsforth and Dawson\'s Corner in Pudsey, specifically mentioning the Fink Hill junction, Horsforth roundabout, and the creation of a cycle route from Horsforth roundabout to Rodley roundabout.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('de570ff3-433c-4543-80ee-72252bbb6189','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Skelton Grange EfW facility to the south is currently under construction and expected to be completed by 2025. This facility will be connected to a major new £25m heat network being planned in the Aire Valley region. The development of this network is being led by SSE and is subject to a GHNF application. ... Existing heat networks: Leeds PIPES is the largest heat network... Networks are also planned for Aire Valley and South Bank.','Heat Network Zone Opportunity Report - Leeds (GOV.UK)','GOV.UK','2025-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGVBTwaObUPFaIL_ZRCvodCXfPMJ918TwYblErJiYsTziHMQe2iV0wBMJyY2ShoEfTTgw_LLTdnb9JXuYk115br-n5ud2Ta-NxDCpqNIM5nr0d4a8Z-wrQHJP4YwmyBpWErL51ezR7KBrw_b88dRk0ViTqoLwvhoiCJRtmmiq6IoB1-ZiX-5N9_LsZHLiXpiD_Qdx_gaARGUX0qVn5AAk-otLFdHe1oc9SbCtOKdGWwi_A=','This official government report identifies potential heat network zones in Leeds, explicitly mentioning the planned Aire Valley heat network which connects to the Skelton Grange EfW facility, expected to be completed by 2025. It integrates the Aire Valley project into Leeds\' broader heat network and decarbonisation strategy.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('de9ca9b4-2d6e-46cc-ae35-cb45f91441bd','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Senior councillors are set to introduce a long-term plan for electric vehicle charging across the Wakefield district. The council\'s new strategy outlines its vision for EV charging so that residents and businesses have enough access. ... Cabinet members are expected to approve the strategy at a meeting on Tuesday March 21.','Wakefield Council set to introduce electric vehicle charging plan across the district','Wakefield Express','2023-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF1T0dmTSXnVh__qbsfdHxBm82vP4fdi7hmpF9NNDD3MfkQv51F5otXqTkt-xG1cMVQs4oap37_LODOn8a9ecxJqkrRrry-agZ7sU9o6lLZaWO8-b3Rfx_mAeetVXLEvZNWl7lCMWemZ7ggEHQG5sI0kLzoUHVOiXCgvBGzhEqHbEq3SeZwj4zk4y22VpnTbg6cIfS7ivvgpb9NXFaWW6caRNQ4bdVu1KpeQ24guAk11uABBljDIt91QD1nqjP-IW5ZEI4-YGQT','Wakefield Council\'s cabinet was set to approve a long-term strategy for electric vehicle charging across the district. This strategy outlines the vision for EV charging, aiming to provide sufficient public charging infrastructure for residents and businesses, including working with charge point operators and considering council-owned car parks for \'charging hubs\'. This move supports the growing number of electric vehicles in the district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dea4fa0e-af62-42e7-9f9a-28afc225ddaa','infrastructure-enfinium-skelton-grange-energy-from-waste-facility',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.539','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'As part of its commitment to working in partnership with local communities, over £100,000 of funding will be made available every year through a new Skelton Grange Philanthropic and Community Fund, which will provide support to appropriate community and environmental projects.','Skelton Grange Philanthropic and Community Fund launched','enfinium, Circular Online, theenergyst.com','2025-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHs6t8YxNOHH0OUzaWM9H1oVnmMYXVBozYAV4G7CVJMoodDWJe-l77ADaQ0y8tlfiKKSfigVCVKf1GqBRe2NE7zpz6iHZ6HB2qrOAP_wbff1JCVVues6yr2HVGuO2rbo5RHsrH1Pw5Qgden-f-v1QblRvKLoO-aOsKYkoUz87DvANsGvWbYwiQdclw=','Coinciding with the opening of the facility in September 2025, Enfinium announced the launch of a new Skelton Grange Philanthropic and Community Fund, committing over £100,000 annually. This fund will support appropriate community and environmental projects in the local area, demonstrating Enfinium\'s commitment to community engagement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('df0e1891-db65-43b4-a779-2b20ec008cc8','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-ministry-of-justice-leeds-courts-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.352','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme opened for applications at 2pm on Wednesday 6 October 2021, with scheme guidance published on Wednesday 8 September 2021. [6]','Launch of Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme Phase 3a Guidance','Salix Finance','2021-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.salixfinance.co.uk/public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme','The guidance for Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme was published on 8 September 2021. This scheme is designed to provide grants to public sector bodies in England to fund heat decarbonisation and energy efficiency measures, contributing to the UK\'s net-zero goals.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('df1233e7-0419-4ec7-af0c-a330142e61b4','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority is working to bring more electric vehicle charge points to the region through its £17 million Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme. People are being urged to have their say on where these should go - to ensure the right charge points are installed in the right places, particularly in neighbourhoods where driveway charging isn\'t an option. ... The consultation runs until Thursday, September 12, with people able to feedback at various drop-in sessions, webinars, online.','West Yorkshire: Public to have their say on £17m plans to improve EV charging infrastructure (Consultation Start)','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-07-25 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGv7t-VrpYBQYxjjKB1U8li7E0qkSj_ut7qcgFgDPhqXB08VGq9r8-RzmYVKN_xh_-4-Z65oXeSYjt7ZqixV0ZZGpNhIkXkYyL_8GbcaKS1iF1y4LTlcTFQ9QHRqZ7kW3ovqAZDlXUGwDAiCJZBip6l84Lwk5bmttIchqLIy1Gk2beiW1CDXdpt4x2V0ztbTT-OXI9utg4_e1AzxG1llHENhXbLSVt3-xlclL36hllVp54WQcaQWaPdojuMTmX9bFz5q4Si7sJyVvi6XU4PS5mwRjZ16bsF8sHbUc6j8PMm7ZEoZHo8u0g=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public consultation as part of its £17 million Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) programme and Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy. The consultation, running from July 25 to September 12, 2024, sought public input on the placement of new EV charge points, especially for residents without off-street parking, aiming to build a more connected and greener region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('df264f11-0720-42ca-a55e-278006cae82c','infrastructure-kirklees-almondbury-housing-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.769','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'What is being assessed: A project. Outline of the proposal and the overall aims/purposes: The purpose of the disposal of the Site is to support the Council\'s Housing Delivery Plan which seeks to bring forward Council-owned Sites, by working with partners, services, developers, and funders to unlock sites and build a mix of new homes including affordable, specialist and market housing to meet housing need, and to promote low carbon and modern construction. The council aims to secure innovative, efficient, quality market and affordable homes delivered at pace to meet identified housing need; to address inequalities, and to reduce the environmental impact and energy usage of new homes. The council also seeks to develop quality places and opportunities for local communities and supply chains, and to maximise employment and training opportunities for local people. Fundamentally, the delivery of housing is recognised as a key pillar in supporting economic growth and is necessary for accommodating a growing workforce within the district. Who does this proposal impact upon: Residents. Does this proposal concern health care, education or housing: yes. What wards will be affected by this proposal: Almondbury. What intelligence and insight were considered to assess the proposal and its relevance to equality: Other https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-planning-policy-framework https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/planning-policy/pdf/local-plan-strategy-and-policies.pdf https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/planning-policy/pdf/sustainability-appraisal-2016.pdf. Comments in relation to intelligence and insight considered: The Kirklees Local Plan contains a Sustainability Appraisal that integrated an Equalities Impact Assessment, as well as a Health Impact Assessment. Furthermore the Fenay Lane site (HS9) is included in the list of housing sites under Policy LP65. This includes information on constraints, an indicative capacity, technical reports required for a planning...','Fenay Lane - Integrated impact assessments - Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council','2023-10-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/integrated-impact-assessments/pdf/fenay-lane-iiab.pdf','This document outlines the purpose of disposing of the Fenay Lane site to support Kirklees Council\'s Housing Delivery Plan. It aims to deliver a mix of new homes, including affordable, specialist, and market housing, promoting low carbon and modern construction. The assessment notes the site\'s inclusion in the Kirklees Local Plan as housing site HS9 and mentions that the eventual developer will consult with residents through the planning process.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('df614214-4350-4981-98f3-4ec6537e1cd9','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.902','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet discussed updated plans for Phase 2 of the A629 scheme, including proposed changes to the alignment on Church Street to incorporate land from a recently demolished warehouse. The project, fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, aims to improve pedestrian and cycle access, upgrade the highway network, and support economic development.','Update on plans to transform Halifax town centre to be revealed by Calderdale Council Cabinet','Halifax Courier / Calderdale Council','2021-10-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/update-to-plans-to-transform-halifax-town-centre-to-be-revealed-3406322','Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet discussed updated plans for Phase 2 of the A629 scheme, including proposed changes to the alignment on Church Street to incorporate land from a recently demolished warehouse. The project, fully funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, aims to improve pedestrian and cycle access, upgrade the highway network, and support economic development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('dfbafeef-e7b2-4dee-a0c9-dbc86d76dd59','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside-development---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.698','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Cabinet members have agreed to £2m funding and given their backing to the wider North Kirklees Growth Zone (NKGZ) project, dubbed the “blueprint for the regeneration of Dewsbury.” It will see the council bid to restore key historic buildings, some into living accommodation. Promoted Stories. And they have agreed to enter a memorandum of understanding with housebuilder Miller Homes for the Dewsbury Riverside site where around 4,000 new homes are set to be built.','£2m boost to major regeneration plans around Dewsbury','YorkshireLive','2018-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG9h7TrZvrBouu4aXhoc3OPNFZFEB3s6aNjR4SzKMgOSlhidZ_2KB2u2icVALAtCxsK9hGP3RQdWOtcvcRKujPsLJQwyB6FHZ7XsFDz5YvPiwelCp0opqB718NXPhDx2-LXpavJE-Yp9l7blxkh3Icw60pehj-If_4rxA8tYoywETpm0Qy8VpvaTEvYIDxoSslemOTgxlxkxiRxXxnM','Kirklees Cabinet members agreed to £2m in funding for the North Kirklees Growth Zone project, which includes the Dewsbury Riverside site, and entered into a memorandum of understanding with housebuilder Miller Homes for the development of around 4,000 new homes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e007535d-12bf-4309-bcfb-17abfc8e6d3e','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Landowners in Calderdale could benefit from a new round of funding to support the creation of natural flood management measures on their land. Calderdale Council and the Environment Agency have launched the latest round of the NFM Grant Scheme, which aims to support farmers and landowners in implementing natural flood management (NFM) techniques. [6]','Calderdale Council and Environment Agency Launch Natural Flood Management Grant Scheme','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-01-28 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/grants-support-natural-flood-management-in-calderdale/','Calderdale Council and the Environment Agency launched the latest round of the Natural Flood Management (NFM) Grant Scheme to support landowners in implementing NFM techniques. This contributes to broader flood resilience efforts in Calderdale, which would indirectly benefit areas like Cottonstones by slowing water flow upstream.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e04205a1-7cc5-49ac-9a58-c6f7d02fe36f','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire franchised bus network is poised to transform public transport across the region... An integral pillar of the revamped bus network is its focus on sustainability. ... Franchise operators are therefore mandated to incorporate low-emission fleets, featuring a significant proportion of battery-electric and hybrid buses, thus advancing the UK\'s legally binding net-zero targets. This environmentally considerate provision offers an attractive substitute for private car travel, subsequently ameliorating congestion and mitigating air quality challenges in regions of high visitor density. [11]','Travel in Style: West Yorkshire\'s New Bus Network Delivers Eco-Friendly Adventures for Tourists','Travel Daily News','2025-08-27 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHK-LneiLBx_q5C43qw4XtxvFBa782VwKOJ6ju56cfvljSDTL_5ewWjvU_LF3radp_EMtixBDmmfdM-7o4mB3X51aVyXo3BW2IQq9jpO6G4pqecny_aXRVOZ8kO58M6f8aR-JEnllowC_jy7xCU0N6QJrGhHXpwYU69a9dr47vHjPUtFNbQMaMHnqK--j9wJbWtfTR0PrA8bLzBOe7p8TpEHtCC1ezairMFRlX0A25n4lGF1LBIeyBOxaQYDGyiAgvrNoXlk1lujMY=','This article highlights the focus on sustainability within the upcoming West Yorkshire franchised bus network. It emphasizes the mandate for franchise operators to incorporate low-emission fleets, including battery-electric and hybrid buses, to contribute to the UK\'s net-zero targets. The new network aims to transform public transport by offering eco-friendly options, reducing congestion, and improving air quality, making bus travel an attractive and sustainable choice for both residents and visitors. [11]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e0c3be3e-a203-4c2b-ba73-2bfa176e37f2','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.580','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'MORE areas in Bradford city centre have reopened following the completion of paving works. The Future Bradford newsletter tells of how the Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme is progressing. This week\'s edition focuses on the works that have taken place on Broadway and Leeds Road. This week, a large area of paving has been laid on Broadway, between Landmark House and Britannia House between the new planter structures. Further progress has been made at the southern end of Market Street, where new paving is being completed in the pedestrian areas on the east side, around the ground level planter areas. A period of overnight works started on Monday, September 2 on the inbound section of Leeds Road, near the Broadway Shopping Centre. This work will facilitate the realignment of a kerb line to widen areas for the new cycleway.','More areas in Bradford city centre reopen as works continue','Telegraph and Argus','2024-09-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24578130.areas-bradford-city-centre-reopen-works-continue/','Further progress on the Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme was reported, with more areas reopening after paving works. This included a large area of paving laid on Broadway and progress on the southern end of Market Street. Overnight works also commenced on Leeds Road to realign a kerb line for a new cycleway.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e0e35336-e5ba-41fb-9f63-be81ac70d4b2','infrastructure-a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction-improvement-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.993','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council are set to unveil £12m plans to improve travel along the A639 Park Road in Pontefract for all road users. Previous public consultation to determine how best to improve and expand the A639, between Beechnut Lane and Princess Drive, provided the Council with several priorities for the scheme. Updated plans for the project, based on this feedback, will be available to view at Pontefract Racecourse in the Paddock self-service dining room on 21 November between 1pm – 4pm. And at Aspire @ The Park on 9 December between 3pm – 6pm. People can also comment on the proposals and give feedback at www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/A639parkroad from now until 11 December 2024. Funding for the work is being provided by West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [6]','Plans unveiled to improve Park Road in Pontefract','Wakefield Council','2024-11-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/news/news-archive/2024/plans-unveiled-to-improve-park-road-in-pontefract','Wakefield Council announced £12 million plans to improve the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. These updated plans, based on previous public consultation feedback, include widening the road, realigning the carriageway, and creating new and improved crossing facilities and cycle lanes. Public drop-in sessions were scheduled for November 21 and December 9, 2024, with feedback accepted until December 11, 2024. Funding is provided by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. [6, 7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e103e559-0709-4b49-97db-483f685632e8','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-bus-carriageway-repair-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.853','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A further resurfacing and waterproofing scheme was brought forward in 2020 and a drainage survey was undertaken in June 2021 to inform the works that were required to rectify the ongoing issues of water ingress. In 2022, the Combined Authority appointed contractors to carry out works to deliver a comprehensive resurfacing and re-waterproofing of the entire bus carriageway at Bradford Interchange.','Bradford Interchange Resurfacing and Waterproofing Scheme Brought Forward','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHCTbxhXir1wT0zuV3Njv78NjGj5Z7Vn680fjdspYOE5h-KB4PGlKdVXbmzQR-gQ6hqVVey8qO566TFhYBwJQxG2l7hwnlXATWMyZVktKx9uTXhPWt1TFpDf8ya_UOiY4ViBg10be1Noz-7kG-rm7p5wO5L-8UkeTEMowtqHO1QTP2Txkp7LHeQ6FisaQ==','A resurfacing and waterproofing scheme for Bradford Interchange was brought forward in 2020. A drainage survey was subsequently undertaken in June 2021 to identify works needed to address ongoing water ingress issues. By 2022, the Combined Authority appointed contractors to deliver comprehensive resurfacing and re-waterproofing. [5]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e10c8492-a717-4155-9e38-4c77dd845930','infrastructure-wakefield-cathedral-square-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.682','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council has invested in businesses in the area around Bread Street at the top of Westgate to improve the look of the area ahead of a broader regeneration project. [8] The project was supported by the Cathedral Square Shop Improvement Grant Scheme, which offers up to £12,000 per property for external works. [14]','Shopfront Revamps on Bread Street Highlighted Ahead of Wider Cathedral Square Project','Wakefield Express, Fibre Construction','2025-05-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/shopfront-revamps-and-cathedral-square-projects-will-help-transform-city-4598075 [8], https://fibreconstruction.co.uk/projects/bread-street-wakefield-regeneration/ [14]','In May 2025, Wakefield Council showcased the ongoing success of its Shop Improvement Grant Scheme on Bread Street. The scheme provides grants to local businesses, enabling them to restore traditional shop facades and contribute to the improved aesthetic of the area in preparation for the main Cathedral Square development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e1442744-d810-4514-bc25-3efcdd1d7c4e','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Today (Thursday 3 April), the regional mayor and five district leaders of West Yorkshire cemented their commitment to the long-term prosperity of Bradford by approving funding for its City Village scheme, pending final business case agreement. The Mayor’s in-principle investment of £13.2 million for Bradford City Village is another major boost for the UK’s City of Culture 2025, after the Government committed £30 million of funding for the scheme, which will be delivered by Bradford Council working with ECF, formerly the English Cities Fund.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Approves £13.2 Million Funding for City Village','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHAhaETx8lMT1ljM-5AcRcCHsbfrZrJdjZW5Xd2QrTU_NnAh-rpRhAk0-SHr-t5rGKKoLT48B4OQ5zaJTOUdWqbMZgjNgs12Y2h_uE0b-q78eBxCw3VHmrFqjmivbbuhcf-IQKUnRu5d0w8_KWpE4CXw1bhSJoWcvJax5OBN9CHMe2LmPrhkvVE04QKCFbb_w-Z4RFcBS776HQVOMAYZVZxYBHZ3yocWVIFu77gK0dlxSOtQvAMapt1OR19x_tvzT-EvQ','Regional leaders of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority approved an in-principle investment of £13.2 million from the West Yorkshire Mayor’s Brownfield Housing Fund for the Bradford City Village scheme, pending final business case agreement. This funding is crucial for Phase 1 of the project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e156bbbf-a6ba-4ad9-8ca7-163734d07547','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The new Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme is now available across the district to help qualifying private households install free solar power, insulation and other measures. [22]','Wakefield Council launches new £1.5m scheme to provide free home energy improvements (HERO)','Wakefield Council','2025-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHVEOn2CeP69pvPKBDFDWUW9KpIDHRqOaiWjlmEaJ_YTTy9YvprDoaXsosU6Pi87zPeEUsNCxQGTmNSXGkDjCsLk6xprt53rfIFxvKcpb_rtc8YirZCbPdjHsDzmmVnc1s5GKIDj-xYDpZrEMTrOO3UcxXX7Iyc1cEWQvmwd6bPsWzw_TAmHh6xS-7PhaL7_RUMXK6VzUH-TEWh-TEkF9BvLJqadDCd8NQUAA_2rwn0lw0gfLj6m6AiRKAdXPSQe-LtzRDJw9SC7aLEu9Q==','On August 7, 2025, Wakefield Council launched the new Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme, a £1.5 million initiative as part of the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme. Available across the district, HERO helps qualifying private households (potentially including landlords) install free solar power, insulation (loft, cavity wall), air source heat pumps, and high-efficiency electric storage heaters. Funds are allocated on a first-come, first-served basis.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e1d82fb5-f327-49df-a1c1-036e7342eae1','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'ve submitted plans for the first phase of the new sustainable community known as \'City Village,\' which will transform Bradford\'s former commercial core into a thriving new city centre neighbourhood. Bradford City Village, which is being delivered by ECF (our partnership between Homes England and L&G and Muse) and Bradford Council, is proposed to be built across the \'Top of Town\' area, which includes the Oastler, Kirkgate and Chain Street sites. [7] A detailed planning application for Phase One, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site, has been submitted. Plans for phase one include: – The creation of 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. – A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces. [7]','Plans submitted for Bradford City Village','ECF - The English Cities Fund','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://ecf.co.uk/news/plans-submitted-for-bradford-city-village/','ECF and Bradford Council formally submitted a detailed planning application for Phase One of the City Village, alongside an outline application for the remainder of the site. Phase One includes 97 new townhouses across the Chain Street and northern Oastler sites, with later phases planned for over 700 apartments. The project is backed by over £43 million in public funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e1e784ef-e550-4e86-9c4c-a4eeaad40eb0','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Combined Authority is also investing £2.6 million in the Wyke Beck Flood Alleviation Scheme in East Leeds, £3.9 million in phase two of the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme and £1.7 million in natural flood management schemes in the Colne, Calder and Upper Aire catchment areas. In February 2020, £1.9 million was approved by Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee to help start a £27.2 million scheme in Hebden Bridge being led by the Environment Agency... Last updated Quarter 4 2019/2020. [6]','Flood alleviation - West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) Programme Overview','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2020-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQESx-Xf2vyISuzsh3jeriaUq7WGHINd1S0u9-4fkAQ6H24a0rlEoMlIB2vh2BABNQOegam86Ri1gekafydGPxg0PHU5VkOgE36AdE6GwomFebthLa20VHloQZoE-Gt2zQBec0vExS2bT-bq1-k9ZuoCVC7G1bQN60LrsC6zlOMYo6WKVLU=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced an investment of £1.7 million in natural flood management (NFM) schemes across the Colne, Calder, and Upper Aire catchment areas. This forms part of a larger £20 million flood protection programme in the Leeds City Region, with updates on related schemes in late 2019/early 2020. [6]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e2073e65-b505-41fc-98ab-0a0664c65f58','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Members of the public are being invited to have their say to help shape plans for Bradford City Village, which is set to deliver 1,000 new homes and revitalise the former retail heart of the city centre. Bradford Council and the English Cities Fund (ECF) are working in partnership to create a new sustainable neighbourhood at the heart of the city centre in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, which includes the sites of the Kirkgate and Oastler shopping centres. [8]','Public consultation launched to help shape masterplan for Bradford City Village','Bdaily / Place Yorkshire','2023-11-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHWeTH1b9wRfd2AKl3xUxVfChyM7e-HEF7ONVcyoPy1rvmlNc9TMu3-q39g19tVhe-9EWhMFJN-xMwTQp1SXFs2KWYn0m4lUOOppMNjcSI7qV1OMF0apvKrWCheMsuv23dDafm7Y6IxDMY5LFmUwY1vouTV2H_m8fKpcbZSzmCdlk60tvoDWKV51HvOjWSz_ilvJlNA2KxAUmP8KOiKsOTlW0j9YHNag1q8FtqnkVqs70q6rA=, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFPBKEFNS1wMir-053_3Cj47KkPO-I7_w_oK5Orq_4shZsbLsbiR2bLfXBilBTG9DFWFFb7K-5K_p1GUkhAMMbez2sPbljTDLBEeVCYSRa4POpT4wHwqZd7DxCK_8rZqQoqXzVtV3szmrKZXzcP0nSYSxPL9GKAiLQPskROCGvX9mSLdKEDy3Dg_77AvI=','Bradford Council and the English Cities Fund (ECF) launched a public consultation on the masterplan for Bradford City Village, aiming to deliver 1,000 new homes and revitalise the city centre. The plans included the Kirkgate and Oastler shopping centres. This initial consultation allowed residents and businesses to provide feedback on ideas, with a planning application submission anticipated for late 2024. [8, 13]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e235897a-b215-4ff1-8b8c-30311d2e6277','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-star-multi-academy-trust-monk-fryston-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.364','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Primary School has a Ground Source Heat Pump, installed and commissioned last autumn and Headteacher Rick Weights reports that it is working very well. They have removed their gas boilers and thereby reduced consumption by around 95% as gas is still required for cooking in the school kitchen.','Monk Fryston and Hillam Sustainability Project Update: School\'s Heat Pump Commissioned','Community Support North Yorkshire','2022-11-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.communitysupportyorkshire.org.uk/news/monk-fryston-and-hillam-sustainability-project-update','An update on the Monk Fryston and Hillam Sustainability Project confirmed that the Ground Source Heat Pump at Monk Fryston Primary School was installed and commissioned \'last autumn\' (referring to autumn 2022). The headteacher reported it was working very well, reducing gas consumption by around 95%.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e238c496-6580-4f4f-96b7-f86568049779','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans for a new, revitalised market at the heart of Brighouse have moved forward as part of the £19.1 million investment in the town centre. Following the three-week engagement process in the summer by Calderdale Council and the Brighouse Town Deal Board, the design of the distinctive new market building has been finalised, a planning application is being submitted, and the tender process to find a contractor is due to start soon. [12] A location has now been provisionally secured and the current market will temporarily move to Daisy Street car park for around 12 months while construction is underway. [12]','Milestone for Brighouse Town Deal as plans progress for new market','News Centre - Calderdale Council','2023-10-18 00:00:00.000','https://news.calderdale.gov.uk/milestone-for-brighouse-town-deal-as-plans-progress-for-new-market/','In October 2023, plans for a revitalised Brighouse market moved forward. Following public engagement, the design for the £3 million canalside market building was finalised, a planning application submitted, and a tender process initiated. A temporary market site at Daisy Street car park was provisionally secured.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e242cdb0-e86d-4f4e-ba2f-7372b78c2b54','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Luddenden Conservation Area - Appraisal and Management Plan - Calderdale Council (2013-04-24). An appraisal informs local planning policies and guides development control decisions in relation to applications both within, and affecting the setting of, the conservation area.','Luddenden Conservation Area - Appraisal and Management Plan','Calderdale Council','2013-04-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGeTHu1gKCdykc8DDGcUegrAxSidNPuM0xhh4_Pt5qPy9EE68z-FJelw1t7IKFCisYqJutY9kD_FNYEN-HhH4kQ4emmhIIwnTegYXh7Mht_jN9dH_Kpo_GOGZTH0i0Zf5Vo88OlxF7LUKGdfaKRNyKr0xMctiytV2ZHl03OPYnI26oDTOvJFa-eq9dXbJ1SOQaxMgsxdgkEV7g4-S013N4=','This appraisal document for the Luddenden Conservation Area defines and records the special characteristics of the area. It helps inform local planning policies and development control decisions, providing a comprehensive understanding of the physical development and significance of Luddenden, which includes the Railes Close area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e3170322-5506-4adb-894e-64a7d027fa5e','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) has issued a preliminary market engagement notice, signalling a step towards the development of a large-scale Mass Transit programme spanning the region\'s urban centres. This early engagement aims to gather valuable supplier insights to inform the evolving business case for the new public transport system, which will connect the region\'s five principal towns and cities: Leeds, Bradford, Wakefield, Huddersfield and Halifax. [24] Mott MacDonald-Jacobs JV was appointed as the design development partner on the £2.5bn scheme. [24] In addition, three potential routes have been considered for the Bradford line, aimed at connecting Bradford and Leeds city centres and covering areas such as Thornbury, Laisterdyke, Pudsey, Armley and Wortley. [24]','West Yorkshire kicks off early engagement for £2.5bn Mass Transit contracts','Place Yorkshire','2025-05-19 00:00:00.000','https://www.placeyorkshire.co.uk/west-yorkshire-kicks-off-early-engagement-for-2-5bn-mass-transit-contracts/','West Yorkshire Combined Authority issued a preliminary market engagement notice to gather supplier insights for the Mass Transit programme, which aims to connect Leeds, Bradford, Wakefield, Huddersfield, and Halifax. Mott MacDonald-Jacobs JV was appointed as the design development partner. The engagement document highlighted potential routes for the Bradford line through Thornbury, Laisterdyke, Pudsey, Armley, and Wortley.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e37d4fa3-2bee-43d5-8095-32085f2ce384','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Councillor Dave Young announced the following schemes for the Calder Valley as part of the A646 corridor improvement project: ... Cycle provision at Heptonstall Road; ... Public Engagement for these proposed schemes are being planned for August and September, over a 6 week period. Dates still to be confirmed. There will be a drop in session and an online portal showing the proposals for the schemes and the public will be invited to have their say in the form of a survey.','A646 Corridor Improvement Project announced in Hebden Bridge','Hebden Bridge Web Forum','2018-07-22 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEmbQaSCl-BKD8bhbmgYo4AP_V8qf7MbW8Mf7JrWlMdaJNQnHarDqTqLYpHCcWPbC8ACC2hC0Zv6x0YV7dPNLGH1U005gQICC5iV-qhBBB4wfmskLMoy1e15LuJ4o_WgA8vBJ1jxLfXI0fRQ4hi','Councillor Dave Young announced schemes for the Calder Valley as part of the A646 corridor improvement project, which included \'Cycle provision at Heptonstall Road\'. This indicates early planning and scope for improvements at the junction, with public engagement activities planned for August and September 2018.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e3c078bb-7ee9-4258-a6e6-37e030125d15','infrastructure-darley-street-market',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.082','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BRADFORD Council has now submitted its full scheme to re-develop a city centre street to create a new market and public square. The authority first revealed its plan to demolish a number of buildings on Darley Street, including the former Marks & Spencer building, and build a new food market and public square in their place. The development is expected to cost at least £21 million. Now a full planning application for the development has been submitted, detailing the layout, elevations, and access for deliveries among other things. ... The Oastler Centre will close, with food stalls opening in this new market and non-food stalls moving to a refurbished Kirkgate Market. To view the application type in reference 19/00737/REG on Bradford Council\'s planning portal website. People have until May 20 to have their say. The Council has also set up an online survey to gather people\'s views of the scheme.','Planning application for Darley Street market and public square submitted','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2019-02-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/','Bradford Council submitted a comprehensive planning application for the redevelopment of Darley Street to establish a new market and public square. This ambitious project, projected to cost at least £21 million, involved the demolition of several existing buildings, including the former Marks & Spencer. The new facility was designed to host food stalls, aiming to replace the Oastler Centre, while non-food retail would be relocated to a renovated Kirkgate Market. Public feedback on the plans was invited until May 20.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e477bfe2-70f3-4351-bc93-b1650f597503','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A meeting of the council\'s executive board taking place next Wednesday, July 21, will discuss plans for the necessary funding to be drawn down from the £25m committed by the Government to support the British Library project as part of the West Yorkshire devolution deal. Subject to executive board approval, a request will be made for the release of up to £5m by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, which is administrating the overall £25m sum allocated to the British Library project. [10]','Leeds City Council approves £5m funding for Temple Works stabilisation','Design and Build UK / Leeds City Council','2021-07-21 00:00:00.000','https://designandbuilduk.net/british-library-site-temple-works-leeds/','Leeds City Council\'s executive board approved up to £5 million in funding, drawn from the West Yorkshire devolution deal, to protect and stabilise Temple Works. This funding supports the British Library\'s ambition for a new northern centre within the historic building.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e4cd4d47-5bc3-4b65-8ff1-459f61b4eeb2','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water announced the start of a £180m investment program over two years to reduce discharges from storm overflows across the region. This plan targets overflows that discharge most frequently or for the longest duration, aiming to reduce overall discharges by at least 20%. This comprehensive plan provides the wider context for specific projects like the one in Bradley.','Work Begins On Yorkshire Water\'s £180m Storm Overflow Reduction Plan','Yorkshire Water','2023-06-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirewater.com/news-media/work-begins-on-yorkshire-waters-180m-storm-overflow-reduction-plan/','Yorkshire Water announced the start of a £180m investment program over two years to reduce discharges from storm overflows across the region. This plan targets overflows that discharge most frequently or for the longest duration, aiming to reduce overall discharges by at least 20%. This comprehensive plan provides the wider context for specific projects like the one in Bradley.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e4f7bc94-8e13-402c-a408-e2c1e8011624','infrastructure-safe-routes-to-schools---christ-church-primary-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.187','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council has secured £900,000 from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority as part of Active Travel England funding to improve routes and access to schools. Five schools across the borough will benefit from the funding, which will be used to develop and deliver improvements to crossings and junctions around the schools to make walking, wheeling and cycling easier and safer. Work will include new road layouts, wider pavements, safer crossing facilities as well as landscaping improvements to support sustainable drainage. Work is due to take place in summer 2025. The article mentions \'School streets at St Mary\'s, Halifax\' in an image caption, suggesting Halifax schools are beneficiaries of similar schemes.','Funding supports better access to Calderdale schools','Calderdale News Centre','2025-04-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHXywSxaJ2HEhDDaU3Gf4x0hViZ4iaRQU3joIjUmJyr2SEnSPXLm7wcHvFuJp8zbPv2GgI87z8OmD5Roy-a0MxABPFxrJaUWHz4-KMOMmwo6y-x1GYG5yADvH-AWE7YIw-hKOGQ90lnbi1E3Hgp-aPQHx_ImKkCV9FpMYh5WBX7dTDqNAJIUC7u4yCfpMJl8A==','Calderdale Council secured £900,000 from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, via Active Travel England funding, to enhance routes and access for five schools across the borough. The funding will support improvements such as new road layouts, wider pavements, safer crossings, and landscaping, aiming to make active travel easier and safer. Work is projected for summer 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e53d5d47-f86a-4b0e-945a-02f0ae6d5b16','infrastructure-bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-phase-2-pedestrianisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.047','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The scheme was completed on time, including the opening of all city centre core roads ahead of the Bradford City of Culture 2025 opening celebrations. [13] With a focus on sustainability, the team achieved 27% Biodiversity Net Gain, with Norfolk Gardens now home to over 7,700 plants/shrubs of 173 different species, including 57 trees. [13] Positively impacting the local community, the team have delivered over £9.8m of social value add. [13] Working as a collaborative partner with City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council (CBMDC), West Yorkshire Combined Authority (the Combined Authority) and Sweco, we expertly guided CBMDC from Strategic Outline Business Case (SOC) through to safe completion of the works. [13] The scheme is already considered best practice in placemaking/transportation, with Active Travel England eager to showcase it as a model for other cities. [13]','Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme - Regional Winner','Constructing Excellence','2025-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.constructingexcellence.org.uk/winners/bradford-city-centre-walking-and-cycling-improvements-scheme/','The Bradford City Centre Walking and Cycling Improvements Scheme was completed on time, with all city centre core roads opened ahead of Bradford\'s UK City of Culture 2025 celebrations. The project, delivered by Balfour Beatty in partnership with Bradford Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority, achieved a 27% Biodiversity Net Gain with new planting and trees, and generated over £9.8 million in social value. It received a regional award for Infrastructure Project of the Year, with Active Travel England showcasing it as a model for other cities.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e55f76d0-8b4c-4e19-aca7-24fe8d30e87c','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Project Name Fink Hill Junction Improvements – A6120 (outer Ring Road) Broadway and Fink Hill. Project Period 04/01/2023 - 03/01/2024. The main construction starting in January 2023, after the busy Christmas period to allow for minimum disruption to road users. Leeds City Council started construction last November [2022] to improve connectivity between communities north and south of the ring road.','Main Construction Begins for Fink Hill Junction Improvements','Considerate Constructors Scheme / Leeds City Council News','2023-01-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEjT8-__QUXcIHmWvPVUhOphS-hDp2EspJ_umZNQKetDTnwqKWUHwFte94JS1YzfCTmwltuzpxsWDSv43urJmLnL1EmcYKrNXbM4uXBsmgc4M0uImb0l_M-m3n-IqUEJdqEIItGMKecJkdO7jheMbZcPDDKfj80vOiPoAMko7T0srzkjVchXs-A4jwrdWa3HyKio726AHHcsfBAJ9buH6cPoE0XVfJVHvoIJcKwFQcKJt7P-A==, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH4ARm1n3HdfoAtXxWosycGlgZxwCuXgAw277AWzXsWVpJNAv2b_vx8D57FSJviJvzAAWAvukUJV48ukwH8lWVq-9yW6Tthqd5OHOoUkFrgBRLXboq87oBV6-uVYWjUAFOmKxbAh_1m7Z6v1UrmMAXruBpK-tQ2NcEoMW62eMzjZDyNiLiIbs4FBLKO2kLzHcGExGK_ZoSXUgMYizs=','The main construction phase for the Fink Hill Junction Improvements, part of the A6120 Outer Ring Road, officially began on January 4, 2023. This phase involved significant works to improve the junction layout, pedestrian crossings, and cycle lanes. The project period was scheduled from January 2023 to January 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e5665be2-a785-457c-83f1-bb05ebf0a832','infrastructure-bus-lane-enforcement-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.094','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale bus lane enforcement plan which has come under criticism has finally been approved ... Coun Collins replied that capital costs were coming from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, which would not have agreed to the investment unless there was clear evidence it was worthwhile.','How the under fire bus lane enforcement camera plan was passed','Halifax Courier','2018-09-24 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/how-under-fire-bus-lane-enforcement-camera-plan-was-passed-1-9366155','The Calderdale bus lane enforcement plan, including the use of ANPR cameras, was finally approved after a thorough debate at a scrutiny board meeting. Councillor Barry Collins confirmed that capital costs were coming from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, emphasizing that the scheme\'s purpose was not primarily about raising money but about improving traffic management and supporting public transport.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e59a4c12-ae5d-47e0-83d7-9a21f1501a7d','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'UK Construction Online reported the achievement of the first milestone for the Mytholmroyd flood defence project. This involved the installation of a new steel footbridge and the construction of flood walls as part of the initial phase at Cragg Brook, providing pedestrian access upstream of the railway viaduct.','Milestone achieved at Mytholmroyd flood defences','UK Construction Online','2019-02-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.ukconstructionmedia.co.uk/news/milestone-achieved-mytholmroyd-flood-defences/','UK Construction Online reported the achievement of the first milestone for the Mytholmroyd flood defence project. This involved the installation of a new steel footbridge and the construction of flood walls as part of the initial phase at Cragg Brook, providing pedestrian access upstream of the railway viaduct.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e5d7537c-e582-4873-9e26-77cecd42880c','infrastructure-knottingley-community-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.679','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2021-10-01) Renovation at Kellingley Social Club continues to transform it into a flexible, multi-use facility. It\'s to become the home to the new Knottingley Community Hub serving the communities of Ferrybridge and Knottingley. In September, initial preparatory internal works and measurement surveys have been completed and tenders being prepared to hire a contractor to start main works. Children and Young People services will be one of the services available at the new hub.','Knottingley Community Hub September 2021 Renovation Update','Wakefield Council (YouTube)','2021-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEMISnfE4OWP68x8sp3NpMN8RG5tNZbIdbJF0T6n9H_m9e--epe0C3SYHJgBRZKP3T2hSRosB1stLnHuBsLuLKNhFxYfngf30suuvgHVUBoI2XVuBh9kALicyLmG01VdRWNaMaWJ68=','Another video update from Wakefield Council on the Kellingley Social Club renovation. It details that initial preparatory internal works and measurement surveys have been completed, and tenders are being prepared for the main building works. Children and young people\'s services are highlighted as a key focus for the new hub.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e5ddb7d9-54db-42bf-a2ac-7b2a915cf889','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In February 2020, £1.9 million was approved by Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee to help start a £27.2 million scheme in Hebden Bridge being led by the Environment Agency which will reduce the risk of flooding from a 20% risk to a 2% risk in any given year. This project will reduce the flood risk to 231 commercial properties and move 180 commercial properties to a lower flood risk band, directly safeguarding approximately 700 jobs. In addition, the scheme will better protect 183 residential properties and move 130 to a lower flood risk band and improve the resilience of the A646 road towards Mytholmroyd and the M62.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Approves £1.9m for Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Flood alleviation','2020-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFzjWEd1vOy1a8r3ofGjFO4GjwUnVjaIgKYbd_XfYw6qYxbJALbcxN2dbXJ7hcXkamWPhZmQxpjAYNhnaq2JKqY3GwVomY9PoHItXe40itNQB-rMypp0vinWq783A7_sPN0VOjeoxxv8Z9AJps3Gr1i-JrTNOXn3q7IsYCE_J7QYnb1v4E=','In February 2020, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Investment Committee approved £1.9 million to initiate a £27.2 million flood alleviation scheme in Hebden Bridge. This Environment Agency-led project aims to significantly reduce the risk of flooding from a 20% risk to a 2% risk in any given year.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e5f8daef-2aaf-4015-a43b-c2b7b274c46d','infrastructure-elland-rail-station-and-access-package-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.897','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Progress to deliver a new rail station in Elland has taken a major step forward after a contractor was appointed for the final stage of development work. Surveys will take place on site over the coming months to develop the detailed design of the project. [5]','Keltbray Infrastructure Services appointed for final stage of Elland Rail Station development','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-09-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/elland-rail-station-project-takes-another-step-forward/','On September 5, 2024, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority appointed Keltbray Infrastructure Services Limited for the final stage of development work for Elland Rail Station, involving site surveys and detailed design leading to a full business case.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e62468c7-c508-478d-a351-e05ceec6d292','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The City Village, which aims to completely transform Bradford city centre, is set to be one of the first examples of devolution in action – delivered thanks to a collaborative partnership between Bradford Council, ECF, Homes England and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA).','Landmark Development Agreement Signed for Bradford City Village','Muse Developments','2024-12-20 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHT-wwr7p_Xf9z8BygYcZAGQZLy8YPXLVyAfNqfmuOMPhbwbBGDwiL1P50uL9ZKtd2r_8iibMTXt-_7NWTKP31gB8jrX5vKuhB3Mr9yFpcZIHz6cJ32pw-wr8t3JTpIDxZV4hhTz7dKcIvi0jKmq-FIByFNlmjAYJZMy7qm-7UNZTuAr2y-zX4nLd6g1y-aAEeH099hawPb-Fw','A formal Development Agreement was signed between Bradford Council, ECF (a partnership of Homes England, Legal & General, and Muse), and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, to deliver the ambitious Bradford City Village regeneration project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e67c5f3e-681d-411b-8d7b-42c557c3489d','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council are developing Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans for West Yorkshire. ... Phase one of the LCWIP for Calderdale includes plans to improve walking in Halifax town centre and Park Ward, and plans to improve cycling provision in Brighouse. ... Further stakeholder engagement was undertaken in winter 2019 to get feedback on the proposals.','Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans: Calderdale | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2019-09-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/cityconnect/local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-calderdale/','This outlines the Phase One LCWIP for Calderdale, developed by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Calderdale Council. The plan focuses on improving walking in Halifax town centre and Park Ward, and cycling provision in Brighouse, as part of a longer-term development process to secure funding for active travel infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901');
