	('e6cadc97-343a-4974-b509-70a23ca78957','infrastructure-instavolt-wakefield-hub-ev-charging-station',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.523','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'InstaVolt is upgrading more than 200 of its existing 50kW chargers so that they will be capable of outputting up to 125kW. The upgrades will be completed over the next six weeks, with all upgrades finalised by the end of March 2023. The newly upgraded chargers will join InstaVolt\'s already established network of high-speed chargers.','InstaVolt to upgrade 50kW chargers to 125kW','electric fleet - charging and infrastructure','2023-02-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.electricfleet.co.uk/charging-infrastructure/instavolt-upgrade-50kw-chargers-125kw','InstaVolt announced plans to upgrade over 200 of its existing 50kW chargers to be capable of outputting up to 125kW. These upgrades were scheduled to be completed by the end of March 2023, reducing charging times for EV drivers. While this is a general company announcement, it indicates the potential for existing 50kW sites, like the Wakefield Paragon Avenue hub, to receive or have received power upgrades.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e6e310ec-1a0b-48a6-8d38-afa3a31a190d','infrastructure-calderdale-flood-recovery-and-resilience-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.616','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Calderdale Flood Action Plan is five years old this month and to acknowledge this important milestone, the Environment Agency, Calderdale Council and its partners are reflecting on key successes since 2016. Progress to date has been strong, with over 50 per cent of actions completed or nearing completion. One key achievement since the creation of the plan has been the completion of the £41m flood defence scheme at Mytholmroyd, which now better protects over 400 homes and businesses. [20]','Fifth Anniversary of Calderdale Flood Action Plan Highlights Progress','GOV.UK (Environment Agency news)','2021-11-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fifth-anniversary-of-the-calderdale-flood-action-plan','On November 4, 2021, the Environment Agency, Calderdale Council, and partners celebrated the fifth anniversary of the Calderdale Flood Action Plan. A key achievement noted was the completion of the £41 million flood defence scheme in Mytholmroyd, which now protects over 400 homes and businesses, demonstrating strong progress with over 50% of the plan\'s actions completed or nearing completion. [20]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e6eee46b-c3f5-496b-93b2-f4648170f67a','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On March 14, 2024, Caddick Developments received a unanimous resolution to approve from Leeds City Council\'s planning committee for a major mixed-use neighbourhood at South Bank, Leeds. The 2m sq ft scheme, previously named City One, was rebranded as \'South Village\', and has the potential to provide up to 1,925 homes, 650,000 sq ft of commercial space, and significant landscaped areas centered around a \'village green\'. [12, 17]','Approval for new mixed-use city neighbourhood','TheBusinessDesk.com','2024-03-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/2099719-approval-for-new-mixed-use-city-neighbourhood','Leeds City Council\'s planning committee gave unanimous resolution to approve a major mixed-use neighbourhood at South Bank, Leeds. The 2 million sq ft scheme, previously named City One, was rebranded as \'South Village\' on this decision. It includes up to 1,925 homes, 650,000 sq ft of commercial space, and landscaped areas.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e70aae11-ef72-4107-b6d4-9bfae193625d','infrastructure-walsden-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.226','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Latest Information - September 2024. The Environment Agency is currently investigating what the preferred option is for reducing flood risk to Walsden. To assist the project team in determining a preferred option ground investigations (GI) have been carried out in Rochdale Road and are now complete. We are now reviewing the results of the (GI) to inform our next steps.','Environment Agency Updates on Walsden Flood Risk Investigations (September 2024)','Eye on Calderdale','2024-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.eyeoncalderdale.com/strengthening-defences','As of September 2024, the Environment Agency is continuing its investigation into the preferred option for reducing flood risk in Walsden. Ground investigations on Rochdale Road have been completed, and the project team is currently reviewing the results to determine the next steps for the scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e72d5775-a98a-4449-b8ab-2ffbe226d0a4','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'With this investment, the construction of schemes can now be kickstarted or progress closer to completion across Yorkshire and the Humber. Here is a list of Calderdale schemes to be invested in between April 2025 and March 2026: Erringden Hillside. Cottonstones near Lumb, Calderdale flood alleviation scheme. [3]','Environment Agency Announces Funding Boost for Calderdale Flood Schemes Including Cottonstones near Lumb','Halifax Courier','2025-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/environment/list-of-calderdale-flood-schemes-to-receive-a-funding-boost-the-environment-agency-has-announced-4573216','The Environment Agency announced significant investment between April 2025 and March 2026 to kickstart or progress 108 flood schemes across Yorkshire and the Humber, totalling £59.5 million. The \'Cottonstones near Lumb, Calderdale flood alleviation scheme\' is specifically listed among the projects to receive this investment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e7ea40db-2baf-48c7-aca9-63efe50c7188','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A statutory consultation was held by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on the revised Mass Transit Vision 2040, inviting feedback from statutory consultees, key stakeholders, and the public. This consultation ran for three months, gathering views on the long-term vision for the transport system.','West Yorkshire Mass Transit Vision 2040 Statutory Consultation','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-10-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFHqVnthallafXqofEhbF8SyUFuuPpkUfyQJpNr0l_LhW3p0DKx8cfxWOqerZUR1UNIgKbud4AAyQ38OqUTW1QDDRXoFKdWp1skFbHDK-SuSAzQE37gJSfK4_g8ysBgB5ljSNACM2uBaowmhsLTUls1A9iesZtO','A statutory consultation was held by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority on the revised Mass Transit Vision 2040, inviting feedback from statutory consultees, key stakeholders, and the public. This consultation ran for three months, gathering views on the long-term vision for the transport system.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e80383a0-e08c-41ce-9984-fd89cf256a05','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A survey to gauge the public\'s reaction to proposed improvements to the A639 Park Road,Pontefract will close on August 4. [14]','Last chance to have your say on improvements to Park Road, Pontefract','Wakefield Express','2021-08-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/last-chance-to-have-your-say-on-improvements-to-park-road-pontefract-3332029','Wakefield Express reported on the impending close of the public consultation for improvements to the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. Issues identified included poor walking and cycling facilities and traffic congestion. Wakefield Council and West Yorkshire Combined Authority were seeking feedback to shape plans aimed at encouraging walking, cycling, and public transport use.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e831947d-2a58-42fb-aa7e-89b7b8f07ecc','infrastructure-penistone-line-capacity-improvements-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.942','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Local voluntary and support groups have worked with the Penistone Line Partnership on various projects to improve station presentation, develop walks, artwork and take part in special events to promote the line. ... We want to improve our community rail service and environment for local users. By engaging with stakeholders in the rail industry, businesses near the Penistone Line and support services, we can build a network of people to work together to put their local station at the heart of the community. [15]','Communities - Penistone Line Partnership','Penistone Line Partnership','2024-07-04 00:00:00.000','https://penline.co.uk/communities/','The Penistone Line Partnership, a community rail organization, highlights its ongoing engagement with local voluntary and support groups to improve station presentation, develop walks, artwork, and participate in special events along the line. This demonstrates active community involvement in enhancing the railway environment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e895d43d-3ea4-4cc9-ab99-be9f14b41a9e','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'10 April 2025. Code Building Solutions have been appointed to carry out the improvements to Todmorden Town Hall with work on site now underway. Todmorden Town Hall will remain open throughout the renovations. ... This project is part of the Todmorden Town Deal, a £17.5m regeneration programme to develop the local economy and transform this market town.','Todmorden Town Hall | Calderdale Next Chapter (Work Underway)','Calderdale Next Chapter','2025-04-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFT8mvi_BQhpujsK6tc5qGNSTZ5TwsE73zpOUdB0B-TyfAqAuTTVRST_DozBo2Yj6NoDswAyqwcQntMp-BibDsBWk71l71bHoVHvL40fcawi36uWdTp5csiL3rKpHHVQs9AMu5_afWBDfGKcW-9hNIBBYuyw1yhhF4bmaxwpkoP','Calderdale Next Chapter confirms that Code Building Solutions has been appointed to carry out the improvements to Todmorden Town Hall, with work now underway as of April 10, 2025. The project aims to enhance accessibility, welcome, flexibility, and sustainability, as part of the £17.5 million Todmorden Town Deal.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e8c74e9a-e387-4d58-812e-db2a4c216e15','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle charging points will be installed across the district if Wakefield Council\'s key decision makers give the go ahead at their meeting next week. Cabinet are being asked to accept a grant of £1,520,938 from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority\'s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant funding scheme. The decarbonisation of the transport sector is an important part of the West Yorkshire region\'s target to be net zero by 2038. The LEVI fund supports local authorities in England to install public charge points for residents without access to private parking, and to improve the roll-out and commercialisation of local charging infrastructure. Cabinet will meet on Tuesday 15 October at 10:30am.','More EV charging points coming to Wakefield as part of our plans to go green','Wakefield Council','2024-10-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/news/more-ev-charging-points-coming-to-wakefield-as-part-of-our-plans-to-go-green','Wakefield Council announced that its cabinet would consider accepting a £1,520,938 grant from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority\'s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) scheme to install more EV charging points across the district. The plan aims to meet the growing demand for EV charging, particularly for households without off-street parking, and aligns with the region\'s net-zero targets for 2038.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e8fa5e2c-9d32-4291-b4f2-20fa75f9983e','infrastructure-wakefield-landlords-energy-savers-loan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.518','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Lendology partners with West Yorkshire Combined Authority to offer responsible home improvement loans at a fixed 3.26% interest rate. Available to eligible homeowners in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield, these loans support energy-efficient upgrades like solar panels, insulation, heat pumps, and double or triple glazing. [4]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Lendology: Energy Efficiency Loans for West Yorkshire','Lendology','2024-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFZ71JXkUcxmZ84vLaMDqpvxTJnAiNVp5zcjV3yOCof2YW8QYMn1xihwKkNGiklKIAnioVVuayUoUjGCL_zJ_6YqXgL1Xy4PJayzmY6wUjT92AM1Cl7PXMcJoOEsBf_iO0I-kTGejDht0e165N5IdzAI-lp9n8BkpThZP_lZNwHxRXp','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority, in partnership with Lendology, offers council-funded loans to homeowners and private landlords across Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, and Wakefield. These loans, with a fixed 3.26% interest rate, are available for energy-efficient upgrades such as solar panels, insulation, heat pumps, and double glazing, helping to create warmer, low-carbon homes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e914e689-a454-4818-87dd-0f771a2e41ff','infrastructure-brighouse-town-investment-plan-projects',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.268','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Ideas. July 2019. Government announces £3.6 billion Towns Fund with the intention of giving places new energy and new life. September 2019. Government asks towns to develop proposals for Town Deal funding – Brighouse is one of 100 invited. [9]','Government announces Towns Fund and invites Brighouse to develop proposals','The Brighouse Deal - The Timeline','2019-09-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.brighousedeal.co.uk/the-timeline/','In July 2019, the UK Government announced the £3.6 billion Towns Fund. By September 2019, Brighouse was among 100 towns invited to develop proposals for Town Deal funding.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e93e6996-0928-44a6-8151-ed12e8f8c96a','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans have been formally submitted for the first phase of City Village, a new sustainable community set to transform Bradford\'s former commercial core into a thriving city centre neighbourhood. The multi-million regeneration is being delivered by ECF – a partnership between Homes England, Legal & General, and Muse – working alongside Bradford Council. Phase One proposals include: • 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. • 64 two- and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around courtyards and green spaces.','Planning Application Submitted for Bradford City Village (Phase 1)','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / ECF - The English Cities Fund','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHYDoPcmgFKERKCfaa7kwvAwi3Qcut8n8AVodaIGLjvZgt3McKrksZUiVi4FHzLiGfpikZttvvX1WQabtsvOAQ45PlUv5xwpdkSpg21_cM__NlSeIGQDPd-0Fe1_lWVLNl0xQkLHYCm_4gTGeG1D6TH6CbYP4iZ2iWGXBOaLwmrkJOYUyMnSjeRFck9r1fLIkgksfVXiRceJlGRlp4x_lqG01KPJj8ENPShndEOuXMkR-OKLCAyEg_x','A detailed planning application for Phase One of Bradford City Village, including the 33 Chain Street townhouses and 64 Oastler North townhouses, was formally submitted by ECF in collaboration with Bradford Council. An outline application for the wider development was also lodged.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e99332a2-abe9-4f44-94b7-9c1dcb049e9d','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-05-07) The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy sets out how the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, and the region\'s five councils, will collaborate in an effort to ensure there are enough places to charge cars and vans in public where people need them. The strategy, which was agreed by members of the Combined Authority\'s transport committee on Wednesday, April 16, outlines investment priorities, design guidance, and an action plan.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority EV Infrastructure Strategy Agreed','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-05-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG0QZY2NT2voUDqhWxX42SwB62ewWlpZLqk9Nfx8RdMuPRZgVo1Lk2cefHQjtGp-lJja0nB4cM4KXgSR0sXb8d3FqJV7fCO5CpDX2-luSlgbDuu_tYeqi9UHsNR0EO0i69uz-kFgGeX3lvnIUv4HwBD46Y1jLBlIoyxszBLd0wcMFvRaJtpD0dbhmnXqTPq7CzCa31Fj1PZ695RU4uXMg4azCw-RoGmlsb1gg==','The Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy for West Yorkshire was agreed, outlining how the Combined Authority and its five councils will collaborate to ensure a comprehensive network of public EV charge points. The strategy sets investment priorities and design guidance to achieve net zero carbon by 2038.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e993ebd4-62a4-4392-a3d7-89b421077bdd','infrastructure-a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction-improvement-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.993','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A639 Park Road - Construction Works. The Council of the City of Wakefield. Pipeline notice - Procurement Act 2023 - view information about notice types. Notice identifier: 2025/S 000-027419. Published 25 May 2025, 6:24pm. Contract dates (estimated). 1 October 2026 to 31 July 2028; 1 year, 10 months. Main category. Works. CPV classifications. 45233000 - Construction, foundation and surface works for highways, roads. Contract locations. UKE45 - Wakefield. [10]','A639 Park Road - Construction Works - Find a Tender - GOV.UK','GOV.UK','2025-05-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.find-tender.service.gov.uk/Notice/027419-2025','A pipeline notice on GOV.UK for the construction works of the A639 Park Road. This procurement notice, published on May 25, 2025, indicates estimated contract dates for construction from October 1, 2026, to July 31, 2028, with a duration of 1 year and 10 months. The contracting authority is The Council of the City of Wakefield. [10]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e9b6f769-d5d1-4b05-aef8-429400394c01','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Chargepoint with electric car chargers in Leeds. The EV location have 6 outlets with max capacity 11 kW. This charge point is part of the charging network E.ON. © 2025 - ChargeFinder - Charging stations for electric cars (EV) [7]','Thorpe Park 6923-4 - E.ON EV charging stations in Leeds','ChargeFinder','2025-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.chargefinder.com/charging-stations/thorpe-park-hotel-spa-century-way-leeds/6923-4','ChargeFinder lists Thorpe Park Hotel & Spa as having E.ON EV charging stations. The location has 6 outlets with a maximum capacity of 11 kW, part of the E.ON network.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('e9e20b23-a002-4607-91e7-423564d77a38','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority has released a consultation report which indicates that more than two-thirds of people, surveyed across the region, are supportive of plans to create a tram system. The system would initially cover Bradford and Leeds. [27] The latest consultation report from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) reveals that more than two-thirds of respondents are in favour of the initial phase of the tram system, which will focus on connections between Bradford and Leeds. [28]','Consultation Report Reveals Strong Public Support for West Yorkshire Trams','Bradford Telegraph and Argus / Railway-News','2025-02-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24131548.consultation-report-reveals-support-west-yorkshire-trams/ ; https://www.railway-news.com/support-revealed-for-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-tram-network/','A consultation report released by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority indicated strong public support for the proposed tram system, which would initially cover Bradford and Leeds. More than two-thirds of respondents backed the Leeds-Bradford line plans, and over three-quarters supported the line from St James\'s Hospital to the White Rose. This feedback will help select the preferred scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ea247c82-f660-4bb1-a4e8-e1a64c35ce4a','infrastructure-transforming-cities-fund---a61-and-a639-wakefieldleeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.614','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) was a devolved programme of transport infrastructure investment secured as part of the West Yorkshire Devolution Deal... The Transforming Cities Fund has since been incorporated into the City Regional Sustainable Transport Fund (CRSTS). [21]','Kirklees Major Transport Schemes; West Yorkshire Transport F','Kirklees Council (Cabinet Report)','2024-01-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH5khHu6FAmj28JBHP5bPZ1mnj1h1-1cHwUi5ZzXN4cEBb1FLGhKCFLi6bA392bQONMYVgmDpGxt6NUlqbI-l-MJrKGFVUaEZKS9_Yugy1xUHCNu5oc_iQv7ku1KynYDsx_mRt38mTOUtgN7rvQlqs4moacbGurRJxaMR5G5VH_7QIGXvRm431XdJeo1gS3HwYD8pjt-m1EePNXcLZ7_Deyd6jGXM6YOwH_7L_DS2MohXG4_vvANZ4EGRrB1PRt2_mJmFgvPEhAdf54hQeIaoyqgKZxR_zFP37j4nQ=','A Kirklees Council Cabinet report, dated January 3, 2024, noted that the Transforming Cities Fund (TCF) had been incorporated into the City Regional Sustainable Transport Fund (CRSTS). This indicates an evolution in the regional transport funding structure, though TCF-supported projects, including those on the A61 and A639, continued under the new framework. [21]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ea306591-cc10-41c2-a2b4-af3e8ed8d454','infrastructure-school-streets-initiative-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.133','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Clean Air, Bradford has called on Bradford Council to put School Streets in place around primary schools in Bradford to protect children, carers and teachers when children return to school. Following Boris Johnson\'s announcement on Sunday 10th May that schools would be reopening for some year groups Clean Air Bradford have written to Bradford Council asking them to accelerate School Streets plans. The Government released new statutory guidance to Councils on Saturday saying that it \'expects local authorities to make significant changes to their road layouts to give more space to cyclists and pedestrians.\' It specifically lists School Streets as a measure Councils can take to encourage more walking and cycling to school and that it will help social distancing outside schools.','School Streets needed now to protect children returning to school','Clean Air Bradford','2020-05-13 00:00:00.000','https://cleanairbradford.org.uk/2020/05/13/school-streets-for-social-distancing/','Clean Air Bradford urged Bradford Council to implement School Streets around primary schools to ensure social distancing and safety for children, carers, and teachers upon the reopening of schools, following government guidance on changes to road layouts to give more space to pedestrians and cyclists.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ea99b98c-212c-48d0-9a32-869631cc39bf','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---leeds-conservatoire-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.442','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More people in Leeds will soon enjoy affordable, reliable, and low carbon heat thanks to four new connections to the Leeds PIPES district heating network that have been confirmed by Leeds City Council today. New plans for two major extensions to the award-winning network—which would enable dozens more buildings to connect—have also been published by the local authority and discussed by senior members. ... The four latest buildings, including the first private-sector residential developers, which have confirmed their intention to connect to the network within the next 12 months are: ... Leeds Conservatoire on Quarry Hill. [22]','Plans to extend Leeds PIPES network into new areas of the city revealed, as four more buildings set to connect.','Leeds City Council (via The Business Desk)','2023-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/2102143-plans-to-extend-leeds-pipes-network-into-new-areas-of-the-city-revealed-as-four-more-buildings-set-to-connect','Leeds City Council confirmed the intention of four new buildings, including Leeds Conservatoire, to connect to the Leeds PIPES district heating network within the next 12 months. This announcement also detailed plans for two major network extensions and highlighted the network\'s existing benefits in reducing carbon footprint and energy costs.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eaa21104-7744-45ea-8c4b-b952ee24b2d2','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2023-06-12) Leeds has a long history of flooding, most recently in 2020 with Storm Ciara and Storm Eva in 2015. ... The Aire Resilience Company aims to establish Natural Flood Management interventions which provide a reduction in peak flows on the River Aire at Leeds during flood events of up to and including a 1-200 year flood event including an allowance for climate change to 2069. In addition, these interventions will provide multiple ecosystem services (NFM+) for the benefit of the catchment. [16]','Aire Resilience Company - Delivering Natural Flood Management in the Aire Valley','ArcGIS StoryMaps (Aire Resilience Company)','2023-06-12 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQF3pzLtAvWnl-NVssEp4_fNeXknXFh_mav4kqYtDHNGUPUpKvj4odKCtlHG-EUJbT-8cGDBNr7Idj-bYeMykco8iJ4bpL-YVS381u0yHgyFvcUO_hPr-eDGwKBoov31B8-w_tg5VqbhVoxcVnSKmLCE0maVNogJF-jxfLxcnBaoEA==','The Aire Resilience Company (ARC) was established as a Community Interest Company to lead and fund natural flood management interventions in the mid and upper Aire Valley. Its objective is to complement the Leeds Flood Alleviation Scheme by securing private finance for NFM measures, aiming to reduce peak flood flows in Leeds during severe weather events and provide additional ecological benefits. [16]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eaaee471-00e4-40cf-9366-dfda1f045f53','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In a further boost for residents in Lovell Park Grange, Lovell Park Heights and Lovell Park Towers, the council recently announced that all three blocks are set to be connected to the flagship Leeds PIPES district heating network.','Leeds council flats: Six tower blocks transformed as hundreds of flats get cheaper heating','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-03-21 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/council/leeds-council-flats-six-tower-blocks-transformed-as-hundreds-of-flats-get-cheaper-heating-4562094','The Yorkshire Evening Post provided an update on a wider £100m council-led transformation program. It noted that Lovell Park Grange, Lovell Park Heights, and Lovell Park Towers were among the blocks receiving energy-saving upgrades and were \'set to be connected\' to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, reinforcing the ongoing nature of the project.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eaec4650-bc42-4a05-a93f-e63978359347','infrastructure-aire-valley-low-carbon-district-heating--electricity-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.512','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'SSE Energy Solutions is to develop a new £25m low carbon district heating and electricity scheme in Aire Valley, Leeds. Announced today [8th June] at the Decarbonisation Summit 2022, the scheme aims to serve local businesses including Yorkshire Water who it is estimated will save 5000 tonnes of carbon emissions per year alone - the equivalent annual electricity use of 3,200 homes. The energy network is planned to be served by enfinium\'s new Skelton Grange Energy-from-Waste facility which is currently under construction...','New £25m low carbon energy network to serve businesses of West Yorkshire','West Yorkshire Combined Authority / SSE Energy Solutions (via news articles)','2022-06-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHJEU3fDlSfckbTxbCSB3TmZCyeVPKrTtgbsOmSR_GvShqwH4qXShOSbqxblKdvoOFK91-i7RGvIrYfCMUTv84XTy0HcCLMGI2E3r_uk9Mmiz90wQm-0PzS8h6Oo59yaZ7BrkYfrV_7OCk-mVpO2hiya7z9aPwbi5I=','SSE Energy Solutions announced plans to develop a new £25m low carbon district heating and electricity scheme in Aire Valley, Leeds. The scheme, unveiled at the Decarbonisation Summit 2022, aims to serve local businesses, including Yorkshire Water, and is planned to be supplied by enfinium\'s new Skelton Grange Energy-from-Waste facility.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eb44919a-eb5f-4469-aeb5-6f415600bc2e','infrastructure-bt-digital-switchover-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.309','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'BT is set to visit Halifax ahead of announced plans to roll out its new home phone service, Digital Voice. ... The demonstration vehicle will be at Morrisons on Keighley Road in Halifax on August 19. [27]','Business: BT to visit Halifax ahead of roll out of new home phone service','Halifax Courier','2023-08-19 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH5Gyljl9VaHLkfWHVNaGpuIMB0Fq3YxW4w_i7wxo60u4Hc_aiS8b--Kfl-0f_hljFb4VLRp94Z1pB0M5ddSz8fO1FBwE1YQGD6HkneLstnbnji8hApGSbQISop4TnREIF1cmXE7E5fkv3N7bmVcK4p0UzgNmL0Y25jYVpQ83KCKWnR02k4qDQXfjljMmTv5bPblD9FrCA1pQH2bI-ENU2JIC67JWHjipLq-TdfhPlWPGR5lV24','BT announced plans to roll out its new home phone service, Digital Voice, to Halifax. A demonstration vehicle visited Morrisons on Keighley Road to allow customers to speak to BT staff and understand the new technology as part of the regional rollout across Yorkshire and the Humber.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eb70b240-52d3-41c4-8b76-2f256fe84edd','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-outline-southern-oastler-site-apartments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.078','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'At a meeting of West Yorkshire Combined Authority on Thursday morning, members voted to award over £13m to help kickstart the City Village project, which will eventually see 900 homes built on the Kirkgate and Oastler Centre sites and other city centre locations. [20]','£13m funding towards Bradford City Village is approved','Telegraph and Argus / Place Yorkshire','2025-04-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQG9FNBBeuWjyY4JkmcCCaUPe9IGvtje8x-70Qrz-3mYBFolLoZF31fxCwFTDkyvB57FQQI0GlQpRkacnZ7nXVv4sHdTnoLz55pXEcDlxMxZjTdASslvGP7NX4RxnKS9QwddbfbGbrTIDg8bjt0UdlGNkcU4VpCEpOa6Pe27Mj2UtURPqNqGJUS3093XQjwT1dLPl8L_Gr1N3h2pR3d6oTq6Lby9, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGdTUH8a7Ytlp2Zt0wCMRc_FejNhtBbapPLIJnz4QLS_u9JDs5T4eqH1PoXEOOaw_Q-UG-ojBoAUy1y0HM0qCZo9zyl8F-asSocnqvhikCVwMrqgdOsJ4vuclZtM5eauObkNDbHA3ZM_Eu5TNy-8ADiq94bV_FvDGGRfitO7ClveHxpGHu04rVhlVM2XMOBVWmwYW10OpSPyAY=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) approved over £13 million in funding for the City Village project. This brings the total public investment to over £43 million (including the £30m from Homes England) and is crucial for de-risking the site and ensuring the commercial viability of the initial phases of the scheme, which will include new homes on the Oastler Centre site. [20, 21]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ebf5597f-6957-4f3c-bf2a-cd66f8d8f654','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The UK government\'s official summary of projects funded under Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS) details a £9,296,722 award to Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust. This funding is specifically for reducing carbon emissions at St James\'s Hospital by removing fossil fuel heating systems, connecting buildings (including Leeds Cancer Centre, Sir Robert Ogden Macmillan Centre, and Thackray Museum of Medicine) to a council-owned district heating network, and installing energy efficiency measures like roof insulation, draught proofing, and double glazing. This document was last updated on April 17, 2025.','GOV.UK: Phase 3a Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme: project summaries (Updated)','GOV.UK','2025-04-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/phase-3a-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme-project-summaries','The UK government\'s official summary of projects funded under Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS) details a £9,296,722 award to Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust. This funding is specifically for reducing carbon emissions at St James\'s Hospital by removing fossil fuel heating systems, connecting buildings (including Leeds Cancer Centre, Sir Robert Ogden Macmillan Centre, and Thackray Museum of Medicine) to a council-owned district heating network, and installing energy efficiency measures like roof insulation, draught proofing, and double glazing. This document was last updated on April 17, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ebfb55f4-3ef5-45d6-b006-a69c9d1bb0cb','infrastructure-railes-close-luddenden-and-midgley-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.209','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Under the Flood and Water Management Act, Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council has a legal duty to develop, maintain, apply and monitor a Local Flood Risk Management Strategy. This Strategy is a tool to help understand and manage flood risk within Calderdale. Its principal aims are to tackle local flood risk including flooding from surface water, groundwater and ordinary watercourses. The Strategy has been produced as a result of the Flood and Water Management Act 2010 and redeveloped following the flooding experienced on Boxing Day 2015.','Local Flood Risk Management Strategy (Version 2)','Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council','2016-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFrYYI8IL7dtVr79qvs5_G4nHZjPT9WUswNPAz37y3YJhc5qJLx7PQ5mwiMrnfw3f3Oqr-FI3VSaXPGV4ne2Er15DJtg5SVxUeW6XtdYQ2pmhmhX4Ih5o0HoaVEnvA3dVZcEzsRbHm1OWusxucxdCv68DX__U262XVkYaqxvj65m32y33UfX3o0v9eCqVwxQ0LqeeeEGU5gKQgqXoOt','Calderdale Council\'s Local Flood Risk Management Strategy outlines its legal duty to manage local flood risk, including surface water, groundwater, and ordinary watercourses. The strategy was redeveloped following severe flooding in 2015 and mentions historical flooding in Luddenden Brook, highlighting the need for schemes like the one at Railes Close.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ec38f912-4d86-4567-92db-4ae97e38a2d0','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-diocese-of-leeds-south-crosland-primary-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.359','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Phase 3 of the PSDS is providing £1.425 billion of grant funding over the financial years 2022/23 to 2024/25, with a budget of £475 million for each financial year. Phase 3a launched in October 2021 and will provide funding over the financial years 2022/23 to 2024/25; funding was awarded to 170 public sector organisations, covering 231 projects. ... Regardless of the project timeframe, Phase 3a grant recipients were required to commence project delivery in the financial year 2022/23. ... A greater emphasis upon funding and installation of heat decarbonisation rather than energy efficiency measures, albeit with an expectation of applicants evidencing \'fabric first\' approaches to buildings.','Evaluation of Phase 3 of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme','GOV.UK','2023-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-phase-3-of-the-public-sector-decarbonisation-scheme','This evaluation report from GOV.UK discusses the overall framework and implementation of Phase 3 of the PSDS, including Phase 3a. It mentions that Phase 3a launched in October 2021 and awarded funding for projects to be delivered over financial years 2022/23 to 2024/25. It also notes that grant recipients were required to commence project delivery in the financial year 2022/23 and highlights changes in scheme design, such as a greater emphasis on heat decarbonisation.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ec861517-887f-4db9-a29d-6e22472b8d8f','infrastructure-wakefield-corridor-improvement-programme---a639-park-roadbeechnut-lane-junction',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.602','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is looking to make improvements to the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. The improvements are intended to encourage and enable more walking and cycling in the area as well as encouraging more bus use. We would like your feedback on the proposed improvements.\n\nKey Dates:\nEngagement starts: 07 July 2021\nEngagement ends: 04 August 2021 [12]','A639 Park Road, Pontefract - Corridor Improvement Programme Public Consultation','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2021-07-07 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/a639parkroad-cip','Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, launched a public consultation on proposed improvements to the A639 Park Road in Pontefract. The consultation aimed to gather feedback on proposals to enhance walking, cycling, and bus use, and address issues like congestion, poor active travel facilities, and expected traffic demand increases due to local developments. The improvements cover the section between Stuart Road and Junction 32 of the M62.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eca18091-a6cd-4f46-8248-fe8ef9ba6375','infrastructure-wakefield-district-housing-solar-pv-project',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.544','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'RPS Group has undertaken a Solar PV project in collaboration with Wakefield District Housing. The project involves the installation of Solar Photo Voltaic Panels in over 220 homes across the Wakefield borough, aimed at promoting sustainable, energy-efficient living. ... As of the current update, the Solar PV installation project is underway, with Rothwell Plumbing Services Group actively contributing to the reduction of residents\' electricity bills, minimising bill shock, and lowering carbon footprints. The project scope includes a desktop survey of approximately 600 properties, technical surveys, structural assessments, and the supply and installation of Solar PV Panels to around 220 selected properties.','Solar PV Installation for Wakefield District Housing (RPS Group)','Rothwells Plumbing Services','2024-01-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEh9i1T9lZ7KJni_qXnHpyNwYJCh0x8MXynyg5L3S9Mpm4PZKDRvicgNln-SsX9NFAnetqAWjoIYIGIHc9vPl_t7x4BOl4Ke1YyCH5l2Y3xLzGXm0T-PNuS3M8v_YPB4EWYAMfDE7Gen33EKGprQtbNdptc_QGBXFP7uVqNg1NTPOA3IaYco0VffnbyMy5r9P8=','RPS Group announced their collaboration with Wakefield District Housing (WDH) on a Solar PV project involving the installation of panels in over 220 homes across the Wakefield borough. The initiative aims to promote sustainable, energy-efficient living, reduce residents\' electricity bills, and lower carbon footprints. The project includes desktop surveys of approximately 600 properties, technical surveys, structural assessments, and the supply and installation of panels, with a focus on design optimisation and tenant engagement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ed10f727-d102-46d8-ac6a-3dea29602955','infrastructure-art-and-about-trail-halifax-town-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.260','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In early 2020, the Leeds City Region Enterprise Partnership (the LEP) proposed a Cultural Framework and a Culture Vision document that aimed to unlock the full potential of culture, sport and major events in the region. These documents were produced as a result of collaborative work between members of the cultural steering group and following an engagement with the cultural funding bodies (including Arts. Council England, Heritage Lottery Fund, Historic England, and Yorkshire Sport/Sport. England). The LEP and the CA endorsed the Cultural Framework in February 2020, and its priorities have been embedded into the West Yorkshire Investment Strategy. [11]','Leeds City Region Cultural Framework endorsed','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2020-02-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFGWcgKSMFU2eBjlZ4spqZ2aqtDNCDLYUamXaFAEjWbiRIY2et1iWaCwJl6dMK31HqzPjOQgGyU4sqaxhWG1zXxnB0w5G_5YgUFrvl3XobIum2E73lPFRn6B6F1N5dvzqxsN55UPYheoQV9Yaq3ClMdVhjRPipruNGhHXfX5GbeLxiFI00dGKJy','In early 2020, the Leeds City Region Enterprise Partnership (LEP) endorsed a Cultural Framework and Vision document. This framework aimed to unlock the full potential of culture, sport, and major events in the region, with its priorities embedded into the West Yorkshire Investment Strategy. This provides the strategic context for projects like the Art and About Trail.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ed8161d5-e93d-48e3-b1a6-67e36c0f162d','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Detailed plans for phase 1 of the neighbourhood, which ECF, our partnership with Homes England and L&G, is delivering in partnership with Bradford Council, were revealed today (Wednesday 21st May) as part of Bradford Council\'s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock... The final phase of consultation launches today – inviting feedback on updated plans for the neighbourhood ahead of a planning application to be submitted in late summer. It will include: – The creation of 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. – A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces. – Supporting infrastructure including safer roads, landscaped public spaces and active travel routes.','Detailed Plans Unveiled and Final Public Consultation for City Village Launched','Muse / Bradford City Village Website','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEYc5CckVNkjO9D4tFEYKkQqEdnnxm38K2Zu2armyuzrumWBjl95TcAYWNMNwvOhY-ns0uPlGTb1qAzVsPoyo1bIPEXPFAogjT6lqaiTJHxGi4R69mo6epjrg5XB786_lSsaHSZPhW__RIQPLg8s1VptqTlhQC-q-47wCHLNb-H8DhMsJ7ny0ZdqV4Ec4BMhAhJRvixo0PmRPr6m7zOT8gkd0xrs1zQIco_h9oOBf3_PCRzUpzt','Detailed plans for Phase 1 of Bradford City Village were revealed, launching the final phase of public consultation. This phase includes 33 townhouses on Chain Street and 64 on the northern Oastler site, alongside supporting infrastructure.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ed94fac9-d948-444d-b821-4be4b547b6e6','infrastructure-wakefield-cathedral-square-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.682','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Two major buildings in the city centre look set for demolition as Wakefield Council submits plans to transform Cathedral Square into a social and cultural hub. If approved, the Cathedral Square project will see a new, greener and larger outdoor public space created. [19] A planning decision is expected to be made by December 2024. If approved, demolition of the Bread Street buildings will start in summer 2025 and construction of the public space will begin in late 2025 through most of 2026. [3]','New Public Outdoor Space Planned; Planning Decision Expected by December 2024','TheBusinessDesk.com, Wakefield Express','2024-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/new-public-outdoor-space-planned-as-part-of-multi-million-pound-regeneration [3], https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/wakefield-cathedral-square-more-images-revealed-of-plan-that-aims-to-transform-city-centre-into-a-thriving-and-culturally-vibrant-place-4394017 [19]','News reports in early November 2024 provided detailed insights into the Cathedral Square project, confirming plans for demolition of buildings on Bread Street, the creation of a large, green public square with interactive play and event spaces, and Bread Street resurfacing. A planning decision was expected by December 2024, with demolition anticipated for summer 2025 and construction continuing through 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('edbba773-5fd1-4808-b097-12ca5ff7c7be','infrastructure-leeds-climate-innovation-district',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.733','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'ve delivered our first social homes at the Climate Innovation District in Leeds - working with one of the UK\'s leading sustainable property developers, Citu. The four-bedroom and two-bedroom homes at the country\'s largest sustainable development are being made available for social rent – providing truly affordable and secure housing options for people in need during the housing crisis.','Yorkshire Housing Delivers First Social Homes at Climate Innovation District','Yorkshire Housing','2025-01-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGAxR_b7A4jZg6yCiwKUZdNDZL9X29d7AWFDvY_J_r6lPQnx_STgP6b6zQbxWT9CD7TUZWjMiuDyQNy4IwGn73T1mK7xchlui9sWL0IL_yI39AkZrC6Y7ypkZAVX4C6MRoU-fK4Lz1iRV3U4VZdpmuRFD1_2ITPwOQ96jgnBflPglP6XBtptJwZ3LUT7LZ_47lSqjiYWGqLZW_ivuYW8MpWMSCk3VJWDSLpXw==','Yorkshire Housing announced the delivery of its first social homes within the Climate Innovation District in partnership with Citu. These four-bedroom and two-bedroom homes are being made available for social rent, providing affordable and energy-efficient options.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('edbfb105-000b-4470-bd29-56a7ea115ca7','infrastructure-leeds-to-micklefield-rail-upgrades-transpennine-route-upgrade',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.980','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Transpennine Route Upgrade 2024 report reflects on a successful year that saw several key milestones achieved. October saw the completion of public consultation on plans for rail upgrades between Stalybridge and Diggle (Saddleworth). The programme was granted a Transport and Works Act Order (TWAO) to bring further upgrades to the route between Leeds and Micklefield, outlining plans to replace five level crossings with safer alternatives, work to a number of bridges to enable electrification, and the installation of some small-scale infrastructure. [17]','Transpennine Route Upgrade 2024 Report Highlights Progress','Railway PRO (Major achievements for Transpennine Route Upgrade 2024 report)','2025-01-20 00:00:00.000','https://www.railwaypro.com/2025/01/20/major-achievements-for-transpennine-route-upgrade-2024-report/','A report reflecting on the achievements of the Transpennine Route Upgrade (TRU) in 2024, noting significant progress across the route. Key milestones included the approval of the Transport and Works Act Order (TWAO) for the Leeds to Micklefield section in October, and advancements in station upgrades and electrification elsewhere on the route.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('edc5f217-bf34-4f52-8154-76a3c0ec8693','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Trust was successful in securing a total of £21.3 million from Phase 1 and Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. This included the installation of LED lighting, double glazing and ventilation upgrades, improvements to building and pipework insulation.','Leeds Teaching Hospitals \'one of the greenest NHS trusts in the UK\' with £21.3m PSDS funding','Salix Finance','2024-09-12 00:00:00.000','https://www.salixfinance.co.uk/news/leeds-teaching-hospitals-one-greenest-nhs-trusts-uk','Salix Finance highlighted Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust\'s success in securing a total of £21.3 million from Phase 1 and Phase 3a of the Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme. This funding facilitated energy efficiency measures, including LED lighting, double glazing, ventilation upgrades, and improved insulation, contributing to the Trust being recognised as one of the greenest NHS trusts.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('edf216ce-992b-4d45-a6ce-c6b3998cca6d','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale Council is reviewing parking across the borough, ensuring the right parking is provided in the right place, considering the requirements of individual towns in the borough. As part of the Council\'s agreed Parking Strategy, work is taking place to develop individual Parking Area Plans for each of the six towns in Calderdale – Brighouse, Elland, Halifax, Hebden Bridge, Sowerby Bridge and Todmorden. ... At the meeting of Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet on Monday 4 November, Members will note the progress made in developing local parking plans and also consider proposed changes to parking charges and times in some locations in Brighouse, Halifax and Hebden Bridge.','Supporting the right parking in the right place - Calderdale Council – News Centre','Calderdale Council – News Centre','2024-10-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEC-Q-g7cjzgFGYe4h8ns177lwyXVzGVKNZCMc3HQgiws44Kw2yNSYrysFD2uopAadWyVTl9iDooHDMkQqzTUUz2AKM7PQWV-Q20MTUEcPgSWRXsozAAAZBZtOXXXnZ66LIvZVdwaLaq8JeQtzRLyYBZ3QuzFOQxf8dDTcylSF95D9gxRxttCVchlTEnQ==','Calderdale Council announced a review of parking across the borough as part of its agreed Parking Strategy, with work ongoing to develop individual Parking Area Plans for six towns (Brighouse, Elland, Halifax, Hebden Bridge, Sowerby Bridge and Todmorden). This involves assessing characteristics, topography, and parking supply/demand, and considering proposed changes to parking charges and times. The announcement indicates a strategic approach to managing parking, including resident parking.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ee1525e5-7333-4aa7-b718-ae9e7c7229b0','infrastructure-aire-park-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.453','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Developer Vastint UK has brought forward 190,000 sq ft of office space at 1 and 3 South Brook Street in the mixed-use Leeds district. [...] Offering 190,000 sq ft across some of the largest floorplates available in Leeds at around 23,500 sq ft, the target is BREEAM Excellent, while the buildings have been pre-certified for a WELL Gold accreditation. [14]','Practical Completion Achieved on First Commercial Buildings (1 & 3 South Brook Street)','Place Yorkshire','2024-09-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHGkQxavuLjPtFFf-l2jpm1JAg6G7fIvsZL3BFbMH4ozBiZfuNl0idroYRDpfgO7ngKKMZI84Dpe-CROPLp7kEneQPejSeaQsj5tr24Rj4KHjKmwGmZMCtMS6ITyuRbebnRTLO7l4jvOOfOesap1bOwwrMxhLSWvjmoAZYMw7ZcXFkbf6D-h9GPgxRG2bWjhHvx0gCn-_A [14]','Developer Vastint UK announced the practical completion of the first two commercial buildings at Aire Park, 1 and 3 South Brook Street. These buildings collectively offer 190,000 sq ft of Grade A office space and mark a significant milestone in bringing commercial activity to the new district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ee1cce65-3c35-497f-8e7c-8a7d9385f462','infrastructure-kings-road-corridor-improvements-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.809','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'PEOPLE have just a few days to have their say on a multi-million pound scheme to improve a major Bradford route. The £35m project will focus on Kings Road, which runs from Wrose to Bradford city centre and will see new bus and cycle lanes, parking laybys and an improved underpass. There will also be wider pavements, better bus stops and more roadside green spaces. A consultation on the scheme began last month, and will end on Sunday. Funding for the project comes from West Yorkshire\'s City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement, a £830m fund awarded to the region by the Department for Transport for projects to be delivered by 2027.','Last chance to have your say on £35m road improvement scheme | Bradford Telegraph and Argus','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-03-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGjyb8Ae-mrFXjynzi2z1UFk65cjrLFqXB-AMp46nOOgOG12MBKtU4DQeMHySd-CW0_2WCigcXovF3eOiM5d45yJlLzbtjkZV0dtNEHULTIN11Begdru11DQRfi7hg0GH9zPyhOGb7BNUgCGKlPOFz_REhZ_-8RMbDj3ETchFIVFy5PzpuR_BPbHqglPXHUqMSLoY01jG3J59UNiAc=','This news article highlighted the nearing end of the public consultation period for the Kings Road Corridor Improvements scheme. It reiterated the £35 million project\'s scope, including new bus and cycle lanes, parking laybys, an improved underpass, wider pavements, better bus stops, and more roadside green spaces, all funded by the West Yorkshire\'s City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ee3721d8-402d-484d-a752-0ca0c1c28c07','infrastructure-cottonstones-near-lumb-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.205','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'River Calder catchment in Calderdale. ... History of significant flooding. ... Hydrometric analysis of 26/12/15 flood event. ... Impact of the event. ... Review of response activity. ... Going forward ensuring infrastructure resilience and better land management. [16]','Review of December 2015 Flood Event and Need for Infrastructure Resilience in Calderdale','APSE (Association for Public Service Excellence) / Calderdale Council','2015-12-24 00:00:00.000','https://apse.org.uk/apse/assets/events/upload/2015/calderdale_flood_risk_management.pdf','A report by Mohammed Amjid, Flood Risk Manager for Calderdale Council, reviews the significant flood events of December 2015 in the River Calder catchment. The report highlights the impact on homes, businesses, and infrastructure, and emphasizes the need for increased infrastructure resilience and sustainable flood risk management, providing a key driver for schemes like Cottonstones near Lumb.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ee89a773-0593-4bc0-984e-7d5d7fc4ac1b','infrastructure-landscapes-for-water-project-upper-calder-and-colne',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.246','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Thousands of trees have been planted on Marsden Moor as part of a new forest scheme. The White Rose Forest spans North and West Yorkshire and has seen an incredible 800,000 new trees planted this year alone. As part of the project the National Trust and Yorkshire Water teamed up to plant 65,000 trees at March Haigh near Marsden. Project lead for the National Trust, Jess Yorke, said: “The completion of phase 1 and the planting of 65,000 trees feels like a milestone in what we are trying to achieve with Landscapes for Water. By creating these clough woodlands we are protecting the landscape for the future.” Over the next five years some 350 hectares of new native woodland will be planted across five main areas of the South Pennines – around 300,000 trees.','Around 65,000 trees planted at March Haigh near Marsden as part of White Rose Forest','Huddersfield Hub','2024-08-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.huddersfieldhub.co.uk/around-65000-trees-planted-at-march-haigh-near-marsden-as-part-of-white-rose-forest/','By August 9, 2024, approximately 65,000 trees had been planted at March Haigh near Marsden as part of the Landscapes for Water project. This significant milestone, a collaboration between the National Trust and Yorkshire Water within the White Rose Forest scheme, contributes towards the overall goal of planting 300,000 trees across the South Pennines to boost the environment and reduce flood risk.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eec3ad2a-f3d6-48e1-ade4-1f1bdc6876fb','infrastructure-bradford-southern-gateway-masterplan',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.643','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Council wishes to appoint appropriately skilled and experienced consultants to produce: • Lot 1: Part A – Bradford Sustainable City Development Framework together with Part B – Bradford Southern Gateway Masterplan and Part C – Holme Wood Urban Design Framework.','Bradford District Development Frameworks and Related Services Tender Issued','Find a Tender (GOV.UK)','2022-03-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHKZ7Rv6De_MUK_T3LNKQgrJMf18K2M_cWgbs4Z33EJv5AdZ-z3ficMl1sHPES4L8Aw4L-p_zwiP-3IRUhQbY9mqQft1uo_5TARxXNmBfR4zSZ1SoD92C0Gmk3hr2uHsLiQ7lJbf734m3IeQJTet8Q5TQbXeE_w9w==','Bradford Council issued a tender for consultancy services to produce several development frameworks, explicitly including the \'Bradford Southern Gateway Masterplan\'. This marks an early, formal step in planning the project\'s future development.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eef069f1-25c4-49bd-b556-2bfe19d3985e','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Yorkshire Water reduced the number of discharges from storm overflows to the region\'s watercourses by 12% in 2024 – a reduction of 9,595 discharges. As well as a reduction in the number of discharges, there was also a 17% drop in the amount of time Yorkshire Water discharged to watercourses – which equates to 86,906 hours. The reductions in discharges in 2024 resulted from both a drier year than 2023 and the hard work of our teams to deliver our £180m investment programme. In the last two years, Yorkshire Water has invested in 142 storm overflows across Yorkshire to reduce discharges and improve water quality. Eighty-four projects are complete now and helping to reduce the frequency and duration of discharges into watercourses.','Yorkshire Water reduces storm discharges to watercourses by 12% in 2024','Yorkshire Water','2025-03-27 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirewater.com/news-media/yorkshire-water-reduces-storm-discharges-to-watercourses-by-12-in-2024/','Yorkshire Water announced a 12% reduction in storm overflow discharges (9,595 fewer) and a 17% drop in discharge duration in 2024. This progress is attributed to a drier year and the ongoing £180m investment program, which has completed 84 projects and has 58 more underway, including those aimed at increasing storm water capacity and separating surface water from combined sewers.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('eefc1167-e2fa-41e7-bde1-907cd6e707ae','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More people in Leeds will soon have access to affordable low carbon heat thanks to four new connections to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, as confirmed by Leeds City Council. New plans for two major extensions to the network – which would enable dozens more buildings to connect – have also been published by the local authority. The four latest buildings, including the first private-sector residential developers, which have confirmed their intention to connect to the network within the next 12 months, are: Spinner\'s Yard around Mabgate, developed by Rise Homes. By using heat and energy recovered from non-recyclable waste at a Recycling and Energy Recovery Facility (RERF) to provide warmth and hot water to buildings in the city, the Leeds PIPES district heating project is helping businesses and residents move away from costly fossil-fuel powered heating systems.','Further expansion revealed for city\'s £62m heating network','TheBusinessDesk.com','2023-08-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.thebusinessdesk.com/yorkshire/news/further-expansion-revealed-for-citys-62m-heating-network','TheBusinessDesk.com reported on Leeds City Council\'s confirmation of four new connections to the Leeds PIPES district heating network, including Spinner\'s Yard in Mabgate, developed by Rise Homes. The article emphasized the network\'s role in providing affordable, low-carbon heating and its contribution to carbon reduction.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ef3ab0b5-1704-4add-afe5-ca420939b1c6','infrastructure-a638-doncaster-road-corridor-improvement-programme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.997','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Birkwood Road: Closed for approximately 40 metres from September 15 to 20. A diversion is available via Birkwood Road, Ferry Lane, Nellie Spindler Drive, Neil Fox Way, Doncaster Road, Black Road, Wakefield Road, Normanton Bypass, Snydale Road, High Street, King Edward Street, Altofts Road, Station Road, Lee Brig, High Green Road, Birkwood Road and vice versa. ... Dewsbury Road: Closed at the roundabout between Dewsbury Road and Leeds Road from September 15 to October 10. A diversion is available via Leeds Road, Ossett Bypass A638 (roundabout), Leeds Road.','Traffic and travel: Upcoming road closures and diversions in September and October for Wakefield, Notton, Normanton, Ossett, Durkar, and Overton (Relevance to A638 Doncaster Road)','Wakefield Express','2025-09-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/traffic-and-travel/traffic-and-travel-upcoming-road-closures-and-diversions-in-september-and-october-for-wakefield-notton-normanton-ossett-durkar-and-overton-4760599','A news article detailing upcoming road closures in Wakefield mentioned a diversion for Birkwood Road, which includes Doncaster Road. While not directly about the \'Corridor Improvement Programme\' construction, it indicates ongoing traffic management and the A638 Doncaster Road\'s role in local diversions, affirming its status as a key route.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ef653859-b15a-40d1-a1ba-b513be33b5d4','infrastructure-leeds-to-micklefield-rail-upgrades-transpennine-route-upgrade',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.980','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Network Rail requested a screening decision from the Secretary of State as to whether an environmental impact assessment (EIA) was required for the proposed Order application. In response to that request, the Secretary of State issued a decision on 17 May 2023 that an EIA was not required. [15, 16, 18]','Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) Screening Decision','GOV.UK (Network Rail (Leeds to Micklefield) order decision)','2023-05-17 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/network-rail-leeds-to-micklefield-order-decision','The Secretary of State for Transport issued a decision stating that an Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) was not required for the proposed Transport and Works Act Order (TWAO) application concerning the Leeds to Micklefield Enhancements scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ef67dc5c-3c0e-44c2-93e3-3188dfff515c','infrastructure-bradford-interchange-rail-gateway-enhancements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.018','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On March 24, 2025, multi-million-pound transformation work at Bradford Interchange was officially completed. This £4 million project, delivered by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority in partnership with Bradford Council via funding from the Transforming Cities Fund, created a new public plaza and improved the lower concourse and rail station access ramp. These enhancements aimed to create an enhanced gateway to the city centre. Passengers and residents now benefit from newly refurbished toilets, enhanced flooring and ceiling, and new artwork inside the lower concourse, creating a welcoming entrance and complementing Bradford City of Culture 2025 celebrations. The area outside the entrance was transformed into a new public plaza with fresh paving, seating, and planting. Taxis were relocated to Bridge Street, and the ramped access to the train station was resurfaced with new lighting, handrails, and artwork.','Entrance to Bradford Interchange transformed into enhanced gateway','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-03-24 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFjDXw8owaXXMXm-MpJahGhSn5--MJVDqho9_-zWK23anLyGUETw68fav6ntffrBTmsjZvUdvSOuTTLwMLI8yh__8KCh6Jva6rg43yYFxuuOHFB8HpbCmIkb_VMm5aXoPPaeP0jY1N5FE5d2bYOfpAHWtQlf2laO38FtJnqKE3jbkRWgDPvn3XhuJa0s_GuaVsXVtZ1iEjXgVKnSNzZ4BQUhsFUgma-wq5CBhQzHQ==','Multi-million-pound transformation work at Bradford Interchange, a £4 million project, was officially completed. This included a new public plaza and improvements to the lower concourse and rail station access ramp, creating an enhanced gateway to the city centre. Passengers now benefit from refurbished toilets, enhanced flooring and ceiling, and new artwork, complementing Bradford City of Culture 2025 celebrations. The project was delivered by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Bradford Council via the Transforming Cities Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ef6c0004-b07c-4ab3-98a8-77cc9f9cff39','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---chain-street-townhouses-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.570','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A transformation of Bradford\'s former retail heart into a community known as “City Village” has advanced with the launch of the final phase of public consultation. Detailed plans for phase one were revealed today – 21 May – as part of Bradford Council\'s three-day Bradford Showcase event at Leeds Dock, which is running alongside this year\'s UKREiiF. Phase one will include: Creation of 33 townhouses on the Chain Street site, centred around a new community green. Featuring a mix of two and three-bedroom homes.','Detailed Plans Unveiled and Public Consultation Launched for Phase One','Bradford Council / Place Yorkshire','2025-05-21 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGHaghcf5FJuArVgLRcJVIjnEWZOJHlFauvp8hiIEg0-idCtVH39i0QCBbzghpzaH0Mt5ppzefmKQX2N_LnjqF193YCPCev6MZt5s01z65NYW-MwM6AmXGXgVrWO87oF9jJ0jy0V3urP14oYCI58YGniEUiZFgaCbJbtjCsN-xLR3KJq6Ig4pn-bGvG5YNmXz0e0ncK3RgY8ARXnXT23d-eewdSD4rdJSkS_YFaLD0MnlORSlCBK91o','Bradford Council launched the final phase of public consultation for Bradford City Village, unveiling detailed plans for Phase One, which includes the 33 townhouses on Chain Street and 64 on the northern Oastler site. The consultation ran until June 18, inviting community feedback.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ef8d4cbc-2327-426e-8c4d-58caac7ca791','infrastructure-proposed-highway-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.142','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Transport Fund has been partly funded through the Leeds City Region Enterprise Partnership (LEP) Growth Deal. A £1 billion package of Government funding to drive growth and job creation across the Leeds City Region. Major transport improvements in Calderdale include: A629 Salterhebble to Shaw Hill (Phase 1a). A629 Calder and Hebble Junction (Phase 1b). A629 Halifax Town Centre (Phase 2). A629 Halifax to Huddersfield (Phase 4). A629 Ainley Top to Huddersfield (Phase 5 - Kirklees led). Halifax rail station. Elland rail station. A641 Bradford - Brighouse - Huddersfield.','West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund - Major Transport Improvements in Calderdale','Calderdale Council','2025-02-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGpNMM_QvzY-F2nUdoj_uyL5PJvW7BC3nVuucw7_6qBMsKzmMv79buOn2acI6WS7mWdA6MU20V54PevqOKgSqhU5WKQSUVN_1_IpVmN08C4Sseub1N4Im1663I4TA7n6qBgrmBhP0fRVYpQ_MU6oizQPnSxUyvbmAh0DtexLwGNvPSoG4Im6_cfP0SpDJyTUZC0vt6oyO7dC64nJdX1-A1SIufvLphpOg==','This page provides an overview of major transport improvements in Calderdale, funded through the West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund and Leeds City Region Enterprise Partnership. Projects include several phases of the A629 (Salterhebble to Shaw Hill, Calder and Hebble Junction, Halifax Town Centre, Halifax to Huddersfield, Ainley Top to Huddersfield), and improvements to Halifax and Elland rail stations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('efa666a5-acff-4efb-bbe3-5ddb43fb3494','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2022-07-04) Residents and businesses are being asked for their views on proposals to invest up to £22.5 million in two key roads connecting Leeds and Wakefield – the A61 and the A639. ... The proposed package of measures include dedicated bus lanes and cycle lanes, new crossings, wider pavements and footpaths. It would be delivered in partnership with WYCA as part of the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund, which aims to provide an accessible, attractive, and cleaner alternative to car journeys. ... This engagement will close at 11.59pm on Sunday 14 August 2022. The outcome reports can be viewed on the project pages (A61), (A639). The information below was presented during the public consultation between Monday 4 July to Sunday 14 August 2022. To view all updates on this project please visit Wakefield Council website. Drop in events. ... Monday 11 July. 16:00- 19:00. Sandal Methodist Church, WF1 5NU.','A61 and A639 scheme: Public consultation to be held on new bus and cycle route plans for key Leeds to Wakefield roads','Yorkshire Evening Post, West Yorkshire Combined Authority, UK Construction Online','2022-07-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFcOJBB4P_IvlI_PPRDl02EfTnOLTE32hewjBcMchgzBuUswd6YVAQ1EXRXxtYO3vO57GEynzQ2vYQEMOw3I89z67-fnwAuwenm7BQs3BzGMglyYtkdI_UCvGuRNRRD49Wv0j86xUQ2Fu2yls9K_tlcMTGvt7SGdOPeE_V-__fkxAoa5Vo7XB7GoBHwn3YSshO7YP_rBVXNrRYPajDnPdYaUeGdFio_YdJ9Nz63FEN0F_L7-Bh2RY_9eM74PM2TERSEiF3hk1P-Ipn4BDU3ZnKcHKGFqIayyR-r0T6LhuDOa_fxEhsAQVhfBtjpAwxJ','A public consultation was launched on July 4, 2022, seeking feedback on proposed improvements to the A61 and A639 corridors, connecting Leeds and Wakefield. The schemes, part of the Government\'s Transforming Cities Fund, involve an investment of up to £22.5 million to make travel easier and safer for bus users, cyclists, and pedestrians, while also reducing congestion and improving air quality. The consultation included drop-in events in various locations, such as Sandal, Outwood, and Glasshoughton, and concluded on August 14, 2022. [4, 9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('efa9228c-12bd-42b0-bca1-0d32dfaa89e0','infrastructure-minor-traffic-and-parking-improvement-schemes-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.110','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The updated strategy will guide how we plan, invest in and deliver transport across Calderdale. We plan to start this (second consultation) in October 2025. You will have the chance to review and comment on the full Draft Transport Strategy. [9]','Transport Strategy - Calderdale Council','Calderdale Council','2025-10-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/v2/residents/transport-and-streets/transport-strategy','Calderdale Council is refreshing its Transport Strategy, with a second consultation planned for October 2025. This overarching strategy includes the \'Minor traffic and parking improvement scheme\' as one of its components, demonstrating ongoing policy development and community engagement for future transport initiatives.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('efba48d1-d55d-4284-9cea-8631574a56ae','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'An article from Leeds-List, dated December 16, 2024, summarizes major developments in Leeds, confirming that \'South Village gets the green light\'. It reiterates that Caddick Developments received unanimous approval from Leeds City Council for the mixed-use neighbourhood in the South Bank, which will bring up to 1,925 homes and 650,000 square feet of commercial space, originally called City One. [10]','5 Major Developments Coming Soon to Leeds - South Village gets the green light','Leeds-List.com','2024-12-16 00:00:00.000','https://leeds-list.com/culture/five-major-developments-coming-soon-to-leeds/','An article summarizing major Leeds developments reaffirms the approval for South Village (formerly City One) by Leeds City Council, highlighting its plans for up to 1,925 homes and 650,000 sq ft of commercial space around a village green. This piece acts as a retrospective confirmation of the project\'s progress.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('efefdcb7-837d-4650-bc74-c3e41adb3556','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Metro rail strategy was formally agreed at WYCA\'s full meeting in March, and includes as top-ranked (Tier 1) schemes: The Calder Valley line extending the government\'s Leeds-Bradford proposal to Calderdale, Preston and Manchester. [15] West Yorkshire needs significant investment in its rail network to support economic growth, improve accessibility and deliver against our decarbonisation targets. ... What we need are: ... Electrification of our railway lines with the Calder Valley line identified as a priority. [13]','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Rail Strategy: Our Requirements - Electrification of Calder Valley Line a priority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHeWnvD7YuzI1GkS82caovcok1rYjM4xih2BkLu-uYwlun5jHkVqWT304eSzkDLOEP2HJmXfpVn8GajNRILMrWosQBbeZ2LzH-SOcvCbjP3dpYq7sszbA3jLcpT5VJgviBF0EBcFpLjgYZQgl1OlHL5iLZguJaPMBsTdzKjojDrHRTwovVyenzmKJI1E6-4lDAj42eByb-OqMyb034exroZCM_v5LZzlw==','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s Rail Strategy identifies the electrification of railway lines, with the Calder Valley Line as a priority. It notes a current proposal to electrify the line between Leeds and Bradford and advocates for a further commitment to electrify the entire line to Manchester Victoria, including links via Brighouse.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f03088f4-27c7-4282-9360-4505cac2d1a7','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Public consultation for the A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Programme Scheme took place from 7 June - 18 July 2021. A report has been produced that includes all the feedback received during the consultation period. The report can be found here. ... 14/10/2021 - A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme. 1) That approval be given in principle to the scheme.','A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme - first consultation and in-principle approval','Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority / Council and democracy - Kirklees Council','2021-10-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQErH6PoOeX3wnaZbeZEvqwLUvXXO_JZk95PM11q-IowTnLeQo3C3xFBjowMeIw6CqYY-X47lo6hU1PrLeiGfJyvNwAjdBZsX3occUqdkE00YAY_ZQsCI9ViEOuWg7IEoEUcJh5z_0SZAUagarog2HhdDSLgig==','A public consultation for the A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Programme Scheme took place from June 7 to July 18, 2021, presenting a preferred option to enhance the existing network at Cooper Bridge and Bradley junctions. Subsequently, on October 14, 2021, approval was given in principle for the scheme. [6, 14, 18]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f031d494-c81d-4011-a3a6-3473100d883c','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle (EV) charging points are set to be installed across the Wakefield district after senior councillors agreed to accept £1.5m of funding. Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept the grant from West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of measures designed to achieve net zero targets. WYCA has been allocated more than £14m of government funding as part of the local electric vehicle infrastructure (LEVI) scheme. Wakefield will receive a total £1,520,938, based on a University of Leeds study into EV charger requirements for the region.','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for EV charging points across district','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-10-15 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHmVlXv-6fBs148lWRBC2Yg5kzJAj0jWy_g0zjjlb6KV1dYTYkFRWtBKd-n9mJtkeFa19avFW0eEgan_AOTuqPYEOU4Whz9vifP31r6JB6OdjpEH32J0P0smr7XpKWz5OeddbafY_yZX07qiSGFTRP1uQLhHJTbrYGyo9qvFqdyZ-2gUp-fZpYSrD2ytPMvAXBmrxrOhDhD2Fb2zNoWbBYa6f_bL8tn4cBC93N9SUxw-NLrVZLEFdptQdgVpe_WkOZKFLIs-qvPSbmmmRvseF8Itqyy0YyUzlnMJWo=','Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept a £1,520,938 LEVI grant from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) to install more public EV charging points across the district. This funding is part of a larger £14m government allocation to WYCA for the LEVI scheme, aiming to support residents without access to private parking and contribute to net-zero targets by 2038.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f03c7ffd-49d7-424d-839e-5fd9d99c6a86','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A PROJECT that has transformed parts of Bradford\'s Top of Town area has won a prestigious town planning award. The heritage-led regeneration of the area scooped the Best Project award at the Yorkshire Awards for Planning Excellence, beating schemes such as the Heart of the City project in Sheffield. The £2m Lottery-funded project has seen the area around the Listed Richard Ostler Statue transformed into a greener space, with raised flower beds and improved landscaping. Areas around North Parade and Rawson Square have been refurbished, with new seating, planting and new, wider paving. The Top of Town area of the city is due to undergo even more changes in recent years, with the planned “City Village” development planned for the Oastler Market site. [19]','Work to transform Bradford\'s Top of Town area wins award','Telegraph & Argus','2025-07-06 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24436577.work-transform-bradfords-top-town-area-wins-award/','A heritage-led regeneration project in Bradford\'s \'Top of Town\' area, focused on public realm improvements around North Parade and Rawson Square, won the Best Project award at the Yorkshire Awards for Planning Excellence. This £2m Lottery-funded project is a precursor to the larger City Village development, which will be planned for the Oastler Market site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f0ca6194-b7d9-48fe-9921-481a5579d11f','infrastructure-leeds-bradford-cycle-superhighway-extension-thornton-road-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.856','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Announced by Active Travel England today, the £5.5 million investment will help to make travelling on foot, wheeling and cycling, a more attractive option for people making local journeys... Over half of today\'s investment (£3 million) will fund six new projects, with communities set to benefit from wider canal towpaths and improved crossing points, as well as improved facilities and infrastructure in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees and Leeds. [12]','Bradford to benefit from multi-million pound investment for walking and cycling','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2024-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHZQ_wks5lVVvuJR6bV-X-yNBS_AvSzyTmNkImNI7cynATIh8WL8BSD5F2QEWWJLqDIy_KJETUIw5QS6Q1CSS6KGHIBUUrZykPdoxEbmxn_uLbKRNtA-WANW5nBuNAD5pSU3ErSgKAHOGJ4MQkrzkF5OGnr-hkH822O2wxeitI-V-KNOoGlra-VYGvqA5ZzufGFL2sWdSyHCkAZaMkZ4AkNy6c=','Active Travel England announced a £5.5 million investment for West Yorkshire, with over half (£3 million) specifically funding six new projects. These projects include improved facilities and infrastructure for walking and cycling in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, and Leeds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f10f7509-adb4-4180-b2b5-d16b2f31559e','infrastructure-mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.576','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Following the devastating Boxing Day 2015 floods, the Environment Agency announced an action plan for Mytholmroyd. This plan committed over £10 million to flood defences, with construction aiming to start by the end of 2016. Proposals included raising and constructing new walls, widening the river channel, and strengthening buildings. Public consultation was a key component.','Mytholmroyd Flood Alleviation Scheme Action Plan published','GOV.UK','2016-05-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/mytholmroyd-flood-alleviation-scheme-action-plan-published','Following the devastating Boxing Day 2015 floods, the Environment Agency announced an action plan for Mytholmroyd. This plan committed over £10 million to flood defences, with construction aiming to start by the end of 2016. Proposals included raising and constructing new walls, widening the river channel, and strengthening buildings. Public consultation was a key component.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f15fb20f-4c89-467f-a28b-91ade98a434c','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---lovell-park-tower-blocks-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.461','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council has announced that 259 council properties in the Lovell Park area will soon be connected to the Leeds PIPES network. Residents from Lovell Park Heights, Lovell Park Grange, and Lovell Park Towers will soon receive heat from the Leeds PIPES network. Councillor Mohammed Rafique, the council\'s Executive Member for Climate, Energy, Environment and Green Space said: “Their bills will go down; they will save on their energy bills.”','Leeds City Council Expands Low Carbon Heat Network As Residents Turn To Warm Banks','Yorkshire Voice','2023-12-14 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirevoice.org.uk/2023/12/14/leeds-city-council-expands-low-carbon-heat-network-as-residents-turn-to-warm-banks/','Yorkshire Voice reported on the Leeds City Council\'s announcement regarding the connection of 259 council properties in Lovell Park to the Leeds PIPES network, framing it within the context of the cost-of-living crisis and rising energy bills. Councillor Mohammed Rafique emphasized that residents\' bills would decrease.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f192924b-6c8c-410c-b530-6c327844a2d8','infrastructure-manchester-road-bus-improvements-scheme-south-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.869','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Live Now: Public consultation on proposed bus improvements on Manchester Road. Bradford Council are currently seeking the public\'s views on proposed changes to Manchester Road. The Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme proposes a series of changes to buses, some walking, wheeling and cycling improvements, and new planting and landscaping. The public consultation on the proposals began on the 19 March 2025 and will run till Tuesday 22 April 2025. You can get in touch with the Manchester Road Bus Improvements team through email, phone, or Freepost.','Live Now: Public consultation on proposed bus improvements on Manchester Road','Future Bradford Newsletter (Bradford Council)','2025-03-28 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFGkbgUXHK2Aa9RjXflLO0jIfo3mTx_axmcze3a4nTCw76ltjZyK89-EIdZw9WEAyyWeRJdAJP70d8ElvfXT6kIQi6CEY0HdhB3jX7y8bhhWlkjlk5qiGHTllbYsWFxT4PGoZAn_Vn4VRTwyw0_egvzWPfDrfPyR1TCRaX_xzDPiWw2P_W2N5iks8c=','The Future Bradford Newsletter announced the ongoing public consultation for the Manchester Road Bus Improvements Scheme. It provided an overview of the proposed changes to buses, walking, wheeling, cycling, and landscaping, emphasizing their aim to reduce congestion and improve travel options between South Bradford and the city centre. Contact information for the project team was also included.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f1c5d650-4cc1-41a0-94bc-168c619d42b9','infrastructure-kirklees-council-digital-inclusion-device-loan-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.300','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Digital Hubs programme has secured funding as part of the UK Shared Prosperity Fund which will allow community-based organisations to apply for a capital grant to improve their Digital Equipment or infrastructure. The final round of funding is now open, the maximum amount of funding a community organisation can apply for is £5000. Funding Year: Year 3 2024-25 round 3. Funding Available for: £45,206. Indicative Timeline for Applications to open: Apr 2024.','UKSPF Digital Infrastructure Capital Funding - Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council','2024-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE4j50AnXeo6aSFrivxVqTZC5mPgPnWuZAT1u2dpTd2ejY_-gbSObokBZubrfOmn9v0_-dSPbEQxVnRkfExwzRX59tx4jsrzS1vipK3lrmjQTV2mrEvIzQWAcUnx2Y98oqp-sfJCnWdFSlts-Fxj-aepkpshCjEZDgiJYosSwrymKNiZXORTeD4_ntv','Kirklees Council announced the final round of UK Shared Prosperity Fund (UKSPF) capital grants for the 2024-25 financial year, making £45,206 available. Community-based organizations within Kirklees can apply for grants of up to £5,000 to enhance their digital equipment or infrastructure, with applications opening in April 2024, specifically benefiting end-users and local residents.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f1e8fb86-5872-4736-b018-72ebdb30280a','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Regional leaders are set to approve £40 million in funding for detailed planning and development work on the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system at a West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting on September 18, 2025. This funding will support technical and environmental assessments, business case progression, and keep the project on track for a 2028 groundbreaking. Over 5,000 environmental surveys have already been conducted between Leeds and Bradford.','WYCA to move Mass Transit plans forward / Mass transit and bus franchising plans set to accelerate after £40m funding boost','Place Yorkshire / Yorkshire Evening Post / UKTram / West Leeds Dispatch / Public Sector Executive / Rayo / Wakefield Express / Telegraph and Argus','2025-09-18 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE8ZmMid0tztk7z0i5CoVRSXxorPX_0PGEjccWPw9KmipR5hSE8oK80E6vN2dBy-W8_v0fwJo_BaguJkCEtpCs5-fHUty0R3d8y4GkVYzyiOXdXTRDWvWTxXUonMouRePIJ6qf9k6HJv6mewECAE90zYHvCnqkA7bv0jHEFkhF8nhef1qg=','Regional leaders are set to approve £40 million in funding for detailed planning and development work on the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system at a West Yorkshire Combined Authority meeting on September 18, 2025. This funding will support technical and environmental assessments, business case progression, and keep the project on track for a 2028 groundbreaking. Over 5,000 environmental surveys have already been conducted between Leeds and Bradford.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f206622a-cd8b-4706-a7e8-38e46b336c1d','infrastructure-elland-rail-station-and-access-package-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.897','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'New details about a planned railway station for Elland have been revealed in another planning application for the project. Calderdale Council has put in detailed plans for access routes – including pedestrian and cycleway bridges – as part of the £25 million scheme. [17]','Detailed plans for Elland Access Package submitted by Calderdale Council','Halifax Courier','2023-08-30 00:00:00.000','https://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/transport/elland-railway-station-more-details-revealed-about-calderdale-towns-new-railway-station-as-new-planning-application-goes-in-4273578','On August 30, 2023, Calderdale Council submitted detailed plans for the Elland Access Package, including new pedestrian and cycle bridges, as part of the wider £25 million scheme.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f25389af-909f-4eec-88f7-24698582330e','infrastructure-five-towns-leisure-hub-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.669','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council has revealed plans to replace three existing swimming pools in West Yorkshire with a new £14.8m “flagship” leisure centre for the region. Facilities at the new centre, to be located at Pontefract Park, will include a 10-lane swimming pool, studio pool with moveable floor and a splash pad water confidence area. The centre will also house a large health and fitness club, exercise studios, a two-court sports hall, a \'clip and climb\' area, café and soft play area as well as meeting rooms for community use and referral rooms for exercise and weight management support. Outdoor facilities include tennis courts, an activity and exercise space and five-a-side 3G football pitches. The plans now need to receive the green light from councillors when they are discussed in detail at a full cabinet meeting on 27 September. [11]','£14.8m leisure hub planned for Pontefract','Leisure Management','2016-09-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQER97WvqGLGir6uCGMxrV4odbd1xE3FYhiRty8713hF8wETuvPJB-RFHa8QqnqZwoZXnE48AxFahWP7O7HK3ckYX5OlqmpJPc3exFs7m_wZX8VFhm1NlZ5uPje_A2hkiES4XPm1LCXdTyI9smamkUBd-LwobmCSROP1Q5w_wYzQWiSD1G_Z','Wakefield Council unveiled plans for a new £14.8 million \'flagship\' leisure centre at Pontefract Park. The facility aimed to replace three existing swimming pools and include a 10-lane swimming pool, health and fitness club, exercise studios, sports hall, climbing area, café, soft play area, tennis courts, and 3G football pitches. The proposals were due for discussion at a full cabinet meeting on September 27, 2016.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f27b47c5-fe47-4fe6-8ca0-b85970d03d7c','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A further 4,500 homes and businesses across rural West Yorkshire and the York area can now access the fastest, most reliable broadband on the market, thanks to broadband provider Quickline Communications. Communities in rural West Yorkshire and areas surrounding York, including the villages of Escrick, Crofton, Elvington, Sutton upon Derwent and Wheldrake, are the first to benefit from gigabit-capable broadband under a £60 million government contract awarded to Quickline earlier this year. [7, 11]','Quickline\'s £60m Gigabit Broadband Build in North and West Yorkshire UK Goes Live, covering first 4,500 premises','ISPreview UK, Quickline','2024-09-26 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGsgb0e4Nqdfx_5kGcsw69QoU8NWwVAkv0HtQMdp3xG3lMENvOTlG1vWb5iACUH4nz3c084XXtRIhB-vebBBCSnZPsRCUVZb_tOa35rp8893uPKnjx-YuHzlg23DG3384-6pY2ugO8Bpy1XCTTdkQOM9zBZjwF4AjO5qh0Vmizld0ooSDyo9i6Yjm8cmjlL6qG1p44rpHj2ACWZiHuIa2JjBf3Sq9_4G8Or3MRhsJbPMQ5sQqRRWbjHMVMphZ62','Quickline announced that the first 4,500 premises under their £60m state-aid supported gigabit broadband roll-out contract for North and West Yorkshire (Lot 8), including remote areas surrounding York, have been covered by the new network. This is part of the goal to reach 28,000 premises.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f2ab7430-cf56-4d35-848c-0c58527d1244','infrastructure-a629-halifax-town-centre-corridor-improvement-phase-2---eastern-side-works',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.138','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'This is about land acquisition and use of Compulsory Purchase Powers for the A629 Phase 2 Corridor Improvement Scheme. (1) The Borough Council of Calderdale (Halifax town centre) (Highway improvements) (West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund, A629 Phase 2) (Side roads) Order 2020. This is an Order under Section 14 and 125 of the Highways Act 1980. CD 1.1 A629 Phase 2 SRO Order Signed and Sealed. (2) The Borough Council of Calderdale (Halifax town centre) (Highway improvements) (West Yorkshire Plus Transport Fund, A629 Phase 2) Compulsory Purchase Order 2020. This is an Order under Sections 239, 240, 250 and 260 of the Highways Act 1980. [22]','A629 Phase 2 Public Inquiry 2025','Calderdale Council','2025-04-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.calderdale.gov.uk/council/councillors-committees-elections/committees/agendas/cabinet/2021/agenda-item-8/a629-phase-2-public-inquiry-2025/index.jsp','A public inquiry page on Calderdale Council\'s website providing details on land acquisition and the use of Compulsory Purchase Powers (CPO) and Side Roads Orders (SRO) for the A629 Phase 2 Corridor Improvement Scheme. The page references signed and sealed orders from 2020.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f2f41a1a-39f2-4b84-be8c-6621800672fa','infrastructure-todmorden-area-a646-corridor-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.925','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans are moving forward to transform travel in and around Hebden Bridge, to help make it safer and healthier for people to get to the town, and to support local businesses. Following the pause to the Fallingroyd part of the £5 million A646 Corridor Improvement Programme (CIP), Calderdale Council has now agreed a way forward. The CIP is being delivered in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority to improve road safety, journey times, air quality, opportunities to walk, wheel and cycle, and access to jobs and homes on the busy A646 / A6033 route from Todmorden to Skircoat Moor in Halifax.','Plans Progress for Hebden Bridge as Part of A646 Corridor Improvement Programme','Calderdale Council News Centre','2025-02-11 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHyd99kYpFXdMQPWrIOan3anw3c11vclJvMjW8oDGY8Tcu274rS5s2Bj88y-oEF-5Y8ZhAnqOQg8zWm9Cha8d8UV4LqJ_GiaxTrxGlNwsmi7D6OQb0Yx3I2eHTxQ1JwjC99oRfaYNXc8vA6bIAJaTFudqcABHazF7FAYA1RLZwKutgyofOBytJ-1scK-dWrbXZEbttU0MKYCA==','Calderdale Council announced that plans are moving forward to transform travel in and around Hebden Bridge, a component of the £5 million A646 Corridor Improvement Programme. Following a pause, an agreed way forward for the Fallingroyd section was reached, including new double yellow lines and formalized parking to improve road safety and traffic management. This update reflects the Council\'s ongoing commitment to the CIP.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f3046866-6c60-4360-933e-209502b27ccd','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.631','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet was set to approve plans on July 8, 2025, to form a new regional partnership to shape the planning and delivery of the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system. This step includes preparing a joint Spatial Development Framework, with initial routes focusing on Leeds and Bradford, and later phases extending to North Kirklees, including a planned Dewsbury line.','Kirklees is \'open for business\' as mass transit plans take next step this week','Yorkshire Live','2025-07-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGKoKZVYsOs8pfIHJjG-5iF9zlxnmB6iTeQRj3xl4pM6J9UEKOkh-lJgO0YBOYPRo148YzGpazgvC7AkD7tI4uQJzzY8ZJW0G6ybmYv44L28soVgAi_AXtMO5xadGo1tcFe1TAGsmA_2XMaXVdIi4IGP66Gynxh8XNqHiesA6IkDr0Ejqu09_AaZBN0aCvWYhhRMatXYgmxawZVAP3nxQ8=','Kirklees Council\'s Cabinet was set to approve plans on July 8, 2025, to form a new regional partnership to shape the planning and delivery of the West Yorkshire Mass Transit system. This step includes preparing a joint Spatial Development Framework, with initial routes focusing on Leeds and Bradford, and later phases extending to North Kirklees, including a planned Dewsbury line.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f31bec89-497b-4d59-a628-36a14554477e','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The EP Scheme is made on 1 November 2022 and shall come into operation on this date and has subsequently been varied on 29 March 2024. The Combined Authority, in collaboration with Operators and Local Authorities, will identify services to be delivered through Tranches 2 and 3, by no later than 30 June 2024. These services will be implemented no later than 28 February 2025. [14]','West Yorkshire Enhanced Partnership Scheme','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-03-29 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFbns9nFrHy39WajLW60btayFXy1701FS_FRGJUrcjX0jr8W3ul-fTPIkWSX4udhMeqJfnvLR1ta_9-ePWunesS4bFKU-P3caLhz2Ago5JKfBSNGAB20mkW1Kg0oUCaT9_8Bm-ddzoLpGVggv1-gpk68nw2ESWBvMOmsv4cgTvAjYC4mb3FuVbhxBXDm1wPwXkh9yg','This document, which is associated with the Enhanced Partnership Plan, sets out specific obligations and requirements for the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), the five local authorities, and bus operators to achieve intended improvements in bus services. It states that services identified for improvement through tranches 2 and 3 will be implemented no later than February 28, 2025. [14]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f33289f7-d1b6-44b0-8917-38a3a8cf9e4b','infrastructure-dewsbury-riverside---main-access-road-and-first-350-homes',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.689','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Dewsbury Riverside is the largest of the Local Plan\'s housing allocations, expected to accommodate up to 4,000 homes with community infrastructure and open spaces. In August 2023, planning permission was granted for the main access road and the first 350 homes to be constructed, with these expected to be finished by 2030. In November 2023, cabinet gave the go-ahead for the council to enter into legal agreements with Network Rail and Homes England, and carry out work to appoint a master developer. Work on the highways is ongoing to establish the impact the development would have on the road network and legal advice commissioned for some elements of the scheme. (See Source [7] for full context).','Update on Kirklees\' Biggest Housing Projects, Including Dewsbury Riverside','YorkshireLive','2024-04-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/update-kirklees-biggest-housing-projects-28923053','An update on Kirklees\' major housing projects, dated April 2, 2024, highlighted that Dewsbury Riverside is the largest housing allocation, aiming for up to 4,000 homes. It confirmed that planning permission was granted in August 2023 for the main access road and the first 350 homes, which are anticipated to be finished by 2030. The report also noted ongoing work on highway impact assessments and efforts to secure a master developer.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f34231d2-aa48-4a2e-84b0-da083f7bb954','infrastructure-wakefield-cathedral-square-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.682','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Cabinet members will consider the proposal at a meeting on January 16. [7] Wakefield Council has agreed to buy city centre business premises to allow an ambitious regeneration project to go ahead on time. [9]','Wakefield Council Approves Acquisition of Business Premises for Cathedral Square Project','Yorkshire Post, Wakefield Express','2024-01-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/council/cathedral-square-project-council-set-to-buy-business-premises-to-hit-deadline-for-ps65m-cathedral-square-project-4477817 [7], https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/council/cathedral-square-project-council-to-buy-business-to-meet-ambitious-deadline-4482270 [9]','On January 16, 2024, Wakefield Council\'s cabinet agreed to acquire the final business premises slated for demolition on Bread Street. This decision was critical to prevent delays and ensure the £6.5 million Cathedral Square project could proceed on its ambitious timeline.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f3cbcad6-de81-483a-a372-4dcf963c240e','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The new Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme is now available across the district to help qualifying private households install free solar power, insulation and other measures. The HERO scheme can offer fully funded improvements to help residents save energy and be warmer and healthier in their homes. These upgrades can make a big difference to keeping homes warm. It also helps to save money from lower heating costs. So, I would encourage people to apply now and see what might be available to them. HERO is a £1.5m Wakefield scheme which is part of the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme. And applications are now being taken. The HERO scheme is available until March 2028, but funds are restricted each year and will be allocated on a first come, first served basis so interested residents are urged to apply now. Contact the Council\'s Energy Team on either 01924 305887 or email energyteam@wakefield.gov.uk who will help with applications.','Council launches new scheme to provide free home energy improvements','Wakefield Council','2025-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEzCxVh2vIf-djJCCkjvnmpld5tkJzOclbtADhamqMmqBRnfEejO6ORHldOvJeuS5T9cIInjjZb7LjSvlpB5qft6SQ1CVCkdevETynhy9gACTud5jREIog3R2Xm0ra0UnTcW9rshXVDhMaFVvLU0KoMLME7rCAgsOwu_VfFMe_uSULaKlhEn1KCaex3FwO5KJM05OCatAETDH6ScMKMCw6ixbMaLJF7LCIDHw==','This press release from Wakefield Council announces the launch of the new Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) scheme, effective from August 7, 2025. It details the £1.5m scheme, part of the Government\'s Warm Homes: Local Grant programme, offering free solar power, insulation, and heat pumps to qualifying private households in the Wakefield district until March 2028. Cllr Jack Hemingway encouraged residents to apply due to limited funds.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f44c9a64-d35d-42bb-af99-7a1cfde19109','infrastructure-calder-valley-line-electrification-bradford-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.028','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Calderdale MBC. Wards Affected. All. Cabinet. 3rd. September 2018. The Contribution of Rail to the Economy of the Leeds City Region; Pressing the. Need for Investment on the Calder Valley Line. Report of Director, Regeneration and Strategy. 1. Purpose of the report. 1.1 To inform Members of the potential benefits that may arise from the electrification of the Calder Valley Line in order to inform any subsequent lobbying strategies with HM Government, DfT, local MPs, Network Rail etc. [9] It is recommended: 3.1 That Cabinet adopt an effective strategy for lobbying HM Government, Department for Transport, local MP\'s, Network Rail and others in order to bring forward the electrification of the Calder Valley Line. [9]','Calderdale Council Cabinet Report: The Contribution of Rail to the Economy of the Leeds City Region; Pressing the Need for Investment on the Calder Valley Line','Calderdale Council','2018-09-03 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGToAxoE8XEO5GZEQglpk9M7mr-Nfo8Rev1ToeYfOgREiyhvkr--jpmdz706WF24RhhgQrAWJaz3YVk0380JkDLl3-mgi75yhsXTLJQV_lRqqiuZnHrtX_mR8Z64ny6PscaE0FEvEMXnaNmFDeB2zFqZpvB1rSpu5TZBWID8LubQ5Kdk4rVJfajnTogA-2fDul10nCvYA==','This report to Calderdale Council\'s Cabinet outlined the potential benefits of electrifying the Calder Valley Line, including faster journey times, reduced infrastructure wear, positive environmental impacts, and increased passenger numbers. It recommended adopting an effective lobbying strategy to advocate for the electrification.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f45e67d6-29f0-4631-bcc1-3ddb9ca7d1e8','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Chancellor Rachel Reeves is to confirm the allocation of £2.1bn of local transport funding to West Yorkshire which will enable the Combined Authority to start works on West Yorkshire\'s tram project by 2028. The funding will also support other transport infrastructure projects across the region including new bus stations in Bradford and Wakefield, extensive bus priority measures and cycleways on the A641 and North Kirklees transport corridors.','Government Confirms £2.1bn Transport Funding for West Yorkshire, Including New Wakefield Bus Station','Wakefield First / Yahoo News UK','2025-06-09 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefieldfirst.com/news/government-to-confirm-2-1bn-transport-funding-for-west-yorkshire-ahead-of-spending-review/','The Chancellor Rachel Reeves is set to confirm £2.1 billion in local transport funding for West Yorkshire, enabling significant infrastructure projects. This funding will support not only the West Yorkshire mass transit project but also other vital schemes, including the development of a new bus station in Wakefield, as well as one in Bradford. This indicates continued government investment in improving transport connectivity across the region.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f494c916-1f8d-451f-9896-dfe214021251','infrastructure-morrisons-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.330','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Wakefield Council\'s cabinet approved a recommendation to accept the grant from West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of measures designed to achieve net zero targets. WYCA has been allocated more than £14m of government funding as part of the local electric vehicle infrastructure (LEVI) scheme. Wakefield will receive a total £1,520,938, based on a University of Leeds study into EV charger requirements for the region.','Wakefield Council to get £1.5m for EV charging points across city after study from Leeds university','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-10-16 00:00:00.000','https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/wakefield-council-to-get-ps15m-for-ev-charging-points-across-city-after-study-from-leeds-university-4819702','Wakefield Council\'s cabinet officially approved the recommendation to accept a £1.5 million grant from the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) as part of the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) scheme. This funding, based on a University of Leeds study, will support the installation of more EV charging points across the Wakefield district to meet the increasing demand for greener transport.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f4a9a8ec-3600-416a-8aae-226c126574ed','infrastructure-leeds-outer-ring-road-a6120-improvements---phase-1-horsforth--fink-hill',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.710','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The A6120 Fink Hill highway scheme in West Yorkshire has been transformed with new pedestrian crossings, road widening, cycle lanes, and tree planting near Featherbank Primary School, funded by the Levelling Up Fund. The enhancements include the introduction of pedestrian crossing facilities on all branches of the Fink Hill junction. Road widening efforts between Horsforth roundabout and Fink Hill have been executed to perfection, presenting two lanes in both directions, alongside a designated left-turn lane that eases the flow of vehicles converging onto the junction. The scheme doesn\'t stop there; from Fink Hill to Charles Street, the road has been expanded to accommodate two lanes for each direction, with an additional right turn lane for those transitioning from the A6120 into Fink Hill. Government investment from the Levelling Up Fund and West Yorkshire Transport Fund.','Fink Hill Highway Scheme Transformed and Completed','Leeds City Magazine','2024-03-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEwGvshlxaTDQwoFKvgO5Wdf3nS1qzITKjE9PHbkAyMXf7ZE_lCzfQuNxghsZUIRNc0NU5IFwNYlLGs_3RduKbgElYJ9M366SBpHNnsYCgnMbOUY3mpmaLPBL_lqapX8URC_hvc0ynPqzFPlwHqzFtNjXn7iY65RZWtcwMgMwc8Di1oJXQEGrNoQn3FKYeC16f0OmVIsGORsu6ENw3cOgnyZAsTJxfq7pM3Vfd8dKstM_J8YoA246MZr3oN34uRYLWviXUklR8p_euqaVC0q9lHroCy7oXRgXiPmPML','The A6120 Fink Hill highway scheme saw its transformation completed by March 8, 2024, after approximately a year of work. The improvements include new pedestrian crossings on all branches of the junction, road widening between Horsforth roundabout and Fink Hill (providing two lanes in both directions), new cycle lanes on the Outer Ring Road, and the planting of 165 new trees. The scheme was funded by the Levelling Up Fund and West Yorkshire Transport Fund.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f4ef62e4-fa1a-4227-b100-e59800620698','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising-calderdale-impact',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.101','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin has joined forces with a local bus operator to take back and improve a Calderdale bus route. Passengers using the 571 service, which runs between Halifax and Shelf, via Brighouse, Southowram and Hipperhoime, were seeing poor performance from the previous operator on the service. But the West Yorkshire Combined Authority has stepped up to not only retender the service to a new operator, Go Ahead Buses, but also to increase its frequency. A revised timetable – starting this week – was introduced for the service, paid for using money from the Combined Authority\'s Bus Service Improvement Plan.','West Yorkshire Mayor teams up with local operator to improve Calderdale bus route','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2025-02-26 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/news-events/news/west-yorkshire-mayor-teams-up-with-local-operator-to-improve-calderdale-bus-route/','West Yorkshire Mayor Tracy Brabin announced an interim improvement to the 571 bus service in Calderdale (Halifax to Shelf, via Brighouse, Southowram and Hipperholme). The West Yorkshire Combined Authority retendered the service to a new operator, Go Ahead Buses, and increased its frequency, demonstrating proactive action on bus services ahead of the full franchising rollout.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f543c36c-62a5-40db-9e23-1c440bbcc660','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---bradford-line-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.644','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'West Yorkshire Combined Authority has unveiled potential routes for West Yorkshire\'s long-awaited tram mass transit system and has opened its public consultation for both the Leeds Line and the Bradford Line. The statutory preferred route consultation will be completed in 2025, and the Mayor has previously promised to have spades in the ground on the project by 2028. [25] This brochure provides the information you need to take part in the consultation for the West Yorkshire Mass Transit phase one route options. For both the Bradford Line and the Leeds Line, we want your views to help us choose the route for the tram that best connects communities with each other, whilst also improving access to our city centres and places around them like our hospitals, universities and colleges. [33] You can give us your feedback during the consultation period, between Monday 15 July and Monday 30 September 2024. [33]','West Yorkshire opens public consultation on Bradford and Leeds tram routes','West Yorkshire Combined Authority (Your Voice) / Transport Network','2024-07-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.transport-network.co.uk/West-Yorkshire-opens-public-consultation-on-Bradford-and-Leeds-tram-routes/20090','West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public consultation on potential route options for Phase 1 of the Mass Transit system, including three options for the Bradford Line connecting Bradford city centre to Leeds city centre. The consultation ran from July 15 to September 30, 2024, inviting public feedback to help inform the preferred routes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f57c11b6-1141-4629-a826-b01bc9d80c38','infrastructure-natural-flood-management-schemes-colne-calder-upper-aire-catchments',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.568','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2021-08-05) The Environment Agency, Leeds City Council and the White Rose Forest partnership are calling for landowners to introduce natural flood management measures on their land to help mitigate climate change and reduce the risk of flooding in the River Aire catchment, from Malham to Leeds. [9]','Environment Agency encourages landowners to introduce natural flood management techniques in the River Aire catchment - GOV.UK','GOV.UK','2021-08-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGn65ORDYT2_u1FZ-ciKKcn6gzkmX_8w95Z6l9WNgPqV_dVZcStjgdOUqxwhf8KfUsCUph_ZyWJ1UJ1zjbaTML4YRiMQFlPONwnEIBOvFIEVrAYSCLtTIPzVbWwr1HCGmryzsvSieHEQ6JxKihKzYYE-Dfb3WLWVCxRGhJVtid6emIyHhMddV0xO82W-ORbLJu0A15ZZaywrlzFJENNq253YCkXJN-JVaMpmwRCLYB_jBYMmdXUFRabfJwLvviH4zYFsRc0FGc618qFk8zDzDvXQLToJQ==','The Environment Agency, in partnership with Leeds City Council and the White Rose Forest, called upon landowners in the River Aire catchment (from Malham to Leeds) to implement fully-funded natural flood management measures. The initiative aimed to reduce flood risk, enhance biodiversity, and improve water quality by leveraging natural processes. [9]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f5bc6e39-1953-4e98-b057-7327d23e5f30','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-bus-franchising',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.776','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bus franchising could be introduced in West Yorkshire from June 2026, with a decision on whether such an avenue will be followed due to be made by Mayor Tracy Brabin on 14 March 2024. ... Details of the franchising proposals are within documents including a consultation that were published by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) on 10 October. It believes that reregulation of services in the conurbation is the best way to deliver improvements. ... The consultation notes that implementation would cost in the region of £358 million, with a £252 million fleet element of that involving 868 zero-emission buses (ZEBs) owned by WYCA spread over 14 years. Acquisition of 10 depots, and fit-out out for ZEBs, is estimated at £85.5 million. ... West Yorkshire would be broken into 10 zones centred on existing large depots. Leeds is made up of three zones. ... The consultation closes on 7 January 2024. [20]','West Yorkshire bus franchising plans revealed as consultation is go','RouteONE magazine','2023-10-10 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGYkwq7BQHIGDJTfWju5QSQEuD8XyTbknvLu42TgXuK7yfwuhreNnAvPoW9G9wvq2IODkbWuKLWJW095t1ya3_CLkLklLXwO_YXDkzlpcZnfSovdHeXfS9MBbAB9salfMPKByQOMcdRlNmgYhhLRMmePMoZnf9tKMIFSwUHQLVCsCTlihhoRHpF_J-sSzua3JGYnaNbl1ZQjlsFHLIK','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA) published detailed proposals for bus franchising, initiating a public consultation. The plans outlined a potential introduction from June 2026, breaking West Yorkshire into 10 zones for contracting. The estimated implementation cost was £358 million, including £252 million for 868 zero-emission buses and £85.5 million for depot acquisition and fit-out. Mayor Tracy Brabin had made bus reregulation a manifesto commitment. The consultation period was set to close on January 7, 2024. [20]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f5d460d7-2c2d-4f6e-a916-f9c97a647d9e','infrastructure-west-yorkshire-mass-transit-system---overall-programme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.604','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority in collaboration with partner councils are developing a mass transit system which will offer a new public transport option and an attractive alternative to car travel. The plan sets out a bold and ambitious plan for a new form of transport for West Yorkshire. ... The purpose of this commission is to undertake Environmental Impact Assessments and produce an Environmental Statement to support the West Yorkshire Mass Transit programme. Award Detail. 1, Jacobs (London). Environmental Impact Commission (Mass Transit); Reference: 025313-2023-1-1; Value: £10,000,000. [22]','Environmental Impact Commission (Mass Transit) Awarded to Jacobs','BidStats (Contract Award Notice)','2023-08-29 00:00:00.000','https://www.bidstats.uk/tenders/025313-2023/environmental-impact-commission-mass-transit-award','A £10 million contract was awarded to Jacobs (London) for undertaking Environmental Impact Assessments (EIA) and producing an Environmental Statement to support the West Yorkshire Mass Transit programme. This commission is crucial for evaluating the environmental impacts of the proposed system.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f624a764-c299-4172-bb04-891b7ea20e3c','infrastructure-bradford-city-village',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A HUGE scheme to turn a “tired and rundown” area of Bradford city centre into a new urban village has now been submitted. The first planning application for Bradford\'s City Village is now officially live, and - if it is approved – work could begin with the demolition of the Oastler Shopping Centre later this year. [7]','Plans for 1,000 home \'City Village\' Project are Submitted','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/24574921.plans-1-000-home-city-village-project-submitted/','The first planning application for Bradford\'s City Village project has been officially submitted to Bradford Council. The plans detail the first stage of development, including housing on Chain Street and a section of the Oastler site, new roads, public green spaces, and cycling/walking routes, with outline details for the rest of the 1,000 homes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f66c63d6-3360-46d1-a128-452b9a9db589','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-heptonstall-road-junction-improvements-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.909','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The programme includes the following proposals in Hebden Bridge: ... Heptonstall Road – improving pedestrian facilities outside the Fox and Goose pub, which has already been delivered.','Transforming travel in and around Hebden Bridge - Project Update','Hebden Bridge Web','2024-10-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGBEv5wrqNbQsYe8AiOBkMHi82Ovu8TIUUljqAH-vLhK0XqMW2R9zQfv4jX5tXGYAr-3Iq0gva911zraPLgAs7jbpFeAI69BFHrre5lTWreI7G8_AC6NLn4A0E8tMYuVGRtp-T8jgPts3U1Wqc=','An update on the A646/A6033 Corridor Improvement Programme confirms that improvements to pedestrian facilities outside the Fox and Goose pub on Heptonstall Road have already been delivered. This signifies the completion of the specific junction improvement works.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f674bdc2-3ca1-4278-b294-c9cdb12d0232','infrastructure-ceg-temple-leeds-south-bank',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.719','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Developer CEG has gained the planning green light for a £350m joint office, retail and residential development around what would be the tallest building in Yorkshire. Leeds City Plans Panel has unanimously voted to approve detailed planning permission for two office developments totalling 270,000 sq ft. Outline planning permission will also be granted for the wider mixed-use development of over 1m sq ft of offices, retail, leisure, hotel, health, and up to 750 new homes, along with new public spaces and landscaping. [21]','Green light for £350m Leeds South Bank scheme including tallest building in Yorkshire','Construction Enquirer News','2018-04-22 00:00:00.000','https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2018/04/22/green-light-for-350m-leeds-south-bank-scheme/','Developer CEG received planning approval for a £350 million mixed-use development at Leeds South Bank, featuring offices, retail, residential, and potentially the region\'s tallest building. Outline planning was also granted for wider development, including up to 750 new homes.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f74ff8c8-efac-4647-a6a5-102ceef5adee','infrastructure-bradley-storm-overflow-reduction-project-huddersfield-broad-canal',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.588','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The proposed development site covers mainly the existing Bradley Golf Course, near Huddersfield, but also incorporates some agricultural fields as well and buildings at Bradley Villa Farm. The proposed site is bounded by the M62 motorway to the North West, a quarry to the North East and residential housing to the East, South and West. Foul water sewers receiving flows from two or more properties and pumping stations could be offered for adoption by Yorkshire Water under S104 agreements. Direct connections with no further works may be possible to the watercourses that run from the northwest of the site beneath the M62 motorway and the watercourse that runs off site to southeast and beneath Bradley road. This would involve the construction of a new overflow channel/watercourse to convey flows to the River Calder.','Drainage Assessment Report Bradley Masterplanning Bradley, Huddersfield - Kirklees Council','Kirklees Council','2016-01-25 00:00:00.000','https://www.kirklees.gov.uk/beta/planning/pdf/drainage-assessment-bradley-masterplanning.pdf','This report provides a drainage assessment for a proposed development site mainly covering Bradley Golf Course, near Huddersfield. It discusses existing watercourses, potential for surface water drainage solutions, and foul water sewers possibly adopted by Yorkshire Water, laying groundwork for future infrastructure needs in the Bradley area.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f765fe37-ff49-4e83-a171-0d3f7918482d','infrastructure-a62-to-cooper-bridge-corridor-improvement-scheme-phase-1-kirklees',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.931','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme represents a critical opportunity to address long-standing issues on one of the busiest routes in Kirklees. However, the current proposals fall short of delivering the transformative change needed to prioritise active travel effectively. ... Cycle Kirklees has assessed the scheme using tools like the Cycling Level of Service (CLoS) and found it scores only 59%—far below the 70% threshold for Department for Transport (DfT) funding.','Cycle Kirklees Raises Concerns Over Cooper Bridge Scheme\'s Cycling Infrastructure Design','Cycle Kirklees','2024-12-18 00:00:00.000','https://cyclekirklees.org.uk/cooper-bridge-consultation-response/','Cycle Kirklees submitted a response to the latest consultation (ending December 2024), expressing concerns that the proposed designs for the A62 to Cooper Bridge Corridor Improvement Scheme do not meet national guidance for cycle infrastructure (LTN 1/20). Their assessment using the Cycling Level of Service (CLoS) tool resulted in a score of 59%, below the 70% threshold for Department for Transport funding, advocating for separated cycling infrastructure. [19, 20]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f7bfac02-77b2-4778-aa48-e88e871d2eb7','infrastructure-calderdale-corridor-improvement-programme-phase-1-a58a672-and-a646a6033',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.888','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work is progressing as part of a major road improvement programme which is set to improve journey times, reduce congestion and support active travel. The A646/A6033 and the A58/A672 Corridor Improvement Programme is being delivered in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. Work started earlier this year in the Todmorden area to accommodate improved pedestrian facilities, junction improvements and improvements to paving and bus stop facilities. A new puffin crossing has also been installed on Halifax Road. The next steps in this programme will involve the demolition of the former Sowerby Bridge Market. This is due to start on Monday 17 October and should take around three weeks to complete. [5]','Improvements Continue on Two Key Routes in Calderdale','Calderdale Council News Centre','2022-10-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFgxFddImEWLIgEE45zbM4kbS12zWkcS-5IwQ7uyX2ZPDyKvCZAYFb4VncU0jpCDwmPlaco6aumGKLVhVolitaVBT7L_izfLtaWuRGO7hbMRSedn4vB3iTsKyEWXCfAhOC-UTwxffPR3-bMJTp8NQsgPWLpUgmqSFmOcmbA48qiHtxGioZkCTHnwTc_lIWjeUU=','Calderdale Council announced ongoing work for the A646/A6033 and A58/A672 Corridor Improvement Programme, including work started in Todmorden for improved pedestrian facilities and junction improvements, and the upcoming demolition of Sowerby Bridge Market.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f806148a-fc33-46bf-8754-44c59d0b6699','infrastructure-wellington-square-development',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.519','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Along with the West End build-to-rent tower and offices, Leeds\' city plans Panel...Since McLaren\'s proposals for Wellington Square in the Lisbon Street area went through that same pre-application process, its plans have been refined. Planning permission is now sought for the demolition of all existing buildings and the repositioning of Skinner Street to allow the Glenn Howells Architects-designed project to advance. ... This will pave the way for the erection of a mixed-use development comprising a 46-storey building providing 464 apartments; two multi-level office buildings...','PLANNING | McLaren tipped for 46-storey green light','Place Yorkshire','2024-04-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGwSeu-dyPwtU5vnUuqytjcbJqIaYEEKZY--Ev8BsUk1wbEYucCrH57pI3DuwsnJgmcn88t1QksmMlYwXY9DYJBlmqg5f9tOHbPmZ4DBMUSQMzePER749wdCaSN_Yg7J-N8p5FAGsKJpxKdfYpdE2Fzqnq6UMh6uob-sBAEGYwm8LwkeSnzQVHinnHHjlVK','McLaren\'s Wellington Square proposals in the Lisbon Street area were recommended for approval by Leeds City Council\'s City Plans Panel. The refined plans sought permission for the demolition of existing buildings and repositioning of Skinner Street to facilitate the Glenn Howells Architects-designed project, which includes a 46-storey building with 464 apartments and two multi-level office buildings. [11]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f81d213d-2377-40e2-bcb0-7c85682cd58d','infrastructure-eon-thorpe-park-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.384','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'...read the Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030 (PDF, 507KB). [13]','Electric vehicle charging in Leeds','Leeds.gov.uk','2022-01-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.leeds.gov.uk/parking-roads-and-travel/connecting-leeds-and-transforming-travel/electric-vehicle-charging-in-leeds','Leeds City Council\'s official page outlines its strategy for EV charging infrastructure, including supporting commercial partners in installing chargers in locations like retail settings. It refers to the \'Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030\'.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f86e5fc1-6ba3-4b86-87e1-541309d5a248','infrastructure-westgate-phase-2-and-palatine-chambers-halifax',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.265','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Work on \'Westgate Phase II\' – an expansion of Westgate Quarter – should be finished in early 2025, say leaders of the project property firm O and C. Described as a “high-end shopping and leisure destination”, the new development will be anchored around Westgate Arcade. As this video shows, the stylish building will transform the area that formerly housed Horton House. It will offer up to 12 units in a range of sizes for a mix of retail, leisure and office uses. [6]','Video shows how new Halifax town centre Westgate expansion will look as developers reveal expected opening date','Halifax Courier','2024-07-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHfbh0ZR_zVKBRnG_3WJVVwgOIoSIjPakyXD032fFc3zHKZTn2jVitQG39G3TlmpY8rL1A-6SZ7e_OR9XOSRAEkR5fNLmSAlI-wFFenO-BSYTdY-Uesv2Vyp3zOdK3VwTP5C5uc_zub_StjEhOCFzvt4TTjsLDeViFR26An8EAZYuVaFVNcbch9sXriNw9eGYrFFGn3T2MloGllqn8TPBSkhs7GcJFvXjDGTJ_1tr89WkxBvAm3IBME-5bcG-EfCIzVy1sVNMKonoAvi_AaNR9282B3hDW3ye7uMWg2Zp5pzY0zcQZsLPnz-jWj52996RbnLLaXi42pxA==','The Halifax Courier reported that work on \'Westgate Phase II\', an expansion of Westgate Quarter, was expected to be finished in early 2025. The project by O and C would offer up to 12 units for retail, leisure, and office uses, transforming the area that formerly housed Horton House.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f89d57ce-4220-40be-87c6-e75c2ae61a3a','infrastructure-ionity-leeds-skelton-lakes-ev-charging-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.372','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'A second set of amended plans was lodged with Leeds City Council in spring 2016, and permission for the site, 2.5 miles (4.0 km) southeast of Leeds Dock, was granted with an interim bill of £50 million in early 2017. The services started to be constructed in the summer of 2018, at the M1\'s junction 45 with the A63, it is accessible in both directions of the motorway and from the A-road. [14]','Planning Permission Granted for Skelton Lake Services','Wikipedia - Skelton Lake services (citing official sources)','2017-01-04 00:00:00.000','https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skelton_Lake_services','A second set of amended plans for the Skelton Lake motorway service area, which includes provisions for future amenities, was lodged with Leeds City Council in spring 2016, and permission for the site was granted in early 2017. Construction subsequently began in summer 2018.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('f91049f2-49ac-4733-a544-b353edd5bd5d','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Balancing the books to protect vital public services is the priority for the next financial year after the budget for 2023/4 was agreed at Budget Council on Monday 27 February 2023. Cllr Tim Swift, Leader of Calderdale Council said: Yet again we are setting a budget in challenging circumstances. We continue to experience the impact of the pandemic, the war in Ukraine and the cost of living crisis as do our residents, our communities and our local businesses. ... In October 2022, the Council\'s Medium Term Financial Strategy (MTFS) estimated the impacts of the economic situation on the local authority. These included: providing for pay settlements which ensure the Council can retain and attract staff; a likely fall in income as residents cut back on spending; higher contract costs due to inflation; higher energy costs and. a significant fall in car parking income.','Approved budget for 2023/24 to 2025/26 - Calderdale Council','Calderdale Council','2023-10-17 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEkuzlwctmy_gNWJ4a6nJ9BVJ3yydo12pfm8t2wea4Afe-gNBGmbLhQ9bx-j2dNJrQJVltLOSfUkR5nw49AMfmWhVwuYJ5mDlS0PZBGacH3ZTxHkca2vqclg7Hey3Ei_eNz4n3Ytl9c_u6Y-QlHNdzjklQEqPmjQD3E31qmAbzRB5RZebI2lNQTuTA==','This budget report highlights a significant fall in car parking income as one of the impacts of the economic situation on the local authority. It shows the financial context in which parking policies, including those for residents, are managed and budgeted for, with a focus on balancing the books and protecting vital public services.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fa130340-378c-446c-b3e4-3b9e0a719de2','infrastructure-evbox-whitehall-road-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.404','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Leeds City Council has partnered with charge point operator Believ, to rollout a series of fast and rapid electric vehicle (EV) charge points across the district to support its ambition to provide more sustainable methods of transport for local residents... [7]','Leeds City Council Partners with Believ for EV Charge Point Rollout','Transport + Energy news','2024-10-31 00:00:00.000','https://transportenergy.com/news/leeds-city-council-partners-with-believ/','Leeds City Council announced a partnership with the charge point operator Believ to install fast and rapid electric vehicle charging points in council-owned car parks and public sites across the district, advancing the city\'s ambition for sustainable transport. [7]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fa301407-5178-4b97-a98b-bc55fd09a904','infrastructure-starbucks-snowhill-wakefield-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.333','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The design of an electric vehicle charging programme is a significant project ... We proposed a network of 88 charging points across the West Yorkshire region ... To fund the development of the network, we were able to secure almost £2 million from the Office for Zero Emission Vehicles for the project and we provided an additional £1.2 million in matched funding. ... Updated Dec, 2024.','West Yorkshire electric vehicle charging network | sustainable transport - Carbon Copy','Carbon Copy','2024-12-01 00:00:00.000','https://carboncopy.eco/solutions/west-yorkshire-electric-vehicle-charging-network','Carbon Copy provides an overview of the West Yorkshire Combined Authority\'s (WYCA) efforts to develop an EV charging network across its constituent areas, including Wakefield. It highlights the securing of nearly £2 million from the Office for Zero Emission Vehicles and an additional £1.2 million in matched funding for 88 charging points, which were offered free of charge until October 29, 2021. The article was last updated in December 2024, reflecting ongoing commitment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fa6018cb-1641-4000-b3b5-0db304887f3b','infrastructure-armley-gyratory-improvement-leeds',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.664','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-08-01) Armley Gyratory\'s three brand new replacement footbridges are now fully opened, as part of a multi-million-pound scheme to offer improved routes for pedestrians and cyclists, negotiating one of Leeds busiest junctions. The replacement footbridges over Wellington Road (A58), Spence Lane and Gelderd Road; are part of wider works, worth more than £41.96 million project around the Armley Gyratory, which is funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority via the West Yorkshire Plus Transport fund. Work started in January 2024 to demolish the existing footbridges, which were of a poor standard and approaching life expiry and replace them with more accessible structures. They follow highways works to the main gyratory which were completed in winter 2023.','Completed Armley Gyratory footbridges improving vital routes for walking and cycling','Leeds City Council News','2025-08-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHS2gP9rTD6lsPY_HzF9iEez5ZkXqv5q4vPyv0x7MJHK9bu_F_63o2XK_V8jgC2fnaYMk3l4YRtHzwtKNjWoPfhJXyrQYqEucvifAL9cgvNjZu4ASFvqqvpxZcP14wGwKQeSruGXH0FAOfGK0-vtC5ew9k4ZWgAQEFXdIMukddtJ_T274HpO_duFmYKEfZDpXKGgpmYrOy6b6m9uunEhiRsvXOiOsJLihVGcIW8Sdk=','Armley Gyratory\'s three brand new replacement footbridges over Wellington Road (A58), Spence Lane, and Gelderd Road were officially opened. These bridges are part of a multi-million-pound scheme valued at over £41.96 million, funded by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority. The project aimed to provide improved, more accessible, and safer routes for pedestrians and cyclists, enhance traffic flow, and alleviate congestion. Work on the footbridges began in January 2024, following the completion of main gyratory highways works in winter 2023.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fa7b9f56-ba49-46b0-9797-d51f80894088','infrastructure-home-energy-retrofit-offer-hero-scheme-wakefield',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.554','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) Scheme. This scheme is part of the Warm Home: Local Grant programme from the Department of Energy, Security and Net Zero (DESNZ). In Wakefield, we have secured £1.5m to help households switch from fossil fuels like gas, coal, LPG, and oil. This funding will also improve home energy efficiency. The HERO scheme helps homeowners and private tenants, who live in the Wakefield district. You don\'t have to pay anything; all the work is free. Improvements available: insulation (cavity wall and/or loft); low carbon heating systems, e.g. air source heat pumps or high efficiency storage heaters; solar PV (electric producing panel system). The HERO scheme runs until March 2028. However, funds are limited each financial year. We will give out funds on a first come, first served basis. They might run out, so if you\'re interested, it\'s best to apply right away. Complete this form to apply. You can contact the Council\'s Home Energy Team for help with your application. Call 01924 305887 or email energyteam@wakefield.gov.uk.','Home Energy Retrofit Offer (HERO) Scheme - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2025-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEIwcdztdBxuOvz9NfaJX0ynbpDAgB1w5WJd_7a9yZeYrEd1g8OZQwyHxKVY1ahPzH8kqOBdt5hm3-Oo6ZDeAfaGWa7ZsbaunPjP723pujEGOEdvjHdNYfXeZEXET187jvTFUN-ETd9KDFHlEV-fFKPUeAulAs0djTBy4rChYXtQ8AiuUBIBQ4d1JlPcJP7NQ==','This is the official Wakefield Council page for the HERO Scheme. It confirms the scheme is part of the Warm Home: Local Grant programme from DESNZ, with £1.5m secured to help households in the Wakefield district. It offers free insulation, low-carbon heating systems (e.g., air source heat pumps), and solar PV. The scheme is for homeowners and private tenants meeting specific income and EPC criteria (D-G) and runs until March 2028. Applications are processed on a first-come, first-served basis.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fa7e8ad4-1b6e-4162-b08e-bd3daebcb74f','infrastructure-leeds-pipes-district-heating-network---spinners-yard-connection',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.468','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More people in Leeds will soon enjoy affordable, reliable, and low carbon heat thanks to four new connections to the Leeds PIPES district heating network that have been confirmed by Leeds City Council today. The four latest buildings, including the first private-sector residential developers, which have confirmed their intention to connect to the network within the next 12 months are: Spinner\'s Yard around Mabgate, developed by Rise Homes; Leonardo and Thoresby buildings on Gt George Street, developed by McLaren on behalf of Arrow Leonardo; The redevelopment of Leeds Technology Campus on Cookridge Street, developed by Metropolitan & District Securities; Leeds Conservatoire on Quarry Hill. The £62 million network continues to expand and is regularly connecting to new buildings. By using heat and energy recovered from non-recyclable waste at the Recycling and Energy Recovery Facility (RERF) to provide warmth and hot water to buildings in the city, the Leeds PIPES district heating project is helping businesses and residents to move away from costly fossil-fuel powered heating systems.','Plans to extend Leeds PIPES network into new areas of the city revealed, as four more buildings set to connect','Leeds City Council News','2023-08-07 00:00:00.000','https://news.leeds.gov.uk/news/plans-to-extend-leeds-pipes-network-into-new-areas-of-the-city-revealed,-as-four-more-buildings-set-to-connect','Leeds City Council announced that four new buildings, including the private residential development Spinner\'s Yard (Mabgate) by Rise Homes, have confirmed their intention to connect to the Leeds PIPES district heating network within the next 12 months. This marked the first time private residential developers committed to connecting.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fae33f81-d20c-4fb1-af92-0eb6365269b7','infrastructure-local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips-for-bradford',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.061','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Bradford Council are developing Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans for West Yorkshire. ... Phase one of the LCWIP for Bradford includes plans to improve walking in Keighley town centre and plans to improve cycling provision in south Bradford. ... The proposals have been developed through workshops with key stakeholders, street audits, data analysis and technical assessments of potential improvements. Further stakeholder engagement was undertaken in winter 2019 to get feedback on the proposals.','Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans: Bradford | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority - Your Voice','2019-09-02 00:00:00.000','https://www.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/projects/cityconnect/local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-bradford/','This document introduces the Phase One LCWIP for Bradford, developed by West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Bradford Council. It outlines the strategic approach for identifying cycling and walking improvements, focusing on cycling routes in South Bradford and walking improvements in Keighley town centre. The plan aims to secure future funding for these improvements, based on stakeholder workshops, street audits, data analysis, and technical assessments.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fb00e8ce-6d72-4693-8510-6c986b722e50','infrastructure-bradford-city-village-phase-1-chain-street--oastler-site',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.068','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The transformation of Bradford\'s former retail heart into a vibrant new sustainable community known as \'City Village\' has taken a further step forward with the launch of the final phase of public consultation. To be built across the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, which include the Oastler, Kirkgate and Chain Street sites, the new City Village will repurpose what was historically Bradford\'s commercial area. It will create up to 1,000 energy-efficient homes including affordable housing, as well as independent retail and leisure opportunities, business spaces and new high-quality public realm, including three new green spaces. A detailed planning application for phase 1 of \'City Village\' will be submitted this summer, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site.','Public Phase of Consultation Launched on \'City Village\' for Bradford','Anita Morris Associates','2025-06-06 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFa4N43fcF43ZC3qPQlmHzPbQuVn8quSQi8McQpgLSwLFDamXZrLOeyWaacfka7Z33482w3gslobneSbGrg2Nj9fBFYHBV1pkaBNbfX7JH1E9o2O5OLOBlc02nyDaqBSOQig4eBrbpdeCdPIcBE2mH51k0ps55uf4oX2JPq--Es7-78EGq9nH0T79RzWoaUiLs9GvjtUGE3LPMXp4Lj_cL9wo8oSfT-6YMXgEj35b-4wdoa4ZEhgJw47ezdeg==','Anita Morris Associates reported on the launch of the final public consultation phase for Bradford\'s \'City Village\'. The project aims to transform the city\'s former retail heart into a sustainable community with up to 1,000 energy-efficient homes across Oastler, Kirkgate, and Chain Street sites.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fb87e77d-e8bc-410e-82fd-73ba840fa411','infrastructure-wakefield-ev-charging-points-levi-grant-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.529','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Funding (LEVI) With a closing date again of March 31st 2025, LEVI funding is a scheme that applies exclusively to English local authorities. Aimed at supporting the delivery of charge points for residential use, application for the LEVI funding is done in three stages: stage 1: expression of interest. stage 2: application form. stage 3: contract review.','LEVI Funding Scheme Application Deadlines','EV Charger Grants: A Complete Guide','2025-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEf1wY2Ky-Ucq3lyB-o5-kttbFDgmx6TOdIaAOICnvVPvTfFyl9s-NbL-6GIJw1UVGS_XSvINVPu8BuAfiYarXh4nYQL1UCthJiICWFxvr3e1MklycU3viYCP6pAeHGgGZ5r8kb_UFsgdIIf_gdzpoh41xMoNqXM7WSrmV1mehk5a_7et9eg9a9nA==','The Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) funding is an exclusive scheme for English local authorities to support the delivery of charge points for residential use. Applications are submitted in three stages (expression of interest, application form, contract review), with a closing date for funding of March 31, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fb9c27fc-d2fc-4844-a43a-f12b5eeaee85','infrastructure-hebden-bridge-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.215','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Environment Agency has completed detailed designs for a scheme to better protect 400 homes and businesses from the risk of flooding in Hebden Bridge. Working in partnership with Calderdale Council and Yorkshire Water, the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme is designed to reduce flood risk from the River Calder and Hebden Water. Detailed designs are now complete, and the planning application is expected to be submitted in Spring 2025. It is anticipated that pre-construction preparation work will commence later in 2025. Planning permission has already been secured for work to construct a canal overflow. This is planned to start next spring. The main construction work is targeted to commence in 2026, delivered over approximately three years.','Work continues to reduce flood risk to people in Hebden Bridge','News Centre (Environment Agency / Calderdale Council)','2024-12-05 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/government/news/work-continues-to-reduce-flood-risk-to-people-in-hebden-bridge','The Environment Agency confirmed on December 5, 2024, that detailed designs for the Hebden Bridge Flood Alleviation Scheme are complete. The scheme, in partnership with Calderdale Council and Yorkshire Water, aims to protect 400 homes and businesses from river and surface water flooding. Planning application for the town centre work is expected in Spring 2025, with pre-construction starting later in 2025 and main construction targeted for 2026 over approximately three years. Planning permission has already been secured for a canal overflow, with work planned to start in spring 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fc3cdbe2-8951-4d98-9924-e5932bda73bc','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Bradford Council, in partnership with the English Cities Fund (ECF), is inviting the public to play a pivotal role in shaping the future of Bradford City Village, a project poised to deliver 1,000 new homes and breathe new life into the former retail hub of the city centre. This visionary initiative, set in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, including the sites of the Kirkgate and Oastler shopping centres, aims to create a sustainable neighbourhood at the heart of the city centre. The consultation ran until January 7, 2024.','Public consultation launched to help shape masterplan for Bradford City Village','UKREiiF, Bdaily, Place Yorkshire','2023-11-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHU9Q9DA_JQAoNDP2Xiw5SLyH6zJ3i9UdAT7kX5IUCR4iIso1JvmMUSb5Go0ff1oAso8-LpF46_neJuIVT9y38F1kNq9jC_LrEusEi5JaJnARvEUIoXbeUehudu8VJ-yyLX8udICsUKJQJ6hW9dM25CiEe_jGmot6HmMteV, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEbfwVIcr_ZauNu4BWcbVfIozoSpvBGMXmYepWedgGkilk2hYWDE-DymXBKa9hxSko_-XPiIVwdJpRSxDCMJD4-yyyhLv0ecErzxPB9gWIYouQxIGaQUoZ2_fmAkalFCYF8U2yDsDzMUFHrQpQRq5b7HBlSlKeTdNVwC0jdchB5lPHVioI3FijOipIUqtqODPW5iFft5i_NepQUmiFTk4a9kgPnbP1O8OvR4AYyWoIZDFL_IA, https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE8KRu6NrIzKDeDSFCkVNxUADsIfJx6aHawmocM5BTm0G8AMhi1_gOLibPlfBVD7EcIZFd8JwMAGvAoVCEk9e5JBIkthvaVq-5tOR7-TWOlUH-vMrPVu7DOAMT2ktxBKiUheRzk0LMWBYRojHtGJIE7NKkFQnv6IgL6J0fwUPnDDQFiuamYb6Oq6JIFTew','Bradford Council and the English Cities Fund (ECF) launched a public consultation for the Bradford City Village masterplan. This initial phase of engagement aimed to gather feedback on early ideas for regenerating the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, including the Kirkgate and Oastler shopping centres, to deliver approximately 1,000 new homes and revitalise the city\'s former retail core.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fc41c66a-a870-4391-9d25-e0d826ddf2c8','infrastructure-transforming-cities---wakefield-city-centre',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.611','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), work continues to develop our plans to make Wakefield city centre better for walking, cycling, and using public transport. For more information, see our April 2023 News update. Originally, funding for the project was planned from the Transforming Cities Fund. But, due to the current economic climate and a spending freeze, the project will be extended over a longer period while we explore additional funding options.','Wakefield City Centre Transport Improvements Update','Wakefield Council','2023-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://www.wakefield.gov.uk/roads-and-travel/wakefield-city/wakefield-city-centre-transport-improvements','An April 2023 news update from Wakefield Council detailed ongoing work, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, to develop plans for improving walking, cycling, and public transport within Wakefield city centre. The project aims to reduce traffic, improve active travel routes, and enhance bus operations. The update noted that while original funding was from the Transforming Cities Fund, the project may be extended due to economic conditions while exploring additional funding options.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fc69e879-981a-4ead-b5af-547599f71ce4','infrastructure-woolpack-inn-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.397','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2024-08-05) Residents are set to have their say on plans to improve electric vehicle infrastructure across Leeds and West Yorkshire. ... It brings together both the LEVI programme and the Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy for West Yorkshire – two Combined Authority projects aimed at improving the charging network for the region.','West Yorkshire Combined Authority Public Consultation on £17m EV Charging Plans','Yorkshire Evening Post','2024-08-05 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGMAsRjpsX3yx8WBHintD1TVJ8pwU7cRawsCQ_s-FiDWqxWx_sK2KlLlDa29tSTJ4vC_sVevOBpkvURqYx8LOSSJVHiagEr9qz5gOBGAuSMfjTleSIHXh1fJciKIc1IPxGTeDO7dloZec4VdujVinJL_kBy2t5dRhPJVXVKO2aLTDg_zmJI0Ca5ld3fMTY10cadlotHJbSrVErUqN1ouKnfP_eBKx51cEDZw0t2EvK-QyydLomSkYIqrmpX97WOhTbiU=','The West Yorkshire Combined Authority launched a public consultation on its £17 million plans to improve EV charging infrastructure across Leeds and West Yorkshire. This consultation covers both the LEVI programme and the Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Strategy for the region, aimed at increasing accessible and reliable charge points.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fc7efc04-64f3-48ac-84ce-169d606af1db','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---overall-regeneration',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.535','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Plans to create a new neighbourhood in the heart of Bradford city centre are out for consultation. Built across the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas, the new City Village will repurpose places traditionally used for retail, by creating 1,000 homes and a sustainable community. Bradford Council has now set out its vision in the hopes of reducing what it called outdated retail stock and reshaping Bradford around changing times in the economy. The public consultation is open until January 7, 2024. [26]','Bradford City Village plan out for consultation: Have your say','Telegraph & Argus','2023-12-04 00:00:00.000','https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/23966567.bradford-city-village-plan-consultation-say/','Bradford Council launched the initial public consultation on plans to create the new City Village in the \'Top of Town\' and Darley Street areas. The vision is to repurpose retail spaces into a sustainable community with 1,000 new homes, aiming to submit a planning application towards the end of 2024. The consultation ran until January 7, 2024.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fc90aa9a-f804-4f0e-bc7e-834b2a718ba5','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---kirkgate-apartments-future-phase',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.594','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'PEOPLE have been able to view plans for a major city centre regeneration in a building that will soon be demolished to make way for the scheme. Bradford City Village will see close to 1,000 homes built on three sites in Bradford city centre – the site of the Kirkgate Shopping Centre, the site of Oastler Market and on a number of car parks off Westgate. A public consultation into the first phase of the plans began earlier this month, and on Thursday, the first in a series of drop-in events was held in the former Samsung unit at Kirkgate Shopping Centre. The second phase will include a higher density of homes - more than 300 apartments on the southern half of the Oastler site, currently occupied by Oastler Market, and about 400 apartments on the Kirkgate Shopping Centre site.','Model of planned City Village on show in Kirkgate Shopping Centre for public consultation','Bradford Telegraph and Argus','2025-05-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGTMNSmg_fObnFjwavQ88kejWbKWOWlIFY3HKJEKoLRyPFEhnNuvP-15guSn1WDRj4KsG9Ri1Z7yxqBXRFSsQ8BVNNzAETB-rjmDU9ag-bVQHq751hoFHUTCH6_WnmBoheSCMRp8a9MAAsB9ddNwd6x-6sVhmnV9H5QhNzP_T8muw_A6ARo0tiI7_BBX1Q_fSWOMXdxFMEuJk2neEItByMc','As part of the public consultation on the Bradford City Village masterplan, a series of drop-in events were held, including one in the former Samsung unit within the Kirkgate Shopping Centre itself. Visitors could view a 3D model of the planned development and provide feedback on the first phase, which included townhouses, while also learning about future phases that include over 300 apartments on the Oastler site and about 400 apartments on the Kirkgate Shopping Centre site.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fc9a24e8-f0bf-4b9e-bfa9-bf8eb2e21433','infrastructure-residents-parking-zones-calderdale',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.129','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'On Tuesday 7th February 2024 HRBF held an information session with Calderdale Council outlining the HX7 parking strategy. The work to create a holistic, integrated parking plan for Hebden Bridge is just beginning, and Calderdale Council are seeking active involvement from local people and businesses to help devise a plan that supports the strategic aims (see slide 1 below). ... For this new strategic, integrated plan Calderdale will carry out a number of \'on the ground\' surveys in February 2024, counting cars, assessing car parking space availability, condition etc.','Calderdale Parking Strategy - Hebden Royd Business Forum','Hebden Royd Business Forum','2024-02-14 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE1kBx-FGklPuGy6jnkitR8p3eFFe_eMGIUxHC3ecWbAdYrwnlr2fv4VVg1XRJjuVXufok8kqVmFMy6cbK2QcjRmY-rWKYLQp1ggqsaEMOlg7P88XKQ5AHrh8V9uZcb5m9gTU6i_IhvYtX6NApFAAE1','An information session held on February 7, 2024, outlined the HX7 (Hebden Bridge area) parking strategy. This involved gathering \'on the ground\' survey data in February 2024 to create a holistic parking plan. The strategy aims to improve parking provision and encourage less carbon-intensive transport options, indicating a broader approach that would include residential parking considerations.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fcb2aec7-4ea0-41ee-a85e-bf8a8716c259','infrastructure-zapmap-ring-road-middleton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.435','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Asda Middleton charging point This electric car charging point located at Asda Middleton, LS10 4TQ is part of the GeniePoint network. There are 1 device and 3 connectors available at this charging location. ... Address: Asda Middleton. Asda Stores Ltd. Leeds. Yorkshire and the Humber. LS10 4TQ. ... Updated: 13th September 2025.','Asda Middleton EV Charging Point on Zapmap','Zapmap','2025-09-13 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHh-h3AV0EOs0U_dhrDWvKz6dJI6H3i27KBc4uE1niTlYK4sf5ZdWfu6du8P06wRRCneVaZHFOP0pIyrRJDmonEN7lh0wHWcvcA_ViJQj5PikqgQZuNnmatA1D57rIiNAPEqMSpy4hOibs_gu9scg==','According to Zapmap, there is an electric car charging point located at Asda Middleton, LS10 4TQ. This charger is part of the GeniePoint network and offers one device with three connectors. The listing was updated on September 13, 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fcda0673-d251-46fa-bc09-77574866621f','infrastructure-digital-enterprise-3-business-digital-grants',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.313','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Digital Enterprise is for growth-focused small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) with their main operational base in one of the 5 West Yorkshire local authorities (Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, or Wakefield). Businesses must: have been trading for a minimum of 3 years; operate predominantly as a business-to-business (B2B) organisation; have a minimum of 5 employees; have a minimum annual turnover of £100,000. How much you can get. Digital Enterprise offers match-funded grants. There are 2 grant types: Digital Accelerator Grant. This grant covers up to 50% of project costs, up to a maximum of £10,000, for projects costing between £2,000 and £25,000. High Impact Grant. This grant also covers up to 50% of project costs, with a maximum value of £35,000, for projects between £25,000 and £100,000. Organiser. Leeds City Council (lead partner and accountable body). Published 15 September 2025. [9]','Digital Enterprise - GOV.UK','GOV.UK','2025-09-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.gov.uk/business-finance-support/digital-enterprise-west-yorkshire','The GOV.UK page provides an official overview of the Digital Enterprise program. It confirms it\'s for growth-focused SMEs in Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, or Wakefield, meeting specific criteria (3+ years trading, B2B, 5+ employees, £100,000+ turnover). It lists the Digital Accelerator Grant (up to £10,000) and High Impact Grant (up to £35,000) for digital transformation projects. Leeds City Council is named as the organiser. The page was published/updated on 15 September 2025.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fd327252-6ca5-4dbf-8170-1a02919cd5a1','infrastructure-snowhill-retail-park-wakefield-ev-hub',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.322','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'More electric vehicle charging points will be installed across the district if Wakefield Council\'s key decision makers give the go ahead at their meeting next week. Cabinet are being asked to accept a grant of £1,520,938 from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority\'s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant funding scheme.','More EV charging points coming to Wakefield as part of our plans to go green - Wakefield Council','Wakefield Council','2024-10-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFq_CPlZ6keqMt16v2fohcBXGP03mu7AHKn9uQo3y2mQ-jKG1hN9cXPRas1dt93B0jQfxN-ZFH8Il_QWu2eMA-NCrtPEuezU45Zs3s1vjX6w6zBi3MiksqqrF6q4LaqpL0n3y_bFEz3CSEOB5ve8chMMJRDumZLafUInmJ4oWVTZxIa47roaibJqqmnmuCqAcMttOKWqczED0Z6dohsY1HzgKBr-ABj9gb7mquJ7YUEUx6aMA','Wakefield Council\'s Cabinet was set to consider accepting a grant of £1,520,938 from the West Yorkshire Mayoral Combined Authority\'s (WYMCA) Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) grant funding scheme. This funding aims to increase public EV charging points across the district to meet growing demand.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fdb6d3df-a603-4dbd-a186-e22fe06120ee','infrastructure-quickline-project-gigabit-rural-rollout-west-yorkshire--york',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.282','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'By the end of March 2025, Quickline was required to connect 6,273 funded premises in West Yorkshire and the York area. This target was surpassed, with 6,426 homes and businesses connected, including premises in communities such as Harden, near Bingley and Bradshaw, near Thornton. [12, 14]','Quickline surpasses Project Gigabit milestone in West Yorkshire and York','Quickline','2025-03-31 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH9mfwtm-DTZc0XoY4apY00x4jn3HBBtA98NLQkR9_YQ3nTED-QBFXmXULJlG5bw9o5haZQOzsFkLthiEoZ3A2AE2SVYDMonTkFO2a9lG4frGnUnHYCn1uIg3t7jeGN2tFWjJGOqTB1CgkdnQ-L5cwrMLIDmtTuyt3CFKUfJd_GFk5A8ZxwqU-o8h9Xp8uVXkarZxHJO91sGolOp1CEZZkHtFp1eVWY3oQfDvTnUOq-yqlN','By the end of March 2025, Quickline surpassed its target for the West Yorkshire and York area (Lot 8) Project Gigabit contract, connecting 6,426 funded premises against a target of 6,273. Communities benefiting include Harden (near Bingley) and Bradshaw (near Thornton), both within the Bradford district.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fdd06294-c5d3-4ab4-9d8a-e4f1aba6cdf4','infrastructure-copley-village-flood-alleviation-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.237','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Sheet pile installation is now complete along the entire length of the embankment, from Old Rishworthian Rugby Club to Railway Terrace. ... Construction works in Copley Village are currently planned to be completed in February 2025, subject to no unforeseen issues occurring. The embankment will be covered with grass seed and will remain closed to the public until at least Summer 2025 to allow the grass to fully establish.','Copley Flood Alleviation Scheme (FAS) Information Bulletin No.4 – November 2024','AWS / Environment Agency','2024-11-04 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH8CBAnBYtvTecNLSeGLMNMUd7tMv6P6XLIibaB2KAvupLmx2DDpfxN6YBKV3621YTG7_iHdmJ60AuwmTdN7hOMJ0jvcp_9GsDOBGPvnVOSN7JpmmYnhqNqlL6gR3is0xTn1dup4JRhVblYGsrPOrqwUYbUZrJ3o5FW-Cv8eoSx3LfCBXeWNhcg2LAGtljmd5OhiReXATX2PqI6YSnWYJmBDJY5JBqMXKbmVXNzzr7XBiUySpVuYHH0RhTykUskYciiBYbNL37g','This information bulletin reports that sheet pile installation is complete along the entire length of the embankment. The main construction works in Copley Village are currently planned for completion in February 2025, with the embankment remaining closed until at least Summer 2025 for grass establishment.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fe646657-23e4-4e17-a9d5-79bbbdf73ac4','infrastructure-halifax-to-shelf-bus-service-571-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.106','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The West Yorkshire Enhanced Partnership Scheme for Buses is made in accordance with Section 138G(1) of the Transport Act 2000 by: West Yorkshire Combined Authority, City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council, Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council, Kirklees Council, Leeds City Council, City of Wakefield Metropolitan District Council. This EP Scheme is made on 1 November 2022 and shall come into operation on this date and has subsequently been varied on 29 March 2024. [8, 14]','West Yorkshire Enhanced Partnership Plan','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2022-11-01 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFoLjl4lriPfz5Ns6CB-x6sBPMn5YvHpDL4PdKnaWGenv_zwXktBcMW7QRLEZ5pvgoY7Lve4d2jph7tiAs_7hu4_z9Y3E-SVg0JaSl1zs09eQ3R24gOCcm1V7YD_891ssjJuGdf5ipCC6tb2RvlJjymyqtFonn34qPoUA-p0e-rKQR3gw','The West Yorkshire Enhanced Partnership Scheme was officially made and came into operation, providing a statutory framework for collaboration between the West Yorkshire Combined Authority (WYCA), the five local authorities (Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds, Wakefield), and bus operators to deliver improvements across the bus network. This plan underpins broader bus service improvement initiatives, including those like the 571 route improvements. [8, 14]','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fe78f8d4-74cb-4a0e-b8d2-7db645232cba','infrastructure-psds-phase-3a-leeds-teaching-hospitals-nhs-trust-st-jamess-hospital-decarbonisation',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.355','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'In April, Beckett Wing at St James\'s University Hospital became the first Trust building to connect to Leeds PIPES. The heating network provides affordable, reliable and sustainable heat to connected buildings. It uses recovered heat to serve the households and businesses across the city, including the Trust, to provide a low-carbon alternative to the traditional burning of fossil fuels for hot water heating.','Beckett Wing at St James\'s Hospital connects to Leeds PIPES','Hefma / EM Magazine / Bevan Brittan LLP','2022-04-01 00:00:00.000','https://hefma.co.uk/news/psds-funding-moves-decarbonisation-project-to-next-phase-for-leeds-teaching-hospitals','In April 2022, the Beckett Wing at St James\'s University Hospital became the first building within the Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust to connect to the Leeds PIPES district heating system. This connection is a key part of the hospital\'s decarbonisation efforts, providing a low-carbon alternative to fossil fuels for heating.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fe7b20ea-6e1e-4297-a956-bde55fd2ae54','infrastructure-zapmap-ring-road-middleton-leeds-ev-charger',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.435','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Find out more about our approach, read the Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030 (PDF, 507KB).','Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030 (Mentioned)','Leeds.gov.uk','2022-03-23 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFfJlWnpbPVgD6DhOi5S76SX0EWlfhEHZWg4vF_VEVOAILHZia8NtFKrNPboswV9PKigy6nHr9OaShG5CSmBIjtJjK4UDdKe3AfbSoWZJ7pVVcH-B8JsLohRaP6oz6JCkrE9B6FYT5Y1sZX3mlU9SxJ0q07mroLG06vHKYw72Y8OjQNbC7XGfarezqb_RYSkN6DwR6rLa92MYpxeyr4yTM6tTkhJpn55d0O0ci-Qt1ee2CJYVv0VWLb','Leeds City Council has a strategic document, \'Leeds Electric Vehicle Charge Infrastructure Strategy and Action Plan 2022 to 2030\', which outlines the city\'s approach to increasing EV charging points. This strategy is part of the council\'s broader transport and climate action plans.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fe9a8f6f-5846-4123-a513-262ffd19cfd7','infrastructure-bradford-city-village---north-oastler-site-homes-phase-1',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.635','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'We\'ve submitted plans for the first phase of the new sustainable community known as \'City Village,\' which will transform Bradford\'s former commercial core into a thriving new city centre neighbourhood. A detailed planning application for Phase One, alongside an outline planning application for the rest of the site, has been submitted. Plans for phase one include: – A further 64 two and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, arranged around a series of courtyards and green spaces, each with designated parking space. Subject to planning approval, demolition of the Oastler site is anticipated to begin later this year, with construction starting in spring 2026. [8, 11]','Plans submitted for Bradford City Village - ECF - the English Cities Fund','ECF - The English Cities Fund','2025-09-08 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFH48x8LzuCkejfuoc11oIhr1UypCm2xHsv6-KRTL8HgN6Hs_vhrj2cIkvffcJ0OUj6m5kN8GLfnvRoegeuXybC1ZPbfZaBhtpzb184n_U88nSfqgqizfSz1T6c79fNs_LgQMMy8jRr8DnmR9ekkf2cF0I8RZ9NrTAOEoOpXwumGBBdZdMTdYpjdMw4LI4=','ECF and Bradford Council submitted detailed plans for Phase One of the City Village, which includes 64 two- and three-bedroom townhouses on the northern Oastler site, alongside 33 on Chain Street. The submission also contained outline plans for the wider development. Demolition of the Oastler site is anticipated later in 2025, with construction of Phase One slated for Spring 2026.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fecc280c-59db-4015-8f15-695c71e450c8','infrastructure-wakefield-city-centre-transforming-cities-fund-improvements-a61-and-a639',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.005','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'(2025-07-16) Ambitious plans to regenerate Wakefield city centre are accelerating, with Wakefield Council set to formalise its partnership with Muse – one of the UK\'s leading placemaking and regeneration specialists. This announcement marks the next phase in delivering the city\'s long-term transformation, starting with the Cathedral Quarter and Borough Road. These changes are part of the wider Wakefield City Centre Masterplan and supported by the Towns Deal investment, which aims to create a more vibrant, connected, and economically thriving Wakefield.','Wakefield BID Welcomes Bold Plans to Transform Wakefield City Centre','Wakefield BID','2025-07-16 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFQrq2Owl8XTTNqILQ66vxKGRGym1seDByhzG6Xf9577jp32XfxE-f4kEGWJiikK_i9CBhUMiCQxcRBw2dAay7-HHHDKB-ZUqmAhtk6QM6AB2n09HQOE6xQLXo6PYpWtT3w7Jvl36ylmqy_iSoQTHaH9nBq_eYBjmKstAuluywDEX9-IV5YsR5kwsVlSHAX8_59uj9xdjuGHDZj-BPttjcLdXeoSy7r20Ai','Wakefield BID announced that ambitious plans to regenerate Wakefield city centre are accelerating, with Wakefield Council set to formalize a partnership with Muse, a regeneration specialist. This next phase of the city\'s long-term transformation, supported by Towns Deal investment, will focus on areas like the Cathedral Quarter and Borough Road, aiming to create a more vibrant and connected city. This ongoing regeneration, while not solely TCF, contributes to the overall city centre transformation objectives.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('fede5e8c-0b84-4391-a8b9-3c3494c06d83','infrastructure-castleford-growth-corridor-scheme',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.675','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The Castleford Growth Corridor scheme will connect the town centre and Ferry Fryston via a new continuous, largely traffic-free route for people walking and cycling, including a new bridge over the railway. Wakefield Council, in partnership with the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is proposing a number of measures within the scheme, with the aim of easing congestion, improving connections, and making walking and cycling safer and more attractive. This consultation will close on Monday 12 February 2024 at 11.59pm. [5]','Castleford Growth Corridor and Wheldon Road Bridge | Your Voice - West Yorkshire Combined Authority','West Yorkshire Combined Authority','2024-01-15 00:00:00.000','https://www.yourvoice.westyorks-ca.gov.uk/castleford-growth-corridor-and-wheldon-road-bridge','A public engagement portal by the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and Wakefield Council announced a consultation on the Castleford Growth Corridor scheme. The scheme proposes a new continuous, largely traffic-free route for walking and cycling between Castleford town centre and Ferry Fryston, including a new bridge over the railway, aimed at easing congestion and improving connections.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ffa020ed-5f6c-41da-8414-bc32f6488965','infrastructure-todmorden-town-hall-improvements',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:20.250','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'The magnificent main hall was refurbished in 2021, and this next series of improvements that are taking place throughout 2025 will include: Opening the grand entrance and installing an external ramp, allowing visitors to enter through the Victorian lobby.','Main hall refurbishment completed (mentioned in later report)','Calderdale Council','2021-06-30 00:00:00.000','https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGOFwd-GflThI2oyQBKPrB1dn_WN9VQ6BconmAEkJjK-zewh6foEbu0bybo36xrqF76vF6OO_q-rO8CBunu7V4wK98OIAepyZ6gULT1AmcORnGrp55puZIeA08VyId4I8yKrXjeNKOCIfJgLoyFqeX2CXErFeyhE_cqEbMLpcZ7','A later report from Calderdale Council mentions that the magnificent main hall of Todmorden Town Hall was refurbished in 2021, indicating earlier significant work on the building that forms a foundation for current improvements.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901'),
	('ffc2f444-16e9-49fd-8ab8-86fc948cb61d','infrastructure-south-village-formerly-leeds-city-one',1,'TEXT','2025-09-18 12:50:19.503','APPROVED',NULL,NULL,'Caddick Developments announced receiving unanimous resolution to approve from Leeds City Council planning committee for a major, new, mixed-use neighbourhood in the South Bank of Leeds. The 2m sq ft scheme, previously named City One, has been rebranded as South Village, reflecting its location within one of the UK\'s largest brownfield regeneration sites and its design as a contemporary urban village. [5]','WE’VE RECEIVED UNANIMOUS APPROVAL FOR SOUTH VILLAGE','Caddick Developments','2024-03-14 00:00:00.000','https://caddick.co.uk/news/weve-received-unanimous-approval-for-south-village','Caddick Developments announced the unanimous planning approval from Leeds City Council for their major mixed-use neighbourhood in South Bank, Leeds. Concurrently, the 2m sq ft scheme, formerly City One, was officially rebranded as South Village, reflecting its urban village design concept.','2025-09-18 20:51:57.901');
